<head>
<title>Transportation</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<pre>              Statement by the AFL-CIO Executive Council

                                  on

       A New Tack in the Campaign to Get Rid of American Workers

                            August 2, 1995
                                Chicago


      Congress shortly will be considering legislation specifically
designed to weaken the American domestic waterways transportation
system by gutting the existing cabotage law and opening up the
trade to foreign companies allowed to replace American workers with
imported, low-cost foreign workers not covered by any U.S. labor
laws. Of vital concern to all American workers is the precedent
such action would have, leading to an incursion of foreign
interests and foreign workers exempt from U.S. protections in all
forms of domestic transportation -- including rail, trucking and
air.

      These efforts to destroy the U.S. domestic transportation work
force are being led and funded by American companies with foreign
flag shipping interests and foreign corporations anxious to move
into the domestic transportation scene with foreign workers hired
from the world's most exploitable pools of labor. These forces
choose to ignore the fact that there are vital national security
and economic factors that have long ensured that transportation
within the physical confines of the United States has been in the
hands of American companies and U.S. workers.

      All American workers in domestic transportation are threatened
by any legislation which aims to replace workers earning U.S. wage
and benefit levels with workers from underdeveloped nations who
would be exempt from the nation's labor laws and protections.
Ironically, such legislation, if adopted, would signal every U.S.-
based company that they no longer need to go offshore to evade
American labor standards. Such legislation implies that in the not
too distant future, Congress will entertain the idea that exploited
foreign labor can be imported to the United States and made exempt
from U.S. laws.

      Recognizing that efforts to devalue America's cabotage laws
are nothing but a transparent attempt to reduce the standards of
all workers employed in America's domestic transportation systems,
the AFL-CIO registers its vigorous and absolute support for the
nation's existing cabotage laws.</pre>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="/estatements/estatement.html">Executive Council Page</a></p>
