<title>Bieber</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<pre>           Statement by the AFL-CIO Executive Council

                               on

                           Owen Bieber

                         August 2, 1995
                             Chicago


     Whereas our friend and brother Owen Bieber has retired as a
member of this Executive Council;

     Whereas Owen Bieber has been part of the trade union movement
since he was 19 years old, when he joined the United Auto Workers
as an assembly-line worker in Grand Rapids, Michigan;

     Whereas Owen Bieber has given more than four decades of
service to the United Auto Workers as local president, regional
staff representative, international representative, regional
director, vice-president, and president;

     Whereas the United Auto Workers under Owen Bieber's leadership
has brought job and income security to hundreds of thousands of
working women and men, and expanded its organizing and education
programs;

     Whereas Owen Bieber has contributed to this Executive Council
as the chair of the Committee on Economic Policy and the Committee
on South Africa and as a member of the committees on International
Affairs, Legislation, Political Education, Article XX Review, the
Balanced Budget Amendment, Botto House, Defense, Energy, Evolution
of Work, Health Care, Legislative Priorities, National Information
Infrastructure, Older and Retired Union Members, Pension
Investment, Political Work, Training, and the United Negro College
Fund;

     Be it resolved that the Executive Council of the AFL-CIO
thanks Owen Bieber for his many years of service and his unflagging
commitment to the principles of trade unionism, and wishes him a
happy, fulfilling retirement; and,

     Be it further resolved that this expression of gratitude,
affection, and esteem be spread upon the permanent records of the
AFL-CIO.</pre>
