<head>
<title>Voting</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<pre>           Statement by the AFL-CIO Executive Council

                               on

         Thirtieth Anniversary of the Voting Rights Act

                        February 21, 1995
                        Bal Harbour, Fla.


     This year marks the 30th anniversary of one of the country's
most successful civil rights laws, the Voting Rights Act.  This
landmark legislation, and the success of subsequent efforts to
strengthen it, have played a critical role in curtailing the
discriminatory practices that once prevented millions of Americans
from exercising their right to vote because of their color or
ethnic background.

     But this commemoration should also serve as a reminder that
the struggle for voting rights continues and that the full
participation of all citizens in the country's political process
remains an unfulfilled goal.  The Voting Rights Act must continue
to be vigorously enforced by the U.S. Department of Justice, and
Congress must continue to extend and improve the Act.

     We urge strong enforcement of the new federal &quot;Motor-voter&quot;
law, which will make it easier for Americans to register to vote,
and rejection of the ludicrous assertion that participation in
democracy imposes an unfair financial burden on state governments.

     Finally, we urge our affiliated unions, state federations and
local central bodies to take part in next month's re-enactment of
the historic 1965 Selma-to-Montgomery March in Alabama, an event
which was lead by Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr. and which launched
the campaign to pass the Voting Rights Act.</pre>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="estatement.html">Executive Council Page</a></p>
