<head>
<title>PR 1/15/97 AFL-CIO sues on behalf of 120,000 unemployed
workers</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<p align="left">FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<br>
For information contact: <br>
Maureen Anderson or Lisa Hubbard, 415-546-6656<br>
Richard Greer, AFL-CIO, 202-637-5279</p>
<p align="center"><font size="3">AFL-CIO sues on behalf of
120,000 unemployed workers<br>
Oakland A's ticket clerk at center of case that could affect many
states</font></p>
<p align="left">San Francisco, Jan. 15, 1997 -- The AFL-CIO today
filed a<br>
class action suit against a California state agency on behalf of
at<br>
least 120,000 unemployed workers for whom $230 million in<br>
unemployment insurance benefits are delayed or denied.<br>
<br>
The suit charges that California law violates federal law<br>
requiring unemployment insurance to be paid as soon as possible
and<br>
has forced thousands of workers onto welfare.<br>
<br>
Besides the AFL-CIO, the plaintiff in the suit is Khadijah<br>
Jacob, an Oakland A's ticket clerk who, after being laid off, was<br>
deprived of unemployment insurance even though she had earned<br>
enough to qualify for benefits.<br>
<br>
Under California law, benefits can be delayed for as long as<br>
seven months after a worker is laid off due to an anachronistic<br>
provision of the insurance code that keeps the state from<br>
considering a worker's most recent earnings in calculating<br>
benefits. The provision stems from an era when technology did not<br>
permit prompt processing of claims.<br>
<br>
Currently, benefits are based on earnings within a one-year<br>
base period that ends anywhere from four to seven months before
the<br>
date a worker files a claim. For example, if a worker becomes<br>
unemployed and files a claim this month, the claim would be based<br>
only on wages earned from July 1, 1995 through June 30, 1996.<br>
Thousands of workers -- particularly low-wage workers, seasonal<br>
workers and women -- need these earnings counted to qualify for<br>
benefits. Yet, they must wait to receive benefits until
California<br>
counts recent wages, which can mean a seven-month delay.<br>
<br>
Benefits are not retroactive and the applicant would have to<br>
still be unemployed to receive benefits. If not, benefits are
lost.<br>
<br>
That is basically what happened to Jacob. <br>
<br>
Under the law, her entire earnings with the A's were excluded.<br>
She was forced onto welfare while looking for a new job.<br>
<br>
&quot;I do not want to receive welfare,&quot; said Jacob. <br>
<br>
A 1996 report by the state's unemployment insurance agency,<br>
the California Employment Development Department, showed that<br>
121,824 California workers are either denied unemployment
insurance<br>
or have benefits delayed due to the law. The cost to workers in<br>
lost benefits was estimated at $92.7 million and $140 million in<br>
benefits were delayed.<br>
<br>
The state could eliminate the delays by using a one-year base<br>
period that includes recent wages for workers.<br>
<br>
The agency's own report estimated that denying and delaying<br>
benefits costs taxpayers $40.9 million in unnecessary welfare<br>
payments because 28,800 of the workers are forced onto welfare.<br>
Welfare benefits are paid by taxpayers; unemployment insurance is<br>
funded by businesses. <br>
<br>
&quot;In the absence of good jobs and when much of the country's<br>
social safety net is under attack, unemployment insurance is the<br>
minimum workers deserve,&quot; AFL-CIO Executive Vice President
Linda<br>
Chavez-Thompson said. &quot;Unemployment insurance is intended to
go to<br>
workers quickly to allow them to seek other employment, to offer
a<br>
bridge between jobs without having to rely on welfare and to<br>
protect community businesses from losing consumers. Delays shift<br>
the cost from business to taxpayers.&quot;<br>
<br>
At least 10 states' unemployment insurance laws count a<br>
worker's recent earnings, minimizing delays. The AFL-CIO suit
could<br>
be seen as a bellwether for other states that have a system
similar<br>
to California's.</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../index.htm">Public Documents Page</a> | <a
href="../publsear.htm">Public Documents Search</a></p>
