<html>
<head>
<title>PR 12/23/96 MORE LABOR VICTORIES ROLL IN</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<p>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<br>
For Information: Deborah Dion 202-637-5036<br>
December 19, 1997</p>
<p align="center">MORE LABOR VICTORIES ROLL IN<br>
NEARLY 4000 WORKERS WIN HUGE VICTORY AFTER<br>
YEAR-LONG BATTLE WITH YALE UNIVERSITY</p>
<p>Washington, December 19 -- A week after 312 workers, their<br>
supporters and AFL-CIO President John Sweeney were arrested at a<br>
massive demonstration at the campus, employees at Yale University<br>
have reached a tentative agreement with the university. <br>
The agreement between Locals 34 and 35 of the Federation of<br>
University Employees and Yale University offers a six-year pact<br>
which includes extraordinary job security, pension improvements,<br>
part-time workers protection and increased health care benefits. <br>
The victory over the university's corporate-like agenda to<br>
slash pay and benefits by outsourcing jobs comes as the AFL-CIO<br>
begins implementing a $30 million program to organize new workers<br>
and on the heels of several similar victories. <br>
Last week, 2,500 state of Maryland workers won union<br>
representation, joining 7,800 corrective workers who also won<br>
union representation this year. In November, 3,000 workers won<br>
union recognition at the MGM Grand in Las Vegas. In October, 170<br>
women workers at Richmark, a Boston-area curtain maker, quickly<br>
won union recognition after public pressure from revitalized<br>
labor movement brought the company to terms.<br>
&quot;The Yale victory sends a strong message to Corporate<br>
America that _America's Working Families Are Back' and that<br>
united, workers can beat back corporate profiteers at rich<br>
institutions, on Wall Street and in corporate board rooms all<br>
across this nation,&quot; said AFL-CIO President John Sweeney.<br>
&quot;By reaching agreements with its employees over job<br>
security, Yale has set a standard for other institutions and<br>
organizations where workers are organizing to improve their<br>
lives,&quot; he added.<br>
For the past year bitter negotiations for new contracts for<br>
Yale's unionized workers had broken down over university demands<br>
for the right to subcontract much of the on campus work,<br>
following the nationwide push by corporate America to replace<br>
full-time jobs with contingent, low-wage, no-benefit labor. <br>
Yale faced action by the National Labor Relations Board for<br>
&quot;interfering with, restraining and coercing Yale employees,<br>
discriminating against employees for union activity, and refusing<br>
to bargain in good faith&quot; with the two campus unions
struggling<br>
to keep their jobs at the university.<br>
&quot;We all have cause to celebrate today, thanks to the courage<br>
and determination of our membership and the heroic efforts of the<br>
clergy, elected officials and community activists throughout the<br>
region,&quot; said Local 34 President Laura Smith. &quot;When you
add up<br>
all the elements, these contracts offer the best job security<br>
provisions in the country.&quot;</p>
