<title>PR 11/18/96 Sweeney Addresses 5000 Public Health Officials</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<p>Contact: Deborah Dion 202-637-5036<br>
<br>
Media Advisory for Monday, November 18<br>
<br>
AFL-CIO PRESIDENT JOHN SWEENEY ADDRESSES 5000 PUBLIC<br>
HEALTH OFFICIALS AT APHA ANNUAL MEETING IN NEW YORK<br>
<br>
Sweeney Kicks-off Opening Session<br>
as Margaret Baggett Dolan Lecturer<br>
<br>
Just two weeks after an election in which the AFL-CIO drove the<br>
national debate on issues important to working families like<br>
Medicare and Medicaid, AFL-CIO President John Sweeney will
keynote<br>
the opening session of the American Public Health Association's<br>
21st annual meeting in New York City.<br>
<br>
Sweeney will speak as the 1996 Dolan Lecturer honoring public<br>
health nurse Margaret Baggett Dolan, the first woman to hold the<br>
APHA presidency. Sweeney will talk about the need to increase<br>
expectations of our nation, improve living standards and protect<br>
two of the nation's leading health care programs -- Medicare and<br>
Medicaid. Sweeney will also talk about the need to support<br>
legislation to provide health coverage to our nation's 13 million<br>
uninsured children.<br>
<br>
ON THE AGENDA: MONDAY, NOVEMBER 18, 1996<br>
<br>
10:00 AM AFL-CIO President John Sweeney - Keynotes<br>
APHA 21st Annual Meeting, New York<br>
Coliseum, 4th floor, 10 Columbus Circle<br>
New York City<br>
<br>
12:00 noon President's Press Conference -- APHA<br>
President E. Richard Brown and John<br>
Sweeney, New York Coliseum, Room 324 --<br>
The Assembly Room, 2nd Floor ###</p>
