<head>
<title>PR 10/11/96 REPUBLICANS TRY TO SILENCE THE VOICE OF
WORKING FAMILIES</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<p>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE Contact: Denise Mitchell 202-637-5340<br>
Deborah Dion 202-637-5036<br>
<br>
REPUBLICANS TRY TO SILENCE THE VOICE OF WORKING FAMILIES<br>
<br>
In a desperate attempt to silence the voice of working<br>
families and hide from the voting records of Newt Gingrich and<br>
the Republican Congress, the National Republican Congressional<br>
Committee is airing shamefully dishonest commercials around the<br>
country.<br>
<br>
What the Republican ads say: &quot;The big labor bosses in<br>
Washington are spending big money spreading big lies to buy their<br>
control of Congress.&quot;<br>
<br>
Reality Check: Spending by big business overwhelms the AFL-CIO's<br>
campaign. Corporate interests are -- and always have been -- far<br>
outspending labor in all areas of the political arena, including<br>
PAC and individual campaign contributions and so-called
&quot;soft&quot;<br>
money contributions, as well as in voter education. According to<br>
the most recent analysis by the non-partisan Citizen Action,<br>
between January 1, 1995 and May 31, 1996, corporate interests<br>
gave roughly 4 times as much in PAC contributions to House<br>
members as labor PACs. (It's the Money II: An Analysis of 1995-<br>
1996 Campaign Contributions to House Members, Citizen Action,<br>
8/1/96)<br>
<br>
In fact, business has historically outspent labor in PAC giving<br>
to all federal candidates by about three to one. Corporate PAC<br>
giving rose 26% between 1987-1988 and the last cycle -- twice the<br>
rate of increase of Labor PAC giving (13%).<br>
<br>
What the Republican ads say: &quot;Here in Arizona, they're<br>
running ads in favor of Steve Owens.&quot;<br>
<br>
Reality Check: The ads educate the public on both candidates'<br>
positions. The purpose of the AFL-CIO voter guide ads is to<br>
educate workers about congressional candidates' positions on<br>
issues that are central to working families' lives. The ads do<br>
not urge the viewer to either vote for or against either<br>
candidate. Instead, the guides lay out each candidate's position<br>
on the issue in question in a fair and evenhanded manner.<br>
The AFL-CIO's voter guides are covered by a new section of FEC<br>
regulations that specifically allows corporations and unions to<br>
make treasury money expenditures for election-related<br>
communications to the public so long as those communications<br>
don't &quot;expressly advocate&quot; the election or defeat of a
clearly<br>
identified candidate. The new regulations allow a corporation or<br>
labor organization to do a &quot;general voter guide consisting
of two<br>
or more candidates' positions on campaign issues...&quot;provided
that<br>
the voter guide does not &quot;expressly advocate&quot; the
election or<br>
defeat of a candidate and is prepared without &quot;contact&quot;
or<br>
&quot;coordination&quot; with candidates (11 C.F.R. 114.4
(c)(5)(1)).<br>
<br>
What the Republican ads say: &quot;The big labor bosses are tax
&amp;<br>
spend liberals. They fought welfare reform. Stopped term limits.<br>
Blocked a balanced budget.&quot;<br>
<br>
Reality Check: Working families deserve a voice. The AFL-CIO has<br>
been speaking out on issues of importance to working families.<br>
Newt Gingrich and the Republican Congress have launched an<br>
unprecedented attack on basic protections that America's working<br>
families have a right to expect -- including retirement security,<br>
workplace safety and environmental protection. Working families<br>
deserve the opportunity to fight back. The AFL-CIO's campaign has<br>
been successful in passing an increase in the minimum wage and<br>
largely derailing the Republican effort to make enormous budget<br>
cuts in programs such as Medicare, education and health care.</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../index.htm">Public Documents Page</a> | <a
href="../publsear.htm">Public Documents Search</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
</body>
