<html>
<head>
<title>PR 10/09/96 Sweeney to Richmark</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<p>For information: Richard Greer, AFL-CIO,<br>
1-888-858-7243, PIN *104769 <br>
(pager); 202-637-5279<br>
<br>
TO BOSTON AREA NEWS MEDIA, NATIONAL LABOR REPORTERS<br>
<br>
John Sweeney to Richmark: We will fight you and those like you<br>
Sweeney, community leaders demand companies accept workers'<br>
choice<br>
<br>
Washington, Oct. 7, 1996 -- AFL-CIO President John Sweeney<br>
will join Boston area workers and community leaders Tuesday in a<br>
march on Richmark International, a company where employees report<br>
sub-minimum wages, unaffordable health insurance, no sick pay and<br>
monitoring of bathroom breaks.<br>
When workers at the curtain company tried to improve their<br>
conditions by organizing -- a majority of employees supported the<br>
Union of Needletrades, Industrial and Textile Employees --<br>
several were fired. A sympathy walk-out erupted Sept. 23. A<br>
strike continues.<br>
&quot;Unfortunately this is not new,&quot; said Sweeney.
&quot;What is new<br>
is that the AFL-CIO and workers aren't accepting it anymore. When<br>
employers ignore their employees' legally-protected right to work<br>
to improve their conditions, we'll be there. We're starting with<br>
Richmark in Everett, Massachusetts.&quot;<br>
Sweeney said it is ironic that corporate America preaches<br>
individual responsibility, but that when employees take<br>
responsibility businesses fire them.<br>
&quot;Richmark workers, like thousands of other workers in the<br>
nation, are trying to improve their lives, their families and<br>
their communities. It is wrong for the big foot of business to<br>
try and crush them. From here on out, organized labor says to<br>
Richmark and companies like them: We will fight you whether it's<br>
in Everett or Birmingham, Akron or Spokane.&quot;<br>
The workers and community leaders in Everett will attempt to<br>
meet with company officials and demand that they respect the<br>
choice of their employees.<br>
<br>
WHEN, WHERE: Everett City Hall, 484 Broadway, 11:30<br>
a.m. Tuesday, Oct. 8, followed by march on Richmark, 329 Second<br>
St., Everett.</p>
