<html>
<head>
<title>PR 09/27/96 -- AFL-CIO Compares Candidates on TV &amp;
Radio with Voter Guides</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<p>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE For Information:<br>
Deborah Dion 202-637-5036<br>
David Saltz 202-637-5318<br>
<br>
AFL-CIO COMPARES CANDIDATES ON WORKING FAMILY ISSUES IN<br>
NEW SERIES OF TV &amp; RADIO VOTER GUIDES<br>
<br>
Washington, Sept. 27 -- As part of a stepped-up effort to raise<br>
issues of importance to working families and provide information
to<br>
voters, the AFL-CIO today launched a new series of TV and radio<br>
voter guides in 24 congressional districts.<br>
&quot;The electronic voter guides are one more step in the AFL-<br>
CIO's continuing effort to raise the issues that are central to
the<br>
lives of working Americans and to shine a light on Congress' and<br>
candidates' records with respect to those issues,&quot; said
AFL-CIO<br>
President John Sweeney.<br>
The non-partisan voter guides highlight issues like education<br>
and retirement security that grew out of the 29 America Needs a<br>
Raise town hall meetings the AFL-CIO held this year, as well as<br>
polling and focus groups of AFL-CIO members and non-union
workers.<br>
&quot;We have been speaking for working families all this year,
not<br>
just for our members but for all working families,&quot; Sweeney
said.<br>
&quot;We plan to continue to lobby officeholders and would-be<br>
officeholders to adopt positions on issues like education, health<br>
care and retirement security that are good for working
people.&quot;<br>
The electronic voter guides were tested under the coordination<br>
of Peter D. Hart Research Associates, an independent research
firm.<br>
Voters who viewed preliminary versions of the spots and completed<br>
questionnaires overwhelmingly concluded that the guides
&quot;provided<br>
information they didn't know,&quot; &quot;dealt with issues that
will be very<br>
important in this year's election,&quot; provide information that
seems<br>
&quot;believable and accurate,&quot; and is &quot;fair in how it
describes the two<br>
candidates and their positions.&quot;<br>
The electronic voter guides urge listeners to call an 800<br>
number to receive a copy of the AFL-CIO's written voter guide<br>
comparing information on these same elected officials' votes as<br>
well as their challengers' position on additional issues
important<br>
to working families.<br>
According to another poll conducted by Geoff Garin of Peter D.<br>
Hart Research Associates, AFL-CIO members support the AFL-CIO's<br>
issues oriented educational campaign by an overwhelming majority,<br>
and by a margin of six to one members say they want their union
to<br>
be involved in speaking out on political issues.<br>
Additionally, 84 percent of AFL-CIO members say they approve<br>
of voter guides that compare positions of candidates, compared to<br>
12 percent who disapprove.<br>
The voter guides are part of the 13.1 million member AFL-CIO's<br>
continuing outreach program to America's working families.</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../index.htm">Public Documents Page</a> | <a
href="../publsear.htm">Public Documents Search</a></p>
