<html>

<head>
<title>PR 09/19/96 New effort to bring voting message to low-income  women workers.</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>MEDIA ADVISORY FOR OCTOBER 4-11, 1996<br>
<br>
                               Contact: Deborah Dion 202/637-5036<br>
                               Deborah Sedillo Dugan 202/637-5365<br>
                                      Carmen Murguia 414/274-0928<br>
<br>
            AFL-CIO &amp; 9to5 LAUNCH NEW EFFORT TO BRING<br>
           VOTING MESSAGE TO LOW-INCOME WOMEN WORKERS<br>
<br>
      HUNDREDS OF GOTV ACTIVITIES PLANNED FOR OCTOBER 4-11<br>
<br>
Washington, D.C. -- Low-income working women will play a pivotal<br>
role in this year's elections, and that is the message behind<br>
hundreds of voter registration/GOTV activities planned for the week<br>
of October 4-11 -- the last week in most cities to register to<br>
vote. The unprecedented effort, Working Women Vote, is sponsored by<br>
the new AFL-CIO's Working Women's Department and 9to5, National<br>
Association of Women, a nonpartisan organization.<br>
<br>
     The centerpiece of this campaign is reaching out to women<br>
voters -- in grocery stores or shopping malls, at day care centers,<br>
in union halls and at union worksites, during their lunch hours --<br>
places where women spend most of their time. Voter<br>
registration/GOTV events will be held in about 100 selected<br>
communities with about 10,000 women activists participating<br>
nationwide.<br>
<br>
     According to the political pundits, the women's vote will be<br>
the deciding factor in this year's election. Women are concerned<br>
about &quot;pocketbook issues&quot; like Medicare, pension, education, wages<br>
and family leave -- and the impact of these issues on their lives<br>
and their families.<br>
<br>
     &quot;These women are union members and their best friends. White<br>
collar and blue collar women. No-collar, no-income women who cook,<br>
clean and care for the kids so the husband can work two jobs.<br>
Retired, and just plain tired. They've been left out the political<br>
process,&quot; said AFL-CIO's Working Women's Department head Karen<br>
Nussbaum.<br>
<br>
     &quot;Working women have a lot at stake in this election,&quot; Ellen<br>
Bravo, 9to5's executive director, said. &quot;We have to mobilize our<br>
power, organize to influence the agenda and determine the outcome.&quot;<br>
<br>
     In February, AFL-CIO President John Sweeney established the<br>
first-ever Working Women's Department within the AFL-CIO. Sweeney<br>
appointed Nussbaum, former U.S. Department of Labor Women's Bureau<br>
Chief to direct it. Nussbaum and the Working Women's Department is<br>
charged with injecting the concerns of working women into every<br>
major program at the AFL-CIO and to develop programs that speak to<br>
working women.<br>
<br>
     A list of cities and events will be released next week.</p>
