<html>

<head>
<title>PR 09/16/96 Strawberry workers rally</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>For immediate release<br>
Assignment editors, labor and agriculture reporters <br>
<br>
For information: Richard Greer, AFL-CIO, 202-637-5279<br>
Jocelyn Sherman, UFW, 805-635-5787 (pager)<br>
<br>
More than 50 cities support strawberry workers as thousands rally<br>
<br>
Sept. 16, 1996 -- In more than 50 cities across the nation<br>
today, a coalition of workers, labor unions, clergy and<br>
community leaders spoke up for 20,000 California strawberry<br>
workers.<br>
Monday's activities come the day after 6,000-7,000 workers<br>
and supporters marched in Watsonville, the heart of California<br>
strawberry country.<br>
The strawberry workers are trying to improve their lives by<br>
organizing with the United Farm Workers. <br>
Supporters from Anchorage to Denver to Miami met with<br>
supermarket managers seeking pledges on behalf of basic rights<br>
for the workers. In Los Angeles, city council members were to<br>
sign a pledge of support and vowed to push for an official<br>
resolution of support. In Miami, supporters took the message to<br>
dozens of supermarkets. <br>
The workers are seeking basic rights: clean drinking water<br>
and bathrooms in the fields, a living wage, health insurance, an<br>
end to sexual harassment, and protection from arbitrary firings<br>
and reward for years of loyalty.<br>
The average pay for the workers is about $8,000 a year. For<br>
only 5 cents per pint, the $650 million-a-year California<br>
strawberry industry could greatly improve conditions for the<br>
workers.<br>
That's what it could cost to increase workers' pay rates by at<br>
least 50 percent and in some cases as much as 100 percent,<br>
according to a California study.<br>
&quot;Is 5 cents for fairness too much to ask? We don't think<br>
so,&quot; AFL-CIO Executive Vice President Linda Chavez Thompson said<br>
of the campaign, which is one of the largest current union drives<br>
in the U.S.<br>
A partial list of cities where supporters were expected to<br>
turn out: Albany, Ga.; Albany, N.Y.; Albuquerque; Anchorage,<br>
Alaska; Annandale, Va.; Atlanta; Baltimore; Birmingham, Ala.;<br>
Boston; Boulder, Colo.; Casper, Wy.; Cheyenne, Wy.; Cincinnati;<br>
Cleveland; Columbus, Ohio; Dayton, Ohio; Denver; Fairbanks,<br>
Alaska; Fort Lauderdale, Fla.; Foster City, Calif.; Gillette,<br>
Wy.; Green Bay, Wis.; Indianapolis; Lawrence, Mass.; Los Angeles;<br>
Lynn, Mass.; Miami; Orlando, Fla.; Milwaukee; Palm Beach, Fla.;<br>
Panama City, Fla.; Pensacola, Fla.; Peoria, Ill.; Philadelphia;<br>
Portland, Ore.; Roanoke, Va.; St. Joe, Fla.; St. Louis; San<br>
Francisco; Sante Fe, N.M.; Seattle; Sheridan, Wy.; Springfield,<br>
Ill.; Tampa, Fla.; Vallejo, Calif.; Washington, D.C.; Wichita;<br>
Worcester, Mass.</p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="/publ/publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
