<head>
<title>PR 09/12/96 Backers of strawberry workers speak up</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>For information: Richard Greer, AFL-CIO, 202-637-5279<br>
Marc Grossman, UFW, 916-441-0766<br>
Jocelyn Sherman, UFW, 408-763-4820<br>
Or your local Central Labor Council<br>
<br>
NEWS MEDIA ADVISORY<br>
TO ASSIGNMENT EDITORS, LABOR AND AGRICULTURE REPORTERS<br>
<br>
Backers of strawberry workers speak up<br>
Thousands to march, supporters on the move in dozens of cities<br>
Their question: &quot;Is 5 cents for fairness too much to ask?&quot;<br>
<br>
Washington, Sept. 12, 1996 -- Thousands of workers and their<br>
supporters will speak up for struggling California strawberry<br>
pickers Sunday and Monday.<br>
<br>
On Sunday, several thousand workers are expected to march in<br>
Watsonville, Calif., the heart of strawberry country.<br>
<br>
On Monday, hundreds of supporters in hometowns from Alaska to<br>
Alabama will be on the move. They'll visit supermarkets across the<br>
nation and ask store managers to tell the California strawberry<br>
industry they support better conditions for the workers. In<br>
Richmond, they'll deliver fresh drinking water to grocery customers<br>
to draw attention to the conditions of field workers. In Los<br>
Angeles, city council members will back the workers.<br>
<br>
Strawberry pickers, who are trying to organize with the United<br>
Farm Workers, earn an average of $8,000 a year. According to a<br>
California study, doubling their pay rates would cost<br>
the $650-million-a-year industry only 5 cents per pint of berries.<br>
<br>
The pickers work in pesticide-treated fields for as many as 12<br>
hours a day. Workers face on-the-spot firings, sexual harassment<br>
and the lack of clean drinking water and health insurance.<br>
<br>
As part of one of the largest union organizing campaigns in<br>
the country, the workers are struggling for five basic rights:<br>
* A living wage<br>
* Protection from arbitrary firings and rewards for their<br>
years of loyalty<br>
* Clean drinking water and bathrooms in the fields<br>
* Health insurance<br>
* An end to sexual harassment in the fields.<br>
<br>
Among the locations where activities will occur:<br>
Albany, Ga.<br>
Albany, N.Y.<br>
Albuquerque, N.M.<br>
Anchorage, Alaska<br>
Annandale, Va.<br>
Atlanta<br>
Baltimore<br>
Birmingham, Ala.<br>
Boston<br>
Boulder, Colo.<br>
Casper, Wyo.<br>
Cheyenne, Wyo.<br>
Denver<br>
Detroit<br>
Fairbanks, Alaska<br>
Foster City, Calif.<br>
Gillette, Wyo.<br>
Green Bay, Wis.<br>
Lawrence, Mass.<br>
Los Angeles<br>
Lynn, Mass.<br>
Miami<br>
Orlando, Fla.<br>
Palm Beach, Fla.<br>
Panama City, Fla.<br>
Pensacola, Fla.<br>
Philadelphia<br>
Portland, Ore.<br>
Richmond, Va.<br>
Roanoke, Va.<br>
Salt Lake City<br>
San Francisco<br>
Sante Fe, N.M.<br>
Seattle <br>
Sheridan, Wyo.<br>
St. Louis, Mo.<br>
Tampa, Fla.<br>
Vallejo, Calif.<br>
Washington, D.C.<br>
Wichita, Kan.<br>
Worcester, Mass.</p>
