<head>
<title>PR 09/05/961 Clinton's Health Care</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE                            For information:<br>
                                     Denise Mitchell 202/637-5340<br>
<br>
                    Statement by John Sweeney<br>
                        AFL-CIO President<br>
          on President Clinton's Health Care Initiative<br>
<br>
President Clinton's decision to create a national commission on<br>
health care quality is good news for health care consumers. It is<br>
a concrete step that, by protecting consumers in the often<br>
confusing and coercive health care situation of today, should<br>
lessen their anxiety and make their lives a little easier.<br>
<br>
Like the health care legislation signed by the president last<br>
month, this action is a modest but meaningful step that carries<br>
through on a significant part of the president's health care reform<br>
initiative of 1993, consumer protection.<br>
<br>
For average wage workers and their families, like the 40 million<br>
plus whose health benefits are bargained by the unions of the<br>
AFL-CIO, it is a welcome step by their government.</p>
