<title>PR 09/05/962 Family Agenda</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<p>MEDIA ADVISORY For information:<br>
TO ASSIGNMENT EDITORS, REPORTERS Richard Greer, 202-637-5279<br>
Deborah Dion, 202-637-5036<br>
Deborah Sedillo Dugan, 202-637-5365<br>
<br>
AFL-CIO OFFICERS TO KEEP PUSHING WORKING FAMILY AGENDA<br>
They'll fan out into communities in post Labor Day sprint<br>
New York march Saturday<br>
<br>
Washington, Sept. 5, 1996 -- AFL-CIO President John J. Sweeney
and<br>
federation Executive Vice President Linda Chavez-Thompson will
lead<br>
workers at the New York City Labor Day parade Saturday.<br>
The parade, which was changed to the Saturday after Labor Day,<br>
is expected to attract thousands of workers.<br>
After a successful summer that culminated with workers' issues<br>
in the forefront at the Democratic National Convention, AFL-CIO<br>
officers plan to move out into communities around the nation.
They<br>
will be speaking up for workers in organizing campaigns and<br>
strikes, and ont he political and legislative front.<br>
Officers will continue to expose the extreme right wing that<br>
dominates Congress and encourage workers to vote in November.<br>
Here are some other events the week of Sept. 9 and Sept. 16:<br>
* The Trade Union Congress of Great Britain is eager to<br>
hear about the new AFL-CIO. Secretary-Treasurer Richard Trumka
will<br>
meet with delegates to the Congress during the week. On Monday,<br>
Sweeney will address the New York State AFL-CIO. On Sept. 12,<br>
Trumka will address the International Brotherhood of Electrical<br>
Workers in Philadelphia. On Sept. 13, Chavez-Thompson will speak
to<br>
workers at the Frontier Hotel in Las Vegas. The workers will have<br>
been on strike for five years as of Sept. 21. On Sept. 14,
Chavez-<br>
Thompson will meet with the United Food and Commercial Workers<br>
Women's network conference in Las Vegas.<br>
* On Sept. 16, Sweeney will speak to the Graphic<br>
Communications International Union convention in Anaheim, Calif.
On<br>
Sept. 17, Sweeney will address the United Paperworkers<br>
International Union convention in Las Vegas, and on Sept. 19,<br>
Sweeney will speak to the International Brotherhood of Electrical<br>
Workers Union convention in Philadelphia.</p>
