<html>

<head>
<title>PR 08/29/96 AFL-CIO Releases New TV and Radio Ads</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<pre>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE: Wednesday, August 28, 1996

For more information:  Deborah Dion, 202-637-5036
</pre>
<h2 align=center>AFL-CIO RELEASES NEW TV AND RADIO ADS<br>
AIMED AT 27 MEMBERS OF CONGRESS<br>
WHO VOTED TO SLASH MEDICARE</h2>
<h3 align=center>New commercials take issue with Republican leaders' false<br>
claims on Medicare votes </h3>
<p>CHICAGO, August 28 -- New television and radio commercials produced by the AFL-CIO 
issuing stern warnings to members of Congress who voted to slash Medicare -- and who are now 
denying it -- will begin airing in 27 cities around the country today. Released this morning at a press 
briefing in Chicago, the new spots call on 27 House Republicans to change their votes and protect 
Medicare in upcoming budget deliberations. </p>
<p>&quot;We're running the spots at this time because the Republicans in Congress are running shamefully 
dishonest television commercials around the country falsely claiming Medicare benefits would 
increase under their proposals,&quot; said AFL-CIO President John J. Sweeney, &quot;and because another 
key Medicare vote may come up this Fall.&quot; </p>
<p>Last November, every House Republican but one voted for budget proposals that would have cut 
$270 billion out of Medicare over the next seven years. By allowing Medicare funding to fall well 
below increases in healthcare costs and the eligible population, the Republican budget would have 
cost the average Medicare recipient an additional $400 in premiums in the year 2002. </p>
<p>&quot;It's pretty scary when you remember that this budget also included a tax cut primarily benefiting the 
rich and big corporations,&quot; Sweeney said. &quot;And it all would have become law had it not been 
greeted by massive public opposition -- generated in large part by an all-out AFL-CIO campaign 
-- and a veto by President Clinton.&quot; </p>
<p>The new ads were produce din response to a recent series of Republican-sponsored commercials 
claiming that Republicans in Congress are trying to &quot;save&quot; Medicare and that they had actually 
voted to increase Medicare benefits. They ask voters to call their representatives in Congress and 
tell him or her &quot;we know the truth about his/her vote to cut our Medicare benefits. Another vote is 
coming. This time, we'll be watching.&quot; </p>
<p>The ads are part of a campaign launched by AFL-CIO unions this year to educate and mobilize 
working families around issues such as Medicare, pensions, and the minimum wage. The campaign, 
which involves grass-roots mobilization as well as television and radio advertising, was funded in 
March when AFL-CIO unions voted to allocate 15 cents per member per month from existing 
resources to the effort. </p>
<p>Ever since, Republican leaders in Congress in partnership with business interest groups have 
retaliated by inundating TV and radio stations with intimidating letters and phone calls threatening 
legal action, and by intensifying a coordinated disinformation campaign falsely charging the 
AFL-CIO with acting illegally and against the wishes of its members. </p>
<p>Contrary to Republican allegations, recent polls show that union members support the AFL-CIO 
education campaign by a more than six to one margin. &quot;Members want their unions to represent 
their interests in the political and legislative arenas,&quot; said Geoff Garin of Peter D. Hart Research 
Associates, who conducted a poll of union members in early August. </p>
<p>&quot;Our campaign is about issues that matter to working families,&quot; said Sweeney. &quot;It's not about 
Democrats or Republicans. It's about fair wages, health care, retirement security and education. 
And it's about holding elected leaders accountable to the women and men who put them in office.&quot; </p>
<p>&quot;And it's working,&quot; he added. &quot;As an example, we were a major factor in the recent passage of the 
minimum wage increase. We ran extensive ads, and in the end, half of the members of Congress we 
named in the ad voted for the increase.&quot; </p>
<p>To help bring declining living standards into the forefront of the national agenda, the AFL-CIO 
conducted 30 &quot;America Needs A Raise&quot; town hall hearings around the country this spring. In 
addition, Sweeney, who will speak before the democratic convention later this evening, recently 
authored a new book called America Needs A Raise published by Houghton Mifflin for release on 
Labor Day. </p>
<p>The AFL-CIO is the nation's umbrella labor organization, representing 13.1 million union members 
nationwide.</p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="/publ/publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
