<html>
<head>
<title>PR 08/28/96 Labor Day Statement</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<p>LABOR DAY STATEMENT BY THE AFL-CIO<br>
John J. Sweeney, President<br>
Richard Trumka, Secretary-Treasurer<br>
Linda Chavez-Thompson, Executive Vice President<br>
August 29, 1996<br>
<br>
Working families and their unions celebrate Labor Day 1996<br>
with less money in their paychecks and less faith in their<br>
employers and their government, but more determined than ever to<br>
make America work for people who work.<br>
<br>
Our rebounding economy presents a cruel paradox; corporate<br>
profits are up, the stock market is up, executive compensation is<br>
way up, but the wages of millions of workers are not. Over the
past<br>
20 years, American workers rose to the challenge of global<br>
competition and increased our productivity 24 percent. But it<br>
didn't help the workers -- real wages went down 15 percent.<br>
<br>
To meet the challenge of decreasing incomes, more family<br>
members are going to work. Parents are working longer hours and<br>
worrying constantly about choosing between their work and their<br>
families. With employers downsizing, outsourcing, cutting
benefits<br>
and raiding pension funds, workers are angry and anxious.<br>
<br>
They are not, however, plunging into pits of apathy or fits of<br>
apoplexy. They're getting involved in unions and in politics as<br>
they haven't in years, and they are changing the way America
works.<br>
<br>
The victories on the picket lines have been stunning: 25,000<br>
machinists talking Boeing to the ground, 12,000 supermarket<br>
butchers and clerks stamping Safeway's ticket, 5,000 janitors<br>
cleaning up in San Jose, and 35,000 telephone workers taking Bell<br>
Atlantic to the bank without a strike.<br>
<br>
We're also winning again in Washington. By speaking out<br>
forcefully, and with President Bill Clinton backing us up, we<br>
canceled the &quot;Contract on America,&quot; passed a minimum
wage increase<br>
no one thought would even come to a vote, and forced the radical<br>
right to abandon a play to pay for tax breaks for the rich with<br>
massive cuts in Medicare, Medicaid, college loans, and<br>
environmental protections.<br>
<br>
With working families hurting as never before, our unions are<br>
responding as never before. We had an inspiring &quot;Union
Summer,&quot; as<br>
1,500 young students and workers took our message into organizing<br>
campaigns around the country. And the 30 town hall meetings we<br>
sponsored drew thousands of workers eager to proclaim
&quot;America<br>
Needs a Raise&quot; and put working family needs at the top of
the<br>
national agenda.<br>
<br>
This Labor Day, working Americans are looking to their unions<br>
to be a bigger force, to fiercely champion their values and their<br>
interests. They want us to get after the greedy corporations who<br>
force them to choose between being underpaid and unemployed. They<br>
want us to help them support politicians who will listen to them<br>
and their concerns. And they want us to build an economy that
works<br>
for everyone and not just the rich.<br>
<br>
As First Lady Hillary Clinton says, &quot;it takes a village to<br>
raise a child.&quot; American workers are rediscovering that it
takes a<br>
union to get a raise.<br>
<br>
For more information : Deborah Dion, 312-819-9356 or 202-637-<br>
5036.</p>
