<head>
<title>PR 08/26/961 Organizing</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<p>For information: Richard Greer, 202-637-5279<br>
<br>
<br>
MEDIA ADVISORY TO ASSIGNMENT EDITORS, REPORTERS<br>
FOR LABOR DAY <br>
<br>
ORGANIZING, MOBILIZING AND REAWAKENING HOPE<br>
Some items to consider in Labor Day coverage<br>
<br>
What has changed in a year in organized labor? American<br>
workers and their unions are starting to win again. <br>
From the successful push for a higher minimum wage to<br>
contract wins covering thousands of workers, the benchmark of<br>
what is possible has risen.<br>
John J. Sweeney won the AFL-CIO presidency on Oct. 25, 1995<br>
in the federation_s first contested election with a series of<br>
promises: massive restructuring of the federation; organizing new<br>
members at an unprecedented pace; a labor leadership that looks<br>
more like America_s work force, and a movement that speaks out<br>
for working families.<br>
To be sure, American workers are still struggling. In<br>
Detroit, newspaper workers, on strike for more than a year, need<br>
a contract. Hundreds of Bridgestone-Firestone workers are still<br>
waiting to get back the jobs the company took from them when they<br>
went on strike. For most employees real wages continue to<br>
stagnate, while bank accounts for the rich are bloated. <br>
But, after decades of decline in organized labor, many would<br>
say those conditions now inspire mobilization, not<br>
demoralization.<br>
As you prepare stories for Labor Day, here are some ideas<br>
and themes you may want to consider:<br>
<br>
* Labor has a new face, one that more closely resembles the<br>
backgrounds of the fastest growing segments of the work force. Of<br>
51 AFL-CIO vice presidents, 14 are women or people of color. A<br>
woman and a Hispanic -- Linda Chavez-Thompson -- is executive<br>
vice president.<br>
<br>
* The federation has recruited the best and the brightest,<br>
from Karen Nussbaum, who left the U.S. Labor Department to head a<br>
new working women_s effort in the labor movement, to David Chu,<br>
one of the country_s top researchers, who will lead strategic<br>
research.<br>
<br>
* Organizing new workers is the top priority. Funding for<br>
the Organizing Institute, known for turning out aggressive,<br>
enthusiastic organizers, has increased. The federation funded a<br>
new Organizing Department with $20 million. The initiatives are<br>
bearing fruit -- for example, the AFL-CIO and the United Farm <br>
Workers have begun the largest current organizing drive in the<br>
U.S., aiming to improve the lives of 20,000 strawberry workers.<br>
<br>
* The change in the AFL-CIO has rippled throughout the labor<br>
movement. Contract battles that not long ago might never been<br>
fought are being won. The word concessions isn_t in the contract<br>
for 35,000 Boeing workers -- their strike won improved pay and<br>
benefits, and job protections.<br>
<br>
* Aiming to transform the AFL-CIO from a Washington-based<br>
institution to a grassroots movement, the federation is<br>
revitalizing the country_s more than 600 central labor councils<br>
and training hundreds of community activists. Their role is <br>
becoming instrumental in organizing and political activism.<br>
<br>
* In the America Needs a Raise campaign, the federation held<br>
hearings in 30 cities, bringing to the forefront the anxieties<br>
and anger of working Americans. To further communicate their<br>
fears and show that the labor movement offers solutions, the<br>
federation president has penned a book, _America Needs a Raise._<br>
It will be released by Houghton Mifflin on Labor Day.<br>
<br>
* By becoming a voice for working families, the AFL-CIO has<br>
unleashed long-sleeping power. With targeted broadcast<br>
advertisements through its information departments, the<br>
federation has helped lead the fight against cuts in Medicare<br>
and Medicaid and the battle to raise the minimum wage.<br>
<br>
* Concrete change is leading to real change in the way<br>
Americans view organized labor. About 62 percent of Americans<br>
have a positive view of unions, according to a July Newsweek<br>
poll. More importantly, young people are even more positive -- 68<br>
percent are open to unions.<br>
<br>
<br>
TRANSFORMING AN INSTITUTION<br>
When the first new leadership in 17 years arrived at AFL-CIO<br>
headquarters last October, the infrastructure was antiquated.<br>
Computer systems, for example, were operating on outdated<br>
software that stymied internal communication.<br>
Things are getting in line. Federation officials believe the<br>
AFL-CIO is well on its way to becoming what they envisioned: an<br>
agile fighting machine for working families. Labor_s new faces<br>
are key to the massive restructuring of the AFL-CIO that will<br>
change its direction and build a vital force to represent<br>
America_s workers.<br>
In addition to leaders like Chavez-Thompson, others have<br>
joined the federation leadership. William Lucy, a top AFSCME<br>
officer and leader of the Coalition of Black Trade Unionists, is<br>
now a vice president. So is Arturo S. Rodriguez, president of the<br>
revitalized United Farm Workers.<br>
Nussbaum isn_t the only key Clinton administration official<br>
lured to the movement. Steve Rosenthal, former associate deputy<br>
secretary at the U.S. Labor Department, was attracted as the<br>
federation_s political director.<br>
A new Corporate Affairs Department, designed to fight bad<br>
employers in boardrooms as well as the streets, is gearing up<br>
under Ron Blackwell, former chief economist for UNITE! David Chu,<br>
one of the top researchers in the country, will soon direct the<br>
Strategic Research division of the Corporate Affairs department.<br>
Bill Patterson, the top union activist on using the power of<br>
pensions and stock ownership for the good of working people, will<br>
lead the Center for Worker Ownership and Governance. Nancy Mills,<br>
who headed a large health care local union, is acting as head of<br>
a new Center for Workplace Democracy in the Corporate Affairs<br>
Department. <br>
The International Affairs unit is shifting toward<br>
representing workers in a global economy and protecting worker<br>
rights in trade agreements. Barbara Shailor, a top aide at the<br>
International Association of Machinists, has joined the<br>
federation staff as International Affairs director.<br>
New General Counsel Jonathan Hiatt is focusing the Legal<br>
Department on pro-active legal strategies to aid organizing and<br>
bargaining, rather than appellate litigation.<br>
The federation_s new Organizing Department is up and running<br>
under Richard Bensinger, the former director of the Organizing<br>
Institute.<br>
The Public Affairs Department has shifted to pro-active<br>
outreach under a new assistant to the president, Denise Mitchell.<br>
Field offices are focusing on organizing and building<br>
community alliances under the director of Field Mobilization,<br>
Marilyn Sneiderman. The number of field offices have been reduced<br>
from 12 to four, while a coordinator if being placed in every<br>
state.<br>
The Education Department has launched a new program of<br>
economics education under a new director, Bill Fletcher, and<br>
assistant to the president, Robert Pleasure.<br>
<br>
ORGANIZING TO SPREAD THE BENEFITS OF THE UNION MOVEMENT<br>
Organizing unorganized workers is the top and most urgent<br>
priority of the new AFL-CIO.<br>
To prepare the field for organizing and sustain hope in the<br>
years to come, 1,500 young people participated in Union Summer.<br>
As labor movement interns, they worked on organizing campaigns<br>
from California to South Carolina and 20 cities in between. They<br>
offered a new perspective to the labor movement and many will be<br>
back, in the trenches for future generations of workers.<br>
Expectations for Union Summer were surpassed. More than<br>
3,000 people from 45 states applied for the internships.<br>
In a few short months, the interns have had some remarkable<br>
achievements. In Los Angeles, they helped restaurant workers win<br>
union recognition. In Michigan, they helped drug store workers<br>
win a union contract. In St. Louis, they helped put a living wage<br>
referendum on the ballot.<br>
In their first two months, the interns distributed more than<br>
150,000 leaflets, made about 5,000 visits to workers in their<br>
homes, visited 1,500 work sites, helped organize 235 protests and<br>
rallies and organized workers who speak 10 languages, from<br>
Spanish to Tagalog.<br>
Their enthusiasm is vital in the current political and legal<br>
environment that aims to thwart workers at nearly every turn.<br>
Gains in the past year are real, but many battles are just<br>
beginning.<br>
The AFL-CIO, with its new Organizing Department, and the<br>
United Farm Workers have mounted the largest organizing campaign<br>
in the U.S. today. Together, they will bring the benefits of a<br>
union to as many as 20,000 strawberry workers in California.<br>
It is a David and Goliath struggle. The workers are poor,<br>
earning an average of $8,000 a year for 10, 11 and 12 hour<br>
workdays without basic dignity. The industry is rich, with a near<br>
lock on the $650 million-a-year business. The campaign is moving<br>
into high gear this month.<br>
Joint strategic organizing campaigns planned for the coming<br>
months will cut across entire industries, such as health care,<br>
and regions, such as the South. They will present a united front<br>
of affiliated unions, the AFL-CIO and allies from other<br>
progressive groups. They will be supported by a multi-million<br>
dollar organizing fund.<br>
Not all will be joint projects. Affiliated unions have<br>
begun more organizing work on their own. For example, UNITE! aims<br>
to organize thousands of nursing home workers in Florida. The<br>
United Food and Commercial Workers and the Service Employees<br>
International Union are doing the same throughout the country.<br>
<br>
<br>
REAWAKENING A VOICE<br>
Mobilizing working people like never before has paid off.<br>
Central Labor Councils across the country are being<br>
strengthened and organized to build grassroots campaigns<br>
politically, and in organizing drives, such as the one among<br>
strawberry workers.<br>
Unions are regaining confidence at the bargaining table. In<br>
addition to the Boeing workers, more than 100,000 rail workers<br>
won contracts this month that increase pay, improve benefits and<br>
protect jobs. It is the first time in a decade that a national<br>
rail agreement has been reached without a strike or government<br>
interference. The unions succeeded because they were unified and<br>
the AFL-CIO was behind them.<br>
The America Needs a Raise campaign sponsored 30 town hall<br>
meetings across the nation. The hearings gave workers, whether<br>
they made the minimum wage or were well-paid, a chance to speak.<br>
Those who testified ranged from established families in Chicago<br>
to immigrants in Los Angeles, from flight attendants in Atlanta<br>
to a construction company executive in New York.<br>
Labor spoke up politically, as well, and did it loudly.<br>
Before the right wing Congress elected in 1994 could<br>
dismantle a half-century of social advancement, the AFL-CIO<br>
unleashed the power of its base. Much to the credit of labor,<br>
anti-worker and anti-family legislation failed.<br>
Among labor_s successes are beating back the TEAM Act,<br>
helping enact a minimum wage increase, exposing right-wing plans<br>
to cripple Medicare and Medicaid, enact education cuts, and<br>
telling Americans about a plan to let corporations raid the<br>
country_s pension plans. The federation stopped efforts to gut<br>
OSHA, defeated national _right-to-work_ legislation and beat back<br>
efforts to undermine wage standards and overtime protections.<br>
Newt Gingrich and his gang have been put on the defensive.<br>
Labor accomplished its legislative successes through<br>
effective media campaigns, inspiring members to speak out, and<br>
by raising issues important to working families independent of<br>
candidates and holding candidates accountable on those issues.<br>
The political front continues with this fall_s elections.<br>
The union movement has put 131 coordinators in 86 Congressional<br>
districts, is training 2,500 activists and recruiting more than<br>
10,000 union members to volunteer on political campaigns.<br>
<br>
(For more extensive fact sheets or assistance in setting up<br>
interviews, contact Richard Greer, 202-637-5279.)</p>
