<head>
<title>PR 08/21/96 Health Care Bill</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<p>For Immediate Release For information:<br>
August 21, 1996 David Saltz 202-637-5318<br>
<br>
<br>
Statement by<br>
AFL-CIO President John J. Sweeney<br>
on the Signing into Law of the<br>
Kennedy-Kassebaum Health Care Bill<br>
<br>
The AFL-CIO applauds President Clinton's signing into law the<br>
Health Care Availability and Affordability Act, also known as the<br>
Kennedy-Kassebaum health care bill. At a time when far too many<br>
Americans do not have health care insurance and even those who do<br>
are worried about losing that coverage when they change or lose<br>
their job, this is a step in the right direction.<br>
<br>
While this legislation does not address the still serious and<br>
unmet need for broad health care reform, it has achieved what<br>
appears to be possible to accomplish in this Congress -- it<br>
provides insurance portability, a much needed remedy to the
problem<br>
of insurance loss that too often comes with a job change or<br>
unemployment. The Kennedy-Kassebaum bill also makes important<br>
progress in addressing the problems of Americans who have been<br>
excluded from coverage because of pre-existing conditions.<br>
<br>
We regret that the law that is being signed today includes<br>
provisions for 750,000 families to enroll in Medical Savings<br>
Accounts, but we suspect that this experiment will only validate<br>
concerns that MSAs will be used primarily by the wealthy and the<br>
healthy to the disadvantage of the overall insurance system.<br>
<br>
It is our fervent hope that, with a Congress more sympathetic<br>
to the needs of working families, this new law will be the<br>
foundation for additional reform in the areas of quality, access<br>
and affordability.</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../index.htm">Public Documents Page</a> | <a
href="../publsear.htm">Public Documents Search</a></p>
