<head>
<title>PR 08/20/96 Minimum Wage</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<p>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE For information, contact:<br>
August 20, 1996 David Saltz 202-637-5318<br>
Deborah Dion 202-637-5036<br>
<br>
<br>
Statement by<br>
AFL-CIO President John J. Sweeney<br>
on the Signing Into Law of the Minimum Wage Increase<br>
<br>
President Clinton's signing of this fair increase in the minimum<br>
wage is a victory for America's working families, both for those<br>
who depend upon it to survive and for those who kept the pressure<br>
on the Gingrich/Dole Congress until the Republican leadership was<br>
forced to do the right thing and finally bring it up for a vote.<br>
<br>
This modest increase in the minimum wage is a small, but<br>
important step in our nation beginning to address the wealth and<br>
wage gap that increasingly divides us into two societies -- the<br>
privileged few and the rest of us. We cannot continue down that<br>
path and remain a healthy society.<br>
<br>
The minimum wage is not a poverty program. It is intended to<br>
establish a wage floor so that a person working full time, year<br>
round, can achieve and maintain a minimal decent standard of<br>
living. This overdue increase -- 90 cents an hour over two years
--<br>
will help lift the lives of the more than 11 million Americans
who<br>
currently earn less than $5.15 an hour. This is a raise they've<br>
earned, their employers can afford and the American people<br>
overwhelmingly support.</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../index.htm">Public Documents Page</a> | <a
href="../publsear.htm">Public Documents Search</a></p>
