<head>
<title>PR 07/11/96 Hearing on Union Activities</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<pre>July 11, 1996                          For Information: David Saltz: 202-637-5318
For Immediate Release                  Deborah Dion: 202-637-5036
</pre>
<h2 align="center">Statement by AFL-CIO President John J. Sweeney<br>
on the </h2>
<h1 align="center">Subcommittee on Human Resources and
Intergovernmental Relations<br>
Hearing on Union Activities</h1>
<p>This week, the Gingrich House Republican campaign against the
interests of working families moves to a new stage: show trials
at taxpayer expense. </p>
<p>Today's hearing is part of an organized smear campaign against
union leaders by the House Republican leadership -- an attempt to
divert public attention away from their core agenda: cutting
Medicare, tax cuts for the wealthy, and reduced environmental and
workplace safety protection. </p>
<p>This hearing isn't legitimate legislative activity. It's a
naked political payback to punish America's unions for telling it
like it is on Medicare, tax cuts for the rich and the minimum
wage. We've stood up to bullies before -- and we will again. This
kind of harassment won't fool the public and will only make us
more active in shining a light on congressional attacks against
working families. </p>
<p>Subcommittee Chairman Chris Shays of Connecticut is using
taxpayer money to attack unions, in contrast to our use of
private money to protest their cuts in Medicare, worker safety
and college loans. </p>
<p>If anyone's ethics should be investigated, it's the Republican
leadership's. While the AFL-CIO has run a fully public issues
education campaign on how Congress is performing on the issues
that matter most to working families, the Republican House
leadership has unleashed a private vendetta campaign against
America's unions -- an abuse of Congressional power at taxpayer
expense.</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../index.htm">Public Documents Page</a> | <a
href="../publsear.htm">Public Documents Search</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
</body>
</html>
