<head>
<title>PR 07/08/96 Team Act and Right-To-Work</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<pre>Media Advisory                          For Information:   David Saltz 202-637-5318
July 8, 1996                            Deborah Dion 202-637-5036
</pre>
<h1 align="center">More than 1,000 Rank-and-File Union Members<br>
Expected At U.S. Capitol on Tuesday and Wednesday </h1>
<h2>Workers Coming To Tell Their Senators:<br>
Pass A Clean Minimum Wage Increase;<br>
Vote No on Team Act and Right-To-Work</h2>
<p>WASHINGTON--More than 1,000 union members from around the
country will come to Washington, Tuesday, July 9, and Wednesday,
July 10, to urge their senators to pass a clean minimum wage
increase and to defeat the so-called Team Act and a national
right-to-work bill. </p>
<p>The two days' grassroots lobbying activities will begin
Tuesday at 11 a.m., when the members of a dozen different unions
take part in a minimum-wage press conference and rally led by
Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle and Sen. Edward Kennedy on the
west steps of the Capitol. </p>
<p>After lobbying their home-state senators, union members will
join supporters for a minimum-wage vote watch in the Senate Labor
and Human Resources Committee Room, 430 Dirksen Senate Office
Building, where they will be available for interviews. </p>
<p>Lobbying activities will continue on Wednesday, as union
members urge their lawmakers to vote against the so-called Team
Act, which would take away workers' right to choose their own
representatives to deal with their employer; and against passage
of a national right-to-work bill that would undermine unions by
allowing employees to receive union representation, wages,
services and benefits without paying union dues.</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../index.htm">Public Documents Page</a> | <a
href="../publsear.htm">Public Documents Search</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
</body>
</html>
