<head>
<title>PR 06/28/96 Town hall meetings</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<p>AFL-CIO News -- June 28, 1996 </p>
<h1 align="center">Town hall meetings elevate debate on wages</h1>
<h2 align="center">By David Kameras</h2>
<p>The AFL-CIO completed a series of 29 town hall meetings with
another round of powerful testimony plainly showing the
challenges facing today's workers. </p>
<p>At the meeting in San Jose, Calif., Imelda, a Mexican
immigrant, told of how she once provided care for an 82-year-old
woman who lives by herself. But earning $4.25 an hour two hours a
day and being eight months pregnant, she had no one to attend to
her daughter and is now out of work. </p>
<p>&quot;When I used to take care of this woman, my work
reflected compassion and quality, but this doesn't seem to mean
anything in the labor market,&quot; she told the gathering, which
included AFL-CIO Executive Vice President Linda Chavez-Thompson. </p>
<p>Billie Anne Martin, a single mother now off welfare and
employed as a county eligibility worker, said one of her
paychecks goes for the rent, the rest to necessities, and even
that is threatened by Republican Gov. Pete Wilson's bill to
contract out government work. </p>
<p>&quot;The safety net of the American working class and the
meager benefits for the disadvantaged are being slowly carved
away,&quot; she said, noting that a local center that houses
disabled children is being closed by the year 2000. &quot;I'd
like to know where these children are going to go and what kind
of benefits they're going to receive.&quot; </p>
<p>&quot;When we see where CEO salaries in the last 15 years have
increased by 514 percent, and workers' wages haven't even kept
up, and with the average CEO of a Fortune 500 company now making
over 149 times what the average worker makes, I think it's time
to take from the hands of the greedy and put it back into the
hands of the needy,&quot; added Ray Biosa, a member of Service
Employees Local 715, which represents public workers in Santa
Clara County. </p>
<p>On June 12, Atlanta was burning again, this time with the
fires of indignation over lost jobs and frustrated dreams, as
Chavez-Thompson continued the federation's quest for more
evidence that America Needs A Raise to present to recalcitrant
lawmakers. </p>
<p>When Susan Clayton, a Flight Attendants local president,
joined now-grounded ValuJet Airlines, &quot;little did I know I
would end up a slave laborer, helping to line the pockets of
those people who started the airline with gold.&quot; </p>
<p>When not fired for union activities, workers, who were hired
through a temp agency owned by the CEO's daughter and ex-wife,
were forced to work excessive shifts for substandard pay and buy
uniforms from an owner's son-in-law, who &quot;stated we would
all be replaced with Coke machines and vending machines if he had
his choice,&quot; Clayton said. &quot;He said we can strike until
we starve.&quot; </p>
<p>&quot;Thank God for unions, because with the union, we're able
to fight back and work on getting a fair contract,&quot; she
said. </p>
<p>The Rev. Sandra Robinson, director of the Georgia Citizens
Coalition on Hunger, reminded the meeting that many of the people
on public assistance are workers, including &quot;single men who
have become homeless because they are being exploited by labor
pools, because they are being paid minimum wage, and then they're
being deducted for helmets, and deducted for boots, and deducted
for transportation, and deducted for a $2 baloney sandwich, and
then at the end of the day, they don't have enough to take care
of their own human needs.&quot; </p>
<p>At a June 13 meeting in Pittsburgh, AFL-CIO Secretary-
Treasurer Richard L. Trumka heard 51-year-old Sandra Israel tell
how her age prevents her from finding new employment after losing
her job of 15 years. &quot;I am a black American woman standing
here asking you to join in, that we don't have to take a
$5-an-hour job.&quot; </p>
<p>Bea Sutton is a licensed practical nurse who was permanently
replaced by a nursing-home facility operated by notoriously anti-
union Beverly Enterprises after protesting unfair labor
practices. </p>
<p>&quot;Fighting a large corporation like Beverly is really
tough, but we get more determined every day that we are going to
win,&quot; she said. &quot;This is not just a Beverly worker
fight. This is a fight to maintain the dignity, the rights and
the respect for all workers. We cannot allow the large
corporations to continue to put profits before people.&quot; </p>
<p>Tom Pegler stayed home for two years to take care of his
children so that his wife could get off welfare and go to school.
But then she became too ill to work, a child became ill as well,
and he went back to work double-time. &quot;It's very, very hard
to work two minimum-wage jobs and be able to be home with your
sick family,&quot; he noted. </p>
<p>&quot;The answer to low wages is high wages,&quot;
Steelworkers President George F. Becker said. &quot;So why don't
we have high wages? Well, when 85 percent of the work force in
America is unorganized, </p>
<p>85 percent of the wages and the salaries in America are
unilaterally set by companies whose best interest is to keep it
as low as the marketplace will allow it to be.&quot; </p>
<p>House Speaker Newt Gingrich (R-Ga.) and two Massachusetts GOP
congressmen were in Boston June 18 for a $1,000-a-plate dinner
with their corporate backers when the final town hall meeting was
being held there, and Trumka invited them &quot;to give up that
dinner and come to listen to Boston's working families'
struggles. This will enable you to take these stories back to
Congress before voting on more cuts in programs that hurt working
families to give another tax break to the rich and special
interests.&quot; </p>
<p>Had they attended, they would have heard from: </p>
<ul>
    <li>A Chinese immigrant who, after seven years of working
        12-hour days, six days a week in restaurants, now works
        in a community association trying to change working
        conditions. </li>
    <li>A 13-year transit worker who is the sole supporter for a
        disabled husband and three children, and two paychecks
        away from homelessness. </li>
    <li>A service worker who works up to seven days a week to
        raise her four children on $5.25 an hour. </li>
    <li>A Steelworker locked out of Commonwealth Gas for turning
        down a contract calling for more than 50 concessions
        dictated two weeks after $3 million was given to
        management personnel, made possible by a record $54
        million in profits. </li>
</ul>
<p>&quot;Unfortunately in our nation in recent years, we have
seen a split between the privileged and the rest of us,&quot;
said the Rev. Edward Boyd of the Boston Labor Guild. He called
for confronting the nation and its leadership &quot;to understand
what is at stake here -- not only bread on the table, but a
spiritual bread, that spirit of mutual concern and mutual sharing
that is at the heart of our life.&quot;</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../index.htm">Public Documents Page</a> | <a
href="../publsear.htm">Public Documents Search</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
</body>
