<head>
<title>PR 06/21/96 AFL-CIO supports Brazilian workers' strike</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<pre>PRESS ADVISORY                           FOR INFORMATION CONTACT:
FOR FRIDAY, JUNE 21                      Mark Anderson 202/637-5178
</pre>
<h2 align="center">AFL-CIO WILL JOIN IN SUPPORT OF<br>
BRAZILIAN WORKERS' GENERAL STRIKE </h2>
<p>On June 21, 1996, the AFL-CIO and affiliated unions will
demonstrate in solidarity with the general strike called for by
the three principal labor confederations of Brazil to protest the
anti- worker policies of the Brazilian government. Demonstrations
will be held at the Brazilian Embassy in Washington, D.C. from
noon to 1 p.m., the Brazilian consulates in Boston, Miami, Los
Angeles, and San Francisco and the Brazilian mission to the U.N.
in New York. </p>
<p>Brazilian workers are seeking fair wages, the establishment of
decent retirement benefits, a forty-hour work week, enforcement
of labor laws, job creation, fair wages, land reform, and social
and economic policies that protect workers. A recent Gallup poll
found 81 percent of Brazilians in support of this general strike. </p>
<p>Brazilian workers face the same attempts at out-sourcing and
privatization, downsizing, union-busting and downward pressure on
wages and working conditions that workers in the U.S. confront. </p>
<p>&quot;Just as American laws and lawmakers fail to protect
American workers' jobs, the Brazilian government pays only lip
service to current laws designed to provide workplace fairness in
Brazil. Brazilian workers need a raise, too,&quot; said AFL-CIO
President John J. Sweeney.</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../index.htm">Public Documents Page</a> | <a
href="../publsear.htm">Public Documents Search</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
</body>
