<title>PR 05/20/96 Minimum Wage Ad</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<pre>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE                 For Additional Information,
                                      CONTACT: David Saltz 202-637-5318 
</pre>
<h3 align="center">New poll finds 68 percent want a clean vote on
minimum wage now </h3>
<h1 align="center">Stop Voting To Block A Minimum-Wage Increase,<br>
AFL-CIO Ads Tell Congress This Week</h1>
<p>WASHINGTON, May 20--The AFL-CIO this week is airing two new
ads calling on Congress to increase the $4.25 minimum wage as
part of its expanding program to educate the public on key policy
issues. A vote could come this week. </p>
<p>The TV and radio ads begin running today in 27 districts where
House members have repeatedly voted to block a minimum-wage
increase. The ads cite members of Congress who have voted to
block increases as many as five times. They also contrast
skyrocketing corporate profits and executive salaries and the 30
percent raise Congress gave itself to the plight of working
families, who have lost ground since the last minimum-wage
increase five years ago. </p>
<p>&quot;We will continue to inform working families about what
Congress is doing about increasing the minimum wage and how they
can make their voices heard,&quot; said AFL-CIO President John J.
Sweeney. </p>
<p>Bolstering its efforts, the AFL-CIO pointed to a new Peter D.
Hart Research poll, conducted May 14-16, that found 68 percent
support for considering a minimum-wage increase with a
&quot;straight up-or-down vote now,&quot; compared to 26 percent
approval for &quot;consider later on as part of a larger
package.&quot; On the basic question of whether to increase the
minimum wage, 84 percent of Americans say yes, according to a
March CBS/New York Times poll. </p>
<p>The spots also call on members of Congress who &quot;voted to
cut Medicare and college loans, all to give a big tax break to
the rich,&quot; to &quot;stop playing political games and start
voting for working families for a change.&quot; </p>
<p>The ads will run in districts in California, Connecticut,
Georgia, Illinois, Indiana, Iowa, Kansas, Kentucky, Maine,
Michigan, Nebraska, North Carolina, Ohio, Oregon, Pennsylvania,
Tennessee, Washington and Wisconsin.</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../index.htm">Public Documents Page</a> | <a
href="../publsear.htm">Public Documents Search</a></p>
