<title>PR 04/30/96 Minimum Wage</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<pre>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE                 For Additional Information,
                                Contact: David Saltz 202-637-5318
</pre>
<h1 align="center">Vote Now To Raise the Minimum Wage,<br>
New AFL-CIO Ads Tell Congress </h1>
<p>WASHINGTON, April 30 -- The AFL-CIO this week is expanding its
program to educate union members and the public on key policy
issues with two new ads calling on Congress to vote immediately
to increase the $4.25-an-hour minimum wage. </p>
<p>The radio ads, scheduled to run today through Friday in 29
districts where House members recently voted twice to block
minimum-wage increases, pointedly note that corporate profits and
executive compensation &quot;have gone through the roof,&quot;
and members of Congress voted themselves a 30 percent pay raise,
while working families have lost ground since the last
minimum-wage increase, five years ago. </p>
<p>&quot;There is no excuse for any further delay. Congress
should act now and schedule a straight up-or-down vote to give
working families the raise they deserve and have earned,&quot;
said AFL-CIO President John J. Sweeney. &quot;The AFL-CIO will
continue to inform the American public about those members of
Congress who don't believe that working families deserve a living
wage.&quot; </p>
<p>Running in 21 states, the ads point out that these same
members of Congress twice voted to block minimum-wage increases
after they had voted to cut Medicare and college loans to give
tax cuts to corporations and the wealthy. The spots also note
that 84 percent of registered voters support raising the minimum
wage. </p>
<p>The spots close by urging viewers and listeners to call a
toll-free number and tell their member of Congress to &quot;stop
the games, stop the gimmicks, and raise the minimum wage.&quot; </p>
<p>Radio ads will run in districts in Arkansas, California,
Connecticut, Illinois, Indiana, Iowa, Kansas, Kentucky, Maine,
Maryland, Michigan, Mississippi, Nebraska, New York, New Jersey,
North Carolina, Ohio, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Washington and
Wisconsin.</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
