<title>PR 04/26/96 Job Safety</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<pre>REVISED
Media Advisory for                      For Information Contact:
Friday, April 26th                      Deborah Sedillo Dugan at 
                                        202-637-5365
</pre>
<h1 align="center">Gore, Reich, Sweeney and Workers<br>
Look At Job Safety 25 Years After Passage of OSHA<br>
At The Department of Labor </h1>
<p>In observance of the 25th anniversary of the Occupational
Safety &amp; Health Act, a Department of Labor ceremony with Vice
President Gore, AFL-CIO President John J. Sweeney, Secretary of
Labor Robert Reich, and injured workers and their family members
is scheduled for Friday, April 26, at 10 am at the Department of
Labor Auditorium, 200 Constitution Avenue, N.W. </p>
<p>Vice President Gore will issue a statement on the OSHA law and
will ask for a recommitment to safe jobs and to improve workplace
safety and health protections. President John J. Sweeney and two
workers will also make statements. </p>
<p>Worker Speakers: </p>
<p>James Duriett, a New York construction worker who fell off a
scaffold and suffered serious head and other injuries; and
Shirley Smith, a North Carolina poultry worker who suffers
repetitive strain injury. </p>
<p>Also: Official Release of AFL-CIO Report on 25 Year Health and
Safety Record </p>
<p>Since the passage of the OSHA law, the U.S. has made
significant progress in improving workplace safety, particularly
in industries where government enforcement and standards have
been focused. OSHA has passed standards to protect workers from
significant hazards such as confined spaces, asbestos and
bloodborne diseases. The agency has inspected millions of
workplaces and penalized employers who fail to comply with the
law. But last year alone, 6,588 workers lost their lives on the
job and an estimated 50,000 more died because of workplace
diseases. And some in Congress want to weaken job safety laws. </p>
<p>The anniversary of the Occupational Safety &amp; Health Act
coincides with the AFL-CIO's 8th annual Workers Memorial Day on
April 28, a day where workers and their unions remember
colleagues killed, injured or made ill on the job. Events are
scheduled in hundreds of communities.</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../index.htm">Public Documents Page</a> | <a
href="../publsear.htm">Public Documents Search</a></p>
