<title>PR 04/24/96 Health and Safety Report</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<pre>For Information Contact:			Deborah Sedillo Dugan at 202/637-5365
</pre>
<h1 align="center">AFL-CIO to Release Report Detailing 25 Years<br>
of Worker Safety and Health</h1>
<p>Washington, April 24 -- The AFL-CIO will release a new report
on the status of job safety 25 years after the enactment of the
Occupational Safety and Health Act during a 2 p.m. press briefing
Thursday, April 25, at its headquarters at 815 16th St. N.W. </p>
<p>The report documents the injury and fatality reductions that
have occurred since the OSHAct went into effect, shows which
industries have become safer under the law, details current
upward trends of injury rates and costs in some industries and
shows emerging problems. </p>
<p>It also shows that the nation's commitment to worker safety
and health pales in comparison with the commitment to protect the
environment and to address other public safety and health
concerns, while states' worker compensation systems remain
woefully inadequate. </p>
<p>The briefing marks the first event of nearly 200 planned in 37
states to mark the 8th annual commemoration of Workers Memorial
Day. Among other events, AFL-CIO President John J. Sweeney will
rally with workers in Milwaukee and Madison, Wis., on April 27,
Executive Vice President Linda Chavez-Thompson will join workers
in Alton, Ill., and St. Louis for a service on April 28 and
Secretary- Treasurer Richard L. Trumka will address a Los Angeles
breakfast April 29.</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../index.htm">Public Documents Page</a> | <a
href="../publsear.htm">Public Documents Search</a></p>
