<head>
<title>PR 04/23/96 Workers Memorial Day</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<pre>For Immediate Release                    For Information Contact:
                                         Deborah Sedillo Dugan at 202/637-5365
</pre>
<h1 align="center">Workers To Mark 8th Workers Memorial Day </h1>
<p>Washington, April 23 -- Workers and their unions are preparing
to mark the 8th annual Workers Memorial Day on April 28 in memory
of colleagues killed, injured or made ill on the job. Events are
scheduled in hundreds of communities and workplaces across the
country. </p>
<p>Workers will call on their employers and congressional
representatives to sign a pledge for safe jobs and to denounce
bills pending in Congress that would weaken the OSHA law. </p>
<p>This year's observances also mark the 25th anniversary of the
Occupational Safety and Health Act, the nation's promise to
workers of safe jobs. A White House ceremony is scheduled for
Friday, April 26, hailing the anniversary, and will include the
participation of injured workers and their family members from
around the United States. </p>
<p>Close to 200 events in some 37 states will range from the
Festival of American Dreams in Columbus, Ga., the dedication of a
memorial in Groton, Conn., tree plantings in Lafayette, Ind., and
the unveiling of a statue of a worker cradling a co-worker in
Tacoma, Wash. </p>
<p>Other events planned in conjunction with Workers Memorial Day
include: </p>
<ul>
    <li>April 25 -- The AFL-CIO will release a report detailing
        the state of job safety protections 25 years after the
        OSHAct went into effect. </li>
    <li>April 27 -- AFL-CIO President John J. Sweeney joins
        activists in Milwaukee and Madison, Wis., for rallies to
        show support for strong safety and health laws and
        ceremonies to honor fallen workers. </li>
    <li>April 28 -- AFL-CIO Executive Vice President Linda
        Chavez- Thompson joins workers in Alton, Ill., and St.
        Louis for a religious service, motorcade and memorial
        service along the Mississippi River. </li>
    <li>April 29 -- AFL-CIO Secretary-Treasurer Richard L. Trumka
        addresses a memorial breakfast in Los Angeles to remember
        workers killed or injured on the job. </li>
</ul>
<p>Workers in more than 30 countries also will mark April 28 as
an international day of mourning for workers killed and injured
on the job.</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../index.htm">Public Documents Page</a> | <a
href="../publsear.htm">Public Documents Search</a></p>
