<head>
<title>PR 04/17/96 Sweeney To Congress: Vote Now to Increase Minimum Wage</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<pre>For Immediate Release         For Additional Information Contact:
                              David Saltz at (202)637-5318
               
</pre>
<h1 align=center>AFL-CIO President John J. Sweeney To 
Congress:<br>
Vote Now to Increase Minimum Wage </h1>
<p>WASHINGTON, April 17--This afternoon, AFL-CIO President John J. Sweeney sent a letter to 
all members of the U.S House and Senate urging Congress to vote without delay for a 
long-overdue raise for America's minimum-wage workers. </p>
<p>Earlier today, 14 House Republicans introduced a bill that would increase the minimum wage to 
$5.25 an hour over the next two years. This action came two days after the AFL-CIO finished 
airing a wave of radio and TV ads in 30 House districts highlighting a March 28 House vote against 
considering a minimum wage increase. </p>
<p>&quot;The AFL-CIO intends to make the stagnation of wages for America's workers, particularly 
minimum-wage workers, an issue that cannot be ignored,&quot; Sweeney wrote the lawmakers. </p>
<p>&quot;There should be no more delay. Congress needs to act now without the procedural maneuvers 
that have kept working Americans from getting the raise they deserve and have earned. </p>
<p>&quot;In light of today's action in the House, combined with the clear 55-vote majority in the Senate in 
support of a minimum wage increase, it is incumbent on every member of this Congress who 
supports American working families to insist your leadership schedule a floor debate and final 
legislative action on this issue.&quot; </p>
<p>April 17, 1996 </p>
<p>Dear Representative: </p>
<p>The AFL-CIO urges Congress to vote now to increase the minimum wage. There should be no 
more delay. It is clear that there is an emerging bi-partisan majority in the house for such an 
increase and there is already a 55-vote majority in the Senate. It is now time to pass legislation that 
will provide some relief to America's lowest-paid workers. </p>
<p>The minimum wage workforce is largely adult and comprised mostly of women, minorities and 
single heads of households; its wages support families as well as the economy. The value of the 
minimum wage has declined to its lowest level in 40 years. At a time when workers are struggling 
more and more with declining living standards, American families desperately need this raise. </p>
<p>The AFL-CIO intends to make the stagnation of wages for America's workers, particularly 
minimum wage workers, an issue that cannot be ignored. Congress needs to act now without the 
procedural maneuvers that have kept working Americans from getting the raise they deserve and 
have earned. </p>
<p>With bi-partisan support growing in the Congress and the support of 84% of the American public it 
is incumbent on every member of this Congress who supports American working families to insist 
that a floor debate and final legislation action be taken on this issue now. </p>
<blockquote>
<p>Sincerely yours, </p>
<p>John J. Sweeney President, AFL-CIO</p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="/publ/publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
</blockquote>
</body>

