<head>
<title>PR 04/09/96 RADIO AND TV ADS</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<pre>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE                              For Information: David Saltz, 202-637-5318    
                                                                    Norm Kurz, 202-842-3100
</pre>
<p align="center"><em>The vote against raising $4.25 an hour
minimum wage keeps millions of workers stuck below poverty line! </em></p>
<h1 align="center">AFL-CIO LAUNCHES NEW WAVE OF RADIO AND TV ADS<br>
CITING MEMBERS OF CONGRESS <br>
WHO VOTED <em>AGAINST </em>RAISING MINIMUM WAGE</h1>
<p>Washington, April 9 -- Taking the next step in its
wide-ranging program to educate the American public on key public
policy issues, the AFL-CIO today unveiled new television and
radio ads focusing on Congress' recent votes opposing a raise in
the minimum wage. </p>
<p>The spots, scheduled to begin running today in 31 districts
where House members voted against a minimum wage increase,
pointedly note that the vote follows similar votes by the same
members to cut Medicare and college loans while providing tax
cuts to corporations and the wealthy. </p>
<p>&quot;We haven't had an increase in the minimum wage since
1991, and the value of today's $4.25 an hour rate is about to dip
to a forty year low in terms of real value,&quot; said AFL-CIO
President John J. Sweeney. &quot;Today's minimum wage amounts to
a salary of $8800 a year, while the poverty line for a family of
four is more than $15,000. I think we have a responsibility to
inform Americans about those Members of Congress who don't
believe working families deserve a livable wage.&quot; </p>
<p>Running in districts held by both Democrats and Republicans,
the ads point out that &quot;back in 1991, the minimum wage was
four dollars and twenty five cents an hour. Since then, corporate
profits and executive salaries have soared. But working families
have lost ground. And the minimum wage is still just four twenty
five an hour.&quot; </p>
<p>The spots close by urging viewers and listeners to call a
toll-free number and, &quot;tell (Congressman) to raise the
minimum wage and start voting for America's working
families.&quot; </p>
<p>TV ads will run in districts in Arkansas, California, Indiana,
Iowa, Kansas, Kentucky, Maine, Michigan, Mississippi, Nebraska,
New York, North Carolina, Nevada, Ohio, Oregon, Texas, Washington
and Wisconsin. Radio spots will air in Connecticut, Illinois,
Maryland, Massachusetts, Ohio and Texas.</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../index.htm">Public Documents Page</a> | <a
href="../publsear.htm">Public Documents Search</a></p>
