<title>PR 04/04/96 POLICE BATONS TO IMPOSE STREET JUSTICE</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<pre>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE              FOR INFORMATION CONTACT:
APRIL 4, 1996                      DENISE MITCHELL (202) 637-5340
                                   DEBORAH DUGAN (202) 637-5365
</pre>
<h1 align="center">AFL-CIO CONDEMNS USE OF POLICE BATONS TO
IMPOSE STREET JUSTICE </h1>
<h2 align="center">AFL-CIO Executive Vice President Linda
Chavez-Thompson<br>
issued the following statement in response to the<br>
police beatings of two suspected undocumented<br>
Mexican immigrants near Riverside County.<br>
</h2>
<p>&quot;The recent police beatings of two Mexican immigrants in
Los Angeles has hit close to home for the labor movement.
America's unions have all too often felt the brunt of police
batons when they rained down on janitors peacefully marching in
Century City and on peaceful drywall construction workers
protesting throughout Southern California.&quot; </p>
<p>&quot;Our movement will not tolerate this type of police
brutality nor will we excuse officers because the situation is
volatile and fraught with emotion. This is not a question of
immigration rights, but of basic civil and human rights.&quot;</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../index.htm">Public Documents Page</a> | <a
href="../publsear.htm">Public Documents Search</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
</body>
