<title>PR 03/20/96 REPUBLICAN RETREAT ON JOB SAFETY BILL</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<pre>For Immediate Release                      For information contact:
Wednesday, March 20                        David Saltz (202-637-5318)
                                           Peg Seminario (202-637-5366)
                                           Keith Mestrich (202-637-5210)
</pre>
<h2 align=center>AFL-CIO WELCOMES REPUBLICAN RETREAT <br>
ON JOB SAFETY BILL</h2>
<p align=center>AFL-CIO President John J. Sweeney issued the following statement in response to Cass 
Ballenger's announcement reported in today's Charlotte Observer that the North Carolina 
Representative has shelved his job safety overhaul proposal (H.R. 1834): </p>
<p>Ballenger's announcement that he is abandoning his efforts to overhaul the nation's job safety laws is 
a victory for American working families. Local union activists should take pride in today's 
announcement. It has been their efforts to hold Washington accountable that stopped this legislation 
to cut safety and health protections for 100 million American workers. </p>
<p>Extreme measures to strip workers of their rights and to weaken the government's ability to enforce 
safeguards have no public support. The only proponents of this legislation are business lobbyists 
and their Republican allies. </p>
<p>This should not be viewed as an end to Republican and employer attempts to weaken job safety 
protections. Equally damaging measures in the Senate (S.1423) and Republican-sponsored budget 
cuts still pose significant threats. The AFL-CIO, its member unions and workers across the country 
will continue fighting these efforts all the way to the November elections.</p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="/publ/publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
