<title>PR 03/20/96 Minimum Wage</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<pre>For Immediate Release                      For information contact:
Wednesday, March 20                        David Saltz at (202) 637-5318
                                           Karla Garland at (202) 637-5376
</pre>
<h2 align="center">Statement by Richard L. Trumka<br>
Secretary-Treasurer of the AFL-CIO<br>
On The Need To Raise The Minimum Wage</h2>
<p>Last night on television, after Senate Majority Leader Bob
Dole announced that the battle for the Republican nomination was
over, he said the battle for America's future was beginning. </p>
<p>By his refusal to schedule a vote on legislation raising the
minimum wage, Senator Dole has made it clear that his definition
of America's future doesn't include working families, who are
under attack as never before. His vision doesn't include workers
at the bottom of the economic ladder, who hold down full-time
jobs, but can never lift themselves out of poverty on a minimum
wage that pays just $8,500 a year. </p>
<p>The wage and wealth gap is a huge problem and the least we can
do is raise the minimum wage. Working families today are
pressured as never before and, while executive pay and corporate
profits are reaching all time highs, the minimum wage is at a
40-year low and hasn't been increased since 1989. </p>
<p>Bob Dole is the nominee who said in New Hampshire that he
didn't realize that jobs and the economy were that important. Now
that he realizes it, he should let us do something about it,
starting with this modest increase in the minimum wage. There are
steps we can take, but Senator Dole doesn't want us to take them.
Last year, 51 senators agreed that the Senate should get the
chance to vote on increasing the minimum wage. Let America's
working families have that vote.</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../index.htm">Public Documents Page</a> | <a
href="../publsear.htm">Public Documents Search</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
</body>
