<head>
<title>PR 02/22/96 Credit Card Deal</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<pre>FOR RELEASE NOON, FEBRUARY 22      For information, contact:
                                   Deborah Dion (305) 867-2145
</pre>
<h3 align="center">AFL-CIO Streamlines Its Field Operations, Taps
Household Intl. to Handle Credit Card </h3>
<p><strong>UNION MEMBERS GET A BETTER CREDIT CARD DEAL,</strong> <strong>LABOR
GETS $375 MILLION OVER NEXT FIVE YEARS</strong> <strong>FOR
ORGANIZING AND OTHER NEW SWEENEY PROGRAMS</strong> </p>
<p>Miami, February 22 --- The AFL-CIO Executive Council completed
its work here today by radically changing and streamlining its
organizational structure and negotiating a new credit card
arrangement which gives its members a better deal while providing
the 13 million member federation an estimated $375 million new
dollars for organizing and other new programs over the next five
years. </p>
<p>&quot;It's a better deal for our members and its sends a good
portion of what are now the bank's profits back into our movement
so we can help build a more secure future for working
Americans,&quot; said AFL-CIO President John J. Sweeney as he
announced approval to negotiate a final agreement with Household
International to switch the AFL-CIO's 2 million credit card
holders from the Bank of New York. </p>
<p>Unless the Bank of New York matches the offer from Household,
the changeover will take place February 28, 1997. </p>
<p>Under the Household proposal, the $375 million will come out
of program revenues in the form of royalty payments on
outstanding receivables, with the card rate staying at prime plus
5 percent, which currently translates into a 13.5 percent
interest rate. This rate is more than 4 percent below the
national average and compares to 17.4 percent for cards issued
members of the American Association of Retired Persons (AARP) and
16.4 percent for members of the American Nurses' Association. </p>
<p>The Household proposal, Sweeney said, includes a &quot;grace
period&quot; card for members who pay their balance each month
and a &quot;secured card&quot; for union members with past credit
problems. Union members who owe money on other credit cards will
be able to transfer their balances to their new card and pay the
prime rate for as long as it takes to pay off the balance. </p>
<p>&quot;Household's experience as a consumer finance company
lending money to workers and their families allows the company to
approve qualified members other lenders might reject,&quot; he
said. </p>
<p>Winding up a grinding week of work, the 54-member council
matched its financial coup by approving a streamlining of its $11
million per year field operation and naming 39-year-old Teamster
education director Marilyn Sneiderman to head it. Twelve regional
offices across the country will be condensed into four to six
regions and overlapping structures will be eliminated. </p>
<p>The Council also consolidated the economic research and
employee benefits Department into a new public policy department. </p>
<p>Negotiations over the credit card, which is managed by the
federation's &quot;Union Privilege&quot; arm, have been going on
for the past fifteen months. Three bids were received, including
one from the Bank of New York. </p>
<p>&quot;We accepted the bid from Household --- an acknowledged
leader in the credit card industry --- because it maintains our
rate, pays us millions of dollars in royalties and carries
union-sensitive elements such as union neutrality, a loan program
for striking workers and buy/build union provisions,&quot;
Sweeney said, noting it is the first time the labor federation
has been able to negotiate such an agreement into one of its
benefit programs. </p>
<p>The AFL-CIO receives only minor administrative costs under its
current arrangement with the Bank of New York. Sweeney said the
labor federation was able to negotiate a better deal because its
card now has a 10-year history. </p>
<p>&quot;Household was willing to share a good deal of its
program revenues because union members have proven to be the best
credit card customers in the industry,&quot; said Hans Morris of
Smith Barney, which along with the Auremma Consulting Group was
hired to guide the negotiations on behalf of the AFL-CIO.
&quot;They use their cards, they are loyal, and they pay their
bills on time.&quot; </p>
<p>Morris said the AFL-CIO members have a delinquency rate that
is half the national average. </p>
<p>Household International, through its subsidiaries, is a major
provider of consumer financial services in the United States,
Canada and the United Kingdom. Its primary businesses include
HFC, the nation's oldest consumer finance company, and Household
Bank, one of the largest issuers of private label and general
purpose credit cards in the United States. </p>
<p>Earlier this week, the Executive Council of the AFL-CIO
reviewed plans for a national organizing drive to rebuild its
membership base, named Karen Nussbaum, now head of the Women's
Bureau at the Department of Labor, to head a new working women's
program for labor, announced a campaign to &quot;close the
gap&quot; between rising corporate profits and dwindling worker
incomes and launched a comprehensive political and legislative
counterattack against &quot; the radical right-wingers in
Congress.&quot;</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../index.htm">Public Documents Page</a> | <a
href="../publsear.htm">Public Documents Search</a></p>
