<body>
<h3 align="center">Statement by John J. Sweeney<br>
President of the AFL-CIO<br>
</h3>
<p align="center"><b>February 4, 1996<br>
</b></p>
<p align="center"><i>On the tentative contract settlement
achieved this morning by 35,000 office building janitors in New
York City after a month-long strike: </i></p>
<p>``The strikers are to be congratulated for a solid contract,
achieved after great sacrifice. They won because they stuck
together in the face of concession demands from some of the most
powerful real estate interests in the country. Their victory was
assured when members of the other unions in the city decided to
risk their own jobs by honoring the picket lines. It sends a
message to the nation that we are entering a time of renewed
solidarity among working Americans.'' </p>
<p align="center">-end- </p>
<p>For further information, contact Ray Abernathy (o)
202/842-3100 or (h) 202/362-3745</p>
