<head>
<title>PR 01/31/96 Wyden</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<pre>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE TO           FOR INFORMATION, CONTACT:
POLITICAL AND LABOR REPORTERS      Denise Mitchell, 202/637-5340
</pre>
<h3 align="center">Statement by John J. Sweeney President,
AFL-CIO On the Election of Ron Wyden to the U.S. Senate January
31, 1996 </h3>
<p>Working families and their unions made the difference in
electing the first Democratic senator from Oregon since 1962. We
put together an unparalleled political effort -- recruiting 500
union members as volunteers, dedicating 35 union staff to the
Wyden campaign full time, providing information about both
candidates' records to voters and working intensely to boost
voter turnout through more than 230,000 phone calls and 350,000
pieces of mail. In some counties, union member turnout was as
much as 11 percent higher than overall turnout levels. </p>
<p>Wyden wore the union label on his lapel and won, overcoming a
$1.1 million spending disadvantage favoring Gordon Smith as well
as historically higher turnout by Republican voters in special
elections. His election reverses Oregon's turn toward Republican
politics in 1994, when Republicans gained control of both houses
of the state legislature for the first time in 40 years. </p>
<p>The Oregon race provides a vital first chapter in a new
textbook on politics we're going to write this year, as we
recruit and train activists to build the core of a powerful new
grass-roots movement to improve the lives of American working
families.</p>
