<title>PR 01/29/96 Detroit Newspaper Plant</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<pre>                                  For Immediate Release January 29, 1996
                                 Contact: Candice Johnson (202) 637-5010
</pre>
<h3 align="center">Unions Petition Justice Department to Save
Detroit Riverfront Newspaper Plant </h3>
<p>Washington, D.C. -- The AFL-CIO and striking Detroit Newspaper
unions today petitioned Attorney General Janet Reno to require
the newspapers to maintain Detroit's Riverfront newspaper
printing plant intact until she has ruled on whether the
newspapers still enjoy Joint Operating Agreement antitrust
immunity. Alleging that the Riverfront Plant is being considered
for closure or reduction in capacity, the petition asks Reno to
require the newspapers to maintain the plant as a separate and
competitive production facility until the antitrust issue is
resolved. </p>
<p>The supplemental petition amends the AFL-CIO's anti-trust
complaint to the Department of Justice made last August 15th
which alleged that Gannett Company's Detroit News and Knight
Ridder Inc.'s Detroit Free Press had forfeited their antitrust
immunity in 1992 by filing an anti-labor amendment to their Joint
Operating Agreement without public comment or the permission of
the Attorney General. </p>
<p>&quot;We will not allow Gannett and Knight Ridder to close or
downsize the Riverfront Plant and block a remedy by the Justice
Department,&quot; said AFL-CIO President John Sweeney. &quot;The
Detroit Newspapers abused their monopoly for the purpose of
unionbusting, and that plant is necessary to preserve
competition.&quot; </p>
<p>The AFL-CIO's special counsel for the case, Donald Baker,
said: &quot;The Detroit Newspapers were granted a special license
to do what other competitors go to jail for -- collectively
setting the prices in newspapers and advertising. We believe they
lost that immunity and must now compete in compliance with the
Sherman Act. To do that, they need competitive printing capacity
and therefore the Riverfront Plant must be preserved
intact.&quot; </p>
<p>The petition also asks Reno to require the newspapers to
respond to the unions' original complaint. More than five months
have transpired since it was filed, during which more than 2,000
workers have remained on strike against unfair labor practices by
the newspapers.</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../index.htm">Public Documents Page</a> | <a
href="../publsear.htm">Public Documents Search</a></p>
