<head>
<title>PR 01/24/96 Sweeping Changes at AFL-CIO</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<pre>For Release 12:15 p.m. 1/24/96         For Further Information:
                                       Denise Mitchell (202) 637-5340
</pre>
<h3 align="center">Sweeney Announces Sweeping Changes at AFL-CIO,<br>
Names Richard Bensinger to Top Organizing Post;<br>
Allison Porter to Head Organizing Institute<br>
</h3>
<p><b>Washington, DC, January 24</b> -- AFL-CIO President John
Sweeney today announced sweeping structural and program changes
for the 13 million-member labor federation, and named 45-year-old
Richard Bensinger to head a new Organizing Department charged
with leading a turnaround of the organization's long membership
slide. Bensinger, a former regional organizing director for the
Amalgamated Clothing and Textile Workers Union (ACTWU), has been
head of the AFL-CIO's highly successful Organizing Institute for
the past five years. He is succeeded in that post by Allison
Porter, 35, who has been deputy director of the institute since
its founding. </p>
<p>The announcements came at a special one-day meeting of the
federation's governing Executive Council three months after
Sweeney's election as president. </p>
<p>``Today marks an historic turning point for the AFL-CIO,''
Sweeney said, noting that 70 representatives from 20 different
unions served on five work groups that analyzed AFL-CIO
departments and programs for the past two months and today laid
out for the Executive Council their plans for new programs and
structural changes. </p>
<p>Creation of the new Organizing Department, which will oversee
the work of a greatly expanded Organizing Institute and
administer a $20 million organizing fund, was a key plank in
Sweeney's election platform at the AFL-CIO convention in New York
last October. Among the department's chief assignments are a
drive to improve federal and state laws and regulations governing
organizing of workers and development of a long-term program for
organizing the South and the Sun Belt. </p>
<p>In the political arena, Sweeney said that in 1996 the labor
movement will build a permanent base of at least 100 union
grassroots political and legislative activists in each
congressional district, train all field staff for political
action and flood 2,500 union activists and staff into
congressional districts for ``get-out-the-vote'' efforts during
the last six weeks of the 1996 campaign. The federation will also
create a new media fund to ``give air cover for our ground war,''
he said. </p>
<p>The AFL-CIO will proceed full-speed with another key component
in the Sweeney platform by establishing a National Labor
Political Training Center to develop union campaigners, create
educational materials for members, work with affiliates and
provide polling, research and message development. </p>
<p>Sweeney also announced the start-up of a new Center for
Strategic Campaigns, which will help unions apply economic
leverage in organizing drives, bargaining campaign and strikes,
and a Worker Ownership and Governance Institute to assist unions
with employee buyouts, coping with corporate restructuring
schemes and monitoring union pension fund investment managers. He
said the AFL-CIO International Affairs Department will be
reorganized to help American workers and unions deal with the
impact of the global economy. </p>
<p>The federation's communications functions will be consolidated
and strengthened to project a ``compelling new public face for
unions.'' A four-division public affairs structure will fold in
the resources and staff of the existing Labor Institute of Public
Affairs as an ``electronic and other media'' component. Media
outreach and speechwriting and public message functions will be
beefed up and all AFL-CIO publications, including the bi-weekly
AFL-CIO News, will be revamped. To communicate quicker with its
leadership as well as key external audiences, the AFL-CIO this
week began publishing a two-page faxed update called ``WORK in
Progress.'' </p>
<p>Finally, a ``union education and training' work group
recommended a series of new programs designed to educate workers
in the ``political economy'' and to train leaders for work in
organizing, political action and strategic campaigns. </p>
<p>In addition to announcing the results of the work groups,
Sweeney briefed the Executive Council on ongoing reviews of the
federation's field structure and legal department, which has been
charged with becoming much more active in providing legal support
for organizing, strategic campaigns and regulatory and
legislative efforts. He also named Laborers' Union President
Arthur Coia chair of the Executive Council's committee on
organizing, AFSCME President Gerald McEntee chair of the
political action committee and Food and Commercial Workers
President Doug Dority chair of the public affairs committee.</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../index.htm">Public Documents Page</a> | <a
href="../publsear.htm">Public Documents Search</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
</body>
