<title>PR 01/16/96 OSHA Problem</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<h3 align="center">BOGUS INDUSTRY ANALYSIS DISTORTS SERIOUS
SAFETY AND HEALTH PROBLEM </h3>
<pre>
For Immediate Release           Contacts: Candice Johnson (202-637-5014)
January 16, 1996                            Peg Seminario (202-637-5366)
                                           Keith Mestrich (202-637-5210)
</pre>
<p>Statement of AFL-CIO President John J. Sweeney on the industry
backed National Coalition on Ergonomics' analysis of OSHA's draft
ergonomics rule: </p>
<p>The analysis released by the industry coalition is the latest
effort in its ongoing campaign to use power, money and
distortions to keep the government from protecting workers from
crippling repetitive strain injuries and illnesses. This is not
about science. It's about industry trying to rid itself of all
regulations and gut job safety protections. </p>
<p>Last summer, the Coalition - led by the American Trucking
Association and UPS - stopped the public rulemaking on OSHA's
ergonomic standard by lining up right-wing Republicans to block
publication of the proposed rule. Now, with the public frozen out
of the process, they've bought their own scientific analysis and
are claiming that ergonomic injuries and illnesses are not a
serious workplace safety and health problem in need of
regulation. </p>
<p>This is one of the grossest distortions of the truth and
demonstrations of corporate irresponsibility seen in a long time.
By employers' own reports, ergonomic injuries and illnesses
account for more than one-third of all serious workplace injures
and illnesses - over 730,000 in 1993 - and the numbers are
increasing. The trucking and courier industry - which is a leader
in this coalition - reports some of the highest rates and numbers
of ergonomic injuries and illnesses. For these employers to claim
that there is no problem and no need for an OSHA regulation to
control ergonomic hazards is simply incredible. Are they trying
to tell the hundreds of thousands of workers who are disabled by
these injuries each year that their pain and suffering doesn't
exist and that ergonomic hazards don't need to be controlled? </p>
<p>Many employers like Ford, GM, Chrysler, IBP, Masland
Industries and others have recognized that ergonomic injuries and
illnesses are a serious problem and have instituted comprehensive
control measures to prevent them. It's shameful that UPS, the
American Trucking Association, the National Association of
Manufacturers and others in the Coalition have decided to spend
millions of dollars to stop OSHA from protecting American workers
instead of acting responsibly to help to control ergonomic
hazards.</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../index.htm">Public Documents Page</a> | <a
href="../publsear.htm">Public Documents Search</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
</body>
</html>
