<html>

<head>
<title>PR 12/15/95 Job Injury</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<pre>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE DEC. 15
                                        For information, contact:
                                  Colleen O'Neill at 202/637-5010
                                 or Peg Seminario at 202/637-5366
</pre>
<h3 align=center>JOB INJURY REPORT SHOWS SOME PROGRESS, BUT SERIOUS 
PROBLEMS REMAIN </h3>
<p>Peg Seminario, director of the AFL-CIO Department of Occupational Safety and Health, made the 
following comment on the annual report on occupational injuries and illnesses released today by the 
Bureau of Labor Statistics: </p>
<p>The 1994 BLS Annual Survey on Workplace Injuries and Illnesses contains mixed news for 
American workers. </p>
<p>The reported reduction in the workplace injury rate shows some progress in improving worker 
protection. The most significant progress was in the construction industry, which reported the 
greatest decrease and its lowest injury rate in 20 years. </p>
<p>At the same time, the number and rate of cumulative trauma disorders (CTDs) caused by poor job 
design and repetitive motion continue to increase at alarming rates. In 1994, more than 332,000 
cases of CTDs were reported, an increase of 800 percent over the last decade. </p>
<p>In many high-hazard industries like meatpacking, foundries and auto assembly, overall injury and 
illness rates remain unacceptably high -- and they are increasing in some sectors. </p>
<p>Today's BLS report underscores the desperate need for an OSHA ergonomics standard to prevent 
crippling repetitive motion injuries and illnesses and for OSHA to do more to focus its efforts in 
highhazard industries. </p>
<p>It also shows that efforts of Republicans in Congress to stop OSHA's ergonomics standard and to 
slash OSHA's budget and enforcement program are wrongheaded and will leave millions of 
American workers without much needed protection.</p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="/publ/publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
</body>

