<title>PR 12/08/95 Crisis in CA Health Care</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<pre>MEDIA ADVISORY FOR FRIDAY, DECEMBER 8
                       For Information: Deborah Dion 202-898-3266
                                         On 12/7/95  415-546-5195
</pre>
<p align="center">NEW AFL-CIO PRESIDENT JOHN J. SWEENEY TRAVELS
TO SAN FRANCISCO TO ADDRESS MOUNTING CRISIS IN CA HEALTH CARE </p>
<p>Nation's Top Labor Leader Calls For Labor-Management
Partnership in CA Public Hospitals; Leads March and Rally In
Support of Vencor/Hillhaven Nursing Home Workers </p>
<p><strong>WHEN: FRIDAY, DECEMBER 8, 1995</strong> </p>
<pre>
<strong>WHAT:          11:15 AM - 12:15 PM</strong>
               ADDRESS -- CALIFORNIA ASSOCIATION OF PUBLIC HEALTH
               PARK 55 HOTEL
               55 CYRIL MAGNIN STREET (DOWNTOWN)

               12:30 PM
               LEADS VENCOR/HILLHAVEN MARCH/RALLY
               MARCH BEGINS AT HILLHAVEN -- 1359 PINE (@HYDE)
               MARCHERS PROCEED DOWN PINE ST. TO HILLHAVEN NURSING
               HOME AT 2707 PINE (@ DIVISADERO) FOR 1:00 PM RALLY
</pre>
<p>San Francisco, CA -- Newly elected AFL-CIO President John J.
Sweeney will join striking Vencor/Hillhaven nursing home workers,
hundreds of their supporters and local politicians in a march and
rally to protest Vencor/Hillhaven's poor record of patient care
and treatment of workers. </p>
<p>Prior to the march, Sweeney will address several hundred
county health officials and hospital administrators attending the
California Association of Public Health's Annual Conference.
Sweeney will speak about the need for new labor-management
partnerships to build a strong public health system in California
and around the country where massive health care restructuring is
occurring in the industry. </p>
<p>The new AFL-CIO leadership team of John Sweeney, Rich Trumka
and Linda Chavez-Thompson swept the top AFL-CIO offices just six
weeks ago in the first-ever contest in the 13 million-member
labor federation. Sweeney was elected the fourth president in
AFL-CIO history after launching a six-month insurgent campaign
for ``A New Voice for American Workers.''</p>
