<head>
<title>PR 12/06/95 AFL-CIO Condemns Senate Job Safety Bill</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<pre>For Immediate Release                          For information, contact:
                                          Candice Johnson (202/637-5010)
                                           Keith Mestrich (202/637-5210)
                                              David Saltz (202/637-5318)
</pre>
<h3 align="center">AFL-CIO CONDEMNS SENATE JOB SAFETY BILL THAT
EXEMPTS THREE-QUARTERS OF EMPLOYERS FROM INSPECTIONS </h3>
<p>WASHINGTON, Dec. 6 AFL-CIO President John Sweeney today
condemned Senate bill, S.1423, that would weaken the nation's job
safety laws, citing a new finding that 73 percent of the nation's
employers would be exempt from Occupational Safety and Health
Administration inspections under the Republican Senate plan. </p>
<p>Senate Democrats released statistics indicating that 3 out of
every 4 U.S. employers would automatically be exempted from
generally scheduled OSHA inspections. OSHA uses such inspections
to target the nation's most hazardous workplaces. </p>
<p>``This bill would let even hazardous employers off the hook,
denying the benefits of OSHA protections to some forty million
workers,'' he said. Sweeney called the bill ``bad public policy''
because it would weaken safety and health protections for workers
who need them the most. </p>
<p>Many exempted employers are in some of the nation's most
dangerous industries. ``This means that even employers in very
hazardous areas like meatpacking, shipbuilding, foundries and
construction would be exempted without demonstrating a true
commitment to improving job safety and health conditions,''
Sweeney noted. </p>
<p>``These provisions destroy the foundation of America's job
safety law. Inspections and strong enforcement have led to
significant decreases in job fatalities and injuries in areas
where OSHA has focused its resources. This progress would be
reversed and more workers would be killed or injured,'' he said. </p>
<p>The Senate bill requires OSHA to exempt employers if the
workplace has been reviewed by a state consultant or other third
party, or if the workplace has had no fatalities in the last year
and has fewer lost work days due to injuries than the average for
the employer's industry. Employers would also be exempted if they
have fewer than ten employees and are in so-called ``safe''
industries or if they operate a farming operation. </p>
<p>The statistics cited by Democratic senators include only those
employers exempted based on the number of employees and the lost
workday injury rates. Thousands more employers would be exempt
under the third party certification criteria. </p>
<p>AFL-CIO Executive Vice President Linda Chavez Thompson, in her
testimony opposing the bill last week, noted that the bill would
``drastically limit worker rights and protections, change the
basic structure of the OSHA law, and redefine the government's
role in overseeing workplace safety.'' </p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../index.htm">Public Documents Page</a> | <a
