<head>
<title>PR 11/29/95 AFL-CIO Exec. Vice Pres. on Job Safety Bill</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<pre>For Release Wednesday, Nov. 29, 1995
                                        For information, contact:
                                     Colleen O'Neill 202/637-5027
</pre>
<h3 align="center">AFL-CIO EXECUTIVE VICE PRESIDENT
CHAVEZ-THOMPSON CONDEMNS SENATE JOB SAFETY BILL </h3>
<p>In her first appearance before Congress as AFL-CIO executive
vice president, Linda Chavez-Thompson condemned Senate attacks on
the nation's job safety laws. </p>
<p>Testifying before the Senate Labor and Human Resources
Committee, Chavez-Thompson said that recently introduced
legislation to overhaul the Occupational Safety and Health Act
would &quot;drastically limit worker rights and protections,
change the basic structure of the OSHA law and redefine the
government's role in overseeing workplace safety.&quot; </p>
<p>The Occupational Safety and Health Reform and Reinvention Act
(S. 1423) was introduced by Sens. Nancy L. Kassebaum (R-Kan.) and
Judd Gregg (R-N.H.) The bill would take away workers' rights to
have OSHA investigate serious workplace hazards, shift OSHA's
focus away from enforcement toward voluntary compliance and
exempt large numbers of employers from safety and health
inspections. </p>
<p>&quot;Workers in this country still suffer a terrible toll of
workplace injury and death,&quot; Chavez-Thompson said.
&quot;Each year, more than 55,000 workers die from job hazards, 7
million are injured and 60,000 permanently disabled.&quot; Noting
that the legislation fails to respond to the significant dangers
workers face, Chavez-Thompson said &quot;this Congress has
instead decided to respond to those in the business community who
have raised objections to the OSHA law. In our view, business's
interests -- not workers' interests or the national interest --
are driving the legislative agenda.&quot; </p>
<p>In urging senators to reject the bill, Chavez-Thompson
responded to characterizations of S. 1423 as a moderate measure.
This bill &quot;is by no means a moderate proposal. The
provisions of S. 1423 go right to the heart of the only
protections that workers have . . . they weaken OSHA enforcement,
limit workers' rights (and will result) in more workplace
injuries, illnesses and deaths, and less safety and health
protections for workers.&quot; </p>
<p>&quot;The bill breaks the promise made 25 years ago to the
workers of this country that the government would assure safe and
healthful working conditions. Workers in this country need more
protection, not less.&quot;<br>
-end-</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../index.htm">Public Documents Page</a> | <a
href="../publsear.htm">Public Documents Search</a></p>
