<head>
<title>PR 11/22/95 New Hart Poll Finds Americans Side With
Clinton on Budg</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<pre>For Immediate Release                 For information:
Wed. Nov 22, 11:30 am		      Norm Kurz 202/842-3100 or
                 		      Candice Johnson 202/637-5014
</pre>
<h3 align="center">NEW HART RESEARCH POLL FINDS AMERICANS SIDE
WITH CLINTON, DEMOCRATS ON BUDGET, REJECT REPUBLICAN PROPOSALS
FOR CORPORATE TAX BREAKS, CUTS IN MEDICARE, MEDICAID, EDUCATION,
AND PENSION FUND RAIDING </h3>
<p>WASHINGTON, NOV 22 -- Most Americans believe the Republican
budget goes too far and reject the idea of compromise at any cost
to get a budget, according to a new poll by Peter D. Hart
Research Associates, Inc. conducted for the AFL-CIO. President
Bill Clinton, they say, should reject any budget that gives tax
breaks to corporations, cuts Medicare, Medicaid and education, or
allows employers to take money out of pension funds for other
purposes. </p>
<p>Americans in every age group, educational category, and region
of the country are now more likely to trust President Clinton and
the Democrats over the Republicans on the budget. Women are
especially likely to hold this view, favoring President Clinton
and the Democrats by a 53 to 28 percent margin. </p>
<p>Americans reject the Republican contention that they are doing
what is necessary to get government under control. By a margin of
58 to 36 percent, they believe Republicans are &quot;going too
far with this budget&quot; amd advancing &quot;the wrong kind of
change,&quot; rather than &quot;making the tough decisions needed
to get government under control and put our fiscal house in
order.&quot; This view is held even by southerners (55 to 42
percent), men (53 to 41 percent), and upper income voters (54 to
43 percent). Independents fall away from Republicans on this
question by a margin of 58 to 28 percent. </p>
<p>The poll, conducted November 15 - 19, shows that Americans do
not favor a compromise at any price. For a series of Republican
budget proposals, they were asked if &quot;President Clinton
should accept this provision in order to get the budget
passed.&quot; </p>
<ul>
    <li>Eighty-six percent say President Clinton should reject a
        budget if it includes the Republican proposal that allows
        corporations to take money out of their employees'
        pension funds for other purposes. </li>
    <li>Eighty-one percent say Clinton should reject a budget if
        it includes the Republican proposal that gives large new
        tax breaks to big corporations and wealthy individuals.
        Even Republicans, by a 63 to 27 percent margin, say
        Clinton should reject a budget that includes these
        breaks. </li>
    <li>Seventy-three percent say the President should reject any
        budget that makes major cuts in Medicaid, and 71 percent
        say he should reject a budget if it contains major
        Medicare cuts. Adults under age 35 are as likely to feel
        this way about Medicare cuts as other members of the
        public. </li>
    <li>Seventy-two percent say President Clinton should not
        accept any budget that cuts the student loan program, and
        71 percent say he should reject a budget if it makes
        major cuts in federal support for public education. </li>
    <li>Sixty-five percent want the President to reject any
        budget that reduces enforcement of occupational safety
        and health protections. </li>
    <li>By 59 to 29 percent, Americans say the President should
        reject the budget if it weakens his order to prevent
        government contractors from permanently replacing
        striking workers. And by 54 to 33 percent, they say he
        should reject a budget if it includes the Republicans_
        proposals to weaken laws against unfair labor practices
        by employers. </li>
</ul>
<p>The poll surveyed a representative cross section of 801
Americans age 18 or older; the margin of error is +3.5%.</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../index.htm">Public Documents Page</a> | <a
href="../publsear.htm">Public Documents Search</a></p>
