<title>PR 11/16/95 AFL-CIO President Announces More Key Staff
Changes</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<pre>For Immediate Release			  For information, contact:
Thursday, Nov. 16, 1995                   Candice Johnson 202/637-5010
</pre>
<h3 align="center">AFL-CIO President Announces More Key Staff
Changes </h3>
<p>WASHINGTON, NOV. 16 -- New AFL-CIO President John Sweeney
announced today that Steve Rosenthal will be the federation's new
political director, beginning December 1. Rosenthal is currently
associate deputy secretary of the U.S. Department of Labor, where
he is a key advisor to Labor Secretary Robert Reich on
labor-management issues. He served previously as deputy political
director at the Democratic National Committee, with
responsibility for the party's nationwide 1992 coordinated
campaign. For 12 years, he held key positions in the labor
movement with the Communications Workers of America, getting his
start in state and local political work. </p>
<p>``Steve will head up the AFL-CIO's political work, with
responsibility for implementing the political goals laid out in
our platform for change,'' said Sweeney. Reinvigorating the grass
roots capacity of the AFL-CIO by ``building a powerful,
progressive national movement of working people'' was one of the
highest priorities of Sweeney's successful insurgent campaign to
lead the 13 million member labor federation. </p>
<p>Rosenthal rounds out the top government affairs team which
includes Gerald Shea, who will serve Sweeney as assistant to the
president for government affairs, and Peggy Taylor, AFL-CIO
legislative director. </p>
<p>``Steve Rosenthal will be a valuable asset in the new
leadership's mission to revitalize the nation's union movement,''
commented Secretary Reich.</p>
