<title>PR 11/02/95 AFL-CIO Sec. Treas. Trumka visits Indiana</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<pre>Media advisory                                  Contact: Candice Johnson
November 2, 1995                                            202/637-5010
                   or the Indiana AFL-CIO office at the Adams Mark Hotel
                                                  317/248-2481, Room 156
</pre>
<h3 align="center">New AFL-CIO Leader Meets with Indiana Labor </h3>
<p>AFL-CIO Secretary-Treasurer Richard Trumka will be in
Indianapolis Thursday, Nov. 2, and will speak to union members
attending the Indiana AFL-CIO convention. </p>
<p>Trumka will address the convention at about 4 p.m. at the
Adams Mark Hotel, Golden Ballroom IV, 2544 Executive Drive,
Indianapolis. </p>
<p>Following his address, about 4:45 p.m., Trumka will meet with
reporters at a news conference in the Directors Row 3 room, at
the Adams Mark. </p>
<p>For information and media availability, contact Candice
Johnson, 202/637-5010, or call the Indiana AFL-CIO office at the
Adams Mark Hotel, 317/248-2481, Room 156. </p>
<p>Trumka is one of the AFL-CIO's newly elected officers who were
swept into office at the federation's convention in New York last
week. The new officers are President John J. Sweeney, who headed
the 1.1 million members Service Employees International Union;
Trumka, who served as president of the Mine Workers; and
Executive Vice President Linda Chavez-Thompson, an executive vice
president of AFSCME who is the first person of color to hold a
top leadership post at the AFL-CIO. </p>
<p>Also elected at the New York convention were 51 vice
presidents -- 15 of whom are women and people of color -- with
the executive council expanded to bring about more diversity in
federation leadership roles. Among the membership are nine
AfricanAmericans, six women, and the first Asian Pacific American
and first Latino.</p>
