<head>
<title>PR 10/27/95 Minimum Wage</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<pre>For Immediate Release               Contact: David Saltz at 202/637-5318
October 27, 1995                      or Candice Johnson at 202/637-5010
</pre>
<h3 align="center">New AFL-CIO President Criticizes Senate
Failure on Minimum Wage Resolution</h3>
<p>AFL-CIO President John J. Sweeney today expressed outrage at
the U.S. Senate's failure to muster the 60 votes needed to
provide for consideration of a resolution calling for debate and
a vote on raising the minimum wage by the end of this legislative
session. </p>
<p>``The Senate's failure to even allow a vote on increasing the
minimum wage while rushing to give a $224 billion tax break to
large corporations and wealthy individuals speaks volumes about
whose side they're on,'' said Sweeney, who was elected president
of the AFL-CIO Wednesday, at the labor federation's convention in
New York. </p>
<p>Working families have suffered a steady loss in real wages
over the past decade. Minimum wage workers today earn less as a
percentage of average hourly earnings than at any time in the
last 40 years. </p>
<p>``America needs a pay raise,'' said Sweeney. ``Instead they
got the cold shoulder from most Republicans in the Senate.'' </p>
<p>``The more than 13 million members of AFL-CIO unions will know
who voted against even considering an increase in the minimum
wage. This vote will be a cornerstone of the massive coordinated
political education campaign I will have the federation launch
next year.'' </p>
<p>The Clinton administration is committed to increasing the
$4.25 federal minimum wage by 90 cents over two years to $5.15. </p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../index.htm">Public Documents Page</a> | <a
href="../publsear.htm">Public Documents Search</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
</body>
