<title>PR 10/13/95 Don't Break Promise to Seniors</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<pre>For Immediate Release                     Contact: Candice Johnson
October 13, 1995                                      202/637-5010
</pre>
<h3 align="center">AFL-CIO to Congress: Don't Break Promise to
Seniors </h3>
<p>With the House of Representatives moving toward a vote on
Medicare, the AFL-CIO is reminding Republican members of Congress
that working people oppose the GOP's plan to slash Medicare and
raise premiums for seniors. Television and radio ads aimed at 36
members of Congress go on the air today in 18 markets and will
run through October 19. The ad also will be aired on CNN, for a
total buy of nearly $1.2 million. </p>
<p>The ads feature Ron Collins, a telephone worker, who notes
that the Republican plan will cut Medicare by $270 billion and
raise annual premiums for seniors by some $500, all to give a
$245 billion tax break to the rich. Both the television and radio
ads encourage working families to use the AFL-CIO's toll-free
number to call their congressional representative and make
certain their voices are heard. </p>
<p>The television and radio ads complement the grassroots
activities of local union members, including phone banks,
meetings with members of Congress, postcard and letter writing
and other efforts to remind members of Congress to keep their
promise with America's seniors. </p>
<p>This Medicare push is a part of the AFL-CIO's Stand UP for
America's Working Families campaign for good jobs, good wages,
worker protections and a real voice on the job for working men
and women. </p>
<p align="center">### </p>
