<head>
<title>PR 09/27/95 Workers Shut Out Under ``Team Act''</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<pre>For Immediate Release                  Contact: Candice Johnson at 202-637-5010
September 27, 1995                               or David Saltz at 202-637-5318
</pre>
<h1 align="center">AFL-CIO: Workers Shut Out Under ``Team Act'' </h1>
<p>AFL-CIO President Tom Donahue issued this comment following
the House vote on the Teamwork for Employees Act: </p>
<p>We applaud the 202 members of the House of Representatives who
stood up to the Republican leadership and voted to reject the
so-called ``teamwork in the workplace'' offered by the GOP.
Despite a 1990s label, this is actually an attempt to bring back
the company unions that historically many employers used so well
to block workers' rights on the job. </p>
<p>Today's vote means that the veto promised by President Clinton
will be sustained should the bill reach his desk. </p>
<p>Under this bill, a company can set up the employees'
organization, pick the employees' representatives, set the
agenda, determine the outcome, and finally, abolish the
organization if and when the outcome isn't to the employer's
liking. </p>
<p>This kind of thinking doesn't fool anyone. Without changing
existing labor law, employers and workers already can take full
advantage of all forms of employee involvement, partnership and
teamwork. The only thing current law doesn't allow is employer
domination of employee representatives.</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../index.htm">Public Documents Page</a> | <a
href="../publsear.htm">Public Documents Search</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
</body>
</html>
