<head>
<title>PR 09/14/95 New TV Ads</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>For immediate release                    Contact: Candice Johnson<br>
September 14, 1995                                   202/637-5010<br>
                                   or David Saltz at 202/637-5318<br>
<br>
<br>
          New AFL-CIO TV Ads Answer GOP Medicare Plan;<br>
                Coalition Ads Attack Program Cuts<br>
<br>
     The AFL-CIO will air a new round of television ads blasting<br>
the Republican Medicare plan for raising costs and cutting benefits<br>
for working families in order to fund a tax cut for the rich. <br>
<br>
     The two ads are set to air on CNN and five Washington, D.C.,<br>
TV stations beginning Saturday, Sept. 16.<br>
<br>
     The spots are part of a series of ads that appeared in<br>
selected congressional districts over the past four congressional<br>
recesses, spotlighting the Republican Congress's plans to cut<br>
programs that working families rely on so they could pay for a tax<br>
cut that primarily benefits the wealthiest Americans. <br>
<br>
     The ads will air through Sept. 24 on CNN's Daybreak, Daytime,<br>
Inside Politics, Moneyline, Crossfire and Larry King Live programs,<br>
as well as on local Washington, D.C. stations. <br>
<br>
     This $250,000 media buy supplements the nearly $2.5 million<br>
the federation has spent this year on media ads as part of its<br>
Stand UP for America's Working Families campaign to focus attention<br>
on the need for good jobs, good wages, health and safety and a real<br>
voice on the job.<br>
<br>
     Also airing now are ads sponsored by the Save America's<br>
Families Coalition which demonstrate the impact of Medicare cuts on<br>
a family confronting the cost of caring for an elderly parent. The<br>
spots are part of a $2 million multimedia campaign by the group of<br>
labor and public-interest organizations aimed at illustrating the<br>
devastating financial and emotional effects of major proposed<br>
budget cuts in Medicare, education, occupational health and safety<br>
and other programs.</p>
