<head>
<title>PR 09/13/95 AFL-CIO Urges Public-Sector Partnerships</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<pre>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE                     CONTACT: James B. Parks
September 13, 1995                                 of the AFL-CIO
                                                  at 202/637-5022
</pre>
<h2 align="center">AFL-CIO Urges Public-Sector Partnerships</h2>
<p>Workers in the public sector are ready for a new kind of work
system based on partnership with state and local governments,
AFL- CIO President Tom Donahue told the Labor Secretary's Task
Force on Excellence in State and Local Government Through
Labor-Management Cooperation today. </p>
<p>Such partnerships are the best way to improve the quality and
cost-effectiveness of public-sector services, Donahue said,
pointing to the AFL-CIO's landmark 1994 report advocating the
revolutionary new work systems. </p>
<p>But excellence in delivering public services cannot be
achieved without first harnessing the knowledge and expertise of
front-line workers, which is best done when workers choose an
independent representative, Donahue said. He called it a
&quot;disgrace&quot; that 26 states that deny all or some of
their public employees -- about 5.4 million workers -- &quot;the
basic democratic right&quot; to select their own representatives
to deal with their employer. </p>
<p>&quot;Today's workers are hungry for a new way of dealing with
their employers,&quot; Donahue said, but &quot;the labor movement
has not kept up with the changing workforce and has not
sufficiently adapted to the new workplace. </p>
<p>&quot;It is the responsibility of the AFL-CIO to help this
generation -- and to develop a new generation -- of labor leaders
who are prepared to function in a very different environment
requiring expertise and skills quite different from those
required in the past,&quot; he said. </p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../index.htm">Public Documents Page</a> | <a
href="../publsear.htm">Public Documents Search</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
</body>
</html>
