<html>
<head>
<title>PR 09/11/95 Donahue Blasts House Proposal on Trade
Benefits</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<pre>For Immediate Release                   Contact: Candice Johnson
September 11, 1995                               202/637-5010 or
                                         Mark Anderson, 637-5178
</pre>
<h2 align="center">Donahue Blasts House Proposal on Trade
Benefits</h2>
<p>In the best display of chutzpah so far this session, the
Republican-controlled House Ways and Means Committee is voting on
a proposal to abolish benefits for workers who lose their jobs
because of trade, so it can provide tariff relief for
multinational corporations operating outside the United States. </p>
<p>The committee will vote on eliminating benefits for workers
under both the North American Free Trade Agreement trade
adjustment assistance program and the TAA program established in
1962, in order to extend two programs that reward corporations
with tax breaks for moving jobs overseas -- the Generalized
System of Preferences and the Caribbean Basin Economic
Development Act. </p>
<p>In a letter to U.S. Trade Representative Mickey Kantor, Labor
Secretary Robert B. Reich and White House chief of staff Leon
Panetta, AFL-CIO President Tom Donahue called on the Clinton
administration to work hard against the proposal, because
``workers deserve better treatment.'' </p>
<p>``It is difficult to understand how anyone could support a
proposal that provides tariff relief for U.S. and foreign
multinational corporations, thereby causing the loss of tens of
thousands of U.S. jobs, and then pay for these corporate tax
breaks by killing programs specifically designed to assist
American workers victimized by those corporate actions,'' Donahue
wrote. </p>
<p>He noted that TAA benefits were adopted some 33 years ago
because ``no matter what position one has on trade, everyone
agrees that U.S. workers have been, and will continue to be,
adversely affected by trade.'' </p>
<p>Donahue also pointed to the Labor Department's certification
of 35,000 workers in the past 18 months who lost their jobs
because of NAFTA as evidence that workers' interests are being
harmed, and added that another 35,000 have applied for benefits. </p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
