<head>
<title>PR 08/24/95 Workers in S.C. Protest</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE                            CONTACT: Barbara Kelley<br>
August 24, 1995                                          at 803/244-0997<br>
<br>
              Workers in S.C. Protest Attack on Job Safety<br>
<br>
     Workers from South Carolina, North Carolina and Georgia<br>
gathered outside the Pickens County (S.C.) Administration Building<br>
this afternoon to protest proposed legislation that would dismantle<br>
the nation's job safety laws.<br>
<br>
     Three members of the U.S. House of Representatives -- Reps.<br>
Cass Ballenger (R-N.C.), Lindsey Graham (R-S.C.) and Charles<br>
Norwood (R-Ga.) -- held a hearing in Pickens today on Ballenger's<br>
legislation, H.R. 1834, which seeks to change the emphasis of the<br>
Occupational Safety and Health Administration from enforcement to<br>
consultation, strip away worker rights and weaken safeguards to<br>
protect workers.<br>
<br>
     Ron Hayes of Fairhope, Ala., testified before the committee<br>
about the need for strong job safety protections. His knowledge was<br>
gathered first-hand after the death of his 19-year-old son,<br>
Patrick, who was sucked into corn and suffocated while working in<br>
a silo.<br>
<br>
     &quot;Patrick was a hard worker and a good employee,&quot; Hayes told<br>
the panel. &quot;He did as his supervisors told him -- and he was killed<br>
for it. I am still haunted by the pain I saw in Patrick's face when<br>
-- after five-and-a-half hours -- the rescue crews finally pulled<br>
his body out of the bin.<br>
<br>
     &quot;Patrick's company thought they could get away with breaking<br>
the law because OSHA already had so few inspectors to enforce<br>
health and safety protections -- protections that are supposed to<br>
save lives,&quot; Hayes said. &quot;When businesses are allowed to take that<br>
chance, people die.&quot;<br>
<br>
     Hayes urged the lawmakers to strengthen job safety and health<br>
agencies, not weaken them through legislation such as H.R. 1834 and<br>
the House-passed Labor, Education and Health and Human Services<br>
appropriations measure.<br>
<br>
     Working men and women across the country are using a national<br>
media campaign to focus attention on Republican members of Congress<br>
for their attacks on job safety protections, Medicare and other<br>
programs that assist working families. Television ads that are part<br>
of a million-dollar buy are running in the Greenville-Spartanburg,<br>
S.C., area.</p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="/publ/publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
</body>

