<html>

<head>
<title>PR 08/22/95 Workers to Protest Congressional Attack on Job Safety</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>PRESS ADVISORY CONTACT: Barbara Kelley, 803/244-0997<br>
August 22, 1995 or G.O. Smoak, 803/798-8300<br>
<br>
Workers to Protest Congressional Attack on Job Safety<br>
<br>
Workers from three southern states will converge on a<br>
congressional hearing in Pickens, S.C., Aug. 24 to say that pending<br>
legislation to weaken job safety provisions is not acceptable.<br>
<br>
Three members of a U.S. House Economic and Educational<br>
Opportunities subcommittee will conduct the hearing. They are Reps.<br>
Lindsey Graham (R-S.C.), Rep. Charles Norwood (R-Ga.) and panel<br>
Chairman Cass Ballenger (R-N.C.), the author of H.R. 1834, &quot;The<br>
Safety and Health Improvements and Regulatory Reform Act of 1995.&quot;<br>
Workers from all three states will attend the 2 p.m. hearing<br>
Thursday at the Pickens County Administration Building in Pickens,<br>
S.C.<br>
<br>
Ballenger's H.R. 1834 would undercut the nation's job safety<br>
laws by changing the emphasis of job safety agencies like OSHA from<br>
enforcement to consultation, by stripping away worker rights and by<br>
weakening safeguards that protect workers.<br>
<br>
Each year, more than 55,000 Americans die because of workplace<br>
hazards, while 7 million more are injured. Where such agencies as<br>
the Occupational Safety and Health Administration have focused<br>
their resources, the number of deaths and injuries has fallen. The<br>
message to the hearings is that America's workers seek to extend<br>
safety and health protections, not weaken them. <br>
<br>
Ron Hayes of Fairhope, Ala., will testify on the death of his<br>
19-year-old son, Patrick, who was &quot;walking the corn&quot; in a huge<br>
grain elevator while machinery was engaged beneath him. He was<br>
sucked down and suffocated in the corn. Hayes has formed a national<br>
organization of family members of workplace victims.<br>
<br>
Working men and women across the country are using a national<br>
media campaign to focus attention on Republican members of Congress<br>
for their attacks on job safety protections, Medicare and other<br>
programs that assist working families. Television ads that are part<br>
of a million-dollar buy are running in the Greenville-Spartanburg,<br>
S.C., area.<br>
###<br>
<br>
For detailed information on H.R. 1834 and its impact, contact Keith<br>
Mestrich in the AFL-CIO Department of Occupational Safety and<br>
Health at 202/637-5210, or Colleen O'Neill in the AFL-CIO<br>
Department of Information at 202/637-5027.</p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="/publ/publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
</body>

