<html>

<head>
<title>PR 08/21/95 Action Update</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>                                    AFL-CIO Action Update<br>
                                    Monday, Aug. 21, 1995<br>
<br>
       LEGISLATIVE -- At a news conference this morning, AFL-CIO<br>
President Tom Donahue unveiled a series of television and radio ads<br>
-- a media buy totaling nearly $1 million -- targeting Republican<br>
legislators who have voted to slash worker protections and programs<br>
to instead serve their wealthy business benefactors. <br>
<br>
       In the ads, Ron Hayes, whose 19-year-old son was killed on the<br>
job, laments that the House has slashed job safety and health<br>
protections and many other programs that working families count on.<br>
Hayes was at the news conference with Donahue this morning.<br>
<br>
       The ads will run in 26 targeted congressional districts, many<br>
of which will feature press conferences by local union leaders held<br>
simultaneously with the Donahue event, the biggest expansion yet of<br>
the federation's Stand UP campaign. The ads will continue for two<br>
weeks, then move onto national and Washington, D.C., media as the<br>
lawmakers return after Labor Day. <br>
<br>
       The ad concludes: ``Tell Congress to stop pandering to big<br>
business and the rich and stand up for America's Working<br>
Families.'' <br>
<br>
<br>
       SOLIDARITY -- Donahue sent letters to retail chains that are<br>
still advertising in the Detroit News-Free Press scab paper,<br>
warning the advertisers that the AFL-CIO will organize leafleting<br>
at their outlets telling customers about their complicity with the<br>
union-busting efforts of management. The AFL-CIO also petitioned<br>
U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno to declare that the joint<br>
operating agreement for the News and Free Press is illegal and not<br>
protected from antitrust challenges. In asking for the Justice<br>
Department investigation, Donahue called the JOA ``an illegal<br>
price-fixing cartel.''<br>
<br>
<br>
       DIVERSITY -- AFL-CIO Secretary-Treasurer Barbara Easterling,<br>
the pioneering first woman of American labor who is herself Exhibit<br>
A in diversity, will be among the featured speakers at an Oct. 20-<br>
21 conference in New York City, the first ever joint session for<br>
federation support groups. AFL-CIO President Tom Donahue launched<br>
the conference on Aug. 2, his first full day as president of the<br>
AFL-CIO in order to emphasize the priority he puts on full<br>
participation by women, people of color and youth. The session will<br>
be held in New York Oct. 20-21 in advance of the AFL-CIO<br>
convention. Also addressing the groups -- which include the Asian<br>
Pacific American Labor Alliance, the A. Philip Randolph Institute,<br>
the Coalition of Black Trade Unionists, the Coalition of Labor<br>
Union Women, FRONTLASH and the Labor Council for Latin American<br>
Advancement -- will be Lenore Miller, chair of the civil rights<br>
committee; John Sturdivant, chair of the committee on full<br>
participation; and Linda Chavez-Thompson, an AFSCME vice president<br>
and a vice president of the federation.<br>
<br>
<br>
       POLITICAL ORGANIZERS -- Next week is the launch of a critical<br>
phase of Susan Washington's vital work in arming union sisters and<br>
brothers with the tools they need to be more effective in lobbying<br>
and political action. Washington, who has an extensive background<br>
in union education, was tapped by Donahue to put together the team<br>
needed to fulfill Donahue's goal to ``intensify AFL-CIO political<br>
efforts, including training 500 grass roots labor lobbyists over<br>
the next 12 months.'' Washington starts Aug. 27-28, with AFL-CIO<br>
staff, and she expects to devise the model program through<br>
consultation with affiliate staff -- directors of education,<br>
legislative and COPE departments -- as well as with the retiree<br>
groups and other activists well noted for making the program go in<br>
the past. <br>
<br>
       ``From New England, from Colorado and from Iowa, we've got the<br>
makings of a model program,'' Washington says, ``what we need now<br>
is to add the unique experiences of our affiliates who now have<br>
very effective grass-roots action programs.'' Washington says the<br>
first step is a manual that organizes everyone's best<br>
recommendations, and then it's into the field <br>
<br>
       In appointing Washington, Donahue said the program she's<br>
spearheading &quot;will be the most intense political effort in the<br>
history of the federation -- and I am determined that it will be<br>
the most successful. Make no mistake about it, if we falter here,<br>
all else falters.&quot;          <br>
<br>
<br>
       TOM on TV  -- Donahue is preparing to meet Service Employees<br>
President John Sweeney, who is running for AFL-CIO president at the<br>
October convention, in a joint appearance before a California AFL-<br>
CIO conference on Thursday, Aug. 24. Joint appearances also are<br>
scheduled on National Public Radio Aug. 30, Meet the Press (NBC)<br>
Sept. 3 and MacNeil-Lehrer News Hour (PBS) on Sept. 4.<br>
<br>
                                             ###<br>
<br>
       (Action Update is designed to bring the most recent AFL-CIO<br>
activities to your attention, emphasizing events that need maximum<br>
participation. It is complemented by the Issues Update fax service,<br>
which emphasizes talking points on worker issues. For more<br>
information, contact AFL-CIO Press Secretary Candice Johnson at<br>
202/637-5010, FAX 202/508-6908 or LaborNET 71363,204. Action Update<br>
is available on LaborNET in the Public Statements library.)</p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="/publ/publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a> | <a href="../publsear.htm">Public Documents Search</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
</body>

</html>
