<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML//EN">

<html>

<head>
<title>PR 08/21/95 campaign against the Republican attack on working families</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>For immediate release Contact: Candice Johnson<br>
August 21, 1995 at 202/637-5010<br>
<br>
Remarks of AFL-CIO President Tom Donahue on labor's congressional<br>
recess campaign against the Republican attack on working families: <br>
<br>
Since January, the Republicans in Congress have launched an<br>
all-out assault on America's working families -- attacking jobs,<br>
wages, health and safety, and the right to a real voice on the job.<br>
<br>
This month, this GOP attack reached a new level with the House<br>
of Representatives vote on funding for the Departments of Labor,<br>
Education and Health and Human Services. In this bill, Republicans<br>
slashed proven health and safety protections that save lives; they<br>
cut college loans for more than 4 million middle-class families;<br>
they cut back elementary and secondary education; they stripped<br>
workers of fundamental rights on the job. <br>
<br>
And they're not through yet. Republicans are plotting a raid<br>
on Medicare -- the program that retired workers and their families<br>
count on -- to the tune of some $270 billion. And where will all<br>
these so-called savings go? To help pay for a $245 billion tax<br>
break that primarily benefits big business and the wealthy, those<br>
who earn more than $200,000 a year.<br>
<br>
Stand UP for America's Working Families is the AFL-CIO's<br>
national effort to expose these Republican votes against workers<br>
and their families, and in favor of their rich friends. It's our<br>
campaign to let the American people know the truth about what the<br>
Republicans are doing in Washington, and what else they have<br>
planned. <br>
<br>
Union activists now are out working in some three dozen<br>
congressional districts, trying to meet with their member of<br>
Congress, joining town hall meetings, and taking to the streets and<br>
sidewalks, when necessary, to stand up to the actions of this<br>
Republican Congress. <br>
<br>
Backing up these activities, the AFL-CIO has placed television<br>
and radio ads in 26 targeted congressional districts. The ads tell<br>
members of Congress when they voted to cut health and safety,<br>
education and Medicare, they attacked working people back home.<br>
Union activists and supporters in those districts are holding<br>
events and news conferences like this one this week, to make sure<br>
the Stand Up message is clear. <br>
<br>
A $1 million media campaign is complementing the grassroots<br>
work of union members and their families. This message to member of<br>
Congress: to stop their attack on working families -- will be heard<br>
both in home districts starting today and nationally after Labor<br>
Day when Congress returns. <br>
<br>
And over the next 15 months, working men and women will<br>
continue to hold their elected officials accountable for every<br>
vote, for every position, for every attack on working families.<br>
<br>
####<br>
<br>
Statement of Ron Hayes<br>
AFL-CIO Press Conference<br>
August 21, 1995<br>
<br>
On October 22, 1993, my son Patrick went to work, but he never came<br>
home. That day, Patrick was crushed to death in the silo where he<br>
worked.<br>
<br>
My son was just 19 years old when he died.<br>
<br>
Before he died, Patrick said that his supervisors at the mill would<br>
sometimes tell him to do things that were unsafe and illegal. And<br>
on the day he died, Patrick was told to ``walk down the corn'' --<br>
to go to the top of the bin and scrape the kernels off the sides of<br>
the silo while an augur at the bottom slowly sucked the corn down.<br>
``Walking down the corn'' is extremely dangerous -- and it's<br>
against the law.<br>
<br>
Patrick was a hard worker and a good employee. He did as his<br>
supervisors told him -- and he was killed for it. I am still<br>
haunted by the pain I saw in Patrick's face when -- after five and<br>
a half hours -- the rescue crews finally pulled his body out of the<br>
bin.<br>
<br>
Patrick's company thought they could get away with breaking the law<br>
because OSHA already had so few inspectors to enforce health and<br>
safety protections -- protections that are supposed to save lives.<br>
<br>
When businesses are allowed to take that chance, people die.<br>
<br>
But the Republicans in Congress just voted to cut enforcement of<br>
health and safety laws even more -- to cut inspections and scrap<br>
some protections altogether. They're telling businesses that it's<br>
okay to gamble with workers' lives.<br>
<br>
But it is not okay that more than six thousand people like Patrick<br>
die at work every year.<br>
<br>
We need to make health and safety protections stronger -- not<br>
weaker. We don't need to cut OSHA -- we need to improve OSHA so<br>
that safety laws are properly enforced. That's the only way big<br>
businesses will understand that they cannot get away with breaking<br>
the law and risking people's lives.<br>
<br>
My son is gone forever -- but Congress can still save lives. They<br>
can stop cutting inspections and enforcement, stop making health<br>
and safety protections weaker -- and start protecting working<br>
people like Patrick Hayes.<br>
<br>
###<br>
<br>
FACT: The Republican assault on working families<br>
<br>
The Republican leadership in Congress is using the budget<br>
process to slash worker protections and programs that benefit<br>
working families to pay for a huge tax giveaway to the rich and big<br>
corporations.<br>
<br>
The budget resolution passed by Congress in July calls for<br>
cuts of $180 billion in Medicaid and $270 billion in Medicare, as<br>
well as $10 billion in student loans. The appropriations bill for Labor <br>
and Health and Human Services, passed by the House before the August <br>
recess, includes:<br>
<br>
* A one-third cut in Occupational Safety and Health<br>
enforcement. About half of the federal inspectors would face<br>
layoffs, and 50,000 more workplace injuries and deaths could occur<br>
each year.<br>
<br>
* A 12 percent cut in activities to prevent illegal<br>
sweatshops, child labor violations and violations of wage-and-hour<br>
laws.<br>
<br>
* A 30 percent cut in funding for the National Labor Relations<br>
Board, which could force closure of half the NLRB regional offices<br>
and increase dramatically the time it takes to resolve disputes. In<br>
addition, the bill seeks to prevent the board from seeking<br>
injunctions against the most blatant violations of the law.<br>
<br>
* A 7.5 percent cut in the Pension and Welfare Benefits<br>
Administration, which guards the pensions of more than 200 million<br>
Americans.<br>
<br>
The beneficiaries of these cuts in worker programs and<br>
protections are the well-to-do and big business. Tax legislation<br>
passed in April provides 28 percent of its benefit to the<br>
wealthiest Americans. It includes:<br>
<br>
* A reduction in capital gains taxes that would provide 58<br>
percent of the benefit to families making $200,000 a year or more.<br>
<br>
* A $500-per-child tax credit that would be available to<br>
families who make up to $250,000, who are among the wealthiest 10<br>
percent in America.<br>
<br>
August 1995<br>
Contact Candice Johnson, AFL-CIO Press Secretary, 202/637-5010.<br>
<br>
####<br>
Appropriations and spending bills passed by the Republican-dominated<br>
House of Representatives do serious damage to programs that working<br>
families rely on -- like job safety and health, Medicare and education. <br>
<br>
Occupational Safety and Health<br>
<br>
House Republicans are slashing the workplace health and safety<br>
programs that benefit citizens in every state by voting for big cuts in<br>
funds for federal job safety agencies. <br>
<br>
In Illinois, for example, the number of federal inspectors who will<br>
be able to remain on the job drops from 78 to 52. With that lower number<br>
of inspectors, it will take 205 years for each workplace to be inspected<br>
just once. In New Jersey, workers will have to wait 199 years for a<br>
workplace inspection; Nebraskans will be waiting an unthinkable 280 years.<br>
The outlook for other states is equally grim.<br>
<br>
Medicare <br>
<br>
Retirees and working families will certainly see their out-of-pocket<br>
Medicare costs shoot up if the House appropriations action stands. The<br>
GOP's seven-year budget plan will cost each beneficiary an average $2,825<br>
over that period. Florida retirees will take the biggest hit -- an whopping<br>
$4,400, but seniors in California and Massachusetts will also at least<br>
$4,000 in out-of-pocket costs.<br>
<br>
This shifting of costs to retired workers and families is wrong. The<br>
Medicare programs needs some serious adjustments, most health care experts<br>
agree, but tough federal cost controls on private and public health care<br>
costs are the only real solution.<br>
<br>
Our nation must pull together to repair our health care system, and<br>
not allow industry special interests to dictate the direction that reform<br>
will take.<br>
<br>
For more information, contact Colleen O'Neill at the AFL-CIO, 202/637-5010.</p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="/publ/publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
