<head>
<title>PR 08/17/95 AFL-CIO's Fight for America's Working Families</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>For immediate release Contact: Candice Johnson<br>
August 17, 1995 at 202/637-5010<br>
<br>
AFL-CIO's Fight for America's Working Families<br>
<br>
AFL-CIO President Tom Donahue will meet with reporters Monday,<br>
August 21, at 10 a.m., in the AFL-CIO lobby, 815 16th St., N.W.,<br>
Washington, D.C., on the latest round in labor's campaign for<br>
America's working families.<br>
<br>
The campaign, in full swing for the August congressional recess,<br>
includes a $1 million media buy complementing the &quot;back home&quot; lobbying<br>
of union members in some three dozen congressional districts. The ads<br>
will be shown at the Donahue news conference.<br>
<br>
A mix of television and radio ads go on the air in 26 of those<br>
36 congressional districts beginning Monday, August 21 and continue<br>
for two weeks.<br>
<br>
In one of the ads, Ron Hayes, whose 19-year-old son was killed<br>
on the job, tells viewers that a recent House funding vote slashes<br>
job safety and health protections and many other programs that<br>
working families count on. The message continues: &quot;tell Congress<br>
to stop pandering to big business and the rich and stand up for<br>
America's Working Families.&quot;<br>
<br>
Members of Congress will hear that same message when they<br>
return to Congress after Labor Day, with ads placed nationally and<br>
in Washington, D.C.<br>
<br>
Union legislative action committees will meet with their<br>
senators and representatives or will join in town meetings over the<br>
recess to spotlight recent congressional actions that will cut job<br>
health and safety, Medicare and education in order to help finance<br>
a $245 billion tax cut that mostly benefits the wealthy.<br>
<br>
Stand UP for America's Working Families is the AFL-CIO's<br>
national effort to focus attention on the need for good jobs, good<br>
wages, health and safety and a real voice on the job.</p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="/publ/publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
</body>

</html>
