<head>
<title>PR 08/16/95 AFL-CIO's AFL-CIO Asks Reno to Pull Detroit Antitrust Protections</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE                            CONTACT: James B. Parks<br>
August 16, 1995                                           of the AFL-CIO<br>
                                                          at 202/637-5010<br>
<br>
        AFL-CIO Asks Reno to Pull Detroit Antitrust Protections <br>
<br>
     The AFL-CIO and the unions representing Detroit newspaper<br>
employees today petitioned Attorney General Janet Reno to declare<br>
that the joint operating agreement for the Detroit News and Detroit<br>
Free Press is not protected from antitrust challenges. <br>
<br>
     In announcing the petition, AFL-CIO President Tom Donahue said<br>
the Justice Department's Antitrust Division has also been asked to<br>
investigate and take action against the two newspapers' joint<br>
operating agreement which amounts to an illegal price-fixing<br>
cartel.<br>
<br>
     The original Detroit joint operating agreement was approved by<br>
Attorney General Edwin Meese in 1988. But that agreement was<br>
significantly amended in 1992 and the new agreement has not been<br>
approved by the Attorney General. <br>
<br>
     The newspapers are relying on the amended agreement to justify<br>
their attempt to break the strike of their employees by publishing<br>
joint daily and weekend editions.  <br>
<br>
     The 2,600 employees of the News and Free Press have been on<br>
strike since July 13 after negotiations failed to produce a new<br>
agreement.<br>
<br>
     For further information or copies of the petition, contact<br>
James B. Parks at 202/637-5010.</p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="/publ/publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
</body>

