<head>
<title>PR 08/15/95 AFL-CIO Announces National Campaign Against Detroit Papers</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>For Immediate Release Contact: Candice Johnson at the AFL-CIO<br>
August 15, 1995 202/637-5010, and George Curtin <br>
in Detroit at 313/965-1478.<br>
<br>
AFL-CIO Announces National Campaign Against Detroit Papers<br>
<br>
The AFL-CIO Strategic Approaches Committee announced a<br>
nationwide campaign against the Detroit newspapers and their parent<br>
companies, Gannett and Knight-Ridder. <br>
<br>
The campaign will draw on resources from the AFL-CIO and all<br>
of the federation's affiliated unions to coordinate activities in<br>
support of striking Detroit newspaper workers.<br>
<br>
The AFL-CIO program includes:<br>
<br>
* Ensuring strike benefits for all striking workers through a<br>
$1 million fund created by the AFL-CIO and affiliated unions.<br>
<br>
* Initiating a nationwide campaign targeting six companies<br>
that continue to place advertisements in the struck newspapers --<br>
J.C. Penney, Lord &amp; Taylor, Target, Home Depot, Hudsons, and<br>
Montgomery Ward. <br>
<br>
AFL-CIO President Tom Donahue has written these companies<br>
informing them that if they continue to advertise in the Detroit<br>
papers, union members nationwide will be alerted that these<br>
companies are attacking the Detroit unions by continuing to<br>
advertise in a scab-produced paper. <br>
<br>
* Solidarity activities at Gannett and Knight-Ridder<br>
operations nationwide. <br>
<br>
* A Labor Day mobilization in the Detroit area. <br>
<br>
``On Labor Day weekend in Detroit, we plan to send a clear<br>
message to Gannett, Knight-Ridder and to every employer just like<br>
them that we will not tolerate corporations which make record<br>
profits but set out to destroy the living standards of workers and<br>
their families,'' said Mine Workers President Richard Trumka, chair<br>
of the Strategic Approaches Committee.</p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="/publ/publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
</body>

