<head>
<title>PR 08/09/95 Easterling becomes Secretary-Treasurer</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>                         BARBARA J. EASTERLING<br>
<br>
                     Secretary-Treasurer, AFL-CIO<br>
<br>
<br>
      Barbara J. Easterling was elected Secretary-Treasurer of the<br>
AFL-CIO in August 1995, thereby becoming the first woman to hold a top<br>
post at the federation.  Easterling, 62, is also the first woman to<br>
serve as Secretary-Treasurer of the Communications Workers of America,<br>
having held that office from April 1992 to August 1995.  Before that,<br>
she served seven years as an elected Executive Vice President of the<br>
CWA.<br>
<br>
      As AFL-CIO Secretary-Treasurer, Easterling is the federation's<br>
chief financial officer, managing all of its financial matters and its<br>
day-to-day operations.  Her duties also include conducting a complete<br>
review of AFL-CIO staff operations, recruitment and development with an<br>
eye toward increasing and insuring diversity.  Easterling is also<br>
assisting President Thomas R. Donahue in efforts to increase the AFL-CIO<br>
s commitment to organizing American workers, to institute reforms in the<br>
decision-making and governing processes of the AFL-CIO and to create the<br>
most intense grassroots political effort in the history of the<br>
federation.<br>
<br>
      Easterling serves as a member of the executive committee of the<br>
Postal, Telegraph and Telephone International (PTTI) and as the elected<br>
Secretary-Treasurer of the Regional Organization of Workers-Continental<br>
Branch of the International Confederation of Free Trade Unions (ICFTU).<br>
<br>
      Strong Union Principles: Easterling is proud to have brought to<br>
her union career the strong principles of trade unionism she learned as<br>
a child growing up in a Polish family of coal miners and rubber workers<br>
in Akron, Ohio.  Launching her career as an operator at Ohio Bell, she<br>
incorporated those principles into her own life by the time she joined<br>
CWA Local 4302 in Akron.  Easterling served the local as steward,<br>
Secretary and Vice President before accepting an appointment by Ohio<br>
governor John Gilligan to serve as Chief of the Ohio Labor Division in<br>
early 1970.<br>
<br>
      In 1973, she left state government to become a full-time CWA staff<br>
representative and later was promoted to Administrative Assistant to the<br>
Vice President of District 4.  In 1980, she was summoned to Washington,<br>
D.C., to serve as an Assistant to the President of the union -- a<br>
position she held until her election as Executive Vice President in<br>
1985.<br>
<br>
      As Secretary-Treasurer of CWA, Easterling was responsible for<br>
managing the finances and physical facilities of CWA.  She served as a<br>
member of the union's three-member executive committee as well as the<br>
strategic planning and budget committee, which allocates CWA's resources<br>
and sets program goals.  In addition to these constitutional roles, she<br>
also carried out key assignments in the areas of international affairs<br>
and oversaw the government relations and political affairs departments.<br>
<br>
      Honors and Activities: Easterling has received a broad range of<br>
honors and accolades during her union career, reflecting her wide range<br>
of interests.<br>
<br>
      She was inducted into the Ohio Women's Hall of Fame in 1985 and<br>
received the prestigious Women's Equity Action League award in 1986.  In<br>
1992, she was honored by the Midwest Labor Press Association (an<br>
affiliate of the International Labor Communications Association of the<br>
AFL-CIO) as recipient of the association's Eugene V. Debs award.<br>
Previous recipients of the Debs award have included Hubert Humphrey,<br>
Lane Kirkland and the presidents of various international unions.<br>
<br>
      Easterling is an at-large member of the Democratic National<br>
Committee, Vice Chair of the National Alliance to End Homelessness,<br>
Trustee of the National Planning Association (NPA), vice chair of the<br>
NPA's Global Economic Council, and has been a leader in the fight to<br>
raise money for the Pediatric AIDS Foundation.  She also serves on the<br>
board of directors of the National Democratic Institute for<br>
International Affairs and served on the executive boards of the AFL-CIO<br>
s Department of Professional Employees and the Industrial Union<br>
Department.</p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="/publ/publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
</body>

