<html>

<head>
<title>PR 08/09/95 Donahue elected President of the AFL-CIO</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>THOMAS R. DONAHUE<br>
<br>
President, AFL-CIO<br>
<br>
<br>
Thomas R. Donahue was elected President of the AFL-CIO by the<br>
federation's Executive Council at its August 1995 meeting. Donahue had<br>
served as Secretary-Treasurer of the AFL-CIO from November 1979 through<br>
August 1995, having been re-elected to the post every two years. From<br>
May 1973 until 1979 he was Executive Assistant to AFL-CIO President<br>
George Meany.<br>
<br>
He served as Executive Secretary and was twice elected as First<br>
Vice President of the Service Employees International Union between<br>
January 1969 and May 1973.<br>
<br>
Prior to 1969, he served as U.S. Assistant Secretary of Labor for<br>
Labor-Management Relations, a post to which he was appointed by former<br>
President Lyndon B. Johnson in January 1967. In that capacity, he was<br>
responsible for the Department's labor relations activities and was<br>
administrator of the Department's Labor-Management Service<br>
Administration.<br>
<br>
Before his appointment to the Labor Department, Donahue served for<br>
seven years as Executive Assistant to the President of the Service<br>
Employees International Union. SEIU, now the fourth largest union in<br>
the AFL-CIO, represents building maintenance employees and health care<br>
workers throughout the United States and Canada.<br>
<br>
Donahue was born September 4, 1928, in the Bronx, New York, the<br>
youngest of four children of Thomas R. And Mary E. Donahue. After<br>
attending parochial school and Mt. St. Michael's Academy in the Bronx,<br>
he received a BA in labor relations from Manhattan College in 1949 and<br>
an LL.B. from Fordham University Law School (Evening Division) in 1956.<br>
<br>
During his student years, Donahue worked as doorman at Radio City,<br>
bakery worker, truck driver, auto mechanic's helper, school bus driver,<br>
elevator operator and a wire lather.<br>
<br>
He began his labor career in 1948 as a part-time organizer for the<br>
Retail Clerks International Association. From 1949 to 1957, Donahue<br>
served successively as business agent, contract director, publications<br>
editor and assistant to the President of Local 32B, Service Employees<br>
International Union. The second-largest local union in the U.S., Local<br>
32B represents custodial and maintenance workers in commercial and<br>
residential buildings in New York City.<br>
<br>
From 1957 to 1960, he was European labor-program coordinator for<br>
the Free Europe Committee, headquartered in Paris and handling liaison<br>
with West European trade unions and trade unionists in exile from<br>
countries in Central and Eastern Europe.<br>
<br>
He is a member of the Board of Directors of the Muscular Dystrophy<br>
Association, the African-American Institute, the American Arbitration<br>
Association, the Work in America Institute, the National Planning<br>
Association, the Council on Foreign Relations and the Kennedy Center,<br>
and is member of the Board of Trustees of Manhattan College. He is a<br>
member of the President's Commission on Sustainable Development and a<br>
member of the Advisory Council on Unemployment Compensation. Donahue<br>
serves as Chairman of the U.S. Special Trade Representative's Labor<br>
Advisory Committee.<br>
<br>
In 1983, he was the North American spokesman at the Vatican<br>
Convocation on the Papal Encyclical Of Human Work issued by Pope John<br>
Paul II.<br>
<br>
In the AFL-CIO, he has served as Chairman of the Committee on<br>
Evolution of Work which has issued three reports outlining future<br>
courses of growth and development for America's unions. He has<br>
represented the AFL-CIO at a wide variety of international meetings<br>
throughout the world and has headed AFL-CIO and international trade<br>
union delegations to Lebanon, Northern Ireland, Chile, South Africa,<br>
Nicaragua and El Salvador.<br>
<br>
He has received honorary degrees from the University of Notre<br>
Dame, Loyola University (Chicago), the State University of New York,<br>
Manhattan College and the University of Massachusetts at Amherst. He<br>
was honored by the Fordham University School of Law with the<br>
presentation of the Dean's Medal of Recognition.</p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="/publ/publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
