<html>

<head>
<title>PR 06/28/95  AFL-CIO Launches July 4 Lobbying, Media Campaign </title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>For Immediate Release                        Contact: Bill Wagner<br>
June 28, 1995                                        202/637-5334<br>
<br>
<br>
        AFL-CIO Launches July 4 Lobbying, Media Campaign <br>
<br>
Secretary-Treasurer Tom Donahue made the following announcement on the AFL-CIO's Stand<br>
UP Campaign:<br>
<br>
<br>
     Today, the AFL-CIO continues our effort to give voice to the working men and women<br>
whose interests are being abused in the current Congress. This part of the campaign to Stand<br>
UP for America's working families is timed to the Fourth of July recess when members of<br>
Congress will be at home.<br>
<br>
     The campaign began with the seating of the 104th Congress and has included intensive<br>
back home lobbying efforts in the previous recesses in April and for Memorial Day. Those<br>
efforts focused on a smaller number of districts and this is our biggest media effort to date.<br>
<br>
     The Fourth of July effort is in 30 congressional districts, where workers and their<br>
unions will seek meetings with members of Congress to discuss the issues with them. They<br>
will also conduct rallies, pass out leaflets and do all they can to focus attention on their needs.<br>
<br>
     Our TV and radio advertising starts today and will continue through July 8 on TV and<br>
radio -- using local TV stations, national cable TV and local radio. The ads carry a very direct<br>
message: the current Republican majority in Congress continues to be willing to pay for tax<br>
breaks for the rich by cutting the programs working families need if they're to be able to hold<br>
on to a part of the American dream -- programs like college loans, health and safety, job<br>
training, school lunches and medicare.<br>
<br>
     And working Americans will be delivering that same message in face-to-face meetings<br>
with Members of Congress who agree to meet with them.<br>
<br>
     Health and safety provides probably the best example of the distorted priorities of this<br>
Congress. Last November, working Americans did NOT vote to dismantle the job safety<br>
protections provided by the Occupational Safety and Health Act -- protections which cut<br>
workplace fatalities by more than half and cut injury and illness incidence a third in past 20<br>
years. Yet, a dismantling of OSHA is exactly what was proposed last week in the a bill<br>
introduced in the House by Representative Cass Ballenger of North Carolina. <br>
<br>
     While this is the newest and biggest of the efforts thus far in the AFL-CIO's campaign<br>
to Stand UP for America's working families. But the idea behind this Fourth of July effort is<br>
by no means new -- and it's a continuation of our efforts to insure that members of Congress<br>
have ample opportunity to hear from working Americans in their districts -- and not just from<br>
the corporate lobbyists.<br>
<br>
     The Stand UP Campaign resulted from a lot of self-examination by the Federation and<br>
our affiliated unions following last November's election. Through extensive meetings with local<br>
leadership, member polls and focus groups, we took the gauge of union members.<br>
<br>
     Many hours of discussion with union presidents and staff and all of that led to the<br>
conviction that we needed a major overhaul of our grassroots operations. The Stand UP<br>
campaign is our vehicle for reaching that goal, a grassroots campaign to hold onto a piece of<br>
the American dream for millions of working families who are already having a tough time<br>
making ends meet.<br>
<br>
     The Campaign uses home-district meetings with members of Congress and phone calls<br>
from worksites, using cellular phones and our 800 number routing system to the Capitol, to<br>
enable union working families to make their views known. To date, over 21,000 calls have<br>
been logged on our 800 number, and some 1500 union members from 60 different unions have<br>
participated in 92 meetings. Our field staff and the staff of affiliates provide the coordination<br>
and other work necessary to a successful Fourth of July effort.<br>
<br>
     The ads have been placed in 20 districts, with TV ads in six regional areas and radio<br>
in 12 markets that cover 14 congressional districts. In all, ads cost about $500,000.<br>
<br>
     The TV ads will run on local stations in Eureka, Calif.; Terre Haute, Ind.; Tulsa, Okla.;<br>
Chattanooga, Tenn.; Beaumont-Port Arthur, Texas and Casper-Riverton, Wyo.<br>
<br>
     Like the local TV ads, the radio ads are customized to carry the name of the member<br>
of Congress with the AFL-CIO 800 number to the Capitol. The 12 radio markets covering 14<br>
congressional districts are Bridgeport, Conn., Atlanta; Chicago and Peoria, Ill.; Boston; Las<br>
Vegas; Rochester/Buffalo, N.Y.; Raleigh-Durham, N.C.; Rural Ohio Radio; Portland, Ore.;<br>
Philadelphia and Seattle.<br>
<br>
     The other districts with coordinated union member activity are in Alabama, Minnesota,<br>
Mississippi, South Carolina, Virginia and two districts in California not covered by Eureka TV.</p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="/publ/publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
