<head>
<title>PR 06/26/95 AFL-CIO Observers Find Haiti Elections Honest, Fair </title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE                              CONTACT: James Parks<br>
June 26, 1995                                          or Michael Byrne<br>
                                                         of the AFL-CIO<br>
                                                           202/637-5010<br>
<br>
          AFL-CIO OBSERVERS FIND HAITI ELECTIONS HONEST, FAIR<br>
<br>
The AFL-CIO issued the following statement, based on reports from seven union observers to<br>
the June 25 elections in Haiti:<br>
<br>
     Despite some initial confusion and disorganization, the Haitian legislative and municipal<br>
elections are honest and fair.<br>
<br>
     Because Haiti has very limited experience with democratic voting, it would be unfair<br>
and inaccurate to judge its elections by the same standards as those in the United States or<br>
Europe, which have longer histories of free elections.<br>
<br>
     The difficulties in the elections -- late openings, missing ballots, etc. -- were the result<br>
of inexperience, not sabotage or incompetence. The lack of widespread violence also is to be<br>
commended.<br>
<br>
     The 50 percent turnout, by any standard, is a good one and demonstrates the<br>
determination of the Haitian people to be free.<br>
<br>
     Haiti, only a few months ago, was in the grips of a repressive military regime and<br>
suffered from a lack of infrastructure and basic necessities. To have been able to conduct an<br>
election at all in such a short time is a minor miracle.<br>
<br>
     As Haiti becomes more experienced with democratic elections, the kind of problems that<br>
occurred June 25 may be expected to decrease.<br>
<br>
     The U.S. labor federation also commends the Haitian pollworkers, many of whom<br>
worked beyond what was expected, to make this election a success.</p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="/publ/publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
</body>

