<head>
<title>PR 05/16/95 Statement on the National Performance Review's Reinventing OSHA Report </title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>For Immediate Release                      Contact: Colleen M. O'Neill<br>
May 16, 1995                                              202/637-5010<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
The AFL-CIO made the following statement upon the release of the<br>
National Performance Review's Reinventing OSHA Report:<br>
<br>
<br>
      The AFL-CIO endorses the goal of the National Performance<br>
Review's Reinventing OSHA Report -- to improve worker safety and<br>
health by making OSHA a more effective agency.<br>
<br>
      We welcome President Clinton's pledge to protect the nation's<br>
job safety laws and programs from attacks by the Republican<br>
Congress.<br>
<br>
      We particularly support those initiatives designed to focus<br>
OSHA's attention on the most serious hazards and the most dangerous<br>
workplaces, and to address continuing safety and health problems,<br>
such as ergonomic hazards.<br>
<br>
      The NPR document outlines new initiatives aimed at enhancing<br>
health and safety through incentives for employers. There's nothing<br>
wrong with promoting voluntary compliance, but it is important to<br>
remember that under the Occupational Safety and Health Act, it's<br>
not OSHA's job to be the friend of employers -- it's to protect<br>
American workers from serious hazards through promulgation of<br>
effective standards and strong enforcement of the law.<br>
<br>
      Initiatives directed at voluntary compliance will only work<br>
when coupled with meaningful standards and enforcement efforts.</p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="/publ/publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
</body>

