<html>

<head>
<title>PR 05/10/95 AFL-CIO Supports Clinton on Japan Trade. </title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>For Immediate Release                        Contact: David Kameras<br>
May 10, 1995                                           202/637-5017<br>
<br>
<br>
              AFL-CIO SUPPORTS CLINTON ON JAPAN TRADE<br>
<br>
<br>
The AFL-CIO issued the following statement on the Clinton<br>
administration's move to impose trade sanctions over Japan's<br>
restrictive trade policies on autos and auto parts. <br>
<br>
     The AFL-CIO applauds the Clinton administration's tough stance<br>
with Japan. After months of trade talks, it is now time for<br>
results.<br>
<br>
     In order to reach a results-oriented agreement with Japan, it<br>
is necessary now to move forward with the Sections 301 and 304 case<br>
against restrictive policies and practices of Japan, which deny<br>
U.S. access to the Japanese auto parts replacement and accessories<br>
market.<br>
<br>
     American workers in a wide range of industries and occupations<br>
would benefit from the reduction of the U.S. deficit in automotive<br>
trade with Japan and the elimination of discriminatory practices by<br>
Japanese companies directed at U.S. firms.<br>
<br>
     Union members in the rubber, glass, steel, aluminum, textile,<br>
machine tool, chemical, electrical, electronics and other<br>
industries would directly benefit from increased access to the<br>
Japanese auto market for competitive American products. Unionized<br>
workers in other industries, including entertainment,<br>
telecommunications, construction, aerospace and paper, would gain<br>
additional jobs if the Japanese market were truly open and<br>
discrimination against U.S. producers was ended.<br>
<br>
     Ambassador Kantor was correct when he said, &quot;Japan remains<br>
unwilling to take the steps necessary to bring genuine market<br>
access and concrete results in a sector in which Japan has a $37<br>
billion trade surplus with the U.S.&quot;<br>
<br>
     If the auto trade deficit with Japan is reduced substantially,<br>
President Clinton's effort to establish equity in the bilateral<br>
trading relationship could create many thousands of American jobs.</p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="/publ/publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
</body>

</html>
</DOC>
