<html>

<head>
<title>PR 05/09/95 Hatian Labor Rep Wins Red Cross Award</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE                          CONTACT: James B. Parks<br>
May 9, 1995                                             of the AFL-CIO<br>
                                                       at 202/637-5022<br>
<br>
                HAITIAN LABOR REP WINS RED CROSS AWARD <br>
<br>
      Georges Exceus, labor's representative in Haiti and one of the<br>
heroes of the Haitian democracy movement has been named to receive<br>
the American Red Cross 1995 International Humanitarian Service<br>
Award.<br>
<br>
       A Haitian-American from Miami, Exceus, 42, returned to his<br>
native land to direct the Port-au-Prince office of the AFL-CIO's<br>
American Institute for Free Labor Development, arriving three weeks<br>
before the 1991 coup that overthrew President Jean-Bertrand<br>
Aristide.  <br>
<br>
      After sending his wife and young son back to Miami, Exceus<br>
ignored death threats and constant danger for almost four years, he<br>
managed somehow to get food, clothing and shelter for persecuted<br>
unionists and their families -- and all too often, to arrange for<br>
medical treatment and even funerals for the victims of torture and<br>
murder.<br>
<br>
      ``I was tempted to leave many times. But there was so much to<br>
do, always one more life to save. I was on a mission,'' Exceus<br>
said.  <br>
<br>
      Exceus has hidden hundreds of people from the military over<br>
the past three years and, under the auspices of the AFL-CIO, found<br>
scarce hot food, medicine and hospital services for untold numbers<br>
of suffering Haitians. <br>
<br>
      A former organizer for the Clothing and Textile Workers,<br>
Exceus will receive the award at the Red Cross national convention,<br>
May 20-22 in Tulsa, Okla.</p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="/publ/publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
