<head>
<title>PR 05/05/95 `Come Shop With Me' Puts Consumers on Alert </title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>For immediate release                           Contact: Muriel Cooper<br>
May 5, 1995                                            at 202/637-5010<br>
<br>
<br>
              `Come Shop With Me' Puts Consumers on Alert<br>
<br>
      Shoppers are being warned that the pretty sweater from China<br>
they're considering buying for Mother's Day may have been made by<br>
a child forced to work long hours. <br>
<br>
      ``Come Shop With Me,'' a national education campaign by<br>
congressional, labor and consumer supporters, wants shoppers to<br>
look carefully at the products they're buying -- and the practices<br>
they may indirectly be supporting -- when they shop for Mother's<br>
Day and other gifts. <br>
<br>
      A news conference set for 3 p.m., Tuesday, May 9, Rayburn<br>
House Office Building,  Room HC-8, will highlight the miserable<br>
wages and conditions endured by working women, men and particularly<br>
children to produce many of the brand-name products sought after in<br>
the United States and elsewhere.<br>
<br>
      Rep. Marcy Kaptur (D-Ohio) will be joined by Evelyn Dubrow<br>
(Ladies' Garment Workers) and Jean Hervey (Clothing and Textile<br>
Workers), who head the ``Come Shop With Me'' campaign; Patricia<br>
Scarcelli, Coalition of Labor Union Women; and Linda Golodner,<br>
National Consumers League. <br>
<br>
      They will spotlight presents traditionally given for Mother's<br>
Day -- clothing, roses, shoes -- and will supply the not-so-pretty<br>
facts behind those skirts from India and flowers from Columbia. The<br>
campaign is intended to expose company practices that earn billions<br>
in profits at the expense of millions of workers, and children.<br>
<br>
      The year-long ``Come Shop With Me'' educational campaign began<br>
during the 1994 Christmas shopping season, focusing then on the<br>
labor practices of four well-known corporations -- NIKE, Mattel,<br>
Dole and Van Heusen.</p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="/publ/publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
</body>

</html>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT27-B26-124</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA097-001041-B039-379</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://aflcio.org:80/publ/press95/pr05051.htm 204.127.237.106 19970215075645 text/html 20744
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.1
Date: Saturday, 15-Feb-97 07:56:34 GMT
Last-modified: Tuesday, 11-Feb-97 21:10:56 GMT
Content-length: 20558
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML//EN">

<html>

<head>
<title>PR 05/05/95 Economic Slowdown Trend Is Clear. </title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>                         AFL-CIO Secretary-Treasurer Tom Donahue<br>
               Panel on Wealth at the &quot;Facing the 21st Century&quot; Symposium<br>
                              National Planning Association<br>
                              Washington, D.C., May 5, 1995<br>
<br>
<br>
       I am delighted to be here. It is a special pleasure being on<br>
a panel with Jerry Jasinowski and Bob Reich.<br>
<br>
       You may think of the three of us as somewhat disparate, so let<br>
me begin by noting that today, all three of us appear in the great<br>
tradition of Karl Marx.<br>
<br>
       It is not that we believe in the dictatorship of the<br>
proletariat. Rather, it goes back to a story told by Harold<br>
Macmillan about Marx -- actually, about Marx's wife. She reportedly<br>
complained that it would be nice if her husband would talk less<br>
about wealth and instead make more of it.<br>
<br>
       On this panel, the three of us are doing like Karl. We're here<br>
to talk about wealth and no one is being paid for it. What better<br>
site to do it than Washington's fanciest hotel.<br>
<br>
       The logical starting point for a discussion like ours is to<br>
see how the great, the profound, and the noble have viewed wealth<br>
through the ages. <br>
<br>
       I am happy to share some of their insights with you.<br>
<br>
       The Duchess of Windsor was the first to note that you cannot<br>
be too rich or too thin.<br>
<br>
       But some centuries before that, Horace said, &quot;He is not poor<br>
who has enough of things to use. It is well with your belly, chest,<br>
and feet, the wealth of kings can give you nothing more.&quot;<br>
<br>
       Clearly, Horace was not exactly a role model for the Duchess.<br>
<br>
       A publication called &quot;Off the Wall Street Journal&quot; said, &quot;The<br>
Pluto-American Anti-Defamation League said it will bring pressure<br>
to bear on media to upgrade the image of incredibly rich people.<br>
The newly-formed group, which hopes to combat negative portrayals<br>
of incredibly rich people on television and in print, cited the<br>
crucial role that incredibly rich people have played in American<br>
history, and hopes to restore incredible richness as a `positive<br>
aspect of American life.'&quot;<br>
<br>
       Franklin P. Adams described the life of wealth in a poem:<br>
<br>
       The rich man has his motorcar,<br>
       His country and his town estate,<br>
       He smokes a fifty-cent cigar<br>
       And jeers at Fate.<br>
       He frivols through the livelong day,<br>
       He knows not Poverty her pinch.<br>
       His lot seems light, his heart seems gay,<br>
       He has a cinch.<br>
       Yet though my lamp burns low and dim,<br>
       Though I must slave for livelihood --<br>
       Think you that I would change with him?<br>
       You bet I would!<br>
<br>
       Hilaire Belloc, in a comment that presaged trickle-down<br>
economics, noted, &quot;Lord Finchley tried to mend the 'lectric light<br>
himself; it struck him dead and serve him right; it is the business<br>
of the wealthy man to give employment to the artisan.&quot;<br>
<br>
       On a more serious note, Henry George warned, &quot;So long as all<br>
the increased wealth which modern progress brings goes but to build<br>
up great fortunes, to increase luxury and make sharper the contrast<br>
between the House of Have and the House of Want, progress is not<br>
real and cannot be permanent.&quot;<br>
<br>
       Andrew Carnegie, citing a modern-day problem, wrote in &quot;North<br>
American Review,&quot; &quot;The problem of our age is the proper<br>
administration of wealth, so that the ties of brotherhood may still<br>
bind together the rich and poor in harmonious relationship.&quot;<br>
<br>
       The great Catholic churchman Cardinal Gibbons, in that same<br>
magazine two years later, condemned an economic system in which<br>
&quot;the well-being of the car-horse is more solicitously watched over<br>
than that of the driver.&quot;<br>
<br>
       Lyndon Johnson said in a speech in 1964, &quot;The challenge of the<br>
next half-century is whether we have the wisdom to use [our] wealth<br>
to enrich and elevate our national life -- and to advance the<br>
quality of American civilization.&quot;<br>
<br>
       With 30 years of that half-century gone by, it would be hard<br>
to make the case that we have met the challenge.<br>
<br>
       We should probably give the last word to Sophie Tucker. She<br>
said, &quot;I've been rich and I've been poor. Rich is better.&quot;<br>
<br>
       Our symposium is about looking ahead to the 21st century and<br>
wealth in that era; but let me move in the opposite direction and<br>
talk about something that happened more than a half-century ago.<br>
<br>
       When I was a 10-year-old kid in the North Bronx, there was a<br>
magnificent event that took place over on Long Island, the opening<br>
of the 1939 New York World's Fair. Today, it is hard to convey the<br>
excitement and optimism that surrounded it.<br>
<br>
       Most of the exhibitions were about the future.<br>
<br>
       Visitors to the Westinghouse Building could see a<br>
demonstration of Electro, the walking, talking robot. And in the<br>
RCA Building, they could watch &quot;picture radio&quot;  (this was before<br>
people were using the word &quot;television&quot;).<br>
<br>
       I went with my young friends to the General Motors exhibition,<br>
where we got to ride in a car -- quite an event in those days. We<br>
all fought to see who would ride in the front.<br>
<br>
       Along the road, I remember the driver telling me that in the<br>
future, cars would have only a front seat and they would be wide<br>
enough to seat eight people side by side. This made a very deep<br>
impression on me. I think I was probably 16 before I realized that<br>
this guy had to be kidding.<br>
<br>
       Of all the exhibitions at the Fair, the most ambitious, and<br>
certainly the most expensive, was called Futurama. It aimed to<br>
portray what the United States would be like in 1960.<br>
<br>
       No one had ever seen anything quite like it. You could take a<br>
simulated airplane ride over the imaginary American landscape of<br>
the future, with huge suspension bridges and highway systems full<br>
of underpasses and overpasses.<br>
<br>
       You were told that the city of 1960 would have &quot;abundant<br>
sunshine, fresh air, fine green parkways, recreational and civic<br>
centers -- all the result of thoughtful planning and design.&quot;  <br>
<br>
       And as you were leaving the exhibition, you would get a button<br>
that read, &quot;I Have Seen the Future.&quot;<br>
<br>
       Unfortunately, that button was a bit inaccurate. Today, with<br>
our perfect 20/20 hindsight, we can know where the visionaries of<br>
the Fair were somewhat right, and also where they were<br>
spectacularly wrong. <br>
<br>
       The cautionary lesson is obvious. When people make firm<br>
predictions about the 21st century, you should be very kind to them<br>
and simply write down the predictions so they can be checked later.<br>
<br>
       In fact, the 21st century for us is probably something like a<br>
Rorschach ink blot. Each of us sees in it what we want to see, and<br>
what we hear today has a lot more to do with 1995 than with 2005 or<br>
2055.<br>
<br>
       With that reservation in mind, let's turn to the two questions<br>
that this panel has been asked to address. Let me try to address<br>
wealth in America and its distribution rather than income levels,<br>
which Bob Reich has outlined so well.<br>
<br>
       The first question is: &quot;What is the outlook for the U.S.<br>
standard of living in the 21st century?&quot;<br>
<br>
       This is a very good question. Like all such questions, it is<br>
very hard to answer. It is a bit like asking what yesterday's<br>
weather was in the United States. It was one thing in Fairbanks,<br>
Alaska, another thing in Denver, something very different in Miami<br>
Beach -- and a combination of all of those in Washington, D.C.<br>
<br>
       The point is that if the 21st century is much like 1995, then<br>
the standard of living will be one thing for the poorest fifth of<br>
the population, quite different for the middle class, and vastly<br>
different for the wealthiest part of the population.<br>
<br>
       If we can make one very reliable prediction in our symposium,<br>
it is this. If things continue in the direction they are going now,<br>
then in the 21st century, the United States will have the greatest,<br>
the most flagrant inequality in standards of living of any major<br>
industrialized country in the world.<br>
<br>
       This fact and this trend are tremendously important. They<br>
change what we are as a country. They go to what we value the most.<br>
<br>
       We believe in equality. We take it very seriously and we<br>
always have.<br>
<br>
       There are a thousand examples of it throughout our history. In<br>
the &quot;Federalist Papers,&quot; that great conservative hero Alexander<br>
Hamilton wrote, &quot;Happy it is when the interest which the government<br>
has in the preservation of its own power coincides with a proper<br>
distribution of the public burdens, and tends to guard the least<br>
wealthy part of the community from oppression.&quot;<br>
<br>
       Yet we are now becoming the most unequal of nations. In fact,<br>
there is a Twentieth Century Fund report published last month<br>
called &quot;Top Heavy&quot; that indicates we are already there and it is<br>
only getting worse.<br>
<br>
       The report notes that in 1989, the last year for which we have<br>
figures, the top 1 percent of wealth holders controlled 39 percent<br>
of total household wealth. And if you focus on financial wealth,<br>
the richest 1 percent owned 48 percent of the total.<br>
<br>
       It wasn't always this way. Beginning in 1929 (maybe even<br>
earlier, although we don't have reliable statistics before then)<br>
and going up to 1979, something very healthy happened in this<br>
country. In absolute terms, everyone got richer -- but in relative<br>
terms, the rich got poorer and the poor got richer. We became more<br>
equal.<br>
<br>
       Yet in the 1980s, and especially from 1983 to 1989, America<br>
started moving backwards. The share of the richest 1 percent of<br>
wealth holders went up by 5 percentage points, while the wealth of<br>
the bottom 40 percent had an absolute decline.<br>
<br>
       Indeed, during that period, just about all of the absolute<br>
gains in real wealth in America accrued to the richest 20 percent<br>
of wealth holders.<br>
       In &quot;Top Heavy,&quot; Professor Edward Wolff of New York University<br>
compares what is happening here to other nations. Let me quote its<br>
conclusions: &quot;In the early part of this century... America appeared<br>
to be the land of opportunity, whereas Europe was a place where an<br>
entrenched upper class controlled the bulk of wealth.<br>
<br>
       &quot;By the late 1980s, the situation appears to have completely<br>
reversed, with much higher concentration of wealth in the United<br>
States than in Europe. Europe now appears the land of equality.&quot;<br>
<br>
       I would submit that for a country with our values, this<br>
represents a terrible historic failure. There is no law of nature<br>
that makes it inevitable. We know one of the biggest reasons why<br>
this happened in the 1980s: marginal tax rates for the rich and the<br>
very rich were cut.<br>
<br>
       The Clinton administration's budget bill of two years ago<br>
increased the rates for the very rich, but those rates are still<br>
much lower than they were at the beginning of the 1980s.<br>
<br>
       In a sense, the bonanza that the rich enjoyed in the 1980s was<br>
a huge, wild experiment that ended in disaster. And the disaster<br>
resonates not only in our economic life. It rubs salt into all<br>
sorts of social and political wounds. <br>
<br>
       One of the ways we can sensibly prepare for the 21st century<br>
is to clean up the mess that we created in the last decade.<br>
Personally, I would prefer to tax the wealthiest 1 percent at least<br>
at the rates of 1980. It would be even better to go back to the<br>
progressive structure during the administration of the notorious<br>
revolutionary socialist, Dwight D. Eisenhower. <br>
<br>
       But I also realize that in today's political climate, it is<br>
too much to hope for such change. One splendid and more viable<br>
proposal offered by Professor Wolff is a wealth tax similar to<br>
those in Germany, Switzerland, France, and the Scandinavian<br>
countries.<br>
<br>
       According to &quot;Top Heavy,&quot; if such a tax excluded the first<br>
$100,000 of wealth, it would not even touch some two thirds of all<br>
American households. But even a modest tax of wealth above that<br>
level, similar to that of Switzerland, would be enough to have<br>
generated some $40 billion in tax revenue in 1994.<br>
<br>
       The fact is that the 1981 tax cuts brought a stunning shift of<br>
wealth, a shift of over $1 trillion in ten years from 99-1/2<br>
percent of the American people to the wealthiest 1/2 of 1 percent,<br>
people with net worths of over $10 million.<br>
<br>
       I would go much farther than Professor Wolff. I believe we<br>
need to consider a wealth tax on that 1/2 of 1 percent to get back<br>
the $1 trillion and to halt the ongoing transfer of $170 billion<br>
per year to the same 1/2 of 1 percent.<br>
<br>
       The transfer was not the fault of the wealthy. It was nothing<br>
they did. We did it to them. We forced the trillion dollars on them<br>
as part of the Reagan administration's 1981 supply-side tax cut.<br>
<br>
       They didn't really ask for the money. They certainly didn't<br>
need it. The only real effect it had on them was to give their<br>
accountants more figures to add up.<br>
<br>
       The clearest way to see this is to look at the actual numbers.<br>
The top 1/2 of 1 percent now holds about $7 trillion, or about 1/3<br>
of our total wealth of $21 trillion. If we were able to take back<br>
our $1 trillion, we would leave them with $6 trillion. That is<br>
still more than twice the $2.5 trillion they had before Reagan.<br>
<br>
       The fact that the top 1/2 of 1 percent now own a third of our<br>
total wealth is worth more than a passing gasp. History shows that<br>
whenever their share of our wealth rises that high, we are in for<br>
a disaster. In 1929, when their share rose to about that level, the<br>
Great Depression began.<br>
<br>
       This redistribution of our wealth from the middle class to the<br>
very wealthiest 1/2 of 1 percent still goes on. This year, the<br>
transfer will be about $170 billion. To take back the $1 trillion<br>
without stopping the $170 billion annual drain would be like<br>
bailing out the boat but not fixing the hole in the bottom.<br>
<br>
       Now, the last time I checked, tax increases on anyone at all<br>
are not politically popular this year. I'm not sure how many<br>
candidates for 1996 are planning campaigns around the theme, &quot;Make<br>
the rich pay their fair share.&quot;<br>
<br>
       Perhaps someone should have as a theme, &quot;Make the very, very<br>
rich with $10 million or more give us back what we gave them.&quot;<br>
<br>
       For a variety of very good reasons -- to reduce the colossal<br>
disparity among our standards of living, to keep the public sector<br>
from emaciation, to reduce the federal budget deficit, to make our<br>
nation more equal in fact as well as in theory -- such a wealth tax<br>
and an increase in marginal tax rates on the 1/2 of 1 percent to<br>
counteract the continuing transfers to them of $170 billion per<br>
year would be one of the best, most moral legacies we could leave<br>
our children for the next century.<br>
<br>
       So in the end, the answer to the question, &quot;What is the<br>
outlook for the U.S. standard of living in the 21st century,&quot; is<br>
that if we do nothing, it will be very bleak for poor and working<br>
people, and just fine for the affluent, particularly for the<br>
richest 1 percent -- for a time.<br>
<br>
       And that is precisely why we should do something.<br>
<br>
       The second question before our panel is, &quot;Are there tradeoffs<br>
between wealth creation, wealth distribution, and other noneconomic<br>
goals?&quot;<br>
       The answer is that there have been such tradeoffs in the past,<br>
there are today, and unless the world is transformed in ways we<br>
can't imagine, there will be tradeoffs like that in the next<br>
century.<br>
<br>
       It is no secret that market-based capitalism can do a lot of<br>
things very well. As economists from Karl Marx to Milton Friedman<br>
have suggested, it is the greatest engine of prosperity in human<br>
history.<br>
<br>
       It is also not a secret that when it is left to its own<br>
devices, it does other things badly or not at all, like ensuring<br>
social equality, protecting the environment, correcting the<br>
imbalance of power between employer and employee, guaranteeing<br>
universal education, encouraging a sense of community, and<br>
providing security for the poor and the needy.<br>
<br>
       The sad truth is that we can't have it all. We either temper<br>
and restrain the workings of the market to pursue social goals, or<br>
we don't.<br>
<br>
       Unfortunately, this is not the kind of issue that can be<br>
solved by a hand calculator or the latest software. It is in the<br>
realm of philosophy, ethics, or possibly religion.<br>
<br>
       I suspect that if you ask the three of us on this panel where<br>
and how to make the tradeoffs, you will get at least three<br>
opinions, probably more.<br>
<br>
       And as persuasive as each of us is, it is highly unlikely that<br>
any one of us could change the minds of the other two.<br>
<br>
       If we frame the issue as marking the perimeter of the<br>
government's role in a capitalist economy -- and we should frame it<br>
that way -- then this is a season when private wealth creation will<br>
win out against government programs almost every time.<br>
<br>
       But happily, the cycles of history are constantly moving,<br>
sometimes when nobody notices. The time will come when we can once<br>
again make our society more equal, when we can make those tradeoffs<br>
that make it possible for the middle class and the poor to make<br>
their lives more secure and comfortable. It may be in the next<br>
century, but it is not too early to start discussing what should be<br>
done when the time is ripe.<br>
<br>
       John Stuart Mill, when he was a young man, believed that the<br>
world was becoming &quot;more improved; more eminent in the best<br>
characteristics of Man and Society; farther advanced in the road to<br>
perfection; happier, nobler, wiser.&quot;                   <br>
<br>
       These days, as we look to the 21st century, we cannot be<br>
nearly as confident of that as Mill was.<br>
<br>
       Maybe nothing is inevitable -- and if it is, we probably don't<br>
have the slightest idea what it could possibly be.<br>
<br>
       But we can make our best guess. We can think seriously about<br>
what we can do to leave things a little better for our children and<br>
grandchildren, how we can make their lives happier and safer and<br>
more humane. And that will require our finding the ways to ensure<br>
a more equitable distribution of wealth, and of the comfort and<br>
power and security that are its companions.<br>
<br>
       Thank you.</p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="/publ/publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
