<html>

<head>
<title>PR 05/03/95 Lane Kirkland's remarks on the White House's Council on Aging. </title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>For Immediate Release                    Contact: Colleen O'Neill<br>
May 3, 1995            Washington Hilton, Room 2174, 202/939-3291<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
AFL-CIO President Lane Kirkland issued this statement following<br>
President Clinton's remarks to the White House Conference on Aging:<br>
<br>
<br>
     President Clinton is exactly right that Medicare reform can<br>
only be undertaken in an atmosphere of comprehensive health care<br>
reform. He has steadfastly pursued that goal, only to be obstructed<br>
by the same forces who now cite a Medicare `crisis' as reason to<br>
cut Medicare while they enact tax cuts for the wealthy.<br>
<br>
     Medicare has problems -- senior health care is eroding, long-<br>
term care and prescription drugs are not covered and costs for the<br>
two are spiralling ever higher. Funding should go where it's<br>
needed, to correct those problems and assure seniors, the disabled<br>
and others access to proper care.<br>
<br>
     The AFL-CIO will continue to fight to protect Medicare. We<br>
will continue to resist any effort to punish the middle class for<br>
the nation's failure to face up to its health care problems.<br>
<br>
                               ###<br>
<br>
     (To arrange an interview with a labor delegate from your city<br>
or state, contact Colleen O'Neill in Room 2174, 202/939-3291.)</p>
