<html>

<head>
<title>PR 05/01/95 Labor Delegates Join Conference on Aging </title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>Media advisory                                           Contact: Colleen O'Neill<br>
May 1, 1995                                                       at 202/637-5010<br>
                                              After May 2, 202/483-3000 Room 2174<br>
<br>
                     Labor Delegates Join Conference on Aging<br>
<br>
      Some 200 trade unionists are among the 2,200 delegates to the fourth<br>
White House Conference on Aging, which opens May 3 at the Washington<br>
Hilton.<br>
<br>
      Labor delegates will focus on countering the widespread misinformation<br>
on Social Security and Medicare and demonstrating the inter-generational<br>
support for Social Security programs. <br>
<br>
      They also will be carrying the message that Americans overwhelmingly<br>
support Social Security and Medicare and reject Republican attempts to<br>
tamper with Medicare in order to fund tax breaks for the wealthy.<br>
      <br>
      On May 2, beginning at 10 a.m., union delegates will be joined by<br>
seniors, students and others in a symbolic ``passing of the torch'' from the<br>
National Archives to the U.S. Capitol. Following the torch ceremony will be a<br>
10:30 a.m. news conference with Dr. Arthur Flemming and leaders of Save<br>
Our Security, on the east steps of the Capitol.<br>
 <br>
      Past conferences on aging have produced landmark programs, with the<br>
work of delegates contributing to the enactment of Medicare, Medicaid and<br>
the Older American Act in 1961; the Supplemental Security Income Program<br>
and other achievements in 1971; and recommendations leading to the Social<br>
Security Reform amendments in 1981.<br>
<br>
      Individual interviews with delegates and union officers can be arranged<br>
through Colleen O'Neill, AFL-CIO Information Department. Beginning May 3,<br>
contact her at 202/483-3000, Room 2174 at the Washington Hilton.</p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="/publ/publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
</body>

</html>
