<html>

<head>
<title>PR 04/27/95 Memorial Service in Oklahoma City </title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>       Remarks of AFL-CIO Secretary-Treasurer Tom Donahue<br>
                Memorial Service in Oklahoma City<br>
                         April 27, 1995<br>
<br>
     I come today to speak on behalf of the 13 million working men<br>
and women who are the AFL-CIO, on behalf of America's working<br>
families who our unions represent -- and for them, to attempt to<br>
speak the emotions that have flooded through them in the past eight<br>
days.<br>
<br>
     But there are no words with which one describes the horror,<br>
the sorrow, the shock, the anger, the plain misery that all of<br>
America feels at the killing of so many decent men, women, and<br>
children who until eight days ago had whole lifetimes ahead of them<br>
to enjoy their work and families.<br>
<br>
     I am incapable of the full expression of the sympathy we want<br>
to offer to their families and friends.<br>
<br>
     No words are adequate. But by our presence here today, we mean<br>
to convey to the families of those who died here our desire to<br>
share the pain of their loss and our hope that somehow that<br>
knowledge, that sense that others share their grief, may help to<br>
lessen their burdens.<br>
<br>
     The 13 million women and men of the AFL-CIO join in prayers<br>
for your well-being and offer the further prayer that the misery of<br>
the blast may so shock the few in our nation who fan the flames of<br>
hate that their encouragement of conflict might be forever stilled.<br>
<br>
     For those who survived the horror of this blast, we offer a<br>
prayer of thanksgiving for your safety and for your deliverance<br>
from the memories of that day.<br>
<br>
     And on this day, we offer our thanks to the hundreds of union<br>
members and other workers who have labored so hard and long and<br>
with such dedication in the rescue and search operations. The fire<br>
fighters and police; the operating engineers; the ironworkers,<br>
electricians, carpenters, and others in the construction trades;<br>
the city and state and federal employees; the health personnel --<br>
everyone who has lifted a broken chunk of concrete or shard of<br>
glass has earned the gratitude and admiration of the nation.<br>
<br>
     Tomorrow, all across America, the men and women of the AFL-CIO<br>
will meet as they have annually over the past seven years in<br>
hundreds of observances of Workers' Memorial Day. <br>
<br>
     In each of those, there will be a moment of silence for the<br>
thousands of workers who were killed or injured on the job during<br>
the past year.<br>
<br>
     It is our way of reminding America that our workplaces can be<br>
dangerous places, and a reminder of the need for effective<br>
enforcement of occupational safety and health regulations.<br>
<br>
     This year, all of the people attending those Workers' Memorial<br>
Day observances will have in their minds and hearts the federal<br>
workers and ordinary citizens who died here, not because of any<br>
failure of safety and health laws but because of the madness of a<br>
few sick zealots.<br>
<br>
     They will reflect, as we do, on the horrible truth that<br>
ordinary workers -- some of them members of the American Federation<br>
of Government Employees working at four agencies in the building<br>
and a member of the Operating Engineers -- came to their workplaces<br>
as they did every day to perform the duties of the day.<br>
<br>
     They showed up at work to do what they did every day as<br>
federal workers -- to serve the people, to make their government<br>
real to their citizen-clients, to process claims for benefits or to<br>
pursue effective enforcement of our laws.<br>
<br>
     They were like millions of their brothers and sisters all<br>
across America. But within a few minutes, their lives and the lives<br>
to which they were connected were shattered -- smashed in an<br>
avalanche of concrete and glass and metal.<br>
<br>
     There were others. Citizens seeking government service, a<br>
striking member of the Rubber Workers in his own struggle for<br>
justice who was volunteering to help Social Security applicants,<br>
and little children seeking only the joy and comfort of their day<br>
care center while their parents did their jobs -- they had their<br>
lives stolen by the perpetrators of this heinous crime who cared<br>
not about the innocence of their victims. They killed<br>
indiscriminately, presumably to protest some imagined wrong.<br>
<br>
     At this point, it is still too early to know why this bombing<br>
could have happened. But it seems that there is some link -- we<br>
don't know exactly how strong it is -- to a certain kind of<br>
extremism that is abroad in the land.<br>
<br>
     This country has always been dedicated to the idea of free<br>
expression. That is one of the cornerstones of our society. None of<br>
us wants to tamper with that freedom in any way.<br>
<br>
     But today, there is something very ominous and frightening: a<br>
free-wheeling hatred, an eagerness for violence, a reverence for<br>
weaponry, a contempt for democratic government. All of these<br>
apparently found some ultimate sort of expression in the Oklahoma<br>
City bombing.<br>
<br>
     It left a gaping moral wound that we must heal.<br>
     But in the worst events and times, some goodness, some<br>
redemption or resurrection must be found. And surely the hundreds<br>
of people who have worked in the rescue efforts, the tens of<br>
thousands of residents of this city and the millions of Americans<br>
who can only observe and pray, have demonstrated again the<br>
resilience of the human spirit and the natural instincts for<br>
kindness and goodness and solidarity that we all share.<br>
<br>
     Perhaps that can help to fashion a new determination to reject<br>
hate, to root it out of our society.<br>
<br>
     It may be too much to hope for replacing it with love, for<br>
creating a society in which man's inhumanity to man is replaced by<br>
man's love for man -- for following the biblical injunction to love<br>
one another.<br>
<br>
      But it is surely possible for us all to dedicate ourselves to<br>
taking hate out of our national dialogue, and at the minimum to<br>
correct any among us who dares to speak without tolerance or who<br>
attempts to inflame our political discourse.<br>
<br>
     Let us here resolve that each of us will undertake to still<br>
the voices of hate, that we may never again have to memorialize so<br>
many whose lives held so much promise for good.<br>
<br>
     So we pray for the women and men and children who lost their<br>
lives. We pray for their loved ones who survived. We pray for this<br>
community that tries to find its way through its trauma. We offer<br>
a prayer of thanks for all of you who have worked so hard to<br>
relieve its suffering.<br>
<br>
     And let us also pray for our country -- for a reign of<br>
civility and moderation and decency, for peace and a simple respect<br>
for human life.</p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="/publ/publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
</body>

