<head>
<title>PR 04/13/95 Recess Campaign Urges Support for America's Working Families </title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>For immediate release                         Contact: Candice Johnson<br>
April 13, 1995                                         at 202/637-5010<br>
<br>
     Recess Campaign Urges Support for America's Working Families<br>
<br>
      Union members are pressing their congressional<br>
representatives, home for the Easter recess, about the wrong<br>
direction Congress has taken in its so-called ``Contract with<br>
America.'' <br>
<br>
      Working people are sending that message to their<br>
representatives in face-to-face meetings, phone calls, rallies,<br>
radio talk shows and newspaper and television ads. The campaign<br>
stresses that good jobs, good wages, health and safety, and a real<br>
voice on the job are workers' top priorities. <br>
<br>
      April 28, Workers Memorial Day -- and the final day of the<br>
House recess -- remembers those killed and injured on the job.<br>
Workers will call on their representatives to stop congressional<br>
actions that are threatening job safety and health. <br>
<br>
      Television ads, which began in the Washington area, are<br>
running in selected congressional districts in nine states during<br>
the recess. Newspaper ads, which appeared in the national edition<br>
of USA Today and in the Washington Post, also are appearing in<br>
several districts, in states including Kentucky and Pennsylvania. <br>
<br>
<br>
      For example, Pennsylvania legislative action committees to<br>
date have scheduled meetings with six members of Congress and in<br>
Ohio, another half a dozen legislative action committee meetings<br>
have been scheduled. Union members also are planning events where<br>
a member of Congress refuses to meet. <br>
<br>
      There also are two direct mail campaigns underway, aimed at<br>
union members in districts represented by Reps. Harris Fawell (R-<br>
Ill.) and Cass Ballenger (R-N.C.). Legislative action committee<br>
meetings also have been scheduled in other districts, in states<br>
including Illinois, Wisconsin and California. and others. <br>
<br>
      The Campaign for America's Working Families is the AFL-CIO's<br>
national effort to underscore the benefits Congress is offering big<br>
business and the rich at the expense of the middle-income working<br>
families.</p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="/publ/publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
</body>

</html>
