<head>
<title>PR 03/16/95 Senate Rejects Bid to Block Presidential Order </title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>For immediate release                           Contact: Candice Johnson<br>
March 16, 1995                                           at 202/637-5010<br>
<br>
<br>
             Senate Rejects Bid to Block Presidential Order<br>
<br>
AFL-CIO President Lane Kirkland made this comment on the Senate's<br>
rejection of efforts to block the President's executive order:  <br>
<br>
     The Senate's failure to overturn the President's executive<br>
order on striker replacements is a victory for working families. We<br>
applaud those Senators who stood with us in opposing this attack on<br>
workers' rights.<br>
<br>
     The President's order, which bars large federal contractors<br>
from permanently replacing striking employees, sets a strong moral<br>
tone. Labor-management cooperation must be a two-way street.<br>
Working Americans simply will not believe all of the talk about<br>
``workplace cooperation'' and ``partnership'' from the same people<br>
who defend the permanent replacement of strikers.<br>
<br>
     We are grateful to President Clinton and the majority of<br>
Senate Democrats for their firm stance on this issue.</p>
