<head>
<title>PR 02/23/95 Rep. Lowey, Workers Urge Congress to Maintain Funds for a Strong OSHA</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE CONTACT: Colleen M. O'Neill,<br>
202/637-5010<br>
February 23, 1995 or David Saltz, 202/637-5318<br>
<br>
<br>
Rep. Lowey, Workers Urge Congress to Maintain Funds for a Strong<br>
OSHA<br>
<br>
<br>
Workers and local union representatives from around the<br>
country joined Rep. Nita M. Lowey (D-N.Y.) in a call to Congress to<br>
preserve Occupational Safety and Health Administration protections<br>
and funding. They were in town to attend an appropriations hearing<br>
where it was anticipated that OSHA funding cuts would be<br>
considered.<br>
<br>
Nearly a dozen people flew in to Washington to give testament<br>
to the power of strong safety and health protections, with stories<br>
ranging from the helplessness felt while watching co-workers die<br>
needlessly to the triumph gained by knowing OSHA-backed sanctions<br>
brought improvements to the workplace.<br>
<br>
``The owner had been ignoring our complaints for many years.<br>
. . . It seems like they were always saying that there's never<br>
money for health and safety,'' said Jorge Deschamps, a Ladies'<br>
Garment Workers member from New York City. ``We need more money for<br>
OSHA, not less. We need more inspectors and more enforcement. We<br>
need every employer to know that there are high fines. It's only<br>
after our employer found out how much the OSHA fines could be that<br>
our employer started fixing the machines.''<br>
<br>
The appropriations measures are one of a series of Republican<br>
attacks on OSHA and regulations to protect citizens. This week, the<br>
House of Representatives is slated to consider H.R. 450 -- The<br>
Regulatory Transition Act of 1995 -- while next week it is possible<br>
that H.R. 9, The Job Creation and Wage Enhancement Act, will be<br>
considered.<br>
<br>
`` As part of their effort to scale back government, the<br>
Republicans may propose drastic cuts in OSHA's current<br>
appropriation and for the agency's 1996 budget,'' said AFL-CIO<br>
Safety and Health Director Peg Seminario. ``This is not an academic<br>
exercise in budget-cutting, however, it is an attempt to weaken<br>
protections for working Americans. <br>
<br>
``The sad result will be weaker enforcement, more workplaces<br>
with safety and health hazards, more injuries and increasing<br>
fatalities,'' she said. ``These proposals are a step backward and<br>
represent a reversal of 25 years of improving job safety.''</p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="/publ/publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
</body>

</html>
