<head>
<title>PR 02/03/95 Lane Kirkland on the President's Minimum Wage Proposal </title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>For Immediate Release                           Contact: Candice Johnson<br>
January 25, 1995                                            202/637-5010<br>
                                              or David Saltz at 637-5318<br>
<br>
The AFL-CIO made the following comment on the president's call for<br>
an increase in the minimum wage:<br>
<br>
     The president is absolutely correct that the nation needs to<br>
``build the middle class and shrink the underclass.'' Further, he<br>
is right in saying that an increase in the minimum wage is an<br>
indispensable step toward achieving that goal. <br>
<br>
     Sen. Edward M. Kennedy (D-Mass.) has introduced a bill to<br>
increase the minimum wage from $4.25 to $5.75 in three steps of 50<br>
cents each. That's the minimum needed to correct the national<br>
blight of letting the real buying power of the minimum wage sink to<br>
the lowest level in 40 years. It takes an hourly wage of $5.85 to<br>
restore the lost buying power cited by President Clinton.<br>
<br>
     The AFL-CIO will be in the forefront of the fight against the<br>
privileged interests who would abuse the poorest of working people.</p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="/publ/publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
</body>

