<html>

<head>
<title>PR 01/13/95 Mexican Loan Terms Stick Workers with the Tab </title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>For immediate release                      Contact: Mark Anderson<br>
January 13, 1995               at 637-5178 (301/652-4932 at home)<br>
                                   or Candice Johnson at 637-5010<br>
<br>
          Mexican Loan Terms Stick Workers with the Tab<br>
<br>
The AFL-CIO issued this statement on Mexico's currency crisis and<br>
the loan guarantee package Congress will consider: <br>
<br>
     Mexico's economic disaster and currency crisis threatens to<br>
once again stick workers in both Mexico and the United States<br>
with the tab.  <br>
<br>
     The central aim of the Mexican government's plan is to<br>
reduce its current account deficit by significantly increasing<br>
Mexican exports, and pricing imports out of the reach of the<br>
majority of Mexican citizens. A key part of its program is to<br>
accelerate U.S. investment in Mexican factories.<br>
<br>
     So working Americans -- as taxpayers -- are once again being<br>
asked to pay for the export of their own jobs, and, in fact, to<br>
push down their own wages. The reported $40 billion loan<br>
guarantee will be used to reinforce a direct appeal to American<br>
business to expand operations in Mexico rather than in the United<br>
States. <br>
<br>
     Mexican workers, under their government's plan, will see<br>
their wages capped at 7 percent this year while inflation is<br>
expected to exceed 19 percent. This follows 10 long years of<br>
austerity for Mexico's workers, and makes it even more unlikely<br>
that they will have the purchasing power to buy U.S. goods. But<br>
while U.S. taxpayers are being asked to prop up the Mexican<br>
economy with billions of dollars, wealthy Mexicans have instead<br>
helped to bring about this crisis by taking their money and<br>
investments to other countries. <br>
     This disaster demonstrates that, for workers, the North<br>
American Free Trade Agreement is a ``lose-lose'' situation.<br>
Extending this flawed structure to the rest of the hemisphere<br>
will only compound the damage. Worker rights and standards must<br>
have a central role in future trade agreements. Working families<br>
everywhere deserve no less.</p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="/publ/publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
</body>

</html>
