<html>

<head>
<title>PR 01/09/95  DUNLOP Report Picks Right Targets, but Falls Short </title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>For Immediate Release Contact: Candice Johnson<br>
January 9, 1995 202/637-5010<br>
or Mary MacDonald<br>
202/637-5305<br>
<br>
DUNLOP REPORT PICKS RIGHT TARGETS, BUT FALLS SHORT<br>
<br>
The AFL-CIO issued this statement in response to the report of the<br>
Commission on the Future of Worker-Management Relations:<br>
<br>
The Dunlop Commission correctly identified the urgent problems<br>
facing American workers -- stagnating wages, longer working hours,<br>
and a growing inequality in earnings. They reaffirmed what we have<br>
known for many years -- that the best way to address these problems<br>
is by giving workers a strong voice in decision-making through<br>
democratic unions of their own choosing.<br>
<br>
Unfortunately, the Commission failed to recommend strong<br>
enough protections for workers who try to achieve that<br>
participation but currently face strong employer opposition.<br>
<br>
Equally unfortunate is the fact that their recommendations on<br>
workplace committees would allow the boss to decide who represents<br>
the workers. Such a hollow version of &quot;representation&quot; runs<br>
counter to basic principles of democracy and threatens to undermine<br>
workers' legitimate representatives. <br>
<br>
American unions have a strong track record of supporting real<br>
employee participation programs and have been partners in many of<br>
the most successful and longstanding examples. But we know that<br>
real &quot;employee voice&quot; means democratically elected representation. <br>
And we know that many of the economic concerns of America's workers<br>
will persist until workers can freely choose their own<br>
representatives.<br>
<br>
The report's recommendations of positive changes in our labor<br>
laws, designed to enlarge and make real the opportunities for<br>
worker voice could, if enacted, alleviate some of the problems<br>
faced by workers.<br>
<br>
###<br>
<br>
AFL-CIO ANALYSIS OF THE DUNLOP COMMISSION'S<br>
RECOMMENDATIONS<br>
<br>
The Commission's Fact Finding Report -- In its June, 1994<br>
Fact Finding Report, the Commission found that the United States'<br>
labor relations system has failed &quot;to adjust to the changing<br>
environment in ways consistent with our past economic history of<br>
progress for virtually all our citizens.&quot; As a result, wages are<br>
stagnating and even falling (&quot;developments unprecedented in the<br>
past 75 years in this country&quot;); inequality is increasing (&quot;the<br>
U.S. earning distribution is the most unequal among developed<br>
countries&quot;), and younger workers, particularly those with less than<br>
college education are suffering, (&quot;their &quot;ability to form families<br>
and buy homes has been compromised by their labor market plight.&quot;)<br>
<br>
&quot;A healthy society,&quot; the Commission warned, &quot;cannot long<br>
continue along the path the U.S. is moving.&quot;<br>
<br>
The Commission's Recommendations -- The recommendations of<br>
the Commission fall far short of meeting the needs of America's<br>
working families which the Commission itself identified. The<br>
Commission states that the &quot;solution&quot; to the &quot;widening earnings<br>
inequality and stagnant real earnings that has characterized the<br>
American labor market over the past ten to fifteen years&quot; lies<br>
&quot;well beyond the mandate of this Commission.&quot; The AFL-CIO<br>
disagrees.<br>
<br>
We believe that a cornerstone of greater economic security for<br>
working men and women is a labor relations system which empowers<br>
workers and enables those workers, through their democratically<br>
elected representatives, to forge full and equal partnerships with<br>
management. The AFL-CIO and its affiliated unions are committed to<br>
creating productive, cooperative relationships in which workers,<br>
through their unions, participate fully in the range of workplace<br>
decisions. Experience in a wide variety of companies and<br>
industries proves that such equal partnerships between labor and<br>
management are the surest path to achieving world class workplaces<br>
and world class labor standards for American workers.<br>
<br>
The Failure of the NLRA and of the Commission's Proposed<br>
Solutions -- The Commission's Fact Finding Report shows that a<br>
principal barrier to achieving an empowered workforce and full<br>
worker participation is our inadequate labor laws. For most<br>
workers in the United States forming a union is &quot;highly<br>
confrontational&quot; and &quot;highly conflictual&quot;; the U.S. &quot;is the only<br>
major democratic country in which the choice of whether or not<br>
workers are to be represented by a union is subject to such a<br>
confrontational process in most cases.&quot; The inadequacies of the<br>
current law thus frustrate the just aspirations of the many workers<br>
who, as the Commission said, &quot;want a voice on their job but fear<br>
the tensions, risk and adversarial climate&quot; currently associated<br>
with organizing a union.<br>
<br>
The Commission's recommendations offer little to alleviate the<br>
&quot;fear&quot; which the Fact Finding Report recognizes to be so pervasive. <br>
Expediting the election process would be a welcome change but<br>
would do little to change the climate in which workers today face<br>
the decision of whether to cross their employer and opt for<br>
workplace representation. The same is true of the Commission's<br>
proposal to expedite reinstatement for illegally discharged<br>
workers. Only the Commission's proposal for a system of first<br>
contract dispute resolution -- including binding arbitration where<br>
necessary -- represents a significant improvement in our current<br>
law.<br>
<br>
The Commission's recommendations in this area fall well short<br>
of what virtually every neutral observer -- including most of the<br>
law professors who testified before the Commission and including<br>
several of the Commissioners themselves in their academic writings<br>
-- have recognized to be the essential elements of a system<br>
designed to make union representation freely accessible to workers<br>
who desire it.<br>
<br>
The Commission's Recommended Change in Section 8(a)(2) -- The<br>
Commission's recommendations not only fail to serve the needs of<br>
those workers who want a union but also allow employers to choose<br>
and control who will represent non-union workers, at least with<br>
respect to certain subject matters.<br>
<br>
Section 8(a)(2) of the NLRA states a very simple principle: it<br>
is unfair labor practice for an employer to &quot;dominate&quot; an employee<br>
organization. This principle is essential if employees are to<br>
enjoy the democratic right to freely choose their own<br>
representatives. And employer domination of employee<br>
representation plans is illegitimate and undemocratic without<br>
regard to the particular matters with which the employer controlled<br>
representatives deal.<br>
<br>
The change recommended by the Commission was not advocated by<br>
any employer representative who appeared before the Commission. <br>
Moreover, this is not a change desired by working men and women;<br>
they want to be free to democratically select their own<br>
representatives and do not want their employers making these<br>
selections for them.<br>
<br>
DUNLOP COMMISSION/FREEMAN-ROGERS SURVEY FACT SHEET<br>
<br>
Some reporters will ask whether the Dunlop Commission<br>
recommendations provide the kind of representation the Freeman-<br>
Rogers survey seemed to indicate workers want -- employee<br>
organizations with no independent power and a cooperative<br>
relationship with management. That finding, of course, merely<br>
reflected the realities of the balance of power in many of today's<br>
workplaces; that very little happens unless management wants it. <br>
<br>
However, the survey also included several findings which<br>
support the view that workers want organizations that give them a<br>
real voice.<br>
<br>
* When non-union workers in companies with committees are<br>
asked how the committee members should be picked, only 9% favor<br>
selection by management; the rest favor elections (49%) or a<br>
volunteer system (36%). <br>
<br>
* Freeman-Rogers find that the majority of workers (56%) do<br>
not want employers to have the final say over the terms under which<br>
their employees work.<br>
<br>
* Freeman-Rogers find that workers want voice on economic<br>
issues. 60% say that it is &quot;very important&quot; for them to have a<br>
&quot;lot of influence&quot; on deciding their benefits, yet only 6% say they<br>
have &quot;a lot of direct involvement&quot; regarding benefits. <br>
<br>
* Most importantly, workers already in unions, who have<br>
experience with independent representation, strongly favor it. <br>
Ninety percent (90%) of current union members say they want to keep<br>
the union in their workplace.<br>
<br>
* The survey also found substantial demand for unions among<br>
non-union workers. Thirty-two percent (32%) of non-union workers -<br>
- 37% if the &quot;no responses&quot; are eliminated -- express a desire for<br>
union representation, and 33% (or 38% without the &quot;no responses&quot;)<br>
say the majority of their coworkers feel the same way.<br>
<br>
* Finally, even managers recognize the value of unions for<br>
their employees. Sixty-four percent (64%) of managers surveyed<br>
said they believed the union improved working conditions for its<br>
members.</p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="/publ/publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
