<html>

<head>
<title>PR 12/21/94 Job Injury Report Shows the Epidemic of Cumulative Trauma Disorders Continues </title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>For Immediate Release                      Contact: Peg Seminario<br>
December 21, 1994                                    202/637-5366<br>
<br>
              Job Injury Report Shows the Epidemic<br>
            Of Cumulative Trauma Disorders Continues<br>
<br>
Peg Seminario, director of the AFL-CIO Department of Occupational<br>
Safety and Health, made the following comment on the annual report<br>
on occupational injuries and illnesses released today by the Bureau<br>
of Labor Statistics:<br>
<br>
     The 1993 BLS survey shows progress in reducing workplace<br>
injuries, but also shows that cumulative trauma disorders (CTDs)<br>
from poor job design and repetitive motion continue to increase at<br>
alarming rates.<br>
<br>
     In 1993, more than 300,000 cases of CTDs were reported.  These<br>
crippling disorders have increased 770 percent in the past decade. <br>
But the rates of CTDs declined for the first time in industries<br>
like meat packing and auto assembly where OSHA and employers have<br>
intervened to prevent CTDs and implement ergonomic control<br>
measures.<br>
<br>
     The message from the BLS report is that OSHA needs to move<br>
forward now with an ergonomics standard so that workers in all<br>
industries can be protected from crippling injuries from poor job<br>
design and repetitive motion.<br>
<br>
                               ###<br>
<br>
   NEW CASES OF CUMULATIVE TRAUMA DISORDERS (Private Industry)<br>
                            1984-1993<br>
<br>
       There has been a 770% increase in new cases of CTDs<br>
                       in the last decade.<br>
<br>
          YEAR                          NUMBER OF CASES<br>
          <br>
          1993                              302,000<br>
          1992                              281,800<br>
          1991                              223,600<br>
          1990                              185,400<br>
          1989                              146,900<br>
          1988                              115,400<br>
          1987                               72,900<br>
          1986                               45,500<br>
          1985                               37,000<br>
          1984                               34,700<br>
