<head>
<title>AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS -- January 6, 1997</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<p align="left"><img src="../images/wip.gif" align="bottom"
width="508" height="135"></p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<p align="left">AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS -- January 6, 1997</p>
<p>JUSTICE CONEXION -- Sprint Corp. must rehire and pay back
wages to 177 workers, mostly Hispanic women, who were fired in
1995 a week before they were set to vote for union representation
by the Communications Workers, the National Labor Relations Board
ruled. The board accused a Sprint vice president of falsifying
documents to make it appear the company was concerned about
finances at La Conexion Familiar, the Spanish-language facility
in San Francisco, when it was shut down. Sprint was ordered to
rehire the workers in equivalent positions, or place them on a
preferential hiring list. Back pay could amount to $15 million.
Sprint says it will appeal. </p>
<p>HEALTH CARE HURRAHS -- AFT scored victories at hospitals in
Pennsylvania and Wisconsin, as nurses at Philadelphia's Episcopal
Hospital rang in the new year Jan. 1 with a 210-31 vote for
representation by the Health Professionals and Allied Employees
and nearly 600 service and support workers at St. Francis
Hospital in Milwaukee gave themselves an early Christmas present
Dec. 18 with a 296-208 pro-union vote. Local 5001 of the
Wisconsin Federation of Nurses and Health Professionals already
represents nurses at the facility. </p>
<p>BULLISH ON UNION -- CWA gained 2,500 employees at Dow Jones
when the Independent Association of Publishers' Employees voted
overwhelmingly (985-311) to affiliate. The new CWA members work
at the Wall Street Journal, Barron's, Dow Jones Information
Service and WBIS-TV. </p>
<p>FIGHT GOES ON -- The Electrical Workers will file objections
and unfair labor practice charges against Baltimore Gas &amp;
Electric after workers rejected the union by a 2-1 margin.
&quot;It is a shame that the laws of our nation allow
corporations to abuse the rights of their workers in this
manner,&quot; said IBEW President John Barry, who accused
BG&amp;E of harassing union supporters, offering wage increases
only if workers voted against the union, and spending nearly $40
million to keep the union out, much of it in fees to the notorous
union-busting consultants, the Burke Group. </p>
<p>HOLD THAT LINE -- In suburban Chicago, 24 of 25 workers in a
cable TV bargaining unit signed a petition urging voluntary
recognition of the IBEW by Time Warner DuPage, and 20 of the
workers showed up in person to present the petition. But the
company said it would require a representation election and has
sought to dilute the bargaining unit by including workers from
two other locations. Tell Time Warner to do the right thing and
recognize these workers' right to a union. Call (708/430-4840) or
FAX (708/430-1870) to Ron Murray, regional manager, Time Warner
Cable in Hickory Hills, Ill. </p>
<p>SNEAK ATTACK -- New labor laws rammed through by South Korea's
majority government in a secret session &quot;turns back the
clock on democratic reform and fundamentally undermines workers'
rights,&quot; AFL-CIO President John Sweeney declared, praising
South Korean trade unions for their general strike in opposition.
Sweeney urged South Korea's president to veto the legislation. </p>
<p>SIGNATURE VICTORY -- In a major victory against corporate
greed, the NLRB backed 300 members of the Graphic Communictions
Union at American Signature in Atlanta, ordering the company to
reinstate the strikers with full backpay. The workers, fired in
1993 after wages were slashed, were supported by a coalition of
other unions, clergy and activists. </p>
<p>BLACK DAY AT RED CROSS -- Some 70 Service Employees members
who collect blood in West Virginia, Kentucky and Ohio went on
strike Dec. 30 over wages, benefits and a proposal to allow
technicians to perform tasks now done by nurses. The workers
rejected an offer that would have raised wages by 9 percent over
three years and brought higher insurance premiums. The employees
average $7.95 per hour. The Red Cross also proposed discontinuing
payments for nurses' continuing education and a $100 annual
allowance for uniforms. </p>
<p>SAVE SOCIAL SECURITY -- A plan to preserve and strengthen
Social Security was unveiled Monday by six of 13 advisory council
members, including AFL-CIO Vice Presidents George Kourpias of the
Machinists and Gloria Johnson of the Electronic Workers, and
Gerald Shea, assistant to AFL-CIO President John Sweeney. They
joined Robert Ball, former Social Security commissioner, in
rejecting Wall Street privatization schemes advanced by other
members of the advisory council. &quot;Our plan will stabilize
Social Security for the next 75 years without huge tax increases
and benefit cuts,&quot; Shea said. The plan includes options to
lengthen the averaging period from 35 to 38 years or to increase
contributions by 0.15 percent, and to move toward a
public-private investment strategy that would put 40 percent of
Social Security funds in an indexed, passively managed portfolio
of equities. </p>
<p>SUPPORT FOR HOUSTON VICTIMS -- The Machinists are mourning the
loss of eight members who died in a pre-Christmas blast at the
Wyman- Gordon Forging Co. in Houston. Two other members of IAM
Local Lodge 15 hurt in the explosion were hospitalized and have
returned home. &quot;Our hearts go out to those who have lost
loved ones in this catastrophe,&quot; said IAM President George
J. Kourpias, who characterized the men as &quot;American working
heroes.&quot; A memorial service is planned for Jan. 12 in
Houston. </p>
<p>A DONE DEAR -- OSHA Administrator Joseph Dear has stepped down
to become chief of staff to the governor-elect of Washington,
Gary Locke. Dear previously was Washington's labor commissioner
and had worked for the state AFL-CIO. </p>
<p>ERGO, IT'S GONE -- In a victory for California workers, the
state Office of Administrative Law has sided with the AFL-CIO in
rejecting as unclear and unenforceable a number of provisions in
the new ergonomics standard. Sending the regulation back to the
Cal-OSHA Standards Board, the OAL cited several of the reasons
raised in a suit filed by the California Labor Federation.
&quot;We are continuing to pursue our legal action to assure that
the Standards Board provides meaningful, enforceable
protections,&quot; said Art Pulaski, executive
secretary-treasurer of the state fed. </p>
<p>GET THE LEAD OUT -- Beginning this month, workers will benefit
from a new program to cut lead exposure if they work in such
industries as battery, manufacturing, lead smelting, lead
chemicals, fabrication using lead and solder manufacturing. The
Lead Industries Association Inc. and the Battery Council
International - - representing some 33 companies -- have agreed
to participate in a voluntary initiative to lower workers'
exposure to lead. The companies will provide protective gear and
engineering devices and offer educational training. </p>
<p>AND THEY'RE OFF -- Bridgestone/Firestone has been removed from
the AFL-CIO's official boycott list at the request of the
Steelworkers. USWA members and the company have ratified
contracts at plants across the country. Meanwhile, Unoven has
been removed from the list at the request of the Oil, Chemical
and Atomic Workers. OCAW Local 7-517 has ratified an agreement
with the company at the Lemont, Ill., refinery. </p>
<p>HOLIDAY HELP -- Texas Oil, Chemical and Atomic Workers locked
out by Crown Petroleum since February received a seasonal boost
of more than $6,000 and four pick-up loads of food from fellow
union members. The Gulf Coast Organizing Committee, Houston Gulf
Coast Building Trades and Electrical Workers Local 66 made
donations to the Crown Hardship Fund and collected food in boxes
at local union halls to help the members of OCAW 4227. </p>
<p>A RANSOM FOR GOOD NAME -- Responding to numerous complaints by
members, the Machinists are seeking $50 million-plus in damages
from Walt Disney Pictures &amp; Television Inc. and two script
writers over the union's portrayal in Mel Gibson's latest movie,
&quot;Ransom.&quot; Gibson plays an airline executive whose past
includes bribing a corrupt union official described as being with
the &quot;Machinists Union,&quot; and the film contains
references to &quot;Machinists Union indictments.&quot; The
company has rejected requests to drop the references. </p>
<p>SENDING A MESSAGE -- A recorded message for members of the Air
Line Pilots at United Airlines signals some dark clouds ahead in
labor- management relations at the employee-owned airline.
Although union leaders approved a contract that members are
voting on this month, they are &quot;disappointed and
angered&quot; by the company position during talks, said Michael
H. Glawe, president of the union's United council. </p>
<p>BAR THE DOOR -- Teamsters President Ron Carey urged Rodney
Slater, President Clinton's choice for new transportation
secretary, to continue a year-long delay in implementing trucking
provisions of the North American Free Trade Agreement. The IBT
contends Mexican trucks are on average three times older and up
to twice as heavy as American trucks, while often lacking
adequate insurance and not complying with U.S. air emission
standards. Giving Mexican trucks access to the four border
states, with total North American access in 2000, would be
&quot;disastrous for highway safety, environmental quality and
good jobs,&quot; Carey said. </p>
<p>JOBS ON DEATH ROW -- Federal Prison Industries announced it
plans to increase its production of office desks, credenzas and
bookcases by almost $40 million a year. The expansion, the third
in less than a year by the government corporation, which supplies
federal agencies, will further retard employment opportunities in
the private sector. </p>
<p>FINDERS, KEEPERS -- You may have already won part of a $10
million jackpot the federal government wants to give away -- if
you are one of 3,000 retirees from 565 companies with terminated
pension plans covered by the Pension Benefits Guaranty Corp. The
Labor Department's &quot;Pension Search Directory&quot; lists
workers, the name and location of their companies and the date
the pension plan ended, and is available on the Internet by
accessing www.dol.gov or http://search.pbgc.gov. Those finding
themselves on the list should contact the PBGC immediately at
1/800-326-LOST. The directory is updated quarterly. </p>
<p>DECK THE HALLS -- Painters at V.R.D. Decorating in Rochester,
N.Y., got a special gift in time for their Christmas party when
they read on their bulletin board a notice from management
admitting that it had violated federal labor law. The posting,
required by the NLRB, came after Local 150 uncovered numerous
union-busting activities, including &quot;losing&quot; the job
applications of identified union members, who are now eligible
for back wages. </p>
<p>OAKLAND STRIKE EXHIBIT -- &quot;We Called it a Work Holiday:
The 1946 Oakland General Strike&quot; exhibit at the Oakland
Museum of California runs through Feb. 23. The exhibit
commemorates the 50th anniversary of the citywide strike in 1946.
The museum is located at 1000 Oak Street. </p>
<p>RELIGION IN CONTEXT -- How the media reports, or does not
report, religious news is the topic of a panel discussion set for
New York City Friday, Jan. 24, 10 a.m. - 1 p.m. The influence of
the religious right also will be discussed. The event, organized
by the Metro NY Labor Communications Council, will be at Judson
Memorial Church, Thompson St. &amp; Washington Square South.</p>
