<html>
<head>
<title>WIP 12/23/96 AFL-CIO Work in Progress, December 23, 1996</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<p align="left"><img src="../images/wip.gif" align="bottom"
width="508" height="135"></p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<p>AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS -- December 23, 1996<br>
<br>
YALE, YALE, THE UNION'S HERE -- Yale University's corporate-<br>
like agenda to slash pay and benefits and outsource jobs crumbled<br>
last week when the school agreed to a six-year pact for 4,000<br>
workers. The contract with Hotel Employees and Restaurant
Employees<br>
Locals 34 and 35 includes extraordinary job security and pension<br>
improvements, part-time worker protection and increased health
care<br>
benefits. Yale's cave-in came one week after AFL-CIO President
John<br>
Sweeney and 311 others were arrested in protest against Yale's<br>
downsizing efforts. &quot;United,&quot; Sweeney said,
&quot;workers can beat back<br>
corporate profiteers at rich institutions, on Wall Street and in<br>
corporate board rooms all across the nation.&quot;<br>
<br>
WE WILL BERRY YOU -- California's largest food retailer, the<br>
Ralph's chain, Friday endorsed the 5 Cents for Fairness campaign
to<br>
improve conditions for the state's strawberry workers. The
company,<br>
which has hundreds of Southern California stores, joined with the<br>
Farm Workers, Food and Commercial Workers and other labor and<br>
advocacy groups in Los Angeles to sign a pledge endorsing the<br>
campaign to win a livable wage, health care, clean drinking water<br>
and sanitation facilities and protection from sexual harassment
and<br>
arbitrary firings for 20,000 California strawberry workers.<br>
<br>
USWA VICTORIOUS AT BRIDGESTONE -- The Steelworker's two-and-a-<br>
half-year battle with Bridgestone/Firestone came to a winning<br>
conclusion Friday. USWA members at the tiremaker's LaVergne,
Tenn.,<br>
plant ratified a new contract. Workers at six other sites OK'd<br>
pacts this month. The vote means &quot;Steelworkers at all of<br>
Bridgestone/Firestone's U.S. plants will be working under fair<br>
agreements . . . the primary goal of the campaign and
boycotts,&quot;<br>
USWA President George Becker said. After the vote the
Steelworkers<br>
called for an end to the consumer boycott and worldwide corporate<br>
campaign against the company.<br>
<br>
HERMAN CHOICE HAILED -- Alexis M. Herman, President Clinton's<br>
selection as labor secretary, &quot;knows and understands working<br>
families concerns...and I know she is committed to putting
together<br>
a strong team to fight for good jobs, justice and dignity for<br>
America's working families,&quot; said AFL-CIO President John
Sweeney.<br>
Herman currently serves as director of Clinton's Public Liaison<br>
Office, and previously was chief of staff for the late Ron Brown<br>
during his tenure at the Democratic National Committee. During
the<br>
Carter administration, Herman was director of DoL's Women's
Bureau.<br>
<br>
FALLON ON GOOD TIMES -- Workers at McDonnell Douglas on the<br>
VanVoorhis Naval Air Station in Fallon, Nev., voted to join the<br>
Electronic Workers. The addition of more than 250 mechanics at
the<br>
&quot;Top Gun&quot; base concludes a good IUE organizing year
that saw more<br>
than 5,000 new members come aboard.<br>
<br>
GRASSROOTS TAKING HOLD -- Last week, union political activists<br>
met with 10 U.S. senators and representatives in initial
grassroots<br>
meetings in five states. Labor's goal is 150 face-to-face get-<br>
togethers with lawmakers before March.<br>
<br>
KEEP THE BRAKES ON -- Last year, at the urging of the<br>
Teamsters, President Clinton delayed a provision of the North<br>
American Free Trade Agreement that would have allowed Mexican<br>
trucks unlimited access to U.S. highways. Now the trucking
industry<br>
and GOP governors Pete Wilson of California and George Bush of<br>
Texas want the ban lifted -- despite evidence that most of these<br>
trucks are improperly licensed, driven by underage drivers, and<br>
have broken suspensions, substandard tires, inoperable brakes and<br>
unsecured loads. IBT is calling for a permanent ban.<br>
<br>
WORKING FAMILIES AGENDA -- 1. Good jobs and pay, including<br>
protecting wage and safety standards, non-discrimination and the<br>
right to organize. 2. Education, including affordable college and<br>
strong job training programs. 3. Health care, including
protecting<br>
health care programs for the elderly and poor and providing<br>
affordable and accessible care for working families. 4. Social<br>
Security and Pensions, fighting against Wall Street schemes to<br>
pillage Social Security and fighting for new ways to protect and<br>
expand private pensions. 5. Fair tax, trade and economic
policies,<br>
including ending tax breaks to U.S. firms that send jobs overseas<br>
and protecting worker rights in trade and economic policies to<br>
create more jobs. The Council meets in February for a more
detailed<br>
study of legislative strategy.<br>
<br>
LABORERS RE-ELECT COIA -- In its first-ever rank-and-file<br>
vote, the Laborers re-elected President Arthur Coia by a 2-1
margin<br>
over Bruno Caruso, president of Local 1001 in Chicago. The
members<br>
also approved a referendum to elect all future executive board<br>
members by rank-and-file vote. Coia called his win &quot;a clear
vote of<br>
confidence for the internal reforms efforts we began two years
ago<br>
in cooperation with the U.S. Department of Justice.&quot;<br>
<br>
SWEATIN' THE BOSSES -- A walkout by immigrant Latino sweatshop<br>
workers at the Rubberstampede factory in Oakland, Calif., has<br>
stirred up city and state government officials. The strikers
charge<br>
the company with speeding up production, paying low wages and<br>
violating their legal right to organize. The city council wants<br>
hearings to jump-start negotiations, and a state legislator is<br>
calling for testimony before the state's labor committee. The<br>
Longshoremen and Warehousemen are challenging the company's
tactics<br>
in an earlier election, and an NLRB hearing is set for January.<br>
<br>
MEGA-MERGER TALKS -- Machinists President George Kourpias will<br>
meet with the CEOs of Boeing and McDonnell-Douglas after the<br>
holidays to discuss the companies' planned merger. &quot;However
the<br>
merger talks proceed,&quot; Kourpias said, &quot;the IAM's
commitments remain<br>
the same. We are committed to promoting domestic aerospace<br>
production, because a solid base of aerospace jobs and
technologies<br>
is indispensable to a modern, high-wage economy.&quot;<br>
<br>
CARDINAL RULES -- BADLY -- Some 450 Catholic high school<br>
teachers for the Archdiocese of New York held a series of rallies<br>
and &quot;sickouts&quot; to protest Cardinal John O'Connor's
decision to<br>
renege on the recently approved contract between the archdiocese<br>
and its teachers, represented by the Laborers. The cardinal wants<br>
the teachers to include a &quot;mission statement&quot; that
would subject<br>
teachers to terminations without hearings on such issues as<br>
divorced teachers dating, certain kinds of demonstrations and<br>
criticizing of principals.<br>
<br>
IUE/GM PACTS -- The Electronic Workers approved a new contract<br>
with General Motors on behalf of 38,000 employees and retirees.
The<br>
agreement includes &quot;unprecedented provisions&quot; for job
security and<br>
&quot;includes no give-backs or take-aways,&quot; said GM
Conference Chairman<br>
Ron Gilvin, IUE's secretary-treasurer-elect. Meanwhile, UAW GM<br>
workers signed their new contract, bringing to an end the Big
Three<br>
auto talks. <br>
<br>
ACROSS UNITE STATES -- UNITE's 1,110 Healthtex workers in<br>
Centreville, Ala., Warrenton, Ga., and Danville, Va., ratified a<br>
three-year contract with job security language and the
elimination<br>
of a two-tier system. In Charlotte, N.C., 600 UNITE workers at
the<br>
TJ Maxx Distribution Center ratified a new three-year contract.
In<br>
Maryville, Tenn., 460 workers at the BTR Sealing Systems Group<br>
Finishing plant accepted a new two-year contract. UNITE workers
at<br>
two Brooks Brothers plants, in Kinston and Garland, N.C.,
approved<br>
a new three-year pact. The contract continues health care
benefits,<br>
increases wages and pensions. And 400 UNITE workers at North<br>
Carolina's Mohawk Industries facility have a new three-year deal<br>
that includes an annual 3 percent wage hike, improvements in the<br>
bonus program, seniority rights and training pay.<br>
<br>
PACT PEAKS WAGES -- Mine Workers who drive shuttle buses at<br>
Denver International Airport ratified their first contract last<br>
week, gaining a $2 wage increase over term, lower health costs,<br>
more sick leave, life insurance, a grievance procedure and strong<br>
safety language. The 150 Republic Parking workers become UMWA
8431,<br>
in honor of their 84-31 vote for UMWA representation.<br>
<br>
THE RIGHTS STUFF -- For the first time, the World Trade<br>
Organization's members pledge to observe core labor standards,<br>
including freedom of association, the right to organize and<br>
bargaining collectively, nondiscrimination in the workplace and a<br>
prohibition against exploitative child labor. But AFL-CIO
President<br>
John Sweeney cautions that more needs to be done. Maintaining the<br>
standards is essential &quot;if the international trading system
is to<br>
raise living standards for working people around the globe.&quot;<br>
<br>
GIANT BROUHAHA -- The delivery trucks have stopped rolling at<br>
Giant Food supermarkets in the Baltimore-Washington area as 320<br>
Teamster drivers walked out Dec. 18 after contract talks failed.
At<br>
issue is Giant's insistence that drivers accept the same<br>
concessions as did drivers at Safeway, its top competitor in the<br>
area. Giant also wants to contract out direct deliveries to some<br>
stores.<br>
<br>
DISCRIMINATION UNDER THE DOME -- AFSCME Local 26 will<br>
represent 15 custodial workers who have filed a sexual<br>
discrimination complaint against the Architect of the U.S.
Capitol.<br>
The complaint with the Office of Compliance claims that the<br>
architect deliberately has kept the wages low for about 300<br>
custodial workers, 98 percent of whom are women, while their
duties<br>
and workload have increased.<br>
<br>
FRIENDLIER SKIES -- Machinists will vote the week of Jan. 6 on<br>
a new mid-term wage adjustment with United Airlines that raises<br>
wages by 10 percent over the next three-and-a-half years. The<br>
24,000 workers may receive lump-sum payments as bonuses in 1998
and<br>
1999, if the company earns $1 billion in the preceding years.<br>
<br>
OUTBOARD OUT $3 MILLION -- Outboard Marine Corp. will pay $3<br>
million in back wages to 109 members of the Laborers who struck
the<br>
Calhoun, Ga., company in 1986. The settlement agreement,
announced<br>
by the NLRB, grew out of a charge by LIUNA Local 752 that
Outboard<br>
improperly delayed recalling strikers back to work by hiring
excess<br>
replacement workers.<br>
<br>
GIVE ME THAT ON-LINE RELIGION -- The National Interfaith<br>
Committee for Worker Justice homepage, located at<br>
www.igc.org/nicwj, provides information on religious support for<br>
worker campaigns, resources on building religion and labor<br>
partnerships and contacts for local interreligious groups
concerned<br>
with labor issues. They can also be reached by e-mail at<br>
nicwj@igc.org.<br>
<br>
UNITY CALENDAR HIGHLIGHTS FUTURE -- Forget someone on your<br>
gift list? Send them a better-late-than-never holiday gift -- the<br>
all-new 1997 Unity Calendar features members of the IAM, UAW and<br>
Steelworkers. Orders may be FAXed to Brown &amp; Bigelow at
800/245-<br>
2654.<br>
<br>
BREAK TIME -- The folks at Work in Progress are taking a<br>
little time off for the holidays. The next WIP will be on your
fax<br>
machines the week of January 6. We wish you a happy holiday
season<br>
and a bountiful and organized New Year.</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../index.htm">Public Documents Page</a> | <a
href="../publsear.htm">Public Documents Search</a></p>
