<head>
<title>WIP 12/17/96 AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS -- December 17, 1996</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<p align="left"><img src="../images/wip.gif" align="bottom"
width="508" height="135"></p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<p>AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS -- December 17, 1996</p>
<p>NEW YEAR RESOLUTIONS -- The AFL-CIO Executive Council met in<br>
Washington Monday to review the 1996 elections and issue a<br>
grassroots and legislative American Working Families Agenda. Vice<br>
President Gore thanked unions for their support during the<br>
election, noting that he and President Clinton are keenly aware<br>
that one-quarter of all votes cast were from union households,<br>
which overwhelmingly voted for Clinton-Gore. He pledged the
Clinton<br>
administration will continue to address workers' concerns in the<br>
next four years.<br>
<br>
GRASSROOTS REVIVAL -- The council approved a budget for 1997 that<br>
sharply increases resources to organizing and accelerates efforts<br>
to revitalize grassroots activity devoted to organizing,
bargaining<br>
and pro-worker legislation. It also saluted the Jobs With Justice<br>
community coalitions and urged participation in a massive rally<br>
next April 13 in Watsonville, Calif., to support strawberry<br>
workers. The federation also unveiled a &quot;Union Cities&quot;
program that<br>
will provide a framework for central labor councils to rebuild
the<br>
labor movement at its grassroots.<br>
<br>
SWEENEY JAILED AT YALE -- AFL-CIO President John Sweeney and more<br>
than 300 Yale University students, university employees and<br>
supporters were arrested in New Haven, Conn., last week in a<br>
massive demonstration that drew more than 2,000. Yale's clerical<br>
and service employees, represented by Hotel Employees and<br>
Restaurant Employees Locals 34 and 35, have been working without
a<br>
contract for almost a year.<br>
<br>
LONG LUNCH AT NYU -- Some 1,600 clerical workers at New York<br>
University walked out in a half-day strike Dec. 11, as they
sought<br>
to jump start negotiations, stalled since Nov. 13. The workers,<br>
members of the United Staff Association of NYU, an affiliate of<br>
AFT, have been working without a contract since Oct. 31.<br>
<br>
DEMS HAVE AYES IN TEXAS -- A big turnout, spurred by union
members,<br>
helped toss out a notoriously anti-worker Republican
representative<br>
and helped a freshman Democrat maintain his seat after<br>
gerrymandering brought in a big GOP enclave. In the special run
off<br>
elections Dec. 10, Nick Lampson (D) shot down gun-lobby-backed<br>
Steve Stockman (R), 53-47 percent. Rep. Ken Bentsen (D) beat
Dolly<br>
Madison McKenna (R) with 57 percent of the vote. The victories<br>
lower the GOP edge in the House to 227-207-1.<br>
<br>
CLOSE CALL -- How close did the labor movement come to reversing<br>
the GOP margin in the House? &quot;If we could have gotten a
little more<br>
than 12,000 votes total in 11 districts where anti-worker<br>
Republicans narrowly won, the Democrats would have had the<br>
majority,&quot; Sweeney told a press conference after the council<br>
meeting.<br>
<br>
CAREY ON TOP -- Sweeney saluted Teamsters President Ron Carey as
a<br>
&quot;unique American hero&quot; after his narrow victory over
challenger<br>
James P. Hoffa in a ballot by the IBT's rank and file. Carey
called<br>
the win a &quot;victory for reform.&quot; Sweeney also credited
Carey with<br>
aggressive organizing and bargaining campaigns.<br>
<br>
MERGER APPROVED -- The Aluminum, Brick and Glass Workers<br>
overwhelmingly approved a merger with the Steelworkers. The vote
by<br>
a special convention was hailed as a &quot;phenomenal
achievement&quot; by<br>
ABGWU President Ernie LaBaff. USWA President George Becker<br>
emphasized the added strength in numbers for the union workers.
The<br>
addition of the 40,000 ABGWU members brings the USWA total to<br>
740,000.<br>
<br>
SOUTHWEST UNIT TAKES OFF -- More than 4,000 ramp agents at<br>
Southwest Airlines, formerly represented by an unaffiliated
union,<br>
joined the Transport Workers. Local 555 has major bases in
Chicago,<br>
Dallas, Houston, Las Vegas, Los Angeles and Phoenix. The
carrier's<br>
flight attendants also are represented by TWU.<br>
<br>
JUSTICE IN TEXAS -- In Ennis, Texas, UNITE gained 500 new members<br>
when workers at the Ennis Automotive plant voted 236-204 for the<br>
union. The mostly Hispanic work force, earning just $5 to $7.50
an<br>
hour, was angered that the company could afford to hire the
union-<br>
busting law firm of Jackson &amp; Lewis.<br>
<br>
MORE MARYLAND WINS -- The drive to organize Maryland's 40,000
state<br>
workers rolls along, with two more units in the fold. A coalition<br>
of AFSCME and the Teamsters handily won the right to represent a<br>
unit of 7,844 public safety and security officers with
two-thirds.<br>
A labor and trades unit of 2,500 workers also voted
overwhelmingly<br>
for AFSCME.<br>
<br>
GETTING THERE OVERNITE -- Overnite workers at Macon, Ga., Nanuet,<br>
N.Y. and Houston petitioned to join the Teamsters as the chorus
for<br>
respect, job security and a voice on the job grows louder at the<br>
company's terminals across the country. In the past six months,<br>
Overnite workers have filed for IBT representation at 13 trucking<br>
terminals, winning nine.<br>
<br>
GOOD HEALTH CARE -- Two California Service Employees locals won<br>
three elections at community health clinics. Local 79 won a pair
of<br>
elections to represent 120 workers at the Bayview Hunters Point<br>
Foundation and 35 employees at Horizons Unlimited in the San<br>
Francisco Bay area. SEIU Local 415 and new organizing director
Dave<br>
Werlin got 49 new members from a vote by Salud Para La Gente in<br>
Santa Cruz.<br>
<br>
CIRCUS IS GOOD GIG -- The dancing elephants, prancing horses and<br>
daring young men and women on the flying trapeze will have a
steady<br>
back beat now that the Musicians have ratified a new three-year<br>
pact with Ringling Brothers Barnum and Bailey Circus. The two<br>
touring troupes each carry a nine-piece AFM band for a 48-week
road<br>
show. The new deal boosts wages and pension contributions and<br>
includes vacation and medical coverage. AFM has represented
circus<br>
musicians since the 1920s.<br>
<br>
REFORMING WELFARE REFORM -- The Executive Council vowed to fight<br>
any attempts to privatize the Medicaid, food stamp, unemployment<br>
insurance and employment service programs, and said the AFL-CIO<br>
will work to ensure that public employees continue to administer<br>
welfare programs. The federation will fight for legislation to<br>
extend worker rights to welfare recipients and will seek pledges<br>
from nonprofit organizations to participate only in
welfare-to-work<br>
programs that treat the participants fairly.<br>
<br>
GRINCH GETS COMEUPPANCE -- Two days before Thanksgiving,<br>
Westmoreland Coal Co. cancelled health benefits for more than 150<br>
retired coal miners. But the Mine Workers -- like the Whos in Dr.<br>
Seuss' &quot;Grinch&quot; -- went to court to force the company
to restore<br>
health benefits and pay $10,000 into an escrow account to cover
any<br>
medical expenses incurred by the retirees during the two weeks
that<br>
they were denied coverage.<br>
<br>
RAIL PENSION RAID -- The Executive Council called on the Railroad<br>
Retirement Board to back off its plan to unilaterally impose<br>
industry standards for determining the conditions that would<br>
disable workers for various railroad occupations. &quot;It
amounts to a<br>
raid on the pension system that (workers) depend on,&quot; the
council<br>
said. &quot;This threat to the health and welfare of rail workers
cannot<br>
and will not go unchallenged.&quot;<br>
<br>
CALLING FOR PEACE -- Cardinal Adam Maida, citing the &quot;human<br>
fallout,&quot; called for an end to the 17-month Detroit
newspaper<br>
strike. The strike is &quot;legitimate,&quot; he said. &quot;The
right of people<br>
to organize is fundamental. Those that exercise that right, I
stand<br>
with them.&quot; Maida said he has contacted each member of the
boards<br>
of Gannett and Knight-Ridder and is working with Mayor Dennis<br>
Archer and U.S. Sen. Carl Levin (D-Mich) on ways to end the<br>
dispute.<br>
<br>
OPEN BORDERS -- Borders Books is resisting organizing efforts,<br>
drawing the wrath of unions. In Ann Arbor, Mich., members of the<br>
National Writers Union\UAW Local 1981 picketed the book seller,<br>
alerting the public to the company's union-busting tactics and
low<br>
wages. They also marked the six-month anniversary of the firing
of<br>
Philadelphia worker Miriam Fried for her organizing attempts.
Among<br>
the &quot;alternative&quot; Christmas carols picketers belted out
was one to<br>
the tune of Hark the Herald Angels Sings -- &quot;Borders fired
Miriam<br>
Fried in the name of corporate greed.&quot;<br>
<br>
FOOD LION GUILTY -- A federal jury in Florida says Food Lion<br>
violated federal wage-and-hour laws for failing to pay overtime
to<br>
two assistant store managers. The Nov. 14 decision means back pay<br>
claims from more than 1,000 other assistant store managers may go<br>
to court. The anti-union grocery chain must pay the pair for
2,700<br>
hours of uncompensated overtime.<br>
<br>
NONUNION 76 -- UNO-VEN Co. and all its Union 76 products are now
on<br>
the AFL-CIO's national boycott list at the request of the Oil,<br>
Chemical and Atomic Workers. The boycott was triggered by the<br>
company's unilateral decision to make sweeping changes in its<br>
contract, including flexibility issues and creating a multitier
pay<br>
structure.<br>
<br>
PARALLEL RUNWAYS -- A federal court last week rejected a lawsuit
by<br>
the unaffiliated Independent Federation of Flight Attendants<br>
seeking to block a representation election petition by the<br>
Machinists for 5,400 TWA flight attendants. While the National<br>
Mediation Board has yet to act on the request, IFFA members are<br>
voting on whether to affiliate with the Association of Flight<br>
Attendants, with balloting expected to end late this month. IFFA<br>
President Sherry Cooper last August reached a merger agreement
with<br>
IAM that was subsequently turned down by IFFA's executive board.<br>
<br>
BOOTING UP IN THE CITY -- The Teamsters National Black Caucus
urged<br>
Circuit City to donate 10,000 computers to the nation's
inner-city<br>
schools as a way to make up for the company's history of racial<br>
discrimination. Two African-American workers were recently
awarded<br>
almost $300,000 in damages after a jury found the electronics
giant<br>
guilty of showing intentional bias in its employment practices.<br>
<br>
SMOOTH SAILING -- Members of the ILA-affiliated Masters, Mates
and<br>
Pilots re-elected union president Capt. Timothy Brown and<br>
Secretary-Treasurer James Hopkins to third terms. Brown called
the<br>
results a vote for continuity in light of a recently enacted<br>
federal maritime program.<br>
<br>
GOODBY-WATER -- The Executive Council bid adieu to one of its
most<br>
outspoken members, William Bywater of the Electronic Workers, who<br>
stepped down in favor of Edward Fire, who defeated him at the<br>
union's convention last month. The council noted Bywater's<br>
unflinching opposition to exploitation of workers, &quot;whether
it is<br>
in the form of injustice and abuse on the job or in the aftermath<br>
of cold, uncaring economic policies and unfair trade
practices.&quot;<br>
<br>
MEXICO'S MAXI ANTI-UNION -- A complaint filed by the
Communications<br>
Workers charging that the Mexican government failed to protect<br>
workers at Maxi-Switch Inc. in Sonora from &quot;brutal
anti-union&quot;<br>
activities will be reviewed by the U.S. agency overseeing<br>
compliance with NAFTA's labor side agreement. CWA says the state<br>
colluded with the pro-government Confederation of Mexican Workers<br>
to block formation of an independent union, and violated the side<br>
agreement by denying workers &quot;fair, equitable and
transparent&quot;<br>
tribunal proceedings.</p>
