<html>
<head>
<title>WIP 12/09/96 AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS -- December 9, 1996</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<p align="left"><img src="../images/wip.gif" align="bottom"
width="508" height="135"></p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<p align="left">AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS -- December 9, 1996</p>
<pre>MARYLAND GOES AFSCME -- In the first-ever collective bargaining
elections by Maryland state employees, AFSCME Maryland was chosen
as the representative for the state's 7,000 health care and human
service employees and the social workers unit. The union won by
better than 3 to 1 among the health care unit and 2.5 to 1 in the
social workers unit. They were the first results in a series of
union votes among Maryland workers involving AFSCME, the Teamsters
and AFT.

UP TO SOMETHING GOOD -- The 5,400 TWA workers in the unaffiliated
Independent Federation of Flight Attendants are closer to
affiliating with the Association of Flight Attendants. Pending
ratification by IFFA members and AFA's Executive Board, the pact
would boost the 40,000-member AFA and give voting rights to the
IFFA, with a merger taking place within four years. &quot;This ground-
breaking affiliation agreement puts all of us in the strongest
position to meet the challenges we face in our industry,&quot; AFA
President Patricia Friend said.

SEIU'S TRIPLE PLAY -- The Service Employees won three new units
last month. Locals 250 and 790 joined forces and organized 540
workers employed by the San Francisco Visiting Nurses and Hospice.
Up in Seattle, Local 1199NW signed up 105 case workers, social
workers, nurses and support personnel at the Eastside Community
Health center. And 70 janitors who clean federal buildings in
Chicago signed on with Local 25.

DOUBLE WINS AT THE INNS -- The Hotel Employees and Restaurant
Employees and the Operating Engineers won separate elections at
Washington-area hotels. Workers at the Crystal City Hilton Hotel in
Arlington, Va., voted for representation by HERE Local 25, the
first successful bottom-up (all workers) hotel organizing drive in
more than 20 years, HERE reported. Issues included dignity, health
care and wages. Meanwhile, congrats go to the IUOE Local 99, which
organized engineers at the Bethesda, Md., Hyatt. The engineers
voted 8-3 for representation.

DOWN ON THE RANCHO -- Some 120 city workers in Rio Rancho, N.M
voted 72-30 for AFSCME representation. The wall-to-wall unit
consists of workers ranging from laborers to accountants.

WALL STREET UNION -- Workers at The Wall Street Journal are urging
fellow employees to vote for affiliation with the Communications
Workers. This is the third time in almost a decade that the
Independent Association of Publishers' Employees has pursued
affiliation with a larger union.

SINGAPORE SLING -- The ministerial meeting of the World Trade
Organization got off on the wrong foot even before it opened
Monday, as a speaking invitation to Michel Hansenne, director
general of the International Labor Organization, was rescinded.
It's an apparent effort to appease developing countries opposed to
linking trade with labor rights. The AFL-CIO delegation to the
meeting is led by International Affairs Director Barbara Shailor.

NO BOW TO CROWN -- OCAW President Robert Wages and several
Baltimore labor leaders were arrested Dec. 6 after blocking the
doors to Crown's corporate headquarters. The &quot;lock-in&quot; and downtown
rally launched a consumer boycott against the oil company to
protest the lock-out of 250 OCAW members at Crown's Texas refinery.

LORDING IT OVER WORKERS -- More than 1,000 anti-sweatshop
activists, led by UNITE, rallied at Lord &amp; Taylor department store
in New York Dec. 6 to expose the May Company's use of sweatshop
contractors to manufacture private label merchandise. May owns Lord
&amp; Taylor's.

DON'T FOLLOW THESE TRENDSETTERS -- Holiday shoppers who care about
worker rights shouldn't use the De CPI SCHEME: CALAMITY CHANGE --
A proposal to lower the Consumer Price Index would in fact lower
wages, Social Security and other benefits tied to the CPI, AFL-CIO
President John Sweeney warned. A new report from a private
commission claims the CPI overstates inflation and should be
adjusted downward, but it is &quot;far from the last word on this
subject,&quot; Sweeney said. Many respected researchers disagree with
the report and believe it may actually understate inflation.
Lowering the CPI &quot;is nothing more than a back-door tax increase on
working people, the elderly and the poor,&quot; Teamsters President Ron
Carey said.

     partment of Labor's 

     Trendsetter list, which includes many nonunion companies, and
some virulent anti-union employers, UNITE says. DoL established the
list to spotlight apparel manufacturers and retailers that have
voluntarily taken extra steps to ensure their goods are not made in
sweatshop conditions, but labor law violators still abound.

JANITORS STRIKE USC -- Janitors at University of Southern
California staged a two-day strike to protest the illegal
intimidation, harassment and firings of their co-workers by
ServiceMaster supervisors, the contractor that provides janitorial
services  for the university. The workers, members of SEIU Local
399, held a March for Justice and rally along with the Dec. 4-5
action.

MOTOWN HOLIDAY CHEER -- Facing their second holiday season on
strike, Detroit newspaper workers need your help. You can give by
subscribing to the striker-produced newspaper, the Sunday Journal,
by calling 313/567-9818, ext. 135. And you can adopt a striking
family by sending a check to the Detroit Striker Relief Fund, 3100
East Jefferson, Detroit 48207. For more information, call 313/877-
9016.

MO' MOTOWN -- Striking Detroit newspaper workers are taking their
struggle to New York City this week. They will distribute
informational leaflets today through Thursday from 8-10 a.m.
outside the Paine-Webber Media Conference at the McGraw Hill
building in Manhattan.

GETTING TO KNOW YOU -- Union members meet tomorrow with first term
Rep.-Elect Julia Carson (D-Ind.). The Indianapolis meeting is the
first of about 150 that unions plan to hold before March with new
and returning members, both Democrats and Republicans. Building on
Labor 96's success, the goal is to make sure lawmakers know and
understand working families' concerns.

WON'T GET FOOLED AGAIN -- While the GOP purrs about bi-
partisanship, Rep. Bill Clay (D-Mo.) warns &quot;it's all rhetoric.&quot;
Republicans on the House Economic and Educational Opportunities
Committee will pursue, he says, the &quot;same stringent, anti-worker,
anti-labor agenda&quot; they did in the last Congress. Committee
Chairman William Goodling (R-Pa.) promises a bill allowing comp
time instead of overtime-bill and so-called TEAM Act legislation.
Attacks on Davis-Bacon and OSHA are expected too. Same old song.

HITTING HOME -- The AFL-CIO Housing Investment Trust, with assets
of about $2 billion, has been selected as the first labor partner
in HUD's National Partners in Homeownership. The partnership has
set a goal of generating 8 million new home owners over the next
four years. &quot;There is no place more fundamental to begin a family's
quest for self-sufficiency than right at home,&quot; said Stephen Coyle,
HIT's chief executive.

NO TENDER LOVING CARE -- When TLC Services Inc., a Milwaukee
trucking company, abruptly shut its doors Nov. 27, tossing out more
than 70 workers with no advance warning, it was engaged in union-
busting, Teamsters Local 200 charges. Some workers were immediately
rehired by another company located next door under the same
ownership after TLC filed for bankruptcy, the union noted. TLC
failed to give at least 60 days warning of closure, as is required
by state law, and still owes its workers several weeks of back pay.

REPETITIVE WHINE -- An American Trucking Association report is the
latest salvo in a corporate campaign to derail an OSHA-issued
ergonomics standard. ATA claims such a rule would cost the trucking
industry some $6.5 billion annually -- more than OSHA estimates the
cost for all industries. Meanwhile, as corporate interests work to
protect their pocketbooks, some 700,000 of their employees lose
work time each year because of ergonomic-related injuries.

CAL'S WEAK ERGO LAW CHALLENGED -- California's new regulation on
ergonomics will be challenged in court after the holidays, when the
California AFL-CIO seeks a truly protective standard. Executive
Secretary-Treasurer Art Pulaski criticized the regulation's
exemption of employers with less than 10 workers and the lack of
required compliance until two or more workers are injured on
identical jobs.

BEEF'S OVER -- Some 1,800 workers at IBP Inc. in Joslin Mo., ended
their month-long strike by accepting a four-year contract with the
beef processing plant. The agreement calls for annual wage
increases totaling 80 cents per hour over the contract term and
continues the profit sharing plan in a modified form, a major
factor leading to the strike.

COMMON GROUND IN BOSTON -- Hotel Employees and Restaurant Employees
Local 26 averted a threatened strike by approving a new contract
with eight Boston hotels. The five-year accord will raise pay for
most workers by $1.98 per hour over term. The agreement is expected
to set a pattern at six other area hotels and cover about 3,500
workers.

 A CASE FOR UNION -- Workers from Case Farms poultry processing
plant in Morganton, N.C. joined with religious leaders, consumers
and environmentalists seeking congressional investigation of worker
abuses in the poultry industry. Last year the workers voted for
Laborers representation, but the company refuses to bargain with
LIUNA.

DOL BEGINS HEALTH CARE CHECK UP -- The health care industry is
being scrutinized by the Department of Labor for compliance with
wage and hour requirements as part of its Fair Labor Standards Act
initiative. The DoL's Wage and Hour Division has found a 60 percent
violation rate on complaint-driven investigations of nursing homes
and home health care providers. The initiative already is examining
the garment industry, agricultural work and child labor.

TEMPS RISING -- The AFL-CIO urged the National Labor Relations
Board to change the rules and let the nation's 2.4 million
temporary and contingent workers organize and negotiate with their
employers to improve their lives, just as other workers can. Under
current rules, companies that use temporary agencies generally
control wages and working conditions for workers, but are not held
accountable for those conditions, the federation and several
affiliates said.

ECONOMY SLOWING DOWN -- More people are out of work and the rate of
job growth is slowing, according to an AFL-CIO analysis of the
November unemployment figures. The official jobless rate rose from
5.2 percent to 5.4 percent, while the real rate, which includes
marginal workers, was 8.9 percent. The number of new jobs was less
than half of the average for the first eight months of the year,
with most of the jobs added in services.

     &#12;Why we do it

     Three generations in the fields...

     Jesus' father was a farmer in Mexico. Today, Jesus and three
of his six children are strawberry pickers in California.

     Before coming to the U.S., Jesus was a sixth-grade teacher in
Mexico. &quot;My real dream was to be a professor,&quot; he says.

     But now Jesus is 46 years old and has spent 11 years in the
strawberry fields near Watsonville.

     Another dream has replaced the old one -- that conditions in
the fields will improve for Jesus' children. Jesus thinks that's
not far-fetched. He said some conditions began improving when the
United Farm Workers started organizing earlier this year. There
were fewer racial slurs used by foremen, and bathrooms and drinking
water were more often clean.

     Still, most workers don't have health insurance or protection
against abuses such as sexual harassment and arbitrary firings.
Wages remain low. The typical strawberry picker made about $8,500
for the 1996 season, even though it would take only 5 cents more
per pint of berries to increase piece pay rates by at least 50
percent.

     When the new season begins next year, Jesus believes workers
will begin to win a union, and with it, a living wage.

     Artist helps spread the word

     The Strawberry Workers Campaign has produced notecards
featuring pastels of strawberry workers by Colorado artist Tony
Ortega. Help spread word of the campaign by using the cards during
the holidays and beyond. They cost $10 for a set of 12 and proceeds
support the campaign. To order, call 202-637-5043; ask for item No.
271.


     Taking the lead

     CLCs, state labor federations and community groups raised the
campaign to a new level from Nov. 13 to Nov. 22 as UFW President
Arturo Rodriguez and strawberry workers traveled to six cities.
State federations and CLCs helped provide the umbrella for:

* More than 40 groups signing on to the National Strawberry
Commission for Workers' Rights during a national news conference
Nov. 13 in Washington D.C.

* A coalition of about 19 people representing labor, religious,
civil rights and community groups in Philadelphia Nov. 18.

* A coalition of 37 people representing civil rights, community,
religious and labor groups in Baltimore Nov. 19.

* A coalition of about 50 people representing labor and religious
groups in New Jersey Nov. 20.

* A coalition of community, religious, labor and government groups
in New York City Nov. 21.

* A coalition of about 125 people representing rank-and-file
activists, students and religious, labor, community and
environmental groups in Boston Nov. 22.

     Other regions of the country will get a similar catalyst. Next
month The Strawberry Workers Campaign will travel the Midwest.

     Please come to Watsonville

     Workers and their supporters from throughout the nation will
meet in Watsonville, the heart of strawberry country, in April for
a massive march.

     The goal is for 20,000 people to march not just in support of
the workers, but as part of a new movement for fairness.


     The Strawberry Workers Campaign: 1-888-AFL-CIOO

     Media Inquiries: 202-637-5279 or 805-822-5571, X255.</pre>
