<html>
<head>
<title>WIP 12/03/96 AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS -- December 3, 1996</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<p align="left"><img src="../images/wip.gif" align="bottom"
width="508" height="135"></p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<p>Work in Progress -- December 3, 1996<br>
<br>
GUESS? WHO DIDN'T MAKE THE LIST -- Guess? Inc., once on the<br>
Labor Department's coveted Trendsetter list, was placed on<br>
&quot;probation&quot; for allegedly violating labor laws. UNITE
President Jay<br>
Mazur noted that &quot;Guess? is a multiple offender of labor<br>
violations, including making use of industrial homework. It's
time<br>
for Guess? to do the right thing and clean up its act.&quot; The<br>
disclosure came as the DoL named 17 new companies to the year-old<br>
Trendsetter list of garment manufacturers and retailers that<br>
voluntarily have taken extra steps to ensure their goods are not<br>
made in sweatshop conditions.<br>
<br>
WORKER RIGHTS IN GLOBAL ARENA -- At the Vatican this week,<br>
AFL-CIO President John Sweeney and other global labor leaders<br>
discussed worker rights, social issues and the role of labor
unions<br>
in the international economy. &quot;Let's work together for a
global<br>
economy that lifts the living standards and honors the human<br>
dignity of every man, woman and child,&quot; Sweeney told the
Pontifical<br>
Council for Justice and Peace. At a Thanksgiving meeting in
Geneva,<br>
Sweeney urged World Trade Organization President Renato Ruggerio
to<br>
back the establishment of a working party or commission to study<br>
the linkage of worker rights and trade. Developing nations are<br>
opposing that linkage, which will be championed at next week's
WTO<br>
meeting in Singapore by the United States.<br>
<br>
SWEATSHOPS EXPOSED -- Two Salvadoran union activists told the<br>
congressional human rights caucus Dec. 2 that their government is<br>
violating worker rights in the free trade zones built with U.S.
tax<br>
dollars. Women work 12- to 17-hour days, six days a week for as<br>
little as 40 cents an hour in sweatshops in the free trade zone,<br>
they said. Nearly all the garments made in the zone are exported
to<br>
the United States. Also testifying were Alan Howard of UNITE and<br>
Charles Kernaghan of the National Labor Committee.<br>
<br>
CHICKEN STICKLIN' -- Responding to a report by the National<br>
Interfaith Committee for Worker Justice that workers in the
poultry<br>
processing industry face harsh and unlawful conditions, the<br>
Department of Labor next year will begin a special targeted labor<br>
standards enforcement program for the industry. &quot;Sweatshop<br>
conditions -- whether in garment factories, fields or poultry<br>
processing plants -- will not be tolerated,&quot; Labor Secretary
Robert<br>
Reich declared.<br>
<br>
UMWA WINS AT NURSING HOME -- Employees of Maple Grove Health<br>
Care in Lebanon, Va., voted 32-5 for Mine Worker representation.<br>
Several UMWA coal miners and workers from the recently organized<br>
Long Airdox manufacturing plant in Saltville, Va., participated
in<br>
the drive. Maple Grove is the third nursing home facility
organized<br>
by the UMWA.<br>
<br>
LEGITIMATE BEEF -- A federal judge in Colorado ordered Monfort<br>
Inc. to pay nearly $2 million in back wages to 5,071 employees at<br>
its Greeley, Colo., beef processing plant. The order resolves a<br>
suit filed by the Labor Department alleging that Monfort violated<br>
the Fair Labor Standards Act by not paying its workers overtime
and<br>
for not keeping required records. The workers are represented by<br>
the Food and Commercial Workers.<br>
<br>
COLLEGE WORKERS CASH IN -- Cashiers at University of Rochester<br>
(N.Y.) dining centers and snack bars have joined SEIU District<br>
1199, which represents some 175 UR campus workers and more than
800<br>
staff members at UR's Medical Center and Strong Memorial
Hospital.<br>
The 12 workers now come under a new two-year pact approved in<br>
October.<br>
<br>
NLRB FLUNKS YALE -- Two just-issued NLRB complaints charge<br>
that Yale University threatened to fire workers for participating<br>
in union activities, transferred employees who supported the
union<br>
and illegally stopped withholding union dues from paychecks after<br>
the last contract expired. HERE Locals 34 and 35 represent the<br>
school clerical, maintenance and technical employees involved.<br>
<br>
FIGHTING FOR SOCIAL SECURITY -- Unions can use their pension<br>
funds to fight moves to privatize Social Security, AFL-CIO<br>
Secretary-Treasurer Richard Trumka said. In a speech to labor<br>
educators at the University of California, Trumka said pension
fund<br>
trustees should avoid investment houses that want to turn Social<br>
Security into a speculative Wall Street venture and shift pension<br>
plans to individual retirement accounts. IRAs &quot;undermine the<br>
leverage workers have on corporations, and they channel
investments<br>
in ways that are indifferent and even hostile to workers'<br>
interests,&quot; Trumka said. &quot;Workers and their unions
should not allow<br>
our pension funds to be used against us.&quot; <br>
<br>
LIMO DRIVERS FIGHT VIOLENCE -- Hundreds of newly organized New<br>
York City limousine drivers rallied Dec. 2 to protest the beating<br>
of one of their union leaders. Aijaz Alamdar was beaten Nov. 22
by<br>
four men on the property of Elite Limousine while conducting
normal<br>
business. The next day, the drivers' union voted to affiliate
with<br>
IAM District Lodge 15. The mostly immigrant workers from
Pakistan,<br>
India, China, Latin America and the Caribbean won the right to an<br>
election when the NLRB rejected Elite's claim the 500 drivers
were<br>
&quot;independent contractors.&quot;<br>
<br>
HEALTH CARE PARTNERSHIP -- In northern California, Service<br>
Employees Local 250 reached an unprecedented master agreement
with<br>
the West Bay Region of Catholic Health Care West that recognizes<br>
union rights and protects against subcontracting. The four-year<br>
pact prohibits subcontracting on site and gives the union the
right<br>
to offer alternatives to off-site subcontracting. A mutual code
of<br>
conduct for organizing campaigns was established, as were<br>
procedures to speed up union elections. Workers also gained a
voice<br>
in patient care through a new joint committee.<br>
<br>
ALTITUDE ADJUSTMENTS -- The Air Line Pilots reached a<br>
tentative agreement with UAL Corp., the parent company of United<br>
Airlines, that features a 10 percent wage increase over four
years<br>
and a profit-sharing plan. The pact, which affects 8,500 pilots,<br>
also contains increases in expense per diem and international<br>
expense override. ALPA members will be receiving ratification<br>
ballots in mid-December and votes will be counted a month later.<br>
Some 22,000 Flight Attendants at the airline have been without a<br>
contract since March.<br>
<br>
POOR PUMMELED BY BUDGET CUTS -- Programs designed to help the<br>
poor took much bigger hits in the GOP-controlled 104th Congress<br>
than other programs. A report by the Center on Budget and Policy<br>
Priorities shows that programs aimed at the poor account for 37<br>
percent of entitlement spending between 1997 and 2002, yet absorb<br>
93 percent of the entitlement budget cuts. In the entire
nondefense<br>
budget, low-income programs account for 23 percent of spending
but<br>
will absorb 53 percent of the spending cuts.<br>
<br>
UNIONS MEAN PAY EQUITY -- Union representation not only<br>
usually affords higher wages for women and minorities but also<br>
provides a voice at the workplace and in the courts to press for<br>
equal wages, a report by the National Committee on Pay Equity<br>
concludes. The &quot;Intersection Between Pay Equity and
Workplace<br>
Representation&quot; is available from the Committee at
202/331-7343.<br>
<br>
MEETING OF THE MINDS -- Screen Actors Guild and Television and<br>
Radio Artists leaders have formally backed plans to merge the two<br>
unions of performers and broadcasters. The plans now must be<br>
approved by the unions' boards individually, by the AFTRA<br>
convention in August 1997 and finally by 60 percent of the
members<br>
of each union via secret ballot. The plans would create 30 locals<br>
covering 120,000 current members governed by a national board
with<br>
a national president, secretary-treasurer and four vice
presidents,<br>
a biennial convention and offices in Los Angeles and New York.<br>
<br>
WALKOUT IN AKRON -- After more than a year of stonewalling and<br>
union-busting tactics by management, workers at the Akron City<br>
Hospital said &quot;no more&quot; and walked off the job. The
only result of<br>
a year's worth of talks, AFSCME Local 684 says, has been constant<br>
threats to job security. The hospital tried to establish a co-pay<br>
for health insurance for the predominantly female,
African-American<br>
workers, whose average pay is $8.50 an hour. No talks are<br>
scheduled.<br>
<br>
MAKE IT A UNION GIFT -- UNITE launched a holiday campaign to<br>
urge consumers to &quot;Wear what you believe: UNITE!&quot; The
ad urges<br>
consumers to look for the union label, and will run for two weeks<br>
beginning Nov. 29 in The New York Times, New York Times Magazine,<br>
The Washington Post, Women's Wear Daily, the Daily News Record
and<br>
The New Republic magazine.<br>
<br>
WORKERS' GUIDE TO INVESTMENTS -- Want to learn how unions can<br>
make worker-friendly investments? Pick up a copy of the<br>
federation's digest on capital strategies. It outlines investment<br>
in plants, equipment, modernization, training, innovation and new<br>
work systems using workers' own pension funds. The guide explores<br>
strategies for such investments and the legal framework behind<br>
them. It also includes sections on shareholder activism and<br>
employee ownership programs. The guide can be ordered through the<br>
AFL-CIO's Corporate Affairs Department, by calling Christine Tate<br>
at 202/637-5162.<br>
<br>
HIGHER PENSION GUARANTEE -- The maximum retirement benefit to<br>
be guaranteed by the federal government next year is $2,761.36
per<br>
month, or $33,136.32 per year. Those benefits are payable by the<br>
Pension Benefit Guaranty Corp.'s insurance program to retirees in<br>
underfunded single-employer defined-benefit plans that are<br>
terminated in 1997. Since 1974, the PBGC has guaranteed the<br>
benefits of nearly 400,000 private-sector workers and retirees<br>
participating in 2,084 pension plans.<br>
<br>
ADJUSTING TO NAFTA -- In a deal brokered by the UAW, workers<br>
displaced by the North American Free Trade Agreement but denied<br>
income-support benefits under an earlier eligibility definition<br>
have a new chance for help. A recent agreement with the Labor<br>
Department applies to those persons certified for NAFTA Trade<br>
Adjustment Assistance but denied income support under a since-<br>
rejected provision. Workers have until April 15, 1997, to contact<br>
their local Employment Service office for redetermination of
their<br>
TAA eligibility.<br>
<br>
DEEPER IN DEBT -- September's trade deficit was the worst<br>
ever, a whopping $17.7 billion. The deficit for the year is<br>
projected to hit $180 billion, breaking 1995's record of $173<br>
billion. So far this year, imports of manufactured goods have<br>
exceeded exports by $129.7 billion. China topped the month's list<br>
at $4.7 billion, and is fast approaching Japan as the largest<br>
bilateral deficit trading partner.<br>
<br>
PUBLIC SECTOR DELIVERS -- In a strong endorsement of the<br>
public sector, the U.S. Department of Labor has issued a three-<br>
year, multimillion dollar grant giving Washington state's<br>
Employment Security Department prime responsibility for
developing<br>
and operating the &quot;One-Stop Shopping System.&quot; The
grant, which<br>
ranges from $2.5 million to $5 million annually, keeps the full<br>
range of employment services in the hands of state employees
rather<br>
than a private company.</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../index.htm">Public Documents Page</a> | <a
href="../publsear.htm">Public Documents Search</a></p>
