<html>
<head>
<title>WIP 11/26/96 AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS -- November 26, 1996</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<p align="left"><img src="../images/wip.gif" align="bottom"
width="508" height="135"></p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<p>AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS -- November 26, 1996<br>
<br>
WORKLIFE AT MGM -- IT'S GRAND -- After a four-year organizing<br>
drive, nearly 3,000 workers at the MGM Grand Hotel in Las Vegas
won<br>
union representation under a card-check agreement between the
hotel<br>
and Hotel Employees and Restaurant Employees Locals 226 and 165.<br>
The unions, which gathered the signatures of more than half the<br>
workers, also gained recognition for a smaller number of
employees<br>
at the Main Street Station hotel/casino in downtown Las Vegas.<br>
<br>
HEALTH WORKERS GO LIUNA -- More than 1,000 registered nurses,<br>
LPNs and technicians at two Redding, Calif., hospitals said yes
to<br>
LIUNA representation. The workers seek better wages and safer
work<br>
conditions in an atmosphere poisoned by hospital and staff
cutbacks<br>
that drastically increase patient-to-nurse ratios.<br>
<br>
TEAMSTERS ROLL -- Workers at Overnite Transportation in<br>
Decatur, Ala., and Little Rock, Ark., voted for Teamsters<br>
representation --by 15-4 and 18-13 votes, respectively. Workers
may<br>
see more Overnite success because six more terminals filed for
IBT<br>
representation last month: Baltimore, Charlotte, N.C., Tupelo,<br>
Miss., Florence S.C., New Orleans and Oakland.<br>
<br>
UNION BUSTER'S BALLOON BURST -- An imported union buster lost<br>
a four-month fight with 160 A&amp;E Transport drivers in
Syracuse, N.Y.<br>
The drivers, who provide transportation for special-needs school<br>
children, rolled over the lies and voted for representation by<br>
Service Employees Local 200B. Meanwhile, in Greene County, N.Y.,<br>
SEIU Local 4053 didn't let a county move to privatize former
public<br>
sector jobs deter its organizing efforts. The local went after<br>
them, winning the right to represent 42 health care<br>
paraprofessionals who work for a private contractor at a<br>
correctional facility.<br>
<br>
UPGRADING TO FIRST CLASS -- The Communications Workers hope to<br>
win the votes of nearly 10,000 USAir passenger service workers in<br>
balloting next month. If approved, it would be the first airline<br>
shop for the CWA and the first union for the airline's ticket and<br>
reservation agents and others who assist passengers at more than<br>
100 airports and reservation centers. Other unions at USAir
include<br>
the Air Line Pilots, Flight Attendants, Machinists and Transport<br>
Workers. Ballots will be mailed Dec. 17.<br>
<br>
ABSOLUTELY, POSITIVELY IBT -- Workers at Federal Express<br>
suddenly got a 3 percent raise and lump-sum direct
profit-sharing,<br>
apparently resulting from an aggressive Teamsters organizing<br>
campaign. Just a few months ago, CEO Fred Smith declared that<br>
workers would no longer get scheduled pay increases, and profit-<br>
sharing monies would go into retirement accounts. &quot;Just
think how<br>
much more they'll win with a legally binding contract,&quot;
President<br>
Ron Carey said. Workers at eight FedEx stations have filed for<br>
representation elections, and organizing is taking place at<br>
hundreds of other stations nationwide.<br>
<br>
CRASH CLAIMS IAM VP -- Machinists are mourning the death of<br>
Vice President Larry Downing, who directed the union's nine-state<br>
Midwest Territory. He was one of the 14 victims in the crash of a<br>
commuter plane and private plane last week in Quincy, Ill.
Downing,<br>
who was traveling to Quincy on union business, is survived by his<br>
wife, Pat, a son and two daughters.<br>
<br>
CONFRONTING GANNETT -- More than 100 Detroit newspaper<br>
strikers and their supporters challenged corporate scofflaw
Gannett<br>
and its private goon squad, Vance Security, in three days of<br>
protest in the D.C. area. Apparently frightened by peaceful<br>
protesters and picket signs, Gannett put its Rosslyn, Va.,<br>
headquarters under virtual lock-down. At the headquarters of
Vance<br>
Security -- whose squads have harassed strikers -- protesters had<br>
a spirited, peaceful face-off with dozens of police officers and<br>
scores of security guards in riot gear. The next day, the
strikers<br>
leafleted at the National Press Building, where Gannett and
Knight-<br>
Ridder have bureaus.<br>
<br>
NEW ORGANIZING APPOINTMENTS -- Chris Woods, former Organizing<br>
Institute recruitment director, has been named deputy director of<br>
the AFL-CIO Organizing Department. Four new assistant directors<br>
also have been announced: Bob Lawson, for organizing education;<br>
Stephen Lerner, for campaign strategies; Andy Levin, for<br>
cooperative campaigns; and Peter Rider, for national campaigns.
All<br>
have been involved in the restructuring of the department under<br>
director Richard Bensinger, and Levin was director of Union
Summer.<br>
They join Allison Porter, who heads the Organizing Institute and
is<br>
assistant director for recruitment and training.<br>
<br>
YALE FAILS -- Yale University will face charges if it doesn't<br>
settle with teaching assistants who are trying to unionize, the<br>
NLRB told the Ivy League school. A strike by the Graduate
Employees<br>
and Students Organization ended in January after the university<br>
threatened to take away the teaching jobs of assistants who<br>
withheld grades. The precedent-setting case could make it easier<br>
for teaching assistants to form unions.<br>
<br>
FIGHTING TO THE NTH DEGREE -- More than 1,200 striking<br>
graduate teaching assistants were joined by thousands of other<br>
student employees in their strike at three University of
California<br>
campuses. They are protesting the nine-campus system's refusal to<br>
recognize the union of graduate student instructors. More than
two-<br>
thirds of GSIs at UCLA, UC San Diego and UC Berkeley signed<br>
representation cards for the UAW-affiliated unit.<br>
<br>
FIRE WINS AT IUE -- Ed Fire was elected president of the<br>
Electronic Workers, defeating incumbent Bill Bywater 64,865 to<br>
59,787 Saturday at the union's convention in Orlando, Fla. Fire,<br>
59, had served as secretary-treasurer since 1982, when Bywater,
76,<br>
was elected president. Ron Gilvin, 51, chair of the IUE GM<br>
Conference Board, was elected secretary-treasurer, defeating Tom<br>
Rebman. The new officers take over Jan. 1.<br>
<br>
HERE'S BRIDGE FOR JUSTICE -- HERE Local 11 members, calling<br>
themselves the &quot;building bridges for justice&quot;
delegation, took<br>
their long-running fight with the New Otani Hotel &amp; Garden in
Los<br>
Angeles to Japan. A delegation of union members met with
executives<br>
of the hotel's parent New Otani Co. Ltd, U.S. Ambassador Walter<br>
Mondale and Japan Trade Union Confederation officials. They also<br>
demonstrated at New Otani's offices in Tokyo.<br>
<br>
CITARELLA IS GROCERY CRUELLA -- Food and Commercial Workers<br>
Locals 174 and 1500 rallied in front of Citarella grocery in New<br>
York City demanding reinstatement of workers fired for supporting<br>
a union. The union also filed unfair labor practice charges with<br>
the NLRB. Many of the store's mostly Latino workers put in 66 to
80<br>
hours a week while earning barely more than the minimum wage,<br>
working in Citarella's basement with only one exit.<br>
<br>
A TASTE OF VICTORY -- SEIU Local 82 reports progress in its<br>
seven-week janitors' strike against P&amp;R Enterprises, the
largest<br>
non-union cleaning contractor in Metropolitan Washington. At<br>
National Airport, P&amp;R's joint venture partner, PRIEM Building<br>
Services, agreed to settle many strike issues with janitors, and<br>
the strikers there have been able to return to work. But more
than<br>
150 janitors at other locations in downtown Washington remain on<br>
strike as the holidays approach. Hundreds rallied behind the<br>
Justice for Janitors banner last Thursday.<br>
<br>
ACT NOW ON BLACK LUNG -- The Mine Workers say it's time for<br>
quick action on 20 recommendations by the Labor Department to<br>
eradicate black lung disease and silicosis. UMWA President Cecil<br>
Roberts calls speedy implementation &quot;a major step toward
stopping<br>
the progress of these diseases among today's miners, and entirely<br>
preventing these diseases among the next generation.&quot;<br>
<br>
HUNGERING FOR JUSTICE -- Six laid-off Price Pfister workers<br>
are on a weeklong hunger strike to protest the Pacoima, Calif.,<br>
company's cruel treatment of its largely Latino work force. The<br>
hunger strike continues through Thanksgiving eve, when workers
will<br>
present the company with the &quot;Turkey of the Year&quot;
award. The 1,000<br>
workers at Pfister, members of the Teamsters, are fighting the<br>
company for its layoff of 300 workers in the last year in order
to<br>
shift production to Mexico.<br>
<br>
FAIR BALL -- Reebok International Ltd. announced that by this<br>
spring the company's soccer balls will bear labels guaranteeing<br>
they were made without child labor. Reebok has pledged to
implement<br>
a rigorous monitoring program and is supporting educational and<br>
vocational training programs for children previously employed in<br>
the industry. The action was in response to the &quot;Foul
Ball&quot;<br>
campaign mounted by labor and its allies to spotlight the use of<br>
child labor to make the balls.<br>
<br>
JUST DO IT, MICHAEL -- In a letter-writing campaign, children<br>
around the world are asking hoop hero Michael Jordan to put<br>
pressure on Nike, one of his biggest sponsors, to pay its workers<br>
a living wage. The Council of Labor Union Women says that
Jordan's<br>
Nike endorsement earns him $20 million a year, more than Nike's<br>
entire 120,000-strong Indonesian work force earns annually. CLUW<br>
has extended its deadline to receive letters from union members.<br>
For information, call 202/466-4610.<br>
<br>
ADDING UP EDUCATION -- It shouldn't be a surprise, AFT says,<br>
that an international survey shows American 8th graders below<br>
average in math and above average in science. &quot;We're kidding<br>
ourselves if we think we'll see any real improvement in student<br>
learning in this country until we put in place a system of<br>
fundamental changes: high standards for all students, a solid<br>
curriculum with challenging academic content and a serious,<br>
disciplined environment for learning,&quot; notes AFT President
Albert<br>
Shanker.<br>
<br>
HOLD THAT LINE -- Utility Workers President Don Wightman urged<br>
Home Box Office to stop using a promo that shows children picking<br>
up a wire (that leads to a spaceship). The ad &quot;gives a
message to<br>
children that there is something fun at the end of a downed wire,<br>
while what really awaits them may be live electricity and
death,&quot;<br>
Wightman wrote.<br>
<br>
&quot;RANSOM&quot; SLINGS MUD AT IAM -- Mel Gibson's latest
movie,<br>
&quot;Ransom,&quot; takes some cheap shots at the Machinists.
Gibson plays an<br>
airline owner whose son is kidnapped. Another actor plays a
corrupt<br>
IAM union official. Large numbers of outraged members have called<br>
IAM's headquarters to complain about the union's portrayal. The<br>
union legal department is exploring what action, if any, can be<br>
taken.<br>
<br>
ERGONOMICS, TAKE TWO -- An OSHA-NIOSH conference on effective<br>
workplace practices and programs dealing with ergonomics is set
for<br>
Jan. 8-9, 1997, in Chicago. Check out OSHA's home page on the<br>
Internet at www.osha.gov for information, including a
registration<br>
form, or call VisionsUSA, the conference coordinator for OSHA, at<br>
404/880-0006, Ext. 227.<br>
<br>
HEALTH CARE CONFAB -- Workers interested in pushing for<br>
universal health care gather in Arlington, Va., Dec. 6-8 at the<br>
Universal Health Care Action Network's sixth annual conference.<br>
Service Employees and UNITE representatives will address the<br>
delegates. Other sponsors include 1199 National Health and Human<br>
Services Employees Union, UNITE, Oil, Chemical and Atomic
Workers,<br>
the Indiana State AFL-CIO, OCAW Local 6-10 and Musicians Local
802.<br>
For more info call UHCAN! at 216/241-8422 or 800/634-4442.</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../index.htm">Public Documents Page</a> | <a
href="../publsear.htm">Public Documents Search</a></p>
