HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.1
Date: Saturday, 15-Feb-97 08:26:42 GMT
Last-modified: Tuesday, 11-Feb-97 21:16:36 GMT
Content-length: 12269
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3O/DTD HTML//EN">

<html>
<head>
<title>WIP 11/18/96 AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS -- November 18, 1996</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<p align="left"><img src="../images/wip.gif" align="bottom"
width="508" height="135"></p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<p>Monday, November 18, 1996<br>
<br>
STRAWBERRY TRAILS -- Representatives from more than 50 labor,<br>
community and religious organizations joined AFL-CIO President
John<br>
Sweeney and Farm Workers President Arturo Rodriguez Nov. 13 to<br>
launch a new National Strawberry Commission on Workers Rights.
The<br>
commission will monitor working conditions in strawberry fields,
as<br>
well as seek support for the workers from supermarket managers
and<br>
the public. Rodriguez and several strawberry workers on Sunday<br>
began a tour of East Coast cities to drum up support.<br>
<br>
GOT THEIR ATTENTION -- Further evidence that the AFL-CIO's<br>
Labor `96 campaign brought working families back to the political<br>
limelight comes from the Coalition, the alliance of powerful big<br>
business and trade groups that is planning a permanent
organization<br>
to fight workers' efforts in coming elections. Why? &quot;We want
to<br>
continue to counter a resurgent labor movement,&quot; a Coalition
leader<br>
said.<br>
<br>
PARK UNION -- A campaign by the Parking Attendants Rights<br>
Committee of the Hotel Employees and Restaurant Employees won a<br>
huge victory after MetroPark agreed to sign a union contract<br>
covering all its facilities in the metropolitan Washington area.<br>
The win comes 18 months after workers voted in favor of union<br>
representation.<br>
<br>
POWER DEMAND -- As the merger nears between non-union<br>
Baltimore Gas &amp; Electric and Washington's PEPCO, the
Electrical<br>
Workers intensified its organizing campaign at BG&amp;E during a
Nov.<br>
15 rally led by AFL-CIO President John Sweeney and IBEW President<br>
John Barry. &quot;BG&amp;E has resisted our efforts with a litany
of<br>
tactics, including the hiring of a union-busting law firm and<br>
outright lies about the IBEW,&quot; Barry said.<br>
<br>
RAISIN' UP IN HOUSTON -- Under the banner &quot;Six-fifty for the<br>
City,&quot; the Houston Coalition for a Living Wage turned in
more than<br>
30,000 signed petitions Nov. 7 to put a citywide, $6.50-an-hour<br>
minimum wage on the ballot. &quot;We found broad and enthusiastic<br>
support&quot; to give the city's 54,000 minimum-wage workers a
raise,<br>
said Richard Sawyer, Harris County AFL-CIO secretary-treasurer.
The<br>
referendum is scheduled for Jan. 18.<br>
<br>
OVERNITE SENSATION -- Workers at Overnite Transportation Co.<br>
in New Orleans and Oakland joined their brothers and sisters at<br>
other locations around the country in filing election petitions
for<br>
Teamsters representation. So far, IBT has been selected at 21<br>
Overnite terminals, and the NLRB has issued bargaining order<br>
complaints at another 14 sites. &quot;The time has come to join
the<br>
Overnite movement for fairness and respect on the job,&quot;
Oakland<br>
city driver Aaron Gettle said.<br>
<br>
DARK DAYS AT SUNBEAM -- Chainsaw Al has done it again. Roving<br>
terminator Albert Dunlap, who earned the moniker after laying off<br>
a third of Scott Paper Co.'s workers in 1994, plans to get rid of<br>
50 percent of Sunbeam Corp.'s work force, chopping down 6,000<br>
workers. Analyst John Challenger said the slash-and-burn action<br>
&quot;certainly ranks up there with the largest cuts&quot; --
this after a<br>
decade marked by wholesale downsizing. Labor Secretary Robert
Reich<br>
called the move &quot;irresponsible corporate behavior,&quot; a
view shared<br>
even by many on Wall Street.<br>
<br>
BAD BUSINESS -- Pennsylvania's working families will converge<br>
on the State Capitol in Harrisburg Nov. 19 to challenge state<br>
leaders to abandon policies that encourage low-wage jobs and take<br>
up a new direction to create good jobs and strengthen families
and<br>
communities. &quot;At the moment, Pennsylvania may be open for
business,<br>
but it's the wrong kind of business,&quot; said William George,
state<br>
fed president.<br>
<br>
GUESS AGAIN -- UNITE's anti-sweatshop campaign is putting the<br>
heat on Guess? Inc., which uses sweatshop labor for its trendy<br>
clothing line. Students at more than 20 campuses, spearheaded by<br>
Union Summer grads, will demonstrate against Guess?. For more<br>
information, contact the Stop Sweatshops Campaign (212) 819-0959,<br>
or go straight to the source and call 1-800-39GUESS and ask them<br>
why they use sweatshop labor.<br>
<br>
GRASSROOTS REVIVAL -- State federation leaders are in<br>
Philadelphia early this week, meeting with AFL-CIO President John<br>
Sweeney, Secretary-Treasurer Richard Trumka and Executive Vice<br>
President Linda Chavez-Thompson to map out new grassroots<br>
strategies for organizing and legislative activism. Workshops are<br>
being held on subjects ranging from workers' compensation and<br>
training systems to welfare reform. <br>
<br>
ONE PILL COSTS YOU MONEY -- Nursing home residents and their<br>
families may face possible price gouging by the Pharmacy Corp. of<br>
America, a subsidiary of Beverly Enterprises. The Family and<br>
Advocates Network sponsored by the Service Employees found that
PCA<br>
may be overcharging from between 11 percent to nearly 300 percent<br>
for their prescriptions. Last week, the Network kicked off a<br>
nationwide campaign to alert the public.<br>
<br>
CHRISTMAS TOY JOY -- The Labor Students and Alumni of Indiana<br>
University in South Bend launched a Christmas toy drive for the<br>
children of striking Detroit newspaper workers who are spending<br>
their second holiday season on the picket lines. And they are<br>
urging local unions across the country to do the same thing. For<br>
more information on ways to help the strikers, call 313/877-9016.<br>
<br>
SEE YOU IN COURT -- Legal Aid lawyers and support staff have<br>
sued the City of New York, claiming the city violated their labor<br>
rights during their 1994 strike. The short strike by the
attorneys,<br>
members of UAW Local 2325, against the nonprofit Legal Aid
Society<br>
ended when GOP Mayor Rudolph Giuliani announced he was canceling<br>
the society's contract to provide legal services to the city's
poor<br>
and would not pay for services by any lawyer who did not report
to<br>
work the next day.<br>
<br>
REAL DOWNER -- Real average hourly earnings dipped 0.3 percent<br>
in October. Working families feel the pinch because hourly
earnings<br>
have not increased for a year, while prices have gained a bit.
Real<br>
weekly earnings dropped even further, 1.5 percent, and are down
0.6<br>
percent for the 12-month period. Meanwhile, prices rose 0.3
percent<br>
for the month, indicating that inflation is moderate and steady,<br>
with no indication of a major upsurge any time soon.<br>
<br>
UFCW TO IBP, LET'S SHARE -- Last year, for the first time<br>
since it was instituted, some 1,800 members of UFCW Local 1540 at<br>
IBP beef processing plant received a significant payout from a<br>
profit-sharing plan. So when IBP's latest contract offer killed
the<br>
plan, the workers at the Joslin, Mo., plant last week rejected
the<br>
pact and walked off the job.<br>
<br>
REBUILDING HOPE -- UNITE has helped to rebuild three black<br>
churches burned in South Carolina over the past 18 months. Union<br>
President Jay Mazur traveled to Effingham, S.C., to join the<br>
pastors of the churches to mark UNITE's offering. &quot;Evil
meant to<br>
triumph in this burning, but God meant it for good,&quot; said
Rev. Troy<br>
Shaw of Effingham Baptist, one of the three churches. &quot;Labor
has<br>
truly supported us during this time of trouble.&quot;<br>
<br>
TWO MORE WINS -- A year-and-a-half struggle at Bulk Lift<br>
International near Chicago ended when UNITE members there won a<br>
first contract that gives preferential reinstatement rights to 56<br>
workers fired for union activity. AFSCME members working for New<br>
Mexico's Children, Youth and Family Services Department won an<br>
arbitration in which the state admitted changing work schedules
to<br>
avoid paying overtime.<br>
<br>
NEW CLASS AT HARVARD -- Harvard University's determination to<br>
cut health care premium payments prompted the AFSCME-affiliated<br>
Harvard Union of Clerical and Technical Workers to set up<br>
informational picketing starting Oct. 30. If the Ivy League
school<br>
has its way, more than 500 part-time workers will see their
health<br>
care costs go up $700 annually.<br>
<br>
FREE TRADE'S JUST ANOTHER WORD -- A poll by BankBoston reveals<br>
that most Americans aren't buying the argument that free trade<br>
equals job growth. The survey found that 51 percent think trade<br>
agreements result in fewer jobs, with only 23 percent foreseeing<br>
greater opportunity. On top of that, a whopping 73 percent of<br>
Americans think labor and environmental provisions should be<br>
included in trade pacts.<br>
<br>
STANDARD ISSUES -- The White House plans to continue linking<br>
labor standards and trade, as exemplified by its push for a labor<br>
standards work group at the World Trade Organization. However,
its<br>
reluctance to reopen the labor side agreement of the North
American<br>
Free Trade Agreement means that American workers, like those
fired<br>
at a Spanish-language Sprint subsidiary in San Francisco, still<br>
would lack redress, according to the AFL-CIO Task Force on Trade.<br>
<br>
CALIFORNIA TAKES ON ERGONOMICS -- The nation's first state<br>
standard addressing the spreading scourge of repetitive motion<br>
injuries is in place in California -- but the rule is too riddled<br>
with loopholes to do much good. &quot;It is an unenforceable
standard,&quot;<br>
said Tom Rankin of the California AFL-CIO. The rule could be<br>
useful, said AFL-CIO Occupational Safety and Health Director Peg<br>
Seminario, in that it shows a significant problem and the
necessity<br>
of government action in solving the problem. &quot;That said, the<br>
solution being put forward is the most minimal action that could
be<br>
taken. It was not a serious effort to protect workers.&quot;<br>
<br>
REPETITIVELY SPEAKING -- A conference on effective workplace<br>
practices and programs dealing with ergonomics is set for Jan.
8-9,<br>
1997, at the Sheraton Chicago Hotel and Towers. Co-sponsored by<br>
OSHA, NIOSH and the Voluntary Programs Participants' Association,<br>
the conference also will provide a forum for labor, government,<br>
business and academia representatives to share information. For<br>
more information, contact Kathy Lea at the VPPPA at 703/761-1146.<br>
<br>
HEALTH CARE BACK IN SPOTLIGHT -- Two weeks after an election<br>
in which the AFL-CIO drove the national debate on issues
important<br>
to working families like Medicare and Medicaid, President John<br>
Sweeney keynoted the American Public Health Association's annual<br>
meeting. Sweeney was the 1996 Dolan Lecturer honoring public
health<br>
nurse Margaret Baggett Dolan. A one-day conference examining the<br>
role of labor and consumer organizations in safeguarding health<br>
care quality is slated for Nov. 21 at the Gramercy Park Hotel in<br>
New York City, during the annual meeting. The conference is<br>
sponsored by the AFL-CIO's Department for Professional Employees.<br>
For more information, contact DPE's Pamela Wilson at
202/638-0320,<br>
Ext. 2, or Marjorie Wheeler at 202/638-0320, Ext. 4.<br>
<br>
SPINNING THE INFO.WEB -- The AFL-CIO will hold InfoTech, an<br>
information technology conference, on Nov. 20. The one-day<br>
conference at federation headquarters shows how the booming<br>
cyberspace race can be used by unions to boost organizing,<br>
political action, membership services and much more. For<br>
information, or to reserve a space, contact Renate Lawson at
(202)<br>
637-5362.</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../index.htm">Public Documents Page</a> | <a
href="../publsear.htm">Public Documents Search</a></p>
