HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.1
Date: Saturday, 15-Feb-97 08:28:03 GMT
Last-modified: Tuesday, 11-Feb-97 21:16:36 GMT
Content-length: 12472
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3O/DTD HTML//EN">

<html>
<head>
<title>WIP 11/14/96 AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS -- November 14, 1996</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<p align="left"><img src="../images/wip.gif" align="bottom"
width="508" height="135"></p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<p>November 14, 1996<br>
<br>
WORKING FAMILIES ARE BACK! -- The unprecedented Labor '96<br>
grass-roots effort forced Newt Gingrich and his allies to retreat<br>
from their extremist agenda and campaign on working family
issues.<br>
Incumbents with anti-working family records were defeated in 18<br>
congressional districts where the labor movement ran aggressive<br>
campaigns. Pro-worker Democrats also won three open seats and
eight<br>
Senate seats where Labor '96 had active campaigns.<br>
<br>
WORKERS GET OUT AND VOTE -- Twenty-three percent of all voters<br>
were from union households, up from 14 percent in 1994 and 19<br>
percent in 1992. These 21 million voters were the key in many<br>
congressional races, where 68 percent of AFL-CIO union members<br>
voted Democratic and 32 percent voted Republican, according to a<br>
Peter D. Hart post-election poll. That compares with 45 percent<br>
Democratic and 53 percent Republican among nonunion households.<br>
Unionists favored President Clinton by 64 percent, with 28
percent<br>
for Bob Dole and 8 percent for Ross Perot.<br>
<br>
UNION MEMBERS APPLAUD CAMPAIGN -- Among union members who had<br>
heard about the AFL-CIO campaign, 70 percent approved, 13 percent<br>
were neutral and only 15 percent had a negative reaction, the
Hart<br>
poll showed. Even among those who voted Republican, 33 percent
had<br>
a positive view of the AFL-CIO campaign.<br>
<br>
WINNING RESPECT -- Working families will get more respect in<br>
the next Congress, AFL-CIO President John Sweeney predicted after<br>
the election. &quot;Despite the fact that working men and women
and<br>
their unions were outspent by business 7 to 1, this election<br>
amounts to a sea change in Congress for working families. The
105th<br>
Congress will legislate under the spotlight of a working families<br>
agenda, not a business-driven Contract with America,&quot;
Sweeney said.<br>
But those business interests will still be there, &quot;and we'll
be<br>
there, watching out for working families and holding Democrats as<br>
well as Republicans accountable.&quot;<br>
<br>
REICH'S FAMILY LEAVE ACT -- Labor bids a reluctant farewell to<br>
Secretary of Labor Robert B. Reich, who is leaving the Cabinet to<br>
spend more time with his family. Reich has been a strong voice in<br>
government for workers and their unions.<br>
<br>
WIN AT BRIDGESTONE -- After two-and-a-half years of bitter<br>
struggle, the Steelworkers announced a tentative contract that<br>
meets all the demands of the union. Some details still need to be<br>
worked out, USWA President George Becker said, but the workers<br>
scored wins on the issues of wages, pensions, work rules, pattern<br>
bargaining and the return to work of all union workers. Becker<br>
credited the solidarity of the Bridgestone workers and support
from<br>
then labor movement for the win.<br>
<br>
UNION MOMENTUM IN MARYLAND -- With 40,000 state workers<br>
eligible for the benefits of union representation, mail ballots<br>
went out Nov. 8 to workers in three units petitioned by AFSCME. A<br>
unit of public safety and security officers, being organized<br>
jointly by AFSCME and the Teamsters, will get their ballots next<br>
week. AFSCME filed last week to represent a fifth unit, covering<br>
9,000 employees, and AFT is preparing to file petitions to<br>
represent workers in two other units. Workers are learning the<br>
importance of collective bargaining thorugh radio ads and direct<br>
mailings prepared by AFSCME. On Nov. 7, Baltimoreans United in<br>
Leadership Development/BUILD, a group of 50 churches, sponsored a<br>
rally to support the organizing effort.<br>
<br>
SCHOOL'S IN -- About 400 non-instructional employees at<br>
Montgomery (Md.) College said &quot;No more!&quot; to
second-class treatment<br>
and joined AFSCME's District Council 67.<br>
<br>
REORGANIZED COAST TO COAST -- AFL-CIO President John Sweeney<br>
has appointed new directors and deputy directors in a Department
of<br>
Field Mobilization streamlined from 12 to 4 regions. Directing
the<br>
West is Mark Splain, an Organizing Institute veteran, and the<br>
deputy director is Pat Lee, a founding member of the Asian
Pacific<br>
American Labor Alliance; Mary Fears Creighton moves from the New<br>
York region to direct the Midwest, assisted by Bruce Colburn,<br>
secretary-treasurer of the Milwaukee central labor council; Kirk<br>
Adams, international health care organizing coordinator for the<br>
Service Employees, will direct the South, and his deputy will be<br>
Ken Johnson, who has directed the Southern Labor Institute;<br>
directing the East will be Jose (Joe) Alvarez, who has been
UNITE's<br>
political director, and the deputy director will be Merrilee<br>
Milstein, now the Connecticut deputy secretary of state and
former<br>
political director of the state AFL-CIO. Directors for each state<br>
will be announced later.<br>
<br>
FOCUS ON GLOBAL ECONOMY -- The AFL-CIO Industrial Union<br>
Department convention voted to restructure to build &quot;a
strong<br>
global strategic action framework&quot; to help unions deal with<br>
transnational corporations that &quot;shop the world for the
lowest<br>
labor costs and the least restrictive health and safety,<br>
environmental and investment laws.&quot; Delegates elected Peter
diCicco<br>
president and Joe Uehlein secretary-treasurer.<br>
<br>
UAW GAINS SECURITY AT GM -- The UAW's new contract with<br>
General Motors will go to the membership for ratification Nov.
15,<br>
the union announced. The new deal, patterned after accords with
the<br>
other two Big Three automakers, guarantees that 95 percent of
GM's<br>
215,000 UAW workers will keep their jobs. GM had sought to cut as<br>
many as 70,000 jobs over the next three years. The contract also<br>
calls for pension increases and improved health care benefits.<br>
<br>
WORKERS KEEP SHIRTS -- Workers at the C.F. Hathaway shirt<br>
plant in Waterville, Maine, approved a three-year contract with
an<br>
investor group that agreed to buy the plant to avoid a threatened<br>
shutdown. The new contract initially freezes pay, reduces
holidays<br>
and requires workers to contribute toward health insurance while<br>
preserving severance benefits and guaranteeing production at the<br>
facility. Warnaco Group, the former owner announced last May that<br>
it planned to shut or sell the plant, threatening the jobs of 515<br>
UNITE workers.<br>
<br>
OTHER DETROIT DAILIES SETTLE -- Detroit newspaper workers<br>
reached tentative agreement with two Detroit suburban dailies --<br>
the Macomb Daily and the Daily Tribune in Royal Oak. The workers,<br>
who made wage and benefit concessions in 1993, will receive a 9<br>
percent raise over the next three years. &quot;I think it speaks
very<br>
loudly that the Council of Unions (which represents the newspaper<br>
workers), when it has a reasonable newspaper management to deal<br>
with, can negotiate a labor agreement without the strife and<br>
bitterness that we have seen with the downtown newspapers,&quot;
said<br>
Louis Mleczko, president of Newspaper Guild Local 22.<br>
<br>
MEANY CENTER CHIEF -- Susan Schurman has been named executive<br>
director of the George Meany Center for Labor Studies. She has<br>
directed the Labor Extension Programs at Rutgers University since<br>
1992 and is a two-term president of the University and College<br>
Labor Education Association. Schurman, who assumes the new post
in<br>
January, succeeds Bob Pleasure, now assistant to President
Sweeney<br>
for education.<br>
<br>
MECHANICS TO LINK WITH UAW -- The Mechanics Education Society<br>
of America announced it will merge with the UAW next year,<br>
effective Jan. 1. MESA represents about 3,000 skilled trades and<br>
production workers at manufacturing facilities in Ohio, Michigan<br>
and New York.<br>
<br>
JOINT FLYING EXERCISE -- The Canadian Air Line Pilots<br>
Association, meeting in convention Nov. 19-21, will consider a<br>
proposal to merge with its U.S. counterpart, a move already<br>
approved by the ALPA executive board. &quot;This merger will be
the<br>
first step toward ensuring that pilots of different nations will<br>
not be pitted against one another, and that the hard-fought-for<br>
standards of the piloting profession will not be eroded,&quot;
said ALPA<br>
President J. Randolph Babbitt.<br>
<br>
MAIL HANDLERS RE-ELECT OFFICERS -- The Mail Handlers re-<br>
elected President William Quinn and Secretary-Treasurer Mark<br>
Gardner to their second terms in mail balloting that concluded
Oct.<br>
28. The union, a division of the Laborers, represents 50,000<br>
workers at the U.S. Postal Service.<br>
<br>
SCAB WATCH -- The use of striker replacements would be an<br>
unfair labor practice in many cases in Canada under a proposal by<br>
Labor Minister Alfonso Gagliano. While not prohibiting their use<br>
during a legal strike or lockout, the amendments would prohibit<br>
their use as a way to undermine a union's representative
capacity,<br>
and would give strikers employment preference after resuming
work.<br>
Canadian unionists criticized the proposal for not including a<br>
general ban on the use of striker replacements.<br>
<br>
FREE PAKPAHAN -- A top-level delegation from the International<br>
Confederation of Free Trade Unions, led by Secretary-General Bill<br>
Jordan, visited Indonesia and demanded the release of jailed
labor<br>
leader Muchtar Pakpahan. Pakpahan, who heads Indonesia's free
trade<br>
union federation, SBSI, has been held in solitary confinement
since<br>
July 29 and is charged with subversion, a capital offense.
AFL-CIO<br>
Vice President Leon Lynch of the Steelworkers was a member of the<br>
delegation. Earlier this year, Pakpahan testified before the U.S.<br>
Congress about worker rights abuses in Indonesia. To find out how<br>
you can help, contact the International Affairs Department at
202-<br>
637-5050, FAX 202-637-5325.<br>
<br>
TRUCK STOP -- The AFL-CIO has joined with the Teamsters and<br>
other groups to run print and radio ads urging the U.S.
government<br>
to bar unsafe Mexican trucks from highways in California and
Texas.<br>
Republican governors have demanded that the trucks, which now
must<br>
unload within a narrow strip along the border, be permitted<br>
anywhere in their states, putting at risk the jobs and safety of<br>
their constituents. The ads note that the trucks are used only<br>
because drivers in Mexico are paid as little as $8 a day.<br>
<br>
TRADING RIGHTS FOR WRONGS -- Trade unionists will descend on<br>
Singapore early next month to push for including standards in<br>
upcoming trade agreements. The global effort at the first<br>
ministerial meeting of the World Trade Organization will include
a<br>
planning conference followed by the WTO meeting, where many<br>
unionists will serve as delegates. A draft agenda for the meeting<br>
ignores the issue of worker rights, which the Clinton<br>
administration has vowed to pursue.<br>
<br>
JOB INSECURITY -- Despite an expanding job market and<br>
declining unemployment, 4.2 million workers were displaced from<br>
jobs they held for more than three years between January 1993 and<br>
December 1995. That was down only slightly from the 1991-1993<br>
period surveyed by the Labor Department, which covered part of a<br>
recession and slow recovery. Workers, only 43 percent of whom<br>
received advance written notice, said most frequently that plant
or<br>
company closings or moves were responsible for their
displacement.<br>
<br>
HO HO HO! AN INTERESTING OFFER -- Many participants in Union<br>
Privilege's Union Credit Card Program will pay no interest on<br>
purchases made in November and December. The gift ends at the end<br>
of the year, with the regular interest rate charge assessed to<br>
those November and December purchases beginning in January. </p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../index.htm">Public Documents Page</a> | <a
href="../publsear.htm">Public Documents Search</a></p>
