<html>
<head>
<title>WIP 11/04/96 AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<p align="left"><img src="../images/wip.gif" align="bottom"
width="508" height="135"></p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<p align="left">AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS -- November 04, 1996</p>
<p>VOTE! YOUR LIFE MAY DEPEND ON IT -- Saying that Mine Workers
and<br>
their families face a &quot;life-or-death situation&quot; in the
face of<br>
congressional attacks on health and safety rules, union President<br>
Cecil Roberts called a memorial period covering all 75,000
members<br>
for Election Day, Nov. 5. Roberts, who has the right to call<br>
memorial days under UMWA contracts, urged members to use the day
to<br>
vote, and to make sure that as many other working people vote as<br>
possible for candidates who will &quot;protect their health,
safety and<br>
retirement security.&quot;<br>
<br>
KEY STRAWBERRY VICTORY -- In support of the AFL-CIO/Farm Workers<br>
Strawberry Campaign, Lenore Miller, president of the Retail,<br>
Wholesale and Department Store Union, convinced Key Foods<br>
Supermarkets in New York City to sign on to the pledge for<br>
strawberry workers' rights. Key Foods operates a chain of 148<br>
stores. Latest developments in the strawberry campaign are
included<br>
on Page 3.<br>
<br>
SETTLEMENT AT GM -- The UAW-GM council will meet Nov. 6 to review<br>
a tentative national contract before sending it to members for<br>
ratification. No details were released, but UAW President Stephen<br>
P. Yokich said the union worked hard to craft an agreement that<br>
would fit all of the Big Three automakers and &quot;that's
exactly what<br>
we have now accomplished.&quot; While there is a national
agreement,<br>
local disputes continue. Workers at an Indianapolis metal
stamping<br>
plant ended a five-day local strike that had crippled production
of<br>
GM pickups and sport utility vehicles. A walkout continued at a<br>
Jaynesville, Wis., plant.<br>
<br>
RAIL UNIONS UNITED -- Rail labor will unite to jointly analyze<br>
competing Conrail merger proposals and take a collective position<br>
on any sale or merger of the company, AFL-CIO President John<br>
Sweeney announced after a meeting of the unions and the<br>
federation's Transportation Trades Department. The unions also<br>
established firm unity ground rules that rail unions will meet<br>
collectively only as a unified group under the TTD. The unions<br>
involved are the Train Dispatchers, Maintenance of Way<br>
Employes,Railway Signalmen, Machinists, Boilermakers, Electrical<br>
Workers, Firemen and Oilers Conference of SEIU, Sheet Metal<br>
Workers, Transportation Communications Union, Transport Workers
and<br>
United Transportation Union.<br>
<br>
HERE WINS AIRPORT VOTE -- Stuck in a rut for 18 years, Hotel<br>
Employees and Restaurant Employees Local 355 got results by<br>
switching 40 percent of its budget to organizing. Workers at<br>
Rexall's food and beverage operation in Miami Airport voted 78-42<br>
for union representation. &quot;This is just the beginning. We
are<br>
spending three days doing rep work and devoting two days to<br>
organizing workers,&quot; said Secretary-Treasurer Andy Balash.<br>
<br>
HOOSIERS TAKE ON FEDEX -- Across the country, FedEx employees are<br>
fired up over Congress' &quot;midnight special&quot; favor to
FedEx that<br>
helps the company avoid organizing. Hundreds of FedEx workers
from<br>
throughout the Midwest converged on Indianapolis Nov. 3 in
support<br>
of their brothers and sisters seeking Teamsters recognition at
the<br>
carrier's facilities there and in Muncie and Columbus, Ind.
&quot;FedEx<br>
workers built their company and are proud of what they've
built,&quot;<br>
the union said. The IBT represents 200,000 workers at UPS,
Airborne<br>
and other FedEx competitors.<br>
<br>
PUTTING ON A NEW KOAT -- NABET-CWA members at KOAT-TV in<br>
Albuquerque, N.M., have a first contract after bargaining for
more<br>
than a year. Local 407 garnered community support via news<br>
conferences, picketing and letters to advertisers, a strategy<br>
NABET-CWA locals also have used in Buffalo, San Diego and Detroit
-<br>
- and banner-toting airplane flyovers.<br>
<br>
GETTING OUT THE MESSAGE -- Election volunteers across the country<br>
are making the final push to turn out informed worker/voters on<br>
Nov. 5, working the phones and plant gates and going door to
door.<br>
AFL-CIO President John Sweeney and 10,000 working families
rallied<br>
with Vice President Gore and Democratic Sens. John Kerry and
Edward<br>
M. Kennedy in a pre-election gathering in Boston Nov. 1. The
rally<br>
came in the midst of a whirlwind of activity by Sweeney,
Secretary-<br>
Treasurer Richard L. Trumka and Executive Vice President Linda<br>
Chavez-Thompson, as the three criss-crossed the country in the<br>
final days before the election reaching out to working Americans.<br>
Sweeney toured Maine, New Hampshire, Massachusetts and Rhode
Island<br>
and rode a bus through four Ohio cities before traveling back to<br>
Massachusetts, where he attended rallies in four cities. In just<br>
two days, Nov. 1-2, Trumka spoke to seven rallies: in Pittsburgh;<br>
Philadelphia; Long Island, N.Y.; three in New Jersey; and<br>
Gillespie, Ill. Chavez-Thompson spent the weekend stumping
through<br>
Texas.<br>
<br>
NORTHWEST RAISE UP IN AIR -- Arbitration has begun to determine<br>
whether Air Line Pilots at Northwest Airlines will get a full
&quot;wage<br>
snap-up.&quot; Under the 1993 ALPA contract, pilots are entitled
to a<br>
snap-up determined by averaging wage increases at four other<br>
airlines at the time concessions were made years ago. Management<br>
says the amount should be less than the 3 percent sought by the<br>
union.<br>
<br>
KENNECOTT UNIONS MINE RAISE -- Members of six unions ratified a
new<br>
six-year contract with Kennecott's Utah copper mining facilities<br>
that raise wages by an average of $2.90 an hour, 50 cents the
first<br>
five years and 40 cents in the last. Pension benefits and
sickness<br>
and accident benefits also were increased. The 1,800 workers are<br>
represented by the Steelworkers, Machinists, Operating Engineers,<br>
United Transportation Union, Office and Professional employees
and<br>
Electrical Workers.<br>
<br>
UNION BEATS GREED -- Members of Teamsters Local 528 voted 300-40
in<br>
favor of a new contract with Atlanta Gas &amp; Light, ending a
five-day<br>
strike. AG&amp;L made more than $77 million in profits during the
fist<br>
nine months of this year, but provoked a strike by demanding that<br>
workers agree to contracting out their jobs, a wage freeze and an<br>
increase in co-payments for health insurance.<br>
<br>
ROCKIN' FOR DETROIT NEWSPAPER WORKERS -- British rock musician<br>
Billy Bragg brought his social conscience and music to Detroit in<br>
a benefit concert for striking newspaper workers. The benefit<br>
netted $5,100 for the strikers.<br>
<br>
STRIDES IN JANITORS' STRIKE -- As the Washington Justice for<br>
Janitors' strike entered its sixth week, more than 1 million
square<br>
feet of office space cleaned by P&amp;R Enterprises in three
different<br>
buildings was put out to bid. The janitors also started a
&quot;Rit<br>
Thompson Watch&quot; asking the public to contact Justice for
Janitors<br>
if they spot Thompson, who is president of P&amp;R, so he can
respond<br>
to his workers' concerns.<br>
<br>
STILL GETTING THE SHAFTA -- The number of U.S. workers certified<br>
for assistance after losing their jobs under the North American<br>
Free Trade Agreement jumped 40 percent in the last year to nearly<br>
90,000, according to the U.S. Labor Department. But, some
analysts<br>
think the true figure of those displaced may be five times that.<br>
Robert E. Scott, a researcher at the University of Maryland,<br>
estimates that between 392,000 and 484,000 jobs have been lost
due<br>
to NAFTA. The Labor Department says that eligibility for income<br>
support while in training will increase, thanks to the recent<br>
settlement of a suit brought by the UAW.<br>
<br>
FED UP -- In a letter to the Federal Reserve Board, AFL-CIO<br>
Secretary-Treasurer Richard L. Trumka assailed the reduced time
and<br>
information available for those who to want to comment on
proposed<br>
bank mergers and acquisitions. Particularly hard hit would be<br>
minority, low- and moderate-income communities, who need the
two-or<br>
three-month period now available to learn about and respond to<br>
merger proposals. The Fed wants that period shortened to 15 days.<br>
&quot;Given the rapid and soon-to-accelerate rate of banking
industry<br>
consolidation, more information about bank mergers and
acquisitions<br>
and more careful scrutiny of their impact on the public prior to<br>
approval is needed, not less,&quot; Trumka said.<br>
<br>
JOBLESS RATE HOLDS STEADY -- The nation's unemployment rate<br>
remained steady in October at 5.2 percent. Payroll employment
rose<br>
by 210,000, with the largest gains in services and retail trade,<br>
while manufacturing was unchanged. When marginally attached
workers<br>
and those working part time involuntarily were added in, the rate<br>
was 8.8 percent, down from 9 percent in September.<br>
<br>
VIOLENCE COMMENTS SOUGHT -- OSHA again has extended the deadline<br>
for comments on its draft &quot;Guidelines for Workplace Violence<br>
Prevention Programs for Night Retail Establishments,&quot; with
comments<br>
now due by Dec. 4. The draft addresses exchange of money, working<br>
alone or in small numbers, late at night or early in the morning,<br>
in high-crime areas, as a guard or in community settings.
Comments<br>
may be sent to Patricia D. Biles, Workplace Violence Program<br>
Coordinator, Department of Labor/OSHA, 200 Constitution Ave.
N.W.,<br>
Room N3107, Washington, D.C. 20210.<br>
<br>
SILICOSIS TARGETED -- The Labor Department's announcement of an<br>
initiative to prevent silicosis comes as welcome news to the more<br>
than 1 million workers exposed annually to silica dust. Free<br>
materials on the education campaign &quot;If It's Silica, It's
Not Just<br>
Dust&quot; are available by calling 1/800-35-NIOSH. DoL
inspectors also<br>
will distribute such material on silicosis, a lung disease which<br>
kills 250 American workers annually.<br>
<br>
CHAMPION . . . NOT -- A federal appeals court reversed an NLRB<br>
decision that labor law was violated when a supervisor told
workers<br>
in the midst of an organizing campaign, &quot;I hope you guys are
ready<br>
to pack up and move to Mexico.&quot; The U.S. Court of Appeals
for the<br>
7th Circuit ruled that &quot;off-handed&quot; remarks were not
coercive or<br>
threatening, while conceding that the comments came &quot;close
to the<br>
edge&quot; of running afoul of the National Labor Relations Act.
The UAW<br>
filed the complaint against Champion Laboratories Inc.<br>
<br>
NO HOLIDAY IN MEXICO -- The Labor Department will hold a hearing<br>
Dec. 3 to air charges that Mexican federal workers are being<br>
prevented from organizing an independent union. Labor and human<br>
rights groups say the Mexican government eliminated the
government<br>
trade union for employees of the Fishing Ministry and prevented
it<br>
from registering again. DoL's National Administrative Office is
to<br>
issue a report that will recommend whether ministerial<br>
consultations, a prescribed &quot;remedy&quot; under NAFTA, are
warranted.<br>
<br>
CAPITALIST TOOLS -- McDonnell Douglas Corp. is being scrutinized
by<br>
a federal grand jury for allegations that it sold high-tech
machine<br>
tools to China's military in exchange for orders for its Chinese-<br>
built MD-80 and MD-90 jetliners. While the U.S. manufacturer has<br>
been building the planes in China for more than a decade, it was<br>
warned three years ago that failure to deliver the equipment
would<br>
&quot;have a big influence on the program and long-term
cooperation.&quot;<br>
Both McDonnell Douglas and Boeing have been sharply criticized by<br>
unionists for trading away U.S. technology and U.S. jobs in<br>
exchange for market share.</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../index.htm">Public Documents Page</a> | <a
href="../publsear.htm">Public Documents Search</a></p>
