<html>
<head>
<title>WIP 10/29/96 AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<p align="left"><img src="../images/wip.gif" align="bottom"
width="508" height="135"></p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<p>AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS -- October 29, 1996</p>
<p>IT'D BE FUNNY IF . . . Rep. Steve Stockman (R-Texas), in his<br>
continued bumbling war against AFL-CIO advertising, took the
stand<br>
yesterday in a hearing for a preliminary injunction. He admitted<br>
under cross-examination that he did not read Congressional Budget<br>
Office reports, did not know the name of the director, and
refuses<br>
to read the New York Times or the Washington Post. He was seeking<br>
an injunction to stop ads that hadn't run in his district in<br>
months. His two witnesses about the harm he'd been caused
included<br>
one who admitted he'd never seen the ads prior to court and one
who<br>
didn't live in his district. The judge denied his motion.<br>
<br>
UAW, GM TALKING FOR NOW -- Talks between the UAW and GM resumed<br>
Oct. 29, two days after a strike deadline had passed. President<br>
Stephen P. Yokich said the union had no immediate plans for a<br>
strike, but he left open the possibility that some locals could<br>
call strikes at individual plants. UAW-GM locals with no local<br>
agreements are free to call walkouts. Last week, the Canadian
Auto<br>
Workers approved a new three-year contract with GM after a 21-day<br>
strike caused the layoff of nearly 20,000 U.S. and Mexican
workers.<br>
<br>
DOCS STEP UP FOR UNION -- Associations representing most of the<br>
nation's podiatrists have formed the first nationwide labor union<br>
for doctors. The First National Guild for Health Care Providers
of<br>
the Lower Extremities will become part of the Office and<br>
Professional Employees, and expects at least 10,000 of the
nation's<br>
14,000 podiatrists to join. The union wants to give podiatrists
and<br>
other doctors more power in dealing with managed-care<br>
organizations.<br>
<br>
NURSES NOT FOOLED -- Genesis Health Systems wanted to bust<br>
Teamsters Local 332 by merging Flint Osteopathic Hospital with<br>
nonunion hospitals. What they didn't count on was the
determination<br>
of the nurses to keep union protections. Registered nurses at the<br>
merged facility voted 406-249 for the IBT.<br>
<br>
BE FAIR WITH CARE -- AFL-CIO President John Sweeney will join<br>
hundreds of workers today in a rally for a fair contract at the<br>
Rhode Island Hospital in Providence. The 1,900 workers,
represented<br>
by the Teamsters, have been working without a contract since
Sept.<br>
30, and are fighting management's efforts to eliminate job
security<br>
provisions. They rejected the most recent contract offer by 97<br>
percent.<br>
<br>
BRIDGESTONE EXPOSED -- The Steelworkers released a hard-hitting<br>
expose of corporate renegade Bridgestone/Firestone and pledged to<br>
continued fighting until workers win a fair contract.
&quot;Running Over<br>
the American Dream: A Case Study in Corporate Greed and<br>
Irresponsibility,&quot; will be printed in four languages and<br>
distributed in countries where Bridgestone does business. USWA<br>
President George Becker also announced that three Saturn dealers
--<br>
two in Ohio and one in Iowa -- have joined the union's
&quot;Don't Buy&quot;<br>
campaign against Bridgestone.<br>
<br>
NO BLUE RIBBON FOR PABST -- After 152 years, Pabst is moving its<br>
brewery out of Milwaukee, leaving 250 workers without jobs a week<br>
before Christmas and betraying the trust of employees and the
city.<br>
Effective Dec. 17, the company is shifting its production to a<br>
plant in La Crosse, Wis., owned by Stroh's. The workers, members
of<br>
the UAW's Brewery Workers Local 9, have launched a national<br>
campaign against the company.<br>
<br>
WHAT A DIFFERENCE A CONTRACT MAKES -- The Farm Workers signed a
new<br>
contract with Monterey Mushroom Co. that gives workers pay<br>
increases from 20 to 35 percent over the next five years. During<br>
the Oct. 28 contract signing, UFW President Arturo Rodriguez also<br>
presented union pension checks -- one for $16,732 -- to four<br>
retired farm workers and the widow of a fifth who didn't know
they<br>
were eligible for retirement benefits.<br>
<br>
ON THE ROAD -- Many international union presidents have joined
the<br>
AFL-CIO's John Sweeney, Rich Trumka and Linda Chavez-Thompson on<br>
the hustings as the Nov. 5 Election Day looms nearer. Among the<br>
activists urging union members to vote for candidates who stand<br>
with working families are Presidents George Becker of the<br>
Steelworkers, Gerald McEntee of AFSCME and John Sturdivant of
AFGE,<br>
who on Thursday join Sweeney in Ohio for a GOTV bus tour. Andy<br>
Stern of the Service Employees joins Sweeney Friday in<br>
Massachusetts. Electronic Workers President Bill Bywater last
week<br>
was with Trumka in Evansville, Ind., where 600 union members
rocked<br>
the city's coliseum with a pre-election rally. Machinists
President<br>
George Kourpias has been out all month traveling from work site
to<br>
work site, urging union members to vote. Becker has been
tireless,<br>
with forays into Minnesota, Alabama, Ohio, New York and<br>
Pennsylvania.<br>
<br>
LIVING BETTER WITH LESS CHEMISTRY -- The government issued a rule<br>
negotiated with labor to limit exposure to 1,3-butadiene, a<br>
flammable, carcinogenic chemical used in making synthetic rubber.<br>
The regulation, signed at a union hall in Akron, Ohio, by OSHA<br>
Administrator Joe Dear, substantially reduces permissible
exposures<br>
and provides for employee training, exposure monitoring, hazard<br>
communication, medical surveillance and recordkeeping. The<br>
Occupational Safety and Health Administration predicts that the<br>
rule, which affects nearly 10,000 workers, will prevent about 79<br>
deaths over a 45-year working lifetime.<br>
<br>
NO JUSTICE NO PEACE -- Janitors in Washington continued their<br>
weekly protests at National Airport Oct. 23 as they entered their<br>
fifth week of strikes. More than 250 union and nonunion janitors<br>
who clean National Airport are holding firm despite threats and<br>
harassment from PRIEM Building Services. Contracts covering 1,700<br>
union janitors in the city expired Sept. 30.<br>
<br>
LIUNA REFORM APPROVED -- A federal appeals court upheld the<br>
Laborers' internal reform program, throwing out a challenge by
two<br>
suspended union vice presidents. The U.S. Court of Appeals for
the<br>
7th Circuit said the LIUNA board &quot;used powers bestowed upon
them by<br>
the members' own votes&quot; to enact the new ethical practices
code.<br>
<br>
GOOD NEWS ON THE PACIFIC RIM -- South Korea will only be admitted<br>
into the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development if<br>
it brings its labor laws into conformance with international<br>
standards. The condition was added after an AFL-CIO petition<br>
convinced the White House to reverse its earlier support for the<br>
fast-developing Asian country's entry into the world body without<br>
such a requirement. Korea's labor laws are a legacy of its
earlier<br>
military government, and have been used to restrict the
collective<br>
bargaining process and intimidate thousands of union members and<br>
leaders.<br>
<br>
STOP AT THE BORDER -- The Teamsters moved ahead with its lawsuit<br>
challenging trucking provisions of the North American Free Trade<br>
Agreement. In a new brief filed in federal court, the union<br>
attacked proposed federal rules to certify Mexican carriers as
safe<br>
for U.S. highways, pointing to General Accounting Office warnings<br>
of significant safety problems. Nearly half of the trucks
inspected<br>
between Dec. 18 and April 5 have been taken out of service. Under<br>
the proposed rules, the application form for certification would<br>
require no proof that safety requirements have been met,
including<br>
those governing the transport of hazardous materials.<br>
<br>
COMPETITION CUTS BOTH WAYS -- A report by the Council on<br>
Competitiveness concludes that the United States over the past<br>
decade has outperformed other advanced industrial economies in<br>
several key measures of competitiveness. But the glass is clearly<br>
half empty. While the U.S. position has improved in global market<br>
share, per capita domestic production, growth in industrial
output,<br>
budget deficit reduction and employment, the council found the<br>
United States slipping in wage stagnation and inequality,
national<br>
saving rate, investment in plant and equipment, R&amp;D outlays
and<br>
education.<br>
<br>
INSENSITIVITY TRAINING -- Giving a new twist to job training, the<br>
New Jersey Business and Industry Association sponsored a seminar<br>
called &quot;Dismissing Employees&quot; to help bosses
&quot;satisfy all legal<br>
requirements in a termination, whether it is a single dismissal
or<br>
a larger layoff.&quot; In response, the state's Industrial Union
Council<br>
last week joined unemployed workers in a press conference held at<br>
the seminar site, and presented BIA with a big pink slip saying,<br>
&quot;Stop the Layoffs!&quot; IUC Secretary-Treasurer Lois
Cuccinello called<br>
for passage of a law that would provide income to affected<br>
employees and communities affected by downsizing, while
penalizing<br>
corporate do-badders.<br>
<br>
SWEATSHOPS ON THE RUN -- Labor Secretary Robert B. Reich last
week<br>
added the &quot;power of the pulpit&quot; in his campaign to
eradicate<br>
sweatshops. Representatives from a broad spectrum of organized<br>
religions pledged to carry the anti-sweatshop message to their<br>
congregations. The national campaign is working: A DoL report
shows<br>
that child labor was down significantly in several Central
American<br>
countries and that many manufacturers for American industry have<br>
developed codes of conduct which ban child labor.<br>
<br>
UNIONS GET LABOR MANAGEMENT FUNDS -- The Machinists, Teamsters
and<br>
Roofers will receive $100,000 each as part of a $1.5 million<br>
federal grant to create labor-management committees or to expand<br>
existing cooperative workplace efforts under grants from the<br>
Federal Mediation and Conciliation Service. Municipal governments<br>
and their public-sector unions, including AFT, the Graphics<br>
Communications Union, the Boilermakers and UNITE, were awarded<br>
funds ranging between $54,000 and $75,000 to develop performance<br>
systems or expand employee involvement committees.<br>
<br>
CYBER JOB SEARCHING -- The Labor Department last week launched a<br>
new Internet web site that provides federal employees who face<br>
downsizing with on-line search and career transition services.
The<br>
exit off the information superhighway is<br>
http://safetynet.doleta.gov.<br>
<br>
QUAN IS UNITE VP -- Katie Quan was elected a vice president of<br>
UNITE, making her the first Asian-American elected to a top<br>
leadership position with the union. Quan has been manager of the<br>
Pacific Northwest District Council of UNITE.<br>
<br>
MARITIME LEADER DEAD -- Seafarers Vice President Joseph Sacco
died<br>
Oct. 19 after a heart attack. He was 58. Sacco, a member of the
the<br>
executive board of the AFL-CIO Maritime Trades Department,<br>
supervised and directed organizational and operational activities<br>
in ports nationwide, coordinated contractual negotiations and<br>
supervised the union's political activities. In lieu of flowers,<br>
the family asked that contributions be made to the Joseph Sacco<br>
Scholarship Fund, Tom DeVivio, trustee, 5201 Auth Way, Camp<br>
Springs, Md. 20746.<br>
<br>
LABOR NEWS PIONEER DIES -- Henry Fleisher, the first director of<br>
publications of the AFL-CIO and a public relations consultant for<br>
unions and nonprofit associations for many years, died Oct. 25 of<br>
pneumonia in Washington, D.C. He was 83. Fleisher was the
assistant<br>
editor of CIO News and director of publicity for the CIO before<br>
being named to head publications for the merged AFL-CIO in 1955.</p>
