width="508" height="135"></p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<p>AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS -- October 21, 1996</p>
<pre>ENDGAME -- With just two weeks left, tens of thousands of union
activists are mobilizing across the country to make sure union
members make the difference on Election Day. The Machinists are
working through 23,000 in-plant union representatives. The Service
Employees have signed up 7,000 leaders and members to take part in
at least five political action activities. Hundreds of AFL-CIO and
union staff are in targeted congressional districts to spread the
word on how candidates stand on the issues and to urge union
members to vote.

     YELLING ALL THE WAY TO THE BANK -- While Republicans are
howling about union political activities, a new report by the
Center for Responsive Politics shows that business groups have
contributed $242 million to candidates this political season,
mostly to Republicans. That's &quot;nearly seven times the $35 million
given by labor groups and more than $10.6 million given by such
ideological or single-issue groups as the National Rifle
Association, which opposes gun control,&quot; the Washington Post
reported.

     GOING TO WORKERS -- Activists in Washington state will be
spending their lunch hour Wednesday at plant gates all across the
state, distributing hundreds of thousands of leaflets urging union
members to vote. They will be trying to reverse the 1992 election
result that sent six anti-worker legislators to Congress.

     THE SUNSHINE STATE -- AFL-CIO Secretary-Treasurer Rich Trumka
and Robert A. Georgine, president of the Building and Construction
Trades Department, helped celebrate the Jacksonville United Labor
Alliance's get-out-the-vote campaign Oct. 18. Florida is a key
state in this year's critical election, Trumka told an audience of
more than 500 people.

     WHAT'S AT STAKE? -- The AFL-CIO Transportation Trade
Department is distributing a rank-and-file union member voter guide
entitled &quot;What's at Stake for Transportation Workers in the Race
for President?&quot; Contact TTD at 202/628-9262.

     FIGHTING FOR SOCIAL SECURITY -- Trumka pledged an all-out
fight in the next Congress to prevent the Wall Street-backed plan
to privatize Social Security. While the system &quot;requires some
thoughtful, timely adjustments, which we'll support, we will not
support any sort of tampering with or undermining of the current
system,&quot; said Trumka, who joined consumer and seniors' advocates
Oct. 17 in a news conference to release a new expose in Mother
Jones magazine.

     LESS IS MORRELL -- Hundreds of John Morrell &amp; Co. retirees
were joined by their union, the Food and Commercial Workers, and
Rep. Tim Johnson (D-S.D.) at a press conference last Thursday to
focus attention on their continued fight to regain their company
health insurance. The union took the case to the Supreme Court, but
the court refused to hear it. The workers now depend on Medicare.
In another case, on Sept. 27, a federal judge ruled that Pabst
Brewing Co. could cancel health benefits for its retired workers.
Johnson, who is running against incumbent Republican Sen. Larry
Pressler, announced his support for the workers' cause.

     IFPTE ENGINEERS TWO WINS -- About 150 employees in the
Pittsburgh District Office of the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers
voted two-to-one for representation with the Professional and
Technical Engineers. Meanwhile, across the state, 1,240 employees
at the Naval Surface Warfare Center voted overwhelmingly for IFPTE
representation.

     WAVING THE BLACK FLAG -- The Steelworkers will release a
report Oct. 22 at AFL-CIO headquarters that will point the finger
at Bridgestone/Firestone as a flagrant corporate lawbreaker.
&quot;Running Over the American Dream: A Case Study in Corporate Greed
and Irresponsibility&quot; describes the way the company abuses its
workers, the environment and workplace safety standards while
ducking civic responsibility in the communities that host its
plants. Press conferences are scheduled Oct. 22 in Akron, Ohio;
Bloomington, Ill.; Decatur, Ill.; Des Moines, Iowa; Kings
Mt./Gastonia, N.C.; Nashville, Tenn.; Noblesville, Ind.; Oklahoma
City; Prescott, Ark.; and Russellville, Ark.  GETTING DOWN TO
BUSINESS -- AFL-CIO President John Sweeney is taking workers'
messages directly to business groups this week. He's in New York
Monday to meet with the U.S. Council for International Business,
and returns to the city Friday to speak with Business for Social
Responsibility. On Wednesday, he's in Arizona for a Work-in-America
Roundtable and, on Thursday, he's in Chicago for the Common Ground
Project. Secretary-Treasurer Rich Trumka and Executive Vice
President Linda Chavez-Thompson will join Sweeney on the road for
GOTV from Texas to Indiana, Minnesota and Montana. 

     

     JOBS AT STAKE -- Three union leaders warned that thousands of
American high-tech jobs will be lost if the Federal Communications
Commission doesn't soon adopt national standards for high-
definition television. In a letter to Vice President Gore,
Presidents John Barry of the Electrical Workers, Morton Bahr of the
Communications Workers and  Bill Bywater of the Electronic Workers
urged adoption of standards agreed to by the Grand Alliance -- the
group of computer industry manufacturers and consumer electronic
broadcasters. Two members of that group, Thompson and Philips, have
pledged to manufacture HDTV receivers in the United States if the
FCC sets a transmission standard.

     HARBORING OMNIOUS THOUGHTS -- Omni Inner Harbor Hotel in
Baltimore was slapped with a formal complaint and hearing by the
National Labor Relations Board after the luxury facility refused to
recognize Hotel Employees and Restaurant Employees Local 7, which
has represented its workers for more than 20 years. The complaint
itemizes such union-busting activities as offers of money and other
incentives to get workers to decertify the union, threats and
unilateral changes to wages and benefits. Contract negotiations
broke down more than a year ago.

     LOOKING UP DOWN ON THE LINE -- UAW members voted by a 73
percent margin to approve a new three-year pact with Chrysler Corp.
that adds job security provisions and raises wages. The contract,
which is similar to one reached with Ford Motor Co., improves
pension benefits and provides for a $2,000 lump sum payment in the
first year followed by two annual 3 percent raises. Combined with
other features, economic gains could total $13,900 for a typical
worker, the union said. Talks with General Motors are ongoing.

     HANDS ACROSS THE WATER -- Canadian Auto Workers were joined on
the picket line by Detroit newspaper strikers, who crossed the
Detroit River in a show of international solidarity. Two dozen
newspaper strikers showed up at General Motors' Delphi plant, which
has cut its union work force from 2,600 to 1,000. Labor and
management at GM have set noon today as a deadline for reaching an
agreement. &quot;We are facing the same anti-union aggression from our
employers,&quot; said Louis Mleczko, president of The Newspaper Guild
Local 22, one of six unions on strike against the Detroit News and
Detroit Free Press since July 13, 1995. GM and CAW have set an Oct.
21 deadline to settle that strike.

     BEVERLY CHALLENGE -- AFL-CIO President John Sweeney helped
open three days of public demonstrations by Beverly nursing home
workers in Harrisburg, Pa., last week, urging good-faith bargaining
by the company. Beverly employees in 18 facilities have been
working without a contract since Dec. 1, 1995, and workers at two
facilities have been working without a contract since Dec. 31,
1994. Service Employees President Andy Stern and Mine Workers
President Cecil Roberts also participated in the rally.

     STOP PICKING ON WORKERS! -- The Strawberry Campaign is
targeting 25 cities, including the largest strawberry markets, to
heighten consumer awareness of the plight of strawberry workers.
Targeted cities include Atlanta, Baltimore, Seattle, Wichita, San
Diego and New York. To build public support for the workers, the
campaign will seek backing from supermarket managers and consumers,
as well as allies, including environmental, consumer, Latino and
religious groups.

     TAKING A BITE OUT OF APPLE -- A federal judge in Brooklyn,
N.Y., is allowing to let stand a lawsuit filed by a worker at Yale
University who says severe pain in her right hand, wrist and elbow
resulted from her on-the-job use of computer keyboards and a mouse.
The court rejected arguments by Apple Computers that the statute of
limitations should date from the first time Marice Dorsey touched
a keyboard. Judge Jack Weinstein ruled instead that the clock
starts running when the injury first becomes evident.

     NEW PACT AT FOAMEX -- UNITE workers at the Foamex plant in
Cornelius, N.C., ratified a new three-year contract that includes
a wage increase, increases in pension and insurance benefits and
improved language on overtime and job-bidding policies. The
facility employs 140 workers who manufacture foam for the auto,
furniture and carpet industries.

     UNLUCKY GUESS? -- UNITE members are asking Guess? to sign a
union contract that ensures decent wages and benefits for all
workers in its contracting shops. The members staged demonstrations
outside 30 high-volume Guess? boutiques around the nation to
protest the use of sweatshops by the company.

     EDUCATION FOR A LIFETIME -- The Steelworkers' Career
Development Program at Inland Steel in East Chicago, Ill. will
receive the 1996 Knowles Award for Outstanding  Adult Education
during the meeting of the American Association for Adult and
Continuing Education.

     FUN WITH NUMBERS -- Two educational programs are available to
explain the economy's increasing inequality. &quot;The Growing Divide:
Inequality and the Roots of Economic Insecurity&quot; is a workshop that
has used group discussion, experiential exercises, flip charts and
a comprehensive information packet to inform over 15,000
participants in 450 training sessions. &quot;Art for a Fair Economy&quot;
incorporates street theater, dance performances and graphic arts to
make economic data accessible, and can lead into the workshop. For
information, contact United for a Fair Economy, phone 617/423-2148.

     SING OUT FOR VOTES -- The Labor Heritage Foundation is
offering lyrics to four get-out-the-vote songs, sung to the
melodies of old standards. To get copies of the lyric sheet FAXed
to you, call Rocky Delaplaine at 202/842-7879.

     @END RULE =

     For details of these and other stories, check out the News and
Views library on LaborNET (CompuServe), or the AFL-CIO web page at
http:\\www.aflcio.org. To receive Work in Progress, or to submit
information, FAX to 202/508-6908.</pre>
