<title>WIP 10/14/96 AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<p align="left"><img src="../images/wip.gif" align="bottom"
width="508" height="135"></p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<p>WORK IN PROGRESS -- October 14, 1996</p>
<p>CURTAINS FOR HARASSMENT -- It worked in Everett, Mass. It can
work<br>
other places too. Richmark International, a curtain maker in the<br>
Boston area, fired and harassed workers trying to improve their<br>
lives by forming a union. On Oct. 8, AFL-CIO President John
Sweeney<br>
rallied employees outside Richmark's plant while community
leaders<br>
were getting arrested inside. Less than a week later, Richmark<br>
changed its attitude. The company recognized the workers' union,<br>
UNITE!, and is reinstating fired workers with back pay.<br>
<br>
WOMEN RALLY FOR VOTE -- Working Women Vote '96 continues its<br>
campaign now through Election Day, Nov. 5. On tap this week are a<br>
rally at Cleveland's Old Arcade on Oct. 18, with an address by<br>
President Sweeney. Women in Wichita, Kan., go on a two-day bus
tour<br>
through nine cities of the 4th congressional district Oct. 19-20<br>
under the banner &quot;Make them listen . . . Vote.&quot; Other
actions are<br>
planned for Fort Worth, Texas, (contact Stormy Moore,
817/246-2444)<br>
and San Jose, Calif. (contact Cyndy Chavez, 408/266-3790).<br>
<br>
COMING TO A CITY NEAR YOU -- Sweeney, Secretary-Treasurer Rich<br>
Trumka and Executive Vice President Linda Chavez-Thompson have<br>
begun a three-week dash crisscrossing the country to mobilize
union<br>
members to vote. Sweeney's tour this week includes Seattle and<br>
Spokane, Wash.; Harrisburg, Pa.; Cleveland; and Superior and<br>
Kenosha, Wis. Trumka will visit Waterbury and Groton, Conn.
Chavez-<br>
Thompson begins her trek next week in Texas, Colorado and
Montana.<br>
<br>
MARCHING FOR JUSTICE -- Union members took their places beside<br>
their brothers and sisters in two marches in Washington this<br>
weekend. Chavez-Thompson and Electronic Workers President Bill<br>
Bywater addressed hundreds of thousands of Latinos who marched
Oct.<br>
12 for worker and immigrant rights, affirmative action and a<br>
livable wage. Later that evening, unions supported AIDS research<br>
during the 1996 NAMES Project AIDS Memorial with an exhibit booth<br>
and reception, and marched with candles under the banner,
&quot;Labor<br>
Cares.&quot;<br>
<br>
ORGANIZING BUILDING TRADES -- The building trades will take on<br>
a multicraft, marketwide organizing campaign, involving all 15<br>
building trade unions. &quot;With determination, we will organize
our<br>
target, whatever it is, in two years,&quot; said Robert Georgine,<br>
president of the AFL-CIO's Building and Construction Trades<br>
Department. The campaign will be based on worker-to-worker<br>
organizing and will target an entire market, which will be<br>
announced later.<br>
<br>
SI, SI SINDICATO -- SEIU gained nearly 3,000 members with the<br>
affiliation in Puerto Rico of the Sindicato Puertorriqueno de<br>
Trabajadores (SPT). The new members are health care and education<br>
workers. SEIU President Andy Stern and executive vice president<br>
Eliseo Medina were on hand to participate in the official<br>
affiliation signing ceremony.<br>
<br>
HOST UNION HERE -- Workers for the Host Marriott food service<br>
cafeterias and bars at the airport in Hartford, Conn., airport<br>
voted 40-27 for representation by Hotel Employees and Restaurant<br>
Employees Local 217. The organizing drive follows a successful<br>
organizing drive by Marriott workers at Hartford's Trinity
College.<br>
<br>
DANIA UNITES ALL THE WAY -- Licensed practical nurses at Dania<br>
Nursing Home in Miami voted unanimously to become UNITE members,<br>
joining the certified nursing assistants, housekeeping, dietary
and<br>
laundry workers who had voted for the union in August. &quot;This<br>
victory shows the company that everyone at Dania Nursing Home
means<br>
business in their struggle for justice. Everyone is together now
as<br>
they look forward to a good contract,&quot; said organizer John<br>
Belizaire.<br>
<br>
BORDERS BOOKS UNION -- The employees of Borders Books &amp; Music<br>
store in Chicago voted 28-17 for representation by the Food and<br>
Commercial Workers. The win is credited to the workers' refusal
to<br>
yield to the company's anti-union pressure.<br>
<br>
JUST THE FACTS -- Leaflets for union members comparing the<br>
records of candidates on working family issues are available for
95<br>
congressional races, seven senate battles and one gubernatorial<br>
race. If you are interested in getting the word out to your union<br>
brothers and sisters, call your state federation to see whether<br>
leaflets are available for races in your area. <br>
<br>
UNION GROWTH HORMONE -- Keeping their promise to organize as<br>
neverof candidates on working family issues are available for 95<br>
before, the Service Employees' Central States Conference reports<br>
that theycongressional races, seven senate battles and one<br>
gubernatorial have gained 5,376 workers this year. Local 880, the<br>
Illinoisrace. If you are interested in getting the word out to
your<br>
union homecare organizing giant, added 855 new members, while
Local<br>
73 inbrothers and sisters, call your state federation to see<br>
whether Chicago added 691 new members. leaflets are available for<br>
races in your area. <br>
<br>
DON'T FORGET YOUR (RWDSU) JACKET -- Workers at Andrew Marc<br>
Outerwear Co. in Secaucus, N.J., voted 23-5 to join the Retail,<br>
Wholesale and Department Store Union. When the predominately<br>
Hispanic work force raised objections over discrimination and no<br>
wage increases, they were told they had two choices -- either
walk<br>
back to work or walk out the door. They did walk -- to a union<br>
office.<br>
<br>
IBT PITCHES IN -- The Teamsters will give $200,000 to the Los<br>
Angeles Manufacturing Action Project to step up organizing,<br>
research and community activism to build an industry-wide union<br>
movement along the L.A.-Long Beach corridor. There are some
300,000<br>
manufacturing workers within LAMAP's target area -- about 70<br>
percent of whom are Latino and 90 percent of whom are nonunion.<br>
<br>
TEACH-INS CONTINUE -- Following up on the magnificent success<br>
of the kick-off teach-in at Columbia University, two more take<br>
place this week -- at the University of Wisconsin, Madison, Oct.<br>
15-16, and Wayne State University in Detroit, Oct. 18. The teach-<br>
ins offer unions and the academic community a chance to explore<br>
their common goals and forge new partnerships to help America's<br>
workers.<br>
<br>
MOTOR CITY MADNESS -- &quot;Permanent replacement&quot; isn't a
nasty<br>
enough tactic for the union-busting Detroit Newspapers. Last week<br>
they fired 20 striking workers for taking part in a sit-down<br>
demonstration outside the Detroit News Building. One of those
fired<br>
was Susan Watson, co-editor of the strikers' Detroit Journal
paper<br>
and the only black columnist at the Detroit Free Press. The
firing<br>
of Watson and the others drew the condemnation of the Detroit
NAACP<br>
and City Council. Also last week, the Teamsters Black Caucus<br>
arrived in Detroit and slammed newspaper management for claiming
it<br>
is helping minorities by hiring them at scab papers.<br>
<br>
CLEANING UP AFTER THEMSELVES -- Showing more class than their<br>
strike-bound employer and respect for the traveling public, SEIU<br>
members cleaned up National Airport after their Oct. 10<br>
demonstration there. Union President Andy Stern and Farm Workers<br>
President Arturo Rodriguez joined the picket action. The janitors<br>
struck two weeks ago against PRIEM, a joint-venture partner of
P&amp;R<br>
Enterprises, one of the largest nonunion janitorial companies in<br>
the Washington area, over unfair labor practices.<br>
<br>
ILWU NOT BLUE IN HAWAII -- The Longshoremen's and<br>
Warehousemen's Union has reached agreements with The Orchid at<br>
Mauna Lani and Renaissance Wailes Beach Resort in Maui covering<br>
more than 1,000 members. The union credits public protest aimed
at<br>
management companies and owners for spurring the movement at the<br>
table.<br>
<br>
NOT A PENNY FOR CROWN -- At the request of the Oil, Chemical<br>
and Atomic Workers, Crown Central Petroleum has been added to the<br>
AFL-CIO boycott list. The company locked out 250 members of OCAW<br>
Local 4-227 from its oil refinery in Pasadena, Texas, with a
&quot;take-<br>
it-or-leave-it&quot; contract ultimatum.<br>
<br>
CWA FLIPS MAXI-SWITCH -- A U.S.-based manufacturer of computer<br>
keyboards and game sets has engaged in brutal anti-union
activities<br>
at one of its Mexican plants and that country's government has
not<br>
enforced its labor laws to stop the abuse, the Communication<br>
Workers charged. In a complaint allowed under the terms of a
NAFTA<br>
side agreement, the CWA says the company, the government and a<br>
government-approved union acted in collusion to prevent workers<br>
from organizing a real union at the Cananea, Sonora plant. Union<br>
activists have been threatened, fired and beaten.<br>
<br>
UAW AIDS YOUTH -- At-risk youths get a helping hand from a<br>
joint UAW/General Motors Corp. effort centered on the automaker's<br>
tough apprenticeship program. The program works so well, it was<br>
honored by the U.S. Department of Labor. Since 1992, more than 70<br>
students have completed the school-to-work Manufacturing
Technology<br>
Partnership program, gaining two-year scholarships at Baker
College<br>
in Flint, Mich. -- and 96 percent have passed the apprenticeship<br>
test.<br>
<br>
AFM BACKS `FIRST' SAX PLAYER -- The Musicians have endorsed<br>
the Clinton-Gore ticket for re-election. AFM President Steve
Young<br>
noted recent cuts in arts funding, and said &quot;we feel it is<br>
imperative to support the president and his efforts to keep live<br>
music alive in this country . . . we also support his veto of the<br>
`TEAM Act' and his concern for working families in America.&quot;<br>
<br>
BEETLE MAKER NOT FAB -- The Teamsters have taken on<br>
Volkswagen over the carmaker's decision to abandon its operations<br>
at the Port of Wilmington, Del., dislocating 340 IBT members who<br>
had served the company for 18 years. &quot;Volkswagen is
destroying<br>
family wage jobs in America and ripping off taxpayer
subsidies,&quot;<br>
IBT President Ron Carey said. After a protest at German Week<br>
celebrations in Washington, union members handbilled five of VW's<br>
largest dealerships last weekend informing shoppers about the<br>
automaker's action and about the many recalls VW has made during<br>
the `90s.<br>
<br>
USDA SHELLS NUTMAKER -- The U.S. Department of Agriculture<br>
barred Diamond Walnut from government business for three years in<br>
the wake of the government-related bribery conviction of the
parent<br>
company's president. Some 600 Teamsters have been on strike
against<br>
the nut company for five years. The strikers rallied in
Pleasanton,<br>
Calif., this month to urge the USDA to take this action.<br>
<br>
PROJECT AGREEMENTS UPHELD -- The San Francisco Airport Project<br>
Stabilization Agreement is &quot;constitutional and consistent
with the<br>
purposes underlying competitive bidding,&quot; Superior Court
Judge<br>
David A. Garcia ruled. It was the latest in a series of court<br>
rulings upholding the agreements, which require union labor on<br>
public projects. <br>
<br>
JOBS ON THE WEB -- Finding the right federal job has been made<br>
a lot easier with the U.S. Office of Personnel Management's new<br>
Employment Information Homepage, &quot;USA JOBS.&quot; The
homepage, located<br>
at <a href="http://www.usajobs.opm.gov">http://www.usajobs.opm.gov</a>,
provides worldwide job listings<br>
updated daily. Non-Internet users can conduct job searches by<br>
dialing 912/757-3000.</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../index.htm">Public Documents Page</a> | <a
href="../publsear.htm">Public Documents Search</a></p>
