<html>
<head>
<title>WIP 10/08/96 AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<p align="left"><img src="../images/wip.gif" align="bottom"
width="508" height="135"></p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<p>WORK IN PROGRESS -- October 8, 1996<br>
<br>
WOMEN'S VOTES COUNT -- Working Women Vote Week is going full<br>
tilt, underscoring the fact that women will cast the deciding<br>
ballots this election year. The project, cosponsored by the
AFL-CIO<br>
and 9to5, the National Association of Working Women, runs through<br>
Oct. 11 with voter registration and GOTV events at more than 100<br>
sites nationwide. Nearly 10,000 union activists are reaching out
to<br>
women in grocery stores, shopping malls, day care centers, union<br>
halls and union worksites. Brochures and materials are available<br>
from Liz Gonchar at 202/637-5314.<br>
<br>
CURTAINS FOR SCOFFLAWS -- Companies that fire or harass<br>
workers who try to improve their lives by joining unions won't
get<br>
away with it, AFL-CIO President John Sweeney declared at a rally<br>
Tuesday in Everett, Mass., where workers at Richmark
International<br>
are trying to organize under UNITE's banner. The curtain<br>
manufacturer fired five workers for signing union authorization<br>
cards and laid off three more who distributed union literature<br>
before work. &quot;As long as workers are fired for an injustice,
we are<br>
going to be fired up for justice,&quot; Sweeney said.<br>
<br>
TEACH AND GROW -- An overflow crowd of more than 1,700<br>
university professors, students, labor leaders and union members<br>
swarmed a &quot;teach-in with the labor movement&quot; at
Columbia University<br>
Oct. 3-4. &quot;We need your help in making basic economic
education<br>
accessible to every American, so everyone can understand what is<br>
happening to their family budget and who is doing it to
them,&quot;<br>
President Sweeney said. Secretary-Treasurer Richard Trumka and<br>
Executive Vice President Linda Chavez-Thompson also participated.<br>
Nine other teach-ins are scheduled around the country this month.<br>
<br>
UNION IS HERE AT MARRIOTT -- The Marriott Hotel, the largest<br>
non-union hotel in San Francisco, has agreed to recognize the
Hotel<br>
Employees and Restaurant Employees Local 2. It is the first time<br>
that the huge Marriott chain has recognized a card check for<br>
organizing workers. &quot;This is an historical breakthrough that
is<br>
directly related to the local refocusing on organizing,&quot;
said AFL-<br>
CIO Organizing Director Richard Bensinger, who participated in a<br>
press conference in Mayor Willie Brown's office to announce the<br>
union victory.<br>
<br>
CHICKEN A LA RWDSU -- Workers at the Tyson's Foods poultry<br>
plant in Cleveland, Miss., voted 248-195 for representation by
the<br>
Retail, Wholesale and Department Store Union. The 550 workers had<br>
plenty of reasons to seek out the union: They were forced to work<br>
with injuries, could only take one seven-minute bathroom break a<br>
day and were subject to sexual harassment by supervisors.<br>
<br>
HILL COPS TRUCKIN' FOR IBT -- More than 450 Capitol Hill<br>
police officers signed petitions to be represented by the<br>
Teamsters. The petition vote came after enactment of the<br>
Congressional Accountability Act, which made Congress subject to<br>
the same labor laws as the rest of the country.<br>
<br>
VALUJET MECHANICS VALUE IBT -- Mechanics at ValuJet, concerned<br>
that their reputation and professionalism had been tarnished by
the<br>
airline's subcontracting much of its maintenance and safety work,<br>
voted for Teamsters representation. Following a May 11 crash<br>
killing all on board, the FAA grounded the airline for safety and<br>
maintenance problems, most tied to subcontractors said the IBT.
The<br>
airline resumed limited operations Sept. 26<br>
<br>
OCAW GAINS MEMBERS -- Some 1,100 members of the independent<br>
Union of Transportation Employees have voted to affiliate with
the<br>
Oil, Chemical and Atomic Workers.<br>
<br>
IT'S WHAT WE WANT, IT'S WHAT WE GOT -- Despite fear tactics by<br>
management at Coral Gables Convalescent Center in Southwest
Miami,<br>
workers voted 31-20 for UNITE representation. &quot;It's a simple
matter<br>
of respect. That's what we want, and that's what we voted for<br>
today,&quot; said 20-year employee Prima Washington,.<br>
<br>
ATTACK DOGS -- Viewers say the AFL-CIO's electronic voter<br>
guides now running in 25 congressional districts are informative<br>
and fairly depict candidates' positions. But that hasn't stopped<br>
the Republican party bosses from launching an all-out assault on<br>
the federation's issues-based campaign. The GOP last week began<br>
airing a nasty set of ads that attack &quot;Big Labor's Big
Lies,&quot; and<br>
filed a &quot;public relations lawsuit&quot; against the Federal
Election<br>
Commission for not moving faster on its frivolous complaints.
AFL-<br>
CIO General Counsel Jon Hiatt said the GOP's lawsuit is designed<br>
&quot;to distract public attention from the real issue in this
year's<br>
campaign -- the Republican Congress' dismal record on working<br>
family issues such as Medicare, health care, education, taxes and<br>
pension rights.&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
A STITCH IN TIME -- Pensions for some 70,000 workers in the<br>
men's garment industry will be protected under a government plan<br>
backed by UNITE and men's suit manufacturers. The fund was facing<br>
$253 million in liabilities, mainly because contributors had<br>
dropped from 575 employers 10 years ago to 200 today.<br>
<br>
NEW RULES AT FIELDCREST -- Citing Fieldcrest Cannon's<br>
&quot;scorched earth&quot; approach during a 1991 union
organizing campaign,<br>
a federal appeals court has ordered a new election under tough
new<br>
rules. The election for the plants in Cabarrus and Rowan counties<br>
in North Carolina will be held at a neutral site. The court also<br>
gave the union access to the company's nonunion facilities, equal<br>
time to answer company charges, and approval for a 30-minute
speech<br>
to workers up to 48 hours before the vote. It upheld an NLRB
order<br>
to reinstate 11 workers with $450,000 in back pay.<br>
<br>
USWA STRIKES WHEELING-PITT -- Some, 4,500 Steelworkers walked<br>
off the job Oct. 1 at eight Wheeling-Pittsburgh Steel plants
after<br>
the company refused to bring its pension plan near industry<br>
standards. USWA negotiators are seeking a defined pension plan<br>
paying retirees $40 per month per year of service. But the
company,<br>
which currently has pension costs about one-quarter of that of<br>
other steelmakers, wants a risky defined contribution plan with<br>
benefits based on the investment performance of its pension
funds.<br>
The company also has huge cash reserves that could help fund<br>
pensions.<br>
<br>
DETROIT PAPERS SNUB MAYOR -- A unique effort by the<br>
Metropolitan Council of Newspaper Unions and Detroit Mayor Dennis<br>
Archer to end the 15-month old Detroit newspaper strike was<br>
rejected by Gannett and Knight-Ridder Oct. 2. The unions agreed
to<br>
the mayor's call for binding mediation by a panel of three<br>
independent mediators. &quot;It takes two sides to bargain and
its<br>
obvious that the newspapers aren't interested in good faith<br>
bargaining, even under the wing of independent leaders such as
the<br>
mayor,&quot; said Al Derey of the Newspaper council. Also last
week,<br>
City Council President Maryann Mahaffey joined civil rights<br>
activist Dick Gregory and religious leaders in a 24-hour fast in<br>
support of the strikers.<br>
<br>
SENATE DELIVERS FOR FEDEX -- Succumbing to end-of-Congress<br>
fever, the Senate approved an FAA spending bill that puts up a
huge<br>
roadblock for 45,000 Federal Express drivers and their bid to<br>
unionize. FedEx is expected to use the provision to argue that
its<br>
drivers are covered by the Railway Labor Act, instead of the<br>
National Labor Relations Act, forcing companywide organizing,<br>
rather than site by site. FedEx employees spoke at a Capitol Hill<br>
news conference Thursday describing how they are facing
contracting<br>
out, reduced hours and harassment for their pro-union stands.
&quot;I<br>
worked 96 hours some weeks to help build this company . . .<br>
whatever it took,&quot; said Bill Chafin. FedEx continues to
deliver<br>
large profits, but not to its workers.<br>
<br>
CHECK YOUR CHECK -- Labor's push for a minimum wage increase<br>
became reality Oct. 1 for more than 4.3 million U.S. workers, who<br>
saw their earnings rise by 50 cents an hour in the first of two<br>
scheduled hikes. A 40-cent increase is set for Sept. 1, 1997.
AFL-<br>
CIO President John Sweeney said the increase was &quot;a raise
workers<br>
have earned, their employers can afford and the American people<br>
overwhelmingly support.&quot;<br>
<br>
UAW &amp; CHRYSLER NEAR -- CAW &amp; GM NOT -- The UAW's National<br>
Chrysler Council give its approval to a tentative contract
covering<br>
the carmaker's 66,000 union workers, who now will vote on<br>
ratification. Like the recently ratified Ford contract, the<br>
Chrysler deal calls for improvements in job security, wages and<br>
pensions. While the UAW continues talks with General Motors, the<br>
Canadian Autoworkers began a series of escalating strikes
Thursday<br>
against GM of Canada after talks broke down. Outsourcing is the<br>
main stumbling block, CAW officials say.<br>
<br>
ILA, ILWU RATIFY PACTS -- Longshoremen on the East and Gulf<br>
Coasts approved a five-year master agreement calling for a wage<br>
increase of $4 an hour over term for between 15,000 and 30,000
dock<br>
workers. On the West Coast, members of the Longshoremen's and<br>
Warehousemen's Union ratified a three-year deal for 8,000 workers<br>
at 26 ports. The contract calls for $3-an-hour pay increases over<br>
term.<br>
<br>
MORE BERRY PICKINGS -- More than 100 Coalition of Labor Union<br>
Women members participated in a demonstration at Sam's Club in
St.<br>
Louis in support of the Farm Workers' strawberry campaign. CLUW<br>
President Gloria Johnson, who led a delegation into the store,
not<br>
only met with the general manager but persuaded him to FAX the<br>
pledge and leaflet to Sam's corporate office. The general manager<br>
also said he &quot;would encourage them to sign the pledge.&quot;
Meanwhile,<br>
in South Florida, where worker delegations are visiting stores
each<br>
Tuesday, six more stores agreed to sign the pledge.<br>
<br>
PEACE ON THE RAILS -- A dozen railroad unions and 35 major<br>
freight carriers have reached agreement on five-year contracts<br>
covering some 145,000 workers nationwide, marking the first time
in<br>
nearly a decade accord was reached without strikes or imposed<br>
settlements. Maintenance of Way Employees President Mac Fleming<br>
said he hoped the negotiations could &quot;mark a turning point
in our<br>
recent, acrimonious relationship with the railroads.&quot; Two
smaller<br>
contracts await completion.<br>
<br>
STUDY TOGETHER -- Representatives who provide referral<br>
services for union members with substance abuse and other
personal<br>
problems under Member Assistance Programs can get help preparing<br>
for certification. If you have worked at least 3,000 hours<br>
providing these services and are ready to take a written exam to<br>
become a Certified Employee Assistance Professional, you qualify<br>
for the week of study, Dec. 2-6 at the George Meany Center for<br>
Labor Studies. For more information, call the Substance Abuse<br>
Institute at 301/431-1239.<br>
<br>
PETER J. BRENNAN DIES -- Peter J. Brennan, 78, a New York<br>
building trades leader who served as President Nixon's Secretary
of<br>
Labor from 1973-75 died Oct. 2. Labor Secretary Robert Reich
noted<br>
that Brennan's tenure was marked by laws protecting pensions and<br>
employment rights of the disabled, as well as strictly enforced<br>
workplace safety laws.<br>
<br>
SUPPORT STRAWBERRY WORKERS<br>
<br>
Why we do it<br>
&quot;A house and children...&quot;<br>
<br>
It's Romoco's first year in the strawberry fields. He picks<br>
berries near Salinas from 6 a.m. to 5 p.m. at the peak of the<br>
season. As the season winds down, the 18-year-old is only able to<br>
pick about 12 boxes of berries a day, for which he says he'll get<br>
about $24.<br>
<br>
Romoco says the bathrooms are cleaned about every two weeks<br>
and drinking water is sometimes dirty. He lives with five other<br>
people in a $175-a-week room at a run-down motel. He pays $12 a<br>
week to get to and from work.<br>
<br>
It's a six-day-a-week job. The mention of Sundays, when he<br>
plays basketball with his friends, brings a smile.<br>
<br>
Of course, Romoco would like better conditions in the fields.<br>
<br>
But, like other workers in the strawberry fields, Romoco has<br>
a bigger dream that depends on changing the conditions.<br>
<br>
&quot;I want a job that's enough to have a house and
children,&quot; he<br>
says.<br>
<br>
It's not out-of-the question. For 5 cents a pint more per<br>
berries, wages for 20,000 strawberry workers could be increased
by<br>
at least 50 percent, according to the University of California.
Who<br>
wouldn't pay that? Consumers would. The strawberry corporations<br>
won't.<br>
<br>
Get ready<br>
<br>
Strawberry workers and United Farm Workers President Arturo<br>
Rodriguez will travel to Washington, Baltimore, Philadelphia,<br>
northern New Jersey, New York City and Boston the week of Nov.
18.<br>
They'll seek support for the campaign. Tours in other regions of<br>
the country are being planned.<br>
<br>
Taking the lead<br>
<br>
On Sept. 16, central labor councils fought for strawberry<br>
workers in more than 60 cities. The massive activity came the day<br>
after at least 6,000 workers and supporters marched in
Watsonville,<br>
the heart of California strawberry country.<br>
<br>
* In Gainesville, Fla., students, women's rights activists,<br>
religious leaders and labor movement leaders visited stores and<br>
garnered news coverage from two TV stations, one radio station
and<br>
three alternative newspapers. CLC President Elsie Allen led the<br>
group.<br>
<br>
* In Flint, Mich., one man made a difference. Jose Vasquez,<br>
president of the Flint LCLAA Chapter, took a day off work to
visit<br>
nine stores. Now Vasquez is working with his CLC to organize<br>
delegations to visit more stores.<br>
<br>
* In Norfolk, Va., 80-year-old Joe Christian visited 20
supermarket<br>
managers, six of whom signed a pledge. Christian, a retired
member<br>
of the Graphic Communications International Union, also leafleted<br>
customers.<br>
<br>
* In Los Angeles, 130 people attended a press conference, where<br>
city council members signed the pledge.<br>
<br>
CLCs surpassed expectations. A complete list of active CLCs is<br>
attached.<br>
<br>
News from the fields<br>
<br>
* The strawberry corporations are gearing up to beat the<br>
workers, using an expensive public relations firm and lobbying<br>
political friends. They've conducted a whisper campaign among<br>
workers, saying the United Farm Workers are threatening a
boycott.<br>
In fact, the corporations are the ones talking about a boycott
and<br>
they're doing it to make the workers afraid for their jobs.<br>
<br>
The Strawberry Workers Campaign: 1-888-AFL-CIOO<br>
Media Inquiries: 202-637-5279 or 408-763-4820</p>
