<html>
<head>
<title>WIP 10/01/96 AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<p align="left"><img src="../images/wip.gif" align="bottom"
width="508" height="135"></p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<p>-- TUESDAY, OCTOBER 1, 1996</p>
<p>HEX ON FEDEX -- Intensive weekend lobbying by transportation<br>
unions and the AFL-CIO held off approval of an FAA funding bill<br>
that contains a &quot;midnight special&quot; special interest
favor for<br>
Federal Express, which the Teamsters termed &quot;a crass attempt
to<br>
further insulate the company from organizing efforts.&quot; The
&quot;killer<br>
amendment&quot; would allow FedEx to argue that its 45,000
drivers<br>
should fall under the Rail Labor Act, not the National Labor<br>
Relations Act. That means drivers must be organized throughout
the<br>
entire company, instead of site by site. The Senate stayed in<br>
session to wrangle over the authorization measure, which
Democrats<br>
vowed to kill if the favor to FedEx isn't pulled.<br>
<br>
BEATING BUSTER -- Workers at the Family Service Society of<br>
Yonkers, N.Y., beat back a vicious campaign by the union-busting<br>
firm of Jackson, Lewis and voted 115-21 for AFSCME
representation.<br>
It was the second time District Council 1707, which picks up the<br>
unit of 215 home care employees, has beaten the law firm. The win<br>
brings to 1,013 the number of new members DC 1707 has gained in
the<br>
past four months.<br>
<br>
NEW PLOT AT GENERAL HOSPITAL -- Employees of the Irvington<br>
(N.J.) General Hospital have affiliated with AFSCME. More than
200<br>
hospital workers took a stand for better wages and benefits when<br>
their employee association affiliated with the National Union of<br>
Hospital and Health Care Workers Union, Local 1199J, an AFSCME<br>
affiliate.<br>
<br>
LABORERS WIN DEMOLITION DERBY -- Almost 1,000 mostly immigrant<br>
demolition workers in New York City have joined Laborers Local
79.<br>
That strength forced contractors to sign a new four-year contract<br>
covering about 75 percent of the city's demolition market; the
pact<br>
includes wage increases and health benefits. Rank-and-file
members<br>
played a huge part by paying house calls to the nonunion workers,<br>
followed by mass meetings and roving job-site pickets and
strikes.<br>
<br>
SHORESIDE SOLIDARITY -- Public employees in Jacksonville<br>
Beach, Fla., voted 105-49 for Laborers' representation. LIUNA
also<br>
has organized municipal workers in the surrounding beach<br>
communities of Atlantic and Neptune and the city of Jacksonville.<br>
<br>
DRIVERS PICK MINE WORKERS -- Continuing to build on its<br>
successful use of members recruiting members, the Mine Workers
won<br>
an election to represent 148 shuttle drivers employed by Republic<br>
Parking at the Denver airport. UMWA President Cecil Roberts<br>
credited rank-and-file members from Colorado, Montana, New
Mexico,<br>
Utah and Wyoming who went to Denver to explain the benefits of
UMWA<br>
membership.<br>
<br>
TWO DOWN, ONE TO GO -- UAW members ratified one contract with<br>
a Big Three auto maker and tentatively agreed to another. By
votes<br>
of 90 percent and 83 percent, respectively, production workers
and<br>
skilled crafts ratified the new contract with Ford on Sunday. The<br>
same day, the union reached a tentative agreement with Chrysler,<br>
leaving only General Motors without a deal with the UAW. The<br>
union's Chrysler Council will meet Oct. 3 to vote on whether to<br>
send the agreement to the membership for ratification.<br>
<br>
BRIDGESTONE PROGRESS -- After 26 months, almost all workers<br>
who struck the company have been called back to work at Japanese-<br>
owned Bridgestone/Firestone. This dramatic turnaround is &quot;a
result<br>
of our escalating campaign&quot; said John Sellers, executive
vice<br>
president of Steelworkers' Rubber/Plastics Industry Council. But<br>
the USWA campaign against the tire maker will continue until it<br>
meets the union's demands to recall 150 illegally fired workers,<br>
negotiate a decent union contract, pay back wages to the replaced<br>
workers and settle all pending unfair labor practices charges<br>
against the company.<br>
<br>
MADE OF STEEL -- The Steelworkers ended their 42-month strike<br>
against Bayou Steel Corp. with a new six-year contract that<br>
reinstates 220 members of Local 9121 with full seniority, calls
for<br>
a bonus to all returnees and an incentive plan that will have the<br>
effect of raising wages and protects workers against contracting<br>
out. &quot;They could not have ousted the scabs and won this
great<br>
victory if they had not maintained their solidarity and
commitment<br>
to trade union ideals,&quot; said USWA President George Becker.<br>
<br>
VOTER GUIDES ON THE AIR -- The AFL-CIO on Friday launched a<br>
new series of nonpartisan TV and radio voter guides to highlight<br>
candidates' stands on important working-family issues in 24<br>
congressional districts. The continuing campaign is focusing on<br>
issues raised at 29 America Needs A Raise town hall meetings this<br>
year, as well as polling and focus groups of union and nonunion<br>
members. &quot;We plan to continue to lobby officeholders and
would-be<br>
officeholders to adopt positions on issues like education, health<br>
care and retirement security that are good for working
people,&quot;<br>
AFL-CIO President John Sweeney said.<br>
<br>
D.C. JANITORS STRIKE LOOMS -- Some 1,700 janitors in the<br>
nation's capital were set to strike at midnight Monday when
Service<br>
Employees Local 82's pact with area cleaning contractors expired,<br>
but negotiators kept talking past the deadline. More than 100<br>
Washington-area trade unionists rallied at National Airport
Friday<br>
in support of janitors trying to organize a union at P&amp;R<br>
Enterprises, a major area janitorial firm that also holds the<br>
airport cleaning contract.<br>
<br>
CONGRESS AT THE WIRE -- Congressional negotiators and the<br>
White House reached agreement on a massive spending package,<br>
including many labor-backed provisions in the Labor/HHS<br>
appropriations portion. No destructive riders were attached.<br>
Immigration reform was approved only after several objectionable<br>
provisions opposed by the AFL-CIO were dropped, including a ban
on<br>
public education for children of illegal immigrants, restrictions<br>
on public programs used by legal immigrants and provisions making<br>
it harder for workers -- especially in sweatshop situations -- to<br>
collect back pay.<br>
<br>
OTANI ON TRIAL -- Three Latina women fired by the New Otani<br>
Hotel for supporting the Hotel and Restaurant Employees'
organizing<br>
drive finally will have their day in court this week before the<br>
National Labor Relations Board. The hotel has bitterly fought the<br>
union since the organizing campaign began in early 1993, but the<br>
union has won every NLRB charge it has filed.<br>
<br>
HOSPITAL PRIVATIZATION PARRIED -- Hospital workers and their<br>
allies, cheered by the support of Executive Vice President Linda<br>
Chavez-Thompson and the Rev. Jesse L. Jackson, rallied in<br>
Cincinnati Sept. 24 to protest a plan to lease out the city's
only<br>
public and teaching hospital to a private company for $1 a year.<br>
The proposal, which faces a final vote by trustees Oct. 8, would<br>
nullify all contracts and abolish union representation for
interns,<br>
resident physicians and fellows.<br>
<br>
NUKE NEWT -- Union members rallying outside outnumbered House<br>
Speaker Newt Gingrich and his guests inside a GOP fundraiser in<br>
Sheffield, Ala., last week. &quot;Everything they stand for is
against<br>
everything we stand for,&quot; said Michael Lemay, Carpenters
Local 109<br>
business manager. Unions in that district are urging workers to
get<br>
out and re-elect Rep. Bud Cramer (D).<br>
<br>
WAVE THAT FLAG -- The Senate has sent to President Clinton a<br>
maritime reform bill that &quot;ensures America's national and
economic<br>
security while producing jobs for American merchant
mariners,&quot;<br>
Seafarers President Michael Sacco said. The bill sets up a
10-year,<br>
$1 billion program for U.S.-flag carriers that promise to their<br>
ships available to the U.S. military in emergencies.<br>
<br>
MAIN STREET SLAMS WALL STREET -- As the Federal Reserve<br>
pondered raising interest rates last week, working families in<br>
Minnesota chimed in with more than their two cents' worth on
fiscal<br>
policy. The Jobs Now Coalition denounced 9th District Federal<br>
Reserve Bank President Gary Stern for his lead role in pushing
for<br>
restrictive monetary policies, including higher interest rates,<br>
that kill jobs and create economic hardship, taking issue with<br>
Stern's belief that working families are &quot;making too much
and that<br>
small businesses' access to capital is too easy,&quot; declared<br>
coalition Director Kris Jacobs. The Fed decided against a rate<br>
hike.<br>
<br>
PROXY NATIONS -- Think the power of corporate wealth is<br>
overstated? Of the 100 largest economies in the world, less than<br>
half are countries -- the majority are corporations, the
Institute<br>
for Policy Studies found. The combined sales of the top 200<br>
corporations far exceeds a quarter of the world's economic<br>
activity, yet they employ less than three one-hundredths of one<br>
percent of the world's population. The new study &quot;The Top
200: The<br>
Rise of Global Corporate Power&quot; can be obtained from IPS at<br>
202/234-9382.<br>
<br>
CLIPPING THEIR WINGS -- The Flight Attendants filed suit<br>
seeking a stay against a Sept. 26 decision by the Transportation<br>
Department to permit safety-challenged Valujet Airlines to resume<br>
operations. A May 11 Valujet crash killed all on board, and the<br>
government grounded the airline last summer after finding a
pattern<br>
of repeated safety and maintenance problems.<br>
<br>
NO SWEAT -- Garment manufacturers would be legally responsible<br>
for ensuring their contractors' operations are not sweatshops
under<br>
legislation introduced by Sen. Edward M. Kennedy (D-Mass.) and
Rep.<br>
William L. Clay (D-Mo.) UNITE President Jay Mazur said the bill<br>
&quot;closes a glaring loophole in our labor laws that has
allowed<br>
sweatshop production to once again invade the apparel
industry.&quot;<br>
<br>
DIAMOND IN THE ROUGH -- Strikers at Diamond Walnut will rally<br>
Oct. 1 in Pleasanton, Calif., to urge the Agriculture Department<br>
to bar the company from getting subsidies or other benefits in
the<br>
wake of the conviction of its parent, Sun Diamond, of bribing<br>
former Agriculture Secretary Mike Espy. The 600 workers, members
of<br>
the Teamsters, struck Diamond Walnut five years ago.<br>
<br>
LABORERS ELECTION SET -- Holding its first secret ballot<br>
election, delegates to the Laborers' convention nominated LIUNA<br>
President Arthur Coia and Local 1001 President Bruno Caruso to<br>
appear on what will be the first rank-and-file ballot for LIUNA's<br>
top office. Balloting will be held from Nov. 2 through Dec. 16.
The<br>
convention also urged greater use of volunteer organizers and<br>
expanded their program to organize nonunion contractors.<br>
<br>
IAM SAYS YES TO MERGER -- Delegates to the Machinists'<br>
convention in Chicago overwhelmingly approved plans to merge with<br>
the UAW and the Steelworkers. The convention also voted to free
up<br>
funds earmarked for the strike fund for organizing, education and<br>
other services. Several speakers, including AFL-CIO President
John<br>
J. Sweeney, urged the delegates to vote like workers and throw
out<br>
the anti-worker Republican Congress in November.<br>
<br>
REAL HEROES -- The Letter Carriers have honored four of its<br>
workers with NALC Hero of the Year Awards. Joan Barr was
recognized<br>
for crawling under a train wreck to save trapped victims inside a<br>
burning car. Guy A. Young, Mark A. Hopkins and Carlos E. Tichenor<br>
received regional heroes awards and Donald Coldwell was selected
as<br>
the national humanitarian for his commitment to the foster care<br>
program.</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../index.htm">Public Documents Page</a> | <a
href="../publsear.htm">Public Documents Search</a></p>
