<html>
<head>
<title>WIP 09/23/96 AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<p align="left"><img src="../images/wip.gif" align="bottom"
width="508" height="135"></p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<p>-- MONDAY, SEPTEMBER 23, 1996<br>
<br>
BUILDING JOBS THAT LAST -- UAW members will vote Sept. 29 on<br>
a tentative three-year contract with Ford Motor Co. that, for the<br>
first time, includes a guaranteed employment floor. Under the<br>
agreement, Ford would maintain a minimum employment floor of 95<br>
percent of the current number of UAW-represented jobs, which is<br>
about 105,000. Following a first-year up-front lump sum payment
of<br>
$2,000, Ford employees would receive a 3 percent general wage<br>
increase in the second and third years. The UAW still has<br>
negotiations with General Motors and Chrysler.<br>
<br>
FIGHTING BACK PAYS OFF -- Employees at Burlington Industries<br>
took on their company and the investment establishment to win a<br>
$26.5 million settlement for their retirement plan. Burlington
had<br>
staved off a takeover bid in 1987 by creating an employee stock<br>
ownership plan that benefited its partner, investment banker
Morgan<br>
Stanley, while forcing employees to pay more than twice what the<br>
stock was worth. Also paying up is NationsBank, whose predecessor<br>
was the trustee of the plan. UNITE, then the Clothing and Textile<br>
Workers, helped the workers file the $100 million lawsuit.<br>
<br>
FRANKLY, MY DEAR . . . -- Rep. Gary Franks (R-Conn.) ducked an<br>
invitation to explain his votes to cut college loans and other<br>
education programs in front of a forum at Western Connecticut
State<br>
University. Organized by Youth for Justice, a campus group headed<br>
by Union Summer alum Justin Molitio, the Sept. 19 gathering<br>
featured testimony from several students and parents on the<br>
difficulty of financing a college education.<br>
<br>
TORTILLA DRIVERS ROLL -- After seven weeks on strike, more<br>
than 100 truckers, represented by the Teamsters, ratified a new<br>
five-year contract with Los Angeles tortilla maker Mission<br>
Guerrero. The contract, ratified Sept. 18, boosts worker pay by
$95<br>
a week over the term of the contract, raises the drivers'<br>
commission rate, prohibits the company from unilaterally<br>
contracting out the drivers' jobs and lowers health care costs.<br>
<br>
OVERNITE, IT'S UNION -- Workers at Overnite Transportation<br>
Co.'s Memphis, Tenn., terminal voted 219-201 for Teamsters<br>
representation. IBT has won the right to represent some 2,000<br>
Overnite workers in its nationwide organizing drive, with another<br>
1,000 being challenged. Memphis is the second-largest Overnite<br>
facility in the country.<br>
<br>
ALPA GOT THE SPIRIT -- Spirit Airlines pilots have voted for<br>
representation with the Air Line Pilots. Some 60 percent of the
86<br>
pilots eligible voted for ALPA.<br>
<br>
HOUSE LOSES -- Casino workers on the Admiral riverboat in St.<br>
Louis will get another chance to vote for a union because<br>
management violated labor laws. The National Labor Relations
Board<br>
ordered a new election, with locals of the Hotel Employees and<br>
Restaurant Employees and Service Employees working together to<br>
organize the workers. The St. Louis Federation of Labor and the<br>
Missouri AFL-CIOs launched a boycott of the casino after the<br>
tainted election last October.<br>
<br>
WAGES RISE SWIFTLY -- UNITE textile workers at Swift in Erwin,<br>
N.C., ratified a wage increase of 4 percent. The raise, which was<br>
effective Sept. 9, is the second raise of that size in 13 months.<br>
In the 1990s, UNITE has negotiated an overall 30 percent wage
boost<br>
for the 1,300 Swift workers. &quot;Once again, negotiations at
Swift<br>
have produced the best wage settlement in the textile
industry,&quot;<br>
said Phil Cohen, UNITE's Central North Carolina manager.<br>
<br>
WHAT'S UP? DOCK PAY -- The Longshoremen reached a tentative<br>
container contract with the Carriers Container Council Sept. 17<br>
affecting wages, hours, automation and health and pension plans
for<br>
up to 55,000 workers from Maine to Texas. Such local issues as
work<br>
practices and benefits still must be negotiated before the
current<br>
pact expires Sept. 30.<br>
<br>
PIPELINE TO JOBS -- A $1.1 billion, multiyear water pipeline<br>
project agreement was reached by the AFL-CIO Building and<br>
Construction Trades Department and Parsons Constructors. The
Inland<br>
Feeder water distribution pipeline is a project of the
Metropolitan<br>
Water District of Southern California. Several hundred
construction<br>
workers get started on the project this fall and will work
through<br>
1999.<br>
<br>
MIDWESTERN MOBILIZATION -- Workers were on the march in the<br>
Midwest last week at two huge rallies urging voter registration
and<br>
demanding that elected officials pay attention to the interests
of<br>
working families. More than 10,000 trade unionists marched to the<br>
Michigan state capital building in Lansing in a rally sponsored
by<br>
the state AFL-CIO. The Indiana state federation sponsored a State<br>
of the Union Town Hall Meeting that drew thousands of trade<br>
unionists to the state fairgrounds in Indianapolis. <br>
<br>
LOW PAY BURNS FIREFIGHTERS -- Federal fire fighters are<br>
&quot;dramatically underpaid compared to other federal
employees&quot; IAFF<br>
Vice President Michael J. Crouse said when he testified in favor
of<br>
legislation to correct the wage inequities Sept. 17. The<br>
legislation simply states that federal employees at the same
grade<br>
and step should earn the same hourly salary regardless of their<br>
duties. But the Department of Defense and the Office of Personnel<br>
Management suggested that a forthcoming joint report's<br>
recommendations could resolve the pay issues.<br>
<br>
TEACH YOUR CHILDREN WELL -- America's workers are joining<br>
their academic allies in a national initiative on the
re-energized<br>
labor movement. &quot;A Teach-In With the Labor Movement&quot; is
designed to<br>
promote a new spirit of activism and a national dialogue between<br>
academics and trade unionists. It &quot;adds a powerful new
dimension to<br>
the development of the new and stronger voice for working
families<br>
we're working so hard to create,&quot; AFL-CIO President John
Sweeney<br>
said. A national teach-in at Columbia University is set for Oct.
3<br>
and 4, with regional events set throughout October.<br>
<br>
GIVE IT A REST -- The Federal Reserve Board, scheduled to meet<br>
Tuesday to consider a possible interest rate increase,
&quot;should give<br>
economic growth a chance . . . and not choke off growth on behalf<br>
of a wealthy bondholder elite,&quot; concluded an analysis by the
AFL-<br>
CIO Public Policy Department. The latest consumer price index<br>
showed only a trace of inflation, the bugaboo the Fed cites when
it<br>
decides to raise rates.<br>
<br>
NOW HEAR THIS -- The Transportation Trades Department's<br>
Executive Committee last week urged Congress to scuttle ocean<br>
shipping deregulation, condemned Federal Express for manipulating<br>
labor law to block organizing efforts, attacked proposals to
reduce<br>
the federal gas tax and to privatize airports, and called for<br>
passage of a bill to toughen certification of foreign aircraft<br>
repair facilities.<br>
<br>
YOUNG TO LEAD UPIU -- The Paperworkers elected Boyd D. Young<br>
as president to succeed the retiring Wayne E. Glenn, who was<br>
elected president emeritus. Secretary-Treasurer James Dunn was
re-<br>
elected without opposition. Young, 56, had been a vice president<br>
for eight years. The 2,200 delegates also voted to intensify<br>
organizing efforts.<br>
<br>
IBEW LIGHTS UP THE FUTURE -- Incumbent President John J. Barry<br>
and Secretary Jack F. Moore handily won the right to lead the<br>
Electrical Workers into the 21st century. at the union's 35th<br>
international convention. Re-elected without opposition by the<br>
2,400 delegates at the Philadelphia gathering were Treasurer
Thomas<br>
Van Arsdale and Executive Council Chairman Clyde Bowden. After
days<br>
of debate, delegates voted to go to a secret ballot in future<br>
conventions.<br>
<br>
GRAPHIC APPROACH TO ORGANIZING -- Delegates to the Graphic<br>
Communications Union convention raised per capita to boost<br>
organizing and service to members, and explored ways to make<br>
technological innovation work for workers, not against them.<br>
&quot;Without organizing, we jeopardize our existing wages and
working<br>
conditions,&quot; GCIU President James J. Norton told the nearly
500<br>
delegates.<br>
<br>
TWO UNIONS MEET -- The Laborers and the Machinists hold<br>
conventions this week. For the first time, LIUNA delegates,
meeting<br>
in Las Vegas, will hold secret-ballot elections for vice
presidents<br>
and nominate candidates for president, who will face a rank-and-<br>
file election later this year. LIUNA President Arthur A. Coia<br>
expects opposition, but there is no contest for secretary-<br>
treasurer. The upcoming merger with the Steelworkers and UAW will<br>
top the IAM agenda in Chicago, where delegates certainly will
toast<br>
the IAM's recent victory in the 15-week McDonnell Douglas strike.<br>
<br>
PENSION AUDIT MEASURE ADVANCES -- The Senate backed bipartisan<br>
legislation last week that would ensure meaningful audits of some<br>
$950 billion in private pension funds, enhancing the retirement<br>
security of millions of American workers, retirees and their<br>
families. The Clinton administration has urged the House to move<br>
quickly to approve the measure.<br>
<br>
DEATH RAISES SAFETY ISSUE -- The gruesome death of 18-year-old<br>
Solomon Velasquez, who was killed while cleaning an
industrial-size<br>
blender at Lundy Packing Co. in Sampson County, N.C., has
prompted<br>
the Food and Commercial Workers to launch an investigation.
Workers<br>
allege the company failed to provide legally required programs
on, <br>
and safeguards for, the cleaning and operation of hazardous<br>
machines. Three other workers at the same plant have lost hands
in<br>
the last year. Two years ago there also was an outbreak of<br>
brucellosis, a disease contracted from contaminated hog blood at<br>
the plant.<br>
<br>
METALWORKING PANEL ON THE WAY -- In the wake of a UAW request<br>
for emergency action, OSHA will form an advisory committee to<br>
recommend proposed rules for exposure to metalworking fluids.<br>
Nominations must be postmarked by Sept. 30 and should be sent to<br>
the U.S. Department of Labor/OSHA, Directorate of Health
Standards<br>
Programs, Metalworking Fluids Project Officer, 200 Constitution<br>
Ave. N.W., Room N-3718, Washington, D.C. 20210.<br>
<br>
ALBERTSON'S WORKERS SUE -- Seven current and former employees<br>
of Albertson's grocery chain filed a class-action lawsuit seeking<br>
back pay for work they performed off the clock. The suit, filed<br>
with the help of the Food and Commercial Workers, claims<br>
Albertson's threatens to fire employees who complain about
working<br>
off the clock and fails to permit rest breaks on company time.
More<br>
than 1,500 workers have given declarations that they worked off
the<br>
clock for Albertson's.<br>
<br>
SPEED TRAP -- The Farm Labor Organizing Committee (FLOC) and<br>
individual plaintiffs have filed suit against the Ohio State<br>
Highway Patrol alleging a pattern of stopping and searching<br>
Hispanic motorists and their passengers.<br>
<br>
AIFLD'S FRIEDMAN DIES -- The labor movement lost a longtime<br>
friend and educator when Jesse A. Friedman, executive director of<br>
the American Institute For Free Labor Development, died of cancer<br>
last week at 62. In memoriam, he asked for a celebration, which
was<br>
held at the George Meany Center for Labor Studies Friday.
Speakers<br>
included AFL-CIO President Sweeney and President Emeritus Lane<br>
Kirkland.<br>
<br>
HEAT WAVE<br>
<br>
From the beginning of June through the end of August, the AFL-<br>
CIO's Union Summer activists participated in organizing campaigns<br>
nationwide. Collectively, they racked up impressive numbers:
making<br>
almost 13,000 house visits, distributing more than 200,000 flyers<br>
and leaflets, collecting nearly 72,000 petition signatures for<br>
campaigns, and conducting more than 500 delegation visits to
stores<br>
and office buildings. The activists also helped to score<br>
significant victories for labor this summer. This final Heat Wave<br>
is a sampling of their work.<br>
<br>
During the course of Union Summer in Boston, activists helped<br>
win contracts for ComGas workers fighting a lockout, Hertz
Rent-A-<br>
Car employees and workers at the newly-merged City Hospital.<br>
<br>
Charleston, SC Union Summer activists' summer-long campaign of<br>
&quot;in your face&quot; tactics, including pickets, rallies and
guerilla<br>
theater, helped win the first union contract at the Melrose Club<br>
resorts.<br>
<br>
In their last week, Chicago Union Summer activists scored a<br>
victory when two grocery store managers signed a pledge
supporting<br>
the rights of strawberry workers to dignity, a living wage, and<br>
clean drinking water.<br>
<br>
As a result of Union Summer actions, six Denver custodial<br>
services contractors signed an agreement allowing organizers to<br>
talk to non-union workers about unionizing. Union Summer actions<br>
included joining tenant delegations, talking to property
management<br>
companies, and street demonstrations.<br>
<br>
In Detroit, Union Summer activists' in-store actions and face-<br>
to-face meetings with workers helped 2,000 employees of Rite Aid<br>
Drugstores get a union contract with the United Food and
Commercial<br>
Workers Local 876.<br>
<br>
Through continuous picketing, Los Angeles Union Summer<br>
activists helped HERE convince the owner of Camacho restaurants,<br>
who had reneged on his promise to have union employees at his Los<br>
Angeles Airport restaurant, to agree to negotiate with the union<br>
and hire back employees he'd fired for organizing.<br>
<br>
In just three weeks, Union Summer activists in New Orleans<br>
helped win a first-ever contract for city sanitation workers.
They<br>
also did the legwork and research to launch three new organizing<br>
campaigns: two nursing home drives and a drive with a janitorial<br>
service for local universities.<br>
<br>
New York Union Summer activists' rally and march in<br>
Manhattan's sweatshop district drew many new workers to the
Justice<br>
Center to learn more about unions. Their efforts also helped to<br>
resolve four employee dispute cases and win back pay for those<br>
employees.<br>
<br>
San Diego Union Summer activists recruited 100 precinct<br>
leaders in neighborhoods across San Diego, establishing an active<br>
base of community support for union efforts. The United Nurses<br>
Association of San Diego credits Union Summer activists' pickets<br>
with helping them win a contract for 2,700 nurses.<br>
<br>
Clearly impressed with the Watsonville Union Summer activists'<br>
abilities, corporate anti-union consultants complained publicly<br>
that the UFW had &quot;brought in 112 specially trained
activists&quot; who<br>
&quot;could change the minds of even the most adamant anti-union<br>
workers.&quot; The 16 Union Summer activists in Watsonville were<br>
extremely flattered.</p>
