<head>
<title>WIP 09/16/96 AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h3>Work in Progress</h3>
<p>-- Monday, September 16, 1996<br>
<br>
BRIDGESTONE BURIED IN BIG EASY -- A New Orleans-style<br>
&quot;funeral,&quot; complete with Dixieland band, escorted Bridgestone and<br>
Firestone signs from four New Orleans tire stores to their final<br>
resting place as owner Cal Lucas suspended his use of the tires in<br>
support of the Steelworkers' &quot;Don't Buy&quot; campaign against the<br>
Japanese-owned company. Lucas is the largest independent tire<br>
dealer in New Orleans, doing up to $1 million annually with<br>
Firestone/Dayton. In Atlanta, the city council adopted a resolution<br>
calling for no more city purchases from Bridgestone/Firestone until<br>
its dispute with USWA is settled.<br>
<br>
BIG MAC IS BACK -- The 99-day strike against the nation's<br>
largest defense contractor ended Sept. 11, when 5,600 Machinists<br>
voted 2-1 in favor of a new contract with McDonnell Douglas that<br>
improved job security, retiree benefits and wages. The pact<br>
requires 60 days' notice of subcontracting plans and forces the<br>
company to meet with the union to retain work. It also raises wages<br>
by 4.5 percent, provides three bonuses and allows &quot;30 and out&quot;<br>
retirement at age 50 with what the union says is the highest<br>
defined pension in the aerospace industry. IAM President George<br>
Kourpias said the strike shows that &quot;people don't have to be<br>
victims of job exports or low wages.&quot;<br>
<br>
PUTTING IN THEIR 5 CENTS' WORTH -- Nearly 6,000 strawberry<br>
workers and their supporters marched Sunday in Watsonville, Calif.,<br>
setting the stage Monday for a second national action day of<br>
community activism from Alabama to Alaska. In Denver, a coalition<br>
of workers and labor and religious leaders were visiting<br>
supermarket corporate officers, urging their support in gaining<br>
better conditions in the fields. Similar activity occurred across<br>
the country. In Los Angeles, city council members signed a giant<br>
pledge card to support the workers. A recent study showed that<br>
doubling workers' $8,000 annual wages would cost the growers only<br>
5 cents per pint of berries.<br>
<br>
ORGANIZING . . . AND WINNING!! -- The AFL-CIO's elected leader<br>
task force on organizing spent three days in Chicago in candid<br>
discussions about the obstacles and opportunities faced in<br>
organizing workers. Some unions are doing it -- and winning:<br>
<br>
* Workers at Kitchen of the Ocean shrimp processing plant in<br>
Deerfield Beach, Fla., voted 173-18 for UNITE representation. The<br>
win marks the sixth UNITE victory in the Miami area since January.<br>
<br>
* The Green Bay Symphony Orchestra voted 63-18 to be represented by<br>
Musicians Local 205. The campaign was conducted by the union's<br>
newly established Organizing and Education Department.<br>
<br>
* In Logan, Ohio, workers stood strong against a year of hostility<br>
from the Carborundum Grinding Wheel Co. and voted 40-35 for Mine<br>
Worker representation.<br>
<br>
* City workers in Coeur d'Alene, Idaho, voted to affiliate with<br>
AFSCME's Council 2 in Washington state. The union will represent 93<br>
employees.<br>
<br>
* Teamsters Local 572 won an election to represent 467 maintenance<br>
workers at the Los Angeles Airport. The workers are employed by<br>
Whitewood Oriental Maintenance Co.<br>
<br>
* After a two-year organizing campaign, 130 workers at the Cerebral<br>
Palsy Association of Niagara County, N.Y., voted for representation<br>
with Service Employees Local 652. The unit now plans to go after<br>
almost 1,000 technical employees at Children's Hospital in Buffalo.<br>
Meanwhile, 270 technical employees at Good Samaritan Hospital in<br>
Brockton, Mass., voted for representation by SEIU Local 767. The<br>
local also has filed for an election to represent the hospital's<br>
service and maintenance unit of more than 500 workers.<br>
<br>
LABOR MOVEMENT -- The AFL-CIO's top officers are on the move.<br>
President John Sweeney addresses the Graphic Communications Union<br>
convention in California and the Nevada AFL-CIO convention Monday,<br>
the Paperworkers in Las Vegas Tuesday and the Electrical Workers in<br>
Philadelphia on Thursday. Secretary-Treasurer Rich Trumka is feted<br>
by the Jewish National Committee as the labor recipient of its Tree<br>
of Life Award on Tuesday. He addresses Operation PUSH on Friday.<br>
Meanwhile, Executive Vice President Linda Chavez-Thompson is in<br>
Missouri Monday for the state AFL-CIO convention and in Washington<br>
Friday for that state convention.<br>
<br>
VICTORY AT VET HOME -- Striking AFSCME members at the Anna,<br>
Ill., veterans' home ratified their first contract Sept. 12,<br>
clearing their return to work after walking the bricks for some<br>
five weeks. The three-year pact with ServiceMaster Diversified<br>
Health Services calls for increases over term totaling nearly $4 --<br>
from $4.60 to $4.71 an hour to $8.25 to $8.50 an hour -- with<br>
employer-provided health insurance, additional paid leave, holiday<br>
pay, a 401(k) program, grievance procedures and regular labor-<br>
management meetings.<br>
<br>
BARGAIN, OR ELSE -- A federal judge ordered America West<br>
Airlines to immediately begin contract negotiations with the<br>
mechanics, who voted for Teamsters representation in April. &quot;We won<br>
the election fair and square and now the company has to negotiate,&quot;<br>
said Jim Grace, an America West mechanic for nine years.<br>
<br>
IT'S OFFICIAL -- Never one to resist an opportunity to hammer<br>
workers, Sen. Lauch Faircloth (R-N.C.) offered an amendment banning<br>
&quot;official time&quot; -- the time union reps spend on labor-management<br>
programs and other representational activities -- at the Social<br>
Security Administration and the Heath Care Financing<br>
Administration. But his amendment to the fiscal 1997 Treasury-<br>
Postal appropriations bill was one of more than 100 proposed and<br>
that caused Senate leaders to pull the bill from the floor.<br>
<br>
BILL IS HALF FULL -- When the Senate Appropriations Committee<br>
reported the fiscal 1997 Labor/HHS bill, it included full funding<br>
for the National Labor Relations Board (the House had cut the<br>
funding by 15 percent). It also did not place any ban on OSHA's<br>
ergonomic research or issuance of new ergonomics standards. But the<br>
bill's cuts in education and training have drawn a White House veto<br>
threat. The White House also criticized funding cuts for OSHA and<br>
a DoL program to eliminate sweatshops in the garment industry.<br>
<br>
DETROIT STANDS BY STRIKERS -- The Detroit newspaper strike<br>
continues to hit the scab Free Press and News squarely in the<br>
pocketbook. The two papers admitted that their weekday circulation<br>
has declined 35 percent, and 31 percent on Sunday, since the unfair<br>
labor practice strike began in July 1995 -- that's 10 percent<br>
higher than officials of the two papers were willing to admit<br>
previously. They also admitted that they are distributing some<br>
papers for which no revenue has been collected.<br>
<br>
COTTON DEAL FEELS GOOD -- A tentative agreement was reached<br>
Sept. 9 between UNITE and the multiemployer association<br>
representing cotton garment companies. The agreement, which covers<br>
30,000 employees in the cotton garment industry nationwide, was<br>
recommended by the negotiation committee. The ratification vote is<br>
scheduled in a couple weeks.<br>
<br>
OREOS FOR ALL -- The Bakery, Confectionery and Tobacco Workers<br>
have ratified a five-year pact with Nabisco Biscuit Co. The<br>
agreement covers some 5,700 workers in Pittsburgh, Philadelphia,<br>
Buffalo and Niagara Falls, N.Y., Denver, Atlanta, Houston, Chicago,<br>
Richmond, Va., Portland, Ore., Buena Park, Calif., and Fair Lawn,<br>
N.J., and provides across-the-board increases totaling $4.61 per<br>
hour over term. Workers also gained increases in pensions, health<br>
benefits and the formation of two labor-management task forces.<br>
<br>
ROTTEN TO THE CORE -- Apple processor Stemilt, Inc. of<br>
Wenatchee, Wash., discharged six workers for wanting to organize a<br>
union. Teamsters Local 760 has filed charges of unfair labor<br>
practices against the company. Ironically, Stemilt's President Tom<br>
Mathison was named &quot;Apple Man of the Year&quot; by the International<br>
Apple Institute.<br>
<br>
AMEN, BROTHERS AND SISTERS -- Building on their efforts in<br>
North Carolina, a coalition of religious leaders is expanding<br>
nationwide to increase its campaign for better conditions for low-<br>
wage workers. The Interfaith Committee for Worker Justice will<br>
campaign for better wages and working conditions in the poultry<br>
industry. The committee first mobilized to help 450 striking<br>
workers at the Case Farms poultry plant in Morganton, N.C.<br>
<br>
CALL WILLARD SCOTT -- Four unions that have recently<br>
celebrated or are looking forward to 100-year anniversaries have<br>
been added to the Labor Department's Century of Service Honor Roll.<br>
The Musicians, Iron Workers, Operating Engineers and Horseshoers<br>
join 33 other organizations that have been recognized.<br>
<br>
BEVERLY A BAD BET FOR VA -- The Department of Veterans Affairs<br>
overlooked vehement protests by the Service Employees and has<br>
awarded Beverly Enterprises a multistate nursing home contract.<br>
SEIU had urged the VA not to accept Beverly's bid, citing the<br>
company's dismal record and long history of labor violations.<br>
<br>
ALL ABOARD TCU -- Members of the Transportation Communications<br>
Union overwhelmingly ratified agreements with the nation's major<br>
freight railroads that will yield 16.9 percent wage increases by<br>
the end of the century. The pacts, covering clerks and carmen, also<br>
provide for post-contract cost-of-living adjustments every six<br>
months, no rule concessions and, in 1999, improved health care and<br>
dental benefits and a new vision plan.<br>
<br>
MEANY RUNS &quot;MILE&quot; -- The George Meany Center for Labor Studies<br>
is making it easier for students to transfer labor-education course<br>
credits to four-year colleges in Maryland. The Center's new<br>
Maryland Institute for Labor Education (MILE) was unveiled Friday<br>
in a ceremony featuring AFL-CIO President Sweeney and Maryland Gov.<br>
Paris Glendening, a former college professor who called MILE a<br>
national model of partnership among labor, government and the<br>
private sector. MILE will work closely with colleges, central labor<br>
councils and unionists throughout the state to offer and increase<br>
labor-related studies.<br>
<br>
AWARD-WINNING JOURNALISM -- David Elsila and Andrew Neather's<br>
examination of affirmative action in UAW's Solidarity garnered the<br>
1996 Max Steinbock Award in the ILCA's annual journalism contest.<br>
The award recognizes outstanding individual effort in exploring an<br>
issue of concern to working families, with particularly emphasis on<br>
the human spirit. For a complete list of all awards call the ILCA<br>
at 202/637-5068 or read it in the next AFL-CIO News.<br>
<br>
BACK TO SCHOOL -- The George Meany Labor Studies Center began<br>
its fall semester Sept. 10 with 29 different courses that will<br>
continue through December. Courses range from organizing,<br>
communications and negotiating to labor law and workplace violence.<br>
Contact the Center at 301/431-6400.</p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="/publ/publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
