<html>

<head>
<title>WIP 09/10/96 AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h3>Work in Progress</h3>
<p>-- Tuesday, September 10, 1996<br>
<br>
MAC STRIKERS VOTE -- Members of Machinists District 837 will<br>
vote Sept. 11 on a tentative contract that would end the three-<br>
month strike against McDonnell Douglas. The tentative agreement was<br>
reached late Sept. 6 after 30 hours of negotiations in the Capitol<br>
Hill office of Rep. Richard A. Gephardt (D-Mo.). The unprecedented<br>
involvement of Gephardt and Federal Mediation and Conciliation<br>
Service Director John Calhoun Wells, who personally led the talks,<br>
was one of the key factors in breaking the stalemate. Some 6,700<br>
workers have been out since June 5 over the key issues of job<br>
security and outsourcing.<br>
<br>
COOKING WITH GAS -- The Steelworkers ratified a new six-year<br>
contract ending a bitter five-month lockout of 372 employees at<br>
Boston's Commonwealth Gas Co., in which the company cut off wages<br>
and health benefits. The key issues were health care insurance,<br>
contracting out and wages, according to Lowell Alexander, president<br>
of USWA Local 12004. Workers gained a flat rate for health-care<br>
premiums, a cost-of-living wage increase and job security on most<br>
live gas lines.<br>
<br>
LET IT GROW -- From bus drivers to dancers to pet food<br>
workers, some 2,500 workers decided to sport the union label in a<br>
half-dozen recent elections. Here's a rundown:<br>
<br>
YES, WE CAN -- Workers at the Atwater Canning Co. in Modesto,<br>
Calif., voted 349-273 for Teamsters representation. The win was<br>
part of a renewed drive by the workers to improve benefits, working<br>
conditions and wages in the industry.<br>
<br>
MORE THAN 57 AT HEINZ -- More than 700 production and<br>
maintenance workers at the Heinz Pet Products plant in Philadelphia<br>
voted to be represented by Food and Commercial Workers Local 38.<br>
<br>
BUS DRIVERS' ROUTE TO VICTORY -- The Steelworkers won their<br>
organizing drive to represent 430 Nashville school bus drivers. The<br>
workers organized around stronger safety measures, an end to<br>
overcrowding and unfair distribution of routes and fairer treatment<br>
for workers by the school district.<br>
<br>
DANCERS STEP TO SEIU -- Exotic dancers at San Francisco's<br>
Lusty Lady Theater voted 57-15 for Service Employees<br>
representation. Like other workers, the dancers, bouncers and other<br>
support staff are concerned with seniority, shift scheduling,<br>
working conditions, health insurance and wages.<br>
<br>
UNIONIZE THE PRIVATIZED -- SEIU Local 503 will represent<br>
workers whose jobs have been moved from the public sector to the<br>
private. Joining Local 503 are 120 direct-care workers at the<br>
Oregon Supported Living Program in Eugene and 45 direct-care<br>
workers at a group home in Corvallis.<br>
<br>
R-E-S-P-E-C-T WHAT THE UNION MEANS TO ME -- Dania Nursing Home<br>
in Miami finally won the respect they were seeking as they voted<br>
32-10 for UNITE. &quot;Workers are fed up with the way management treats<br>
them at Dania and they proved that they aren't going to take it<br>
anymore,&quot; said John Belizaire, a UNITE organizer.<br>
<br>
UAW IN DRIVER'S SEAT, AND BACK SEAT -- Workers at Findlay<br>
Industries in West Carrollton, Ohio, voted for UAW representation.<br>
The 316 hourly workers build seats for the Chevy Blazer.<br>
<br>
THEY'RE BACK, NASTY AS EVER -- Returning from a monthlong<br>
congressional recess, the GOP continued its unprecedented attack on<br>
workers. The first shot may be an amendment to the Senate's Labor-<br>
HHS appropriations bill to ban &quot;official time&quot; for union<br>
representatives to spend on labor-management partnership programs<br>
and other permitted representational activities at the Social<br>
Security Administration and the Health Care Financing<br>
Administration. The second volley could be an amendment to the<br>
Treasury-Postal spending bill that would ban official time<br>
throughout the government. Call 1-800-LABOR21 and tell your<br>
senators to oppose this blatant and partisan attack on workers'<br>
rights.<br>
<br>
LABOR'S LIGHT SHINES -- In New York City on Saturday, 100,000<br>
workers presented a spirited, diverse affirmation of trade unionism<br>
at one of the largest Labor Day Parades in years. Labor Day this<br>
year prompted lots of praise and damnation for the resurgent labor<br>
movement. &quot;Labor's engagement takes place against a backdrop of a<br>
rejuvenated and more confident union movement, one that has made<br>
gains in organizing, one that has seen the political tides<br>
apparently turn in its favor,&quot; the St. Louis Post Dispatch stated.<br>
&quot;Americans like winners and the sight of successful labor<br>
leadership has begun to alter a stagnant image,&quot; reported the<br>
Atlanta Journal and Constitution. &quot;Even its adversaries consider<br>
the AFL-CIO's sophisticated advertising and grassroots lobbying<br>
campaign for the minimum wage a major achievement,&quot; said Newsday.<br>
A lengthy Associated Press profile of the AFL-CIO's new activism<br>
appeared in newspapers coast to coast. <br>
<br>
EYEING ERGONOMICS -- Sen. Judd Gregg (R-N.H.) is expected to<br>
offer an amendment to ban the Occupational Safety and Health<br>
Administration from issuing any new ergonomics standards when the<br>
Senate Appropriations Committee, or the labor subcommittee, marks<br>
up the FY 1997 Labor/HHS spending bill Sept. 10 and 12. Ironically,<br>
the Gingrich-controlled House voted to strip such a ban from its<br>
version of the bill. Call your senators (1-800-LABOR21) and tell<br>
them to oppose any ban on ergonomics protections.<br>
<br>
PLUGGED NICKLES -- Angry workers from Oklahoma flooded Senate<br>
offices with phone calls, FAXes and letters to protest a move by<br>
Sen. Don Nickles (R-Okla.) to waive the Davis-Bacon prevailing wage<br>
law for reconstruction of the Oklahoma City Federal Building. The<br>
outpouring, a threatened veto and certain defeat apparently gave<br>
long-time fair-wage foe Nickles second thoughts, and the word is he<br>
will drop his effort. Following the April 19, 1995, explosion that<br>
claimed 168 lives, building and construction trades workers toiled<br>
tirelessly, and sometimes voluntarily, to find survivors, recover<br>
bodies and stabilize the building.<br>
<br>
W. VA. TOYOTA PLANT UNION-MADE -- A project labor agreement<br>
covering construction of a $400 million Toyota Motor manufacturing<br>
plant in Buffalo, W. Va., has been reached. The agreement was<br>
signed by Skilton Construction Co., the AFL-CIO Building and<br>
Construction Trades Department and 15 international unions, the<br>
Charleston Building and Construction Trades Council and its<br>
affiliated unions. Work is expected to begin in the next few weeks<br>
and will provide several hundred jobs for construction workers for<br>
the next two years.<br>
<br>
WORKING TOGETHER -- Three Government Employees locals and a<br>
Fire Fighters local will receive National Partnership Awards at the<br>
White House Wednesday. The unions are part of labor-management<br>
teams at federal agencies that worked together to improve delivery<br>
of customer service. The AFGE locals represent workers at the U.S.<br>
Mint, U.S. Department of Education and the Defense Distribution<br>
Depot, and the IAFF represents firefighters at the U.S. Army<br>
Armaments Research Development and Engineering Center.<br>
<br>
AROUND THE WORLD -- This week, AFL-CIO Secretary-Treasurer<br>
Richard Trumka will be in Great Britain meeting with the Trade<br>
Union Congress. On the other side of the world, Executive Vice<br>
President Linda Chavez-Thompson will speak to workers at the<br>
Frontier Hotel in Las Vegas, who will have been on strike for five<br>
years as of Sept. 21.<br>
<br>
D.C. JANITORS SEEK COMMON CENTS -- Hundreds of workers joined<br>
AFL-CIO Executive Vice President Linda Chavez-Thompson and SEIU<br>
President Andy Stern in a march through downtown Washington Sept.<br>
4 to support 2,000 janitors whose contracts expire Sept. 30. The<br>
janitors' fall campaign, &quot;A Penny for Justice,&quot; highlights the fact<br>
that &quot;it would only cost pennies to give the workers fair wages and<br>
health insurance,&quot; Stern told the crowd. The janitors held another<br>
rally Sept. 6 at National Airport to call attention to the unfair<br>
treatment and wages janitors receive from the airport cleaning<br>
services contractor, Priem Inc.<br>
<br>
BAD APPLES IN NEW YORK -- As a recent series of raids at<br>
Brooklyn garment makers highlights, New York continues to lead the<br>
nation in the number of garment worker wage and hour violations and<br>
in the total amount of back wages collected on behalf of garment<br>
workers. In the period between April 1 and June 30, 56 violations<br>
were uncovered, resulting in $310,347 in back wages for 1,134<br>
workers. The Flatbush raids included one shop linked to the<br>
celebrity Kathy Ireland line sold in Kmart.<br>
<br>
BOSSES: &quot;I SPY&quot; -- Employees are being increasingly spied upon<br>
and monitored at work. So the American Civil Liberties Union<br>
launched its &quot;Campaign for Fairness in the Workplace&quot; with the<br>
release of a 12-minute video and a white paper report that<br>
documents this growing abuse. The educational video, &quot;Through the<br>
Keyhole: Privacy in the Workplace -- An Endangered Right,&quot;<br>
documents a hotel worker who was secretly videotaped while dressing<br>
and undressing in the men's locker room and other abuses. The<br>
report is available on the World Wide Web at http:\\www.aclu.org or<br>
call 212/944-9800.<br>
<br>
HEALTH COMMISSION PRAISED -- Workers hailed President<br>
Clinton's creation of a national commission on health care quality,<br>
with AFL-CIO President John Sweeney calling it a &quot;concrete step<br>
that, by protecting consumers in the often-confusing and coercive<br>
health care situation of today, should lessen their anxiety and<br>
make their lives a little easier.&quot;<br>
<br>
JOBLESS RATE FALLS -- Unemployment fell from 5.4 percent to<br>
5.1 percent in August, the lowest level in seven years. Employment<br>
rose by 250,000, 10 percent of that in manufacturing, a sector led<br>
by motor vehicle and equipment fabrication. Including underutilized<br>
labor, the rate was 9.3 percent, or 12.7 million workers.<br>
<br>
HOW TIME FLIES -- Four unions that have recently celebrated or<br>
are looking forward to centennial anniversaries have been added to<br>
the Labor Department's Century of Service Honor Roll. The<br>
Musicians, Iron Workers, Operating Engineers and Horseshoers join<br>
33 other organizations that have been recognized.<br>
<br>
BRICK BUY BRICK -- Union organizations and rank-and-file<br>
members can buy pieces of the &quot;Hitting the Bricks&quot; 1995 Strike<br>
Memorial to commemorate the Machinists' victory against Boeing.<br>
Personalized bricks for individuals are $69 -- one dollar for every<br>
day of the 1995 strike -- and $321 or one dollar for each day<br>
District 751 has been on strike to date for labor organizations.<br>
The metal sculpture, featuring an eternal flame in the burn barrel,<br>
will be erected in front of the new union hall across from the<br>
Boeing plant in Everett, Wash. Mail your check or money order to<br>
Hittin' the Bricks Memorial, 9125 15th Place S., Seattle, Wash.<br>
98108.</p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="/publ/publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
<hr>
