HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.1
Date: Saturday, 15-Feb-97 08:34:12 GMT
Last-modified: Tuesday, 11-Feb-97 21:16:28 GMT
Content-length: 11756
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3O/DTD HTML//EN">

<html>
<head>
<title>WIP 09/05/96 AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<h3>AFL-CIO Work in Progress</h3>
<p>-- Thursday, September 5, 1996<br>
<br>
DEMOCRATIC REVIVAL -- Labor took its &quot;America Needs A
Raise&quot;<br>
campaign to the floor and to the podium at the Democratic
National<br>
Convention in Chicago as sign-waving, demonstrating delegates<br>
greeted AFL-CIO President John Sweeney, who assailed corporate<br>
irresponsibility while embracing President Clinton and Vice<br>
President Gore as fighters for working families. &quot;Our idea
of a<br>
just society is one in which honest labor raises the standard of<br>
living for all, rather than enormous wealth for a few,&quot; he
said.<br>
<br>
FIGHTING FOR JUSTICE -- Sweeney and Secretary-Treasurer<br>
Richard Trumka put their bodies on the line in Detroit Aug. 30
when<br>
they were arrested for barring the doors at the Detroit News
during<br>
a protest in support of striking workers. The same day, more than<br>
100 trade unionists rallied at the Columbus (Ga.)
Ledger-Inquirer,<br>
which is owned by Miami-based Knight-Ridder, parent of the
Detroit<br>
Free Press, the other struck paper.<br>
<br>
GOP LIES ON MEDICARE -- Sweeney unveiled a new round of AFL-<br>
CIO ads aimed at 27 members of Congress who voted to slash<br>
Medicare, but who now deny it. &quot;Republicans in Congress are
running<br>
shamefully dishonest television commercials falsely claiming<br>
Medicare benefits would increase under the proposals,&quot;
Sweeney told<br>
a news conference Aug. 28. Pollster Geoff Garin, appearing with<br>
Sweeney, presented numbers that show union members overwhelmingly<br>
support the AFL-CIO campaign to educate workers about their
issues.<br>
As the nation's attention turns back to school, the federation<br>
today begins airing ads about efforts by some legislators to cut<br>
student loans.<br>
<br>
PRESIDENTIAL INTERVENTION -- A top priority of the labor<br>
movement over the next two months is to re-elect President
Clinton,<br>
Machinists President George Kourpias told a progressive policy<br>
forum in Chicago sponsored by the Campaign for America's Future.<br>
&quot;The labor movement could not have withstood the assault by
GOP<br>
leaders if the president had not intervened to defend working<br>
families,&quot; he said. Kourpias, who joined Clinton for one leg
of his<br>
train trip to Chicago, urged activists to help Clinton gain a<br>
Congress he can work with.<br>
<br>
WORKING WOMEN'S VOTE -- Women who declined to participate in<br>
1994 out of anger and alienation could be the key constituency to<br>
electing candidates who care about working families, said Karen<br>
Nussbaum, director of the AFL-CIO Working Women's Department.<br>
Nussbaum announced in Chicago that union women will reach out to<br>
all working women during Working Women Vote Week, Oct. 5-11. For<br>
more information, contact the department at 202/637-5087.<br>
<br>
WORKERS FLEX MUSCLES AT ROADMASTER -- Workers at Roadmaster<br>
Corp. in Opelika, Ala., gave the exercise equipment plant a
workout<br>
when they voted 343-150 for UNITE. &quot;The company tried every
trick<br>
in the book to keep the workers from forming a union, but this<br>
crowd stood tough and stayed focused on justice,&quot; said Joe
Gaines,<br>
a UNITE organizer.<br>
<br>
WALKED RIGHT IN, STEPPED RIGHT UP -- Host Marriott workers at<br>
Bradley Airport in Hartford, Conn., walked in on their employer
and<br>
requested union recognition. The company refused to take the<br>
petition from the workers and told them to take it up with the<br>
National Labor Relations Board. A majority of the Latino workers<br>
have signed up for representation by the Hotel Employees and<br>
Restaurant Employees Local 217.<br>
<br>
COMAIR FLIES WITH IBT -- Flight attendants at ComAir, a<br>
regional commuter airline owned partially by Delta Air Lines,
voted<br>
for Teamsters representation. The flight attendants sought IBT<br>
representation because of dissatisfaction with wages and working<br>
conditions. The workers are based in Cincinnati and Orlando, Fla.<br>
<br>
LABOR DAY -- As Americans relaxed for the holiday weekend the<br>
labor movement earned, labor itself was on the move. AFL-CIO<br>
President John Sweeney saluted the drive for justice in the<br>
strawberry fields in an address to the Farm Workers convention<br>
Sunday before flying to Detroit for Monday's Labor Day rally in<br>
support of striking newspaper workers. Also Monday, he joined<br>
President Clinton for a Labor Day picnic in Green Bay, Wis., and
a<br>
rally in Milwaukee. Secretary-Treasurer Richard Trumka was in<br>
Chicago on Labor Day to help the Chicago AFL-CIO celebrate its<br>
100th anniversary. Executive Vice President Linda Chavez-Thompson<br>
attended the Peter J. McGuire Labor Day observance in New Jersey<br>
Friday before heading to Los Angeles for the Labor Day festival
on<br>
Monday. Sweeney will be in New York next Saturday for the annual<br>
Labor Day Parade. <br>
<br>
BACK TO SCHOOL WITH UNION -- The classified staff at St.<br>
Genevieve R-2 School District in Missouri voted 45-16 for the
AFT.<br>
The unit will represent school secretaries, teacher and library<br>
aides, custodians, maintenance personnel, volunteer coordinators,<br>
school nurses, cafeteria workers and parents as teachers.<br>
<br>
FAMILIES IN CRISIS -- At a domestic policy forum Aug. 26<br>
sponsored by the National Policy Council, Sweeney joined<br>
conversations with American families via satellite. Among them:<br>
Kate Hartley, 83, a West Virginia widow struggling to get along
on<br>
Medicare and frightened that Congress would cut benefits. Another<br>
voice came from Garrett Zwack, a retired meatpacker and UFCW<br>
member at John Morrell and Co. in Sioux Falls, S.D., whose
monthly<br>
pension check was cut to $500, and whose health benefits were
taken<br>
away entirely.<br>
<br>
&quot;ALL PAIN, NO GAIN&quot; -- Despite job growth during the
1990s,<br>
the typical American family still faces considerable economic
pain,<br>
according to a report released Labor Day by the Economic Policy<br>
Institute. The State of Working America, 1996-97, finds that all<br>
but the top 20 percent of male earners and most female earners
saw<br>
their hourly wages decline between 1989 and 1995. Since middle-<br>
class workers pay the same proportion of their income in taxes as<br>
they did in the late 1970s, &quot;the rise in inequality and fall
in<br>
living standards reflect what employers aren't putting into<br>
paychecks, not what government is taking out in taxes,&quot; EPI<br>
stresses.<br>
<br>
FIRESTONE FALLOUT -- Bridgestone/Firestone, singled out as a<br>
corporate outlaw by President Sweeney in his speech to the<br>
Democratic convention, was the target of Labor Day rallies in
major<br>
cities across the country. Two years ago, the Japanese-owned<br>
company illegally discharged 2,300 striking Rubber Workers, now<br>
Steelworkers. More than 400 USWA members are still out of work<br>
while those back on the job are without the protection of a<br>
contract.<br>
<br>
BOSTON NURSES GAIN PACT -- Nurses formerly employed at Boston<br>
City Hospital have reached a 15-month pact with Boston Medical<br>
Center, formed by a merger between their hospital and Boston<br>
University Medical Center. The 800 registered and licensed<br>
practical nurses, members of Service Employees Local 285, will<br>
receive pay increases of between $1,000 and $6,000, will carry
over<br>
public pension credits, are eligible for full health insurance if<br>
they choose a designated HMO and will have bumping, recall and<br>
other layoff protection. The pact follows one negotiated for<br>
nonprofessional employees represented by Local 285 and AFSCME.<br>
<br>
NO WAY-VER -- The White House is not buying a bid by opponents<br>
of Davis-Bacon who are trying to get a proposed Senate amendment<br>
that would waive prevailing-wage provisions for reconstruction of<br>
the Oklahoma City Federal Building. The Labor Department said<br>
flatly last week that the Clinton administration is opposed to<br>
waiving Davis-Bacon provisions, and hinted strongly that any bill<br>
carrying waiver language would be vetoed.<br>
<br>
MARYLAND RIPE -- AFSCME Maryland and the Teamsters filed<br>
election petitions on Aug. 21, the first day state employees were<br>
eligible to petition for a collective bargaining representation<br>
election. AFSCME filed election petitions for four bargaining
units<br>
covering 20,000 state employees in labor and trade, health and<br>
human services, social and human services and public safety and<br>
security. The last unit was filed by the United Corrections and<br>
Public Safety Employees of Maryland, a coalition of AFSCME and
IBT.<br>
<br>
ASBESTOS REVISION -- The Occupational Safety and Health<br>
Administration has issued corrections and clarifications to its<br>
final asbestos standards for general industry, construction and<br>
shipyard work to strengthen employee information efforts and<br>
tighten training standards. The changes were published in the
Aug.<br>
23 Federal Register and are effective Sept. 23.<br>
<br>
NOT TOO LATE TO SAVE YOUR SKIN -- The Building and<br>
Construction Trades Department is co-sponsoring a workshop Sept.<br>
15-17 on How to Save Your Skin: Preventing Skin Problems in the<br>
Construction Industry, at the Dupont Plaza Hotel in Washington.
For<br>
more information, call 202/842-7840.<br>
<br>
THE HOUSE THAT LABOR BUILT -- The Teamsters, Painters and<br>
Carpenters have designated the week of Sept. 2 as &quot;Labor for<br>
Habitat Week.&quot; Following a national convention in Atlanta,
Aug. 30-<br>
Sept. 1, Habitat for Humanity International and union volunteers<br>
will participate in a 20-house &quot;Blitz Build&quot; in
Americus, Ga.<br>
<br>
CHILD LABOR CONFAB -- The Child Labor Coalition will host its<br>
second biennial conference on Sept. 8-10 at the Embassy Row Hotel<br>
in Washington. The conference will include a keynote address by<br>
Labor Secretary Robert Reich, along with discussions on trade and<br>
child labor, and lessons learned from the RUGMARK and Foul Ball<br>
campaigns. For more information, contact Sally Moore at 202/835-<br>
3323.<br>
<br>
WORKING WOMEN'S SUMMITS -- The Women's Bureau will launch<br>
&quot;Working Women's Summits&quot; throughout September on
family-friendly<br>
policies that can improve workers' morale and company profits.
The<br>
summits will be held Sept. 4 at Westchester Community College in<br>
Valhalla, N.Y.; Sept. 5 at Sheraton University City in<br>
Philadelphia; Sept. 10 at Palace of Fine Arts Theatre in San<br>
Francisco; Sept. 12 at the University of Washington Conference
Hall<br>
in Seattle; Sept. 17 at several sites, including Denver and the<br>
University of Missouri at Kansas City; Sept. 19 at the Holiday
Inn<br>
Pyramid in Albuquerque, N.M.; Sept. 25 at the Lansing Center in<br>
Lansing, Mich.; and Sept. 27 at the Holiday Inn in Tampa, Fla.
For<br>
more information, call the bureau at 202/219-6606.<br>
<br>
For details of these and other stories, check out the News and<br>
Views library on LaborNET (CompuServe), or the AFL-CIO web page
at<br>
http:\\www.aflcio.org. To receive Work in Progress, or to submit<br>
information, FAX to 202/508-6908.</p>
