<html>
<head>
<title>WIP 08/27/96 AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<h3>AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS</h3>
<p>-- TUESDAY, AUGUST 27, 1996<br>
<br>
A PLACE IN THE HALL -- Working families are well represented<br>
at the Democratic Convention this week in Chicago, with more than<br>
800 delegates who are members of AFL-CIO unions. Combined with<br>
delegates from the unaffiliated National Education Association,<br>
union delegates constitute one-fourth of the 4,320 convention<br>
delegates. Workers set the tone for the convention with an
&quot;America<br>
Needs A Raise&quot; rally at noon Monday in front of the State of<br>
Illinois building, where thousands joined AFL-CIO President John<br>
Sweeney to put working family issues front and center. Sweeney
also<br>
will address the convention on Wednesday night.<br>
<br>
GORE: WE'RE ON YOUR SIDE -- Vice President Gore told a<br>
cheering, chanting labor meeting Sunday that he and President<br>
Clinton would continue their fight for working families into
their<br>
second term. Gore and Labor Secretary Robert Reich praised the
new<br>
vitality and energy of the labor movement and credited labor's<br>
aggressive campaign with forcing the Dole-Gingrich forces to seek<br>
to hide their extremist platform, which, if enacted, would
decimate<br>
workers' rights and programs. Chants of &quot;Four More
Years&quot; rocked<br>
the room.<br>
<br>
MAXIMUM VICTORY -- Giving credit to organized labor's push to<br>
raise the minimum wage, President Clinton signed the 90-cent-an-<br>
hour increase into law last week. He noted that while the vast<br>
majority of union workers earn far above the wage floor, unions<br>
fought for the hike because &quot;it was the right thing to
do.&quot; Before<br>
going to the White House for the signing ceremony, some two dozen<br>
low- and minimum-wage workers and their children lunched at
AFL-CIO<br>
headquarters, where President Sweeney noted that no one thought
the<br>
minimum wage could be raised until they and their unions
&quot;pushed<br>
your members of Congress.&quot;<br>
<br>
GOOD NEWS, BAD NEWS -- Clinton also signed legislation making<br>
it easier for workers to carry their health insurance from job to<br>
job and harder for insurance companies to deny coverage for pre-<br>
existing conditions. Sweeney said it was a good first step, but<br>
&quot;the still serious and unmet need for broad health care
reform&quot;<br>
must be addressed. Sweeney had urged Clinton to veto a welfare<br>
reform measure, but the president signed it anyway, casting many<br>
poor families to the mercies of uneven state &quot;workfare&quot;
programs.<br>
This kind of change in the system &quot;will only serve to
undermine the<br>
value of work for all American families and reduce our overall<br>
standard of living,&quot; said Andy Stern, president of the
Service<br>
Employees.<br>
<br>
TAKING THE FIGHT HOME -- UNITE member Yamil Lopez stood behind<br>
Clinton at the minimum wage signing ceremony and then went home
to<br>
fight for workers at the Hebrew Home in North Miami, Fla.
&quot;The<br>
raise in the minimum wage is a good beginning, but we still have
a<br>
long way to go,&quot; said Lopez. &quot;Even those who make above
the new<br>
minimum wage are struggling to survive. Here at the Hebrew Home
we<br>
can't even afford health care for our families.&quot;<br>
<br>
UAW SHOWS $OLIDARITY -- The UAW showed true solidarity with<br>
striking Detroit newspaper workers, presenting each of the 2,000<br>
strikers with a $150 check for the fourth time since the strike<br>
began July 13, 1995. &quot;I do not know of any other
demonstration of<br>
support of this magnitude that has been bestowed by an<br>
international to individual workers. . . . Thank you from the<br>
bottom of our hearts,&quot; Newspaper Guild President Linda Foley
wrote<br>
to UAW President Stephen P. Yokich.<br>
<br>
ROLL UP YOUR SLEEVES -- Volunteer organizers in Steelworkers<br>
District 7 pitched in to help organize a group of 160 workers at<br>
MEG Corp. in Cambridge City, Ind. The volunteers helped
house-call<br>
more than half of the work force, telling them about the
advantages<br>
of belonging to a union.<br>
<br>
IT'S THE MEMBERS, STUPID -- Union members overwhelmingly<br>
support the drive to educate union members and the public on<br>
legislators' stands on such key worker issues as Medicare,<br>
pensions, education and the minimum wage, a new poll shows.<br>
Republicans had charged, using trumped-up figures, that union<br>
members did not support the AFL-CIO's Labor `96 campaign.
Seventy-<br>
two percent approve the federation's television and radio ads,<br>
while 67 percent have a positive reaction to the AFL-CIO's
overall<br>
campaign, the media push and grass-roots mobilization in<br>
congressional districts. Only 11 percent react negatively. Only
17<br>
percent of those surveyed said they would be more likely to
support<br>
a candidate who has solidly backed Newt Gingrich's GOP agenda in<br>
Congress. The survey was conducted Aug. 2-4 by Peter D. Hart<br>
Research Associates. Summaries are available by calling 202/637-<br>
5041.<br>
<br>
UNSTOPPABLE SEIU -- The Service Employees continue to win<br>
economic justice and dignity for workers, raking up four
victories<br>
in the Midwest and on the West Coast. Health care professionals
at<br>
Peoples Community Care Residence in St. Paul voted for SEIU<br>
representation. In Gary, Ind., a unit of 37 city emergency
medical<br>
workers voted for the union. The R.N. units at Los Robles
Hospital<br>
in the San Fernando Valley voted 167-104 for SEIU. And in
Seattle,<br>
District 925 won an election for 27 patient account reps and
other<br>
employees at Children's University Medical Group.<br>
<br>
CLOSING ON THE REOPENER -- Miners won improvements in pension<br>
benefits, health insurance and wages in a new deal with the<br>
Bituminous Coal Operators Association. A reopener clause in the<br>
1993 contract paved the way for the new agreement that will
affect<br>
about 100,000 pensioners and 40,000 miners. UMWA and BCOA agreed
to<br>
begin bargaining next year in an attempt to reach a new agreement<br>
before this pact expires August 30, 1998.<br>
<br>
A HEALTHY PACT -- The Laborers and the Johns Hopkins<br>
University School of Public Health have joined forces for a five-<br>
year study to identify and address occupational safety and health<br>
hazards of construction and environmental cleanup.<br>
<br>
HAIL NO -- Millionaire Washington Redskins owner Jack Kent<br>
Cooke is trying to weasel out of paying construction workers<br>
prevailing wages on the team's new football stadium in Landover,<br>
Md. The Maryland attorney general issued a decision requiring<br>
prevailing wages on the project, but Cooke's lawyers took the<br>
decision to court. &quot;The Redskins should not want to operate
by a<br>
lower standard for your construction team,&quot; Building and<br>
Construction Trades President Robert Georgine told Cooke.<br>
<br>
USWA GETS BIG SAY -- The Steelworkers reached tentative<br>
agreement on an innovative four-year contract with Northwestern<br>
Steel and Wire Co. that gives the workers decision- making<br>
authority in all aspects of the business. In addition to gaining
a<br>
member of the board of directors, the union will have access to<br>
most of the company's business plans and financial data.<br>
<br>
FIFA SCORES GOAL -- The International Federation of Football<br>
Associations will make sure that their logo only appears on
soccer<br>
balls that are not made by child labor. The AFL-CIO's Executive<br>
Council had urged FIFA not to put their stamp of approval on any<br>
soccer ball made by child labor. Some 35 million soccer balls are<br>
made every year, mostly in Pakistan and other Third World<br>
countries, and about 80 percent of the balls imported into the<br>
United States are hand-stitched by children 5-14 years old.<br>
<br>
A ONE-TWO-THREE PUNCH -- Employees of Precision Castparts<br>
Corp. in Portland, Ore., will be armed with triple protection as<br>
the Steelworkers, UAW and Machinists begin a joint organizing
drive<br>
in the plant stemming from the unification talks that will merge<br>
the three unions in 2000.<br>
<br>
BOLD CHINA PATTERN -- For the first time, the U.S. trade<br>
deficit with China ($3.2 billion in June) exceeded that with
Japan,<br>
reflecting a continued but largely unreported surge in imports
from<br>
a country that uses forced and low-wage labor. Closer to home,
the<br>
gold rush south by U.S. corporations helped to create a
merchandise<br>
trade deficit with Mexico of $8.3 billion for the first six
months<br>
of the year, $600 million greater than in the same part of 1995.<br>
<br>
DISCOVER RHODE ISLAND -- Before the federal minimum wage<br>
increases, Rhode Island's working poor will get some relief Sept.<br>
1 when the state's minimum wage rises from $4.45 to $4.75 an
hour,<br>
and again to $5.15 next Jan. 1. Under the bill, the maximum<br>
allowance for gratuities in businesses like hotels and
restaurants<br>
will increase from 35 percent to 50 percent, with a minimum cash<br>
wage of $2.89 an hour. The income boost &quot;is a step toward
making<br>
sure that people who make minimum wage don't live in
poverty,&quot;<br>
state AFL-CIO Secretary-Treasurer George Nee said.<br>
<br>
CWA, GTE AGREE -- The Communications Workers ratified a<br>
statewide, three-year contract providing wage increases totaling
9<br>
percent for some 9,000 GTE California employees. The first raise,<br>
3 percent, is retroactive to March 17, when the prior contract<br>
expired. The workers also will be eligible for &quot;performance
team<br>
awards,&quot; that could total as much as 3 percent of their
salary for<br>
meeting certain company operations goals.<br>
<br>
MUNCHKIN POWER -- Mickey Carroll, who played a munchkin in the<br>
film, The Wizard of Oz, recently presented a $1,500 check to the<br>
Machinists on strike at McDonnell Douglas and posed for photos<br>
while carrying a picket sign. &quot;I'm for labor,&quot; said
Carroll, 77,<br>
who owns a St. Louis tombstone business. &quot;Everytime I go by
the<br>
picket line, I yell and stick my thumb up.&quot;<br>
<br>
NEITHER RAIN NOR SLEET -- Nearly 3,000 Postal Workers took to<br>
L.A.'s streets in an awesome demonstration at the boycotted New<br>
Otani Hotel, an organizing target of Hotel Employees and
Restaurant<br>
Employees Local 11. The delegates to APWU's 13th biennial<br>
convention met up with HERE members at City Hall and, under a<br>
blazing southern California sun, walked a seven-block circuit to<br>
the hotel, boisterously shouting and chanting, &quot;The boycott
united<br>
will never be defeated.&quot;<br>
<br>
BLAST SPARKS RECONSIDERATION -- An April 1995 explosion that<br>
killed five workers at a union-represented chemical firm has<br>
prompted OSHA to review its list of hazardous chemicals. The<br>
explosion at Napp Technologies in Lodi, N.J., occurred when four<br>
chemicals not covered under the standard exploded while being
mixed<br>
-- an act also not covered by OSHA's process safety management<br>
standard. The former Clothing and Textile Workers represented<br>
workers at the now-closed plant.<br>
<br>
WORKPLACE VIOLENCE -- The George Meany Center for Labor<br>
Studies is offering a one week course on Dealing with Workplace<br>
Violence Oct. 13-18 -- at the center's Silver Spring, Md.,
campus.<br>
For more information call (301)431-5408.<br>
<br>
LABOR DAY HEROES -- &quot;Heroes, 3: Profiles from the American<br>
Workplace&quot; is a one-hour Labor Day special from the public<br>
television series &quot;We Do The Work.&quot; The show pays
tribute to<br>
ordinary people who take action in times of adversity and make<br>
extraordinary contributions to society through their work. Check<br>
your local PBS listings for air times.</p>
