<html>

<head>
<title>WIP 08/20/96 AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h3>AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS</h3>
<p>-- TUESDAY, AUGUST 20, 1996<br>
<br>
ATTACK ON TEACHERS _ While the GOP kept many of its anti-union<br>
attack dogs in check during the convention in San Diego last week,<br>
presidential nominee Bob Dole couldn't resist haranguing against<br>
teachers' unions in his acceptance speech. Back in 1965, Dole voted<br>
against the creation of the student loan program, and he has<br>
continued to vote against education programs _including last year,<br>
when he backed Newt Gingrich in cutting the education budget. Now<br>
he opens his campaign scapegoating teachers. &quot;He should be trying<br>
to bring parents and teachers together, not trying to divide them,&quot;<br>
AFT President Al Shanker said.<br>
<br>
HOW BIG IS THAT TENT? _ Convention honchos tried to present a<br>
face of diversity and moderation. But the numbers tell a different<br>
story. Out of almost 2,000 delegates, there were less than 100<br>
minority delegates. Two-thirds of the delegates were male and an<br>
astonishing 40 percent of the Republican delegates in San Diego had<br>
annual incomes of $500,000 or more. Not all of America needs a<br>
raise.<br>
<br>
DON'T STEP IN IT AGAIN _ Supply-side economics _ the heart and<br>
soul of Bob Dole's economic plans _ sent the nation's deficit<br>
soaring and the wage gap widening in the Reagan `80s. Under<br>
President Clinton, the budget deficit has fallen every year. The<br>
Congressional Budget Office reported last week that the deficit<br>
will drop to $116 billion this year, the lowest level since 1981.<br>
<br>
EARLY FRUIT, GOOD CROP _ The Machinists, with help from the<br>
UAW and Steelworkers, beat back an anti-union campaign against<br>
workers at the Maremount Corp. in Loudon, Tenn, winning a 369-272<br>
representative vote. The workers make automobile mufflers.<br>
<br>
HIGH-FIBER VICTORY _ Workers at the Fiber Sales and<br>
Development Corp. of Urbana, Ohio, voted by a 2-1 margin for<br>
Teamsters representation after a November 1995 vote was set aside<br>
by the National Labor Relations Board. The NLRB said the company<br>
had offered a reduction in employee-paid health care premiums in<br>
order to improperly influence the 1995 election. The employees make<br>
powdered cellulose for use as an additive in other products.<br>
<br>
BEARS, WILDCATS ROAR FOR SEIU _ Service Employees Local 236 in<br>
Chicago won representation rights for ushers employed by Safety<br>
Service Systems, including ushers for the Chicago Bears and the<br>
Northwestern Wildcats. SSS also granted recognition to 180 current<br>
SEIU members after taking over a contract for the now-defunct Andy<br>
Fain Co.<br>
<br>
DISSERVICEMASTER _ Workers at the state veterans' home in<br>
Anna, Ill., struck Aug. 10 after a yearlong struggle under the<br>
AFSCME banner for a first contract with ServiceMaster _ and have<br>
been replaced. Family members of residents have reported that<br>
replacement workers are not showing up _ and when they do, they<br>
lack qualifications and skills and are administering poor care,.<br>
The AFL-CIO Executive Council urged the state to get involved in<br>
the dispute.<br>
<br>
AFTRA CABLE READY _ The Television and Radio Artists have<br>
launched a $1.25 million drive to organize workers in the booming<br>
cable entertainment and news programming industry. AFTRA has cable<br>
network contracts with The Nashville Network, Home Box Office and<br>
E! Entertainment.<br>
<br>
SI SE PUEDE _ Shouts of &quot;Si se puede&quot; (Yes, We Can)<br>
reverberated at rallies in more than 10 cities on Aug. 14 as AFL-<br>
CIO Central Labor Councils kicked off their campaign in support of<br>
the Farm Workers effort to organize 20,000 strawberry pickers in<br>
California. Thousands of trade unionists joined the informational<br>
leafleting and visits to supermarkets to urge store managers to<br>
sign a pledge supporting the workers.<br>
<br>
NO REST _ Anti-worker lawmakers may have fled Washington for<br>
a month, but they're not getting any respite from the AFL-CIO's<br>
grass-roots education campaign. Radio and television ads lambasting<br>
GOP attempts last year to allow big business to raid workers'<br>
pension funds and urging enactment of legislation to protect 401(k)<br>
plans aired in 30 districts for two weeks. Materials documenting<br>
the county-by-county impact of the fiscal 1997 GOP budget cuts for<br>
such programs as Medicaid, Head Start, job training, nutrition<br>
programs and highway construction were sent to the federation's 135<br>
congressional district coordinators. And when President Clinton<br>
signs the minimum wage increase today, district activists will hold<br>
events to celebrate labor's success in winning the wage fight _ no<br>
thanks to the congressional Republican leadership.<br>
<br>
SHIPYARD STRIKERS GAIN HELP _ Some 1,800 striking workers at<br>
San Diego's National Shipbuilding Co. shipyard were bolstered early<br>
last week by visits first from AFL-CIO President John Sweeney and<br>
then from Secretary-Treasurer Richard Trumka. The yard performs<br>
contract work for the U.S. Navy _ and while the NASSCO CEO enjoys<br>
fat raises each year courtesy of U.S. taxpayers, the workers<br>
haven't had a raise since 1992. The strikers belong to the<br>
Ironworkers, Machinists, Electrical Workers, Carpenters, Painters,<br>
Operating Engineers and Teamsters. Donations to help them may be<br>
sent to: Solidarity Fund for NASSCO Workers, c/o San Diego-Imperial<br>
Counties Labor Council, AFL-CIO, 4265 Fairmount Ave., Suite 110,<br>
San Diego, Calif. 92105.<br>
<br>
`ALL CLEAR' IN THIS YARD _ Sweeney ended his week on a very<br>
different note at a Virginia shipyard, saluting a business-labor<br>
partnership at Newport News Shipbuilding to produce five double-<br>
hulled tankers. Union Labor Life Insurance Co. is one investor in<br>
the $240 million project, with union construction set to begin in<br>
1997. The tankers will be U.S.-flagged and U.S.-operated.<br>
<br>
MCDONNELL DOUGLAS STALLS TALKS _ McDonnell Douglas' refusal to<br>
offer job security protections stalled negotiations to settle the<br>
10-week strike between the Machinists and the aerospace giant. The<br>
union made new proposals to accommodate the company's need for job<br>
flexibility, with the clear expectation that the company would meet<br>
the workers' need for job security. The new talks followed a mass<br>
&quot;March for American Jobs&quot; by 10,000 people on McDonnell Douglas<br>
headquarters Aug. 11, led by AFL-CIO Secretary-Treasurer Richard L.<br>
Trumka and IAM President George Kourpias.<br>
<br>
LIUNA REBUILDS CHURCHES _ Members of Laborers Local 1177 in<br>
Baton Rouge, La., and community volunteers repaired or rebuilt<br>
three area churches that were desecrated by vandals in the recent<br>
rash of hate crimes against Southern black churches. LIUNA's<br>
national &quot;Rebuild, Prevent and Protect&quot; program was started at<br>
Sweet Home Baptist Church in Baker, La. LIUNA also donated funds to<br>
Cypress Grove Baptist Church in Zachary, La., to build a safety<br>
fence. The latest church to be repaired is St. Paul's Free Baptist<br>
Church, also in Baker.<br>
<br>
STRONG BONDS _ National religious leaders joined with<br>
community groups in Morganton, N.C., for a &quot;march for justice&quot; in<br>
support of workers on strike at Case Farm poultry plant because the<br>
company refuses to bargain with their union, the Laborers.<br>
<br>
SWEENEY'S TREATISE _ AFL-CIO President John Sweeney is the<br>
author of a new book, &quot;America Needs A Raise,&quot; a blunt account of<br>
America's economic troubles that presents the human face of<br>
American labor. Sweeney disects the realities of the global economy<br>
and argues that strong unions offer hope to all workers beset by<br>
economic insecurity. Copies are available in most bookstores or<br>
from Houghton Mifflin Co., 222 Berkeley St., Boston, Mass. 02116.<br>
<br>
GOING AGAINST CONVENTION _ Fancy digs at the plush San Diego<br>
Hilton Beach and Tennis Club couldn't keep Pennsylvania Gov. Tom<br>
Ridge (R) away from the problems back home. Members of the Service<br>
Employees, demanding that Ridge intervene in the ongoing Beverly<br>
Enterprises nursing home dispute, set up a picket line the governor<br>
had to pass through on his way to the convention.<br>
<br>
PUNCHING DOLE'S TICKET _ Teamsters were at the final<br>
shareholders meeting of Southern Pacific Rail Corp. in San<br>
Francisco Aug. 16 to protest the ties the carrier and its merger<br>
partner, Union Pacific Corp., have with Republican presidential<br>
nominee Bob Dole. During months leading to regulatory approval of<br>
the merger, the two carriers were the third-largest lobbying force<br>
in Washington, with 68 registered lobbyists, and UP's corporate PAC<br>
was the fifth largest donor to the Dole campaign. The merger is<br>
expected to cost 1,300 jobs in the Bay Area alone.<br>
<br>
IT'S IN THE CARDS _ The transfer of Union Privilege's<br>
MasterCard portfolio from Bank of New York (Delaware) to Household<br>
International was completed Monday. Household now will provide all<br>
customer service, send all bills and notices and make all credit<br>
decisions using its own approval criteria. Current cardholders will<br>
be receiving notification of the change starting this week.<br>
Household will offer to cardholders a deal to transfer balances<br>
from higher-interest cards and pay them off at the prime rate.<br>
<br>
CARPENTERS IN TRAINING _ In the second major agreement of its<br>
kind this year, the Carpenters have joined forces with the<br>
Ingersoll-Rand Architectural Hardware Division to improve training<br>
and standards in the construction industry. Ingersoll-Rand will<br>
provide technical support and training materials and will certify<br>
instructors and installers upon completion of the training. The UBC<br>
will provide the apprenticeship and training programs. The union<br>
had signed a similar agreement with Wilsonart.<br>
<br>
GAS WORKERS SETTLE _ The Utility Workers and Chemical Workers<br>
reached tentative agreement on a new two-year contract with<br>
Southern California Gas that protects against layoffs and raises<br>
salaries by 3 percent for 5,100 employees. The deal, worked out<br>
over 10 months of often-acrimonious talks, includes a 2.7 percent<br>
lump sum bonus after ratification and another 2.7 percent payment<br>
in 1997, the same year the wage increase begins. The company agreed<br>
not to lay off any full-time employee in the bargaining unit except<br>
for disciplinary reasons.<br>
<br>
CLINTON, YES. RUNYON, NO _ More than 8,000 delegates to the<br>
60th biennial Letter Carriers convention in Orlando, Fla., voted<br>
unanimously to endorse the Clinton/Gore ticket after Gore addressed<br>
the group via satellite. But the delegates voted no confidence in<br>
Postmaster General Marvin Runyon after NALC President Vincent<br>
Sombrotto told the convention &quot;tough times are ahead&quot; because of<br>
U.S. Postal Service attempts to privatize and implement other anti-<br>
union measures.<br>
<br>
SENDING REINFORCEMENTS _ In Las Vegas, the 39th Iron Workers<br>
convention added a new classification of workers to the union's<br>
official name _ reinforcing iron workers _ who join their brothers<br>
and sisters in the &quot;International Association of Bridge,<br>
Structural, Ornamental and Reinforcing Iron Workers.&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
HEAT WAVE<br>
<br>
Union Summer activists based in Atlanta will be working in<br>
Georgia and Alabama this week. They will demonstrate with the<br>
Communications Workers of America, hold an action in support of the<br>
Detroit Free Press and News workers, help the Georgia State<br>
Employees Union fight privatization, and go to Opelika, Alabama for<br>
an election with workers at Roadmaster, which makes exercise<br>
equipment.<br>
<br>
Boston Union Summer interns will hold an action with locked<br>
out Commonwealth Gas workers on Tuesday. They are helping organize<br>
a demonstration Thursday to create pressure on Budweiser, which has<br>
refused to give Teamster drivers a contract. On Friday, the interns<br>
will demonstrate at area malls with UNITE! in support of Peerless<br>
garment workers.<br>
<br>
In Denver, Union Summer activists will take to the road,<br>
visiting Grand Junction for a day on the UFCW picket line with<br>
striking City Market workers. They will join a picket of Lord &amp;<br>
Taylor at the Cherry Creek Mall in support of sweatshop workers.<br>
House and office visits to support the Justice for Janitors<br>
campaign are also ongoing.<br>
<br>
Union Summer interns in the City of the Angels will join in<br>
several actions this week. They will act as a human billboard to<br>
protest the privatization of Los Angeles County hospitals, meet<br>
with grocery store managers to build support for strawberry<br>
workers, and walk precincts to educate voters on the California<br>
Civil Rights Initiative, which would end all affirmative action<br>
programs in the state.<br>
<br>
This week Union Summer activists in Miami will hold a vigil to<br>
support the Miami Herald boycott, organize skycaps at the Miami<br>
International Airport with the International Association of<br>
Machinists, and hold a demonstration and news conference in support<br>
of farm workers at the Fort Lauderdale corporate headquarters of<br>
Hyde Park Supermarkets.<br>
<br>
Union Summer interns in Puerto Rico are organizing and<br>
conducting house visits with health care, pharmaceutical and<br>
governmental workers around the island with SEIU and AFSCME.<br>
<br>
Sacramento Union Summer interns celebrated a victory last<br>
week. Thanks in part to activists who picketed, leafleted and held<br>
other actions with Justice for Janitors, Somers Building<br>
Maintenance settled with the Service Employees International Union,<br>
reinstating several employees who had been unjustly suspended.<br>
<br>
Union Summer activists in Watsonville will continue their<br>
visits to strawberry fields to survey workers and inspect work<br>
sites. Their activities are prompting responses from strawberry<br>
field owners, who are staging their own anti-union protests and<br>
trying to create a &quot;pro-worker&quot; committee opposed to unionization.</p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="/publ/publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
