<html>

<head>
<title>WIP 08/13/96 AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h3>AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS</h3>
<p>-- AUGUST 13, 1996<br>
<br>
CHANGING THE WAY WE WORK _ AFL-CIO President John Sweeney<br>
continued his overhaul of the federation, naming three new<br>
department heads and other appointments at the Executive Council<br>
meeting in Chicago last week. Ron Blackwell, chief economist at<br>
UNITE, will head the new Department of Corporate Affairs that will<br>
expand the work the federation does to support union organizing and<br>
collective bargaining. Barbara Shailor, an assistant to Machinists<br>
President George Kourpias for trade and international finance, was<br>
named the federation's International Affairs Director. Bill<br>
Fletcher, who has headed SEIU's education and field services<br>
departments, was named the new AFL-CIO Education Director. Among<br>
Fletcher's first priorities will be helping to develop an ambitious<br>
program to educate all union members about workers and the economy.<br>
<br>
The Department of Corporate Affairs will feature three<br>
divisions: a Center for Strategic Research, headed by David Chu,<br>
former research director for the Service Employees; a Center for<br>
Worker Ownership and Governance, headed by Bill Patterson,<br>
corporate affairs specialist at the Teamsters; and a Center for<br>
Workplace Democracy, headed by Nancy Mills, who will serve as<br>
acting director. Mills previously worked on issues of workplace<br>
technology and change with SEIU. Dick Leonard, a 27-year activist<br>
for the Oil, Chemical and Atomic Workers, was named to direct<br>
strategic campaigns as an assistant director in the Department of<br>
Field Mobilization.<br>
<br>
MELROSE, PLACE FOR UNIONS _ The first resort contract ever in<br>
Carolina's coastal resort area was no television drama, it was a<br>
real life victory for resort workers and Union Summer activists.<br>
The Operating Engineers say their contract at Melrose Resort in<br>
Hilton Head, S.C., was due in large part to the persistent and<br>
creative pressure from Union Summer. The nation's press continues<br>
to chronicle the summer sojourn. A New York Times article last<br>
Friday quoted Yale sophomore Daniel Lang: &quot;This is great. I'm<br>
seeing the problems that workers face with my own eyes, and I'm<br>
seeing what unions are trying to do about it.&quot;<br>
<br>
DOLE TAXES CREDIBILITY _ Bob Dole's tax plan &quot;breaks new<br>
ground in its cynical attempt to woo voters with promises of<br>
economic well-being by providing tax breaks to the wealthy,&quot; the<br>
Executive Council charged. Similar supply-side policies of the<br>
1980s resulted in a record federal budget deficit and continue to<br>
threaten programs that serve working families. The council<br>
predicted that workers won't be fooled by &quot;a desperate effort by a<br>
flagging campaign to revisit the failed policies from which this<br>
country has just spent four years trying to overcome.&quot;<br>
<br>
FIBER BLOAT? _ &quot;I will fight the minimum wage with every fiber<br>
of my being,&quot; House Majority Leader Dick Armey (R-Texas) said a few<br>
months back. Last week, he got a chance to eat his words when<br>
Texas union members delivered 515 boxes (the minimum wage will be<br>
raised to $5.15) of high-fiber cereal to his Irving office. Maybe<br>
now he'll be just a regular guy.<br>
<br>
A CUT ABOVE AT KMART _ Meatcutters at a Super Kmart in Oakland<br>
became the first Kmart retail workers in the country to join a<br>
union. The workers voted 10-3 to join Food and Commercial Workers<br>
Local 120. The Teamsters and UNITE have gotten footholds in Kmart<br>
distribution centers, but the company remains virulently anti-<br>
union. The UFCW also used its member-based SPUR organizing program<br>
to enlist 500 new members at H&amp;M Food Systems in Dallas.<br>
<br>
WELCOME TO SAN DIEGO _ Republicans gathering in San Diego for<br>
the national convention Sunday were greeted by thousands of workers<br>
gathered in Balboa Park for an &quot;America Needs A Raise&quot; picnic and<br>
rally. AFL-CIO President John Sweeney told the group working<br>
families will demand that candidates protect pensions, Social<br>
Security, Medicare, prevailing wages and the 40-hour week. Pension<br>
protection is the topic of a new round of AFL-CIO TV and radio ads<br>
that highlight votes to allow corporations to raid pensions. Over<br>
the weekend, the federation also began the member mobilization<br>
phase of its Labor '96 campaign with a three-day planning session<br>
for congressional district coordinators and state federation<br>
officials.<br>
<br>
SPREADING OUT _ Service Employees Local 880, which has<br>
organized thousands of home care workers in Illinois, now<br>
represents 125 employees in Missouri. The vote at Homecare Services<br>
Inc. in St. Louis was 55-28 for SEIU.<br>
<br>
SECURE SOCIAL SECURITY _ Wall Street's drooling over the<br>
chance to get its hands on Social Security funds for so-called<br>
&quot;privatization&quot; and is conducting an orchestrated disinformation<br>
campaign on long-term financing problems. That, the Executive<br>
Council said, is why it's time to make Americans aware of &quot;the true<br>
value of the Social Security system and to discredit the false<br>
notion that private retirement accounts could match Social Security<br>
benefits.&quot; The council called on all unions to begin regular<br>
communications with their members about Social Security and to<br>
encourage activists to publicly defend the system.<br>
<br>
WORKERS DON'T LOSE SHIRTS _ Most of the UNITE workers at the<br>
C.F. Hathaway shirt plant in Waterville, Maine, will keep their<br>
jobs. In May, Hathaway's parent company, the Warnaco Group, said it<br>
would shut or sell the plant, the state's largest unionized apparel<br>
facility. But an investor group announced it will buy the plant and<br>
retain &quot;substantially all&quot; of the current work force.<br>
<br>
NOT JUST ENGLISH _ A measure to make English the official<br>
language of the federal government would &quot;disenfranchise, divide<br>
and disconnect&quot; millions of Americans from their government, the<br>
AFL-CIO Executive Council declared. Rather than penalize persons<br>
who do not speak English, the government should increase funding<br>
for adult education programs and English as a second language, the<br>
council said.<br>
<br>
HUNGER FOR JUSTICE _ Two striking workers at the Case Farms<br>
poultry processing plant in Morganton, N.C. began a hunger strike<br>
outside the plant Monday. More than 450 workers walked off the job<br>
last week after the company refused to recognize and bargain with<br>
the Laborers for more than a year. &quot;The will and spirit of my<br>
fellow workers will sustain me. We demand to be treated with<br>
respect and dignity. We will settle for nothing less,&quot; said Roberto<br>
Mendoza who is joined in the hunger strike by Luis Alberto Gonzalez<br>
and a local religious activist.<br>
<br>
CONVENTION CENTRAL _ Unions met across the country last week<br>
to plan their futures.<br>
<br>
* The Plumbers and Pipefitters, meeting in Las Vegas, elected<br>
new officers _ President Martin Maddaloni, Secretary-Treasurer<br>
Michael Collins and Assistant President Randal Gardner. Maddaloni<br>
replaces retiring Marvin Boede, effective Jan. 1.<br>
<br>
* In Pittsburgh, Steelworker delegates celebrated the planned<br>
unification with the UAW and Machinists in 2000 and heard President<br>
George Becker tell of plans by the Aluminum, Brick and Glass<br>
Workers to meet in special convention to consider joining the USWA.<br>
<br>
* AFT President Albert Shanker told the convention in<br>
Cincinnati that &quot;it is as much our duty to preserve public<br>
education as it is to negotiate a good contract or defend a<br>
competent teacher under attack.&quot;<br>
<br>
* The Fire Fighters, meeting in Honolulu, endorsed President<br>
Clinton after hearing from him in a video address. They also re-<br>
elected Al Whitehead as president and Vincent Bollon as secretary-<br>
treasurer.<br>
<br>
* The Glass, Molders and Pottery Workers pledged concerted<br>
political action for Clinton and re-elected President Frank Carter<br>
and other officers. Delegates passed a $2 dues increase.<br>
<br>
THESE SHOES DON'T FIT _ The Rev. Jesse Jackson described to<br>
the Executive Council the cozy relationship between multinational<br>
corporations like Nike and Reebok and the governments of developing<br>
countries, resulting in minuscule wages and outrageous working<br>
conditions. &quot;I am convinced that unless we address this, the vast<br>
body of oppressed workers can swallow up our labor market and not<br>
even have indigestion,&quot; he said.<br>
<br>
SORRY, WRONG NUMBER _ &quot;It is clear that Bell Atlantic's buyout<br>
of NYNEX would take us in the opposite direction (from the goal of<br>
the 1995 Telecommunications Act): a bigger telecom monopoly with<br>
even less incentive to reverse the companies' existing pattern of<br>
declining service standards, ever-higher rates and the destruction<br>
of good jobs,&quot; the Executive Council said. The AFL-CIO, the<br>
Communications Workers and Electrical Workers have urged federal<br>
and state agencies to nix the deal.<br>
<br>
STRIKE IS HOT SALSA _ Protesting unfair labor practices, 200<br>
Teamster Local 63 delivery drivers struck Guerrero Mexican Food<br>
Products August 4. The firm, which also markets under the &quot;Mission&quot;<br>
brand, is the largest tortilla producer in southern California. The<br>
subsidiary of a huge Mexican corn flour conglomerate closely<br>
aligned with that country's ruling circles, Guerrero has benefited<br>
from corporate welfare and has been driving independent operators<br>
out of business, the union charges. They were joined by other<br>
labor, community, campus and religious groups for a rally last<br>
Wednesday in front of the Mexican consulate in Los Angeles.<br>
<br>
REBUILDING CHURCHES AND FAITH _ The AFL-CIO will mobilize its<br>
affiliated unions and state and local councils to help rebuild<br>
churches, mainly in black communities, that have been burned,<br>
bombed or vandalized by hate criminals. And it will join with<br>
religious and civil rights groups to help foster a climate of<br>
tolerance and unity in the communities where these acts have<br>
occurred. The EC condemned the burnings and other racially,<br>
ethnically and sexually oriented crimes as &quot;acts of cowardly<br>
intolerance.&quot;<br>
<br>
HELP FOR STATE FEDS _ State and local central bodies &quot;are the<br>
backbone and infrastructure of this federation,&quot; Paperworkers<br>
President Wayne Glenn said as he urged the Executive Council to<br>
step up efforts to get local unions to affiliate. The council<br>
approved disbursement of funds to state federations from a program<br>
designed to encourage international unions to increase their local<br>
unions' affiliation with state feds. The money comes from a small<br>
_ one cent per member per month _ assessment on unions that do not<br>
meet affiliation goals approved earlier. Some of the funds will be<br>
reserved for grants of no more than $5,000 for program needs such<br>
as affiliation initiatives, technological enhancements or grass-<br>
roots development.<br>
<br>
STERN ADDITION _ Andy Stern, newly elected president of the<br>
Service Employees, was elected to the Executive Council, replacing<br>
his predecessor at SEIU, Richard Cordtz. Cordtz was praised by the<br>
council for his half-century of service as a labor movement<br>
activist.<br>
<br>
HEAT WAVE<br>
<br>
Union Summer activists working in Chicago received a standing<br>
ovation from the AFL-CIO Executive Council at its meeting in the<br>
Windy City last week. The Union Summer interns told the council<br>
how their experiences have changed their vision of America.<br>
<br>
Wednesday, August 14 is the AFL-CIO's National Action Day on<br>
strawberry workers, and most Union Summer sites are organizing<br>
actions. Other activities include:<br>
<br>
Boston Union Summer activists will picket Commonwealth Gas on<br>
Tuesday to support employees who are locked out. At the end of the<br>
week, they will go to Vermont and New Hampshire to canvass about<br>
Medicare.<br>
<br>
Union Summer activists in Chicago will join Teamsters Friday<br>
for an action to support the Overnight Trucking campaign. Chicago<br>
includes Union Summer's oldest activist _ a 63-year-old whose<br>
grandfather was an organizer for the UAW.<br>
<br>
The final wave of Los Angeles Union Summer interns will focus<br>
on the New Otani Hotel boycott and organizing Superior grocery<br>
store workers. They will also visit professors and students at UCLA<br>
to help the graduate students' union gain recognition from the<br>
University.<br>
<br>
Union Summer activists in Miami spent the week protesting the<br>
wages and benefits paid by Burdines Department Stores, and Tire<br>
Kingdom's record of sex discrimination in promotions. This week,<br>
they will work with the Farm Workers on the Prime mushrooms<br>
boycott.<br>
<br>
Union Summer interns in New Orleans will spend the week<br>
organizing parking attendants and ambulance drivers, and janitors<br>
who work for a private contractor at New Orleans University.<br>
<br>
All week, New York City activists will leaflet sweatshops,<br>
giving workers information about the Workers' Center and the<br>
support available there.<br>
<br>
Union Summer interns in Puerto Rico will recruit health care<br>
workers to join the Service Employees, and conduct house visits to<br>
organize a pharmaceutical company in Humaco. They are also<br>
organizing workers in the Departamento de Familia.<br>
<br>
Sacramento Union Summer activists are supporting the Living<br>
Wage Initiative, organizing opposition to the anti-affirmative<br>
action ballot measure, picketing for Justice for Janitors, and<br>
organizing home health care workers.<br>
<br>
Union Summer interns in San Jose are organizing a<br>
demonstration with Delores Huerta of the Farm Workers on Wednesday<br>
to highlight the plight of strawberry workers.<br>
<br>
The new Watsonville Union Summer activists will survey<br>
strawberry workers at their homes. On Wednesday, they will act as<br>
human billboards at busy intersections in Santa Cruz and Salinas,<br>
educating drivers about the working conditions in strawberry<br>
fields.</p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="/publ/publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
