</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML//EN">

<html>

<head>
<title>WIP 08/05/96 AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h3>AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS</h3>
<p>-- August 5, 1996<br>
<br>
MARCH FOR AMERICAN JOBS _ Unionists from across the country will<br>
march Aug. 11 in St. Louis at McDonnell Douglas world headquarters<br>
to protest the company's use of tax dollars to slash jobs and<br>
export them overseas. The nation's largest defense contractor,<br>
McDonnell Douglas also is spending tax dollars to hire scab and<br>
security goons to try to break a two-month strike by the<br>
Machinists. Leading the march will be IAM President George<br>
Kourpias, UAW President Stephen P. Yokich, and Steelworkers<br>
President George Becker. For information, call 314/731-0603.<br>
<br>
&quot;REVOLTING&quot; REPUBLICANS YIELD _ Hoping to gain some political<br>
advantage, Republicans abandoned their &quot;revolution&quot; to allow final<br>
passage of pro-worker legislation championed by Democrats before<br>
heading home for a month. The minimum wage will jump from $4.25 to<br>
$5.25 in two 45 cent increases, Oct. 1 and Sept. 1, 1997. Clinton<br>
also got a health insurance reform bill that provides insurance<br>
portability from job-to-job and coverage for pre-existing<br>
conditions. Much still needs to be done &quot;to address the still<br>
serious and unmet need for broad health care reform,&quot; AFL-CIO<br>
President John Sweeney said.<br>
<br>
WAR ON THE POOR _ In what Sweeney called &quot;bad for the country . .<br>
. and harmful to poor families,&quot; Congress passed the GOP's welfare<br>
&quot;reform&quot; bill. Clinton said he would sign the bill, which would end<br>
the government's 61-year-old guarantee to provide a federal safety<br>
net for America's less fortunate. Now _ surprise _ The Wall Street<br>
Journal reports that Republican leaders are considering using the<br>
projected $56 billion in welfare cuts to finance tax breaks that<br>
may be aimed at America's wealthiest.<br>
<br>
SYLVANIA WORKERS SEE THE LIGHT _ The Electronic Workers were able<br>
to break a 40-year union drought when workers at the Osram Sylvania<br>
facility in St. Marys, Pa., voted 251-227 for IUE representation.<br>
The workers decided they'd had enough of the company's shenanigans<br>
after Sylvania tried to implement continuous shifts and permanently<br>
laid off 100 workers, sending their jobs to Mexico. IUE also won<br>
recognition for 206 workers after 124 signed authorization cards at<br>
American Roll Form and Manufacturing Co. in Angola, Ind., which<br>
makes auto bumpers. Another 77 probationary workers will be part of<br>
the unit when they become permanently employed.<br>
<br>
WHAT'S UP, AIRDOX _ Workers at the Long Airdox mining equipment<br>
plant in Saltville, Va., wanted security and respect _ so they<br>
voted 49-20 for Mine Workers representation. &quot;They refused to be<br>
intimidated by management's threats and illegal discharge of a<br>
union supporter,&quot; said UMWA President Cecil E. Roberts. The<br>
Saltville plant is the third plant to vote union among the six<br>
plants owned by Long Airdox. Also, members of an independent union<br>
representing workers at a conference center in Banff, Alberta,<br>
voted by a 2-1 margin to affiliate with the UMWA.<br>
<br>
MILE HIGH IN DENVER _ Service Employees Local 105 in Denver, where<br>
members help with organizing, has brought in 500 new members in<br>
recent weeks. The latest victory was July 25, when employees at the<br>
Mental Health Corp. of Denver voted 210-59 for SEIU representation.<br>
The local, which is pushing to organize 1,000 suburban janitors,<br>
took to the streets last week and blocked a major downtown<br>
intersection.<br>
<br>
OVERTIME OUT _ The Senate will be the next battleground in the<br>
fight to save the 40-hour week and overtime pay. Last week the<br>
House passed a bill by Rep. Cass Ballenger (R-N.C.) to give the<br>
boss an opportunity to offer &quot;comp&quot; time instead of paying cash for<br>
overtime worked. The Department of Labor has recommended that<br>
Clinton veto the bill.<br>
<br>
STRAWBERRY FIELDS FOREVER? _ If that's what it takes to win basic<br>
rights for 20,000 California strawberry pickers, who earn about<br>
$8,000 a year. The campaign by the Farm Workers and the AFL-CIO<br>
heated up last week when Central Labor Councils around the country<br>
began a drive to seek pledges of support for the workers from local<br>
supermarkets. The pledge backs five things for the strawberry<br>
pickers _ living wages, clean drinking water and bathrooms, job<br>
security, health insurance and an end to sexual harassment. Stores<br>
that balk at the pledge will be leafletted Aug. 14. The strawberry<br>
campaign is one of the issues the AFL-CIO Executive Council will<br>
take up Tuesday and Wednesday during its annual summer meeting in<br>
Chicago.<br>
<br>
CRACKDOWN ON EGG FARM _ DeCoster Egg Farms operates an &quot;unsanitary<br>
and dangerous workplace,&quot; provides &quot;inhumane living quarters&quot; of<br>
cramped trailers and treats workers deplorably _ as in the case of<br>
a worker who severed several fingers and was forced to wait hours<br>
for medical aid, Secretary of Labor Robert B. Reich said. The<br>
company faces $3.6 million in proposed penalties levied by the U.S.<br>
Department of Labor for safety and health violations _ and criminal<br>
charges are being considered.<br>
<br>
MORE LIFT FOR THE COCKPIT _ Air Line Pilots set up informational<br>
picketing Aug. 3 at airports in Denver, Los Angeles and Seattle to<br>
protest working conditions at Mountain West Airlines and WestAir,<br>
both divisions of Mesa Air Group, where they have been negotiating<br>
for more than a year. The pilots are seeking decent work rules and<br>
benefits and wages commensurate with those paid at other regional<br>
airlines. The airlines operate as United Express carriers.<br>
<br>
JANITORS CLEAN UP _ Janitors ratified a contract with San Francisco<br>
building managers that will raise wages and pension contributions<br>
by 25 percent. Meanwhile, SEIU's Justice for Janitors campaign is<br>
heating up across the nation. In Washington, union janitors marched<br>
alongside nonunion janitors at P&amp;R Enterprises, a company that pays<br>
low wages and provides no health insurance or sick leave.<br>
<br>
QUIET ON THE WESTERN FRONT _ The Longshoremen reached a tentative<br>
three-year contract with the Pacific Maritime Association that<br>
provides wage increases of $3 per hour for 8,000 workers at 26<br>
ports on the West Coast. Under the agreement, the workers receive<br>
a $2 raise in the first year and $1 in the second, the first<br>
increases since 1993.<br>
<br>
MOPPING UP THE SWEATS - The Clinton administration announced the<br>
formation of a blue-ribbon panel to find ways to help consumers<br>
make sure they aren't buying garments made in sweatshops. For the<br>
past year, unions, consumer groups and the Department of Labor have<br>
been leading an aggressive crusade against domestic and foreign<br>
sweatshops.<br>
<br>
POCKETING THE PAYCHECK _ Another underhanded bosses' trick to sway<br>
votes in representation election vote, splitting paychecks _ one<br>
for union dues and the other pay minus dues _ was banned by the<br>
National Labor Relations Board in a unanimous ruling. Citing its<br>
rules against last-minute speechmaking by either side to a &quot;captive<br>
audience&quot; and late campaigning near polling places, the board also<br>
prohibited changing the time, location or method of paycheck<br>
distribution. The case stemmed from a complaint by the Operating<br>
Engineers against Kalin Construction Co. in Sodus, Mich., over a<br>
1994 election. The board ordered a new election.<br>
<br>
AFGE GRASSROOTS EFFORT PAYS OFF _ Lobbying and phone calls by<br>
federal employees on Capitol Hill thwarted efforts by some members<br>
of Congress to eliminate assurances that 60 percent of critical<br>
military hardware maintenance is performed by federal employees.The<br>
provision in the defense authorization bill to privatize<br>
maintenance was dropped in conference.<br>
<br>
CALIFORNIA TEAMING _ The California AFL-CIO July 31 elected Art<br>
Pulaski, secretary-treasurer of the San Mateo Labor Council, as<br>
executive secretary-treasurer, replacing retiring Jack Henning.<br>
Henning's conclusion: &quot;If by suspension of the laws of nature, I<br>
again were young, I would follow no other course, no other flag,<br>
than the flag of labor.&quot; Tom Rankin, state federation research<br>
director and lobbyist, was elected to fill the president's post,<br>
succeeding Albin J. Gruhn, who also retired. Delegates approved the<br>
expansion of the council from 36 to 48 to increase representation<br>
by women and people of color.<br>
<br>
FIGHT INJUSTICE _ The Indonesian government has cracked down hard<br>
on trade unionists. Muchtar Pakpahan, leader of Indonesia's only<br>
independent union, SBSI, was detained earlier this week and charged<br>
with subversion. He endured a lengthy prison sentence last year on<br>
similar trumped-up charges. According to reports, eight other SBSI<br>
leaders and 25 union members have also been detained. President<br>
Sweeney, the ICFTU and many other unions and NGOs have sent<br>
letters. Please send letters of protest to: General Suharto,<br>
President, Government of Indonesia, Jakarta, Indonesia; FAX: 62-21-<br>
360-517, Abdul Latief, Minister of Manpower, Jakarta, Indonesia,<br>
FAX: 62-21-840-2746.<br>
<br>
WITHOUT A PARACHUTE _ Citing continuing safety concerns, the Flight<br>
Attendants asked the Transportation Department to give the boot to<br>
top officers at ValuJet Airlines. Charging that management is<br>
either incapable or unwilling to run a safe airline, the union said<br>
chief executive Robert Priddy and chief operating officer Lewis<br>
Jordan &quot;should not be trusted with the public safety.&quot; ValuJet's<br>
fleet was grounded on June 18 after numerous inspections by the<br>
Federal Aviation Administration turned up serious safety problems<br>
at the cut-rate carrier in the wake of a May 11 crash in Florida<br>
that killed all on board.<br>
<br>
NARI CLEARED FOR TAKEOFF _ The Air Traffic Controllers, an<br>
affiliate of the Marine Engineers, has provided initial funding for<br>
creation of the National Aviation Research Institute, which is<br>
intended to improve air safety through the development of new<br>
technology based on the input of the workers who actually operate<br>
the equipment. Technology of the present air traffic control system<br>
is 10 to 15 years behind, Acting Executive Director Mike Connor<br>
said.<br>
<br>
WHAT WE DO IN COMMUNITIES _ T-shirts and full-color posters with<br>
the legend, &quot;Organizing for Social Justice in our Community,&quot;<br>
produced by the Department of Field Mobilization for central labor<br>
councils, are available from the AFL-CIO. The T-shirts (black) are<br>
$12 each and posters are $1. To order, contact the AFL-CIO, PMO,<br>
Room 209, 815 16th St. N.W., Washington, D.C. 20006.<br>
<br>
<br>
HEAT WAVE<br>
<br>
The Union Summer Southern Bus Tour will travel to Montgomery<br>
and Birmingham, Alabama in the final week of the Care-A-Van.<br>
Activists will handbill at the Estes nursing homes and conduct<br>
house visits with nursing home caregivers. They will tour the Civil<br>
Rights Museum in Montgomery and the Birmingham Jail, where Martin<br>
Luther King, Jr. was incarcerated.<br>
<br>
Bay Area Union Summer interns finished their three-weeks with<br>
a flurry, picketing the Lafayette Park Hotel; blocking traffic to<br>
draw attention to the ongoing boycott of the hotel. In San<br>
Francisco, activists drew more than 1000 people to a rally at the<br>
Embarcadero in support of janitors whose contract had expired after<br>
failed negotiations with employers.<br>
<br>
A new wave of Union Summer activists in Boston pick up where<br>
the last wave left off, organizing nursing home employees and<br>
meeting with union members in New Hampshire and Vermont. They will<br>
also lay groundwork for a Workers' Rights Board in Boston, which<br>
will be made up of 100 prominent citizens who will help non-union<br>
employees defend their rights.<br>
<br>
Union Summer interns in Charleston are taking to the streets<br>
to eradicate the term &quot;plantation&quot; from hotels and resorts in<br>
Hilton Head. Next week, they will sweep the beach to inform<br>
vacationers about job conditions in area hotels and the living wage<br>
initiative.<br>
<br>
Denver Union Summer activists will hit the ground running in<br>
support of the on-going Justice for Janitors campaign, leafleting<br>
downtown office buildings and petitioning tenants to adopt a<br>
responsible contract policy. Next week, activists will visit the<br>
Ludlow Massacre Site in Trinidad, Colorado and will meet with mine<br>
workers in the rural community.<br>
<br>
New Orleans Union Summer interns are organizing parking<br>
attendants and tourist industry employees. They are also meeting<br>
with Jefferson Parish female custodians who are filing a sex<br>
discrimination suit against the school district. The women, called<br>
&quot;maids,&quot; do the same work as male custodians but receive lower<br>
wages and fewer opportunities for advancement.<br>
<br>
In support of sweatshop workers in the garment industry, New<br>
York Union Summer activists will reach out to the community about<br>
worker's rights abuses. Activists will also picket New York<br>
department stores that sell brands associated with these abuses.<br>
<br>
Union Summer interns in Puerto Rico will work on two major<br>
campaigns: half will visit government workers at their agencies as<br>
part of an AFSCME organizing drive; the other half will do house<br>
visits to private sector health care and pharmaceutical workers<br>
with SEIU.<br>
<br>
Thirty-two Union Summer interns in Sacramento will work on the<br>
local Justice for Janitors organizing campaign and visit home<br>
health care workers at their homes. Activists will also support the<br>
United Farm Workers' efforts to organize strawberry pickers.<br>
<br>
Union Summer activists in San Jose are sending delegations to<br>
local stores that sell strawberries to talk to management about<br>
workers' rights violations against strawberry pickers. Interns are<br>
also working to organize mechanics, musicians and home health care<br>
workers.</p>
