<head>
<title>WIP 07/30/96 AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h3>AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS</h3>
<p>-- Tuesday, July 30, 1996<br>
<br>
BLUE LIGHT CONTRACT AT KMART -- UNITE members at Kmart's<br>
Greensboro, N.C., distribution center are celebrating the end of<br>
their three-year struggle with an &quot;excellent&quot; new contract that<br>
includes a pay increase ranging from 22 percent to 52 percent, two<br>
new paid holidays, sick leave gains and nondiscrimination language.<br>
The settlement comes after the dispute pulled together the<br>
Greensboro community behind the workers, including civil<br>
disobedience and a consumer boycott. The starting rate in the<br>
warehouse will increase from $7.25 per hour to $9 over term, while<br>
the base rate of $9 per hour will go to $11.<br>
<br>
HISTORIC RAIL PACT -- Conrail backed off its dispute with the<br>
Maintenance of Way Employees this morning, ending a two-year<br>
struggle to achieve labor agreements between rail labor and the<br>
nation's major freight carriers. If ratified, the tentative<br>
agreements with 13 unions, affecting 145,000 rail workers on 35<br>
railroads, would mark the first time in at least 30 years that the<br>
national rail industry has survived a bargaining process without<br>
strikes or imposed settlements from Congress.<br>
<br>
TALKIN' ABOUT O.T. -- That little extra you work harder for --<br>
overtime -- could be snatched away from you if the House approves<br>
a bill this week to let bosses pay in &quot;time&quot; instead of cash. This<br>
attack on the 40-hour work is orchestrated by Rep. Cass Ballenger<br>
(R-N.C.), who deceptively calls the bill, &quot;Working Families<br>
Flexibility Act.&quot; Some mostly toothless provisions would give<br>
workers no protection from the employer forcing comp time instead<br>
of overtime and, if you do get time, it's the boss who'll control<br>
when you take it. The bill is H.R. 2391. Call 1-800 LABOR-21 and<br>
tell your representative to vote no.<br>
<br>
VETO SIDELINES TEAM -- President Clinton will veto the company<br>
union &quot;TEAM Act&quot; today, scuttling that bill for the rest of this<br>
congressional season. Neither the House nor the Senate passed the<br>
anti-worker legislation with near enough votes -- a two-thirds<br>
majority -- to overcome a veto.<br>
<br>
FAT CATS LOSE -- What do you call a bill that lets rich fat<br>
cats give even more big political donations, halves what worker-<br>
financed political action committees can give and attacks unions,<br>
too? If you're Newt Gingrich, you call it &quot;campaign finance<br>
reform.&quot; But this bill was so outrageously weighted to the wealthy<br>
it fell 259-162 last week. It also would have scrapped current<br>
rules that allow union members to seek dues refunds for non-<br>
collective bargaining expenses and force unions to obtain annual<br>
written permission from every member to engage in spending around<br>
national policy issues.<br>
<br>
NLRB TO GROUP HOMES, &quot;YOU'RE BAD&quot; -- AFSCME's fight for group<br>
home workers in Michigan scored big last week when the NLRB upheld<br>
the union's charges that four home operators refused to bargain in<br>
good faith. The union has prepared similar charges against 35 other<br>
operators.<br>
<br>
ORGANIZING PAYS OFF AGAIN -- In Orlando, Fla., last week, SEIU<br>
Local 750 won the right to represent workers at National Car Rental<br>
on a 38-18 vote. Two Chicago janitor units at CHA properties also<br>
overwhelmingly said yes to SEIU. The votes were 26-0 at Rockwell<br>
properties and 18-2 at Near North Gardens.<br>
<br>
GHOST OF McCARTHY -- A la 1950s Communist witch hunts, the<br>
House Republican leadership is engaging in &quot;an ugly and gross abuse<br>
of government authority . . . the latest chapter in the organized<br>
smear campaign against union leaders,&quot; AFL-CIO President John J.<br>
Sweeney said. Republicans on the House Judiciary subcommittee<br>
staged a show hearing last week on the Laborers' 1995 agreement<br>
with the Justice Department to institute reforms, complete with a<br>
witness behind a screen. The mystery guest has previously testified<br>
publicly, his identity is common knowledge and he has sold info to<br>
the government and tabloids -- but the GOP lauded his credibility.<br>
The hearings &quot;are a naked political payback -- conducted at<br>
taxpayer expense -- to try to punish all of America's unions for<br>
telling it like it is on Medicare, tax cuts for the rich and the<br>
minimum wage,&quot; Sweeney said.<br>
<br>
FRESH, NOT TOXIC -- A fight started with a 1989 AFL-CIO<br>
lawsuit calling for the banning on fresh foods of pesticides<br>
suspected of causing cancer is coming to a successful end. Already<br>
such agents are banned from processed foods, but a House-passed<br>
bill would apply uniform standards to fresh and processed foods. It<br>
also creates higher standards for certain foods and chemicals that<br>
affect children and calls for screening for chemicals that raise<br>
the risk of breast cancer.<br>
<br>
COOK IS SEIU FAMILY AFFAIR -- A two-year fight for dignity and<br>
decent wages by the Service Employees at Cook Family Foods ended<br>
when the workers ratified a new contract. The agreement doubles<br>
current pay levels, exceeding industry standards, the union said.<br>
While the contract does not include a union shop clause, some 188<br>
of the 200 workers who voted in the election joined the union.<br>
<br>
WELD WEDDED TO CORPORATE CASH -- Republican Massachusetts Gov.<br>
William Weld's campaign for the U.S. Senate gets big money from<br>
corporations that have locked out, laid off and cut the wages of<br>
Massachusetts working families, Federal Election Commission reports<br>
reveal. This is &quot;nothing short of a betrayal of the commonwealth's<br>
working men and women,&quot; charged Massachusetts AFL-CIO President<br>
Joseph Faherty. The PAC contributors include Commomwealth Energy<br>
Systems, Kmart, Browning-Ferris Industries and AT&amp;T. In several<br>
cases when the workers have requested Weld's help in keeping local<br>
jobs or maintaining wage and benefit levels, he has refused to act.<br>
<br>
JANITORS MAY STRIKE -- San Francisco janitors may turn up the<br>
heat and strike if negotiations with the Building Owners and<br>
Managers Association do not improve by July 31, when the union's<br>
contract expires. BOMA wants to dismantle the union hiring hall,<br>
reduce health and welfare coverage and eliminate seniority hiring<br>
rights. Meanwhile, SEIU Local 82, which heads up Justice for<br>
Janitors in the nation's capital, unveiled its World Wide Web site<br>
called Toxin Watch. The site includes information on toxic spills,<br>
releases and other environmental problems of select oil, gas, and<br>
chemical companies. The web address is http//www.seiu.org/local/82-<br>
dc/toxin.htm.<br>
<br>
NO TALKS BEFORE RESTORATION -- Steelworkers President George<br>
Becker is willing to meet anywhere, anytime to settle the two-year<br>
strike against Bridgestone/Firestone, but only if replaced workers<br>
are returned to work. Becker's statement was in response to reports<br>
that in a meeting with Rev. Jesse Jackson, Bridgestone officials<br>
said they wanted to meet with Becker and that Becker should be<br>
involved in future negotiations.<br>
<br>
SHELL'S NIGERIAN CONNECTIONS SLAMMED -- More than 200 trade<br>
unionists demonstrated in front of a Shell gasoline station in<br>
support of Nigerian Oil Workers during the Service Employees Civil<br>
and Human Rights Conference in Washington last weekend. Several<br>
leaders and members of the Nigerian Oil Workers have been<br>
imprisoned by the Nigerian government. SEIU President Andy Stern<br>
and Arthur Onovrian of the Oil Workers Union of Nigeria spoke at<br>
the conference.<br>
<br>
NEW HAND ON THE THROTTLE -- Delegates at the Locomotive<br>
Engineers' elected Clarence Monin president by a 320-276 margin. He<br>
served five years as first vice president and alternate president<br>
before defeating incumbent Ronald McLaughlin for the top spot. A<br>
third candidate, Paul Morrison, received 23 votes. Also at the<br>
Detroit convention last week, a thousand members, officers and<br>
family members showed support for striking Free Press and Detroit<br>
News workers and raised $20,000 to help out the strikers and their<br>
families.<br>
<br>
COMMUNITY SERVICES CONFAB -- A mini town hall meeting on youth<br>
and unions and a solidarity court and rally for the Detroit<br>
newspaper strikers are on the agenda for this week's AFL-CIO<br>
Community Services Conference in Dearborn, Mich. Speakers include<br>
AFL-CIO President Sweeney and Executive Vice President Linda<br>
Chavez-Thompson. Sen. Edward M. Kennedy (D-Mass.) is to receive the<br>
Murray-Green-Meany-Kirkland Award.<br>
<br>
BE&amp;K AWARD REVERSED -- A $20 million lower court award against<br>
the Carpenters and the Paperworkers was reversed by the 8th U.S.<br>
Circuit Court of Appeals. BE&amp;K, a nonunion construction firm based<br>
in Birmingham, Ala., alleged that the unions conspired to have the<br>
company removed from a paper mill construction project.<br>
<br>
WORK OK'D FOR TEENS -- Teen-age workers could be allowed to<br>
load cardboard paper balers in use at most grocery stores that meet<br>
American National Standards Institute prescriptions under a measure<br>
approved by the Senate July 17. The House passed a similar bill<br>
last fall. The Food and Commercial Workers, which had fought a<br>
similar measure, signed on to the Senate bipartisan compromise<br>
bill.<br>
<br>
OPPORTUNITY FOR ALL -- NOT! -- San Francisco's Economic<br>
Opportunity Council says no to economic opportunity. California<br>
Professional Employees, an affiliate of the Painters, represents<br>
council workers and has been attempting to bargain a new contract,<br>
but agency officials refuse to negotiate. The agency also is<br>
fighting union efforts to organize other agency employees. The<br>
union has filed unfair labor practice charges with the National<br>
Labor Relations Board over the negotiations and organizing<br>
roadblocks. The city's Board of Supervisors passed a resolution<br>
supporting the union and its workers.<br>
<br>
For details of these and other stories, check out the News and<br>
Views library on LaborNET (CompuServe), or the AFL-CIO web page at<br>
http:\\www.aflcio.org. To receive Work in Progress, or to submit<br>
information, FAX to 202/508-6908.<br>
<br>
Heat Wave<br>
<br>
After an uplifting launch in Memphis, the interns on the Union<br>
Summer Southern bus tour got a scary look at what workers face when<br>
they try to organize. In Jackson, an employer intentionally injured<br>
an activist by sideswiping her with his car, grazing her back with<br>
his sideview mirror as she was handbilling at a nursing home. The<br>
interns will travel to Alabama this week where they will learn<br>
organizing techniques and meet with nursing home workers in Mobile.<br>
They will handbill and &quot;blitz&quot; area nursing homes to inform<br>
residents and their families about working conditions.<br>
<br>
Union Summer interns in the Bay Area will spend the week<br>
working on the boycott of the Lafayette Park Hotel and leafleting<br>
at Long's Drug Stores. They also will mail and phonebank to draw<br>
supporters to a rally at the Sir Francis Drake Hotel on July 30,<br>
and conduct house visits for the United Community Workers Campaign.<br>
<br>
After spending Sunday leafleting and protesting at a Brooklyn,<br>
Michigan car race sponsored by Bridgestone/Firestone that was<br>
expected to draw more than 1,000 spectators, one group of Chicago<br>
Union Summer activists will complete their internships -- and a new<br>
group will begin on Wednesday. The new activists will see action<br>
immediately, traveling to Milwaukee Thursday for a Justice for<br>
Janitors event.<br>
<br>
On Monday, Union Summer interns in Los Angeles will see the<br>
fruits of their labor when the state senate transportation<br>
committee holds hearings to investigate truckers' grievances. The<br>
activists have been circulating petitions to gather support for the<br>
truckers, and calling senators to encourage them to attend the<br>
hearing. On Tuesday, the activists will join a major Justice for<br>
Janitors demonstration. On Wednesday, they will educate shoppers<br>
and clothing store managers at area malls about working conditions<br>
in sweatshops that supply major clothing designers.<br>
<br>
San Diego Union Summer activists are meeting with local union<br>
members to encourage them to join the effort to save the eight-hour<br>
work day, increase the minimum wage, and register voters.<br>
<br>
In San Jose, Union Summer interns will spend the week urging<br>
people not to patronize nonunion auto dealers, visiting home health<br>
care workers at their homes, and educating supermarket shoppers<br>
about problems with strawberries due to unsafe working conditions<br>
for strawberry workers.<br>
<br>
Union Summer activists in Watsonville are identifying labor<br>
law violations that affect strawberry workers, including unsanitary<br>
and unsafe working conditions. They are working with paralegals to<br>
file legal notices of violations. Next week, they will go to Teatro<br>
Campesino to learn about Chicano history.<br>
<br>
To accommodate the overwhelming number of Union Summer<br>
activists, a new site has been added and two additional sites will<br>
start up again in August. The new Union Summer site is Puerto<br>
Rico; Union Summer activists will be based in San Juan, but will<br>
work on organizing campaigns across the island. Sites now scheduled<br>
for an additional &quot;wave&quot; of activists are New Orleans and Boston.</p>
