<head>
<title>WIP 07/15/96 AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h3>AFL-CIO Work in Progress - July 15, 1996 </h3>
<p><strong>`COMEBACK TIME' _ WORKERS WIN BIG ON CAPITOL HILL</strong> Any doubt that 
working families and their unions are reemerging as a national political force was washed away last 
week by a tide of congressional victories. AFL-CIO President John J. Sweeney hailed it as a 
&quot;comeback week for America's working families.&quot; Here's a rundown: </p>
<p><strong>RALLY 'ROUND THE RAISE</strong><br>
The AFL-CIO scored a huge legislative victory when the Senate voted to raise the minimum wage. 
Five GOP senators joined all Democrats in slam-dunking a move to exempt millions of low-wage 
workers from the pay hike. The minimum wage victory came just hours after more than 1,000 
worker activists rallied on the Capitol's steps and lobbied their senators, and after months of TV 
and radio ads by the federation pushing the increase. Showing little grace in defeat, Sen. Don 
Nickles (R-Okla.) threatens to hold up a House/Senate conference on the bill. </p>
<p><strong>TEAM ACT NOT PLAYOFF BOUND</strong><br>
The TEAM Act's fate _ death by veto _ was sealed last week when it squeaked through the 
Senate 53-46, 14 votes short of the number needed to overturn President Clinton's promised veto. 
The company union bill &quot;got a heavy push forward by some of the biggest corporate lawbreakers 
and special-interest seekers in America,&quot; President Sweeney said. But grass-roots action from 
workers and phone and personal lobbying from federation and affiliated staff stymied the GOP's 
hopes for many Democratic defections. </p>
<p><strong>WORKERS, 61; RIGHT-TO-WORK COMMITTEE, 38</strong><br>
Anti-worker forces were on the short end of the lopsided defeat of the national right-to-work (for 
less) bill in the Senate last week. The bill was &quot;intended to punish working families and their unions 
for their new found strength. . . . This bill's defeat is a resounding win over the bully payback tactics 
of this Congress,&quot; Sweeney said. </p>
<p><strong>REPETITIVE VICTORY SYNDROME</strong><br>
In another win, the House stripped away a ban in the Labor/HHS spending bill on federal job 
safety agencies from studying and developing guidelines on repetitive stress injuries. Thirty-five 
Republicans joined 180 Democrats and one independent in voting against the provision. 
Ergonomics-related problems form the fastest-growing category of injuries and illnesses tracked by 
the government; their incidence has increased by 800 percent over the last 10 years. </p>
<p>CLCs RISE AND SHINE _ More than 200 representatives from AFLCIO central labor councils 
nationwide gathered in Denver last week for the first Central Labor Conference. &quot;The future of the 
labor movement depends far more on what CLCs do than what we do in Washington,&quot; President 
Sweeney said. AFL-CIO Executive Vice President Linda Chavez-Thompson and labor 
commentator Jim Hightower also addressed the gathering. Much of the activity occurred in 
workshops on organizing, the role of CLCs, strategies, activities, programs to build membership 
participation, development and Labor `96. </p>
<p>YOU'RE IN ARMEY'S (FACE) NOW _ Rep. Dick Armey (R-Texas), House majority leader 
and rabid union hater, said last week that he &quot;thumbs my nose&quot; at unions. He got a retaliatory 
raspberry back when about two dozen sign-carrying and slogan-chanting union members greeted 
him as he entered the Chamber of Commerce's national headquarters to deliver his standard 
union-bashing drivel to a fundraising breakfast for corporate bosses. A new AFL-CIO report 
documents the GOP's coordinated &quot;big lie&quot; scheme against unions, of which Armey is a main 
architect. </p>
<p>&quot;DAYS OF RAGE&quot; _ On the second anniversary of the Bridgestone/Firestone strike July 13, 
President Sweeney and Steelworkers President George Becker joined more than 2,500 union 
members and supporters for a mass &quot;Days of Rage&quot; rally and concert in Nashville. The 
International Chemical and Energy Workers secretariat also called for a &quot;cyberdemo,&quot; with 
workers bombarding the tire maker's World Wide Web site with protests. Demonstrations of 
solidarity in Turkey and several European and South American countries as well as handbilling by 
union members and Union Summer activists at MasterCare auto service centers, owned by 
Firestone, throughout the United States rounded out the action. </p>
<p>IRVIN UNITES _ Workers at Irvin Aerospace in Red Springs, N.C., voted 2-1 for UNITE 
representation. Issues that motivated workers to organize included low pay, unaffordable health 
insurance and unsafe and unsanitary working conditions. The workers make parachutes for such 
clients as Boeing, McDonnell-Douglas, Lockheed, NASA and the Air Force. </p>
<p>UNION WINS AT RED CROSS _ Red Cross nurses, professionals and technicians at the South 
Jersey-Penn Region of the American Red Cross Blood Services voted to be represented by the 
Hospital Professionals and Allied Employees (HPAE) of the AFT. The victory represents a 
growing trend at Red Cross Blood Services around the country, where 2,000 of the 14,000 
workers are organized. </p>
<p>VICTORY FOR BEVERLY WORKERS _ Service Employees nursing home workers in 
Pennsylvania have won the latest round against Beverly Enterprises Inc., as the National Labor 
Relations Board granted a 10(j) injunction ordering the rehiring of &quot;permanently replaced&quot; strikers. 
An NLRB hearing into unfair labor practice charges centered on the company's anti-worker and 
anti-patient practices begins today. </p>
<p>SPUTTER, SPUTTER, BACKFIRE _ Democratic lawmakers and witnesses turned a Republican 
&quot;show trial&quot; hearing on so-called union corruption on its ear last week. &quot;There has to be a partisan 
Republican attack on labor as the subtext to this hearing,&quot; Rep. Henry Waxman (D-Calif.) said. 
DoL Inspector General Charles Martsen pointed to corruption charges that have brought down 
many company managers. One of his assistant IGs also testified that employers can wind up 
&quot;cheating the union and cheating the employee benefit funds.&quot; </p>
<p>NEEDED: A UNION _ Some 24,000 nonunion employees at United Airlines are bound by the 
terms of the 1994 buyout pact negotiated by the carrier and participating unions, the U.S. District 
Court for the 11th Circuit ruled. It ruled that the nonunion workers had no representative whom the 
airline was required to consult in deciding structure and terms of work, giving further credence to 
the notion that every employee needs a union. </p>
<p>APRI CONFERENCE _ Vice President Gore, Labor Secretary Robert Reich and President 
Sweeney will address the A. Philip Randolph Institute's National Education Conference in 
Washington, July 17- 20. The conference, which will include a rally at the National Press Building 
in support of the striking Detroit newspaper workers, features workshops on communicating with 
the media, effective voter participation and special sessions on black church burnings and 
international workers' rights. </p>
<p>UNIONS PROVE METTLE AT OLYMPICS _ When the Olympics open this week in Atlanta, 
the union label will be in many places _ like the Olympic Stadium (built by union labor), and 
communications, transportation, printing, event staging and even the television broadcasts. The 
Communications Workers, Graphic Communications Union, Theatrical Stage Employees, 
Amalgamated Transit Union, CWA's Broadcast Employees, Electrical Workers and Directors 
Guild of America all are involved in the staging of the Games. Two union members will be going for 
the gold _ boxer Lawrence Clay-Bey (AFSCME) and judo athlete Hillary Wolf (Screen Actors). </p>
<p>AND THE WINNER IS IBPAT _ As the Olympic games begin, &quot;Operation Clean Brush&quot; is 
putting the final strokes on more than 250 homes surrounding the competition. The project is a $1.5 
million collaborative effort of the Painters, businesses and the Atlanta government and has allowed 
almost two dozen unemployed or low-skilled Atlanta residents to learn a skill and participate in the 
union's pre-apprenticeship program. </p>
<p>WORKERS CAMPAIGN AGAINST HARASSMENT _ Women's, labor, legal, religious and 
community organizations have pledged their support for legislation in Massachusetts to clarify and 
expand protections for sexual harassment victims. &quot;We stand solidly with those supporting this 
legislation that will serve to hold responsible parties accountable when perpetrators of sexual 
harassment are negligently hired or retained in the workplace,&quot; said Massachusetts AFL-CIO 
President Joseph Faherty. </p>
<p>GIVING AN INCH AND KEEPING A YARD _ The AFL-CIO Metal Trades Department has 
reached agreement with the Naval Sea Systems Command to facilitate a number of work rule 
changes aimed at boosting productivity in the Navy's public shipyards. </p>
<p>SKIP THIS UTILITY BILL _ Legislation introduced in the House to impose restructuring and 
deregulation on electric utilities would threaten American jobs and communities, the Electrical 
Workers say. &quot;We believe that, despite the good intentions of some of its backers, the bill as it 
stands would cause chaos and disruption in an industry already undergoing massive changes,&quot; said 
IBEW President John J. Barry. </p>
<h2>Heat Waves </h2>
<p>This week, Union Summer activists in Akron will visit nursing home workers at their homes, survey 
voters about health insurance, and leaflet at the African American festival and parade. </p>
<p>Bay Area Union Summer interns are supporting HERE boycotts of the Sir Francis Drake and 
Lafayette Park hotels, organizing nonprofit workers in San Francisco, supporting Justice for 
Janitors on an upcoming strike vote, and organizing part-time workers in Richmond. </p>
<p>Union Summer activists at the all-women site in Boston will join a demonstration and information 
blitz with laundry workers outside hospitals this week with UNITE, make house calls to health care 
workers with SEIU in Pittsfield, and register voters with IUE in Lynn. </p>
<p>After riding out Hurricane Bertha, Charleston Union Summer activists are resuming house visits 
with workers of the Melrose Resort (on the island adjacent to Hilton Head) who are fighting for 
their first contract. </p>
<p>After just a week of work, Union Summer interns in Chicago have gathered more than 500 
signatures for the Chicago Jobs and Living Wage campaign. This week they will rally at a Chicago 
City Council Finance Committee hearing to require city contractors to pay their employees at least 
$7.60 per hour. They also will protest a union-busting law firm. </p>
<p>Union Summer interns in Los Angeles will spend the week organizing truckers at the harbor with 
CWA and hotel and restaurant employees in Santa Monica with HERE. </p>
<p>New Orleans Union Summer activists are supporting a raise in the minimum wage in the city to 
$6.00 per hour. On Thursday they will present their petitions to the City Council. </p>
<p>Union Summer interns in New York will picket to support jewelry workers, attend a hearing on a 
dangerous toxin used in drycleaning, and picket a clothing contractor who engages in unfair labor 
practices. They also will help at the Workers' Center, where non-union workers come to air 
grievances and seek legal assistance against employers. </p>
<p>Union Summer activists in St. Louis will join a large organizing meeting with nurses on Friday. They 
also are leafleting and picketing with Justice for Janitors, and canvassing and making house calls 
with AFSCME. </p>
<p>Volunteers recruited by San Diego Union Summer activists have met with more than 1,000 local 
union members. They are working to save the eight-hour work day, increase the minimum wage, 
and register voters. </p>
<p>A new group of Watsonville Union Summer activists will spend their first week interviewing 
strawberry workers to identify health and safety violations in the field. They will circulate a 
questionnaire and take affidavits from workers.</p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="/publ/publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
