<head>
<title>WIP 07/09/96 AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h2>AFL-CIO Work in Progress</h2>
<p>RALLY FOR WAGES _ More than 1,000 worker activists will swarm over Capitol Hill Tuesday 
morning to tell the Senate to vote for a real minimum wage and give America the raise it needs. The 
workers will join Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle (D-S.D.), Sen. Ted Kennedy (D-Mass.), 
all three top AFL-CIO officers and union presidents at a press conference outside the Capitol. 
Then union leaders and workers will go inside to call on their senators before gathering for a 
minimum wage vote watch in Room 430 of the Dirksen Senate Office Building. The message: Pass 
Kennedy's version and defeat a version from Sen. Kit Bond (R-Mo.) that denies millions of 
workers the wage hike. The Washington lobbying has been augmented by tremendous back home 
pressure, including tens of thousands of phone calls from union members to their senators. </p>
<p>UNABASHED UNION BASHING _ In retaliation for the AFL-CIO's success in bringing the 
minimum wage increase to the nation's attention through a massive media and grass-roots 
campaign, Republicans will try and muscle the TEAM Act and a national right- to-work (for less) 
bill through the Senate on Wednesday. Again, rank-and-filers and union leaders will lobby senators 
to turn back both bills. You can pitch in too. Call 1-800/96AFL-CIO and tell your senators to vote 
against cloture on the right-to-work bill (S. 1788) and to defeat the TEAM Act (S. 295). You can 
also <a href="http://www.standup.westlake.com/cgi-bin/zipsearchform?letternum=0">send a fax from the Web.</a> </p>
<p>GRASS-ROOTS REVIVAL _ More than 200 delegates will attend the first AFL-CIO Central 
Labor Council conference in Denver July 11- 14. The meeting, bringing together those folks who 
do the work for unions at the local level across the country will include workshops on major 
AFL-CIO campaigns and legislative and political issues. AFL-CIO President John Sweeney will 
address the group on Friday. </p>
<p>BRIDGESTONE/FIRESTONE READY FOR PRIME TIME _ The Steelworkers will observe 
the second anniversary of the company's illegal replacement of 2,300 workers during an unfair 
labor practice strike Saturday with a concert and rally in Nashville, nationwide MasterCare 
leafletting and a 30-minute TV special, &quot;They're running over the American Dream.&quot; The show will 
air Friday July 12: Akron, WOAC, 6:30 p.m.; Chattanooga, WDSI, 11 p.m.; Decatur, WFHL, 10 
p.m.; Des Moines, KYOU, 11 p.m.; Saturday July 13: Birmingham, WNAL, 6:30 p.m.; 
Cleveland, WBNX, 9:30 p.m.; Indianapolis, WISH, 2:30 p.m.; Nashville, WXMT, 6:30 p.m.; St. 
Paul/Minneapolis, KLGT 4:40 p.m.; Sunday July 14, Chicago, WCIU, 7:30 p.m.; Duluth, KDHL, 
1 p.m.; Pittsburgh, WPTT, 10 p.m. Check your local listings for times and dates in New York, Los 
Angeles, Austin and other cities. </p>
<p>JANITORS' NEW PACT SHINES _ The janitors that clean the California Bay Area's posh 
offices by night capped a four-year struggle for dignity by ratifying &quot;the best agreement in the local's 
history,&quot; said Mike Garcia, president of Service Employees Local 1877. The four-year pact raises 
wages for 5,000 janitors, makes all members eligible for family health benefits by the end of the 
contract term and brings Bay Area janitors under one master agreement. </p>
<p>IAM CLAIMS HARASSMENT _ McDonnell Douglas has illegally spied on and harassed 
Machinists during the course of the month-long strike, the IAM charges in a July 2 complaint to the 
National Labor Relations Board. The company is infringing on the workers' right to strike by 
forcing picketers to march dangerously close to moving traffic, in one case only 10 inches from 
moving cars, the union said. So far, three picketers have been hit by cars. Luckily, none has been 
critically injured. The union also charged that squads from the security company hired by 
McDonnell Douglas, Asset Protection Team, are following strikers in vans, filming them wherever 
they go in hopes of provoking a confrontation </p>
<p>&quot;IT'S HIP TO BE UNION&quot;... according to an article in the July 8 issue of Newsweek that says 
&quot;anger over corporate cutbacks and meager pay hikes is giving the (labor) movement its biggest 
boost in decades.&quot; A new Newsweek poll shows that 62 percent of Americans approve of unions, 
up from 55 percent in 1981. Among people 18 to 29, 68 percent view unions favorably. While the 
time is certainly right for a resurgence in unionism, the article also credited the new leadership of the 
AFL-CIO for stepping up with aggressive legislative and organizing campaigns, including Union 
Summer. </p>
<p>SEIU NOTCHES TWO _ Health care workers at Nord Center, a mental health facility in Lorain, 
Ohio, voted 53-36 for representation in Service Employees Local 1199. SEIU Local 4 in Chicago 
won card check recognition for 85 nursing home workers at Highland Nursing Home and 50 
workers at the Fairmount nursing facility. </p>
<p>YEAR-OLD NEWSPAPER STRIKE GOES GLOBAL _ One year after it began, the Detroit 
newspaper strike has gone global. The Geneva- based Postal, Telegraph and Telephone 
International urged its 223 affiliated unions in 117 countries to support the AFL-CIO's &quot;Don't buy; 
don't advertise&quot; campaign against USA TODAY, the flagship newspaper of Gannett Corp., owner 
of the Detroit News. Some 2,000 employees of the News and Free Press, owned by 
Knight-Ridder, have been on strike since July 13, 1995. Management and imported scabs from 
other papers are producing the newspapers. </p>
<p>NY `HOT GOODS' LAW _ A New York &quot;hot goods&quot; law singed last week will help state law 
enforcement better protect garment workers. It allows inspectors to stop the shipment of 
merchandise made in violation of minimum wage or overtime laws. It also lets the government seek 
back wages and fines against manufacturers that profited from the use of illegal labor. </p>
<p>BUTTON, BUTTON, WHO'S GOT THE BUTTON _ The UAW won a round in its dispute with 
Caterpillar when an administrative law judge upheld the National Labor Relations Board's support 
for the right of the UAW local union 1415 president to wear a protest button directed at Caterpillar 
CEO Don Fites. The button read &quot;Happiness is waking up in the morning and finding Don Fites' 
picture on a milk carton.&quot; </p>
<p>OVERNITE, BUT NOT OVERTIME _ The Teamsters are on the air with radio ads explaining 
how Overnite Transportation Co. has reneged on its promise to pay workers overtime. The 
company promised time-and- a-half for work beyond 47 hours. Now it says only workers willing 
to work at their normal hourly rate will be given work in excess of 47 hours. </p>
<p>SAFETY RULES CROSS THE LINE _ Succumbing to pressure from trucking firms, 
Transportation Department officials have agreed to weaken a truck safety inspection program on 
the Texas-Mexico border. Under the new plan, companies can self-certify that their trucks have no 
safety problems despite DoT findings that 51 percent of the trucks crossing into Texas were found 
too dangerous to operate on U.S. highways. Trucking deregulation is a provision under the North 
American Free Trade Agreement that the Teamsters and several Mexican driver groups want 
renegotiated. </p>
<p>RUNNING ON TIME _ The Machinists, Maintenance of Way Employees, Sheet Metal Workers 
and Transportation Communications Union say recommendations by presidential emergency 
boards, while constructive, fall short for settlements between rail labor and most of the nation's 
large freight railroads. The boards used as a guideline an arbitration decision in a United 
Transportation Union case that combined general wage increases, lump sum payments and a 
cost-of-living adjustment. The unions challenged the carriers to reach an agreement before the 
current 30-day cooling-off period ends. </p>
<p>ILO ACTION _ Despite intense employer opposition, the International Labor Organization 
adopted a new International Convention on Home Work. The three-pronged approach seeks to 
establish international labor standards for the increasingly precarious nature of work resulting from 
economic globalization. The ILO also spotlighted Nigeria for its widespread disregard of freedom 
of association, Burma once again for its use of forced labor, and Iran for discrimination in 
employment due to gender and religion. </p>
<p>ONE BIG SONGBOOK _ The workers' choir at Whiteville Apparel in Greensboro, N.C., has 
produced a tape of its gospel and labor music. The choir is made up of members of UNITE Local 
1077 and sang at UNITE's founding convention. The tapes are available for $10 from UNITE, 
1010 Tucker St., Greensboro, N.C. 27405. The money raised will be used for the union's political 
action fund. </p>
<p>GO SEE CIO EXHIBIT _ The American Labor Museum/Botto House National Landmark in 
Haledon, N.J., has developed an exhibit commemorating the 60th anniversary of the Congress of 
Industrial Organizations. The exhibit, &quot;The Birth and Formative Years of the CIO in New Jersey,&quot; 
covering the years 1935-1961, will be on display at the Labor Museum July 6 through Sept. 21. 
For more information, call 201/595-7953. The New Jersey Historical Commission provided 
assistance to the project. </p>
<h2>Heat Wave -- July 8, 1996</h2>
<p>A new crop of Union Summer activists, <em>all women,</em> arrive in Akron this week. They will leaflet 
with SCORE (Summit County Organizing for Rights and Equality) for living wages, health care for 
all, a voice on the job and corporate accountability. </p>
<p>Also all women this month, Boston Union Summer interns will organize hospital and health care 
workers in western Massachusetts, work with UNITE! to organize laundry workers in Boston, and 
rally in support of state legislation to give women three years (rather than six months) to report 
sexual harassment or rape that occurs on the job. </p>
<p>Charleston Union Summer activists spent the weekend demonstrating at a 5K running race and 
using guerilla theater at the Melrose Club resort and the Hyatt Hotel to focus attention on unfair 
labor practices by the hospitality industry in Hilton Head. </p>
<p>The second wave of Union Summer interns began work in Chicago this weekend. They will leaflet 
at Sears and Firestone stores to support the Bridgestone/Firestone boycott, visit nursing home 
workers at their homes, and gather signatures for the living wage campaign. </p>
<p>In Detroit, Union Summer activists will join a demonstration next Saturday to mark the first 
anniversary of the Detroit newspaper strike. The event will bring together union members from 
across the state at North Plant, the paper_s largest distribution plant. </p>
<p>Union Summer interns in Nashville are planning demonstrations for the second anniversary of the 
Bridgestone/Firestone strike this Friday and Saturday, July 12-13. They will meet President 
Sweeney on Saturday before he speaks at the big rally. On Tuesday, they will host a Clergy Prayer 
Breakfast for Justice at Vanderbilt University_s chapel. They will also leaflet businesses in Century 
City, where the Bridgestone/Firestone corporate office is located. </p>
<p>New Orleans Union Summer activists are gathering signatures of registered voters to raise the 
minimum wage in the city to $6.00 per hour. They also are supporting efforts to organize hospitality 
industry workers. </p>
<p>Working with UNITE!, New York Union Summer interns are supporting a retailer accountability 
campaign through community outreach and store visits. They will focus on the role retailers play in 
exploiting garment workers. </p>
<p>Twenty-five Union Summer activists in Sacramento will support the Justice for Janitors campaign, 
visit health care workers at their homes, and work on the boycotts against the Hyatt Regency and 
the Beverly Garland hotels. In addition to college students, Sacramento interns include a teacher, a 
single mother, and a woman whose grandfather started a union. </p>
<p>St. Louis Union Summer activists will leaflet with leather goods workers, organize for AFSCME's 
first contract campaign at Beverly Farm in Godfrey, Illinois, and picket with striking McDonnell 
Douglas workers. </p>
<hr>
<p>For Executive Council statements, reports and press conference transcripts, check out 
LaborNET's &quot;News and Views&quot; library on <a href="http://www.compuserve.com">CompuServe</a>, or <a href="http://www.aflcio.org">LaborWEB</a>, the AFL-CIO's Web site 
located at http://<a href="http://www.aflcio.org">www.aflcio.org</a>. To send information for inclusion, or FAX numbers to receive 
Work in Progress, FAX to 202/508-6908, or via E-mail <a href="mailto:71112.53@compuserve.com">71112.53@compuserve.com</a>.</p>
