<html>

<head>
<title>WIP 07/02/96 AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h2>AFL-CIO Work in Progress</h2>
<p>ON THE AIR AGAIN - AFL-CIO television and radio ads that began airing June 27 in 19 
congressional districts slam cuts in Medicare proposed by House Speaker Newt Gingrich (R-Ga.) 
and ask lawmakers to vote against them. AFL-CIO President John Sweeney accused the GOP of 
&quot;double talk in saying they're slowing the growth of Medicare - not cutting.&quot; The ads ask listeners to 
call their lawmakers (1-800/96AFL-CIO) and urge them &quot;not to destroy Medicare - and tell them, 
this time, we're listening.&quot; The federation is also airing minimum wage ads in 11 districts to gin up 
pressure on senators when the bill hits the floor after the July 4 recess. In a letter to union 
presidents, Sweeney warned that tough fights also loom against the so-called TEAM Act and 
national &quot;right-to-work&quot; bill. </p>
<p>THEY CAN RACE, BUT THEY CAN'T HIDE - The <a href="http://www.uaw.org/">UAW </a>and GM Saturn joined the 
Steelworkers' &quot;Don't Buy&quot; campaign against Bridgestone/Firestone by agreeing to allow customers 
of new Saturns to replace, at Saturn's expense, any Firestone tires with another union-made brand. 
The union also warned the tire maker that Saturn may drop Firestone as its exclusive tire when 
contracts expire in 1997. Some 500 USWA members dropped the &quot;Black Flag,&quot; the traditional 
symbol for disqualification, on Bridgestone/Firestone at the Cleveland Medic Drug Grand Prix over 
the weekend. USWA President George Becker also announced a series of worldwide 
demonstrations at the company's plants worldwide next week to commemorate the second 
anniversary of the company's illegal replacement of 2,300 workers during an unfair labor practices 
strike. The union also will run a 30-minute TV program in 20 cities exposing the company's 
activities. </p>
<p>UNION SUMMER ON HILTON HEAD - Union Summer activists descend on the resort village 
of Hilton Head, S.C., this July 4th weekend as part of the drive to organize the low-wage workers 
who toil in the high-priced hotels. Activists plan to carry union signs as they run and walk in the 
Firecracker 5K race. See Union Summer Heat Wave below. </p>
<p><a href="http://www.afscme.org/">AFSCME </a>LOOKS SHARP - Nearly two-thirds of the registered nurses at seven Sharp 
Healthcare facilities throughout the San Diego area voted for representation with AFSCME's 
United Nurses Associations of California. The union has its work cut out: Sharp is in the process of 
being acquired by the anti-union Columbia HCA, the nation's largest for-profit hospital chain. </p>
<p><a href="http://www.teamster.org/">IBT </a>MAKES GRADE - By an almost 2-1 margin (1,129-568) classified supervisors in the Los 
Angeles Unified School District said yes to Teamsters' representation. &quot;Before we had no voice 
and the school district bureaucracy would just ignore our suggestions and complaints,&quot; said Lupe 
Ramirez, area bus supervisor for the district. &quot;Now, with the Teamsters we can be sure to have a 
say in the future of our work, our schools, and the children we serve.&quot; </p>
<p>HOT DOG - Workers at Thornapple Valley, makers of Wilson franks and hot dogs, voted to be 
represented by the Electronic Workers. The 220 member unit in Forrest City, Ark., will be 
chartered as Local 1108. </p>
<p>VICTORY IS SWEET - Agreements were reached last week in three major disputes. Striking and 
locked-out Food and Commercial Workers in Denver and other Colorado towns are back on the 
job after ratifying a new three-year contract with King Soopers and Safeway. The pact, covering 
some 14,000 members of Local 7, includes wage increases and boosts in health and pension 
benefits and job protection. Consumer pressure and worker solidarity helped end the dispute. 
Some 1,200 Paperworkers, locked out since January by Trailmobile in Charleston, Ill., were voting 
Monday on a tentative pact hammered out after an international campaign for justice. And San 
Francisco Bay area janitors, some 5,000 members of SEIU Local 1877, are voting this week on a 
deal to end their four weeks of rolling strikes against offices and high-tech firms that subcontract for 
janitorial work. </p>
<p>POST IT - Thousands of <a href="http://www.apwu.org/">Postal Workers</a> were picketing postal facilities across the country July 1 
to alert the public to attempts to privatize the U.S. Postal Service, problems of postal 
mismanagement and other threats to continued quality service. The demonstrations were held on 
the 25th anniversary of the founding of the union and the creation of USPS as an independent 
agency. </p>
<p>WORK AT ART - Tens of thousands of jobs are in jeopardy, and millions of others could be 
affected, if the GOP is able to kill funding for the Institute of Museum Services, the National 
Endowment for the Humanities and the National Endowment for the Arts are successful, unions 
representing these professional employees say. Trade unionists are urged to press Congress for 
funding for those programs as requested by the White House. </p>
<p>PLANE FIGHT CONTINUES - In the first bargaining session since the strike began June 5, 
Machinists and McDonnell Douglas in St. Louis resumed bargaining June 27 under the auspices of 
the Federal Mediation and Conciliation Service. IAM District 837 members have denounced the 
hiring of replacement workers and the transfer of work to other plants or subcontractors since the 
strike began. In a tragic sidelight to the strike, a Navy F/A-18C Hornet fighter crashed June 19 
outside a St. Louis suburb after having major repair work done by white-collar supervisors at the 
plant. A cause of the crash has not been determined. </p>
<p>NYC HOSPITALS FORCE STRIKE - About 7,500 Service Employee Local 144 health care 
workers are on strike against 13 New York City hospitals and nursing homes. They walked out 
June 24 when management refused to budge from their proposal for a one-year wage freeze, a 
two-tier wage scale and reduced sick leave. The local is a broad spectrum of workers from 
housekeepers to X-ray technicians - who had been working without a contract since the previous 
pact expired seven months ago. Bargaining resumed June 27. The union has set up a strike hotline: 
1-800/875-4219. </p>
<p>TAKE TIME FOR THE FAMILY - The AFL-CIO applauded President Clinton's plan to expand 
the Family and Medical Leave Act by granting up to 24 hours a year for children's school activities 
and family medical needs, urging Clinton to go further and expand FMLA to cover workers in firms 
smaller than the current 50-employee threshold. But unions rejected Clinton's proposal to relax the 
Fair Labor Standards Act overtime provisions. Even worse, a House committee last week 
approved a GOP-backed bill that gives employers the right to offer compensatory time instead of 
paid overtime. With lax employee protections, workers could be forced to give up their overtime. </p>
<p>RETIREES SEEK SLICE OF PIE - Union workers who gave their all for GE rallied June 24 in 
two dozen locations nationwide for a bigger share of the company's overfunded pension plan. The 
15 GE unions in the Coordinated Bargaining Committee said even if pensions were doubled, the 
fund still would have a surplus. Under a negotiated agreement, the company and employees 
contribute to the pension fund - but GE's investments have been so profitable the company hasn't 
put a penny toward the fund since 1987. </p>
<p>DON'T PARK HERE - Oglebay Park in Wheeling, W.Va., has been added to the AFL-CIO 
boycott list at the request of the Hotel Employees and Restaurant Employees. More than 80 
percent of the workers at park voted for HERE representation but the Wheeling Park Commission 
has harassed, fired and intimidated supporters and refuses to recognize the union. </p>
<p>NO MERIT IN BUFFALO - Thousands of Buffalo trade unionists rallied June 24 against Merit 
Construction Alliance, which is trying to impose lower wages and 12-hour workdays, withdraw 
health benefits and create unsafe working conditions on Buffalo-area trades workers. The company 
also has waged a lie-filled $200,000 advertising campaign against the Buffalo Building and 
Construction Trades Council. </p>
<p>NY TEACHERS INK AGREEMENT - New York City teachers and other educational 
employees approved a five-year contract seven months after rejecting an earlier offer. The deal 
increases wages for members of AFT's United Federation of Teachers by 13 percent over term 
and guarantees job security for union members until 1998. </p>
<p>COMBATTING SEXUAL HARASSMENT - The UAW will offer intensive training sessions for 
100 local union officials to heighten workers' awareness of sexual harassment at the Mitsubushi 
Motor Manufacturing plant in Normal, Ill. The UAW also has proposed a joint union-company 
comprehensive sexual harassment awareness program involving virtually the entire Mitsubishi work 
force. Meanwhile, U.S. and Japanese women's groups protested June 27 outside the company's 
shareholders meeting in Tokyo. </p>
<p>UNSAFE AT ANY BORDER - Most trucks entering the United States from Mexico are not 
inspected and almost half the small number that are have dangerous safety problems, a new report 
from the U.S. Department of Transportation says. With NAFTA boosting the number of Mexican 
trucks on U.S. highways, serious accidents will occur, the Teamsters charged. Only about 2 
percent of trucks crossing the border were inspected between December 1995 and March 1996, 
but nearly half of the 12,462 trucks inspected were taken out of service because of dangerous 
safety violations. </p>
<p>FOUL BALLS - Foul Ball is an organization aiming to end the exploitation of kids in the soccer 
ball industry in Pakistan. Labor Secretary Robert Reich attended the group's kickoff to keep 
Pakistani children from stitching soccer balls. He later opened hearings to report on the U.S. 
garment industry's efforts to monitor the use of child labor in products imported from other 
countries. Anne Knipper of the AFL-CIO was among those who testified. </p>
<h2>Heat Wave -- July 2, 1996</h2>
<p>A new crop of Union Summer activists arrived in Charleston, S.C., this weekend. They will 
accompany hotel and restaurant workers to their jobs in Hilton Head and picket hotels in the 
continuing effort to unionize the resort hotels in the city. </p>
<p>In Los Angeles, activists continue their voter registration drive and their efforts to organize home 
health care workers and the local supermarket chain, Superior Markets. This weekend they joined 
a Hotel and Restaurant Employees' picket of a nonunion restaurant at Los Angeles International 
Airport. </p>
<p>Every day this week, Union Summer activists in Nashville will picket and leaflet Mastercare centers 
owned by Bridgestone/Firestone. They are organizing a massive action on July 12, the second 
anniversary of the USWA's labor dispute with Bridgestone Inc. </p>
<p>In just two weeks, San Diego Union Summer activists have already met with more than 150 union 
members. This week they will organize precinct walks and community meetings in support of the 
eight-hour day, the minimum wage initiative and San Diego Needs a Raise. </p>
<p>Seattle Union Summer activists finished out their internships with two rallies. Over 300 interns, 
Teamsters and supporters conducted a mass picket at the regional headquarters of Browning- 
Ferris Industries in nearby Bellevue. They raised a deafening roar by using garbage can lids as 
symbols, forcing BFI's top manager to come out of the plant. A 20-year-old Union Summer activist 
handed the official a mountain of petitions containing over 10,000 signatures calling for BFI to 
respect both their workers and the environment. Earlier in the day, a similar-sized group stormed 
the University of Washington's administration building and occupied it temporarily while SEIU 
District 925 members presented the school's chief negotiator demands for a fair and equitable 
contract. </p>
<p>In Watsonville, Union Summer activists continue their work on the strawberry campaign. This week 
they will lead delegations of farm workers to local supermarkets to educate store managers about 
working conditions in the strawberry fields. They will also meet with Dolores Huerta of the United 
Farm Workers, and tour the UFW headquarters. </p>
<p>Next week, Union Summer starts up in three new locations - New Orleans, New York and 
Sacramento. A second wave of internships begins in Akron, Boston, Chicago, Detroit and St. 
Louis. The San Diego internship continues. And the first of three internships in Watsonville, Calif., 
comes to an end. Thus, young activists will be walking the pavement and talking to workers in 10 
cities across the country. </p>
<p>SUMMER'S HERE! COOL GEAR! - Update your wardrobe with the latest in Union Summer 
fashions - 25-cent buttons, $9 purple and white baseball caps and $12 light grey or purple adult 
T-shirts with the four-color logo front and back in L, XL and 2XL - now available from the 
AFL-CIO. Free full-color posters and $8 VHS videos also are yours for the ordering. Send name, 
organization, local number, street address, city, state, ZIP code, phone and FAX numbers and a 
check or money order made payable to AFL-CIO, PMO, 815 16th St. N.W., Room 209, 
Washington, D.C. 20006. District of Columbia residents only need to add 5.75 percent sales tax. </p>
<hr>
<p>For Executive Council statements, reports and press conference transcripts, check out 
LaborNET's &quot;News and Views&quot; library on <a href="http://www.compuserve.com">CompuServe</a>, or <a href="http://www.aflcio.org">LaborWEB</a>, the AFL-CIO's Web site 
located at http://<a href="http://www.aflcio.org">www.aflcio.org</a>. To send information for inclusion, or FAX numbers to receive 
Work in Progress, FAX to 202/508-6908, or via E-mail <a href="mailto:71112.53@compuserve.com">71112.53@compuserve.com</a>.</p>
