<body>
<h2 align="center">AFL-CIO Work in Progress</h2>
<p>NO CHEERS FOR NEWT -- Compelling evidence that America Needs a
Raise came in Boston June 18 as the AFL-CIO completed a series of
29 town hall meetings focusing on the challenges facing American
workers. Down the street, House Speaker Newt Gingrich (R-Ga.) and
two Massachusetts GOP congressmen were attending a $1,000-a-plate
dinner with their corporate backers, so AFL-CIO
Secretary-Treasurer Richard Trumka posted an oversized letter in
front of TV's Cheers tavern, inviting the House members &quot;to
give up that dinner and come to listen to Boston's working
families.&quot; </p>
<p>GOP MUZZLE -- &quot;Congress has entered the silly
season,&quot; said Rep. Matthew Martinez (D-Calif.) at a hearing
on a bill designed to muzzle labor's political voice. GOP leaders
claim their concern is the rights of union members, but
&quot;anyone who believes that should have their head
examined,&quot; Martinez said. AFL-CIO President John Sweeney
said the hearings weren't called &quot;to examine the right of
union members to spend part of their dues money on issue-based
political education. They were called as part of an orchestrated
assault on America's unions for our new vigilance and vitality on
behalf of U.S. working families.&quot; </p>
<p>PSST...WANNA BUY AN ELECTION? -- Despite anguished wails from
GOP leaders about labor's political education efforts, businesses
and their allies far outspend worker groups, according to a new
Federal Election Commission Report. The FEC found that so far in
the 1995-96 campaign cycle, big business has given almost four
times as much to candidates as all of labor. The majority of
business contributions -- some $46.3 million -- went to
Republicans. </p>
<p>SUMMER BREEZE -- <a href="http://www.aflcio.org/usummer">Union
Summer</a> activists helping to organize women in the Akron,
Ohio, area, were urged to spread the good news about unions to
coalition groups who share unions' concerns about the plight of
working families. Karen Nussbaum, director of the federation's
Working Women's Department, visited the Akron Union Summer
contingent, an all-female group, on June 20. See the Union Summer
&quot;Heat Waves&quot; update on Page 3. </p>
<p>REMEMBER IN NOVEMBER -- Government employees from around the
country are set to &quot;Rally for Action&quot; on the U.S.
Capitol's West Steps Wednesday. The rally's focus is jobs, health
care, OSHA &quot;reform&quot; and other issues. It is part of
AFGE's &quot;Remember in November&quot; political action
campaign. AFGE President John Sturdivant, AFL-CIO
Secretary-Treasurer Trumka and several Democratic and Republican
lawmakers will speak. Vice President Gore is scheduled to address
the union's legislative conference on Tuesday. </p>
<p>UAW TAKES NEW TACK -- The <a kers at two johnson controls
plants. the recognition, gained without an election, covers
plants in plymouth and oberlin, ohio. the1 union has targeted
another johnson1 plant in1 strongsville, ohio, and1 four plants1
owned by dana corp. p>WON IN LAS VEGAS -- The Hotel Employees and
Restaurant cognition for 1,300 workers at the Stratosphere Hotel. </a></p>
<p><a kers at two johnson controls plants. the recognition,
gained without an election, covers plants in plymouth and
oberlin, ohio. the1 union has targeted another johnson1 plant in1
strongsville, ohio, and1 four plants1 owned by dana corp. p>GORES
HEAR WORKERS -- &quot;When there is a conflict between company
needs and family needs, the company wins out,&quot; </a><a
href="http://www.uniteunion.org/">UNITE </a>member Debbie Allen,
an employee of Fingerhut in Piney Flats, Tenn., told
Viceadquarters of Bridgestone/Firestone, which forced 4,000
workers out on strike almost two years ago and illegally replaced
some 2,300 of them. Bridgestone/Firestone working families
participating in the conference came from Decatur, Ill., Des
Moines, Iowa, Oklahoma City, Noblesville, Ind., and Nashville.
Also attes employed by Bob Appetit have joined Service Employees
Local 715, while 38 custodians and maintenance employees in the
Weatherford, Conn., are now members of SEIU Local 760. </p>
<p>PROUD TO SUPPORT UNIONS -- President Clinton told more than
4,000 delegates and guests to AFSCME's convention last ilable on
AFSCME's home page: http:\\<a href="http://www.afscme.org/">www.afscme.org</a>. </p>
<p>TRUCK STOP ROCK -- Hundreds of Southern California <a
href="http://www.teamster.org/">Teamsters</a>, Mexican unionists
and environmental activists rallied in San Diego June 18 to
protest lifting a NAFTA ban on unsafe ght Director Dennis
Skelton. </p>
<p>NALC IN RUNYON'S FACE -- Thousands of <a
href="http://www.apwu.org/">Letter Carriers</a> marched in front
of Post Offices across the country June 19 vowing not to allow
Postmaster General Marvin T. Runyon to take the
&quot;service&quot; out of the U.S. Postal Service tlied for a
fair contract June 21. UFCW Local 7 delivered a comprehensive
package of proposals to both companies and met with management
that same day. At the rally in front of King Soopers
headquarters, workers displayed 100 feet of three-foot tall snow
fence covered with thousands of cards signed by customers pleill
join SEIU Local 1877's 4,000 janitors as they enter their fourth
week of &quot;rolling strikes&quot; in the San Francisco Bay
area. Local 87 represents janitors in the city of San Francisco.
Nearly 1,000 of the janitors in San Ramon and Oakland have agreed
to intensify the strike and stay out for the dura it includes a
wage freeze until October 1997, a $1 million training fund for
union members and a commitment by Kaiser to develop in the next
90 days a computerized job matching system. Laid-off workers will
receive 160 hours of paid training under the contract, and the
company agreed not to subcontract work if it would lead to
layoffs of Local 399 members. </p>
<p>BERRY WORK HAS NOT BEENd to remind festival-goers of the human
suffering involved in producing the harvest the industry
celebrated. The vigil was part of the UFW's campaign to organize
strawberry workers who endure poverty wages and filthy sanitary
facilities -- and who are sometimes forced to use the fields as
rest roomslas' St. Louis plant were shocked by comments during
negotiations from company President Herb Lanese, who said workers
shouldn't consider their counterparts at Boeing and Lockheed
Martin as their brothers and sisters, and that he hoped children
of workers at competing companies &quot;starved to death.&quot;
Donations to hel00 locked-out Trailmobile workers gathered June
19 in front of the Indonesian embassy to protest the
Indonesian-owned company's conduct. The same day, the Australian
Council of Trade Unions held a solidarity demonstration outside
the Indonesian embassy in Canberra. The Paperworkers at the
company's Clinton's re-election, the Electronic Workers June 18
endorsed the Clinton-Gore ticket. In addition, the union
executive board approved a special assessment to support in full
the AFL-CIO's political education campaign. </p>
<p>NEW LEADERSHIP IN STATE FEDS -- Alan Hughes was elected
president of the Arkansas AFLate court. Meanwhile, Gil Koetzle
was elected president of the South Dakota AFL-CIO. Koetzle, a
member of Fire Fighters Local 814, is also a member of the South
Dakota House of Representatives. </p>
<p>WORK IS ART -- The Labor Heritage Foundation's 18th Annual
Great Labor Arts Exchange began Sundtools that unions can use in
organizing drives. </p>
<h2>HEAT WAVES</h2>
<p>Working on an innovative new campaign with SCORE (Summit
County Organizing for Rights and Equality), Union Summer
activists at the all-woman site in Akron will go door-to-door to
visit hundreds of workers to discuss wages, benefits and s in
Boston, Union Summer activists registered 350 voters in
neighboring Lynn, joined locked out ComGas workers on their
mobile picket line, and created a &quot;Human Billboard&quot;
outside City Hall to support America Needs a Raise. </p>
<p>Charleston, South Carolina Union Summer activists spent last
weEmployment. </p>
<p>After gathering more than 3,000 signatures on petitions
opposing California's anti-affirmative action ballot measure this
weekend, Los Angeles activists will register voters, organize
non- union home health care workers, picket Superior Markets, and
support the Otani Hotel boycott. </p>
<p>Union Summer acbeen supportive with the Miami Herald boycott. </p>
<p>St. Louis activists will support striking workers at McDonnell
Douglas, protest unfair labor practices in the riverboat gambling
industry, and gather signatures on petitions to raise the minimum
wage in Missouri. </p>
<p>Union Summer activists in San Diego plan to talk to 5,000
union members in the community in the next several weeks,
supporting the Minimum Wage initiative and San Diego Needs A
Raise. </p>
<p>Seattle Union Summer activists will help organize the nearly
4,000 office, technical and professional workers at the
University of Washington who are negotiating for a new contract. </p>
<p>Last week, activists in Washington, D.C. joined 200 UNITE!
members to protest at a Hecht's Department store that sells suits
made in non-union factories with low-quality working conditions. </p>
<p>Union Summer activists in Watsontrawberry fields. This
weekend, they organized a silent vigil at the annual Strawberry
Festival. </p>
