<body>
<h2 align="center">AFL-CIO Work in Progress</h2>
<h3 align="center">June 18, 1996</h3>
<p>HAVE YOU BARGAINED WITH A FORD LATELY? _ The UAW opened
bargaining with the first of the Big Three automakers June 10
when it sat down with Ford Motor Co., but UAW President Steve
Yokich refused to begin the ceremony until a reporter from USA
Today left the room. USA Today is the flagship publication of
Gannett, the owner of the struck Detroit News. Talks opened June
11 with Chrysler and June 12 with General Motors. Contracts for
about 400,000 hourly workers expire Sept. 14. </p>
<p>SENATE STALLS ON WAGES _ New, more conservative Senate leaders
have yet to say how they plan to deal with the House-passed
minimum wage bill. But they are expected to strike back at
labor's success through anti-worker amendments and companion
bills. If Republicans do not schedule a vote soon, Democrats warn
they will try to attach the pay raise to every bill that moves to
the Senate floor. AFL-CIO President John Sweeney told union
presidents the federation may go back on the air with minimum
wage ads targeted at House members who voted no and at senators
who warrant pressure. </p>
<p>STATES MOVE ON WAGES _ On the state and city level, pay raise
measures are moving. Delaware and Vermont passed laws increasing
the minimum wage. The California living wage initiative garnered
enough signatures to get a place on the fall ballot. And just
days after President Sweeney urged Colorado Gov. Roy Romer to
veto a bill denying a place on the ballot to minimum wage
initiatives issues, Romer killed the bill. Living wage drives are
under way in Boston, Chicago and Denver. </p>
<p>DON'T TOUCH THAT DIAL _ New York's WBAI-FM begins broadcasting
&quot;Union Summer Radio Show&quot; on July 1. The hour-long show
will highlight the campaign and its activists, and will be made
available to other public radio stations throughout the country.
See updates on the Union Summer Heat Waves on page 3. </p>
<p>HOW GRIM IS MY (SILICON) VALLEY? _ Imelda, a Mexican
immigrant, told the AFL-CIO's San Jose, Calif., town hall meeting
June 11 that workers like her need a raise. Imelda used to
provide care for an 82-year-old woman who lives by herself. But
earning only $4.25 an hour for just a few hours a day, the
eight-months- pregnant mother of one could not afford day care
for her daughter and is now out of work. &quot;When I used to
take care of this woman, my work reflected compassion and
quality, but this doesn't seem to mean anything in the labor
market,&quot; she said. In Atlanta last week, workers sang
&quot;My job lies over the ocean&quot; to the tune of &quot;My
Bonnie Lies . . .&quot; And in Pittsburgh, ebullient workers
joined the America Needs a Raise chorus. The final scheduled
event is this week in Boston. </p>
<p>KEEP 'EM FLYING _ Pilots at Southern Air Transport voted for
Teamsters representation, capping a three-year effort. The
workers fly cargo worldwide, including into &quot;hot spots&quot;
for the U.S. military. Meanwhile, at Phoenix-based America West
Airlines, stock clerks filed IBT authorization cards, following
the lead of the airline's mechanics who voted for the IBT in
April. </p>
<p>TRASHING THE GREEDY _ As janitors and their supporters rallied
around the country June 12, Justice for Janitors Day, more than
5,000 janitors in the San Francisco Bay Area prepared for their
third week of &quot;rolling&quot; strikes. Talks continue between
SEIU Local 1877 and eight contract cleaning firms. On Father's
Day, June 16, the janitors held a candlelight vigil and speakout
at the home of Cisco Systems CEO John Chambers, one the largest
clients of Acme, which refuses to negotiate a fair deal. The June
12 observance also called attention to &quot;America's Top
Trash&quot; companies _ nonunion cleaning companies that refuse
to pay decent wages. The 1996 nominees are Hewlett-Packard,
Contract Cleaning Inc., Marine Midland Bank, DQE Inc., University
of South Carolina, Tri-C Community College, Lawrence Lui, City of
Hartford, P&amp;R Enterprises Inc., Creative Building Maintenance
and Koll Real Estate Services. </p>
<p>FIGHTING BACK IN ST. LOUIS _ AFL-CIO President Sweeney joins
Machinists on the picket line at McDonnell Douglas in St. Louis
Tuesday, emphasizing that the IAM members are holding the line
for the entire labor movement. The workers face outrageous
company antics _ temporary replacement workers, increased
subcontracting and a proposal to grant workers one wage increase
in the next four years. IAM District 837 notes that McDonnell
Douglas has $770 million in after-tax profits and a
one-quarter-billion-dollar surplus in its pension fund, but
refuses to bargain additional raises and health care cost
reductions for future retirees. </p>
<p>HILLARY, DETROIT STRIKERS MEET _ First Lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton met with 16 Detroit newspaper strikers last week. The
strikers urged that the Justice Department investigate blatant
violations of the joint operating agreement during the 11-month
strike of the Detroit News and Detroit Free Press. The JOA
governs business practices of the two scab newspapers. </p>
<p>TITHING FOR ORGANIZING _ Communications Workers meeting in
convention in Detroit last week passed a constitutional amendment
requiring the union to devote 10 percent of resources to
organizing. They endorsed the Clinton-Gore presidential ticket,
and heard President Morton Bahr promise &quot;the most vigorous,
energetic and effective political action program that CWA has
ever waged.&quot; </p>
<p>AFSCME IN ACTION _ The November elections loom importantly for
more than 4,000 delegates gathered in Chicago this week at
AFSCME's 32nd convention. &quot;What's at stake is whether
America will be country where every family can get ahead and no
worker is ever left behind, or whether it will be a nation where
only a few make to the top while the rest of us are left to fight
it out on the bottom,&quot; AFSCME President Gerald McEntee told
the delegates. AFL-CIO President John Sweeney and Executive Vice
President Linda Chavez- Thompson also will address the
convention. Get up-to-the-minute coverage of the convention
on-line by going to the AFSCME home page: http:\\www.afscme.org </p>
<p>SHUTTING DOWN FOR ELECTION DAY '96 _ The Service Employees
will put the power of their people behind the power of their
political convictions, shutting down headquarters for the final
two weeks before the November election to facilitate the full
participation of officers, members and staff in this year's
critical elections. SEIU is asking its members to pledge to work
five days between now and November on the national, state or
local level. </p>
<p>IT'S A WRAP AT REYNOLDS _ Aluminum, Brick and Glass Workers
and Steelworkers have ratified six-year contracts with Reynolds
Metals Co. and the Aluminum Company of America, covering more
than 16,000 workers. The agreements increase wages, pension
benefits and job security. </p>
<p>NO TO TRAILMOBILE _ Paperworkers locked out by Trailmobile
Corp. in Charleston, Ill., rejected the latest contract offer by
an 80 percent margin. The company was trying to extend for three
years a wage freeze that has been in effect for nearly four
years. UPIU Local 7951 members also objected to provisions having
the union drop all pending National Labor Relations Board charges
and the local's president apologize for the union's bargaining
strategy. </p>
<p>A LITTLE JINGLE IN THE JEANS _ UNITE, which represents workers
at Levi Strauss &amp; Co., praised the jeans maker's plan to
offer a year's salary as a bonus to all of its 37,600 workers
worldwide, if the company meets its cash flow target by the end
of its 2001 fiscal year. &quot;It is entirely appropriate that a
company as successful and progressive as Levi Strauss &amp; Co.
share the gains of its success with the workers who have helped
make it all possible,&quot; said UNITE President Jay Mazur. </p>
<p>NOT KIDS STUFF _ President Sweeney urged the International
Labor Organization to adopt a convention to ban child labor
&quot;in its most dangerous, degrading and exploitative
forms.&quot; Addressing a ministerial conference June 12 in
Geneva, Switzerland, Labor Secretary Robert B. Reich also called
for an end to child labor abuses. </p>
<p>BRAZIL NEEDS A RAISE _ The AFL-CIO has thrown its support
behind a June 21 general strike called by International
Confederation of Free Trade Unions (ICFTU) Brazilian affiliates _
CUT, Forca Sindical and CGT. In Washington, the demonstration
runs from noon to 1 p.m. at the Brazilian Embassy, 3006
Massachusetts Ave. N.W. Others events are set at Brazilian
consulates in Boston, Los Angeles, Miami and San Francisco. </p>
<p>A NEW DEAL _ Union Privilege selected Household International
to take over the Union Privilege credit card program from The
Bank of New York. President Sweeney said the agreement &quot;will
provide great benefits to our members and give a tremendous boost
to the AFL-CIO and its unions in our efforts to revitalize the
labor movement.&quot; The program will continue to offer a credit
card at a rate well below the national average and will add new
types of cards to meet the needs of more union members. An added
bonus: Household has committed to protecting the rights of
workers to organize. </p>
<p>UNITE PRESSES PEERLESS SUITS _ More than 200 UNITE members
marched on a Gaithersburg, Md., Hecht's department store in
support of workers at Peerless. The mostly immigrant workers at
the Montreal factory of one of North America's largest makers of
men's suits, suffer low wages, sexual harassment and unfair
hiring and firing. The store's managers got so frazzled they
locked out shoppers along with the protesters. </p>
<p>DON'T BOOK EM' DANO _ If you're traveling to Hawaii, call
ahead and ask the hotel if it has a signed union contract. Some
12,000 Longshoremen and Warehousemen have been working without a
contract for nearly a year. The hotels include the Hilton
Waikoloa, the Sheraton Orchid at Mauna Lani and Kauai Resort,
which is on the AFL-CIO boycott list. </p>
<p>BRIEFS:<br>
Union Summer activists in Akron will meet with Karen Nussbaum,
director of the AFL-CIO Working Women's Department, on Thursday
to discuss women in unions. Nussbaum will also speak at an
evening community forum. </p>
<p>During their last week in Boston, activists will protest at a
hearing on hospital privatization, visit city council districts
to generate support for laundry workers, and join a rally for
immigrant workers' rights. </p>
<p>In Denver, as part of a Justice For Janitors campaign,
activists helped force a cleaning contractor to recognize the
union. This week, they will protest at a Metro Waste Water
Reclamation District meeting in support of employees who have not
had a contract in two years. They will also join truck drivers to
picket a local five-star hotel. </p>
<p>Motor City Union Summer will wrap up this week as activists
organize citywide demonstrations at 150 nonunion drug stores, and
leaflet neighborhoods to support striking newspaper workers. </p>
<p>Georgia Union Summer activists will hold a rally following a
city council hearing to protest hospital privatization. </p>
<p>In Los Angeles, Union Summer will kickoff with a drive to
organize home health care workers. Activists will also picket a
nonunion hotel and conduct house calls to unionize a local
supermarket. </p>
<p>St. Louis activists will continue to protest unfair labor
practices in the riverboat gambling industry and will begin
organizing home health care workers. </p>
<p>Union Summer also begins in San Diego this week, where
activists will focus on the campaign to keep the eight-hour day,
the minimum wage initiative and San Diego Needs a Raise. </p>
<p>Last week in San Jose, Union Summer activists turned out more
than 1,000 workers for the city's America Needs a Raise rally.
This week they continue their activities supporting striking
janitors. </p>
<p>Seattle Union Summer activists will join a letter carriers'
picket to protest new national postal policies, and sit in on the
King County Labor Council meeting to hear about area union
campaigns. </p>
<p>After a week of intensive training on the California Labor
Relations Law, Union Summer law student activists in Watsonville
continue to work to expose violations of the strawberry pickers'
legal rights. More Union Summer activists will hit Watsonville
this week to go into the fields to talk with and organize
workers. </p>
<hr>
<p>For these and other stories, check out LaborNET's &quot;News
and Views&quot; library on CompuServe, or the <a
href="http://www.aflcio.org/publ/">Public Documents page</a> on <a
href="http://www.aflcio.org">LaborWEB</a>, the AFL-CIO's Web
site, located at http://www.aflcio.org/. To send information for
inclusion, or FAX numbers to receive Work in Progress, FAX to
202/508-6908, or E-mail <a href="mailto:71112.53@compuserve.com">71112.53@compuserve.com</a>.</p>
