<html>
<head>
<title>WIP 06/11/96 AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<h2 align="center">AFL-CIO Work in Progress</h2>
<h3 align="center">June 11, 1996</h3>
<p>THE WORD ON THE STREET -- Main Street came to Wall Street June
6 when AFL-CIO President John Sweeney issued a challenge to
America's financial community as thousands of New York-area
workers cheered. &quot;For the past 20 years, Wall Street and
corporate America have been putting profits before people,&quot;
Sweeney charged. &quot;Our message to business: Low wages are bad
business and they are bad for business -- put some confidence in
our ideas, put some dollars in our pockets and we'll put you on
the map ANYWHERE IN THE WORLD! The following day, Sweeney carried
his tough message for corporate America to the City Club in
Cleveland, after which local working families, retirees and other
community members shared their personal stories. </p>
<p>ON THE ROAD FOR A RAISE -- Elsewhere on the cross-country
America Needs a Raise campaign, Secretary-Treasurer Rich Trumka
and Executive Vice President Linda Chavez-Thompson listened to
workers in town hall meetings in Baltimore, Albuquerque, N.M.,
and Wichita, Kan. In Baltimore, a 45-year-old minimum wage worker
with six children brought the audience to tears and action as he
explained he was about to be evicted from his apartment. &quot;I
just want a decent paying job,&quot; he said. This week, town
hall meetings are set for San Jose, Pittsburgh and Atlanta. </p>
<p>ROLLIN' UP THE WINS -- Workers are saying Union YES in
workplaces across the country. Respect and fairness were key for
workers at Beatrice Cheese Co., in Mayville, Wis. They brushed
off an anti- union campaign by the company to vote 152-138 for
the Machinists. In St. Louis, what began as a social cookout
ended with 224 employees of the Parkway School District voting
for representation with the Electronic Workers. &quot;I just feel
the union had done so much for me over the past 19 years that I
would like to share the benefits of the union with others,&quot;
said Gary Hodges, president of IUE Local 823, who heard the
workers complain at the cookout and helped them find the
solution. Locomotive mechanics on the Wheeling &amp; Lake Erie
Railroad voted for representation by the Brotherhood of Railroad
Signalmen. And the on-air staff at WFAS AM/FM in White Plains,
N.Y., voted to be represented by the Television and Radio
Artists. </p>
<p>ROCKY TIMES FOR STRUCK STORES -- The 13,000 striking and
locked-out workers at Colorado Safeways and King Sooper groceries
picked up support from other workers and the community as more
people understand the impact of downsizing. Some 617 employees of
Safeway stores in northern Colorado went on strike June 2 after
contracts expired, while the struck stores have lost about 60
percent of their customers since the strike began May 14. GOP
LABOR-BASHING CONTINUES -- Republicans call it the Workers
Right-To-Know Act, but the only thing right about it is that is
yet another right-wing attack on unions. &quot;This bill is
calculated to chill the exercise of our First Amendment rights to
inform our members and the public about the attacks this Congress
is leading against working families,&quot; President Sweeney
said. Even though the current law already imposes on unions the
strictest financial disclosure rules of any organization, and
says employees represented by unions do not have to financially
support union political activities to which they object, the bill
would impose Draconian new rules with the kind of odious
paperwork requirements Republicans profess to oppose. </p>
<p>KEEPING HEAT ON -- Young activists are spreading the message
that working families need a break in Union Summer campaigns in
San Jose, Calif., Akron, Ohio; Atlanta; Boston; Charleston, S.C.;
Chicago; Denver; Detroit; Miami; Oakland, Calif.; San Francisco;
Seattle; St. Louis; Washington; and Watsonville, Calif. See Union
Summer UPDATE, attached. No matter where you are, you can send a
similar message back to Washington as the Senate tries to figure
out what to do with the bill to raise the minimum wage. Now is
the time to RAISE YOUR VOICE. Call 1-800/97AFLCIO and tell you
senator that &quot;America Needs A Raise.&quot; </p>
<p>NLRB NOT ON TEAM -- The Team Act &quot;does not provide for
democracy in the workplace&quot; and would &quot;permit employers
to dominate employees,&quot; NLRB Chairman William B. Gould said
in a strongly worded statement urging the Senate to reject the
company union bill. The Senate is expected to act soon on the
bill, S. 295. Call 1-800-97AFLCIO and urge your senators to vote
NO. </p>
<p>BAD BADGER -- Reebok wants to turn the University of
Wisconsin's Bucky Badger into a symbol for sweatshops, but dozens
of pickets marched outside a Board of Regents meeting urging the
body to say &quot;No&quot; to Reebok's devilish deal. The
athletic apparel company has offered the university $7.9 million
over five years for rights to UW athletic gear. Reebok is one of
the worst corporate violators of human rights, paying Indonesian
workers 16-20 cents an hour for six-day-a-week, 10-hour shifts. </p>
<p>MORE FROM CHEESE LAND -- In Racine, labor's efforts played a
big role in tossing an anti-worker state senator out of office in
a recall election. Not only did the GOP lose George Petak's seat
to Democrat Kim Palche, it lost control of the state senate. That
is the first take-back of a state house since the 1994 elections. </p>
<p>IAM GROUNDS McDONNELL DOUGLAS -- Some 6,700 Machinists at
McDonnell Douglas' St. Louis plant walked out June 5 after
rejecting the aerospace company's latest contract offer. Key in
the talks is McDonnell's increasing use of outside contractors
and the transfer of some work to non-union plants in Mesa, Ariz.,
and Macon, Ga. </p>
<p>PEERLESS SOLIDARITY -- About 500 UNITE members stood with
workers from Peerless Clothing International Inc., at a Macy's
Department store in Atlanta, asking for the store's support to
encourage Peerless to treat its workers with dignity. Peerless,
located in Montreal, is the largest manufacturer of men's suits
in North America. Its largely immigrant workers have been
victimized with low wages, sexual harassment and unfair firings. </p>
<p>CWA CONNECTS IN DETROIT -- First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton
headlines the Communications Workers' 58th annual convention,
June 10-12 in Detroit. On June 11, the 3,000 delegates will march
to the Detroit Free Press and Detroit News to support the more
than 2,000 union members who have been on strike at the Detroit
newspapers since July. </p>
<p>JANITORS CAUSING DUST-UP -- Talks between the Service
Employees, representing more than 5,000 janitors, and eight
contract cleaning firms in the San Francisco Bay area resumed
June 7 after a week of selective strikes. The SEIU's Justice for
Janitors campaign has been using surprise as a key element in the
strategic strike, laying down their brooms at a different site
each night. </p>
<p>ATTENDANTS IN FLIGHT -- Some 50 flight attendants have left
ValuJet since a crash in Florida last month that killed all 110
people on board. The Flight Attendants, which is seeking a first
contract at the carrier, are backing legislation, H.R. 3187,
which would make it easier for workers to report safety lapses,
shield workers from company retaliation and protect management
from frivolous complaints. </p>
<p>UN-FREE PRESS -- Washington unions have rallied to the defense
of former Tacoma News Tribune reporter Sandy Nelson, who was
banished from her reporting job in 1990 for off-duty support of a
Tacoma initiative to protect sexual minorities' civil rights. A
caravan of union supporters from Seattle, Tacoma and Portland,
Ore., will travel to Olympia June 11 to support Nelson's appeal
of a lower court ruling supporting the newspaper's action. </p>
<p>PBS HIGHLIGHTS LABOR -- We Do The Work, the only national
television show devoted to covering working people, will examine
the Detroit newspaper strike and the new leadership of the
AFL-CIO on PBS in June. &quot;Workplace Beat: Covering the Bottom
Line&quot; will examine the issues in the 11-month strike.
&quot;State of the Unions&quot; profiles the new leaders of the
AFL-CIO and their vision of how to improve conditions for
American workers. Check your local listings for air times. </p>
<p>FIGHTING THE BOYS IN THE HOODS -- AFL-CIO President Sweeney
presented the National Anti-Extremist Coalition's Courage Award
to Laborers' organizer Randy Siemers for his work in combatting
hate crimes in Billings, Mont. Siemers garnered community support
for a resolution against hate crimes and worked with local police
to boost security at meetings denouncing the crimes. </p>
<p>WORK AT PLAY -- The Working Theater, dedicated to producing
culturally diverse plays about working people, will present a
free staged reading of &quot;A Drop in the Bucket&quot; at
UNITE's New York Joint Board Auditorium on June 13 at 7 p.m., and
on June 14 at 2 p.m. and 7 p.m. The play is about an elderly
retired woman who finds a new lease on life when a spunky
neighbor introduces her to the thrills of Atlantic City. For
reservations, call 212/967-5464. </p>
<hr>
<p>For these and other stories, check out LaborNET's &quot;News
and Views&quot; library on CompuServe, or the <a
href="http://www.aflcio.org/publ/">Public Documents page</a> on <a
href="http://www.aflcio.org">LaborWEB</a>, the AFL-CIO's Web
site, located at http://www.aflcio.org/. To send information for
inclusion, or FAX numbers to receive Work in Progress, FAX to
202/508-6908, or E-mail <a href="mailto:71112.53@compuserve.com">71112.53@compuserve.com</a>.</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="/publ/publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
