<html>
<head>
<title>WIP 06/04/96 AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<h2 align="center">AFL-CIO Work in Progress</h2>
<h3 align="center">June 4, 1996</h3>
<p>STANDING FOR CHILDREN _ More than 50,000 union members
journeyed to Washington on 650 buses for the June 1 &quot;Stand
for Children&quot; rally, with large contingents from AFSCME,
AFT, NY1199, OPEIU and UNITE. The AFL-CIO staffed an information
booth and helped spread the word that &quot;America Needs a
Raise&quot; with 28,000 buttons, signs and fact sheets. The D.C.
event, organized by the Children's Defense Fund, was mirrored by
one in Los Angeles, the &quot;Stand Against Violence Everywhere:
Los Angeles March for Children,&quot; which attracted more than
6,000 participants in a march on City Hall that denounced
violence in the schools and streets of the city. </p>
<p>LETTUCE BACK ON SALAD BAR _ After a bitter 17-year battle,
more than 400 Farm Workers won an historic contract with one of
the nation's largest lettuce growers. The five-year contract ends
the boycotts, litigation and conflict between the UFW and Bruce
Church Inc. It includes wage increases, a grievance procedure,
the establishment of a pension fund, paid holidays and health
insurance. Former UFW President Cesar Chavez died April 23, 1993,
following two days of testimony in the lawsuit between the
parties. </p>
<p>HEAT WAVE _ The first wave of Union Summer activists, nearly
500 young people, fanned out across the nation beginning May 31,
joining in campaigns to organize workers in nursing homes, the
hospitality industry, lumber yards and government buildings. The
recruits also began working with community groups fighting for
living wage initiatives. Union Summer, modeled after the Freedom
Summer civil rights fight of the `60s, is designed to involve
youth in a high-profile campaign for social justice for American
workers and their families. See Union Summer UPDATE, attached. </p>
<p>UP AGAINST THE WAL-MART _ President John J. Sweeney,
Secretary-Treasurer Richard L. Trumka. Executive Vice President
Linda Chavez-Thompson and UFCW President Doug Dority joined human
rights activist Harry Wu and about 1,000 unionists and allies at
a rally outside a Wal-Mart in Las Vegas May 30. They were
protesting the sale of Chinese-made goods by Wal-Mart, which
bills itself as a &quot;Made in America&quot; chain. The AFL-CIO
has called for a boycott of all Chinese-made products during the
month of June to protest China's abuse of human and worker
rights. Trumka will testify before Congress this week against the
Clinton administration's plan to extend most-favored-nation trade
status to China. </p>
<p>EDDIE BAUER, NO SWEAT! _ Eddie Bauer, J. Crew and Kmart sell
clothes made by underage Honduran workers, according to the
National Labor Committee, which last month exposed abuses in
making Wal-Mart's Kathie Lee clothing. At a news conference May
29, Rep. George Miller (D-Calif.) called on retailers to adopt a
&quot;No Sweat&quot; label that assures customers that products
were not made by exploited child labor. </p>
<p>NO CONTRACT, NO WORK _ In the Bay area, more than 5,000
janitors put three-quarters of all commercial office building and
high-tech real estate behind picket lines after their contract
expired May 31. The janitors, represented by Service Employees
Local 1877, demonstrated at the San Jose International Airport
and in Oakland to publicize their union's effort to gain a master
contract. While negotiations were under way for two months,
employers did not respond to the union's proposals or submit any
counter proposals. </p>
<p>WORKERS SADDLE UP WITH TEAMSTERS _ Workers at Fleming Foods in
Warsaw, N.C., voted for representation with Teamsters Local 391.
The vote came after an intimidating two-year campaign by the
company that included racial and sexual harassment. The workers
were encouraged by IBT volunteers from Fleming plants in Oklahoma
City and Houston. </p>
<p>NURSING HOME UNITES _ Fed up with a lack of respect, workers
at Fountainhead Nursing Home in North Miami voted 2-1 for UNITE
representation. The unit will include certified nursing
assistants, housekeeping, laundry and dietary workers. </p>
<p>GOOD TURN FOR SEIU _ On the heels of SEIU Local 250's victory
for AMR workers in Marin County, a unit of EMT's and paramedics
employed by AMR in San Francisco voted unanimously to join the
local. </p>
<p>AGREEMENT AT VENCOR-HILLHAVEN _ Workers' two-year struggle
with the Vencor-Hillhaven nursing home chain in California ended
as three Service Employees locals signed an agreement that calls
for a labor-management patient care committee, a fast election
procedure to gain new members and average annual wage increases
of 7 percent. The agreement gives the workers a greater voice in
the decisions that affect their jobs and their patients. </p>
<p>GOP TAKES AIM AT OSHA AGAIN _ Like a phoenix rising from the
ashes, congressional Republicans have brought back the specter of
cuts in federal safety and health programs in their fiscal year </p>
<p>1997 proposal. Members of the House Appropriations Labor/HHS
subcommittee once again are pushing for very restrictive language
on ergonomics and deep cuts for the National Institute for
Occupational Safety and Health. The subcommittee markup is
scheduled for June 10. </p>
<p>CBTU MARCHES ON HERALD _ Some 400 members of the Coalition of
Black Trade Unionists rallied in front of the Miami Herald
offices May 24, demanding that the Herald's parent,
Knight-Ridder, negotiate a fair contract with striking workers at
the Detroit Free Press. AFL-CIO Vice President William Lucy,
CBTU's president, led the march from the group's annual
convention. </p>
<p>DRIVIN' THAT TRAIN _ The Locomotive Engineers ratified a
contract with many of the largest rail carriers that will raise
wages for 20,000 members at least 10.5 percent by July 1999. The
pact resulted from &quot;two-track&quot; bargaining that assigned
local issues to the general chairman while the international
union addresses more universal issues. Separate performance-share
wage agreements were reached with Norfolk Southern and Santa Fe
railroads, while an agreement with CSX Transportation is awaiting
ratification and talks continue with Conrail. </p>
<p>PORT CALLS _ The Longshoremen's and Warehousemen's Union
distributed leaflets May 30 in communities all along the West
Coast to pitch their case for keeping ports public and
prosperous. The union is concerned with &quot;port privatization
schemes that displace family- and community-supporting jobs with
cut-rate, low-wage operations,&quot; President Brian McWilliams
said. &quot;Worse, various bills are working their way through
Congress that would wreak havoc on American workers and port
communities.&quot; Public ports account for 15.3 million jobs. </p>
<p>UNDERSTANDING MANAGEMENT _ The best insurance against
declining wages and job loss is a work force that understands and
contributes to management decisions, AFL-CIO President Sweeney
told the Federal Mediation and Conciliation Service's
Labor-Management Conference in Chicago May 29. Sweeney outlined
federation plans to promote this understanding through a new
Corporate Affairs Department, which will provide information and
tools for workers on bargaining and pension funds, and a Center
for Workplace Democracy. </p>
<p>WORKING TOGETHER _ Worker participation is critical to state
and local government success, concludes a report by the U.S.
Department of Labor's Task Force on Excellence in State and Local
Government Through Labor-Management Cooperation. Labor members of
the task force include Al Bilik, president of the AFL-CIO Public
Employee Department; AFT Secretary-Treasurer Edward J. McElroy;
Kent Wong, president of the Asian Pacific American Labor
Alliance; and Ken Young, former executive assistant to AFL-CIO
President Emeritus Lane Kirkland. </p>
<p>HOGAN'S NO HERO _ A federal judge turned down a request by the
Maintenance of Way Employees to permit them to bargain separately
with the nation's rail carriers. BMWE President Mac Fleming
charged D.C. District Court Judge Thomas Hogan, a Reagan
appointee, with political bias against the union, noting the
ruling came on the first day of hearings before a presidential
emergency board charged with helping to resolve BMWE's contract
dispute. Hogan said the issue of multiemployer bargaining is a
matter for Congress to decide, not the courts, and ordered the
union not to strike until all steps under the Railway Labor Act
have been taken. </p>
<p>NAFTA SHAFTS ALL WORKERS _ The number of workers with one
full-time, permanent job is declining as part-time jobs and
demand for temporary or contract workers increase in the United
States, Canada and Mexico, according to a preliminary report by
the North American Free Trade Agreement's Commission on Labor
Cooperation. Despite Mexico's well-publicized economic woes, it
was U.S. workers who took the largest beating in real average
weekly earnings from 1984 to 1995, with an 8.5 percent decline. </p>
<hr>
<p>For these and other stories, check out LaborNET's &quot;News
and Views&quot; library on CompuServe, or the <a
href="http://www.aflcio.org/publ/">Public Documents page</a> on <a
href="http://www.aflcio.org">LaborWEB</a>, the AFL-CIO's Web
site, located at http://www.aflcio.org/. To send information for
inclusion, or FAX numbers to receive Work in Progress, FAX to
202/508-6908, or E-mail <a href="mailto:71112.53@compuserve.com">71112.53@compuserve.com</a>.</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="/publ/publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
</body>
