http://aflcio.org:80/publ/wip96/wip0529.html 204.127.237.106 19970215084029 text/html 11679
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.1
Date: Saturday, 15-Feb-97 08:40:16 GMT
Last-modified: Tuesday, 11-Feb-97 21:08:56 GMT
Content-length: 11493
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>WIP 05/29/96 AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<h2 align="center">AFL-CIO Work in Progress</h2>
<p>MEMORIAL DAY BASHES -- Two Memorial Day weekend institutions,
the Indianapolis 500 and the Yale University graduation, were
given a dose of reality courtesy of thousands of union members
and their supporters rallying for justice. Steelworkers from
dozens of cities descended on Indianapolis to &quot;make
Bridgestone/Firestone Inc. a poster child for corporate greed and
irresponsibility,&quot; USWA President George Becker said. In New
Haven, Conn., 8,000 workers and college students conducted a
People's Graduation ceremony to support members of the Hotel
Employees and Restaurant Employees Locals 34 and 35, lower-income
support staff who are being threatened by Yale's plans to
subcontract jobs. Secretary-Treasurer Richard Trumka and the Rev.
Jesse Jackson addressed the rally. </p>
<p>WAGES YES! POISON NO! -- The House May 23 spit back the
Republican leadership's &quot;poison pill&quot; to exempt small
businesses covering millions of workers from wage and overtime
laws, and subsequently voted to raise the minimum wage. AFL-CIO
TV and radio ads in 30 targeted districts in April and May were
the catalyst for the &quot;yes&quot; vote. The bill calls for a
50-cent boost to $4.75 July 1 and another 40-cent increase July
1, 1997. When the Senate takes up the measure in early June,
workers and unions will be pushing to clean up other amendments
House Republicans attached to the bill. </p>
<p>TEAM BENCHED -- Senate GOP leaders want to give their business
backers the anti-workplace-democracy TEAM Act to make up for
being unable to stop a minimum wage hike. It is expected to come
up when the Senate returns to work June 3. There is still time to
call your senators and tell them to vote NO! on the TEAM Act.
Call 1/800- 97AFL-CIO. </p>
<p>A CALL ACROSS THE NATION -- The AFL-CIO's &quot;America Needs
a Raise&quot; campaign was heard far and wide last week as
President Sweeney, Secretary-Treasurer Trumka and Executive Vice
President Linda Chavez-Thompson listened to workers in town hall
meetings in Washington, Detroit, Louisville, Ky., and Nashville,
Tenn. In Washington, a woman with three college degrees has been
unable to find a full-time, permanent position, and she asked,
&quot;How can I encourage my children to seek an education when
they see what it has gotten for me?&quot; In Detroit, college
students with $20,000 in debts before they graduate, pensioners
trying to survive on as little as $50 a month and Detroit
newspaper strikers who have lost 90 percent of their salaries
told their tales to Sweeney and 300 other workers. Presidents Joe
Greene of the School Administrators and Ron Carey of the
Teamsters participated. This week, workers will tell their
stories in Chicago, Las Vegas and Houston. </p>
<p>WORKERS COUNTER GOP SOB SESSION -- Seven GOP House freshmen,
miffed that the AFL-CIO was advertising in their districts about
their votes against working families, tried to stage a publicity
event to whine in front of the federation's headquarters May 23.
But the TV cameras instead captured a spirited rally for raising
the minimum wage. While the House members holed up a block away,
several workers described their struggles, including a restaurant
worker for 15 years who lost her job for taking a vacation and a
47-year-old woman who has been downsized out of three jobs since
1990 and who challenged Republicans opposed to raising the
minimum wage to &quot;buy groceries and pay the rent on the
minimum wage. I can't.&quot; <a href="http://www.afscme.org/">AFSCME</a>
President Gerald McEntee sent emissaries with flowers to bring
the House frosh down to the event. Violins provided by the
AFL-CIO played as the Republicans spoke. Then they headed back to
Capitol Hill where six of the seven again voted against raising
the minimum wage. </p>
<p>A COLLAR ON HOPE -- An investment group headed by Maine's
former Gov. John McKernan is interested in buying a C.F. Hathaway
shirt factory in Waterville, offering hope to more than 500 <a
href="http://www.uniteunion.org/">UNITE</a> members who were told
the 159-year-old plant was closing at the end of the production
season. Meanwhile, Hillary Rodham Clinton offered her support to
workers prior to addressing the state Democratic convention. </p>
<p>HOME TO THE UNION -- <a href="http://www.afscme.org/">AFSCME </a>District
Council 1707 added 710 New York City home care workers to its
rolls when Metrocare employees voted to join the council.
Metrocare is a proprietary care agency funded primarily from
Medicare and Medicaid contracts with agencies to provide home
health aides. </p>
<p>SEIU FOR MENTAL HEALTH -- The <a href="http://www.seiu.org/">Service
Employees</a> organized their fourth mental health and
retardation facility since April when 120 workers in Boston voted
to join SEIU Local 509 under the &quot;Community Care
Campaign.&quot; </p>
<p>CHAINS OF PROTEST -- Striking Detroit newspaper workers
escalated their 10-month campaign for a fair contract by staging
nonviolent civil disobedience actions. Eight strikers chained
themselves to the front door of the Detroit Free Press building
on May 22. None were arrested. Some 200 workers, led by AFL-CIO
President John J. Sweeney, marched in the rain May 23 to the
Detroit News building. Later, 13 were arrested. The march
followed a morning rush hour traffic slowdown by the strikers on
all the city's major expressways. </p>
<p>PROTEST SPECIAL DELIVERY -- More than 2,000 Letter Carriers
converged on Washington May 23 for an emergency conference to
develop a national plan of action to block Postmaster General
Marvin Runyon's &quot;path to destruction.&quot; Aspects may
include national picketing, advertising to educate the public, a
national rally, letter writing, forming a coalition with other
unions, work to rule and a call for Runyon's resignation. Among
other actions, he unilaterally ended the 14-year-old Employee
Involvement process and implemented a new automated process for
preparing mail for carriers' routes that often results in delayed
delivery. </p>
<p>DON'T GO INN -- The AFL-CIO has placed the Four Points by
Sheraton Hotel in Waterbury, Conn., on its national boycott list
at the request of the Hotel Employees and Restaurant Employees.
The union has been in dispute with the hotel since 1989, when
workers were fired for union activity. </p>
<p>TALKING TRASH -- Union and civic activists dumped all over
Browning Ferris Industries, a <a href="http://www.teamster.org/">Teamsters </a>organizing
target, for paying minimal wages to its largely Hispanic and
Iraqi sanitation and recycling workers in Seattle, a city where
90 percent of the garbage haulers are unionized. &quot;I know
these suckers,&quot; Executive Vice President Linda
Chavez-Thompson told a rally outside BFI's plant gate May 16.
&quot;We are talking about people who have no sense of justice
and no sense of fairness for working people in this
country.&quot; </p>
<p>BRINGIN' HOME THE BACON -- The Senate passed a resolution
supporting the Davis-Bacon Act that &quot;drives a stake through
the hearts of proponents of repeal.&quot; Senate and House budget
resolutions assume the prevailing wage law will be repealed. But
Sen. Ted Kennedy's (D-Mass.) resolution backing Davis-Bacon
passed by a 59-41 margin -- and 12 Republicans voted right. The
Davis- Bacon and Service Contract Acts have been under attack
since the GOP took control of Congress in 1994. </p>
<p>CLARIFICATION -- Painters District Council 51 filed the
complaint that resulted in an NLRB ruling upholding contract
provisions against &quot;double breasting.&quot; The ruling,
reported in the May 21 Work in Progress, will benefit about a
half-million building trades workers. </p>
<p>CHINA MFN MOST UNFAVORED -- President Sweeney May 20
criticized the White House decision to seek a waiver of legal
requirements to extend most-favored-nation status to China. The
federation opposes special trade privileges for a regime that
routinely violates human and worker rights and has benefited from
the transfer by U.S. multinational companies of capital,
technology and jobs. Earlier this month, the federation's
Executive Council called for a boycott during June of all
Chinese-made goods. </p>
<p>RIDIN' THE RAILS -- President Clinton has appointed his third
presidential emergency board in two weeks to try to resolve
contract disputes in national rail negotiations. The latest will
make recommendations toward reaching an agreement between major
carriers and the Electrical Workers, Machinists, Railroad
Signalmen and Sheet Metal Workers. Earlier PEBs were established
with respect to the Maintenance of Way Employees and TCU. </p>
<p>DISCRIMINATION AGAINST DISABLED -- The disabled face the same
discrimination as minorities and women and the solution is the
same: an economy based on sharing the wealth and valuing people
over money, President Sweeney told the President's Committee on
Employing People with Disabilities May 23 in Detroit. Another key
is to elect candidates who support America's workers at the
federal, state and local levels. Sweeney also promised that the
AFL-CIO would set an example by continuing to hire disabled
workers. </p>
<p>WORKERS' REVIVAL -- The United Methodist Church passed a
resolution calling for a programmatic approach to addressing
concerns of working Americans. It calls for a nationwide task
force and conference and encourages local parishioners to become
involved with the unemployed, underemployed and local labor.
&quot;By our actions, we seek to proclaim the sacredness of the
workplace and the dignity of its workers,&quot; the church said. </p>
<p>NEW LEADER IN L.A. -- Miguel Contreras was elected executive
secretary-treasurer of the L.A. County Federation of Labor on May
20. He succeeds Jim Wood, who died of cancer in February. </p>
<p>HAPPY ANNIVERSARIES -- May 29 marks the 50th anniversary of
the Mine Workers Health and Retirement Fund. Some 100,000 retired
coal miners, widows and dependents receive pensions and health
benefits through the UMWA Funds. Union Privilege, labor's
benefits provider and key organizing tool, marks its 10th
anniversary. Mortgages, legal services, health care, life
insurance, a credit card, auto club services, loans and assorted
product discounts are available for union members and prospective
members, with new benefits added constantly. </p>
<hr>
<p>For Executive Council statements, reports and press conference
transcripts, check out LaborNET's &quot;News and Views&quot;
library on <a href="http://www.compuserve.com">CompuServe</a>, or <a
href="http://www.aflcio.org">LaborWEB</a>, the AFL-CIO's Web site
located at http://<a href="http://www.aflcio.org">www.aflcio.org</a>.
To send information for inclusion, or FAX numbers to receive Work
in Progress, FAX to 202/508-6908, or via E-mail <a
href="mailto:71112.53@compuserve.com">71112.53@compuserve.com</a>.</p>
