<head>
<title>WIP 05/21/96 AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h2 align=center>AFL-CIO Work in Progress</h2>
<p>BLACK FLAG FOR BRIDGESTONE -- The Steelworkers will disqualify Bridgestone/Firestone 
at the Indianapolis 500 and its rival race, the U.S. 500 in Brooklyn, Mich., by dropping the &quot;black 
flag&quot;, the racing symbol for disqualifying a car for outrageous rules violations. &quot;We intend to drop it 
on this company throughout the Indy car racing season,&quot; said USWA President George Becker. 
The campaign will ask consumers not to buy Bridgestone/Firestone products or services, such as 
tires, golfing equipment, sporting goods or auto repairs at MasterCare centers around the country. 
The company won't get the green flag until all the workers replaced during a 10-month strike that 
ended a year ago are returned to work with back wages and a fair contract is negotiated. </p>
<p>TO GREEDY FROM NEEDY -- With nearly 15,000 Food and Commercial Workers at most 
Denver grocery stores going on strike one day earlier, there was plenty of anger May 15 to fire up 
the AFL-CIO's fifth &quot;America Needs a Raise&quot; town hall meeting. &quot;The greedy are taking from the 
needy,&quot; said Marje Lidalda, whose disability prevents her from continuing her construction trade, 
and now she looks at the $612 a month after taxes from minimum wage jobs. AFL- CIO Executive 
Vice President Linda Chavez-Thompson said the Denver grocery strike is an example of an 
employer trying to &quot;cheapen&quot; its work force by hiring part-time help. &quot;How can you raise a family 
on part-time work?&quot; she asked. This week, the town halls move to Detroit and Washington, with 
President John Sweeney, and to Louisville and Nashville, with Secretary-Treasurer Richard 
Trumka. </p>
<p>TEAM IN PLAY -- Senate Republicans, bitterly resentful at labor's stunning success in getting a 
minimum wage bill to the floor, will strike back with a vote on the company union bill, the so-called 
TEAM Act, probably Thursday. Last week, the AFL-CIO's Sweeney and Trumka were joined by 
Presidents Gerald McEntee of AFSCME, Arthur Coia of LIUNA, Mac Fleming of BMWE, Andy 
Stern of SEIU and John Sturdivant of AFGE at meetings with Democratic senators about the 
TEAM Act. Call your senators and tell them the TEAM Act would allow employers to hand-pick 
employees to represent other employees and should be voted down. Call 1-800-972-3524. 
Senators who need special attention are Hollings (S.C), Nunn (Ga.), Feinstein (Calif.), Lieberman 
(Conn.), Breaux (La.), Bingaman (N.M.), Bradley (N.J.), Graham (Fla.), Kerrey (Neb.), Leahy 
(Vt.), Pyror (Ark.), Reid (Nev.) and Robb. (Va.). </p>
<p>ORGANIZE, ORGANIZE, ORGANIZE -- Workers around the country keep saying &quot;Union 
YES!&quot; Here are some of the most recent wins: </p>
<ul>
<li>City workers in Las Cruces, N.M., voted 202-17 for the Steelworkers, while 180 
administrative support employees with the Massachusetts Turnpike Authority also won 
representation rights with the USWA. And in Pennsylvania, sirens are ringing as employees 
of the Citizens Ambulance Service turned out at three sites to vote for the USWA. </li>
<li>The Hotel Employees and Restaurant Employees Culinary Local 226 and the Stratosphere 
Corp. in Las Vegas reached an agreement on union representation for 1,350 cooks, maids, 
dishwashers, food servers, bell persons and slot change personnel. </li>
<li>Workers at Flambeau Airmold in Roanoke Rapids, N.C., voted for <a href="http://www.uniteunion.org/">UNITE </a>representation. 
Campaign issues included a high rate of carpal tunnel syndrome among workers, mandatory 
tests in order to get raises and a profound lack of respect. </li>
<li>Surfing the Internet helped bring dignity to workers at Concepts for Living in Trenton, N.J. 
A counselor working in the group homes for developmentally disabled adults learned about 
the Communications Workers by reading the <a href="http://www.cwa.org/">union's Home Page</a>. The workers voted 32-5 
for representation in CWA Local 1040. In Louisville, Ky., workers at Alltel voted to join 
CWA Local 3310. </li>
</ul>
<p>STEALING FOOD FROM FAMILIES -- Working families and community groups in 27 key 
congressional districts are telling lawmakers that voting against the minimum wage is like stealing 
food from working families' tables. Backed by AFL-CIO television and radio ads, they will be 
outside grocery stores, congressional offices or food banks with shopping carts filled with $40 
worth of groceries -- the extra food a worker could buy for the family each week if the minimum 
wage was increased by a dollar. Symbolic $40 grocery coupons, &quot;Good only if Congress passes 
the minimum wage bill,&quot; will be passed out at the events. In the TV spot, UFCW member Gary 
Cease tells viewers that such votes are &quot;. . . just wrong. Our congressman should stop playing 
political games and start voting for working families for a change.&quot; Call 1-800-97AFL-CIO and tell 
Congress to increase the minimum wage. </p>
<p>HATHAWAY SHIRTS THREADBARE -- C.F. Hathaway plans to take the shirts off the backs 
of more than 500 workers by shutting down its shirt factory in Waterville, Maine. <a href="http://www.uniteunion.org/">UNITE </a>is trying 
to identify potential buyers for the plant, where shirts have been made since 1837. Two years ago, 
workers gave up their first year of wage increases as part of a joint labor-management effort to 
increase productivity and secure employment. But despite the workers' best efforts, Hathaway 
pulled its eye-patched model from advertising pages and quietly made plans to go down the tubes. </p>
<p>SPECIAL AT BLOOMIES -- Solidarity and determination by members of Retail, Wholesale and 
Department Store Union Local 3 to protect past contract gains at Bloomingdale's brought them a 
new four-year agreement that provides job security for workers who face job loss due to the 
planned closing of two warehouses. The workers showed their strength by demonstrating and tying 
up traffic for an hour in front of the flagship store on 59th Street in New York City. </p>
<p>HOT TIME, SUMMER IN THE UNION -- On May 31, hundreds of young union activists will 
begin to organize workers for social and economic justice in the first leg of the <a href="http://www.aflcio.org/usummer">AFL-CIO's Union 
Summer</a>. Nearly 30 site coordinators are being trained to lead the 18-city venture. &quot;These are the 
role models who we hope will inspire these young people to want to continue to be involved in the 
labor movement,&quot; said Andy Levin, the project director. Applications for the campaign will be 
accepted until June 1. For more information call 1-800-952-2550 or click on the link above. </p>
<p>PHD FOR THE PEOPLE -- The AFL-CIO has organized a &quot;People's Graduation&quot; in a major 
show of solidarity for the Hotel Employees and Restaurant Employees Locals 34 and 35 at Yale 
University, which conducted separate four-week strikes this year over job security and 
outsourcing. Thousands of unionists, community activists and religious leaders will rally during the 
May 27 commencement ceremonies in an effort to win a fair contract for 3,700 Yale employees. 
AFL-CIO Secretary-Treasurer Trumka and the Rev. Jesse L. Jackson are expected to speak. A 
bus will be leaving Washington, D.C. on the 27th at 2:30 a.m. and returning that evening. For more 
information, call Mike Murphy at 202-393-7939. </p>
<p>BUDGET DEJA VU -- The GOP budget resolution passed by the House last week and under 
consideration this week in the Senate parallels the Medicare-cutting, budget-slashing document that 
fueled last year's bitter budget battle. The House bill would eliminate the Mine Safety and Health 
Administration and NIOSH, drastically cut job training programs and terminate Trade Adjustment 
Assistance for workers who lose jobs due to unfair trade. The Senate bill calls for repeal of the 
Davis-Bacon Act. Rep. John Kasich vows that a capital gains tax cuts aimed at the wealthy will be 
added later. </p>
<p>NEW MOBILIZATION -- State field directors are the centerpiece of the new AFL-CIO Field 
Mobilization Department's restructured operations, Marilyn Sneiderman, field mobilization director, 
told the Executive Council in Portland. Field directors will work closely with state and local 
AFL-CIOs, operating as organizers and mobilizers in strategic campaigns, organizing, legislative 
and political action, membership mobilization and coalition building. Plans are under way now for a 
state federation conference in the fall and a national conference for central labor councils July 11- 
14 in Denver. </p>
<p>BMWE'S FREIGHT -- AFL-CIO President John Sweeney will testify May 28 for the second time 
before a Presidential Emergency Board on behalf of rail workers, this time for the Brotherhood of 
Maintenance of Way Employees. On May 13, he argued for the Transportation Communications 
Union, noting that the wages of rail workers, like those of most Americans, have stagnated, while 
railroads are reaping enormous profits. &quot;Nowhere is the disparity between the fortunes of 
executives and shareholders on the one hand and the workers on the other more glaring than in the 
railroad industry,&quot; Sweeney said. </p>
<p>BUILDING TRADES VICTORY -- Building trades unions won a big victory May 10 when the 
National Labor Relations Board upheld a contract provision that protects construction workers 
from losing their jobs to &quot;double breasting.&quot; The clause requires signatory companies to apply the 
union contract to all work it controls and which the union members would usually perform. </p>
<p>UNION WARN RIGHTS UPHELD -- The U.S. Supreme Court removed an obstacle to 
organized labor's fight against companies that close plants without warning. The court unanimously 
ruled May 13 in Food and Commercial Workers Local 751 vs. Brown Group Inc., that unions 
could sue for money damages on behalf of their members when an employer violates the Worker 
Adjustment and Retraining Notification Act, better known as the WARN Act. The law requires 
companies to give 60 days advance notice before closing a plant or conducting mass layoffs. </p>
<p>BEVERLY NEEDS LABOR RELATIONS REHAB -- The National Labor relations Board has 
issued a massive complaint against nursing home giant Beverly Enterprises for hundreds of federal 
labor law violations. The board said Beverly made unilateral changes in the terms and conditions of 
employment at 20 Pennsylvania nursing homes after a three-day strike in early April by the Service 
Employees. A trial is scheduled for July 15. </p>
<p>APALA WORKERS LEARN ORGANIZING -- More than 30 Asian Pacific American union 
members participated in the fifth organizing training program in Los Angeles sponsored by the 
Asian Pacific American Labor Alliance and the AFL-CIO Organizing Institute. </p>
<p>HELP FOR 'BAMA TEXTILE WORKERS -- The <a href="http://www.dol.gov/">U.S. Labor Department</a> awarded a grant of 
$3.4 million for 1,200 textile workers who are losing their jobs as a result of closures of 25 apparel 
and textile plants in Alabama. The grant authorized under the Job Training Partnership Act will 
provide skills assessment and training, help finding jobs, counseling, support services such as day 
care and transportation. </p>
<hr>
<p>For Executive Council statements, reports and press conference transcripts, check out 
LaborNET's &quot;News and Views&quot; library on <a href="http://www.compuserve.com">CompuServe</a>, or <a href="http://www.aflcio.org">LaborWEB</a>, the AFL-CIO's Web site 
located at http://<a href="http://www.aflcio.org">www.aflcio.org</a>. To send information for inclusion, or FAX numbers to receive 
Work in Progress, FAX to 202/508-6908, or via E-mail <a href="mailto:71112.53@compuserve.com">71112.53@compuserve.com</a>.</p>
