<head>
<title>WIP 05/14/96 AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<h1 align="center">AFL-CIO Work in Progress -- May 14, 1996</h1>
<p>USA UNION BUSTER _ Last week, some 500 trade unionists told
Gannett's stockholders: If there is no fair contract with
striking workers at the Detroit News, there will be no peace. The
marchers demonstrated outside Gannett's corporate headquarters in
Arlington, Va., during the May 7 stockholders' meeting. Inside,
the stockholders were addressed by representatives and supporters
of the strikers, including the 13-year-old daughter of a striker,
who simply asked Gannett to negotiate an end to the strike so her
family could &quot;have a normal life.&quot; But Gannett
officials cut the girl off before she could finish her statement.
Outside, AFL-CIO President John Sweeney was joined by Presidents
Linda Foley of The Newspaper Guild, James Norton of Graphic
Communications Union and Vincent Sombrotto of the Letter
Carriers, Teamsters Secretary-Treasurer Tom Sever and
Metropolitan Washington AFL-CIO President Joslyn Williams. The
2,000 workers at Gannett's News and Knight-Ridder's Free Press
have been on strike since July 1995. </p>
<p>CONTEMPTUOUS CEO JAILED _ Thomas R. Hochschild, president of
Crystal Window Cleaning Co. in Cleveland, was sentenced to 18
months imprisonment for felonious contempt of court after failing
to obey a federal appeals court order enforcing an NLRB ruling.
This is the first time a company or union has been tried by a
jury for failing to obey an NLRB order, the board's general
counsel said. The NLRB found that Crystal Window illegally
discharged employees and failed to honor a collective bargaining
agreement with the Service Employees. On Sept. 23, 1991, the 6th
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ordered Hochschild to reinstate the
workers, give them back pay and follow the contract. After he
failed to follow the order for almost two years, a jury found him
guilty of felonious contempt. </p>
<p>AMERICA NEEDS A RAISE _ Liz Clybourne is a registered nurse
who works the 7-70 night shift at Kaiser Permanente _ seven
10-hour nights in a row so she can get a week off with her
children. For the past two years, she has been working under a
&quot;garbage contract&quot; _ a 1.5 percent annual wage increase
when the cost of living in Portland, Ore., is averaging increases
between 3 percent and 4 percent. &quot;Now, we may go on strike,
which might wipe me out,&quot; she said. &quot;But that's okay. I
just can't eat the bowl of (crap) that Kaiser is giving me. Some
people might say I'm lucky to have a job. No. They're lucky to
have me,&quot; she said to a rousing ovation by more than 300
people who crowded in the Lutheran Community Center for the
AFL-CIO's fourth &quot;America Needs A Raise&quot; town hall
meeting on May 9. President Sweeney opened the meeting after
rallying Kaiser workers for a fair contract and quality patient
care. &quot;If the AFL-CIO is to speak for working Americans, we
must first take the time to listen,&quot; Sweeney said.
Secretary-Treasurer Richard Trumka went on to a town hall meeting
May 11 in Billings, Mont., where he listened to more workers
describe their efforts to find dignity and livelihood in work.
This week, Executive Vice President Linda Chavez-Thompson hears
from workers in Denver and Seattle. </p>
<p>MORE KAISER CRAP _ The rally led by President Sweeney against
Kaiser Permanente in Portland May 9 boosted some 850 nurses at a
hospital and outpatient clinics who have been without a contract
since April 30. The company is seeking to take away $2 million in
benefits from active and retired nurses, wants to impose a
three-year wage freeze and refuses to give nurses a voice in the
redesign and restructuring of health care services. Contracts
with Kaiser involving some 3,500 workers in Oregon and Washington
expire this year. Already, more than 30,000 Kaiser workers in
California are laboring without a contract. </p>
<p>ALERT FROM THE OREGON TRAIL _ The AFL-CIO Executive Council,
meeting in Portland last week, kept its eye on the outrageous
efforts by Senate Majority Leader Bob Dole (RKan.) to package the
company union bill, the so-called TEAM Act, with an increase in
the minimum wage and a repeal of the 1994 gas tax. Council
members broke from the May 8 session to place emergency telephone
calls to key Democratic senators preparing to caucus on the
issue. Those senators argued persuasively to continue the
filibuster against Dole_s political shenanigans. Another vote is
scheduled this week. Call your senators and urge them to vote
against the TEAM Act and for an increase in the minimum wage, and
insist that these issues be voted on separately. Call 1-800- <strong>96AFLCIO.</strong> </p>
<p>MINERS TURN ON THE JUICE _ The Mine Workers scored a big
organizing win as more than 180 workers at American Electric
Power's Philip Sporn generating station in New Haven, W.Va.,
voted for UMWA representation. Rank-and-file coal miners at Arch
Mineral's Ruffner mine and Peabody Coal Co. helped put the union
over the top at Sporn. </p>
<p>NURSES UNITE _ Licensed practical nurses at Hebrew Home for
the Aged in North Miami Beach voted unanimously to join UNITE.
The LPNs' vote followed a March 21 vote to join UNITE by
certified nursing assistants, housekeeping, laundry and food
workers. </p>
<p>HERE'S THE BEEF _ After a 16-year organizing fight, Food and
Commercial Workers Local 22 has been recognized by the National
Labor Relations Board as the bargaining agent for more than 1,600
employees at the Monfort Inc. beef slaughtering plant in Grand
Island, Neb. Kurt Brandt, an organizer for the local, attributed
the win to the determination of the workers, many of whom have
worked at the plant for the entire time the union has been
attempting to organize. </p>
<p>RAIL WORKERS NEED A RAISE _ The AFL-CIO went to bat for rail
workers May 13 as President Sweeney told a Presidential Emergency
Board the concerns of the Transportation Communications Union
members _ &quot;declining real wages, jobs lost to outsourcing,
attacks on workers' health insurance _ are the same issues
bedeviling all of America's workers.&quot; The White House had
appointed the board after imposing a 60- day cooling off period
one day before the May 9 strike deadline. TCU has been trying to
get many of the nation's large rail carriers off the mark after
more than 18 months of fruitless negotiations. &quot;There is no
question the railroads have the ability to pay TCU's economic
proposals, TCU President Robert A. Scardelletti told the board.
The emergency board has 30 days to investigate the dispute and
make its report. </p>
<p>MOTHERS ON THE MOVE _ Hundreds of women gathered in protest
May 8 at Wal-Marts and Kmarts across the nation to urge shoppers
to seek their Mother's Day remembrances elsewhere. The protesters
highlighted the two companies' opposition to a minimum wage
increase, noting that more than 60 percent of those earning the
minimum wage are women, and that women are concentrated in
low-wage industries like retail. Led by the Women's Network of
the Food and Commercial Workers, working women were urged to
fight back &quot;not with a clenched fist, but with a closed
pocketbook.&quot; </p>
<p>POSTMASTER DOESN'T DELIVER _ Letter Carriers President Vincent
Sombrotto has called an emergency NALC conference for May 23
&quot;to block irresponsible U.S. Postal Service officials from
destroying mail delivery in the United States.&quot; Despite
Postmaster General Runyon's promise to end dictatorial policies
of postal managers and replace them with a new culture, Runyon
has made a &quot;180-degree flipflop,&quot; Sombrotto said. This
is the first step for a National Plan of Action in all 50 states
to galvanize postal employees. </p>
<p>NO PLACE FOR SEXUAL HARASSMENT _ The AFL-CIO reaffirmed its
condemnation of sexual harassment &quot;as an illegal violation
of human dignity&quot; in a statement recommended by the new
Committee on Working Women. Gloria Johnson, the committee chair,
urged unions not only to hold employers responsible for providing
a work environment that supports working women, but also to
educate union members on the issue of sexual harassment. </p>
<p>JOBLESS RATE CREEPS DOWNWARD _ Unemployment edged down in
April but was &quot;essentially unchanged&quot; at 5.4 percent,
according to the Bureau of Labor Statistics. Although at its
lowest level since June 1990, it has fluctuated narrowly between
5.4 percent and 5.8 percent since October 1994, and is still
above a pre-recession low of 5 percent registered in March 1989.
Employment grew by a scant 2,000 jobs in April, compared with
first quarter average monthly increases of 206,000. </p>
<p>DON'T BUY CHINESE GOODS _ Responding to the Chinese
government's persistent refusal to stop ongoing and serious
violations of human and union rights, the AFL-CIO has called for
a boycott of all Chinese-made goods during the month of June. In
Portland, the federation's Executive Council noted that American
corporations have mounted a massive campaign to grant China
most-favored-nation trading status, which significantly lowers
import duties on Chinese goods. &quot;We oppose extending MFN to
China,&quot; it said. &quot;We urge the Congress to recognize the
need to send a strong message to the Chinese government by
rejecting MFN extension.&quot; The boycott is intended &quot;as a
concrete statement of our support for human rights in China, and
our call for American corporations to insist on a minimum
standard of decency for workers in China,&quot; the council said. </p>
<p>NATIONAL NURSES WEEK NOTED _ The Federation of Nurses and
Health Professionals met in Linthicum, Md., May 4-7 to discuss
professional issues, including how to get the public involved in
the health professionals' fight to ensure quality care.
Meanwhile, nurses from the Service Employees, AFSCME, AFT,
Communications Workers and other groups met with First Lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton at the White House to urge access to safe
and quality care for all Americans. In addition, the Service
Employees released a report titled &quot;Demanding Quality,&quot;
and organized a &quot;speak-out&quot; and rally on Capitol Hill
May 10 for safety, security and quality in health care. </p>
<p>MAY IS FOR LABOR _ President Clinton proclaimed May Labor
History Month. &quot;Each new generation must embrace the
activism that has characterized labor's rich history, and all
Americans should recognize the role that labor has played in the
continuing progress of our democracy,&quot; he said. </p>
<p>GOLD MEDAL FINISH _ The Painters are giving Atlanta an
&quot;Olympic Finish&quot; as part of their volunteer effort to
paint more than 200 homes surrounding the Olympic Stadium.
&quot;Operation Clean Brush&quot; involves labor, industry,
government and the homeless working together to spruce up the
area for the games. </p>
<hr>
<p>For details about these and other stories, check out
LaborNET's &quot;News and Views&quot; library on CompuServe, or
the <a href="http://www.aflcio.org/publ/">Public Documents page</a>
on <a href="http://www.aflcio.org">LaborWEB</a>, the AFL-CIO's
Web site, located at http://www.aflcio.org/. To send information
for inclusion, or FAX numbers to receive Work in Progress, FAX to
202/508-6908, or E-mail <a href="mailto:71112.53@compuserve.com">71112.53@compuserve.com</a>.</p>
