<title>WIP 05/06/96 AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<h1 align="center">AFL-CIO Work in Progress -- May 6, 1996</h1>
<p>UNION SUMMER IN THE CITIES _ The first 18 sites where 1,000
college students and workers will carry the banner of Union
Summer were announced May 1 at a festive barbecue at AFL-CIO
headquarters. And the cities are: Akron, Ohio; Atlanta; Boston;
Charleston, S.C.; Chicago; Denver; Detroit; Washington; Los
Angeles; Miami; New Orleans; Oakland; Sacramento, Calif.; St.
Louis; San Diego; San Jose, Calif.; Seattle and Watsonville,
Calif. More sites are likely to be added during the summer. The
federation announced two unique aspects to the campaign _ a bus
tour through the Deep South to register voters and support
ongoing organizing campaigns, and a &quot;Labor-to-Neighbor&quot;
drive in San Diego to educate and organize rank-and-file members. </p>
<p>MARCH ON USA TODAY _ For the second time since the Detroit
newspaper strike began, the AFL-CIO and affiliated unions plan to
hold a mass demonstration outside Gannett's headquarters in
Arlington, Va., to support the strikers. Gannett owns the Detroit
News and publishes USA TODAY, and the AFL-CIO is mounting a
&quot;do not buy, do not advertise&quot; campaign against the
national daily. The May 7 march will coincide with Gannett's
annual stockholders' meeting. In Detroit, the combined
circulation of the Free Press and News has dropped 50 percent
overall since the strike began, the unions said. </p>
<p>UMWA GIDDYUPS IN GALLUP _ City workers in Gallup, N.M., voted
162-9 to join the Mine Workers. The UMWA used rank-and-file
members from its P&amp;M mine in the Navajo Nation to help build
support for the union among the Gallup city workers. &quot;This
victory builds on our effort to represent working families in the
coalfields, not only coal miners,&quot; said UMWA President Cecil
Roberts. </p>
<p>ADVOCATE FOR THE UAW _ Newsroom employees at the Advocate in
Stamford, Conn., voted 20-12 to join the UAW, making it the first
daily newspaper editorial staff to be represented by the union.
&quot;We were tired of being treated arbitrarily and
unilaterally,&quot; said Dan Mangan, an Advocate reporter. </p>
<p>UNION HOME WORK _ In the latest chapter of the Service
Employees dramatic home-care organizing sweep across California,
the union gained 5,700 San Francisco home-care workers. The vote
was 1,358-143 to join SEIU Local 250. Previously, 2,000 San Mateo
home-care workers joined SEIU Local 715 and 6,000 Alameda County
workers joined Local 616. </p>
<p>KAISER CUTS CHALLENGED _ Kaiser Permanente's
&quot;restructuring&quot; plans have been challenged in a
petition signed by members of the U.S. Congress, California
lawmakers, consumers and the Service Employees, among others, and
filed with the state's Department of Corporations. The HMO, which
has 4.8 million California members, has proposed to close or
convert hospitals and clinics, increasing referrals to non-Kaiser
contractors, shortening hospital stays, moving surgeries to
less-regulated outpatient settings and limiting access to care
through restrictive policies. </p>
<p>MOM NEEDS A RAISE - On May 8 at more than two dozen Wal-Mart,
Kmart and Sam's Club's stores, women will blow the whistle on
those corporate opponents to raising the minimum wage. Organized
by the Women's Network of the United Food and Commercial Workers,
the protest will make public the heavy behind-the-scenes lobbying
by these big stores against the minimum wage raise. The protest
also will mark Mother's Day as a time to think about a living
wage for working mothers. Two out of three minimum-wage workers
are women. </p>
<p>LIES, DAMN LIES AND STATISTICS _ Several recent reports
attempt to paint a rosy picture of American living standards. But
according to Jared Bernstein of the Economic Policy Institute,
&quot;they each serve to obscure the simple truth that hourly
wage rates have fallen for most American workers.&quot; AFL-CIO
President John J. Sweeney said, &quot;Many indicators show that
the economy is moving again. But now we have to put prosperity in
people's paychecks. America needs a raise.&quot; </p>
<p>ON ROLL FOR RAISE: The Executive Council meets in Portland,
Ore., on Wednesday and Thursday, turning Thursday afternoon to a
regional conference and then to the fourth &quot;America Needs A
Raise&quot; town hall meeting, with President Sweeney presiding.
SecretaryTreasurer Richard Trumka chaired the first two, in
Birmingham, Ala., and Los Angeles, and Executive Vice President
Linda ChavezThompson presided in Columbus, Ohio. Among the
workers telling their stories in Columbus was Rhonda Ware, who
said has worked her way off welfare, but &quot;I lost health
benefits and I'm currently working at a low-paying job at a fast
food restaurant without any benefits at all for my daughter or
myself. . . . If people are willing to work, they just need a
living wage so that they can support their families and they also
need benefits.&quot; </p>
<p>DON'T FEED THE LION _ Food and Commercial Workers demonstrated
May 1 outside the Belgian Embassy to protest the treatment of
U.S. workers by Belgian-based multinational Delhaize, parent of
Food Lion. In solidarity, Belgian employees of Delhaize marched
in front of the U.S. Embassy in Brussels. &quot;Delhaize is an
international hypocrite,&quot; said UFCW Local 400 President
Thomas R. McNutt. &quot;They observe worker rights in Belgium and
France and Greece, but not in America,&quot; he said. </p>
<p>SNAKE EYES FOR FLAMINGO _ The NLRB ruled that the Flamingo
Hilton Casino in Laughlin, Nev., tried to rig the game during a
Steelworkers organizing drive. An administrative law judge upheld
charges by the USW of anti-union actions conducted by the hotel
and ordered the casino to start dealing from the top of the deck
and cease such actions. </p>
<p>HOSTILE HOTEL CHARGED _ The illegal firing of three union
supporters who had worked at New Otani hotel in Los Angeles for
16 years was cited in a complaint filed by the NLRB charging
hotel management with violating federal labor law. &quot;This
action confirms what Local 11 has known for many months _ that
the New Otani workers do not have the liberty to express their
opinions about the union without fear of harassment and
termination from their jobs,&quot; said Hotel Employees and
Restaurant Employees Local 11 President Maria Elena Durazo. </p>
<p>CHEERS FOR FAMILY LEAVE _ Employers have found that
implementing the provisions of the Family and Medical Leave Act
hasn't cost much, has had almost no noticeable effect on
productivity, profitability and growth, and that most workers
took only an average two weeks of leave. A report delivered to
Congress May 1 by the Department of Labor detailed those
findings, with Secretary of Labor Robert B. Reich summarizing
that &quot;none of the dire predictions made by family leave
opponents came true.&quot; Copies of the report are available
from the Women's Bureau, U.S. Department of Labor, 200
Constitution Ave. N.W., Suite S3002, Washington, D.C. 20210. </p>
<p>PLEASE SIR, MORE? _ Giveaways for businesses and the wealthy
hidden in the tax code _ like tax breaks for certain industries
and investments, loopholes, write-offs and accelerated
depreciation _ will cost the federal government $455 billion this
fiscal year, three times the budget deficit. A new study reveals
that these entitlements for the wealthy and corporations cost 2.5
times as much as direct means-tested entitlements like welfare
and Medicaid. &quot;A Congress that is eager to challenge
low-income welfare entitlements ought to be at least as tough _
if not tougher _ on welfare entitlements for the well-heeled and
politically powerful if it truly wants to bring the budget
deficit under control,&quot; said Robert McIntyre, director of
Citizens for Tax Justice, which prepared the report. </p>
<p>DOWNSIDE TO THE DOWNSIZE _ Legislation that would require
corporations with more than 100 employees to provide permanently
laid-off workers with two months of severance for each year of
service was introduced May 2 in the New Jersey Assembly. The Job
Destruction Penalty Act would also levy a $4,000-per-layoff fine
on downsizing companies, to be given to affected communities to
help compensate for lost jobs and tax revenues. The New Jersey
Industrial Union Council is launching a grass-roots campaign for
the initiative. </p>
<p>CHEMICAL REACTION _ The Chemical Workers approved a merger
with the UFCW at a special convention with 91 percent of the
delegates voting for the new alliance. &quot;From everything
we've seen and learned in a year of dealing with the UFCW, the
ICWU, its members and employees will only benefit from the
merger,&quot; said ICWU President Frank D. Martino. UFCW
President Douglas Dority said it &quot;provides positive benefits
for both organizations, and will reinvigorate the bargaining
power of the ICWU and service to its members.&quot; </p>
<p>RUN FOR THE BORDER _ The AFL-CIO will urge changes in the
illegal immigration bill passed by the Senate that also will
affect legal immigrants, children and employers when the bill
goes to conference. The House passed a similar bill earlier.
Controversial provisions in the bills include denial of public
education for children of illegal immigrants, the cut off of
various welfare benefits for both illegal and legal immigrants
and employment verification provisions which could deny legal
immigrants work. </p>
<p>BARNARD WORKERS RALLY _ About 400 unionists rallied May 2 in
support of striking clerical workers at Barnard College in New
York City. The college has adopted an aggressive anti-union
approach, forcing the Technical and Office Professional UAW Local
2110 to strike for the first time since 1978 over labor
practices, health care and pay equity. </p>
<p>POLITICAL CLUW _ AFL-CIO President John Sweeney told the
Coalition of Labor Union Women conference on political
empowerment that the labor movement is counting on working women
to make the difference in the 1996 elections. Labor will demand
&quot;that candidates who run with the union label wear it on the
outside of their lapel . . . rather than hidden in their
pockets,&quot; he said. Other speakers included CLUW President
Gloria Johnson and Rep. Maxine Waters (D-Calif.) </p>
<p>NO TAINTED MUSHROOMS _ Harvey's supermarket chain is dropping
Quincy Farms mushrooms from its vegetable bins in response to
Quincy's firing of 85 Farm Workers who were arrested for
participating in a lunch break protest of working conditions.
Harvey's operates 40 stores in northern Florida and southern
Georgia. </p>
<p>BMWE RELEASED _ The National Mediation Board April 29 released
the Maintenance of Way Employees from mediation in talks with
most of the nation's major freight carriers, and the union is
consulting with its bargaining committees as to whether to accept
the agency's offer of arbitration. &quot;We are dedicated to
moving the bargaining process forward,&quot; said BMWE President
Mac Fleming. &quot;At the same time, we are a democratic union
and must act accordingly.&quot; The union has been negotiating
locally with each railroad, and 10 different committees are
involved. So far, only the United Transportation Union has
accepted arbitration, a step it took after members turned down an
earlier contract offer. Arbitration has been rejected by the
Electrical Workers, Machinists, Railroad Signalmen and Sheet
Metal Workers. </p>
<hr>
<p>For details about these and other stories, check out
LaborNET's &quot;News and Views&quot; library on CompuServe, or
the <a href="http://www.aflcio.org/publ/">Public Documents page</a>
on <a href="http://www.aflcio.org">LaborWEB</a>, the AFL-CIO's
Web site, located at http://www.aflcio.org/. To send information
for inclusion, or FAX numbers to receive Work in Progress, FAX to
202/508-6908, or E-mail <a href="mailto:71112.53@compuserve.com">71112.53@compuserve.com</a>.</p>
