<head>
<title>WIP 04/29/96 AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<h1 align="center">AFL-CIO Work in Progress -- April 29, 1996</h1>
<p>UNION SUMMER BBQ _ Union Summer will be celebrated at an open
house and barbecue between 11:30 a.m. and 2 p.m. at AFL-CIO
headquarters Wednesday, with the announcement of the first round
of sites. The official kickoff of the campaign to put up to a
thousand young unionists and students in communities for
organizing and other social activism will be hosted by President
John Sweeney, Secretary-Treasurer Richard Trumka and Executive
Vice President Linda Chavez-Thompson. You're invited! </p>
<p>HONOR THE DEAD, FIGHT FOR THE LIVING _ Across the nation this
past weekend, workers gathered to renew labor's fight for safe
workplaces on the 8th annual Workers Memorial Day. President
Sweeney on Saturday was in Milwaukee and Madison, Wis., where
about 300 workers and their families gathered at the Madison
Labor Temple's symbolic cemetery for workers killed on the job in
that state. In a moving ceremony, their names and cause of death
were read and placards honoring them were placed at the site. In
Milwaukee, Sweeney told a crowd of 500 that unions are
&quot;fighting a relentless attack by congressional Republicans,
at the behest of their corporate allies, who want to weaken&quot;
safety laws and turn back the clock to a more deadly time.
ChavezThompson also attended job safety rallies in Alton, Ill.,
and St. Louis, Mo., on Sunday, and Trumka attended the annual
Workers Memorial Day breakfast in Los Angeles on Monday. </p>
<p>PROMISES, PROMISES _ Workers and survivors of workplace
accidents and deaths were at the Department of Labor last Friday
for a ceremony honoring Workers Memorial Day and the 25th
anniversary of the Occupational Safety and Health Act. They heard
Vice President Gore promise the administration would fight for
OSHA against the GOP-led onslaught in Congress. Sweeney noted
that safety laws have saved lives, but with continuing deadly
workplace conditions, &quot;It's still not enough.&quot; Labor
Secretary Robert Reich said OSHA's job will not be over, &quot;as
long as the prospect of death and injury stalk the
workplace.&quot; A newly released AFL-CIO study on the
25-year-old safety act, Promises Kept, Promises Broken notes the
industries where progress has been made _ and where the biggest
dangers remain. Copies of the 121-page report may be ordered
through the AFL-CIO's Support Services Department, 202-637-5041. </p>
<p>DETROIT GOES THROUGH MIAMI _ Striking Detroit newspaper
employees and their supporters turned out in force at
Knight-Ridder's annual stockholders' meeting in Miami. Susan
Watson, a 30-year veteran of the Detroit Free Press, told the
stockholders &quot;short-sighted corporate managers have done
terrible damage to a great newspaper and to its reputation for
truth and integrity.&quot; Community and religious leaders also
attacked the company's insensitivity and their plans to retain
scab workers. Knight-Ridder, which owns the Free Press, announced
it has lost $46 million as a result of the strike and expects to
lose $20 million more this year. Gannett, owner of the Detroit
News, has the same amount of losses, since the two papers split
costs under a joint operating agreement.</p>
<p>AMERICA NEEDS A RAISE _ The sprinklers erupted in the room an
hour before the AFL-CIO was to hold the first of about 30 town
hall meetings on America's growing wage gap, then the power went
out just as SecretaryTreasurer Trumka was preparing to open the
meeting in suburban Birmingham, Ala. When the lights came back on
30 minutes into the program, more than 400 people were on the
edge of their seats, listening to the gripping testimony from
people including an ex-gang member, a nurse and a homeless day
laborer Trumka had invited in off the street. A student told
about his mother's struggle to keep the family together as she
worked two and sometimes three jobs at a time. AFSCME
Secretary-Treasurer Bill Lucy proclaimed, &quot;There is no
justification for the continued maldistribution of wealth in our
society. There comes a time when common people with a common
problem need to come together. America needs a raise.&quot; Up
this week: Town hall meetings in Los Angeles and Columbus, Ohio. </p>
<p>STILL JUST $4.25 _ House Democrats tried again last week to
force a vote on raising the minimum wage to $5.15 an hour over
the next two years. They failed, but picked up eight votes over
the previous vote on March 28. Union volunteers were working
phone banks to contact members on the issue, and the AFL-CIO was
preparing to go back on the air with radio ads in 29 districts,
asking listeners to call their member of Congress and insist on a
direct vote to raise the minimum wage. For more information, call
Linda Miller at 202/637- 5211. </p>
<p>TAX POLICY SHELL GAME _ Labor Secretary Reich, speaking at the
Service Employees convention, said a Republican proposal aimed at
ducking the growing demand for a minimum wage hike &quot;goes
from bad to worse.&quot; The plan to cut single workers and
childless adults from the Earned Income Tax Credit sends the
message to 4 million workers earning near the minimum wage: `You
don't get a minimum wage increase, you get a tax increase
instead.' </p>
<p>HOLLY NOT FARMING _ The U.S. Supreme Court ruled that workers
who catch, load and haul chickens for slaughter are covered by
the National Labor Relations Act. The April 23 decision affirmed
an NLRB ruling that ordered Holly Farms, a subsidiary of giant
poultry producer Tyson Foods, to bargain with the Teamsters,
which represents the live-chicken haulers. The company had argued
the workers were agricultural workers and exempt from the NLRA.
But Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg, writing for the 5-4 majority,
said the work was tied to Holly Farms' slaughtering and
processing operations, activities that do not constitute
`farming' under the statute. The case is Holly Farms vs. NLRB. </p>
<p>THE GOOD SIDE OF POULTRY _ Religious leaders will meet with
poultry workers who have been fighting for a year to gain a
contract with Case Farms Processing Plant in Morganton, N.C. The
workers voted for representation with the Laborers last July. The
clergy, organized by the National Interfaith Committee for Worker
Justice, hope to meet with the CEO at Case. For more information,
call Kim Bobo at 312/381-2832. </p>
<p>TOP-HEAVY _ Here's a nugget from Business Week's annual survey
of executive pay: When nursing home owner Vencor Inc. acquired
Hillhaven Corp. last year, CEO W. Bruce Lunsford's compensation
jumped from $1.8 million to more than $4.9 million. But the
company's 2,000 workers, without a contract since 1994, are still
denied a 15 percent increase on wages that start below $6 an
hour. The Service Employees announced a major campaign against
VencorHillhaven and two other health care giants, Beverly
Enterprises and Kaiser Permanente, at its convention last week in
Chicago. </p>
<p>SEIU ELECTS STERN _ Delegates to the 75th SEIU convention set
the stage for renewed union activism with the election of Andy
Stern as president, at 45 the youngest person ever to hold the
post. They also re-elected SecretaryTreasurer Betty Bednarcyzk,
the first woman to be elected to one of the top two offices at
the union. The new officers led more than 1,000 delegates on a
onemile march from the convention hotel through downtown Chicago
to join a rally in support of a proposed city ordinance that
would limit city tax breaks, subsidies and contracts to
businesses willing to pay workers $7.60 an hour, the rate
required to put a family of four at the national poverty level.
AFL-CIO President Sweeney and SEIU Local 73 President Tom
Balanoff met with Chicago Mayor Richard Daley to discuss the
living wage initiative. </p>
<p>YALE FIGHT _ A bitter labor dispute between Yale University
and 3,700 members of the Hotel Employees and Restaurant Employees
Locals 34 and 35, did not stop 120 &quot;on call&quot; workers
from voting to join the union on April 26. The new members plan
to be a part of a massive demonstration against the university on
May 27, graduation day. The union is hoping to draw crowds from
the tri-state area. For more information, call 203/624-5161. </p>
<p>DOLE/GINGRICH PRESCRIBE BAD MEDICINE _ The fate of bipartisan
health insurance reform appears to depend on Sen. Bob Dole's
(R-Kan.) and Speaker Newt Gingrich's (R-GA) insistence on
maintaining two controversial provisions. Passed by the Senate
last week and the House in March, the bill would allow workers to
maintain their insurance coverage when they change or lose jobs
and would also limit exclusions of workers and their families
from health coverage because of pre-existing medical conditions.
But Gingrich and Dole want to add tax breaks aimed mostly at well
off healthy people and cap medical malpractice awards, something
long sought by the medical community. These provisions would
certainly provoke a veto. </p>
<p>DEEP-SIX DE-REG _ Without so much as a hearing, the
GOP-controlled House is ready to vote on a maritime deregulation
bill. Maritime unions have urged their members to contact their
lawmakers to oppose H.R. 2149, the Ocean Reform Shipping Act. The
bill &quot;threatens the livelihoods of hundreds of thousands or
port and maritime workers through the country,&quot; said Brian
McWilliams, president of the Longshoremen and Warehousemen. The
bill is scheduled to be on the House floor this week. You can
help by calling 1-800- 97AFL-CIO and urge your House member to
oppose the bill. </p>
<p>LANDMARK AGREEMENT _ In the Carpenters' first cooperative
training initiative with a major manufacturer, the union
announced the creation of a new program with Wilsonart
International designed to better train carpenters on the
installation of solid surface materials. Under the terms of the
agreement, the UBC, through its Apprenticeship and Training Fund,
will provide training, while Wilsonart will provide technical
support and training materials. </p>
<p>NEW GRAIN MILLERS PACTS _ Grain Millers' policy committees
have accepted new three-year agreements with General Mills and
Pillsbury. The agreements deal only with benefit changes, with
wage provisions, seniority, and work rules left to separate talks
at the individual plants. The General Mills pact covers 3,400
employees at 16 plants and increases the pension formula from $31
per month per year of service to $34, sets up an alternative
health care plan, and establishes a 401(k) plan. The Pillsbury
deal covers 800 employees at three plants and increases the
pension formula from $28 to $32, increases the lifetime maximum
health care coverage and also sets up a 401(k) plan. </p>
<p>LOVING THE WAY THEY FLY _ Air Line Pilots voted to approve a
four-year contract with Delta Air Lines that promises to increase
job security, return furloughed pilots to work, provide employees
with an enhanced retirement plan and stock options and reserve a
seat on the Board of Directors. The ratification came as the
airline seeks to meet competition from low-fare, low-wage
carriers. Delta pilots elected Capt. Bill Brown, three-term
chairman of ALPA's Master Executive Council at Delta, to fill the
board seat. </p>
<p>CONFERENCE ON BARGAINING _ The AFL-CIO Industrial Union
Department will hold a Coordinated Bargaining Conference July
8-12 at the Renaissance Mayflower Hotel in Washington, D.C.
Registration is $55. Contact the IUD at 202/842-7862. </p>
<hr>
<p>For these and other stories, check out LaborNET's &quot;News
and Views&quot; library on CompuServe, or the <a
href="http://www.aflcio.org/publ/">Public Documents page</a> on <a
href="http://www.aflcio.org">LaborWEB</a>, the AFL-CIO's Web
site, located at http://www.aflcio.org/. To send information for
inclusion, or FAX numbers to receive Work in Progress, FAX to
202/508-6908, or E-mail <a href="mailto:71112.53@compuserve.com">71112.53@compuserve.com</a>.</p>
