<html>

<head>
<title>WIP 04/21/96 AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h2 align=center>AFL-CIO Work in Progress</h2>
<p>BARNSTORMING FOR A RAISE _ AFL-CIO President John Sweeney last week carried the 
message &quot;America Needs a Raise&quot; from Boston to Minneapolis to New York to San Francisco, 
where on April 16 he joined others in presenting petitions to put a referendum for a living wage on 
California's ballot. &quot;It is time for Americans to take a look at how corporate America is downsizing 
the American dream and say three simple words: THIS IS WRONG,&quot; Sweeney told a Minneapolis 
forum on renewing the social contract between companies and workers. The first of a series of 
federation-sponsored town hall meetings to hear how working for less is affecting working families 
will be held April 26 in Birmingham, Ala.</p>
<p>WAGE ISSUE SPARKS GOP DEFECTIONS _ The AFL-CIO's pressure on lawmakers to 
raise the minimum wage is working. Last week, 20 Republican House members broke ranks with 
Speaker Newt Gingrich (R-Ga.), joining Democrats in support of a minimum wage. But reports 
from the Hill indicate Gingrich and Senate Majority Leader Robert Dole (R-Kan.) may attempt to 
sabotage the bill by attaching anti-worker provisions. On Friday, President Sweeney pulled 
together all the state AFL-CIOs in a conference call to update them and set new strategy for the 
wage battle. Leaflets were shipped over the weekend to all state feds with an urgent request to get 
them out, and to get phone calls in to Congress. You can get camera-ready art of the leaflet 
shipped overnight by calling Linda Miller at 202/637-5211.</p>
<p>BUILDING WAGES _ Sweeney personally delivered the minimum wage leaflets to delegates of 
the Building and Construction Trades legislative conference April 22, urging them to deliver the 
message to their members of Congress. Some 5,000 delegates and guests at the conference also 
participated in workshops ranging from organizing to grass-roots activism. Labor Secretary Robert 
Reich also addressed the conference, and Vice President Gore is scheduled to speak later in the 
week.</p>
<p>GOP STRIKES BACK _ Angered by labor's aggressive voter education program, Republican 
congressional leaders have launched a double-barreled attack on worker organizations. A Senate 
committee last week marked up and sent to the floor the misnamed TEAM Act, which would allow 
a return to company unions. A House subcommittee held a hearing on codifying the Supreme 
Court's eight-year-old Beck decision, a move clearly designed for retribution. Union witnesses 
argued that workers' Beck rights are established by the National Labor Relations Board and that 
unions are democratic institutions that no one is forced to join.</p>
<p>MECHANICS FLY IBT _ America West Airlines mechanics won a great victory over corporate 
greed April 17, voting 587 to 135 in favor of Teamsters representation. &quot;The workers had the last 
word on an insensitive and greedy management that fired nearly 400 mechanics last December,&quot; 
said Ron Carey, IBT president. In March, a federal mediator ruled that the fired mechanics had a 
right to cast ballots in the election.</p>
<p>OVERNITE, THEY'RE TEAMSTERS _ Workers at the fifth largest service center of Overnite 
Transportation in Lexington, Ky., also voted April 17 for Teamsters representation. The campaign, 
which began in the fall of 1994, has been marked by charges against the company alleging unlawful 
labor practices. The IBT now represents 2,000 employees at 17 Overnite facilities.</p>
<p>WEEK ON THE RUN _ President Sweeney will be in Milwaukee and Madison, Wis., April 27 to 
mark Workers Memorial Day, which falls on Sunday, April 28. Executive Vice President Linda 
Chavez-Thompson will gather with nearly 1,000 trade unionists for the commemoration April 28 
along the banks of the Mississippi River in Alton, Ill., and St. Louis. Secretary-Treasurer Trumka is 
preparing to kick off the federation's &quot;America Needs a Raise&quot; town hall meetings in Birmingham 
on Friday. Sweeney starts the week at the Building and Construction Trades Department 
conference in Washington, then goes to Chicago for the Service Employees convention. 
Chavez-Thompson participates in a Ms Foundation panel in Atlanta Tuesday and addresses the 
UAW legislative conference in Washington on Wednesday. On Saturday, she is in Hartford for a 
Connecticut AFL-CIO unity rally and a labor-community-religious forum.</p>
<p>UNION SUMMER _ Friends and supporters are invited to come to a barbecue and official launch 
of Union Summer at the AFL- CIO headquarters on May 1st. President Sweeney will announce 
the first round of Union Summer sites at the event, scheduled from 11:30 a.m to 2 p.m. About 900 
young unionists, college students and children of union members have applied for the summer 
organizing campaign. June 1 is the deadline for applying for Union Summer assignments. For more 
information, call 800/952-2550.</p>
<p>ILLINOIS WORKERS MAD AS HELL _ More than 20,000 union members marched on the 
GOP-controlled legislature in Springfield April 17 to protest its attack on working families, a 
state-level version of the assault orchestrated in Washington by Gingrich, Dole and friends. 
AFL-CIO Secretary-Treasurer Rich- ard Trumka told the crowd that when the GOP took over 
the Capitol, they &quot;drew a bulls-eye on the back of every working man and woman in Illinois.&quot; 
Workplace safety, prevailing wages, un- employment comp and other issues have all come under 
attack there.</p>
<p>DON'T MOURN, ORGANIZE _ More than 2,000 Farm Workers marched in Watsonville, 
Calif., April 21 to commemorate the third anniversary of Cesar Chavez's death and kicked off a 
stepped-up union organizing drive in the Monterey Bay region. &quot;Strawberry workers endure some 
of the lowest pay and most abusive working conditions in California,&quot; UFW President Arturo 
Rodriguez told the crowd. Starting with the Watsonville march, the union will be targeting Central 
Coast strawberry growers for intensified organizing efforts.</p>
<p>MITSUBISHI HARASSMENT _ UAW President Steve Yokich described as &quot;just plain wrong&quot; 
efforts by Mitsubishi to pressure employees into demonstrating against the Equal Employment 
Opportunity Commission for its investigation of sexual harassment charges at the Mitsubishi plant in 
Normal, Ill. The union and its Local 2488 have been cooperating with the EEOC, Yokich noted, 
and the company &quot;would do better to work with the agency and the union to redress past wrongs 
and make whatever changes are necessary to ensure that its work force is protected from any kind 
of discrimination now and in the future.&quot;</p>
<p>FIRST LADY SPEAKS TO UAW _ The Clinton adminis- tration needs the labor movement's 
help to rebuild the American dream, Hillary Rodham Clinton told more than 1,600 cheering UAW 
activists as she opened the union's legislative conference April 21. The three-day conference 
culminates Tuesday with a day of meetings with members of Congress to urge passage of the 
minimum wage increase and defense of OSHA, Medicare, Medicaid, education and other 
programs vital to working families.</p>
<p>REACHING OUT TO WOMEN _ Karen Nussbaum, director of the AFL-CIO's new Working 
Women's Department, is going on the road to meet with women's organizations and union groups in 
Atlanta, Chicago, Portland (Ore.), Boston and New York City. Nussbaum will stress the 
importance of unions in raising living standards for the growing female work force, as well as the 
essential role women can play in the 1996 elections.</p>
<p>GETTING THE MESSAGE _ After hearing AFSCME President Gerald McEntee on PBS's The 
News Hour with Jim Lehrer outline the AFL-CIO political and legislative mobilization for 1996, a 
Sarasota, Fla., woman was inspired to send a $500 check to the AFL-CIO for use in the Labor 
`96 campaign. McEntee, who is chair of the AFL-CIO political action committee, also went 
head-to-head with Rep. John Boehner (R-Ohio) on CNBC's Politics with Chris Matthews April 
16. Boehner accused the AFL-CIO of illegally using funds in the Labor '96 campaign and of trying 
to buy the November elections. &quot;All we are doing,&quot; McEntee said, &quot;is getting the word out about 
the voting record of members of Congress. So, what are the Republicans afraid of?&quot;</p>
<p>STAMPING ON WORKERS _ The U.S. Postal Service has drawn the ire of both the Postal 
Workers and the Letter Carriers on separate accounts. APWU President Moe Biller accused 
USPS of &quot;bombing without notice&quot; for announcing plans to explore contracting out Priority Mail 
processing centers. NALC President Vincent Sombrotto lambasted USPS's &quot;employer arrogance&quot; 
for unilaterally terminating the 14-year-old Employee Involvement program. The NALC was 
informed of the USPS action in a two-page letter, which stated that all persons employed in 
support of the program be returned to the appropriate craft and management positions by May 25.</p>
<p>A BLUE-LIGHT SPECIAL EFFORT _ Claiming the current board has run the company into the 
ground, UNITE and the Teamsters have mounted an effort to reform Kmart's board of directors 
and to gain approval for resolutions at the May 21 annual meeting. The unions filed proxy 
resolutions to hold an annual election of all board members; eliminate the retirement plan for 
nonemployee directors; and undertake a study to examine ways to improve the stock sale.</p>
<p>LTV THREATENED WORKERS _ The Steelworkers accused LTV Steel Co. of violating labor 
law by attempting to prevent workers from attending the company's annual meeting where union 
leaders ripped management's plans for a nonunion minimill in Alabama. The union filed charges with 
the NLRB claiming that LTV threatened to deny workers time off to attend the meeting, videotape 
attendees, and ban union activities on company premises. Despite the threats, some 1,400 USWA 
members, most of them stockholders, showed up for the April 15 annual meeting in Cleveland, 
occupying most of the seats in the auditorium.</p>
<p>HELP FOR LOCKED-OUT WORKERS _ Paperworkers President Wayne E. Glenn is seeking 
help in publicizing the plight of 1,200 locked-out employees at Trailmobile's Charleston, Ill., plant. 
Members of UPIU Local 7591 were locked out three months ago after refusing to extend a 
four-year wage freeze into a full seven years. To get a packet of materials, including a fact sheet, 
press release, ad slick describing the adopt-a-family program and news stories on the lockout, 
contact UPIU Special Projects Department at 615/834-8590.</p>
<p>CONFERENCE CALLS _ Workplace Learning: The Strategic Advantage, sponsored by the 
AFL-CIO Human Resources Development Institute and several AFL-CIO affiliates, April 29-30 
at the Hyatt Regency in Milwaukee, focuses on planning, implementing, evaluating and negotiating 
workplace learning initiatives. For more information, call 608/263-2929 or 800/446-0399. 
African-Americans, Labor and Society: Organizing for a New Agenda, set for May 10-11 at 
Wayne State University in Detroit, features an address by National Labor Relations Board 
Chairman William Gould and a keynote by AFSCME Secretary-Treasurer William Lucy, president 
of the Coalition of Black Trade Unionists. Contact Prof. Patrick Mason, Department of African 
Studies, at 313/577-2321.</p>
<hr>
<p>For Executive Council statements, reports and press conference transcripts, check out 
LaborNET's &quot;News and Views&quot; library on <a href="http://www.compuserve.com">CompuServe</a>, or <a href="http://www.aflcio.org">LaborWEB</a>, the AFL-CIO's Web site 
located at http://<a href="http://www.aflcio.org">www.aflcio.org</a>. To send information for inclusion, or FAX numbers to receive 
Work in Progress, FAX to 202/508-6908, or via E-mail <a href="mailto:71112.53@compuserve.com">71112.53@compuserve.com</a>.</p>
