<title>WIP 04/16/96 AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h2 align=center>AFL-CIO Work in Progress,<br>
Tuesday, April 16, 1996 </h2>
<p>SOLIDARITY IN DETROIT -- About 3,000 people crowded into Detroit's Cobo Center April 
14 threw down a challenge to the publishing kingpins that own the struck Detroit News and Free 
Press. &quot;Did Knight-Ridder and Gannett think they could crush working families, destroy our lives 
and careers and no one would protest?&quot; AFL-CIO President John Sweeney asked the crowd. 
Secretary-Treasurer Richard Trumka declared that the Detroit &quot;community is revolted and 
disgusted&quot; by the behavior of the publishers. &quot;Readers are finding other things to read. Advertisers 
are finding other places to advertise.&quot; Teamsters President Ron Carey said the publishers' strategy 
to destroy the unions didn't work. &quot;They had no idea of the commitment of the labor movement or 
the strikers.&quot; Also addressing the rally were Service Employees President Richard Cordtz, UAW 
Vice President Carolyn Forrest, Graphic Communications Secretary-Treasurer Guy DeVito, 
Newspaper Guild President Linda K. Foley, Michigan AFL-CIO Secretary-Treasurer Bertha L. 
Poe, Detroit AFL-CIO President Edgar A. Scribner, Rep. John Conyers (D-Mich.), and Detroit 
City Council President Maryann Mahaffey. </p>
<p>BACK ON THE ATTACK -- Newt Gingrich and company are wasting no time in renewing their 
attack on workers and working families after the congressional recess. In the Senate, the Labor 
and Human Resources Committee will mark up the so-called TEAM Act (S.295) April 17. The 
company union bill, a favorite of the business community, is expected to pass the 
Republican-controlled panel, but you can still make your voice heard by using the AFL-CIO's 
toll-free number, 800/962-3524, to urge your senator to vote &quot;no.&quot; The House Employer- 
Employee Relations Subcommittee, meanwhile, is expected to attack the AFL-CIO's voter 
education and get-out-the-vote drive at a hearing April 18, using the Supreme Court's Beck 
decision as cover. While Gingrich and other GOP leaders whine about workers and unions 
exercising their rights, The New York Times reported April 12 that in 1995 alone, &quot;the Gingrich 
money machine has helped raise more than $52 million for Republican coffers.&quot; </p>
<p>FIGHTING &quot;RIGHT TO WORK&quot; -- The anti-union attack is being carried nationwide by the 
National Right to Work Committee, which is mailing letters and press releases in 21 states to 
announce a million-dollar campaign promoting passage of the national &quot;rightto -work&quot; bill. In 
Montana, the state AFL-CIO will hold a news conference Wednesday to upstage an event planned 
by the national committee. Meanwhile, in Oklahoma, the state senate voted 25-18 against a 
Republican attempt to attach a right-to-work amendment to legislation on binding arbitration for 
police and firefighters. </p>
<p>IAM, LOCKHEED AGREE -- The Machinists announced a tentative agreement with Lockheed 
Martin April 12, averting a strike by 4,800 aerospace workers that was set for Monday morning. 
The proposed settlement followed three days of around-the-clock negotiations at the Washington 
headquarters of the Federal Mediation and Conciliation Service. Full details will not be available 
until after the ratification vote, set for April 21, but union negotiators said they had succeeded in 
forcing Lockheed Martin to drop its demands to eliminate union jobs by outsourcing janitorial 
positions and related maintenance work. </p>
<p>BCTD: TOYOTA BUILDS UNION -- The AFL-CIO Building and Construction Trades 
Department reached a project labor agreement covering the construction of Toyota Motor Corp.'s 
T100 pickup truck manufacturing facility near Princeton, Ind. The construction, valued in excess of 
$700 million, is scheduled to start this spring and be completed in 1998. BCTD has a similar 
agreement at Toyota's billion-dollar facility in Georgetown, Ky. </p>
<p>COALITIONS WORK -- AFSCME Council 31 in Godfrey, Ill., has gained allies in its two-year 
struggle for a contract with a privately owned agency for the developmentally disabled. Union 
members lobbied meetings and used community support to encourage the local village board not to 
issue tax-free bonds to finance a new building for the company, Beverly Farm, which receives state 
and federal operating funds. The NLRB has issued seven complaints against the company. </p>
<p>CIVIL RIGHTS INSTITUTE -- AFL-CIO Executive Vice President ChavezThompson keynoted 
the federation's annual Civil and Human Rights Institute, held April 14-18 at the Meany Center for 
Labor Studies in Silver Spring, Md. President Sweeney and Secretary- Treasurer Trumka also are 
addressing the participants, who will hear about the AFL-CIO's plans to mobilize workers for the 
1996 elections and to beef up organizing, as well as discuss such issues as the future of affirmative 
action, immigration and working women. Other speakers include AFL-CIO Vice Presidents Gloria 
Johnson and Clayola Brown, Organizing Director Richard Bensinger and Working Women's 
Director Karen Nussbaum. </p>
<p>NLRB BACKS NURSES -- The National Labor Relations Board has gone to court to force 
Columbia/HCA Inc. to bargain with the Nurses Professional Organization, an AFSCME affiliate, at 
the Audubon Regional Medical Center in Louisville, Ky. Columbia/HCA, the nation's largest 
for-profit hospital chain, waged an illegal antiunion campaign, threatening reprisals if nurses voted in 
the union and announcing last-minute wage and benefit improvements before the election. The 
board petitioned the U.S. District Court for the Western District of Kentucky to order the 
bargaining pending its final disposition of the cases. </p>
<p>TOMA-TEK &quot;SLAPPED&quot; -- A California judge dismissed a trumped-up lawsuit by Toma-Tek 
designed to punish employees and union organizers for exercising their right of free speech. The 
tactic, known as strategic litigation against public participation, or a SLAPP suit, often is used by 
companies to try to intimidate or silence workers and community groups or tie them up in endless 
litigation. Toma-Tek, a tomato processing company, sued the Teamsters on the pretext of trespass 
and &quot;misappropriation of trade secrets&quot; after the union presented a petition signed by 2,400 
employees asking the company to obey the law and respect the right of workers in a representation 
election. INTERNATIONAL SAFETY OBSERVANCE -- April 28, the 8th annual Workers 
Memorial Day, will be marked by the International Confederation of Free Trade Unions as the first 
international day of mourning in remembrance of the 200,000 workers who are killed and the 1.2 
million injured on the job each year. The ICFTU is coordinating the event in conjunction with the 
United Nations Commission on Sustainable Development. April 28 also marks the 25th anniversary 
of the Occupational Safety and Health Act. For more information, contact the AFL-CIO 
Occupational Safety and Health Department at 202/637-5367 or follow the information highway to 
LaborNET or the World Wide Web at www.aflcio.org. </p>
<p>RAIL STRIKE POSSIBLE -- The National Mediation Board released the Transportation 
Communications Union from mediation, and rail workers are bracing themselves for a possible 
national strike as management continues to resist productive negotiations. TCU opened talks Nov. 
1, 1994, only to be told by carriers that its members were overpaid and that work-rule concessions 
and huge rollbacks in health and welfare coverage would be needed. Last August, local officers 
voted 403-2 to strike, and the union declared an impasse. The United Transportation Union, 
meanwhile, agreed to binding arbitration with the carriers. </p>
<p>GM STRIKE AVERTED -- Members of Electronic Workers Local 775 on April 12 ratified a 
contract at two General Motors Delphi Chassis plants in Kettering, Ohio, averting a strike. If the 
2,700 production and maintenance workers had struck, the fallout could have shut down most of 
GM's assembly plants, the same as last month's 18-day strike by the UAW against two other 
Delphi plants in nearby Dayton. The agreement contains language strengthening subcontract 
protection for skilled employees. </p>
<p>TRAILMOBILE LOCKOUT -- Representatives of 1,200 locked-out Paperworkers at 
Trailmobile's Charleston, Ill., plant brought their case to the company's U.S. headquarters in 
Chicago April 11. Trailmobile is owned by Indonesian-based Gemala Group, which has strong ties 
to that country's repressive military regime. The workers were locked out Jan. 21 after they 
rejected company demands to continue a four-year wage freeze for another three years and to 
eliminate certain job classifications, which would cost some 300 workers as much as $1 an hour in 
wages. The UPIU has globalized their struggle by seeking help from trade unions in Australia, 
where Gemala has several joint ventures. </p>
<p>BEVERLY FIGHT ESCALATES -- Hundreds of &quot;permanently replaced&quot; Beverly nursing home 
workers from Pennsylvania will be joined Wednesday by Sen. Paul Simon (D-Ill.) and members of 
the Pennsylvania congressional delegation at a rally and protest on Capitol Hill. The Service 
Employees also took their fight for dignity on behalf of nursing home workers to major shareholders 
of Beverly Enterprises Inc. --Mellon Bank, Wellington Management Investment Co. and Loomis 
Sayles Co., a subsidiary of the New England Mutual Life Insurance Co. The shareholder campaign 
against unfair labor practices comes after more than 300 NLRB charges filed against the company 
for its treatment of workers in 20 Pennsylvania facilities. Trial has been scheduled for May 14. </p>
<p>CONFLICT RESOLUTION -- AFL-CIO President Emeritus Thomas R. Donahue joined with 
William L. Lurie, former president of the Business Roundtable, and veteran labor mediator 
Theodore W. Kheel in launching a new Foundation for Prevention and Early Resolution of Conflict. 
PERC's focus will include labor-management, business, community, environmental and civil rights 
dispute prevention and resolution. The organization also has entered into a strategic alliance with 
Cornell University, which plans to establish a Cornell/PERC institute to study the prevention and 
resolution of conflict. </p>
<p>PRESIDENT'S PENSION REFORM -- President Clinton last week proposed to Congress 
reforms in pension laws that would help some 51 million workers. &quot;This proposal would help stop 
the erosion of private pension coverage in America,&quot; President Sweeney said. He warned that 
Americans face a decrease in private pensions and radical proposals to privatize Social Security. 
The reform provisions include new protections for state and local government employees, increased 
penalties for corporate misuse of pensions funds, 401(k) portability and broader eligibility and 
withdrawal rules for Individual Retirement Accounts. </p>
<p>PAY EQUITY -- President Clinton issued a proclamation decreeing April 11 as National Pay 
Inequity Awareness Day. In the notice, Clinton urges &quot;all employers to review their wage-setting 
practices and to see that their employees, particularly women and people of color, are paid fairly 
for their work.&quot; </p>
<p>AMERICA SPEAKS -- Roll-ins from the AFL-CIO special convention have been combined into 
a 10-minute video with excerpts from the speeches of Sweeney and Vice President Gore. Contact 
the AFL-CIO Department of Public Affairs, Broadcast Division at 202/637-5334. </p>
<p>For details about these and other stories, check out LaborNET's &quot;News and Views&quot; library on 
CompuServe, or <a href="http://www.aflcio.org/">LaborWEB</a> the AFL-CIO's web site located at http://www.aflcio.org. To send 
information for inclusion, or FAX numbers to receive Work in Progress, FAX to 202/508-6908, 
or E-mail to <a href="mailto:71112.53@compuserve.com">71112.53@compuserve.com.</a> </p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="/publ/publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
