<html>

<head>
<title>WIP 04/09/96 AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h2 align=center>AFL-CIO Work in Progress,<br>
Tuesday, April 9, 1996 </h2>
<p>FLUNKING LAWMAKERS -- This week, AFL-CIO unions will be grading 33 members of 
Congress on their actions affecting working families. Not one has a passing grade-point average -- 
cementing their status as the bottom of the class. State and local union officials will announce the 
grades at media events in many of the districts, and more than 400,000 union members in those 
areas will receive &quot;report cards&quot; on their representatives in the mail. </p>
<p>RAISING MINIMUM WAGE -- Recess activities also will include television and radio spots in 
31 districts of flunking lawmakers, focusing on lawmakers' failure to support legislation to increase 
the minimum wage. The ads note that the member of Congress &quot;voted to block a minimum wage 
increase . . . after he/she/they voted to cut Medicare and cut college loans, all to give a tax break to 
the rich.&quot; They urge viewers and listeners to tell their members of Congress to raise the minimum 
wage. </p>
<p>THE CAMPAIGN TRAIN -- Round two of the AFL-CIO's grass-roots training program gets 
under way this week, with more than 40 staffers from affiliated unions taking part in the National 
Labor Political Training Center's week-long classes. The activists will hone such vital political 
campaign skills as organizing district grass-roots committees, get-out-the-vote techniques and 
media relations. Graduates from the center will be in the field until the elections, recruiting and 
training some 3,000 rank-and-file volunteers. </p>
<p>LABORERS ORGANIZE AN INDUSTRY -- A celebration/ratification of an industrywide 
agreement covering three-fourths of New York City's asbestos workers under a Laborers contract 
will be held April 11. LIUNA Local 78 gained 1,500 new members by renewing its organizing 
efforts after coming under trusteeship as part of LIUNA's Mason Tenders District Council. During 
the past four months, the local made 1,600 house calls, exposed the lethal working conditions and 
used a variety of other tactics to gain support for the workers' cause. The union also helped the 
Polish and Latino work force understand their rights. The LIUNA general board recently 
reorganized the Mason Tenders into two newly chartered locals -- one representing building 
workers and the other covering asbestos and lead abatement workers. </p>
<p>8,000 NEW MEMBERS -- An affiliation agreement with the National Federation of Independent 
Unions will bring LIUNA 8,000 new members. Pointing to NFIU's diversity of jobs, LIUNA 
President Arthur A. Coia called the merger &quot;a perfect match.&quot; The NFIU's largest affiliate, the 
2,100-member United Independent Union based in Philadelphia, already has approved the merger, 
with the others expected to follow suit. </p>
<p>UNIONIZING DOUBLE-BREASTERS -- The <a href="http://www.teamster.org/">Teamsters,</a> which battled Ryder Corp.'s practice 
of double-breasting in a strike last fall, won the right to represent workers at QAT in Petersburg, 
Va., one of the nonunion subsidiaries the carhauler had used to avoid providing union wages and 
working conditions. In another victory, IBT gained workers at the Super Shuttle at Phoenix's Sky 
Harbor Airport last week. The election victory comes in the midst of mail balloting by more than 
700 America West mechanics, mostly in Phoenix, who also are deciding on IBT representation. </p>
<p>NAVY WORKERS GO IUE -- Some 130 Loral Training and Technical Services workers at Van 
Voorhis Naval Air Station, Nev., voted for representation by the Electronic Workers in balloting 
last month. The unit has been chartered as IUE Local 1177. In a campaign lasting 15 months, the 
workers -- who are highly specialized in the training of U.S. military combat pilots -- voted 82-40 
in favor of IUE. </p>
<p>SEIU WINS BIG -- The <a href="http://www.seiu.org/">Service Employees</a> were victors in three separate organizing campaigns, 
including one in Florida that would double the size of its Local 362. Member organizers from that 
local, representing 1,300 workers at Disney World, helped in the campaign to organize 1,300 
administrative and service employees of the Lake County, Fla., School District. The vote was 
665-189. Meanwhile, about 200 Head Start workers at the East Baton Rouge (La.) City/Parish 
Government voted 110-53 for SEIU, and the union won its third victory in a series of four elections 
necessary to represent the 450 drivers at Bernie Bus Co. in Syracuse, N.Y. </p>
<p>PRESS ON DETROIT -- AFL-CIO President Sweeney, Secretary-Treasurer Trumka and 
Executive Vice President Chavez-Thompson will add their voices to the call for justice in Detroit at 
a major rally in support of striking newspaper workers next Sunday, April 14. Sweeney also will 
address the Council on Competitiveness in Washington and the Kennedy Library Forum in Boston 
on April 11, and participate in a Minnesota Economic Forum April 12. Chavez-Thompson 
addresses a Workers' Rights Conference in Arlington, Texas, on April 10. </p>
<p>DO NOT BUY USA TODAY -- In a letter to union presidents, AFL-CIO President John 
Sweeney has urged support for a &quot;do not buy, do not advertise&quot; campaign against USA TODAY, 
the flagship of Gannett Publishing, which owns the struck Detroit News. The AFL-CIO, through its 
Strategic Approaches Committee, is coordinating a program of support for workers who have 
been on strike for nine months at Detroit's two newspapers, the News and Detroit Free Press, 
owned by Knight-Ridder. &quot;I hope you will consider asking your employers not to patronize USA 
Today until the strike is settled, and ask them to tell Gannett why they are taking the action,&quot; 
Sweeney wrote. The federation also has launched a campaign against The Miami Herald, 
Knight-Ridder's flagship, by asking South Florida union members to cancel their subscriptions. 
Sweeney urged unions to contribute to the DNA Strike Relief Fund, Detroit Metropolitan 
AFL-CIO, 2550 West Grand Blvd., Detroit, Mich. 48208. Unions and individuals wishing to 
advertise in the strikers' Sunday Journal should contact William Brown, publisher, at 3100 East 
Jefferson, Detroit, Mich. 48207; phone 313/567-9818. </p>
<p>NO PLACE FOR BRUTALITY -- The recent police beatings of two Mexican immigrants in Los 
Angeles &quot;has hit close to home for the labor movement,&quot; Executive Vice President Linda 
Chavez-Thompson said, recalling the use of police batons against janitors marching peacefully in 
Century City and on peaceful drywall construction workers in Southern California. &quot;Our movement 
will not tolerate police brutality nor will we excuse officers because the situation is volatile,&quot; she 
said. &quot;This is not a question of immigration rights, but of basic civil and human rights.&quot; </p>
<p>DIGNITY FOR NURSING HOME WORKERS -- Some 1,200 members of the Service 
Employees from 15 Beverly Enterprises nursing homes in Pennsylvania who went out on an unfair 
labor practices strike April 1 made an unconditional offer to return to work April 4 -- only for 
some to be told they would be permanently replaced. On the first shift, some 150 workers found 
they would not be allowed to return to work -- with some barred by security guards from entering 
facilities. Beverly said in an April 3 news conference it intended to replace one-third of the strikers. </p>
<p>OUTSOURCING RILES UAW -- Delegates to the <a href="http://www.uaw.org/">UAW</a> bargaining convention easily approved 
resolutions that direct union officials to get tough with the Big Three automakers over the use of 
outside, nonunion parts suppliers. Delegates also took a strong stand against health care cutbacks 
and called for less overtime in favor of hiring more workers. Contract talks with the Big Three 
begin in June. National contracts covering 400,000 UAW members at General Motors, Ford and 
Chrysler expire Sept. 14. </p>
<p>JUSTICE IN JEOPARDY -- Federal funding for the Legal Services Corp. is threatened by the 
GOP-led Congress, which also seeks to impose restrictions on legal workers for the poor. The 
National Organization of Legal Services Workers, UAW Local 2320, asks unionists to contact 
their member of Congress during the Easter recess to insist that poor people continue to have 
access to the judicial system. </p>
<p>HIT/BIT GROUND BREAKINGS -- The AFL-CIO's Housing and Investment Trusts will break 
ground for two new projects. On April 9, Executive Vice President Chavez-Thompson will join 
Housing and Urban Development Secretary Henry Cisneros at the ground-breaking ceremony for 
El Azteca housing development in Laredo, Texas. HIT is providing $1.1 million of the $3.4 million 
total cost of the project, which will provide low-income housing for 50 families. The next day, BIT 
will break ground in West Patterson, N.J., for the West Falls Plaza retail center. BIT is providing 
the $12 million needed to build the center. </p>
<p>MECHANICS' MEDICAL FUND -- A health insurance fund has been established to assist 
America West Airline mechanics fired last December. Those who were fired and those still working 
now are participating in the IBT balloting. Contributions can be made to the &quot;Fired America West 
Family Medical Fund&quot; through Bank of America, Account No. 235176969, or may be sent to 
IBT, 4444 West Northern Ave., Suite A-2, Glendale, Ariz. 85301. </p>
<p>ELECTION EARLY BIRD -- AFGE President John N. Sturdivant handed out leaflets during the 
morning rush hour on April 8 at the Virginia Rail Express station to kick off the union's efforts to 
educate federal employees about political issues and encourage voter registration to turn out record 
numbers of government workers on Election Day. The union handouts urge federal workers to take 
advantage of their newfound political freedoms under Hatch Act reform. </p>
<p>WORKERS' FUTURE -- The National Skills Standards Board, comprised of representatives 
from labor, business, education and civil rights organizations, has scheduled public hearings across 
the country to address U.S. worker concerns as it continues its efforts to develop the skills 
standards. The hearings will be held April 9 at the Kansas City Marriot Downtown in Kansas City, 
Mo.; April 11 at the Crowne Plaza Phoenix in Arizona; and April 15 at the Crowne Plaza Miami. 
For more information, contact Sally Conway at 202/254-8628. </p>
<p>MASTER APPAREL -- Employees of Master Apparel demonstrated April 1 outside the gates of 
the Summerville, Tenn., clothing manufacturer to protest the company's refusal to bargain in good 
faith on a new contract. Willie Rudd, president of IUE's furniture workers' division, led the march. 
The AFL-CIO has placed Master Apparel men's and boys' pants on its <a href="http://www.aflcio.org/boycott.htm">boycott list.</a> The pants are 
sold under the &quot;Botany 500&quot; label at Kmart, under &quot;Hills and Archer&quot; at Montgomery Ward and 
under &quot;Blair&quot; through the Blair mail order company. </p>
<p>FREE TRADE TOO EXPENSIVE -- The Commerce Department reported the biggest jump in 
the U.S. trade deficit in January in six months. The deficit in manufactured goods reached $14.4 
billion, compared with $13.8 billion a year earlier. Meanwhile, trade ministers meeting in Colombia 
seeking extension of free trade throughout the hemisphere were greeted by a poll indicating that 
only 24 percent of U.S. citizens think that so-called free trade agreements result in more U.S. jobs. </p>
<p>For details about these and other stories, check out LaborNET's &quot;News and Views&quot; library on 
CompuServe, or <a href="http://www.aflcio.org/">LaborWEB</a> the AFL-CIO's web site located at http://www.aflcio.org. To send 
information for inclusion, or FAX numbers to receive Work in Progress, FAX to 202/508-6908, 
or E-mail to <a href="mailto:71112.53@compuserve.com">71112.53@compuserve.com.</a> </p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="/publ/publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
