<head>
<title>WIP 04/02/96 AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<h2 align="center">AFL-CIO Work in Progress -- April 2, 1996</h2>
<p>UNION SUMMER BLOOMS -- <a href="http://www.aflcio.org/usummer">Union
Summer</a>, which will send hundreds of young activists around
the country to participate in union organizing drives and
get-out-the-vote activity, is focusing recruitment on children of
union members and young adult union members. More than 500
applications have been received, with 80 new applications coming
in each week. While applications will be taken all summer, those
wanting to participate in the June session are urged to get their
paperwork in by April 15. Site selections will be announced
throughout the summer, with the first announcement expected in
April. For information, call 800/952-2550, <a
href="mailto:organizers@aol.com">e-mail</a>, or see the <a
href="http://www.aflcio.org/usummer">Web site</a>. </p>
<p>FOOLS ON THE HILL -- Members of Congress (who earn $140,000
annually), led by GOP stalwarts, said &quot;no&quot; to a minimum
wage increase last week in both chambers. The minimum wage, which
comes to less than $9,000 a year for a full-time worker, has been
unchanged since 1991. Even with the help of eight Republicans,
Senate Democrats were unable to shut off a filibuster led by
presidential candidate and Majority Leader Robert Dole (R-Kan.)
and allow a vote on a measure to raise the benchmark hourly rate
from $4.25 to $5.15 over two years. Democrats have vowed to keep
bringing up the legislation. </p>
<p>GENERAL BOARD SELECTIONS -- AFL-CIO President <a
href="http://www.aflcio.org/sweeney.htm">John Sweeney</a>
announced the selection of four regional state federation
representatives to serve on the General Board, and the formation
of a 20-member State and Central Labor Council Advisory Committee
that will make recommendations to the federation. The regional
representatives are Frank Montanaro (Rhode Island) for the
Northeast; Daniel LeBlanc (Virginia) for the South; Daniel J.
&quot;Duke&quot; McVey (Missouri) for the Midwest; and Claude
&quot;Blackie&quot; Evans (Nevada) for the West. An additional
four members of the advisory committee will be elected during a
national conference for local AFL-CIOs in July. </p>
<p>ORGANIZING CORRECTIONS -- The <a href="http://www.cwa.org/">Communications
Workers</a> now includes some 9,000 corrections and probation
officers in Florida who affiliated with the National Coalition of
Public Safety Officers. The new CWA division represents law
enforcement workers in Texas, New Mexico and Arizona. </p>
<p>WALL-TO-WALL PUSH -- The <a href="http://www.seiu.org/">Service
Employees</a> are coming off two recent victories in New York and
Chicago. Service and maintenance workers at St. Bernard's
Hospital in Chicago voted 154-95 for representation by SEIU,
while the local also has filed on the clerical and technical unit
in a wall-to-wall strategy that eventually has a goal of
organizing registered nurses at the facility. Meanwhile, workers
at the George Junior rehabilitation facility in upstate New York
voted 59-53 for SEIU. They, too, have filed on the remaining unit
of about 40 teachers at the facility for troubled youth. </p>
<p>AMERICA WEST -- Sweeney added his voice and support for
mechanics at America West Airlines who are voting by mail for <a
href="http://www.teamster.org/">Teamster </a>representation after
the company fired 500 workers. &quot;The decision by the National
Mediation Board to send ballots to all America West workers --
those fired and those still working -- is a great victory for
you,&quot; he said. The ballots will be counted April 17. </p>
<p>UNION WOMEN GO TO SCHOOL -- The AFL-CIO Department of
Education and the University and College Labor Education
Association will sponsor four week-long residential schools to
educate female trade unionists. The 1996 Regional Summer Schools
for Union Women are: Western Women's Institute, June 5-9 at San
Francisco State University, contact Brenda Cochrane at 415/338-
2885; Southern School for Union Women, Aug. 11-16 at the George
Meany Center for Labor Studies, contact Brenda R. Moon at
202/637- 5331; Northeast Women's School, July 21-26 at Penn
State, contact Frieda S. Rozen at 814/865-5425; and Midwest
School for Women Workers, July 28-Aug. 2 at Indiana University,
contact Jean Troutman-Poole at 219/237-4469. </p>
<p>NEW HAVEN FOR ACTION -- Yale University food service and
custodial workers walked out March 27, shutting down 22 dining
halls and leaving trash uncollected. The strike began after talks
between Hotel Employees and Restaurant Employees Local 35 and the
university broke down over Yale's decision to subcontract
services. The workers, along with members of HERE Local 34, have
been without a contract since Feb 7. No more talks have been
scheduled. Local 34, which represents clerical workers, staged a
30-day strike that ended March 6. They were supported by the
1,100 workers in Local 35, who remained on the job and shared
their wages with the striking employees. </p>
<p>EYE ON SWEATSHOPS -- With news accounts documenting immigrants
locked behind closed doors and forced to work intolerable hours
in inhuman conditions, UNITE has focused attention on the renewed
fight against sweatshops with the release of art that will be
mass produced for T-shirts and shopping bags. The art, which
mixes words and images, includes a reproduction of a woman's head
in black and grey, with the message &quot;These clothes were not
made by exploited women and children in non-union
sweatshops.&quot; </p>
<p>SWEATSHOPS TWO -- AFL-CIO Executive Vice President <a
href="http://www.aflcio.org/chavez.htm">Linda Chavez-Thompson</a>
toured the L.A. sweatshop district and met with workers from the
El Monte shops, where last summer 70 Thais were discovered
working in virtual slavery conditions. Her March 29 visit
coincided with an announcement by the Labor Department and a
coalition of labor, consumer and religious organizations of a
national campaign to raise public awareness of continued worker
abuse in the U.S. garment industry. The campaign will include
&quot;NO SWEAT&quot; logos on products and &quot;Clues for
Consumers&quot; -- tips for shoppers who want to support efforts
to end sweatshops. </p>
<p>TAKING TO THE BRICKS -- More than 1,000 nursing home workers
employed at 15 homes run by Beverly Enterprises across
Pennsylvania began an unfair labor practices strike April 1. The
Service Employees members were forced out by &quot;Beverly's
flagrant disregard for the law,&quot; according to SEIU. More
than 200 charges are pending against the company, with the
National Labor Relations Board on record that &quot;Beverly is
illegally imposing harsh and restrictive work values designed to
silence Beverly workers.&quot; A rally is planned in Harrisburg
at the Capitol rotunda April 2. Unionists in Pennsylvania can
call a toll-free number for more information -- 800/797-8890. </p>
<p>DETROIT ARRESTS -- Detroit AFL-CIO President Edgar A. Scribner
and 64 other union officials were arrested outside the Detroit
Free Press building March 28 after protesting the Detroit
Newspaper Agency's failure to negotiate an end to the
nine-month-old newspaper strike. &quot;We are here to make it
clear they can't beat us in Detroit,&quot; Scribner said. The
presidents of 17 <a href="http://www.uaw.org/">UAW </a>locals
were arrested along with the leadership of UAW Region 1A and
officers of the Detroit AFL-CIO, <a href="http://www.afscme.org/">AFSCME</a>,
Seafarers, Roofers and Graphic Communications. The protest was
the fourth sponsored by Readers United, an independent Detroit
citizens group. The NLRB delayed hearings scheduled for March 25
on unfair labor practices charges filed by the workers against
the Detroit newspapers. No new date has been set. </p>
<p>NEW PACT FOR EQUITY -- Actors' Equity and the League of
Resident Theatres have reached agreement on a three-year contract
covering some 7,000 actors and stage managers at 64 theaters
across the country. The pact, which calls for salary increases of
more than 9 percent for actors in the largest-grossing theaters
and 4 percent in the smallest-grossing theaters over term,
improved safety conditions and health contributions, goes to
Equity's Council April 8 for determination of membership
ratification procedures. Theaters that operate under the LORT
agreement include Lincoln Center Theatre in New York City, the
Goodman Theatre in Chicago, the Mark Taper Forum in Los Angeles,
the American Repertory Theatre near Boston and Arena Stage in
Washington. </p>
<p>TIES THAT BIND -- Transportation Communications Union members
ended a 21-day strike March 28 at a Koppers Industries railroad
tie treatment facility in Somerville, Texas, after management had
threatened to hire permanent replacements. The strike had spread
to a plant in Galesburg, Ill., after the company shifted struck
work there. TCU struck March 8 after seven months of negotiations
failed to achieve any progress toward reaching a first
settlement. Union President Bob Scardelletti pledged TCU
&quot;will use the streength and experience forged in this
struggle every single day as we continue the fight for economic
justice.&quot; United Transportation Union President Charles
Little had offered UTU's support and cooperation to the Koppers
strikers. </p>
<p>PUBLIC EMPLOYEES DENIED -- State and local employees would be
denied the same job protections afforded federal or
private-sector workers if preliminary labor law recommendations
from the independent Advisory Commission on Intergovernmental
Relations are adopted, union officials said at a March 26 public
hearing. The ACIR's preliminary recommendations, which were
released Jan. 24, would repeal provisions of the Fair Labor
Standards Act, the Occupational Safety and Health Act and the
Family and Medical Leave Act that extend coverage of these
statutes to state and local governments. Addressing the hearing
were AFL-CIO Public Employee Department President Al Bilik and
James Sheedy, president of the Public Employees Federation of New
York State. </p>
<p>PENSION MAKE-GOODS -- The Pension Benefit Guaranty Corp.
announced it will inform about 135,000 people whose pension plans
ended between 1976 and 1981 that a proposed settlement is
expected to pay some 40,000 of them additional pension benefits.
The class- action suit, filed in 1988, was brought on behalf of
workers whose pension plans were not amended to comply with
shorter vesting standards required with the passage of the
Employee Retirement Income Security Act in 1974. A toll-free
telephone number, 800/316-8857, is available for information. </p>
<p>UNION WOMEN GO TO SCHOOL -- The AFL-CIO Department of
Education and the University and College Labor Association will
sponsor four-week-long residential schools to educate female
trade unionists. The 1996 Regional Summer Schools for Union Women
are: Western Women's Institute, June 5-9 at San Francisco State
Univesity, contact Brenda Cochrane at 415/338-2885; Southern
School for Union Women, Aug. 11-16 at the George Meany Center for
Labor Studies, contact Brenda R. Moon at 202/637-5331 Northeast
Women's School, July 21-26 at Penn State, contact Frieda S. Rozen
at 814/865-5425; and Midwest School for Women Workers, July
28-Aug. 2 at Indiana University, contact Jean Troutman-Poole at
210/237-4469. </p>
<hr>
<p>For these and other stories, check out LaborNET's &quot;News
and Views&quot; library on CompuServe, or the <a
href="http://www.aflcio.org/publ/">Public Documents page</a> on <a
href="http://www.aflcio.org">LaborWEB</a>, the AFL-CIO's Web
site, located at http://www.aflcio.org/. To send information for
inclusion, or FAX numbers to receive Work in Progress, FAX to
202/508-6908, or E-mail <a href="mailto:71112.53@compuserve.com">71112.53@compuserve.com</a>.</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="/publ/publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
