<html>
<head>
<title>WIP 03/26/96 AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<h2 align="center">AFL-CIO Work in Progress</h2>
<h3 align="center">March 26, 1996</h3>
<p>WORKING FAMILIES FOR CLINTON _ An historic special convention
of the AFL-CIO overwhelmingly endorsed President Clinton and Vice
President Gore for re-election after a process that
Secretary-Treasurer Richard Trumka said is a signal that labor is
&quot;doing things differently when it comes to politics.&quot;
The decision to endorse Clinton came after surveys of members by
AFL-CIO unions and comparisons of the Clinton record and
positions vs. those of Sen. Bob Dole, the Republican nominee.
Polls show that workers have moved to Clinton after 14 months of
Republican attacks on working families. In a head-to-head matchup
with Dole, union members prefer Clinton 67 percent to 22 percent.
Two-thirds of members said they would approve of their union
endorsing Clinton. Candidates Pat Buchanan and Ross Perot both
are held in low regard by union members, drawing a positive
opinion from only 16 percent and 27 percent, respectively. </p>
<p>CLINTON FOR WORKING FAMILIES _ Gore, addressing the convention
after the endorsement, contrasted the &quot;glaring&quot;
difference between the Clinton record and that of the
Gingrich/Dole Republicans, and promised that he and Clinton would
&quot;speak up loudly, boldly and clearly&quot; for working
families during the campaign. Gore also sent a message to
Republicans who have trumpeted that organized labor is dead.
&quot;As long as you are out of step with the values of American
families, you will not prevail,&quot; he warned. &quot;America's
working families and those who defend them are here to stay. And
we will prevail.&quot; </p>
<p>POLITICAL ACTION _ The nearly 500 delegates to the convention,
the first special convention since the merger of the AFL and CIO,
approved an assessment on affiliated unions of 15 cents per
member per month to fund a $35 million political campaign that
AFL-CIO President John Sweeney said would &quot;tell the
truth&quot; about downsizing and layoffs for short-term stock
manipulation, and the stagnant incomes for workers. Unions also
will tell the truth about Newt Gingrich and other radical GOP
congressional leaders who have attacked programs for workers
while they &quot;do the bidding of their corporate patrons.&quot;
While raising the critical issues affecting working families, the
AFL-CIO program will train 3,000 union activists for
get-out-the-vote activity this year, and build a permanent
network of grass-roots activists in every congressional district. </p>
<p>HATCHET JOB ON LABOR _ Sweeney had a warning for delegates:
&quot;Over the next few months, as our grass-roots legislative
and political program grows and begins to take hold, you are
going to witness the biggest smear campaign, the biggest
disinformation campaign in the history of American
politics.&quot; That GOP smear campaign began March 21 in the
House Oversight Committee with sham hearings to attack the
federation's legislative work. House Democrats called it an
&quot;inquisition&quot; against unions as they walked out.
&quot;The radical right . . . will attempt to convince America
our voice should be stilled _ despite the fact that ours is the
only voice in this country that speaks expressly for working
families,&quot; Sweeney said. </p>
<p>MOTHER OF REINVENTION _ AFGE President Sturdivant saluted the
Clinton-Gore administration March 25 at a conference on federal
&quot;reinvention.&quot; Clinton and Gore &quot;did not see the
federal employee as an obstacle on the road to change,&quot; he
said, &quot;and recognized that labor unions and management have
a mutual interest in making government work better.&quot; The
conference, convened by Gore and the National Performance Review,
runs through March 27 at the National Institutes of Health in
Bethesda, Md. </p>
<p>ORGANIZE AND ENFRANCHISE _ Political action for AFGE includes
an organizing campaign. &quot;Every time we sign up a new member
we will register them to vote,&quot; Sturdivant told reporters
March 20. &quot;The shutdown has taught us some hard political
lessons that we won't soon forget.&quot; Beginning April 1, a
&quot;Bonus Bucks/Passion and Power&quot; campaign will offer
cash incentives for member-organizers to sign new members. </p>
<p>&quot;THOSE WITHOUT SHAME&quot; _ Executive Vice President
Linda Chavez-Thompson, introducing the resolution to fund a $35
million political effort, said Latinos have a word for Republican
extremists who have sought to cut Medicare, Medicaid, college
loans, worker safety and health and labor protections _ sin
verg|enza<d>s, &quot;those without shame.&quot; Union members did
not realize that their votes in November 1994 would lead to this,
she said, &quot;but we exposed them with a broad communications
program. We spent $7 million educating our members and the
general public and we stopped the &quot;Contract With
America&quot; dead in its tracks. Now we need to spend about
seven times that much to bury it six feet under. </p>
<p>UAW EASES UP ON GM BRAKES _ Striking <a
href="http://www.uaw.org/">UAW</a> members returned to work March
22 after ratifying a new agreement with General Motors, ending a
17-day strike that idled most of the giant automaker's assembly
plants, forced the layoff of 177,000 workers and generated losses
to GM of up to $50 million a day. The two sides agreed that GM
would add 275 jobs to the Dayton, Ohio, brake plant to reduce
overtime and provide ergonomic relief in various jobs. The
company also agreed to replace work that was lost as a result of
contracting out antilock brake work. </p>
<p>FEDEX PACT TAKES FLIGHT _ The <a
href="http://www.fedex-alpa.org/fedex-alpa/">Air Line Pilots</a>
reached a tentative agreement with Federal Express Corp. that
features increased compensation and enhanced retirement benefits
for 3,000 pilots. The tentative pact resolves a &quot;scope&quot;
issue relating to the scheduling of bargaining-unit pilots, links
some pay raises to corporate profitability and implements
work-rule changes. No date has been set for balloting, but the
union has indicated it will move expeditiously to present the
agreement to the council and to the membership. </p>
<p>WORKERS BEAT BALLENGER _ Local union activists can take pride
in Rep. Cass Ballenger's decision to abandon legislation that
would gut the nation's job safety laws, said President Sweeney,
who credited &quot;their efforts to hold Washington accountable
that stopped this legislation.&quot; Teamsters President Ron
Carey said Ballenger's announcement means &quot;Newt Gingrich and
Bob Dole are putting their anti- worker attack dogs on a shorter
leash during the election.&quot; </p>
<p><a href="http://www.osha.gov/">OSHA</a> SILVER LINING _ April
28th, the 8th annual observance of Workers Memorial Day, marks
the 25th anniversary of the signing of the Occupational Safety
and Health Act, the nation's landmark job safety legislation.
With the statute under dire threat from extremists in Congress,
workers have a special opportunity to spotlight the need for job
safety this Workers Memorial Day. For information and materials
to help you plan your event, phone 202/637-5367 or FAX 202/508-
6978; or visit the World Wide Web site at <a
href="http://www.aflcio.org">www.aflcio.org</a>. </p>
<p>BLUE-LIGHT SPECIAL _ More than 1,000 labor and civil rights
activists protested and 41 persons were arrested March 24 at an
Atlanta Kmart store as UNITE kicked off a national campaign
against discrimination at a Kmart distribution center in
Greensboro, N.C. Workers at the Greensboro facility, mostly
African-Americans and other people of color, receive an average
of $4 less than white workers at Kmart's other hardline centers.
Those arrested included Bruce Raynor, UNITE's executive vice
president and southern regional director, Clayola Brown, the
union's civil rights director, Norman Hill, president of the A.
Philip Randolph Institute, William Lucy, <a
href="http://www.afscme.org/">AFSCME</a> secretary-treasurer,
Stewart Acuff, president of the Atlanta Labor Council and Richard
Womack, AFL-CIO civil rights director. </p>
<p>LEARN WHILE YOU EARN _ The <a href="http://www.cwa.org/">Communications
Workers</a> and US West signed a &quot;first in the
industry&quot; joint apprenticeship program establishing academic
and technical standards to help new workers gain the skills and
knowledge they need in the telecommunications industry. The
three-year apprenticeships will kick off in Washington state,
where workers will learn skills to establish and repair
telecommunications services for customers. </p>
<p>EARN WHILE YOU LEARN _ Members of the Painters will be able to
turn their union training into college credits thanks to an
agreement signed between the union and Marshall University in
West Virginia. The credits can be applied toward an associate
degree in applied science. The union &quot;is about more than
jobs in the painting and allied trades; it's about creating
careers in our industries,&quot; said A.L. &quot;Mike&quot;
Monroe, PAT president. </p>
<p>APPEALING ON SCABS _ A decision by a three-judge panel of the
U.S. Circuit of Appeals for the District of Columbia to strike
down President Clinton's executive order barring federal agencies
from doing business with companies that replace striking workers
should be reconsidered by the full court, the administration
said. &quot;The executive order is fair and based on a proper
reading of the president's procurement authority,&quot; Labor
Secretary Robert B. Reich said. &quot;Strikes involving
replacement workers are long, bitter, and pose a threat to
federal procurement. I am confident that the court will
ultimately reconsider its ruling and uphold the president's
executive order.&quot; </p>
<p>STRIKE IMMINENT AT BEVERLY _ Service Employees at Beverly
Enterprise facilities are poised to launch the largest nursing
home strike in Pennsylvania history on Friday. &quot;The workers
are fed up with Beverly's flagrant disregard for the law, and we
are prepared to strike to protest non-stop vicious attacks on our
members' rights,&quot; said District 1199P President Tom DeBruin.
Beverly, the nation's largest nursing home operator with over 700
facilities, 72 in the state, is the target of federal prosecution
for numerous labor law violations, and was cited last year by the
General Accounting Office as the nation's leading law violator
among 14 federal contractors. </p>
<p>U-6: FRIDAY, BLOODY FRIDAY _ The federal government has begun
reporting an official alternative unemployment rate that takes
into account discouraged workers, all other &quot;marginally
attached&quot; workers and persons working part time for economic
reasons. The new reporting system was urged by the AFL-CIO and
other members of the Americans for Democratic Action's First
Friday coalition. Using a methodology formally called
&quot;U-6,&quot; the new data will provide a broader, more
representative picture of those facing the uncertainties of an
imperfect economy. In February for example, the alternative rate
of all those affected was 10.7 percent, nearly double the 5.5
percent conventional rate. With the <a
href="http://stats.bls.gov/blshome.htm">BLS</a> officially
blessing the more precise measurement, the AFL-CIO hopes the
media will begin to tell the whole story. </p>
<p>MUSHROOM CLOUD _ Some 150 harvesters were fired March 14 by
the Florida mushroom ranch, Quincy Farms, after a lunch- break
march demanding an end to worker abuses and a contract with the
Farm Workers. At the urging of management, UFW Vice President
Rebecca Flores-Harrington and some 30 laborers were arrested
after the march. The union is requesting all union members to
contact Chairman Dennis Zensen at Quincy's Pennsylvania-based
parent company, Sylvan Inc., at 412/295- 3910 or via fax at
412/295-4111. </p>
<hr>
<p>For these and other stories, check out LaborNET's &quot;News
and Views&quot; library on CompuServe, or the <a
href="http://www.aflcio.org/publ/">Public Documents page</a> on <a
href="http://www.aflcio.org">LaborWEB</a>, the AFL-CIO's Web
site, located at http://www.aflcio.org/. To send information for
inclusion, or FAX numbers to receive Work in Progress, FAX to
202/508-6908, or E-mail <a href="mailto:71112.53@compuserve.com">71112.53@compuserve.com</a>.</p>
