<head>
<title>WIP 03/19/96 AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<h2 align="center">AFL-CIO Work in Progress</h2>
<h3 align="center">March 19, 1996</h3>
<p>POLITICAL OPENER _ More than 500 delegates are expected to
converge on Washington at the Capital Hilton March 25 for a
special convention devoted to the AFL-CIO's political efforts in
1996. Delegates will consider an ambitious nationwide program of
education and mobilization around issues important to working
families, and a special assessment on national unions of 15 cents
per member per month to help fund it. A possible presidential
endorsement also is on the agenda. Activity begins Sunday with a
meeting of central labor council leaders, and spills over into
Tuesday, when state federation officers gather to consider
statewide political campaigns. </p>
<p>UAW'S MESSAGE TO GM _ The UAW strike at two Dayton, Ohio,
General Motors brake plants continues to ripple across the
country, with 24 of 29 North American assembly plants and 44
parts plants closed, leading to layoffs of 111,550 workers. GM is
contesting unemployment benefits to workers laid off because of
the strike. Talks are continuing over the key issue of
outsourcing, which is expected to be a central focus for the
union in national contract talks later this year. The labor
movement is rallying behind the strikers. &quot;The other
employees that have been laid off understand the importance of GM
investing in GM and keeping good GM jobs there,&quot; AFL-CIO
Secretary-Treasurer Richard Trumka said. </p>
<p>SWEET VICTORY _ Hotel Employees and Restaurant Employees Local
217 is celebrating a 63-40 election victory at Trinity College in
Hartford, Conn., where the union will represent about 100
cafeteria workers employed by Marriott Management Services.
AFL-CIO President John Sweeney called to congratulate HERE
organizer Laura Moye, who is spearheading an effort to organize
low-wage workers across the Hartford area. &quot;This is just the
beginning,&quot; Moye said. &quot;These workers need a union, and
we're prepared to fight for them.&quot; </p>
<p>UNION IN STYLE _ Workers at Amity Dyeing and Finishing in
Augusta, Ga., voted overwhelmingly to join UNITE, making their
plant the last of Liz Claiborne's U.S. facilities to organize.
The 184 Amity workers were working without a pension plan, sick
days, shift differential and job security provisions, all
benefits enjoyed by their union brothers and sisters at other Liz
Claiborne plants. They voted 109-68 for the union on March 12. </p>
<p>RIGHT-TO-WORK SHAM _ A national &quot;right-to-work&quot; bill
has nothing to do with protecting rights, but &quot;is about
weakening unions, destroying democracy in the workplace and
forcing workers to labor for 20 percent less than they are now
earning,&quot; Montana AFL-CIO Executive Secretary Don Judge
testified March 15 before the Senate Labor and Human Resources
Committee. Judge led the successful fight against right to work
in Montana last year. Meanwhile, in Oklahoma, an effort to force
a right-to-work provision into another bill was rejected, 66-34,
in the House. </p>
<p>ALL-LABOR FIGHT AT KAISER _ President Sweeney will travel from
San Diego to Los Angeles to Oakland Tuesday for a series of
events to support the 30,000 embattled workers at HMO giant
Kaiser Permanente. Sweeney promised to &quot;renovate the HMO
that labor built&quot; through an escalating series of strategic
initiatives involving all 79 unions affiliated with the AFL-CIO. </p>
<p>COMMON SENSE ON WAGES _ Secretary-Treasurer Trumka, on CNBC-TV
March 14, responding to a question about raising the minimum wage
to $5.15 an hour: &quot;We have people who are working 40 hours a
week, 52 weeks a year and they still live in poverty. That's a
sin in a country like this and it doesn't have to be that way.
And the malarkey you hear _ `We have to pay these low wages to
stay competitive' _ it's just nonsensical because corporate
profits keep going up and up and up, corporate salaries for CEOs
keep going up and up and up. We ought to be sharing that, putting
it in the hands of consumers, so we can really grow an
economy.&quot; </p>
<p>FEWER DOLLARS, MORE DEATHS _ OSHA enforcement is on the
chopping block as Congress considers a bill to fund several
government agencies for the rest of the fiscal year. The House
version slashes the safety agency's enforcement budget by 21
percent and its overall budget by 10 percent. The Senate cuts 20
percent from enforcement and 7 percent overall. Field staff could
be cut by as many as 362 and ergonomic standards are stymied in
both. Other problem areas are education and the environment.
Congress avoided another partial government shutdown by passing a
temporary spending bill Friday, but that expires March 22. Call
your representatives and senators and urge them to restore OSHA
funding. </p>
<p>WORKPLACE VIOLENCE GUIDELINES _ New OSHA guidelines aimed at
preventing violence against health care and social service
workers were announced March 14 by Labor Secretary Robert Reich,
who was joined at a news conference by Merida Rodriguez of AFSCME
Local 420, Donna Edwards of AFSCME Local 112, Marcia Stulman of
Service Employees Local 4053 and Matthew Schultz of SEIU Local
1199RC. The guidelines offer employers common-sense solutions to
prevent workplace violence in the increasingly dangerous health
care and social service fields. </p>
<p>BRIDGESTONE AGAINST THE WORLD _ Representatives of unions from
14 countries joined the Steelworkers in a mass rally and
demonstration March 14 outside the U.S. headquarters of
Bridgestone/Firestone in Nashville. The marchers demanded that
the Japanese-owned tire manufacturer negotiate a fair contract
with its employees and rehire more than 700 workers not recalled
after a 10-month strike. &quot;Give them their damn jobs back.
That's what we want,&quot; USWA President George W. Becker
proclaimed as he opened the first international conference of
unions representing Bridgestone/Firestone employees. Said Vic
Thorpe, general secretary of the Brussels-based, 21
million-member International Federation of Chemical, Energy, Mine
and General Workers' Unions, &quot;We are frankly shocked at the
methods the multinational company has chosen to operate here in
the United States.&quot; </p>
<p>WOMEN ARRESTED IN DETROIT _ A Detroit city councilwoman, a
former state senator and AFSCME Vice President Gloria Cobbin were
among 44 women arrested in front of the Detroit News building
March 14. The peaceful demonstration was part of an ongoing
protest in support of Detroit newspaper strikers by Readers
United, an independent citizens group. &quot;Ending this strike
with a just contract is very important,&quot; said Lana Pollack,
a former state senator and U.S. Senate candidate. &quot;It's also
important to bring an arrogant corporate empire to accountability
under the law.&quot; The NLRB has filed unfair labor practice
complaints against the Gannett-owned Detroit News and
Knight-Ridder's Free Press for various illegal acts, including
&quot;permanently replacing&quot; the strikers. </p>
<p>WORKERS AWARDED MILLIONS _ In two settlements of Fair Labor
Standards Act lawsuits, SEIU has recovered $8.5 million in back
pay for some 21,000 workers. SEIU Local 2028 won $4.5 million for
700 San Diego County workers denied overtime pay, and some 20,000
will receive the final checks from a $4 million settlement with
the state of California, which violated the FLSA by failing to
pay the in-home health care workers on time during budget
impasses in 1990 and 1992. </p>
<p>WASHINGTON INC. THINK _ Hundreds of billions of dollars have
been &quot;diverted from the pockets of working-class Americans
into the bank accounts of America's financial elite,&quot;
declared Rep. Dave Obey (D- Wis.) March 11. He blamed public
policy driven by a network of conservative foundations, think
tanks and national magazines _ what he called &quot;Washington
Inc. Think&quot; _ that over 20 years has helped reshape American
economic policy &quot;from one that was based on the belief that
the needs of working families were as important as the needs of
raw markets to one based on the belief that the only thing that
mattered was the market forces.&quot; </p>
<p>AMERICA'S MOST UNWANTED _ The Teamsters have released a list
of &quot;America's Least Valuable Directors,&quot; 23 corporate
board members at companies marked by poor performance, excessive
executive compensation or both. Topping the list are former
defense secretary Frank Carlucci, 11-board member Vernon Jordan
and Marshall Criser, whose FPL Group reportedly lobbied for legal
changes to stifle shareholder dissent. IBT's report recommends
reforms in corporate governance, disclosure and proxy voting
procedures. </p>
<p>GETTING REAL _ The nation's 60-year-old labor laws no longer
fit the realities of an economy that includes the growing use of
contingent workers, a widening gap in wages between skilled and
low-skilled and the widespread lack of job security, AFL-CIO
General Counsel Jonathan Hiatt told an American Bar Association
audience made up mainly of management lawyers. To receive a copy
of his paper, &quot;Union Survival Strategies for the 21st
Century,&quot; call 202/637-5010. </p>
<p>WE'VE GOT A CONVOY _ Representatives of millions of truck
drivers and freight workers in the United States, Canada and
Mexico adopted an action plan to continue the delay on NAFTA
provisions on cross- border trucking that would hurt jobs,
highway safety and the environment. Included are educational palm
cards, messages on the Internet and CB radio, advertisements in
trade and general publications and joint research to support
organizing and contract campaigns. The plan was launched March 13
by both unionized and nonunion trucking groups at the NAFTA
Truckers' Summit in Chicago. </p>
<p>PRIDE AT WORK _ Pride at Work, the national organization of
gay and lesbian trade unionists, is planning its second biennial
conference in Oakland June 28-29. The conference will map out an
action plan for fighting right-wing attacks against both the
labor and lesbian/gay movements. The AFL-CIO opposes
discrimination based on sexual orientation, and President Sweeney
has written affiliates and local central bodies urging their
support of the conference. For information, contact Pride at
Work, 655 14th St., San Francisco, Calif. 94114; or call
415/861-0318. </p>
<p>DAUGHTERS TO WORK _ A Labor Guide is available for workers who
participate in &quot;Take Our Daughters to Work Day&quot; on
April 25. Participants will be eligible for a college scholarship
sweepstakes. For a free copy of the guide send a self-addressed 8
x 11 envelope with 78 cents postage to: KC Wagner, Cornell
University/NYSSILR, 16 East 34th St., 4th Floor, New York, N.Y.
10016; or call 212/340-2826. </p>
<p>STAND FOR CHILDREN _ Workers from across the country will
converge on the Lincoln Memorial June 1 for Stand For Children
Day. The event will focus on spiritual, family and community
renewal and personal commitment to children. It is sponsored by
the Children's Defense Fund and endorsed by the AFL-CIO and many
of its affiliated unions. For more information, call Marc Baldwin
at 202/637-5202. </p>
<hr>
<p>For details about these and other stories, check out
LaborNET's &quot;News and Views&quot; library on CompuServe, or
the <a href="http://www.aflcio.org/publ/">Public Documents page</a>
on <a href="http://www.aflcio.org">LaborWEB</a>, the AFL-CIO's
Web site, located at http://www.aflcio.org/. To send information
for inclusion, or FAX numbers to receive Work in Progress, FAX to
202/508-6908, or E-mail <a href="mailto:71112.53@compuserve.com">71112.53@compuserve.com</a>.</p>
