<html>

<head>
<title>WIP 03/11/96 AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h2 align=center>AFL-CIO Work in Progress</h2>
<p>BUDGET SHOWDOWN _ President Clinton has threatened to veto a GOP-crafted omnibus 
spending bill that would force cuts in education, training, OSHA and environmental programs. 
OSHA enforcement is cut back severely and the House bill includes a total ban on development, 
issuance and data collection for an ergonomic standard. The House passed the bill March 7 and the 
Senate will act this week. Current funding expires March 15 but may be extended for two weeks 
while the omnibus bill is finished. Write or call now and demand restored OSHA funding and 
standards-setting authority. <a href="http://www.standup.westlake.com/cgi-bin/letterselect">Contact</a> the following conferees: Sen. Mark Hatfield (R- Ore.), Sen. 
Robert Byrd (D-W.Va.), Sen. Arlen Specter (R-Pa.), Sen.Tom Harkin (D-Iowa), Rep. Robert 
Livingstone (R-La.), Rep. David Obey (D-Wis.) and Rep. John Porter (R-Ill.) </p>
<p>FRIENDS HELP _ AFL-CIO Secretary-Treasurer Richard Trumka helped rally Kentucky labor 
in electing Gov. Paul Patton (D) in November, and the new governor has kept his promises. Last 
week, he pushed a prevailing wage law through the legislature that unions have been working for 
since 1981. It was another collective effort by unionists in the state, said state AFL-CIO 
spokeswoman Lisa Wallace. &quot;We had fire fighters and transportation workers who aren't affected 
by the bill lobbying for it. The workers made it a fairness and justice issue and they just couldn't 
refute it.&quot; </p>
<p>BIG CITY UNION WINS _ The Service Employees have set their sights on another 1,000 
nonunion ambulance drivers in Chicago after winning the right to represent a unit of 650 emergency 
medical technicians employed by AMR. The Feb. 11 vote was an overwhelming 301-55 for SEIU. 
In New York City, meanwhile, the union won an election to represent 230 workers at New York's 
Bishop Mogavera Nursing Home. </p>
<p>FIRST SHOT AT KAISER _ Kaiser Permanente's practices have raised questions about the 
quality of care being provided to its 6.6 million subscribers nationwide. Labor participated in a 
North Carolina news conference March 7 that unveiled the problems found by state regulators 
studying Kaiser, including access to care, patient confidentiality, long waiting periods and member 
dissatisfaction. The federation's Industrial Union Department is coordinating efforts to bring about 
fair contracts for Kaiser workers and higher quality care for Kaiser subscribers. </p>
<p>DETROIT CONNECTIONS _ A March 6 demonstration by religious leaders in front of the 
Detroit News building to support striking newspaper workers led to the arrest of 24 people, 
including City Council President Maryann Mahaffey, a Catholic bishop and two Episcopal bishops. 
In Miami, where strikers have set up a phone bank to urge union members not to buy The Miami 
Herald, the flagship of Detroit Free Press owner <a href="http://www.dialog.com/">Knight-Ridder</a>, a new organization _ Sports Fans 
Against the Herald _ was announced at a home plate news conference March 11 in nearby 
Broward County. Knight-Ridder's &quot;two-faced policy toward the Cuban-American community&quot; was 
denounced by the Labor Council for Latin American Advancement, which called attention to a 
Free Press editorial urging the Clinton administration not to let &quot;its policy be held any more hostage 
to the Cuban-exile community than is already the case.&quot; Meanwhile, labor's &quot;don't-buy&quot; campaign 
against <a href="http://www.usatoday.com/">USA TODAY</a>, flagship of Detroit News owner <a href="http://www.gannett.com/">Gannett</a>, is spreading to hotels, airlines and 
other advertisers and distributors. </p>
<p>NAFTA ROADBLOCK _ Representatives of millions of truck drivers and freight workers from 
the United States, Canada and Mexico will roll into Chicago this Wednesday to seek ways to 
protect jobs, highway safety and the environment. The &quot;NAFTA Truckers Summit&quot; at the Hyatt 
Regency Hotel will be the first time union and independent truckers from the three countries have 
joined together to fight for these common interests. Included will be an action plan to extend a 
temporary delay of NAFTA provisions that would allow U.S. trucking companies to shift 
operations to Mexico. </p>
<p>NEWS VIEWS OF LABOR _ CBS Sunday Morning presented a portrait of a resurgent labor 
movement poised to answer the call of anxious workers beset by economic turmoil. New 
Organizing Director Richard Bensinger, shown campaigning to organize Delta flight attendants, was 
depicted as &quot;a circuit-riding preacher&quot; and &quot;chief evangelist for born-again unionism.&quot; AFL-CIO 
President John Sweeney told reporter Martha Tiechner that &quot;the American labor movement is going 
to change with the times. We're going to take some risks. We're going to use confrontation if that's 
necessary.&quot; A New York Times report Monday, headlined &quot;Students Looking to Unions for 
Careers in Social Change,&quot; found 400 students applying since October to be union organizers. &quot;I 
want a job where I can make a difference,&quot; said one history major. </p>
<p>THE SOUND OF BOSSES WHINING _ Representatives of fast food, banking, retail and other 
chains cried to a House Small Business subcommittee that a proposed <a href="http://www.doc.gov/nlrb/homepg.html">NLRB</a> rule on what 
constitutes a single-location bargaining unit for multi-unit companies would do major harm. But a 
UFCW attorney told the committee the rule is both &quot;sound and eminently sensible.&quot; Board 
Chairman William Gould defended the rule, saying it would be more efficient and less expensive to 
settle disputes. </p>
<p>STILL UNION _ Even scabs know a good thing when they see it. Employees at two Pirelli 
Armstrong plants, including more than 100 hired as replacement workers during an unfair labor 
practices strike last year, voted 825-32 to retain the Steelworkers as their bargaining agent after 
some of the scabs sought a decertification vote. &quot;It's a big ice cream social in the plant,&quot; said Lewis 
V. Milton, president of USWA Local 703. &quot;We just wiped them out. Even the replacements are in 
on our celebration.&quot; The vote covers Locals 703 in Hanford, Calif., and 670 in Nashville. </p>
<p>ANOTHER HARVEST OF SHAME _ A devastating plan that could flood the agriculture industry 
with low-cost foreign labor for the fields was added to an immigration bill in the House. The House 
Agriculture Committee ignored opponents who said there is no shortage of workers to harvest 
crops and that these new &quot;guest workers&quot; would drive down already low wages and lousy working 
conditions. In hypocritical fashion, many of the same people who want to give agribusiness a break 
with cheap temporary labor also call for a five-year ban on all other legal immigration. </p>
<p>FIGHTING FOR PEACE _ The <a href="../press96/pr0304.html">AFL-CIO expressed</a> deep sympathies to the nation of Israel 
over the deaths caused by four horrible terrorist bombings in nine days. &quot;It's difficult to see it on a 
day like this,&quot; President John Sweeney said, &quot;but history ultimately is on the side of the 
peacemakers. Unfortunately, the road to peace in the Middle East is a rough one that requires 
those of us who believe in it to struggle and fight to bring it about. Let us pray that day will come 
soon.&quot; </p>
<p>PARTIAL WORK AT GM PLANT _ Some of the 3,000 striking members of UAW Local 696 
at General Motors' Delphi Chassis Systems brake plants in Dayton, Ohio, agreed to return to work 
to produce parts for non-GM customers. The plants make parts for Chrysler, Saab and some other 
automakers. Disputes over subcontracting and health and safety triggered the third strike at the 
plants in five years. Other GM plants already are feeling the effects of the strike, with 11 plants 
idled Monday and others on the verge of shutting down. </p>
<p>BIPARTISAN HEALTH CARE BILL ADVANCES _ The Senate Labor and Human Resources 
Committee unanimously approved a bipartisan bill that would bar insurance companies from 
dropping people when they switch jobs or from denying coverage for pre-existing conditions. It 
would guarantee access to insurance for workers who have been laid off or leave their jobs to start 
a business or take early retirement as long as they have paid premiums for at least 18 months. 
AFL-CIO Legislative Director Peggy Taylor called the bill's provisions &quot;critically important first 
steps towards increased health security at minimal cost.&quot; The measure, S. 1028, is tentatively 
scheduled for floor action April 18. The House companion version, H.R. 2893, was introduced by 
Rep. Marge Roukema (R-N.J.) But House GOP leaders appear to be ignoring her bill _ which has 
the backing of many Democrats _ in favor of others that carry controversial provisions on medical 
malpractice and other issues. </p>
<p>SCHOOL VOUCHER THREAT REVIVED _ Backers of public school quality and funding were 
able to beat back an attempt to set up a voucher program in the District of Columbia that would 
have used public money to send students to private and religious schools. The experimental 
program was part of the fiscal 1996 appropriations bill for Washington that voucher opponents 
were able to stall, but was included in the omnibus spending bill passed by the House. The Senate 
is expected to vote on the spending bill this week and vouchers aren't in its bill. The fight will be in 
the House-Senate conference. </p>
<p>THE $4 CHISEL _ Postal Workers President Moe Biller blasted the Postal Service for using bad 
weather and the federal government shutdown as excuses for delaying by two weeks a 
cost-of-living adjustment negotiated in the latest national agreement. By delaying the COLA from 
the pay period ending March 2 to the pay period ending March 16, the USPS will chisel each 
APWU member out of $4.00, Biller said. The union plans to grieve the delay. </p>
<p>DON'T BUY THESE PANTS _ At the request of the Electronic Workers, Master Apparel was 
added to the <a href="http://www.aflcio.org/boycott.htm">AFL-CIO national boycott list</a> on March 4. IUE has filed unfair labor practices 
charges against Master Apparel, which makes Botany 500 boys pants, because of the company's 
failure to bargain in good faith. </p>
<p>AD CAMPAIGN _ <a href="http://www.seiu.org/">SEIU</a> and the Congress of California Seniors launched a series of print 
advertisements to support their campaign against Vencor/Hillhaven health care facilities. The ads 
will appear in weekly and monthly publications that reach 675,000 seniors. Vencor, which operates 
40 nursing homes and six hospitals in the state, refuses to acknowledge health care workers' 
solutions to patient care problems such as inadequate staffing and training. </p>
<p>ROOM FOR SISTERS _ <a href="http://www.teamster.org/">International Brotherhood of Teamsters</a> President Ron Carey will ask 
the union's July convention to change the name of the organization to include the role of its many 
female members. &quot;The current name has a lot of proud history behind it,&quot; Carey said. &quot;But it leaves 
out hundreds of thousands of Teamsters who are women.&quot; Carey is using the union's publications to 
ask members for their ideas for a new name. </p>
<hr>
<p>For Executive Council statements, reports and press conference transcripts, check out 
LaborNET's &quot;News and Views&quot; library on <a href="http://www.compuserve.com">CompuServe</a>, or <a href="http://www.aflcio.org">LaborWEB</a>, the AFL-CIO's Web site 
located at http://<a href="http://www.aflcio.org">www.aflcio.org</a>. To send information for inclusion, or FAX numbers to receive 
Work in Progress, FAX to 202/508-6908, or via E-mail <a href="mailto:71112.53@compuserve.com">71112.53@compuserve.com</a>.</p>
