<html>

<head>
<title>WIP 03/05/96 AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h2 align=center>AFL-CIO Work in Progress</h2>
<p>SPECIAL CONVENTION _ The call and credentials have gone out for a special convention in 
Washington March 25 to give all federation unions and union leaders a full voice in determining the 
scope and direction of the AFL-CIO political program for 1996. Delegates will discuss an 
ambitious program to &quot;reclaim America,&quot; and consider a special assessment for one year of 15 
cents per member per month to pay for the new activity. The convention also will consider whether 
to endorse President Clinton and Vice President Gore for re-election. </p>
<p>FALL TRAINING _ The first session of the National Labor Political Training Center started 
March 2 at the George Meany Center. The weeklong session is taking 43 AFL-CIO field staffers 
through campaign basics in preparation for this year's unprecedented political push. Eventually, 
3,000 staff and union volunteers will be trained and deployed in the fall get-out-the-vote campaign. </p>
<p>SPRING MEANING _ Groundwork for the federation's political activity will be laid with an 
exploration of a defining political issue _ the growing wage gap between the rich and average 
working families. The AFL-CIO will convene town hall meetings in 29 cities beginning in late 
March to hear from workers about the impact of stagnating wages on their families. </p>
<p>SUMMER ACTIVISM _ Union Summer, the AFL-CIO's program to get the next generation 
involved in the labor movement, is looking for potential participants and potential sites. Some 1,000 
young unionists and students will spend some of their time working on organizing campaigns, and 
will be available for get-out-the-vote and other activity. See the letter from AFL-CIO Executive 
Vice President Linda Chavez-Thompson at the end of this bulletin. </p>
<p>HAIL! HAIL! ROCK AND ROLL _ The Theatrical Stage Employees signed an agreement with 
the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame in Cleveland to represent about 40 workers in visitor service, 
security and audio- visual technicians. Museum Board Co-Chair and CEO William H. Hulett said 
the agreement was a natural outcropping of relationships with labor established during the 
construction of the building, designed by architect I.M. Pei. &quot;We are delighted to enlist in a 
partnership with labor, who has already done so much to support the museum,&quot; he said. </p>
<p>PULLING TOGETHER _ Steelworkers President George Becker and Aluminum, Brick and 
Glass President Ernest J. LaBaff have reached a &quot;handshake agreement&quot; on the basic elements of a 
merger agreement between their two unions. The next step, LaBaff said, would be for the ABG to 
go through its own internal procedures culminating in a convention vote on the proposal, with &quot;the 
prospects good for our merger to be consummated.&quot; The USWA executive board will discuss 
details at its next meeting. </p>
<p>JOINING FORCES _ The AFL-CIO and the Rainbow Coalition will work together to defeat 
corporate greed and the extremists in control of Congress, AFL-CIO President John Sweeney told 
the Rev. Jesse Jackson and a Rainbow Coalition Conference in Chicago last week. Sweeney 
vowed to fight for affirmative action, saying &quot;If affirmative action goes down, Davis Bacon, the 
Service Contract Act, the Fair Labor Standards Act, and the minimum wage bill will all follow.&quot; 
The coalition also honored Detroit's striking newspaper workers with an award and condemned 
media barons Knight Ridder and Gannett. Earlier in the week, Sweeney spoke to top CEOs at a 
meeting of the Business Council and to the U.S. Catholic Bishops Conference, and participated in a 
forum on corporate citizenship sponsored by Sen. Jeff Bingaman (D-N.M.). </p>
<p>ON THE ROAD _ President Sweeney addresses the Food and Commercial Workers' legislative 
and political conference Wednesday and travels to Philadelphia to address the AFL-CIO 
Education Conference on Thursday. He returns to Washington that evening as the guest of honor at 
the DC Friends of Ireland dinner. Secretary-Treasurer Trumka will address the Pennsylvania 
AFL-CIO convention Tuesday and travel to Los Angeles Friday for a series of events. Executive 
Vice President Chavez-Thompson is in Baton Rouge, La., Monday for the Louisiana AFL-CIO 
convention and will travel to Chicago for events with the Carpenters, Steelworkers and UNITE 
before receiving the Chicago AFL-CIO Labor Woman of the Year award. She is in Detroit on 
Thursday to talk with newspaper strikers and travels to Springfield, Ill., Friday for a rally. On 
Saturday, she's in Denver for a Labor Council for Latin American Advancement conference. </p>
<p>AFFIRMATIVE ACTION _ Trade unionists and civil rights advocates gathered at the Louisiana 
State Capitol Feb. 24 to protest Gov. Mike Foster's moves against affirmative action and black 
majority congressional districts. The Louisiana demonstration was a preview of the mass 
grass-roots actions planned across the country to defeat efforts in many states to eliminate 
affirmative action. The biggest test will be in California, where Gov. Pete Wilson successfully led a 
drive to get a ballot initiative to end affirmative action. President Sweeney has urged affiliates to 
help pull together resources and people to help a new coalition of women's and civil rights groups 
that has come together to fight the California proposal. </p>
<p>UNION LABEL BONDS _ Hillary Rodham Clinton on Wednesday will sew the first union label 
into a garment made by workers represented by UNITE at a midtown New York City garment 
manufacturer. Union labels have been used in the garment industry since the 1930s as a way to 
guarantee consumers that the clothing they purchase is made in the United States under decent 
working conditions. In joining UNITE President Jay Mazur and designer Nicole Miller of Nicole 
Miller Ltd., the first lady will be following in the footsteps of Eleanor Roosevelt, who in 1933 
sewed the first such label into a coat as part of the National Recovery Act.</p>
<p>Meanwhile, UNITE announced a new campaign to organize 10,000 nursing home workers in 
Florida. Rep. Carrie Meek (D-Fla.) helped to kick off the campaign Monday, joining Miami 
nursing home workers and religious and community leaders to present a five-foot tall Florida 
Nursing Home Workers' Bill of Rights. </p>
<p>SAVE OUR HOMES _ Unionists and other social activists will gather outside the Department of 
Housing and Urban Development Wednesday, March 6, to protest an attempt to eliminate the 
HUD Assignment Program, which provides mortgage assistance to homeowners who face 
foreclosure due to unemployment, illness, family breakup or other circumstances beyond their 
control. The 11 a.m. to 1 p.m. rally, sponsored by the Philadelphia Unemployment Project, will be 
followed by lobbying by homeowners and their supporters to urge continuation of a program to 
keep families in their homes. You can help by contacting HUD Secretary Henry Cisneros at HUD, 
Room 9100, 751 7th St. SW, Washington, D.C. 20410, or call 202/708-0417. </p>
<p>EARNINGS SHOULD GET REAL _ Average weekly earnings took another nosedive in January, 
falling 1.7 percent for the month and 15.7 percent since January 1979. Stagnant wages, not rising 
prices, are largely to blame. Except for energy prices, there was little if any evidence of inflation. 
Meanwhile, the merchandise trade deficit hit a new record last year at $159.6 billion, up from 
$150.6 billion in 1994. </p>
<p>COFFEE TALK _ CBS Sunday Morning will feature a segment on the labor movement's new 
organizing and political programs. The show, airing at 9 a.m. EST on Sunday, March 10, is 
expected to include reports from organizing campaigns and the AFL-CIO Executive Council 
meeting in Florida. </p>
<p>PUT RAIL SAFETY ON TRACK _ Locomotive Engineers President Ronald McLaughlin told the 
Senate Commerce, Science and Transportation Committee that safety problems that may have 
contributed to the recent spate of rail accidents are not new. &quot;We constantly meet roadblocks from 
the industry and FRA to our recommendations for adequate safety protection for our members and 
the public,&quot; he said. McLaughlin cited fatigue, crew size, substandard radio communications and 
inadequate signal systems. </p>
<p>STANDING BEHIND OSHA _ About 40 Mine Workers, Painters, Postal Workers, Service 
Employees and Plumbers and Pipefitters crowded into a hearing room Feb. 28 as the Senate 
Labor and Human Resources Committee met to mark up legislation that would emasculate OSHA 
protections for workers. But lengthy discussions forced postponement of a final vote until this 
week. </p>
<p>THE OREGON TRIAL _ Besides the &quot;right-to-work&quot; referendum drive, anti-worker forces in 
Oregon are using a ballot initiatives to raise the retirement age for workers in the Public Employees 
Retirement System and to reduce some benefits. Oregon public employee unions, AFSCME 
District Council 75 and Service Employees Local 503, believe the measure is an attempt to divert 
attention from the right-to-work ballot initiative. Backers of the constitutional amendment to 
increase the retirement age have until July 5 to gather 97,681 signatures to place the measure on the 
November general election ballot. </p>
<p>KEYSTONE STATE WELCOMES TRUMKA _ Secretary-Treasurer Richard L. Trumka 
returns to his home commonwealth for the Pennsylvania AFL- CIO convention this week in 
Philadelphia, where Trumka attended law school (at Villanova). Also scheduled to address the 
1,000 delegates to the biennial convention are AFSCME President Gerald W. McEntee, U.S. 
Secretary of Labor Robert Reich, state federation officers William George and Richard 
Bloomingdale, Philadelphia Council President Joseph Rauscher, U.S. Rep. Thomas Foglietta (D- 
Pa.), Gov. Tom Ridge (R) and numerous other national and state labor and political leaders. 
Trumka last week was in Pittsburgh for a Mine Workers testimonial dinner in his honor. </p>
<p>ORGANIZING ANSWERS _ The AFL-CIO and Cornell University are joining forces for a 
Union/University Research Conference March 31-April 2 at the Sheraton Washington Hotel. 
Participants whose registration fee has been received by the deadline, March 19, will receive 
copies of abstracts of the more than 35 papers being specially prepared for the conference. A 
registration fee of $125 covers all conference materials, workshops and plenary session, as well as 
working lunches and dinners. Space at the conference is limited, and it may be necessary to restrict 
attendance. For further information, contact Kate Bronfenbrenner at Cornell (607/255-7581), or 
<a href="mailto:lb23@postoffice3.mail.cornell.edu">E-mail</a>; or Sheldon Friedman at the AFL-CIO (202/637-5310), or <a href="mailto:71112.675@compuserve.com">E-mail</a>; or Vinnie O'Brien at 
the AFL-CIO (202/637-5287 or FAX 202/637-5012). </p>
<p>The following letter from Executive Vice President Linda Chavez-Thompson was included in the 
distribution of the Work in Progress bulletin: </p>
<p>Dear Trade Unionists, </p>
<p>The AFL-CIO is planning an exciting Union Summer designed to bring the next generation into the 
labor movement. You can help by guiding young unionists or students to the program, or by 
providing the organizing campaigns in which they can work. </p>
<p>The federation plans to recruit 1,000 young workers and students to work in organizing campaigns 
and political projects at 10 or more sites round the country between June and August. Recruitment 
efforts are focused on young rank-and-file workers, the sons and daughters of union members, and 
college students. </p>
<p>Those who are accepted to the program will intern for three weeks at a Union Summer site, getting 
training, free housing and a $210 per week stipend. Affiliates soon will receive materials, including a 
video and articles and ads for their publications. Please help spread the word. </p>
<p>The best proposals for Union Summer projects include new organizing or first-contract fights in 
units of 500 or more, as well as campaigns that involve innovative tactics, multiple unions, whole 
industries or regions. </p>
<p>Applicants must be able to host as many as 20 young people in two or three waves and be willing 
to share costs with the AFL-CIO. Submit proposals by March 15 to Union Summer, 815 16th St. 
NW, Washington, D.C. 20006. FAX 202/408-0303. For further information, phone 
1-800/952-2550 or 202/408-0300. To order a video, call 1-800/242UNION. </p>
<p>Together, we can make Union Summer a transforming experience for young people and the labor 
movement. </p>
<p>In solidarity,<br>
Linda Chavez-Thompson<br>
</p>
<hr>
<p>For Executive Council statements, reports and press conference transcripts, check out 
LaborNET's &quot;News and Views&quot; library on <a href="http://www.compuserve.com">CompuServe</a>, or <a href="http://www.aflcio.org">LaborWEB</a>, the AFL-CIO's Web site 
located at http://<a href="http://www.aflcio.org">www.aflcio.org</a>. To send information for inclusion, or FAX numbers to receive 
Work in Progress, FAX to 202/508-6908, or via E-mail <a href="mailto:71112.53@compuserve.com">71112.53@compuserve.com</a>.</p>
