<head>
<title>WIP 02/27/96 AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h1 align=center>2-27-96 AFL-CIO &quot;Work in Progress&quot; 
Newsletter</h1>
<p>FULL SPEED AHEAD _ The AFL-CIO Executive Council launched major organizing, legislative, 
political and public affairs campaigns to build a strong new force on behalf of working families. The 
federation will help fund innovative and well-planned organizing drives, as well as recruit and place 
a thousand young workers and students for an activist Union Summer. Town hall meetings will be 
held in 29 U.S. cities between mid-March and May to air the problems of wage stagnation. 
Thousands of union activists will be trained in message and political tactics, beginning with field staff 
training Saturday, March 2, at the George Meany Center for Labor Studies, and thousands more 
will be enlisted for a massive get-out-the-vote campaign this year. </p>
<p>REORGANIZING _ President John Sweeney announced next steps in AFL- CIO reorganization 
with sweeping changes designed to streamline operations and make them more responsive to the 
needs of affiliated unions. All field services will be brought under one department, headed by 
Marilyn Sneiderman, 39, currently Teamsters education director and a former staffer at <a href="http://www.afscme.org/">AFSCME</a> 
and then the George Meany Center. Field services will be organized into four or five regions, rather 
than the current 12. These changes include: </p>
<ul>
<li>Economic research and employee benefits will be consolidated into a new Public Policy 
Department and all communications are being consolidated in a Department of Public 
Affairs, with divisions for media relations, speechwriting, publications and electronic media 
production. Michael Byrne, 47, editor of the AFL- CIO News since 1989, was named to 
head the publications division, and Richard Foster, 45, assistant director of the former Labor 
Institute of Public Affairs for five years, will head the electronic media division. </li>
<li>Sweeney also announced that a new Department of Corporate Affairs will assist unions 
through three divisions: a center for strategic research, providing research on multinational 
corporations, worker ownership and pension investment strategies; a center for collective 
bargaining, tracking bargaining developments and helping to train union negotiators; and a 
center for workplace democracy, focusing on the voice of workers in technology, job design 
and labor-management issues. </li>
</ul>
<p>EMPOWERED _ Workers at the Gavin Power Plant in Cheshire, Ohio, voted overwhelmingly for 
representation by the Utility Workers. The 176-98 vote on Feb. 22 is just the first step for the 
workers, said <a href="http://www.access.digex.net/~miner/">UWUA</a> President Donald E. Wightman, who said he expected cooperation in 
bargaining with American Electric Power, the parent company that also operates other 
UWUA-represented sites. &quot;We are not just interested in winning elections,&quot; Wightman said. &quot;It is 
our desire to maintain and create good union jobs for the benefit of our members and their 
communities.&quot; </p>
<p>DON'T TURN OUT LIGHTS _ The AFL-CIO warned of a dangerous trend toward deregulation 
of the electric utility industry that threatens hundreds of thousands of jobs, electrical service and 
years of environmental progress. The Executive Council statement also noted that radical 
deregulation of the industry would result in higher rates for residential users. </p>
<p>WORKERS ON THE MOVE _ Nearly 10,000 unionists braved heavy rains Feb. 19 to Rally for 
Working Families at the state Capitol in Olympia, Wash. Speakers included Sen. Patty Murray 
(D), Gov. Mike Lowry (D) and state AFL-CIO President Rick Bender, who decried the &quot;class 
war&quot; being waged on working people by corporations and legislators. &quot;The power of solidarity is 
unions,&quot; the leading banner declared _ with the word &quot;unions&quot; spelled out with logos from 78 
national and international unions. Meanwhile, in Los Angeles, more than 20,000 union construction 
workers took the day off Feb. 26 to protest Gov. Pete Wilson's proposal to lower the prevailing 
wage, the second major California rally over the issue. </p>
<p>COMING TOGETHER _ President John Sweeney addresses the U.S. Catholic Conference 
Tuesday and a business forum on corporate leadership Thursday, both in Washington, and travels 
to Chicago Friday for the Rainbow Coalition National Conference. Secretary- Treasurer Rich 
Trumka is interviewed on Wisconsin Public Radio today and addresses the Utility Workers 
legislative conference Wednesday. Executive Vice President Linda Chavez-Thompson is in 
Washington for the National Hispanic School Fund gala Wednesday, then travels to Massachusetts 
Thursday for the Harvard Trade Union Program. She will address UNITE's Women's Institute for 
Leadership Development Friday before joining Sweeney and Trumka in Pittsburgh Saturday for a 
testimonial dinner for Trumka. </p>
<p>TAKING ON GIANTS _ The villain publishers of Detroit, Gannett and Knight-Ridder, are being 
followed to their home turf by labor's campaign to win justice for strikers at the Detroit News and 
Detroit Free Press. Several airlines have agreed to stop distributing Gannett's USA TODAY, and 
South Florida activists have set up phone banks to urge readers to boycott The Miami Herald, 
Knight-Ridder's flagship newspaper. That campaign also is informing Hispanic readers they are 
being double-charged for the Spanish version, El Nuevo Herald. Gannett is the nation's largest 
publisher and Knight-Ridder is the third-largest. </p>
<p>BLACK MARK ON SAFE JOBS _ The Senate Labor and Human Resources Committee on 
Wednesday takes up legislation sponsored by committee Chairman Sen. Nancy Kassebaum 
(R-Kan.) and Sen. Judd Gregg (R-N.H.) that would emasculate the nation's job safety laws. 
Unionists are urged to call committee members today to voice displeasure at the 
Gregg-Kassebaum bill, which would strip workplace safety and health protections from two out of 
three workers. On this 25th anniversary of the 1971 Occupational Safety and Health Act, unionists 
also are urged to continue making plans to remember fallen co-workers and rally for safe jobs on 
April 28, Workers Memorial Day. For more information, contact Keith Mestrich at 
202/637-5210, or e-mail at <a href="mailto:71363.1544@compuserve.com">71363.1544@compuserve.com</a>. </p>
<p>LOOSE BUCHANAN _ A New York Times poll shows that while GOP presidential candidate 
Patrick Buchanan is trying to tap into the frustration of workers over stagnant wages and bad trade 
deals, his supporters mostly are focused on his social views. Sweeney told reporters at the 
Executive Council meeting last week that Buchanan is anything but a friend of workers: he opposes 
raising the minimum wage, wage standards, worker health and safety protections and the right of 
workers to freely join and form unions. </p>
<p>SPRINT HANGUP _ The <a href="http://dol.gov">Labor Department</a> is holding a hearing today in San Francisco over 
allegations by Hispanic workers that they were fired illegally by Sprint Corp. during a union 
organizing drive at the company's La Conexion Familiar subsidiary. The hearing is the first under the 
North American Free Trade Agreement for complaints brought by the Mexican government over 
violations of U.S. labor laws, and was pursued by the Mexican telephone union in consultation with 
the Communications Workers. Four complaints have been pursued by U.S. unions for violation of 
Mexican labor laws. Under NAFTA, there are no penalties for such violations _ just hearings. </p>
<p>PARTNERS FOR HEALTH _ Sweeney closed out the federation's winter meeting in Bal Harbour 
with a tour of Miami's Jackson Memorial Hospital, where workers are represented by the Service 
Employees, AFSCME and the Office and Professional Employees. He held a community meeting 
with Jackson Memorial CEO Ira Clark to talk about how labor and management can work 
together to save the public health safety net. Jackson Memorial, the country's second-largest public 
hospital, receives nearly half of its revenues from Medicare and Medicaid funding, now under 
attack from Republicans in Congress, to serve the many seniors who have retired to South Florida. </p>
<p>NURSING HOME DRIVE _ The Food and Commercial Workers and Service Employees are 
working together to help improve patient care conditions in Beverly Enterprises nursing homes. The 
two unions brought Beverly workers from Pennsylvania, Georgia and Connecticut to rally with their 
counterparts in Alabama, where they announced a national campaign to improve conditions at 
Beverly facilities. The unions have documented the poor quality care at Beverly, the nation's largest 
nursing home operator which has been cited for numerous labor law violations going back to 1979. </p>
<p>NO SOLUTION FOR EDUCATION _ School voucher programs like the one that Congress is 
trying to ram down the throat of the Washington, D.C., school system &quot;undermine the system of 
public education that working families have fought so hard to obtain,&quot; the Executive Council said in 
a statement issued last week. Pointing to the failed voucher system in Milwaukee, where activist 
parents took their children to private schools and left the public school system fragmented, the 
council called on legislators to seek real reform of the public schools, rather than inviting their 
abandonment. </p>
<p>THIS CARD AN ACE _ The Executive Council approved a new MasterCard proposal from 
Household International that is &quot;a better deal for our members and it sends a good portion of what 
are now the bank's profits back into our movement so we can help build a more secure future for 
work Americans,&quot; Sweeney said. Unless the Bank of New York matches the offer, it is effective in 
February 1997, when the federation and participating unions also begin to collect royalty payments 
for use of the AFL-CIO name on the cards, used by 2 million union members. Sweeney told the 
council those payments could reach $375 million over five years. The card rate will stay at prime 
plus 5 percent (13.5 percent, more than 4 percent below the national average), and it features other 
new benefits. </p>
<p>NEW COMMITTEES _ Issues of the changing workplace will be addressed by a new Executive 
Council Committee on Workplace Democracy, which will be headed by Communications Workers 
President Morty Bahr. Sweeney also created a new Committee 2000, which he will chair, to 
consider the structure and role of the AFL-CIO and its trade and industrial departments, and how 
best to integrate the work of the labor movement. Several committees and subcommittees were 
eliminated and a number of others were combined or renamed. </p>
<hr>
<p>For Executive Council statements, reports and press conference transcripts, check out 
LaborNET's &quot;News and Views&quot; library on <a href="http://www.compuserve.com">CompuServe</a>, or <a href="http://www.aflcio.org">LaborWEB</a>, the AFL-CIO's Web site 
located at http://<a href="http://www.aflcio.org">www.aflcio.org</a>. To send information for inclusion, or FAX numbers to receive 
Work in Progress, FAX to 202/508-6908, or via E-mail <a href="mailto:71112.53@compuserve.com">71112.53@compuserve.com</a>.</p>
