<html>

<head>
<title>WIP 02/22/96 AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h3 align=center>Work in Progress<br>
2/22/96 </h3>
<p>The full text of AFL-CIO Executive Council statements and press conferences are available on 
LaborNET's &quot;News and Views&quot; library on CompuServe, or on the AFL-CIO web page at 
<a href="http://www.aflcio.org">http://www.aflcio.org</a>. </p>
<p>RECLAIM AMERICA _ The Executive Council committed $35 million to mount an issues-driven 
political campaign in 1996 to take back America for working families. The goal: to build a 
permanent grassroots structure this political season that will carry over into the legislative battles of 
1997 and beyond. The federation will strengthen state and local AFL-CIOs, train thousands of 
union activists in message and political tactics and involve thousands more rank-and-file members in 
an intensive get-out the vote effort. The AFL-CIO also will go public with a $15-$25 million buy of 
national television and radio advertising that will champion economic and social justice. </p>
<p>SPECIAL CONVENTION _ The council authorized President John Sweeney to call a special 
constitutional convention to consider a one-year assessment on national unions of 15 cents per 
member per month to help finance the political campaign, and to consider endorsements for 
president and vice president. The convention will be held in Washington, tentatively on March 25. </p>
<p>THE OREGON MODEL _ Labor already has a successful political model for 1996, Sen. Ron 
Wyden told the council as he thanked the labor movement for putting him over the top in a special 
Oregon election in January. &quot;Labor ran a textbook campaign,&quot; he said. &quot;You ignited a grass-roots 
revolution.&quot; Political Director Steve Rosenthal and Deputy Director Rich Walsh directed 40 field 
staff and hundreds of volunteers, turning out 80 percent of union voters in suburban districts and 
giving Wyden an 18,220-vote margin in the mail ballot. </p>
<p>BUCHANAN UNDRESSED _ &quot;Patrick Buchanan is a racist, he's antisemitic, he bashes women 
right along with labor and immigrants and he's a believer in supply-side economics. We are none of 
those things,&quot; Sweeney told reporters after Buchanan beat Bob Dole in the New Hampshire 
Republican primary. &quot;Our movement isn't about dividing people through fear, it's about bringing 
people together through compassion.&quot; </p>
<p>A FIGHT FOR YOUNG AND OLD _ The council explored political coalition-building at both 
ends of the age spectrum, hearing from Marian Wright Edelman of the Children's Defense Fund 
and Steve Protulis of the National Council of Senior Citizens. The union leaders were moved by 
Edelman's impassioned plea for support for her organization's June 1 Stand For Children Day at 
the Lincoln Memorial in Washington, cosponsored by the AFL-CIO and 33 affiliated unions, and 
reinvigorated by Protulis's presentation on the role seniors have played in the Medicare debate, and 
will play in the general election. </p>
<p>MOTOWN SPIRIT _ The council welcomed six strikers from the Detroit News and Detroit Free 
Press as it heard Secretary-Treasurer Rich Trumka report on a wide range of strategic activity 
under way and being planned against publishers Gannett and Knight-Ridder to help the workers 
gain a fair contract. Knight-Ridder's flagship newspaper, the Miami Herald, was banned from the 
hotel, and south Florida unionists are developing a boycott campaign against the Herald and fighting 
discrimination in the distribution of its sister publication, El Nuevo Herald. Unions also are working 
with airlines and hotels to ban Gannett's flagship publication, USA TODAY. Council members 
pledged tens of thousands of dollars to the AFL-CIO &quot;adopt-a-striking-family&quot; program, and to 
publicize the availability by mail subscription of the strikers' alternative paper, The Sunday Journal. </p>
<p>SMALL WORLD _ The impact of foreign trade on American workers is severe and unrelenting, 
the AFL-CIO said as it outlined a fair trade policy that would insist on worker rights as a 
precondition to trade with other countries. The federation also urged the Clinton administration not 
to renew China's most-favored-nation trade status. </p>
<p>EARLY REVIEWS ARE IN _ The nation's eyes are on the Executive Council's last meeting in Bal 
Harbour, Fla., with about 20 reporters from around the country on the scene. Frank Swoboda of 
the Washington Post on Sunday quoted John Sweeney as offering two yardsticks for measuring his 
first year as president of the AFL-CIO: the level of &quot;success in the November elections and 
whether we're starting to show membership growth.&quot; In a Feb. 16 New York Times piece by 
Steven Greenhouse, Sweeney scoffed at the notion that representing working people makes 
organized labor a &quot;special interest.&quot; &quot;I don't get upset being referred to as representing a special 
interest,&quot; he said. &quot;If representing American workers is a special interest, then I'm proud to 
represent that special interest.&quot;</p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="/publ/publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
<hr>
