<head>
<title>WIP 02/21/96 AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h1 align=center>AFL-CIO &quot;Work in Progress&quot; Bulletin 
February 21, 1996</h1>
<p>For the full text of Executive Council statements and reports, consult LaborNET's &quot;News and 
Views&quot; library on CompuServe, or see the AFL-CIO Web pages at http://<a href="http://www.aflcio.org">www.aflcio.org</a>. </p>
<p>AMERICA NEEDS A RAISE _ The AFL-CIO linked its legislative, organizing, bargaining and 
political efforts under a single, powerful theme: &quot;America Needs a Raise.&quot; The Executive Council 
statement came after a panel discussion on the growing wage gap. &quot;The gap between the rich and 
the rest of us is becoming a sinkhole of social and economic conflict, and if we don't fill it in, it is 
going to swallow us all,&quot; AFL-CIO President John Sweeney told reporters. </p>
<p>GOING ON THE ROAD _ Sweeney also announced that he and other federation officials will 
chair town hall meetings in 29 cities around the country from March 15 through May to hear from 
workers on the impact of stagnant wages on their families. &quot;Our goal,&quot; he said, &quot;is to transform 
individual concerns into a compelling national cause, sensitizing politicians and policy-makers as we 
mount a massive educational campaign to motivate unrepresented as well as represented workers.&quot; </p>
<p>MESSAGE FROM REICH _ &quot;We have the beginnings of a movement in this country that is not 
just a trade union movement, although it is led by unions,&quot; Labor Secretary Bob Reich told the 
Executive Council. &quot;It is a movement of working people who are fed up.&quot; Reich said he believes the 
future of American society is at stake in the campaign. &quot;What you are doing is terrific _ you are 
going to be the difference between a just society and an unjust society. </p>
<p>100,000 NEW MEMBERS _ District 1199, the National Health and Human Services Union, was 
welcomed home Tuesday as President Dennis Rivera dedicated his activist membership of more 
than 100,000 New York City hospital workers to help the labor movement achieve its ambitious 
political and economic goals this year. The union began as a unit of 5,000 pharmacists in the Retail, 
Wholesale and Department Store Union, then grew dramatically to serve low-paid health care 
workers. Part of the union later merged with both the Service Employees and AFSCME, then the 
New York unit went out on its own in an amicable split with RWDSU in 1991. &quot;This union has 
done remarkable things for its workers,&quot; said RWDSU President Lenore Miller. &quot;We welcome 
them back.&quot; </p>
<p>SENIORS RALLY IN BAL HARBOUR _ Organized labor will keep fighting to &quot;protect 
Medicare, Medicaid and Social Security _ benefits you have earned,&quot; Sweeney told more than 600 
members of the National Council of Senior Citizens, who rallied in an overflowing ballroom at the 
Sheraton Bal Harbour. Efforts by the AFL-CIO and the NCSC to dramatize the plight of seniors 
as congressional Republicans threaten their programs with deep cuts was praised by House 
Minority Leader Dick Gephardt (D-Mo.), who told the council on Monday that the AFL-CIO 
television advertising and NCSC rallies around the country had forced the GOP to retreat on those 
issues. </p>
<p>NATURAL ALLIANCE _ Susan Bianchi-Sand, chair of the Council of Presidents of National 
Women's Organizations, proposed an alliance of the labor movement and the women's movement 
centered on the issue of economic justice. The proposal will be taken up by the new Women's 
Committee, chaired by Electronic Workers Vice President Gloria Johnson, president of the 
Coalition of Labor Union Women. </p>
<p>TREASURY FIRST _ Bob Rubin, the first Secretary of the Treasury to meet with the executive 
council, said he welcomed a continuing dialogue with leaders of the AFL-CIO. &quot;It will be most 
helpful for us to know what's on your minds as we deal with economic policy,&quot; he said. Labor's 
views are especially important because the current &quot;public policy debate on the budget and 
economic issues may be the most important since the end of World War II,&quot; he said. The council 
praised Rubin for his skill at holding off Republican budget cutters but criticized the monetary 
policies of the Federal Reserve Board and its chairman, Alan Greenspan, and warned that further 
efforts to negotiate trade agreements without provisions for worker rights would outrage American 
workers. </p>
<p>COMING UP _ The AFL-CIO will unveil its 1996 political program today and welcome Ron 
Wyden, who last month became Oregon's first Democratic senator since the `50s largely because 
of labor's political support. Also visiting the Executive Council are Sen. Jay Rockefeller (D-W.Va.) 
and Marian Wright Edelman, executive director of the Children's Defense Fund, who will tell of 
plans for a march on Washington for children this summer. </p>
</body>

</html>
