<head>
<title>WIP 02/20/96 AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h1 align=center>2-20-96 AFL-CIO &quot;Work in Progress&quot; 
Newsletter</h1>
<p>ORGANIZE! SHIFT RESOURCES, SPEND SMART _ The AFL-CIO Executive Council this 
week outlined a broad plan for the federation to lead unions to &quot;Build Power for Workers By 
Organizing.&quot; The plan includes guidelines for a new AFL-CIO fund to help support innovative, 
well-planned organizing projects. The project is designed to help unions build an organizing 
infrastructure and foster a new &quot;culture of organizing&quot; _ down to the local level. The full text of the 
statement is available in the LaborNET &quot;News and Views&quot; library on CompuServe, or on the 
AFL-CIO web page at http://<a href="http://www.aflcio.org">www.aflcio.org</a>. </p>
<p>RISK, FIGHT, WIN _ Workers and organizers from AFSCME, UNITE, CWA, IBEW and the 
Laborers told the council about the fights they're waging to bring justice to workers across the 
country. Monica Russo, UNITE's southern organizing director, summed up euphoria organizers feel 
with the AFL-CIO's plans to lead massive new activity: &quot;Out in the field, we are thrilled because 
we see a new direction in the labor movement. We've been banging away long and hard for many, 
many, many years, and we look forward to working in an environment where we can take more 
risks, pick more and bigger fights, and win bigger victories for workers in the South and all across 
America.&quot; </p>
<p>BONIOR ON ORGANIZING _ Among those listening to the organizers' inspiring stories was 
House Minority Whip David E. Bonior (D- Mich.), who had asked to come early (he was 
scheduled to address the council later in the day) to hear the report on organizing. Later, at a news 
conference, he explained his personal excitement with the reinvigoration of the labor movement, 
saying he senses a &quot;real hunger for community&quot; among the American people. &quot;The labor movement 
is the vehicle that can make that happen.&quot; </p>
<p>A STEAL FOR WOMEN _ The AFL-CIO again raided the U.S. Department of Labor, naming 
Women's Bureau Director Karen Nussbaum to head a new AFL-CIO Working Women's 
Department. Nussbaum, founder of 9-to-5, the National Association of Working Women, and 
subsequently of District 925 of the Service Employees recalled thinking, when listening to the 
problems of working women as head of the Women's Bureau, &quot;this woman shouldn't be talking to 
me. She should be talking to a union organizer.&quot; Steve Rosenthal, now AFL-CIO political director, 
also was an advisor to Labor Secretary Bob Reich, who addressed the council. </p>
<p>LOOKING FOR A FEW GOOD CAMPAIGNS _ The coordinator for Union Summer told the 
Executive Council that he will help put a thousand young unionists and college students into 
organizing campaigns to help also with get-out-the-vote activity and social and economic activism. 
Union Summer Director Andy Levin said the young activists will transport themselves to the sites, 
then receive $200 a week, with affiliated unions and state and local central bodies asked to provide 
lodging and transportation during the intensive three-week campaigns. </p>
<p>SUPPORT FROM THE TOP _ President Clinton will veto any attempt by the Republicans in 
Congress to weaken the nation's job safety laws, Vice President Gore told the Executive Council. 
Gore also reiterated the president's pledge to veto the company union bill (the so-called TEAM 
Act) if it is passed, as well as any weakening of the nation's two prevailing-wage laws _ the 
Davis-Bacon Act and Service Contract Act. Clinton will take the case for an increase in the 
minimum wage to the American people during the 1996 political campaign, Gore said. </p>
<p>DEFINING ISSUE _ Sweeney on Tuesday will announce details of his plans for a series of town 
hall meetings around the country to hear the concerns and ideas of workers about the growing 
wage gap separating the nation's rich and average working families. BLS reported last week that 
pay and benefits together in the private sector rose only 2.8 percent in 1995, down from 3.1 
percent in 1994 and the smallest increase since the agency began tracking the numbers in 1980. </p>
<p>EARLY REVIEWS ARE IN _ The nation's eyes are on the Executive Council's last meeting in Bal 
Harbour, Fla., with about 20 reporters from around the country on the scene. Frank Swoboda of 
the Washington Post on Sunday quoted John Sweeney as offering two yardsticks for measuring his 
first year as president of the AFL-CIO: the level of &quot;success in the November elections and 
whether we're starting to show membership growth.&quot; In a Feb. 16 New York Times piece by 
Steven Greenhouse, Sweeney scoffed at the notion that representing working people makes 
organized labor a &quot;special interest.&quot; &quot;I don't get upset being referred to as representing a special 
interest,&quot; he said. &quot;If representing American workers is a special interest, then I'm proud to 
represent that special interest.&quot; </p>
<p>WAGES NOT PREVAILING _ More than 12,000 union members converged on the Capitol 
steps in Sacramento, Calif., to protest Republican Gov. Pete Wilson's plans to slash prevailing rates 
for construction workers. Under Wilson's plan, construction workers' salaries stand to drop from 
$28,000 a year to $22,000, &quot;hardly a living wage for a working family,&quot; one speaker said. New 
wage rates are expected by July from a Wilson-appointed Industrial Welfare Commission. </p>
<p>A GOOD SIGNAL _ Workers at Allied Signal's Safety Restraint Systems in Knoxville, Tenn. 
ratified a contract that raises wages 12 percent over three years. The 600 members of UNITE 
Local 1742 preserved health care benefits and added pension and vacation improvements, bringing 
the wage benefit increase to nearly twice the national average, the union said. </p>
<p>WORK WITHOUT RIGHTS _ Workers have gone to the barricades in Oklahoma and Oregon, 
trying to beat back so-called &quot;right-to-work&quot; initiatives. More than 200 people rallied Feb. 5 under 
the aegis of the Working Families Coalition of Oklahoma, with TV, radio and newspaper ads 
running and phone banks, education drives and postcard initiatives planned. In Oregon, the 
National Right to Work Committee is paying volunteers $5 for each signature they gather on a 
petition to put right to work on the November ballot. Similar legislation was carried over from the 
last session in Pennsylvania, and may reappear in California, Colorado, Indiana, Montana and New 
Mexico. </p>
<p>UFW'S VALENTINE'S VINDICATION: An Arizona appeals court on Feb. 14 threw out a $3.7 
million judgment against the Farm Workers in their boycott against lettuce grower Bruce Church 
Inc. The decision &quot;is a triumph for the United Farm Workers and a vindication of Cesar Chavez,&quot; 
said union President Arturo S. Rodriguez of his predecessor, who died in April 1993 after a day of 
giving testimony in the case. Rodriguez thanked the Executive Council for its support, particularly 
the unions that came forward to back the UFW financially. </p>
<p>MORALITY IN DETROIT _ More than 200 clergy in the Detroit area issued a renewed call to 
their neighbors to boycott the Detroit News and the Detroit Free Press, denouncing as immoral 
plans by the publishers to &quot;permanently replace&quot; striking workers. The Executive Council 
welcomed Detroit strikers to exhibit fliers and other material, including the strikers' Sunday Journal, 
which may be ordered via mail. Send a check for $15, or VISA or MasterCard number and 
expiration date, with name, address and telephone number to The Detroit Sunday Journal, 
Attention: Subscriptions, 3100 E. Jefferson, Detroit, Mich. 48207. </p>
<p>FRIENDLY SKIES? _ Flight Attendants have reached a tentative four-year agreement with 
United Airlines that puts a halt to the establishment of international bases, a long contentious issue, 
and caps the growth of existing overseas operations. United's plans for the overseas bases were the 
major reason the union opted out of an employee buyout of the airline in 1993. Mail ballot returns 
on the agreement are due in April. </p>
<p>AFSCME SCORES IN NEW YORK _ Forgoing wage increases for two years in exchange for 
keeping their jobs, some 125,000 members of AFSCME District Council 37 in New York City 
voted 19,513-14,438, or 57 percent, in favor of a new five-year contract. The agreement contains 
strong layoff protection through June 30, 1998, and provisional and part-time city employees are, 
for the first time, protected from layoff. Wages will advance 11.13 percent in the three years after 
the two-year freeze. </p>
<p>&quot;TEAM COMCEPT&quot; ILL-CONCEIVED _ United Parcel Service Inc. has drawn heat for its 
&quot;Team Concept&quot; program, which aims to divide union members, increase workloads and 
undermine basic contractual rights, the Teamsters say. The union is concerned that self-directed 
teams will be pressured to discipline fellow union members and assume other supervisory tasks, all 
the while without regard to seniority or compensation. IBT has demanded that UPS provide 
complete program details and objectives, in the meantime directing local unions not to participate. </p>
<p>BRIDGESTONE LAWBREAKING _ The National Labor Relations Board has accused 
Bridgestone/Firestone of a wide range of unfair labor practices that could cost the company &quot;tens 
of millions of dollars&quot; to correct. The charges claim Bridgestone/Firestone prolonged a strike by the 
Steelworkers and illegally fired striking workers. The NLRB will seek an order requiring the 
company to reinstate all the illegally fired workers along with back pay and benefits. </p>
<p>INTERNATIONAL CONNECTION _ Joaquin (Jack) Otero, former AFL-CIO vice president 
and vice president of the Transportation Communications Union, will be nominated to serve as the 
Department of Labor's assistant secretary for international labor affairs, the White House said. 
Otero, a Cuban native, joined the Clinton administration in 1993 as the deputy undersecretary of 
labor. </p>
<p>DEATHS IN THE FAMILY _ Jim Wood, executive secretary-treasurer of the Los Angeles 
AFL-CIO died of cancer Monday. &quot;He's made a great contribution to the labor movement in 
California,&quot; President Sweeney told the Executive Council. Last week, labor lost Marshall M. 
Hicks, the former president of the Utility Workers, who died of cancer Feb. 12. Hicks, who was 
re-elected to a second term last year, &quot;was a tireless worker . . . always available to take phone 
calls, help with stalled negotiations or arbitration,&quot; said Donald E. Wightman, who took the union's 
reins from Hicks in January, when Hicks retired due to the illness.&quot; </p>
<hr>
<p>For details of these and other stories, check out the News and Views library on LaborNET 
(CompuServe), or <a href="http://www.aflcio.org/">LaborWEB</a>, the AFL-CIO's Web site, located at http://<a href="http://www.aflcio.org/"> www.aflcio.org</a>. To 
receive Work in Progress, or to submit information, FAX to 202/508-6908.</p>
