<html>

<head>
<title>WIP 02/13/96 AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h3 align=center>Work in Progress for Tuesday, Feb. 13, 1996 </h3>
<p>GOOD NEWS ON LEGISLATIVE FRONT . . . A Sunday Washington Post article notes that 
business lobbyists are licking their wounds after having nothing to show for the first session of the 
GOP- dominated 104th Congress. &quot;Basically, these (corporate) people have bitten off too much,&quot; 
AFL-CIO Legislative Director Peggy Taylor is quoted as saying. &quot;The Republicans have 
accomplished almost nothing and we feel we've played an important role in that.&quot; </p>
<p>. . . BUT NUMBERS STILL DOWN -- BLS figures on union membership for 1995 reinforce the 
need for the massive organizing effort planned by the AFL-CIO. Union rolls declined by 388,000 
last year, from 16.7 million to 16.4 million. That means the rate of unionization fell from 15.5 
percent to 14.9 percent of employed wage and salary workers. The rate for private industry was 
10.4 percent, and for government it was 37.8 percent. The union advantage remained strong: 
Unionized workers earned 35 percent more than nonunion workers. </p>
<p>YOU CAN HELP IN DETROIT -- Support the more than 2,000 union members striking the 
Detroit newspapers by subscribing to the Detroit Sunday Journal, a full-scale weekly newspaper 
that is written, edited, produced and distributed by union members. For a three-month subscription, 
send a check for $15 or VISA or MasterCard number and expiration date, along with your name, 
address and telephone number, to: The Detroit Sunday Journal, Attention: Mail Subscriptions, 
3100 E. Jefferson, Detroit, Mich. 48207. </p>
<p>YALE OFFICE, MAINTENANCE WORKERS STICK TOGETHER -- SuperGlue can't begin 
to touch the bonding power of members of the Hotel Employees and Restaurant Employees Locals 
34 and 35 at Yale University. Members of Local 34, representing 2,600 clerical and technical 
workers, began a six-week strike on Feb. 7 over work rules, wages, pay scales and retiree 
benefits. Meanwhile, some 1,100 members of Local 35 remained on the job, bringing in wages to 
support both groups. If a contract agreement is not reached by late March, Local 35 may strike the 
university while members of Local 34 return to work. Contract negotiations for both locals have 
been unsuccessful since November. </p>
<p>DON'T SLEEP WITH THE ENEMY -- Hotel Employees and Restaurant Employees Local 11 
has launched a consumer boycott of New Otani Hotel and Garden in Los Angeles. The hotel 
refuses to negotiate with its workers and has created a &quot;climate of intimidation&quot; among its mostly 
women and immigrant employees that makes a free election nearly impossible, said HERE Local 
11 President Maria Elena Durazo. </p>
<p>OFF THE MARK -- The National Governor's Association weighed in on the congressional budget 
debate last week with a series of bipartisan proposals unacceptable to working families. Most 
egregious is the agreement on Medicaid cuts that weakens guaranteed requirements for eligibility, 
scope of benefits and standards of care. The governors also endorsed a slashed welfare plan that 
would cost jobs and supported eliminating overtime provisions of the Fair Labor Standards Act for 
public employees. Call your U.S. senator and representative to tell them you oppose the governors' 
deals. </p>
<p>HITS KEEP COMING ON NLRB -- The assault by Congressional Republicans on the National 
Labor Relations Board budget &quot;has less to do with balancing the federal budget than with 
preserving the imbalance of power that exists in America and in American workplaces,&quot; AFL-CIO 
Secretary-Treasurer Rich Trumka told a Senate subcommittee Feb. 7. So long as the nation &quot;holds 
out to working men and women the promise of a legal right to organize and bargain collectively&quot; 
through the National Labor Relations Act, then it has an obligation to, provide enough money for 
the NLRB to do its job, he said. . </p>
<p>GOIN' SOUTH -- Before heading to Bal Harbour, Fla., for the Feb. 19-22 Executive Council and 
other union meetings, AFL-CIO President John Sweeney will be interviewed this week by CNN 
and CNBC. Secretary- Treasurer Rich Trumka will be interviewed on a segment of the syndicated 
&quot;America's Talking&quot; TV program, and Executive Vice President Linda Chavez-Thompson will be 
on radio in Chicago's &quot;Liz First Show.&quot; </p>
<p>BRINGING IN FREIGHT -- With the vote by workers at Kentucky and New York terminals of 
Union Pacific's Overnite Transportation Co. to join the Teamsters, more than 1,600 workers at 17 
Overnite terminals now have voted for the union. Overnite is the largest nonunion 
less-than-truckload freight carrier in the nation. The NLRB, which is seeking bargaining orders at 
15 other locations where Overnite broke the law, begins a court hearing in Minneapolis this week 
on more than 100 unfair labor practice complaints against the company. Overnite, meanwhile, has 
given workers two pay raises since the campaign began, but that has not stopped the drive's 
momentum. </p>
<p>NURSES NOT SUPERVISORS -- The NLRB ruled last week that nurses at an Anchorage, 
Alaska, hospital and LPNs at a New York State nursing home are employees, not supervisors. It 
was the first nurse classification ruling by the board since the Supreme Court in 1994 boxed some 
nurses into the supervisor category, and it could pave the way to resolve 70 similar cases now 
before the NLRB. </p>
<p>THIS TEAM DESERVES TO LOSE -- Unions are countering a massive selling job by employers 
for the misnamed TEAM Act, which would &quot;give carte blanche to unscrupulous employers to 
establish phony, company-dominated committees in which management would effectively dictate 
who would speak for the workers,&quot; UAW Legislative Director Alan Reuther told a Senate 
committee Feb. 8. AFL-CIO General Counsel Jonathan Hiatt testified that companies have used 
these types of worker committees to create the form, but not the substance, of joint 
decision-making. The employer groups are trying to win veto-proof support for the bill, which 
President Clinton has vowed to fight. Make your feelings known by calling your senator through the 
AFL-CIO's toll-free number: 1-800/97-AFL-CIO. </p>
<p>CALL FOR HEALTH AND SAFETY -- Union activists can help send the message to Congress 
and the White House that the Occupational Safety and Health Administration must be spared the 
massive budget cuts included in the current continuing resolution. Under the CR, which funds the 
Labor Department and other agencies through March 16, OSHA is operating at a 15.5 percent 
budget cut from 1995 levels, while the Mine Safety and Health Administration's budget has been 
cut by 8 percent. It is especially important to contact -- at 1-800-97-AFL-CIO -- the following 
members of Congress: Reps. Richard A. Gephardt (D-Mo.), David E. Bonior (D-Mich.), Vic 
Fazio (D-Calif.), David R. Obey (D-Wis.) and John E. Porter (R-Ill.); and Sens. Thomas A. 
Daschle (D-S.D.), Wendell H. Ford (D-Ky.), Barbara </p>
<ol>
<li>Mikulski (D-Md.), Tom Harkin (D-Iowa), Robert C. Byrd (D-W.Va.), Mark O. Hatfield 
(R-Ore.) and Arlen Specter (R-Pa.). The White House may be reached by calling 
202/456-1111 or through e-mail, at <a href="http://www.whitehouse.gov">http://www.whitehouse.gov/</a> Action materials for the job 
safety campaign are available in the LaborNET safety and health library or by calling Keith 
Mestrich at 202/637-5210. </li>
</ol>
<p>CORPORATE CITIZENSHIP -- In major policy speeches, Labor Secretary Robert B. Reich and 
Sen. Edward Kennedy (D-Mass) have called for using tax incentives to persuade companies to 
better meet the needs of their workers by sharing profits, improving benefits, preserving jobs and 
increasing training. Kennedy also called for stiff penalties for employers who engage in anti-union 
activity. Reich will continue to push for &quot;corporate citizenship&quot; in media interviews this week, 
including an appearance tonight, on CNN's Larry King Live. </p>
<p>A BREAK FOR WORKING FAMILIES -- Unions can help spread the word about a tax benefit 
for working families with modest incomes, working either full time or part time. Information about 
the Earned Income Tax Credit is available from Alan Bosch in the AFL-CIO Department of 
Community Services at 202/637-5193. Meanwhile, the AFL-CIO is fighting efforts by the 
Republicans in Congress to roll back eligibility of this progressive income tax feature while trying to 
give more tax breaks to the rich and big business. President Clinton vetoed legislation that 
contained cuts in the EITC, calling its protection one of his top priorities. </p>
<p>FLOOD RELIEF $$ FLOWING -- Pennsylvania AFL-CIO President William M. George and 
other labor leaders joined President Clinton, Vice President Al Gore and Secretary of Labor 
Robert Reich in a Feb. 7 press conference to announce a U.S. Department of Labor grant for $7 
million for flood cleanup and to assist nearly 700 workers who lost their jobs due to widespread 
flooding in January. </p>
<p>ROTATING THE RUBBER -- Steelworkers President George Becker has named former Rubber 
Workers Organizational Director John Sellers as executive vice president of the Rubber/Plastics 
Industry Conference, filling a vacancy created by the retirement of Kenneth L. Coss, effective 
March 1. Coss, 60, is the former URW president who helped lead the union to merge with USWA 
in July 1995. </p>
<p>CALL WAITING ON AT&amp;T -- Communications Workers and Electrical Workers have blasted 
AT&amp;T for its persistent refusal to release details of its planned reorganization. The unions promised 
to do &quot;whatever is necessary&quot; to help their 100,000 members weather the massive changes coming 
with the layoff of 40,000 workers and the corporate restructuring that will split AT&amp;T into three 
companies. The unions said they would contact the Securities and Exchange Commission and 
pursue legal actions if necessary to shake loose the information. </p>
<p>NEW TACTICS FOR BIG PROBLEM -- The Wall Street Journal last week profiled new 
AFL-CIO Organizing Director Richard Bensinger under the headline, &quot;Chief AFL-CIO Organizer 
to Try Civil Rights Tactics.&quot; Said Bensinger of the labor movement's massive drive to organize 
workers and improve living standards, &quot;If somebody has another way of rebuilding the middle class 
in this country, please tell me.&quot; </p>
<p>To receive Work in Progress, or to contribute information, please FAX to 202/508-6908.</p>
