<head>
<title>WIP 02/05/96 AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h3 align=center>Work in Progress, Feb. 5, 1996 </h3>
<p>BIG WIN IN NEW YORK -- Some 35,000 striking New York building service workers came in 
from their cold picket-line posts after their month-long perseverance and solidarity resulted in a 
tentative contract between Service Employees Local 32B-32J and city building owners and 
managers. The state and city central labor councils were credited with organizing solidarity activity. 
The breakthrough came just days after New York building trades unions agreed not to cross picket 
lines. Special thanks go to the Operating Engineers and Electrical Workers. </p>
<p>OCAW, AMOCO AGREE -- The Oil, Chemical and Atomic Workers have reached agreement 
with Amoco in what is expected to set a pattern for the current round of negotiations with the oil 
industry, OCAW President Robert E. Wages said. Amoco employs 4,500 workers covered by 
OCAW contracts. The tentative pact, which would increase wages by $1.51 per hour over three 
years, came after the union rejected three offers last week, then extended talks beyond the contract 
expiration date. </p>
<p>OREGON MODEL FOR 1996 -- Working families were crucial for Ron Wyden, who became 
the first Democratic senator from Oregon since 1962. Turnout for the state's 120,000 registered 
union voters appeared to be higher than the overall 65 percent level, contributing significantly to 
Wyden's 17,000-vote margin. &quot;We put together an unparalleled political effort,&quot; said AFL-CIO 
President John Sweeney, who pointed to &quot;a new textbook on politics we're going to write this year, 
as we recruit and train activists to build the core of a powerful new grass-roots movement to 
improve the lives of American working families.&quot; The Executive Council has approved a plan to 
raise $35 million devoted to political training and advertising. </p>
<p>ON TO IOWA! -- With the Iowa caucuses coming up, SecretaryTreasurer Rich Trumka rallied 
the state AFL-CIO COPE convention to fight to return Tom Harkin to the Senate and &quot;return Greg 
Ganske and Jim Nussle to Iowa. . . . Use this challenging election year to rejuvenate the labor 
movement here just as we are rebuilding it at the national level.&quot; </p>
<p>&quot;RIGHT-TO-WORK&quot; FIGHT -- The Oregon campaign also was a model in coalition-building 
with environmentalists, women's and other progressive groups, a critical help in the fight against an 
openshop ballot initiative spawned by the anti-union National Right to Work Committee. Another 
state where labor is seeking to check &quot;right-to-work&quot; forces is Oklahoma, where the state 
federation is holding a rally at the state capitol today to castigate Gov. William Keating (R) for a 
right-to-work call in his State of the State address. </p>
<p>LABORERS ADD 1,027 -- Professional and nonprofessional employees at six Phoenix-area 
Indian Health Service facilities have voted for representation by the Laborers. The Jan. 30 vote -- 
268 for LIUNA, 38 for the incumbent National Federation of Federal Employees and 24 against 
union representation (with 35 ballots challenged -- was delayed because of the government 
shutdown. The Federal Labor Relations Authority said 1,027 were eligible to vote. </p>
<p>PAY EQUITY IN TRADES -- Aggressive enforcement and higher affirmative action goals are key 
to achieving pay equity in the construction industry, according to &quot;Building Equal Opportunity,&quot; a 
report by Chicago Women in the Trades. A survey of six construction sites found that men earn as 
much as 19 times more than women. For copies, contact CWIT, 220 South Ashland Avenue, 
Suite 101, Chicago, Ill. 60607-1805; or call 312/942-1444. </p>
<p>EMPOWERING -- Executive Vice President Linda Chavez-Thompson talked about the role of 
unions in empowering women at an EXPO '96 forum sponsored by the Feminist Majority, noting 
that the women's movement and the labor movement belong together. &quot;One of the best friends of 
American women is the labor movement . . . I'm talking about the millions of women who teach our 
kids, drive our buses, make our clothes, work the assembly lines and take care of us when we're 
sick,&quot; she said. </p>
<p>COMING THIS WEEK -- President Sweeney will address Postal Workers at APWU 
headquarters on Wednesday and travel to New York for a meeting of the city's central body 
Thursday. Secretary-Treasurer Trumka testifies to Congress Tuesday about the impact of NLRB 
budget cuts and travels to San Jose, Calif., Friday for a regional conference of central labor 
councils. Executive Vice President Chavez-Thompson speaks to the National Association of 
Government Labor Officials Monday and goes to Minnesota Friday for an AFSCME leadership 
conference. All three executive officers join other Executive Council members in meeting with 
Labor Secretary Robert B. Reich, who will deliver a major speech on corporate responsibility on 
Tuesday. Sen. Edward M. Kennedy also is scheduled to address the issue of wages on 
Wednesday. </p>
<p>COURT STRIKES OUT -- The AFL-CIO intends to fight the Feb. 2 appeals court decision to 
overturn President Clinton's executive order barring federal contractors that permanently replace 
striking workers. Sweeney said the decision is &quot;simply wrong&quot; because it serves those &quot;employers 
who want to wage war on workers and hurts the rest of us.&quot; </p>
<p>WAR ON WORKERS -- The NLRB estimates that more than 40,000 workers, unions and 
employers across the country were adversely affected by the two government shutdowns. The 
NLRB was forced to reschedule approximately 250 representation elections and 350 hearings in 
representation and unfair labor practice cases. When offices opened Jan. 8, NLRB staff faced 720 
new unfair labor practice charges and 120 representation case petitions that had been filed by mail 
during the shutdown, which began Dec. 18. </p>
<p>BECK RULING DECRIED -- The AFL-CIO will appeal a part of a National Labor Relations 
Board ruling on how unions inform workers of their right to object to paying dues for some 
activities, the board's first ruling on the U.S. Supreme Court's 1988 Communications Workers vs. 
Beck decision. Unions object to a provision requiring them to inform employees they have a right 
not to join the union, since employers aren't required to inform workers of their right to join a union, 
said AFL-CIO General Counsel Jon Hiatt. The NLRB decision does give unions a break in the 
way they calculate the reduced dues and litigation costs. </p>
<p>AGAINST BAD LAWS -- On Wednesday, Teamsters General Counsel Judy Scott will testify on 
behalf of the AFL-CIO against a bill by Rep. Peter Hoekstra (R-Mich.) that would bar workers 
from leafleting in front of retail stores. AFL-CIO General Counsel Jon Hiatt will testify Thursday 
against the so-called TEAM Act, which would legalize company unions. </p>
<p>IN THE DOCK ON THE BAY -- SEIU President Richard W. Cordtz was among 42 
demonstrators arrested Jan. 31 in San Francisco's financial district while protesting the quality of 
patient care at California's Vencor-Hillhaven nursing homes. The union also is running radio ads in 
cities throughout the country where the company operates facilities, calling it a &quot;heartless profit 
machine.&quot; </p>
<p>GRASS-ROOTS GAIN -- Public employee grass-roots lobbying efforts are credited with 
convincing the Fair Labor Standards Act task force of the U.S. Conference of Mayors to oppose 
any efforts to strike public employee overtime requirements from the FLSA. The vote was 6-3. </p>
<p>IBT AIRS TRUCK ROADBLOCK -- The Teamsters are sponsoring national radio ads to 
support rallies and a letter-writing campaign calling on the White House and Congress to make 
permanent a temporary delay of a NAFTA provision that would allow thousands of unsafe 
Mexican trucks to enter U.S. highways. Trucks from Mexico are three times as old on the average, 
up to twice as heavy and don't have to meet the same emissions standards or insurance 
requirements. Drivers also don't have to be trained in handling hazardous materials and aren't 
subject to U.S. rules for drug and alcohol testing or hours on the road. A video and fliers are 
available from the IBT Communications Department at 202/624-6911. </p>
<p>FUN IN ACAPULCO -- Mexico has become the top destination for transferring executives, and 
Chile, which has never been in the top 10 but is now the subject of a proposed NAFTA expansion, 
holds the No. 2 spot. As of Jan. 22, the Labor Department had received petitions for NAFTA 
trade adjustment assistance from 768 firms in 48 states. Certifications have been made in 380 
cases covering more than 53,000 workers, but the actual number of workers dislocated by the 
pact has been estimated to be much higher. </p>
<p>A CHILL ON JOBS -- Unemployment was up sharply (0.2 percent to 5.8 percent) in January as 
severe winter weather in the East helped to siphon off 200,000 jobs, pushing the unemployment 
rate up. Even in December, when the jobless rate remained unchanged at 5.6 percent, the economy 
appeared to be sputtering. &quot;There's just no damn work out there,&quot; said New Jersey AFL-CIO 
President Charles Marciante. </p>
<p>MOVING UP ON D STREET - J. Davitt McAteer, a former safety director at the Mine 
Workers, has been named acting solicitor of the Labor Department. Ida Castro, the deputy 
assistant for workers' compensation, was named acting deputy solicitor. David St. John, who 
previously served as an assistant to former AFL-CIO President Lane Kirkland, has been named 
chief writer for the assistant secretary for policy. </p>
<p>FEARS FOR SAFETY -- Although four leaders of one of Nigeria's oil workers unions were 
released from prison earlier this month, NUPENG's General Secretary, Frank Kokori, remains in 
prison without counsel or communication with the outside. He and other trade unionists were 
arrested for organizing and leading a strike in opposition to the military regime in July and August 
1994. There are growing fears Kokori will be condemned to death by the Nigerian regime, which 
recently executed nine human rights activists. Please send letters of protest to: Honorable Alhaji 
Uba Ahmed, Minister of Labour and Productivity, Federal Government of Nigeria, Ministry of 
Labour, Republic of Nigeria; FAX to 011-234-126-92293 or 011- 234-129-9281. </p>
<p>To receive Work in Progress, or to contribute information, please FAX to 202/508-6908.</p>
