<title>WIP 01/29/96 AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h3 align=center>Work in Progress<br>
Monday, Jan. 29, 1996 </h3>
<p><b>TURNING POINT</b> - In what AFL-CIO President John Sweeney described as &quot;an historic 
turning point,&quot; the Executive Council on Jan. 24 considered a number of sweeping structural and 
program changes at the federation. Summaries of recommendations by five transition work groups 
are available in the Public Statements libary of LaborNET on CompuServe, or by calling 
202/637-5010. </p>
<p>PRIORITY NO. 1: ORGANIZING - The AFL-CIO's top priority is organizing, Sweeney said in 
naming Richard Bensinger, 45, to head a new Organizing Department. Bensinger, who has directed 
the federation's successful Organizing Institute since 1989, is charged with administering a $20 
million organizing fund to help affiliates bring in new union members. The new department also will 
oversee the work of the institute, which will be headed by Allison Porter, 35, who has been deputy 
director of the institute since its founding. </p>
<p>TURN, TURN, TURN _ Among key recommendations already in the works are a new Center for 
Strategic Campaigns, which will help unions apply economic leverage in organizing drives, 
bargaining campaigns and strikes, as well as a Worker Ownership and Governance Institute to 
assist unions with employee buyouts, corporate restructuring schemes and pension fund investment. 
The federation's communications structure will be reorganized into four divisions, beefing up our 
ability to speak out for working families. </p>
<p>POLITICAL MIRACLE? _ Secretary-Treasurer Rich Trumka traveled to Oregon Friday to help 
with the 11th hour push to get union members to turn in their mail ballots for Rep. Ron Wyden (D). 
Results in this uphill race will be known late tomorrow. Labor's efforts in Oregon are 
unprecedented, said Political Director Steve Rosenthal, who unveiled to the council a plan for the 
AFL-CIO to invest $35 million into campaigning this year and to organize a cadre of 100 
permanent activists in each congressional district. </p>
<p>PRESSING THE NEWS _ Five major auto dealers have pulled their ads from Detroit's scab 
newspapers, bringing to more than 90 the number of dealers that have dropped out and to more 
than 800 the total number of advertisers that deserted the papers. Meanwhile, the NLRB added 
five more unfair labor practices charges against the papers. On Monday, Jan. 29, the AFL-CIO 
amended its anti-trust complaint against the newspapers, asking the Justice Department to disallow 
a proposed shutdown of the Riverside printing plant. The strikers' newspaper, The Sunday Journal, 
is looking for a few good advertisers. Contact William Brown, publisher, 3100 East Jefferson, 
Detroit MI 48207; Phone: 313/567-9818. </p>
<p>COMMITTEE CHAIRS _ Sweeney announced the appointment of new committee chairs in four 
key areas addressed by the transition work groups: Laborers' President Arthur Coia, to head the 
Organizing Committee; AFSCME President Gerry McEntee, leading the Political Education 
Committee; Food and Commercial Workers President Doug Dority, to direct the Public Affairs 
Committee; and AFT President Al Shanker, to head the Education Committee. </p>
<p>HIGH MARKS FOR CLINTON _ President Clinton received praise from union officers for his 
State of the Union address last Tuesday. The UFCW's Dority said the president was &quot;keeping the 
American Dream alive for average Americans.&quot; Sweeney said that &quot;after 20 years of stagnant 
wages in this country, it was good to see a president who will fight to make sure that hard work still 
pays. We particularly welcome his commitment to raise the minimum wage, to protect pension 
security and health care. </p>
<p>BACK TO GRASS ROOTS _ The council approved a statement to implement a constitutional 
amendment providing for regional representation of state federations on the General Board, which 
will meet sometime in March to consider an endorsement for president and vice president. 
Individual representatives from the four regions must be selected by Feb. 15, with their terms 
running for two years. </p>
<p>TOWN HALL MEETING _ Just prior to a vote that averted a third government shutdown, 10 
members of Congress participated Jan. 25 in a forum with more than 400 Government Employees 
and AFSCME members on Capitol Hill. The representatives, all from the Washington metropolitan 
area, denounced the actions of Congress and called for a picket around the Capitol if the 
government is shut down again. The forum included two Republicans, Reps. Thomas M. Davis 
(Va.) and Constance A. Morella (Md.), who later cast their votes for a continuing resolution to 
keep the government running. That resolution, however, forces many agencies to sharply cut back 
services and may force layoffs. </p>
<p>OSHA, WE'D HARDLY KNOW YA _ Congressional Republicans will be setting strategy over 
the next several weeks for legislation to emasculate OSHA, MSHA and NIOSH, as well as 
_reform&quot; the regulatory process. Labor and its allies also are holding strategy sessions to seize the 
rhetoric and the campaign over regulatory reform. This week, 50 editorial boards across 
Pennsylvania will be receiving material on Rep. Cass Ballenger's OSHA-gutting measure, with such 
mailings planned in other states. Follow-up letters sent locally are encouraged. For information, call 
Keith Mestrich at 202/637- 5210. </p>
<p>UNION REPRESENTATION PAYS _ The Postal Workers won an estimated $63 million in 
back pay for 25,000 transitional employees when an NLRB arbitrator ruled that the U.S. Postal 
Service violated the union contract and federal law. Under the Jan. 9 ruling, the transitional 
employees are entitled to be paid $1.26 per hour for every hour worked since the first full pay 
period in February 1995. </p>
<p>WRITE FOR RIGHTS _ The AFL-CIO is urging unionists to write letters calling for the release of 
Roliati Harefa, vice chair of Indonesia's independent SBSI union. Harefa was fired without 
explanation from her job at a wood factory, twice beaten by company management, and then jailed 
when she reported the second beating. Amnesty International expects that Harefa, like other 
imprisoned trade union activists, will suffer ill-treatment in prison. Letters of protest may be sent to 
H.E. Dr. Abdul Latief, Minister of Manpower; J. Gen. Gatto Subroto; Jakarta Pusat; Jakarta, 
Indonesia. Or FAX to 62 21 840-2746. </p>
<p>SMART STRATEGY _ The $7 million spent by the Communications Workers on a five-month 
corporate campaign, ending in a good contract with Bell Atlantic, is the same amount the union 
would have spent for just one week of strike benefits, CWA President Morton Bahr told the 
Executive Council. The campaign included shareholder and customer outreach, as well as a TV 
advertising campaign that put the company on the spot. If CWA had paid the same benefits to 
workers in the 1989 strike against Nynex, it would have cost close to $170 million, the union said. </p>
<p>UNITE AD CAMPAIGN _ The Union of Needletrades, Industrial and Textile Employees today 
launches its first national advertising campaign. &quot;The Face of Change&quot; is intended to increase 
familiarity with the new 300,000-member union and to position it as a force for social and political 
action. Ads will run on CNN and on major TV networks in New York, Washington and Atlanta. </p>
<p>STRIKING BUILDINGS _ Some 35,000 New York building service workers remain on strike 
after talks broke off with owners of the posh high-rises. Gus Bevona, president of Service 
Employees Local 32B-32J, said the employers' demand for a two-tier wage system is a &quot;prelude to 
replacing long-term office cleaners and other workers with low-paid strangers.&quot; </p>
<p>STAGE SET FOR TALKS _ Actors' Equity has begun negotiations with 64 theaters in major 
cities and states to replace an agreement that expires Feb. 25. Some 7,000 actors are involved, 
working at the regional and repertory theaters in 29 states, including the Lincoln Center Theatre in 
New York and the Goodman Theatre in Chicago. </p>
<p>RALLY FOR HEALTH CARE QUALITY _ Members of the Service Employees Local 250 and 
supporters in the San Francisco area take to the streets this week in the fight for quality patient care 
at Vencor-Hillhaven nursing homes. More than 1,000 workers throughout 25 Vencor-Hillhaven 
homes have worked for a year without a contract. </p>
<p>GOOD NEWS AT NLRB _ The White House announced that former union attorney Sarah M. 
Fox will serve as a recess appointee to the National Labor Relations Board. Fox, who previously 
served as chief counsel to the Senate Labor and Human Resources Committee, will be able to 
keep a seat on the five-member board through the fall of 1997. She served as general counsel to 
the Bricklayers from 1982 to 1990. </p>
<p>For details of these and other stories, check out the AFL-CIO News in LaborNET's Public 
Statements Library on CompuServe, or on the Internet World Wide Web at http:\www.aflcio.org. 
To send information for possible inclusion, send your FAX to 202/508-6908.</p>
