<head>
<title>WIP 01/23/96 AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<h3 align="center">AFL-CIO WORK IN PROGRESS January 23, 1996 </h3>
<p><em>THE FIRST BULLETIN</em> -- In an effort to communicate
more quickly and effectively with union leaders, supporters and
activists across the country, the AFL-CIO today begins
distribution of a weekly FAX bulletin, which also goes to the
media and a variety of outside audiences. Work in Progress will
arrive at your office the first of every week. For further
information, or to send information for inclusion, please send
FAX to 202/508-6908. </p>
<p><em>COUNCIL NOW, GENERAL BOARD LATER</em> -- The new AFL-CIO
Executive Council meets Wednesday, Jan. 24, at the Sheraton
Washington hotel for its first full session since the 1995
convention. Meanwhile, meetings of the General Board and state
federations on the 1996 elections have been delayed because of
scheduling conflicts -- probably until mid-March. At a 12:15 p.m.
press briefing at the break of the council meeting, President
John Sweeney will discuss proposed changes in AFL- CIO programs. </p>
<p><em>THEY'RE BACK, AFTER TAKING FLAK</em> -- Congress returns
this week after many in the Gingrich camp were lambasted with
another wave of advertising and grass-roots activity sponsored by
the AFL-CIO and its affiliates. TV and radio ads, which ran in 25
major cities and nationally, n Republican leaders for using a
government shutdown in an effort to blackmail President Clinton
into accepting their dangerous budget plan. The message: No cuts
in Medicare, Medicaid, education and worker protections to pay
for big tax breaks for the rich and big business. </p>
<p><em>UNIONS STATE CASE</em> -- State and local AFL-CIO
officials have been asked to offer the perspective of working
families to local reporters after President Clinton's State of
the Union address Tuesday evening. &quot;While the White House
and congressional press corps will focus on `inside' reactions
from Washington, the media in the rest of the country should be
much more open to doing stories about public reactions to
Clinton's message,&quot; Sweeney wrote. </p>
<p><em>BIG WIN FOR CWA</em> -- The Communications Workers
announced a tentative agreement with Bell Atlantic after five
months of contentious bargaining. The company had resisted
matching contracts offered by other regional Bell operating
companies, but relented in the face of CWA's massive membership
mobilization and a $7 million corporate campaign that included a
memorable TV ad featuring a bumbling subcontracted repairman
named Larry. CWA President Morton Bahr, meanwhile, denounced
AT&amp;T's plans to lay off 40,000 workers. &quot;This is yet
another case of the kind of mindless job destruction that has
terrorized working Americans in recent years as corporate
executives play to Wall Street,&quot; he said. </p>
<p><em>THE BOSS: UNIONS ARE THE BEST</em> -- Rock superstar Bruce
Springsteen, at a concert in Detroit, donated proceeds from
souvenir sales and matched that amount with a contribution of his
own to striking workers at the Detroit News and Free Press.
Advertisers continue to desert the sinking Detroit papers, owned
by Gannett and Knight-Ridder. Top officials of those companies
sold about $3 million worth of company stock shortly before
admitting to Wall Street that they had severely underestimated
some $250 million in strike losses, reported the strikers' own
newspaper, the Detroit Sunday Journal. </p>
<p><em>RIGHTS TO ACTION</em> -- Executive Vice President Linda
Chavez-Thompson and Secretary-Treasurer Rich Trumka were in
Atlanta last week marching with the King family on the Martin
Luther King Jr. holiday. Honored at the annual King
labor-management breakfast were AFL-CIO President John Sweeney,
UNITE President Jay Mazur and Laborers President Arthur Coia.
Chavez-Thompson later joined Georgia Rep. Cynthia McKinney and
labor's environmental and civil rights allies in a rally against
the exploitative kaolin industry, and spoke at an Industrial
Union Department regional conference on organizing. She finished
the week in Oregon traveling with Rep. Ron Wyden, who is labor's
choice to replace Sen. Bob Packwood (R). The mail balloting ends
there Jan. 30. </p>
<p><em>LOOKING AHEAD</em> -- Trumka travels to Boston Monday for
an address to the Harvard Trade Union Program class and to Lynn,
Mass., to speak to the North Shore AFL-CIO. Sweeney, who joined
the Operating Engineers for their 100th anniversary celebration
in Orlando last week, on Tuesday will address the domestic policy
committee of the U.S. Catholic Conference in Washington. </p>
<p><em>WHAT ABOUT WORKER SAFETY?</em> -- The business lobby will
not get away with their campaign to stop OSHA from creating an
ergonomics standard, Sweeney has declared. An
&quot;analysis&quot; by a coalition led by trucking and
manufacturing industries &quot;is the latest effort in its
ongoing campaign to use power, money and distortions to keep the
government from protecting workers from crippling repetitive
strain injuries and illnesses,&quot; Sweeney said. &quot;This is
not about science. It's about industry trying to rid itself of
all regulations and gut job safety protections. </p>
<p><em>UNIONS UP TO TASK</em> -- Secretary-Treasurer Trumka, in a
front-page story in the Jan. 22 Wall Street Journal, warned that
if corporations &quot;fail to share more of their windfall
profits with workers, they do so at their peril.&quot; The
article, previewing upcoming negotiations with the oil and
airline industries, notes that the new leadership of the AFL-CIO
hopes to turn the growing anger of ordinary workers into
victories at the bargaining table. </p>
<p><em>NEW PRESIDENTS</em> -- The Utility Workers and Police
Associations got new presidents last week. Donald Wightman of
Boston was elected by UWUA to fill the unexpired term of Marshall
Hicks, who retired due to illness. Sam Cabral moved up to
president from secretary-treasurer of the IUPA after Robert
Kliesmet was appointed sheriff of Milwaukee County, a management
position. </p>
<p><em>PBS PROFILES A. PHILIP RANDOLPH</em> -- Public television
will celebrate Black History Month with &quot;A. Philip Randolph:
For Jobs and Freedom,&quot; a 90-minute film documentary produced
by WETA, Feb. 2 at 9 p.m. on PBS stations nationwide. Randolph,
an AFL-CIO vice president and founder of the Brotherhood of
Sleeping Car Porters, led the fight against legal discrimination
in government and the military and helped to organize the 1963
March on Washington. </p>
<p>For details of these and other stories, check out the AFL-CIO
News in LaborNET's Public Statements Library on CompuServe, or on
the Internet World Wide Web at <a href="http://www.aflcio.org">http://www.aflcio.org</a>.</p>
