<html>
<head>
<title>SP 02/07/97 Remarks by John J. Sweeney President of the
AFL-CIO</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<p align="center">Remarks by John J. Sweeney President of the
AFL-CIO<br>
The Commonwealth Club San Francisco February 7, 1997</p>
<p>Thank you for that kind introduction and your warm welcome --
and also thank you for the warm weather and the chance to escape
the mean streets of Washington, DC. And when I say &quot;mean
streets,&quot; I'm not talking about those broad boulevards
outside the United States Capitol where drugs are bought and sold
by night. No, I'm talking about those narrow corridors inside the
Capitol, where the American Dream is bought and sold by day, and
where the working families of America have been getting mugged
for the past two years by a gang of thugs masquerading as members
of the United States Congress. </p>
<p>Well, that's all changed now and we're putting a stop to all
the bad stuff. And it's not because the AFL-CIO did such a great
job in the elections last fall, although we certainly took more
ground than we took fire. And it's not because the Speaker of the
House was reprimanded by the House ethics committee and fined
$300,000, although he certainly deserved it. </p>
<p>No, it's because last Tuesday night, the President of the
United States delivered one of the finest &quot;State of the
Union&quot; addresses in the history of our country, and because
the State of California did its part in assuring the President of
the largest television audience in peacetime history. </p>
<p>I was watching CBS cover the speech live and I have to
confess, I was furious when they cut into his final summation
with the results of the O.J. Simpson trial. But I knew something
extraordinary had happened when I asked my son John the next
morning why he had taken my car the night before without
permission and he replied: &quot;We must be shapers of events,
not observers, for if we do not act, the moment will pass and we
will lose the best possibilities of our future.&quot; </p>
<p>So the President got his message through to a new and bigger
audience and I'm sure that members of the 105th Congress are now
scrambling to get on that train that is going to take us all
across that bridge into the 21st Century, which, as the President
pointed out, is just 1,000 days away. </p>
<p>And because time is running out and we're getting closer and
closer, I hope you'll allow me to skip over all the things the
President said he's going to do to stoke the engine and keep the
train running and keep the construction of the bridge on time and
on budget -- which I'm sure is going to happen if he's using
union labor and paying Davis-Bacon wages. What I want to talk
about are the dangers we face -- not the things we could do
right, but three things we could do wrong, three ways we could
&quot;lose the best possibilities of our future.&quot; We could
pass the balanced budget amendment and privatize Social Security
and derail the train, sending it all the way back to the turning
of the 20th century. Or we could fail to narrow the wage and
wealth gap and watch it swallow up the bridge altogether. All
three are more than just bad for workers and their families --
they are bad public policy, bad economics, bad financial
management, bad business and bad for business. </p>
<p>The balanced budget amendment has for many years been a
favorite war drum for the new right, the far right and the not-
quite-so-right. &quot;You have to manage our country's budget the
way you manage your family budget. You have to run the country
like you run a business.&quot; </p>
<p>Robert Eisner did a good job of exposing their gibberish a few
weks ago in the Wall Street Journal and all of you in this room
understood what he wrote. Run our government like a business?
Then what is a current expense, how fast do you depreciate, what
do you amortize, how do you price inventories, when do you put in
special charges, how do you handle pension funds? Should Social
Security be off budget? Shouldn't our government have a separate
capital budget if we're going to run it like a business? Manage
our country like we manage our family budgets? Where would we all
be without borrowing to finance our homes, to send our kids to
college, to buy durable goods? Businesses borrow, and even state
and local governments have separate capital accounts. </p>
<p>The truth is that if you applied the balanced budget amendment
to a business, you would be out of business. And if we did the
same to our family budgets, half of us would be living in tents.
Secretary of the Treasury Robert Rubin is against the balanced
budget amendment: he knows it would create more layers of
government regulation and whack state and local governments every
other year. Federal Reserve Chair Alan Greenspan is against the
balanced budget amendment: he knows that as soon as we hit a
little recession Congress would run it into a big depression by
raising taxes or cutting spending or both. 1,000 leading
economists, including 11 Nobel prize winners, are against the
balanced budget because, among other things, it just isn't
needed. And John Sweeney is against the balanced budget
amendment: I know, just like you know, that it is a reckless,
indefensible ploy to cut the services and programs and
protections working families depend upon most. </p>
<p>How about you? Which side are you on? I don't mean on the
question of downsizing government -- feel free to take your best
shot on that. I mean on the question of putting our country in an
economic straight-jacket that would prevent federal borrowing to
finance any sort of infrastructure, much less a bridge to a new
century. No, I'm not going to take a show of hands. I don't have
to, because I know most of you are businessmen, not ideologues
and you know what's right when it comes to the balanced budget
amendment. </p>
<p>Now let's look at a second way we can kill the goose that has
laid so many golden eggs for so many of the people in this room,
another way to screw around recklessly with an economy that is
providing a greater standard of living for a greater percent of
our population than at any time in our history: let's privatize
Social Security. </p>
<p>Situation: for 60 years, our Old Age, Survivors and Disability
Insurance system helps build a national community where our
citizens pull together to help everybody, instead of a society
where I look out for myself and the rest be damned. It lifts four
generations of senior citizens out of poverty, allows them to
live in dignity and not have to depend on their ungrateful
children. A few bumps along the way, but we fix them. Unlike many
government programs, it is incredibly efficient, with an
administrative cost of only seven-tenths of one percent. Never
contributes to the national debt. Enjoys the support of 90
percent of the American people. </p>
<p>Problem: the program gets out of whack. It will only provide
full benefits for everyone through 2030, only 75 percent after
that, because the Baby Boomers will be well into their
retirements. You could fix the entire problem with a 2.17 percent
increase in the FICA contribution, but nobody in Congress, and
certainly nobody in California wants a tax increase. </p>
<p>Here's the solution a majority of members of the Social
Security Advisory Council came up with last month: cut benefits
30 percent, increase the payroll tax 26 percent, give individuals
back two to five percent of the contribution and force them to
play our national lottery. If they find a good investment
counselor, and if they buy the right stocks, they come out with
bigger pensions. If they aren't so lucky, they end up in the
county poorhouses, which, of course, we closed down shortly after
we passed Social Security 60 years ago. </p>
<p>Did I run through those numbers too fast? Did you hear the
kicker up there? A 30 percent cut in benefits and a 26 percent
increase in the payroll tax? That's 1.6 percent more under one
plan, 1.5 percent under another, one for 72 years, the other
forever. For a nation that won't tolerate a tax increase! To pay,
in the first 12 years alone, $240 billion in fees and commissions
on more than $4 trillion dollars into the market! </p>
<p>But what about the Chilean model? It works, doesn't it? Sure
it does: the workers pay 20 percent for old age, disability and
survivors insurance and health care, while employers pay nothing.
The for-profit businesses which run the program get a three
percent administrative fee, their investors earn a 22 percent
annual profit, and 70 percent of the workers have less than
$2,500 in their retirement accounts. </p>
<p>Now I really am tempted to ask for a show of hands and ask
everyone in this room how smart it is to invest our future in a
Bull market being fueled by the savings of Baby Boomers who in 30
years, just when we need the money most, are going to be pulling
all that dough out of the market. But I'm not going to ask
because I know what you think. Whether you're conservative or
liberal or neither one, you are sons and daughters and you have
mothers and fathers and children of your own and you know what's
right. </p>
<p>So let's look at a third issue, something that is already
draining away our economic vitality and threatening to send our
children and our grandchildren to the poorhouse right along with
our mothers and fathers. We call it the wage and wealth gap. </p>
<p>For almost 30 years after winning World War II, we all
prospered because we prospered together. We were concerned with
raising the standard of living for all Americans -- not just
accumulating money for a fortunate few. Our social compact was a
formula for the strongest economy, the largest middle class, and
the most successful society this world has ever known. </p>
<p>Those days began to come to an end in the early 1970s when
corporate America made a fateful decision to compete in the new
global economy, not through team-work and know-how, but by
driving down labor costs. Rather than compete on the basis of
quality and expand the markets for their goods and services,
corporations chose to increase their profit margins by moving
plants into low-wage markets and by outsourcing and shipping jobs
overseas. Even employers with proud histories of doing right by
their workers joined the rush to speed up work, freeze wages,
slash health benefits and eliminate pensions. </p>
<p>As a result, the rich got richer, while America_s working
families got left behind. Over the last 20 years, real earnings
declined, average family income stagnated and purchasing power
eroded, leaving the U.S. with the most uneven distribution of
wealth of any major industrialized nation. By 1992, the top 20
percent controlled 80 percent of the wealth! </p>
<p>Meanwhile, the wealthiest Americans are doing better than
ever. Between 1980 and 1995, the Dow Jones Industrial Average
rose 404 percent. That provided huge payoffs for investors -- but
no wage gains for workers. Corporate profits have risen 165
percent since 1980. Corporate chief executive officers are raking
in 499 percent more -- and now they earn 145 times more than the
average factory worker. And that's in spite of the fact that
workers' productivity has risen 24 percent since 1979 -- while
their real wages fell! And now, instead of merely depressing
wages, profitable corporations are wiping out jobs in a frenzy to
jack up their stock prices by taking short-term profits instead
of long-term profitability. </p>
<p>American families tried all kinds of coping mechanisms. They
sent husbands, wives, and teen-age kids into the labor force.
They took second and third jobs. Despite their efforts, median
family income fell five percent between 1989 and 1994. </p>
<p>For American workers and their families, these statistics
paint an ugly portrait of a country that has lost respect for
workers and the jobs they do. American workers are running out of
money, running out of options and running out of hope. They've
exhausted their savings, and they are loaded with debt. They have
little time off from work to spend with their children or their
friends, and they can't afford little things like eating out once
a week, much less a real vacation. They see 20 percent of our
society paying $3.00 for cups of coffee and driving $40,000
automobiles and they wonder, &quot;Who's getting my share?&quot;
They are frustrated and bitter, and their anger is exceeded only
by anxiety over keeping their jobs. </p>
<p>The human toll has been staggering. But in case you are not a
bleeding-heart liberal let me throw up another caution flag: I'm
convinced that at some point our nation will face even harsher
consequences from the reckless pursuit of lower and lower wages
by American business. People who don't have money can't spend
money, and that can be disastrous for an economy historically
driven by optimism and consumer purchases. People who make less
money pay less taxes, and 20 years of depressed wages are taking
a toll on local, state and federal tax coffers and undermining
our Social Security system. Finally, people who have no money
can't save money and our savings rate is already flagging. </p>
<p>Bob Reich, our retiring Secretary of Labor, acknowledged the
wage and wealth gap on behalf of the Clinton administration in
his final speech in office when he said, &quot;Incomes have
become less unequal partly because more people are employed and
they are working more hours and because elderly retirees are
doing better. But earnings inequality among adult wage earners
has continued to widen, right up to the third quarter of 1996,
the latest data we have.&quot; Erskine Bowles, the president's
new chief of staff and a conservative businessman, said of second
term priorities the other day: &quot;We simply have to do
something about that darned wage stagnation that has been
bedeviling the economy.&quot; </p>
<p>Now I am really tempted to take a show of hands. But I'm not
going to take a show of hands because every one of you in this
room knows the basics of macroeconomics better than I do and you
know what's right. </p>
<p>The balanced budget amendment. Privatizing Social Security.
The wage and wealth gap. They make up a devil's brew for our
economy and for our country. But what about you and me? We're in
that upper 20 percent, we're in that upper 10 percent, so what do
we have to worry about? </p>
<p>Let me remind you that, no matter what the new paradigm
suggests, we are still in this together. On a personal level,
many of you in this room between the ages of 35 and 55 belong to
what I call the &quot;club sandwich&quot; generation. </p>
<p>Here's how it works. We privatize Social Security and our
parents come home to live with us. We fail to close the wage and
wealth gap and our children come home to live with us. We pass
the balanced budget amendment and our ignorance comes home to
live with us. </p>
<p>How can we prevent it from happening? As leaders from business
and leaders from labor, we have our legitimate differences, but
we also have a mututal responsibility to work together on issues
like this that transcend all other considerations. Together, we
can find ways to protect and preserve Medicare and Social
Security. Together, we can balance the legitimate demand for
government services and protections against our national
willingness to pay for them. Together, we can create a new high
wage economy, make healthcare and education affordable and
accessible to all and create new respect for workers and the jobs
they do. </p>
<p>Together, we can insist on reason and sanity in our
legislative bodies, so we can get on with the business of making
this a country dedicated to raising the standard of living for
everyone, instead of just building up wealth for a few, a country
where you don't have to hold down three jobs to raise your
family, a country where what you do, rather than who you are,
gets you where you want to go. </p>
<p>Thank you very much .... </p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../index.htm">Public Documents Page</a> | <a
href="../publsear.htm">Public Documents Search</a></p>
