<html>
<head>
<title>SP 11/21/96 Trumka at the Labor ant the Global Economy
Conference</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<p align="center">Remarks by Richard Trumka<br>
Secretary-Treasurer of the AFL-CIO<br>
Labor and the Global Economy Conference<br>
Berkeley, California<br>
November 21, 1996</p>
<p>Thank you for that kind introduction and that warm welcome.<br>
And thank you for inviting me to be keynote speaker for this<br>
ambitious and important conference. &quot;Labor and the Global<br>
Economy&quot; not only describes the agenda for this conference,
it is<br>
the agenda for the AFL-CIO as we attempt to rebuild and<br>
revitalize our movement.<br>
<br>
But before I talk about the global economy, I want to revel<br>
in some good news from one very important small part of the world<br>
and that's Orange County, California. Now this is one of the most<br>
right-wing counties in our country, the home of &quot;tax cut
fever&quot;<br>
and the &quot;Reagan Revolution.&quot; When we got the news back
in<br>
Washington that Loretta Sanchez was going to the House of<br>
Representatives, it put a fitting cap on the most successful<br>
political season we have had in decades. And I want to say, on<br>
behalf of President John Sweeney and Executive Vice President<br>
Linda Chavez-Thompson, &quot;Thank you for sending Bob Dornan to
the<br>
shower he so badly needed!&quot;<br>
<br>
In fact, I'd like to thank the labor movement throughout the<br>
state of California for the great job you did. Nationally, we<br>
took out 17 of the ugliest Americans ever to serve in the United<br>
States Congress and we missed 12 additional targets by a total, I<br>
said a total of 14,000 votes. On election day, union households<br>
accounted for 23 percent of the overall vote, up from 14 percent<br>
in 1994 and 19 percent in 1992. Those 21 million voters were the<br>
key in many Congressional races, where 68 percent of union<br>
members voted for Democrats and 32 percent for Republicans --<br>
down from 40 percent in 1992.<br>
<br>
But here in California, you went beyond that performance by<br>
mobilizing 12,000 union volunteers, contacting 300,000 voters in<br>
key districts, winning three hard-fought Congressional races,<br>
passing a living wage and taking back a state assembly that had<br>
become a &quot;skunk works&quot; for the kind of crap Newt
Gingrich has<br>
been trying to peddle on the national level. They say good<br>
things, as well as bad things, always start in California and<br>
blow east and I'd like to thank Art Pulaski and the California<br>
labor movement for creating a Santa Ana we're glad is blowing our<br>
way!<br>
<br>
My brothers and sisters, we all know that unrestricted<br>
global trade -- just like any other unregulated market place --<br>
inevitably drives down living standards and denies basic human<br>
rights. But I don't think any of us ever imagined that we would<br>
reach the point we have reached today where workers who have<br>
built the strongest and most competitive economy in the world<br>
find ourselves chained by the simple-minded notions that free<br>
markets are fair and that the government that governs least,<br>
governs best.<br>
<br>
<br>
In our high-tech global economy, investment can travel<br>
around the world in a micro-second with a keystroke on a<br>
computer. But working people are bound to their communities and<br>
their countries by ties of family, loyalty and necessity. This<br>
means multinational corporations can circle the globe in search<br>
of cheap labor, settling like vultures on the most vulnerable<br>
targets they spot.<br>
<br>
Working people from every country find themselves in what<br>
has been called &quot;the global hiring hall.&quot; They are
forced to<br>
compete with men and women and children throughout the world who<br>
are forced by poverty or tyranny to work for longer hours at<br>
lower rates with fewer rights. The result is a race to the bottom<br>
and working people in every country are the losers.<br>
<br>
The only winners are multinational corporations that pledge<br>
allegiance to no flag but their profit statement. They move<br>
factories, jobs and investment capital at a moment's notice to<br>
escape national laws, collective bargaining agreements and simple<br>
standards of human decency.<br>
<br>
These corporations are unlike ordinary companies: every<br>
element of an ordinary enterprise -- employees, equipment and<br>
human values -- has been hollowed out, leaving little but an<br>
insatiable appetite for profit. A corporation headquartered in<br>
the United States can sell its products here and rack up billions<br>
in profits, without owning a single factory in this country. In<br>
fact, it doesn't have to own a single factory anywhere. Instead,<br>
by contracting and sub-contracting to factories in low-wage<br>
nations such as Taiwan, South Korea, Malaysia and China, it<br>
avoids any of the traditional responsibilities of an employer.<br>
<br>
Let me tell you what this unrestricted access to the &quot;global<br>
marketplace&quot; has meant for American workers over the past 20<br>
years. From 1979 through 1995, more than 43 million jobs were<br>
eliminated in corporate downsizings -- mass firings by giant<br>
corporations that are supposed to be models of corporate<br>
responsibility. General Motors, IBM, AT&amp;T, Boeing, Chemical
and<br>
Chase Manhattan Banks. And two-thirds of the workers fired ended<br>
up at jobs that pay less than their old ones.<br>
<br>
And we took another hit last week: 12,000 workers in the<br>
street at Sunbeam, courtesy of Albert &quot;Chain Saw&quot;
Dunlap, the man<br>
who claims to be a &quot;doctor fixit&quot; for sick
corporations, but who,<br>
in reality, is the Dr. Kevorkian of a sick American business<br>
community.<br>
<br>
Average hourly wages have fallen -- in 1995 dollars -- from<br>
$12.85 in 1978 to $11.64 in 1995. In order to stay even, working<br>
men and women are working longer hours, taking second jobs,<br>
spending less time with their families, their children, their<br>
churches and schools and PTA's and the result is a profound sense<br>
that the fabric of American life is being torn apart at the<br>
seams. Fringe benefits are also being driven down. From 1987 to<br>
1994, a million people a year lost their health coverage. The<br>
percentage of workers covered by employer-paid pension plans<br>
dropped from 63 to 56 percent.<br>
<br>
During this same period of time, however, worker<br>
productivity in our country increased 24 percent -- 24 percent!<br>
Where did it go? It fattened corporate profits -- up 205 percent<br>
between 1980 and 1985. It fattened executive salaries -- they<br>
went up 500 percent since 1980.<br>
<br>
The result? The biggest economic inequality of any advanced<br>
industrial society in the entire world. Worse than Germany. Worse<br>
than Japan. Worse than Italy and France and the United Kingdom<br>
and Australia.<br>
<br>
Our wage and wealth gap is growing by the day. Working<br>
families have little money to spend and they are loaded down with<br>
debt. They are threatened by restructuring, downsizing, pension<br>
raids, privatizing and outsourcing schemes and runaway plants and<br>
their anger is exceeded only by anxiety over keeping their jobs.<br>
They see the rich getting richer and they are disgusted with<br>
business and with government.<br>
<br>
You don't have to be an economist to know this is a<br>
prescription for social and economic disaster -- when workers<br>
can't secure economic justice through reasonable means, they<br>
either take unreasonable actions on their own, or they fall prey<br>
to right-wing demagogues like Patrick Buchanan and David Duke, or<br>
nutty corporate stooges like Ross Perot and Steve Forbes.<br>
<br>
With working-class Americans and their families hurting as<br>
never before, the labor movement has to respond as never before.<br>
We have to fill the vacuum in national leadership because we are<br>
the only legitimate representatives of those working families.<br>
The problem: America needs a raise -- in wages and benefits and<br>
pensions and security, but also in spirit, and ethics and morals.<br>
The solution: a bigger, stronger labor movement, one that can<br>
restore some sanity to a society that has lost all respect for<br>
workers and the jobs they do. That's why John and Linda and I ran<br>
for the highest offices in the AFL-CIO, that is why we won, and<br>
that is why we are shaking up the AFL-CIO in Washington, DC and<br>
in every state in this country.<br>
<br>
With the help of all our unions and state feds and central<br>
labor councils, we're making the changes that are needed to help<br>
us achieve our goals of organizing more workers, building a<br>
national political force for working families, and providing a<br>
new voice for workers in the global economy as well as in our<br>
local communities.<br>
<br>
We started off by creating the first organizing department<br>
in the history of the AFL-CIO, with a commitment to spend $20<br>
million on organizing during our first two years -- 10 times what<br>
has been spent in the past. We tripled the size of our highly-<br>
successful Organizing Institute, which recruits young workers and<br>
college graduates and trains them for careers in union<br>
organizing. In March of this year, we held the first special<br>
convention in our history and voted a $25 million assessment to<br>
help finance a media and grassroots lobbying effort to defeat the<br>
&quot;Contract With America&quot; and to expose the politicians
behind it.<br>
<br>
In May and June, we hosted a series of 30 town hall meetings<br>
around the country under the banner of &quot;America Needs a
Raise,&quot;<br>
taking testimony from union workers and non-union workers alike<br>
and publicizing the meetings to begin building a new base of<br>
public support for workers and their families. During June, July<br>
and August, we sponsored a watershed program called &quot;Union<br>
Summer,&quot; which we envisioned putting 1,000 young workers and<br>
college students through an experience like &quot;Freedom
Summer&quot; in<br>
the 1960s. We got nearly 4,000 applications and had to expand to<br>
1,500 participants. From the strawberry fields of northern<br>
California to nursing homes and poultry plants in the Deep South<br>
to sweatshops in New York City, these &quot;Union
Summeristas,&quot; as<br>
they called themselves, helped us jump-start a new wave of union<br>
organizing and I can report to you that we've decided one of our<br>
biggest priorities next year will be &quot;Union Summer
1997!&quot;<br>
<br>
By the time fall rolled around, we were ready for big<br>
changes in our structure and the way we do politics and<br>
organizing.<br>
<br>
We decided to transform the AFL-CIO from a Washington-based,<br>
policy-oriented institution to a grass-roots legislative and<br>
political fighting machine. Early in the year, we began<br>
confronting members of Congress with aggressive visits,<br>
demonstrations and sit-ins back home where it hurts. Then we put<br>
138 field coordinators in 110 Congressional districts and asked<br>
them to form standing local committees of at least 100 union<br>
activists to help elect friends of working families to office and<br>
to hold those friends accountable once they were elected.<br>
Finally, we decided to spend our money on an independent, issue-<br>
based television, direct mail, and door-knocking campaign, rather<br>
than donating it to any political party. <br>
<br>
The results, I hope, are obvious: America's unions are back<br>
and we are going to build those grassroots committees in every<br>
Congressional district and regain political strength and<br>
influence on behalf of working families! Our goal is to transform<br>
our movement from one that agonizes to one that organizes, from<br>
one that curries favor with politicians to one that demands<br>
respect from them, from one that lacks diversity to one that<br>
revels in it, from a movement that is slowing to one that is<br>
growing, from a movement that is stuck in the past to one that is<br>
tackling the future.<br>
<br>
On the organizing front, we're urging local and national<br>
unions to increase their organizing expenditures from an average<br>
of 5 percent of their budget to 30 percent of their budget. We've<br>
established a new organizing fund to help jump-start new<br>
campaigns. We're planning to go after entire industries and<br>
entire cities, rather than running piecemeal campaigns scattered<br>
around the country. And we've decided to organize over, around<br>
and beyond our ineffective and unfair labor laws.<br>
<br>
An example is our new campaign by the United Farm Workers to<br>
organize 20,000 strawberry workers in northern California. We're<br>
conducting a national campaign to persuade the owners it is in<br>
their interest to recognize the union for the workers and we've<br>
set up a &quot;National Strawberry Commission for Workers
Rights&quot; to<br>
marshall public opinion on our side.<br>
<br>
More than 100 prominent individuals and organizations have<br>
signed on and we're asking all AFL-CIO unions, central labor<br>
councils and state feds to get involved. As our Organizing<br>
Director, Richard Bensinger, told the press when we announced,<br>
&quot;We'll be in your face and on your conscience until these
workers<br>
get a union.&quot;<br>
<br>
Now I don't want you to think that the new AFL-CIO is all<br>
brawn and no brains. We also revamped our Public Affairs<br>
Department to get us into the 21st Century when it comes to<br>
waging the war over public opinion and I hope you've seen the<br>
results -- we've gotten more positive publicity for workers and<br>
their unions in the past year than we got in the 20 previous<br>
years. And we created a new Working Womens' Department to help us<br>
close a gender gap that is as wide as the Grand Canyon and<br>
revamped our Field Mobilization Department to put more people in<br>
the field and less in Washington.<br>
<br>
We've also created a new Department of Corporate Affairs to<br>
give us the firepower we need for doing battle with the multi-<br>
national corporations who have turned our economy and the world<br>
economy into a jungle. Our goal is to help affiliates deal with<br>
employers on multiple levels -- from corporate ownership and<br>
competitive strategy to collective bargaining, to workplace<br>
organization and technology -- and to find new ways to use our<br>
enormous financial resources to help working families in this<br>
country and around the world. <br>
<br>
Finally, we've made sweeping changes in our international<br>
affairs structure and programming. All of the international<br>
affairs institutes have been collapsed into one Department of<br>
International Affairs and we're now devoting all of our time and<br>
energy and staff to mobilizing world-wide in support of<br>
organizing and bargaining. For too many years, idealology has<br>
been the chief export of the AFL-CIO when it comes to<br>
International affairs. We've changed that and now the chief<br>
export and import of the department will be a far more precious<br>
and relevant commodity, one called &quot;international
solidarity.&quot;<br>
<br>
Our new Corporate Affairs Department and our revamped<br>
Department of International Affairs are the twin engines of<br>
economic justice we're going to use to lead our nation and our<br>
president across that bridge into the 21st century!<br>
<br>
When it comes to using global solidarity to bring employers<br>
to justice, we'll be building on the success and relationships of<br>
many of our affiliated unions. Back during my union's strike<br>
against the Bituminous Coal Operators, trade unions in Australia<br>
and South Africa struck transnational corporations like Hanson<br>
and DuPont on behalf of the UMWA. Recently, the steelworkers led<br>
a successful worldwide corporate campaign against Bridgestone-<br>
Firestone and won because of substantial help from unions in<br>
Argentia, Brazil, Turkey, France, Japan, Spain and a dozen other<br>
countries where the company has plants. <br>
<br>
When Sprint crushed an organizing drive by the<br>
communications workers in San Francsico, Mexican communications<br>
unions came to the CWA's defense by filing a complaint under the<br>
labor-said accords of NAFTA.<br>
<br>
We will also be building on the success of many of our<br>
affiliates when it comes to dealing with Wall Street's obsession<br>
with short-term profiteering through downsizings and<br>
restructuring. Last week when &quot;Chainsaw&quot; Dunlap
announced his<br>
plans for Sunbeam, union-controlled and public pension funds were<br>
the first to challenge him. Last April, the Teamsters and UNITE<br>
ran a candidate for K-Mart's board and led a successful campaign<br>
to remove another director. After the Teamster/UNITE proposal<br>
received 57 percent of the vote, K-Mart conveniently
&quot;lost&quot; 8<br>
percent of the votes, but UNITE and the IBT successfully sued the<br>
company in court. And union-controlled pension funds are leading<br>
the charge against irresponsible corporate citizens like Texaco,<br>
where shareholders are challenging management's toleration of<br>
discrimination against African American workers.<br>
<br>
Let me close with a few comments about two global trends<br>
that are of enormous consequences to the future of workers and<br>
their unions around the world and I'm talking about the<br>
privatization of social security systems and the creation of<br>
individual retirement accounts for workers.<br>
<br>
Both of these trends are being driven by Wall Street firms<br>
like State Street Bank, Oppenheimer, Goldman-Sachs, the<br>
Balckstone Group and T. Rowe Price for their own greedy purposes.<br>
If the American social security system is privatized, for<br>
instance, up to $100 billion would flow into the markets. If<br>
individual retirement accounts are a part of the scheme, it will<br>
mean additional billions of dollars and fees from the 10 percent<br>
that Wall Street charges to manage small accounts.<br>
<br>
The AFL-CIO opposes privatization and we oppose individual<br>
retirement accounts because they threaten workers in many ways.<br>
They injure workers and their families by raising the retirement<br>
age, reducing retirement income, creating retirement insecurity<br>
and undermining solidarity. They undermine the leverage worker-<br>
owners have on corporations. And they channel investment in ways<br>
which are indifferent, even hostile, to worker interests.<br>
<br>
The labor movement around the world is fighting these trends<br>
and I think we should develop and agree to a set of &quot;fair<br>
investment&quot; standards and rank them right up there with our
&quot;fair<br>
trade standards&quot;. These standards should include four
important<br>
ingredients. First, if pensions are privatized, workers should<br>
resist individual funds. If we allow workers to be broken up into<br>
little funds, there is no hope for marshalling the potential<br>
power of labor's capital -- workers will be divided, they will<br>
pay high fees, and they will make bad decisions<br>
<br>
Second, workers should insist on co-managing their pension<br>
funds. The right of workers to do so was passed by the ILO in the<br>
1930s. Last year the ILO rightfully condemned Chile -- the poster<br>
child for the World Bank -- and Peru for violations.<br>
<br>
Third, private pensions should not mean workers must work<br>
longer. Pensions are there because people get to old to work and<br>
because employers do not hire older workers. This is the chief<br>
reason for government programs -- individual accounts cannot<br>
guarantee retirement security.<br>
<br>
Fourth, workers and their unions should fight capital with<br>
capital and not allow our pension funds to be used against us --<br>
voting proxy shares, monitoring corporate executives, taking on<br>
corporations as shareholders.<br>
<br>
Over the next few years, the American labor movement bears<br>
the responsibility for driving a stake through the ugly hearts of<br>
the privatization and individual retirement account movements. We<br>
can start by urging our pension fund trustees and our<br>
international and local unions and our local unions to inform<br>
State Street, Oppenheimer, Goldman-Sachs and T. Rowe Price and<br>
other investment managers that we will no longer allow them to<br>
earn commissions from our fund and then use those commissions to<br>
fund the Wall Street campaign to privatize social security. Then<br>
we must complete the job of building our new grass-roots<br>
legislative and political machinery, because we're going to close<br>
out this century with the fight of the century. In one corner<br>
will be the &quot;Wizards of Wall Street,&quot; and they are the
heavy<br>
favorites because they have heavy pocketbooks and they are big<br>
and ugly and loud. In the other corner will be the &quot;New
Voice for<br>
American Labor,&quot; and that's all of us and we're more like a
short<br>
little guy with a balding head, a big heart and a quiet voice.<br>
<br>
I don't know about you, but I'm putting my money on the<br>
little guy and on every one of us. Because this fight is going to<br>
be just like Tyson and Holyfield. It will go 11 rounds and there<br>
will be blood all over the place. But we will win for the same<br>
reason that we beat Bob Dornan, for the same reason that we<br>
passed that living wage, for the same reason that we will defeat<br>
the California business community in their drive to destroy the<br>
40 hour week, for the same reason we will stop Pete Wilson from<br>
gutting the prevailing wage.<br>
<br>
We will win because we are fed up with scraps from the table<br>
and we want a seat at the table! Because we are 40 million union<br>
members and our families and we are fighting for our future.<br>
Because we are men and women, young and old, black and white,<br>
African-American, Latino, Asian-Pacific and we are fighting for<br>
our families. All of us together! Working together, organizing<br>
together, fighting together, winning together!<br>
<br>
Thank you and Godspeed .....</p>
