<html>
<head>
<title>SP 11/25/96 Sweeney at the Michigan State University
Annual Labor Forum Series</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<p align="center">Remarks by John J. Sweeney<br>
President of the AFL-CIO<br>
Michigan State University Annual Labor Forum Series<br>
November 19, 1996</p>
<p>Thank you, President McPherson, for that kind introduction,<br>
and thank you for taking me on a tour of the College of Law<br>
construction site preceding this forum. It's great seeing this<br>
wonderful university grow and prosper, and it's even better<br>
seeing it done with 100 percent union labor! I note with pride<br>
that this is the second time I've been introduced by the<br>
president of a major university in the past six weeks. The<br>
president of Columbia University introduced me at our teach-in<br>
there in October and I'll repeat what I said then: this is pretty<br>
rarified air for a bus driver's son from Iona College!<br>
<br>
I'm delighted to be here with all of you today to help<br>
inaugurate this labor forum, which will honor Dale Brickner for<br>
many, many years after he retires this December. I hope my<br>
remarks this morning will live up to the standards he has set for<br>
all of us during his 23 years as head of the MSU labor education<br>
program.<br>
<br>
I'm also glad to be here with labor leaders like Frank<br>
Garrison and Bertha Poe from the Michigan State AFL-CIO, Paul<br>
Policicchio from SEIU, and our courageous leaders from the<br>
Detroit Newspaper Council, Ed Scribner and Gloria Corbin. It<br>
gives me a chance to thank them publicly for what they did for<br>
the working families of this country on election day. We had a<br>
huge turnout of union members and their families here and across<br>
the country and we picked up 9 seats in the House by pro-working<br>
family candidates and re-elected a Democratic president for the<br>
first time since Franklin D. Roosevelt. Most of all, I want to<br>
thank them and you for sending Dick Chrysler to the shower he so<br>
badly needed!<br>
<br>
Ed and Gloria, I want to thank you publicly for your<br>
continuing leadership in what is turning out to be one of the<br>
ugliest confrontations in recent labor history at the Detroit<br>
News. And for those who doubt that we are right and that we will<br>
win, I point you to the tremendous victory we just won at<br>
Bridgestone-Firestone after 28 months!<br>
<br>
It has been, to say the least, a very eventful year and I<br>
want to begin by giving you my spin on what just happened at the<br>
ballot box: we won and they lost. I use the word &quot;they&quot;
advisedly<br>
because I know we have at least one prominent Republican here<br>
with us today! The AFL-CIO is a fiercely non-partisan<br>
organization and we don't operate in a framework of right vs.<br>
left, or conservatives vs. liberals, or Republicans vs.<br>
Democrats. Our political axis is bottom vs. the top, and we<br>
represent those on the bottom, which tends to make everyone mad<br>
at us. This past two years, however, we've been forced into what<br>
seems like an anti-Republican stance because the Republicans in<br>
the House of Representatives almost unanimously supported Speaker<br>
Gingrich in his frenzied attack on virtually every federal<br>
program that helps working families, seniors, young people, the<br>
poor, the disadvantaged and the disabled. So when we targeted the<br>
House and Senate seats occupied by anti-worker, anti-family<br>
office holders, all of our opponents turned out to be<br>
Republicans. How did we fare? After starting out the year<br>
electing Ron Wyden to the Senate in Oregon, we ended it by<br>
electing Tim Johnson in South Dakota, and re-electing Paul<br>
Wellstone in Minnesota and John Kerry in Massachusetts. And we<br>
defeated 17 of the ugliest Americans ever to serve in the United<br>
States House of Representatives.<br>
<br>
On election day, union households accounted for 23 percent<br>
of the overall vote, up from 14 percent in 1994 and 19 percent in<br>
1992. These 21 million voters were the key in many Congressional<br>
races, where 68 percent of AFL-CIO union members voted for<br>
Democrats and 32 percent for Republicans, down from 40 percent in<br>
1994. The 68 percent Democratic is compared to 45 percent for the<br>
general population.<br>
<br>
Few analysts, however, figured out just how close we came to<br>
retiring Newt Gingrich as Speaker of the House. In addition to<br>
the 17 House races we won, we lost 12 more by a total of just<br>
14,000 votes, and those would have been enough for progressive<br>
forces to reclaim the majority!<br>
<br>
But the story of this election is more than just numbers.<br>
From start to finish, we drove the national agenda and made<br>
Medicare and education and pensions the issues of 1996. In races<br>
across the country, right wing incumbents ran away from the<br>
Gingrich agenda and the next Congress will be a Congress that<br>
respects workers and their families!<br>
<br>
As you all know, our efforts attracted a lot of attention<br>
from our adversaries and from the media. Over the months, I was<br>
called a lot of things, including a crook and a communist and<br>
even an &quot;old-fashioned liberal.&quot; And as most of you
know, the<br>
Republican Party produced a television commercial and ran it all<br>
over the country calling me a &quot;big labor boss.&quot; Well, I
want<br>
you to know, it beats the hell out of being called a &quot;small
labor<br>
boss.&quot;<br>
<br>
Why did we undertake such an unprecedented political effort,<br>
risking charges of partisanship and the chance we might take on<br>
the Congressional majority and lose? Let me share some of the<br>
background with you.<br>
<br>
If you travelled around the country as I do, you would hear<br>
the same story over and over again from women and men making<br>
$40,000 a year as well as from those making $12,000 a year: _I_m<br>
working harder and harder and I_m making less and less._ <br>
<br>
Over the past 20 years, while productivity and corporate<br>
profits have been going steadily up, family incomes have been<br>
going down. Why? Because our employers have chosen to compete in<br>
the new global economy not by ingenuity and teamwork, but by<br>
cutting wages and benefits. The result? Working families have<br>
little money to spend, they are loaded down with debt and because<br>
more family members are working, they have little time to spend<br>
with their children. They are threatened by restructuring,<br>
downsizing, pension raids, privatizing and outsourcing schemes<br>
and runaway plants, and their anger is exceeded only by anxiety<br>
about keeping their jobs. They are fed up with government and<br>
business and you don't have to be an expert to know this is a<br>
prescription for social and economic disaster.<br>
<br>
And can you imagine in the middle of all of this, the<br>
Republicans giving a tax break to the rich by declaring all-out<br>
war on the programs and policies workers and their families<br>
depend on just for survival?<br>
<br>
When workers can't secure economic justice through<br>
reasonable means, they either take unreasonable actions on their<br>
own or they fall prey to right-wing demagogues like Patrick<br>
Buchanan and David Duke, or nutty corporate stooges like Ross<br>
Perot and Steve Forbes. And so with working-class Americans and<br>
their families hurting as never before, the labor movement had to<br>
respond as never before. We had to fill the vacuum in national<br>
leadership because we are the only legitimate representatives of<br>
those working families.<br>
<br>
Our problem: America needs a raise. And not just in wages<br>
and benefits, but in hope for the future and in respect for<br>
workers and the jobs they do. The solution: a bigger, stronger<br>
labor movement, one that provides more muscle for working<br>
families at the ballot box and at the bargaining table. That_s<br>
why I ran for president of the AFL-CIO, and that_s why we_re<br>
shaking up our movement to rebuild our membership base and<br>
restore our political power. <br>
<br>
It's not just a coincidence that the decline in family<br>
incomes in this country mirrored a decline in the labor movement.<br>
In 1980, 27 percent of our workforce was covered by union<br>
contracts guaranteeing decent rates of pay, adequate health<br>
benefits and retirement security. Today that figure is 15 percent<br>
and it is still going down. In those 15 years, we lost more than<br>
members, we lost our voice and we lost our political power. And<br>
so with the backing of some of the largest and most progressive<br>
unions in this country, Rich Trumka, Linda Chavez-Thompson and I<br>
ran for the top offices in the AFL-CIO in the first publicly-<br>
contested race in the history of our federation and we won with a<br>
platform mandating sweeping changes.<br>
<br>
And we concluded it is axiomatic that if we are going to<br>
build a bigger, stronger labor movement, we must change the way<br>
we do things --- because what we've been doing isn't working. And<br>
so, with the backing of our Executive Council, we're making the<br>
changes that are needed to help us achieve our goals of<br>
organizing more workers, building a national political force for<br>
working families, and providing a new voice for workers in the<br>
global economy as well as in our local communities.<br>
<br>
We started off by creating the first organizing department<br>
in the history of the AFL-CIO, with a commitment to spend $20<br>
million on organizing during our first two years --- 10 times<br>
what has been spent in the past. We tripled the size of our<br>
highly-successful Organizing Institute, which recruits young<br>
workers and college graduates and trains them for careers in<br>
union organizing. In March of this year, we held the first<br>
special convention in our history and voted a $25 million<br>
assessment to help finance a media and grassroots lobbying effort<br>
to defeat the &quot;Contract With America&quot; and to expose the<br>
politicians behind it.<br>
<br>
<br>
In May and June, we hosted a series of 30 town hall meetings<br>
around the country under the banner of &quot;America Needs a
Raise,&quot;<br>
taking testimony from union workers and non-union workers alike<br>
and publicizing the meetings to begin building a new base of<br>
public support for workers and their families.<br>
<br>
During June, July and August, we sponsored a watershed<br>
program called &quot;Union Summer,&quot; which we envisioned
putting 1,000<br>
young workers and college students through an experience like<br>
&quot;Freedom Summer&quot; in the 1960s. We got nearly 4000
applications<br>
and had to expand to 1,500 participants. From the strawberry<br>
fields of northern California to nursing homes and poultry plants<br>
in the Deep South to sweatshops in New York City, these
&quot;Union<br>
Summeristas,&quot; as they called themselves, helped us
jump-start a<br>
new wave of union organizing and I can report to you that we've<br>
decided one of our biggest priorities next year will be
&quot;Union<br>
Summer 1997!&quot;<br>
<br>
By the time fall rolled around, we were ready for big<br>
changes in our structure and the way we do politics and<br>
organizing.<br>
<br>
When it came to political and legislative action, we decided<br>
to transform the AFL-CIO from a Washington-based, policy-oriented<br>
institution to a grass-roots fighting machine. Early in the year,<br>
we began confronting members of Congress with aggressive visits,<br>
demonstrations and sit-ins back home where it hurts. Then we put<br>
138 field coordinators in 110 Congressional districts and asked<br>
them to form standing local committees of at least 100 union<br>
activists to help elect friends of working families to office and<br>
to hold those friends accountable once they were elected.<br>
Finally, we decided to spend our money on an independent, issue-<br>
based television, direct mail, and door=knocking campaign, rather<br>
than donating it to any political party. <br>
<br>
The results, I hope, are obvious: America's unions are back<br>
and we are going to build those grassroots committees in every<br>
Congressional district and regain political strength and<br>
influence on behalf of working families!<br>
<br>
On the organizing front, we began the year with an<br>
educational and motivational program to convince our local and<br>
national unions to increase their organizing expenditures from 5<br>
percent of their budget to 30 percent of their budget. We<br>
established a new local union organizing fund to help start new<br>
campaigns. We decided to go after entire industries and entire<br>
cities, rather than running piecemeal campaigns scattered around<br>
the country. And we decided we had to organize over, around and<br>
beyond our ineffective labor laws, which give the advantage to<br>
employers.<br>
<br>
An example is our new campaign by the United Farm Workers to<br>
organize 20,000 strawberry workers in northern California. When<br>
the UFW tries to organize such workers, the growers get together<br>
and conduct vicious campaigns of intimidation, harassment and<br>
job terminations to stop the workers from gaining decent wages,<br>
health benefits, better sanitation and sexual abuse protections<br>
in the fields.<br>
We're conducting a national campaign to persuade the owners<br>
it is in their interest to recognize the union for the workers<br>
and we've set up a &quot;National Strawberry Commission for
Workers<br>
Rights&quot; to marshall public opinion on our side.<br>
<br>
As our Organizing Director, Richard Bensinger, told the<br>
press when we announced, &quot;We'll be in your face and on your<br>
conscience until these workers get a union.&quot;<br>
<br>
Now I don't want you to think that the new AFL-CIO is all<br>
brawn and no brains. We also revamped our Public Affairs<br>
Department to get us into the 21st Century when it comes to<br>
waging the war over public opinion and I hope you've seen the<br>
results --- we've gotten more positive publicity for workers and<br>
their unions in the past year than we got in the 20 previous<br>
years.<br>
<br>
We created a new Department of Corporate Affairs to help us<br>
do battle with the giant multinational employers that now<br>
dominate the global economy. We brought in four of the most<br>
brilliant young people in our movement to provide us with<br>
strategic research, leverage strategies, a voice on Wall Street<br>
and new strategies to use our enormous financial resources to<br>
help us achieve organizing, bargaining and political goals.<br>
<br>
We also created a new Womens' Department to help us close a<br>
gender gap that is as wide as the Grand Canyon, consolidated our<br>
far-flung international operations into one central department<br>
with the job of exporting solidarity instead of ideology, and<br>
revamped our Field Mobilization Department to put more people in<br>
the field and less in Washington.<br>
<br>
Our goal is to transform our movement from one that agonizes<br>
to one that organizes, from one that curries favor with<br>
politicians to one that demands respect from them, from one that<br>
lacks diversity to one that revels in it, from a movement that is<br>
slowing to one that is growing, from a movement that is stuck in<br>
the past to one that is tackling the future.<br>
<br>
Here's the truth: The weakness of labor encouraged employers<br>
to take the low road. And only by rebuilding our strength can we<br>
bring American business back to the high road of high wages,<br>
health care and pensions. We can no longer afford the luxury of<br>
pretending that productivity, quality, and competitiveness are<br>
not our business. They are our business, our jobs, and our<br>
paychecks. Too many workers have suffered because of failed and<br>
foolish shortsighted management policies.<br>
<br>
As labor becomes stronger and smarter, we will be in a<br>
position to offer business a challenge: take some of your profits<br>
and invest them in growing the American economy and American<br>
wages. Offer your workers the training they need for tomorrow's<br>
jobs -- not just the big-shots in the executive suites, but all<br>
your employees.<br>
<br>
Work with your employees and their unions. Give us a voice<br>
in decision-making. Give us half a chance to improve the quality<br>
of our goods and services. That is the path to lasting prosperity<br>
-- and we want to walk down that road with you.<br>
<br>
Now that we have demonstrated a reawakening of our political<br>
power, we also want to issue a challenge to our government and to<br>
our elected leaders: get busy on a national industrial strategy<br>
that reverses the erosion of our manufacturing base and provides<br>
fair export-import policies. Replace free trade with fair trade.<br>
Restore some sanity to a tax code that has reduced taxes on<br>
millionaires by one-third over the past 15 years while raising<br>
taxes by a similar amount on middle-income Americans. Support the<br>
concept of a living wage. Put some new parameters around the Wall<br>
Street wizards who are operating dangerously beyond the fringe of<br>
current regulation. Beef up Social Security and Medicare, don't<br>
give them up to the privateers --- when the Baby Boomers got<br>
ready to go to kindergarten, this nation didn't tear down<br>
schools, we built more and those Baby Boomers built the strongest<br>
economy the world has ever known. Stop giving away our sweat and<br>
our blood to our trading partners. Stop beating up on the poor,<br>
the young and the elderly. And for God's sake, help us put the<br>
sweatshops out of business and help us stop child labor!<br>
<br>
I hope you all noted the nature of the issues I just cited,<br>
because it is neither widely known, nor greatly appreciated that<br>
organized labor has always been more concerned with the society<br>
around us than with our own narrow interests. Nearly a century<br>
ago, the first president of the AFL-CIO, Samuel Gompers, was<br>
asked, &quot;What does labor want?&quot; His answer,
&quot;more,&quot; has often been<br>
misquoted and used to defame unions. What he actually said was,<br>
&quot;More schoolhouses and less jail, more books and less
arsenals,<br>
more learning and less vice, more constant work and less crime,<br>
more leisure and less greed, more justice and less revenge._ It<br>
was an eloquent statement of values trade unionists still hold<br>
dear. <br>
<br>
And what do working Americans and their unions want as we<br>
draw close to a new century? We want to live in a country where<br>
you can raise a family without having to hold down three jobs to<br>
do it. Where you don_t have to spend so much time at work that<br>
you have no time left to go to a movie or to a ball game with<br>
your kids or your grandchildren. Where health care and retirement<br>
are guaranteed for all, rather than reserved for a chosen few.<br>
Where your lot in life is determined by what you do, and not by<br>
the color of your skin or the accident of your birth. Where our<br>
children and grandchildren can look forward to pay raises instead<br>
of layoff notices. Where we can take things like good schools and<br>
public health and environmental protections for granted. Our idea<br>
of a just society is one in which honest labor raises the<br>
standard of living for all, rather than enormous wealth for a<br>
few. And our notion of a moral nation is one which cares for its<br>
young, its old and its poor and leaves the rich to fend for<br>
themselves.<br>
<br>
Thank you very much ....</p>
