<html>
<head>
<title>SP 08/28/96 Sweeney Democratic Convention</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<p>John J. Sweeney, AFL-CIO President<br>
Speech to 1996 Democratic Convention, Chicago<br>
August 28, 1996<br>
<br>
<br>
My brothers and sisters. You met some of the convention<br>
workers on Monday night. Standing with me tonight are Miaisha<br>
Evans, Sophie Kowalczyk, and Al Molina. They are members of the<br>
Service Employees Union and they represent the cleaners, ushers,<br>
vendors, and parking attendants here at United Center.<br>
<br>
I'm here tonight to speak for them and for all American<br>
workers, those who belong to unions as well as those who do not. <br>
<br>
They want you to know that they are proud of their country,<br>
and the contributions they are making to it. But they also want<br>
you to know that our country can do better. That we have to do<br>
more.<br>
<br>
Over the past two decades, American workers rose to the<br>
challenge of global competition and they increased productivity<br>
24 percent. But it didn_t help them -- family incomes went down<br>
15 percent!<br>
<br>
With Bill Clinton and Al Gore at the helm, our economy has<br>
rebounded, more jobs have been created and we_ve turned the<br>
corner on the tax giveaways of the 1980s. <br>
<br>
But millions of workers are still struggling to catch up.<br>
Families worry constantly about choosing between their work and<br>
their children. With employers downsizing, cutting benefits, and<br>
raiding pension funds, it_s no wonder millions of workers are<br>
getting involved in politics as never before.<br>
<br>
What do working families want? <br>
<br>
They don't want to run the Congress, or the White House or<br>
the political parties. They want to be compensated and respected<br>
for the contributions they make. They want to send their children<br>
to decent schools. They want to go to a safe workplace every day.<br>
They want a doctor when they need one, a little rest when they<br>
are weary, and a pension after a lifetime of work.<br>
<br>
What do working families want of their unions? <br>
<br>
They want us to be a bigger force, to fiercely champion<br>
their values and their interests, independent of party or<br>
candidate. They want us to stick to the issues, and skip the<br>
rhetoric. <br>
<br>
They want us to get after the corporations who force them to<br>
choose between being underpaid and unemployed -- corporations<br>
like Bridgestone-Firestone, which illegally replaced 2,300<br>
striking workers.<br>
<br>
And what do they want of their elected leaders? <br>
<br>
More jobs and more growth, with a greater share for working<br>
families. Greater responsibility from corporate America.<br>
Restoration of the right of workers to organize unions and<br>
bargain for a better future. An economy that works for all of us.<br>
They want to support candidates who listen to them and their<br>
concerns.<br>
<br>
Why do working families support Bill Clinton? <br>
<br>
Because he listened and vetoed the Medicare cuts and vetoed<br>
the TEAM Act and signed a minimum wage increase which Bob Dole<br>
and his colleagues tried to block. <br>
<br>
Because he listened to Kathy Wilkinson, a West Virginia<br>
community college worker, who said as the President signed the<br>
minimum wage bill: &quot;It's going to be such a relief to be
able to<br>
pay the gas and electric all in one month.&quot;<br>
<br>
Working Americans want to live in a country where you don_t<br>
have to hold down three jobs just to pay the gas and electric. A<br>
country where you have enough time left over from work to go to<br>
church and enough money in your pocket to take your kids to a<br>
ballgame. Where your lot in life is determined by what you do,<br>
and not by the color of your skin, the accident of your birth, or<br>
the selection of your partner.<br>
<br>
Our idea of a just society is one in which honest labor<br>
raises the standard of living for all, rather than enormous<br>
wealth for a few.<br>
<br>
And our vision of a moral nation is one which cares for its<br>
young, its old, its disabled and its poor and leaves the rich to<br>
fend for themselves.<br>
<br>
That's the kind of country working Americans want. That's<br>
the kind of country all Americans need. And that's the kind of<br>
America Bill Clinton, Al Gore and a new Congress will deliver!<br>
<br>
Thank you, and Godspeed.</p>
