<html>
<head>
<title>SP 07/18/96 Sweeney at Education Conference</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<h2 align="center">John J. Sweeney<br>
President of the AFL-CIO</h2>
<h1 align="center">27th Annual National Education Conference<br>
A. Philip Randolph Institute</h1>
<h2 align="center">Washington, D.C.<br>
July 18, 1996</h2>
<p>[Acknowledgements: Leon Lynch, APRI chairman and member of
AFL-CIO executive council; Norman Hill, APRI president; Gloria
Johnson, APRI vice president and AFL-CIO executive council
member; Barbara Van Blake, APRI vice president and AFT civil
rights director; Edgar Romney, secretary of APRI and executive
vice president of UNITE.] </p>
<p>Thank you for that kind introduction, and thanks to all of you
for your warm welcome. I bring you the greetings of
Secretary-Treasurer Richard Trumka, Executive Vice President
Linda Chavez Thompson and the 13.1 million men and women of the
AFL-CIO who share your commitment to social and economic justice. </p>
<p>The theme you have chosen for this conference -- &quot;The
Black- Labor Alliance in the 1996 Election: Mobilize, Motivate,
and Militate&quot; -- couldn't be more appropriate. </p>
<p>The Black/Labor alliance that A. Philip Randolph did so much
to create is build on a solid foundation. We share the same
values and the same goals. And, Lord knows, we have the same
enemies -- the race-haters and the labor-baiters, the church-
burners and the union-busters. </p>
<p>With your help, the labor movement is showing the Newt
Gingriches, the Trent Lotts, and the Haley Barbours of the land
that they can lambaste us and lie about us -- but they can no
longer ignore us. And that is why I hope you are finding this an
inspiring and exciting time to be here in Washington. </p>
<p>After nearly 20 years of decline, our labor movement has begun
to find our footing again on Capitol Hill. And we just pumped
home five slam-dunks on our political opponents. </p>
<p>The week before last -- at the decisive moment in the battle
to raise the minimum wage -- I made an emergency call to all the
unions in the AFL-CIO. And our sisters and brothers answered the
call. We swarmed Washington with 1500 rank-and-file lobbyists and
more than a dozen international union presidents. We hit the
airwaves with paid and free media. And union members around the
country volunteered the time and made thousands of telephone
calls. </p>
<p>Together, we made history. We passed the minimum wage in the
Senate. We won a huge victory for the 12 million working men and
women -- 30% of them African-American or Hispanic -- who stand to
benefit directly from an increase in the minimum wage. And we won
a victory for millions more who are also struggling to support
themselves and their families -- and who will benefit from any
upward push on wages. </p>
<p>You know as well as anyone what a mockery it makes of the
American dream when people who work fulltime still live and labor
in poverty. You know what raising the minimum wage will mean for
the women and men who do America's most difficult and dangerous
jobs. You know what a great thing it is to put more dollars in
their paychecks and more dignity in their lives. </p>
<p>Just after our victory on the minimum wage, we won another
one. We defeated a national &quot;right-to-work&quot; bill in the
Senate by another huge margin. And every union member in this
country can breathe a little easier. </p>
<p>Then came our third victory: Newt Gingrich and his radical
right-wing wrecking crew in the House were trying to eliminate
the new OSHA repetitive stress injury regulations that we all
have worked so hard to win. But -- with your help -- we beat
them. We won a big victory for every man and woman in this
country who works with their hands and their backs. </p>
<p>And, for our fourth victory, we defeated the so-called
&quot;TEAM Act,&quot; which would bring back company unions. It
got too few votes to override a presidential veto. And the
working men and women of this country thank President Clinton in
advance for this veto. </p>
<p>Fifth and finally, on Friday, the Gingrich gang read the
handwriting on the floor. They decided to crawl back under their
rocks, and not support a bill before Congress to get rid of
federal affirmative action programs. </p>
<p>I believe they did that because they understood that the labor
movement and the civil rights movement are prepared to fight them
every inch of the way. On behalf of the AFL-CIO, I testified
before a committee of Congress in support of affirmative action.
And I want you to know that we are prepared to continue the fight
from the halls of Congress to the streets of California. Whether
the issue is a federal regulation or a statewide referendum, we
will never let anyone turn back the clock on simple justice. </p>
<p>Every member of this movement can take pride in these
achievements. So I ask you to stand up and give yourselves a
hand. </p>
<p>The victories we're winning make us proud -- but we must
remain vigilant. As you know so well, in the fight for social
justice, there are no lasting victories -- only continuing
struggles. </p>
<p>That is why we will not rest until the minimum wage increase
is signed into law and provided in the paychecks of 12 million
low-wage workers. That is why we will not rest until the so-
called &quot;TEAM Act&quot; is in the wastebasket of history,
along with company unions and company towns. And that is why we
will not rest until this society reaffirms its commitment to
affirmative action. </p>
<p>You know, those right-wingers really have a gift for giving
ugly ideas beautiful names. These are the same people who called
ketchup a vegetable and called union-busting the &quot;right to
work.&quot; Now, they're calling a scheme to bring back company
unions the &quot;TEAM Act.&quot; And they even have the nerve to
call a referendum to gut affirmative action &quot;The California
Civil Rights Initiative.&quot; They want to deceive, divide, and
conquer, but we won't let them get away with it. </p>
<p>We have a message for those who would turn back the clock on
civil rights, workers' rights, or women's rights: If you take one
of us on, you take all of us on. And we_ll beat you, once and for
all, now and forever. </p>
<p>The politicians are finding out that, as Ted Koppel said on
&quot;Nightline&quot; not too many weeks ago, &quot;Labor is
back!&quot; And the best way to tell that we're coming back and
fighting back is to hear how our enemies are crying and
complaining. Our efforts have come under fire from a host of
civic-minded, non-partisan organizations concerned with fairness
and balance in the political process. Organizations like the U.S.
Chamber of Commerce, the National Federation of Independent
Business, and the National Association of Manufacturers. Rich
Trumka calls them the &quot;Harry, Larry, and Moe&quot; of the
American economy. </p>
<p>These three organizations and the big business, anti-worker
forces in Congress have targeted the labor movement and all
working Americans. They're using every half-truth and big-lie
they can find to try to discredit our effort to speak out on
behalf of working families. </p>
<p>Well, I'm proud to be their target. I'm proud to take my place
beside all their other targets: the young, the old, working
families, and the poor. I stand before you today and say I'm
proud to take my lumps for speaking out for simple justice. Will
you stand up and speak out and bear witness with me? </p>
<p>As you can tell, I'm having fun. It feels good to win a few
after years of defeat and retreat. Sisters and brothers, we're
turning the labor movement around -- and we're beginning to turn
our country around. </p>
<p>We're doing it because we're fighting harder and smarter.
Instead of playing by the old political rules, we're lifting the
lid off the House and Senate and letting in some sunshine.
Instead of being victimized by outmoded traditions of collective
bargaining, we're exposing the actions and the motives of our
employers. </p>
<p>We're spending more time and money telling the people and our
own members how their elected officials are voting and how their
business leaders are performing. We've moved our legislative
emphasis from Washington out into the districts where the
politicians have to listen. We've taken our contract fights out
of the streets and into the suites. When a politician or an
employer crosses us, we take them on -- aggressively and
publicly. We are on their doorsteps, in their faces, and on their
consciences. </p>
<p>We're fighting back -- and fighting together. When a group of
workers in one union is in danger, members from other unions
respond, instinctively and effectively. </p>
<p>A good example is the Bridgestone/Firestone boycott. The
rubber workers fought this Japanese conglomerate with all they
had. Then they merged with the Steelworkers and took on new life.
Last weekend, on the second anniversary of the strike, I spoke to
a rally of 2,500 union activists and supporters in Nashville. You
could see the hats and jackets and signs of three dozen different
unions in the crowd. </p>
<p>That morning -- with the help of dozens of unions in 40 cities
-- the Steelworkers handbilled a thousand Firestone Mastercare
centers simultaneously. The United Auto Workers local at Saturn
persuaded their management to offer a free tire swap, nationwide,
for any Saturn buyer who doesn't want Firestone tires. </p>
<p>Another example of a revitalized labor movement is the success
of Union Summer. We started out trying to recruit 1,000 young
workers and students. We ended up getting more than 3,000
applications. So we've put 1,500 in the field. And they've
restored our faith in the young people of this country. They're
organizing nursing home, leather goods, garment and hotel
workers. They're walking picket lines at the Detroit News and
McDonnell-Douglas. And they're registering voters and working on
living-wage campaigns from New Orleans to Seattle. </p>
<p>Sisters and brothers: Labor is back. Over the past seven
months, we've proven we can fight back and win. And now we're
turning our attention to the biggest fight we face this year. </p>
<p>The choice is clear. All the cards are on the table. The chips
are down. </p>
<p>On one side of the table, we have Bob Dole. He's acting kinder
and gentler and pretending he's from outside the Beltway. But
he's still the Darth Vader of American politics, the ultimate
insider. He voted against the Workplace Fairness Bill, against
Davis-Bacon, and against saving Social Security from the Balanced
Budget Amendment. He wants to abolish the Department of
Education, cut student loans, dismantle OSHA, and cut Medicare by
$270 billion and Medicaid by $170 billion to give a tax cut to
the rich. </p>
<p>On the other side of the table is Bill Clinton. He's for
saving Social Security, helping Head Start, and keeping college
loans. He supported the Workplace Fairness Bill, comprehensive
national health care reform, and prohibitions against pension
raids. He vetoed the massive Dole cuts in Medicare and Medicaid,
he vetoed tax cuts for the rich, and he's going to veto the TEAM
Act, as well as any bills that damage OSHA. He's leading our
nation to economic recovery. But he isn't satisfied because he
knows our economy has left too many working families behind. </p>
<p>That is why 70% of our members in a national poll support Bill
Clinton and Al Gore, and that is why the AFL-CIO has voted
overwhelmingly to endorse their re-election. That is why we are
conducting an unprecedented grassroots legislative and political
education program. And that is why we're going to fight and win,
from the courthouse to the White House. </p>
<p>But you know as well as anyone that our fight for social and
economic justice must continue well beyond November. We will not
rest until we organized working people all across America,
rebuilding our labor movement and restoring the spirit of
community in this country. </p>
<p>This year, we held &quot;America Needs a Raise&quot; town hall
meetings in 30 cities, where working people told us about what is
happening to their jobs, their paychecks, and their family
budgets. </p>
<p>At a meeting in Birmingham, Alabama, Nathaniel Jackson II
explained that, even with a business degree from Tuskeegee
Institute and 20 years' experience as a salesman, he is
struggling to say even in the cruel new economy. Mr. Jackson
said: &quot;Now, it's 1996. I've worked as a doorman, a sub, and
now I'm working two and three jobs trying to make a living for
myself. What happens is people are more concerned with filling
their pockets, rather than taking care of others.&quot; </p>
<p>The fabric of social and economic justice in this country has
always been frail. But now, it is becoming torn and tattered, as
we enter a new economy with a handful of winners, too many
losers, and too few standards of decency. </p>
<p>We know that working men and women have seen their wages
stagnate for the past 20 years or more. And we know that
African-Americans still earn only 80% of the average hourly wage
in this country. </p>
<p>As middle class working people find the ground cracking
beneath their feet, too often they turn their anger and anxiety
against those even less fortunate than themselves. And for those
who have suffered from discrimination and exploitation in good
times and bad, there is a harsher economy and a meaner society. </p>
<p>You can see the meanness in the burnings of houses of worship
in the South and across this country. Many unions have pledged
their money and their muscle to rebuild these church buildings.
We can do it -- and we will. </p>
<p>And, just as we can restore the spirit of community in America
by rebuilding our churches, we can restore the spirit of
solidarity by rebuilding our labor movement. We need to raise the
wages of every working American so that, once again, we can turn
to each other and stop turning against each other. </p>
<p>The future of our labor movement depends on how well unions
can convince people of color, women, immigrants and everyone else
who is underpaid and overlooked to join together and join with
us. </p>
<p>I am here to ask for your leadership and your help for a
mighty wave of organizing that will renew and restore the dream
of justice and equality for millions of working men and women,
from the hospitals and nursing homes to the office buildings and
textile mills, to our schools and government agencies. </p>
<p>As you know so well, African-American workers make 18% more
with a union. And unions help workers win not only dollars but
dignity -- the right to hold your head higher, to speak your mind
without fear, and to join together with your sisters and brothers
against every form of injustice. </p>
<p>With your help, we will be everywhere working people are
crying out for a stronger voice, a better deal, and simple </p>
<p>justice. And, as we ask working people to join with us, we
must make sure that the face of this movement reflects the face
of working Americans. </p>
<p>That is why our new leadership team at the AFL-CIO is
absolutely committed to openness and inclusion at every level of
this movement... and why we believe that organizations like the
A. Philip Randolph Institute deserve a place at the table of
labor's leadership. </p>
<p>You probably hear this over and over -- but it is well worth
repeating over and over. </p>
<p>We believe that, as A. Philip Randolph said: &quot;At the
banquet table of nature, there are no reserved seats. You get
what you can take, and you keep what you can hold. If you can't
take anything, you won't get anything, and, if you can't hold
anything, you won't keep anything. And you can't take anything
without organization.&quot; </p>
<p>Together, we can mobilize, energize, and organize. Together,
we can take hold onto the presidency, take back the Congress, and
take back America. Together we can build a movement so strong, so
inclusive, and so energetic that we can raise wages, lift the
spirit, and strengthen the solidarity of all Americans.</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../index.htm">Public Documents Page</a> | <a
href="../publsear.htm">Public Documents Search</a></p>
