<html>
<head>
<title>SP 07/25/96 Opening Statement Panel Discussion on Women
and Economic Change</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<h3 align="center">John J. Sweeney<br>
Opening Statement</h3>
<h1 align="center">Panel Discussion on Women and Economic Change<br>
Leadership Conference on Women, the Economy, and the Elections</h1>
<h2 align="center">Institute for Women's Policy Research<br>
Washington, D.C.<br>
July 25, 1996</h2>
<p>Thank you, Gloria Johnson, for that fine introduction. As the
president of the Coalition of Labor Union Women, as a member of
the AFL-CIO Executive Council, and as director of social action
at the International Union of Electronic Workers, Gloria Johnson
is a leader in the fights for women's rights and workers' rights. </p>
<p>I am also honored to participate in a panel that includes:
Sen. Carol Moseley Braun, who is a leader on so many issues of
concern to working families; Julianne Malveaux, who is one
economist and commentator who speaks out for working Americans;
Prema Mathai-Davis, national executive director of the YWCA-USA;
and Patricia Harrison, of Capital Legislative Services. </p>
<p>And I want to thank the sponsor of this event, the Institute
for Women's Policy Research, and its director, Dr. Heidi Hartman,
for their outstanding research and advocacy. I understand that,
in connection with this conference, the Institute is releasing a
report on the wage gap which still remains between working women
and working men. </p>
<p>This morning, I'd like to talk briefly about how the labor
movement is revitalizing itself by rededicating itself to the
cause of working women. </p>
<p>As you know so well, women are on the frontlines of economic
change -- from the growth of new technologies and global trade,
to stagnant wages, downsizing corporations, vanishing health
coverage, and the burgeoning temporary workforce. The most
important social, economic, and political story of our times will
be how women respond to these changes. The anxious working woman
holds the future of the labor movement -- and, indeed, the future
of American politics -- in her hands. </p>
<p>The same hands that make America work will write the history
of our society as it enters the new century. As leaders like
Gloria Johnson have been insisting for many years, the labor
movement's commitment to working women is not only a moral
imperative -- it is a practical necessity. </p>
<p>Here's why unions have a moral responsibility to working
women. I often say that working Americans need a raise -- and
that's especially true for working women. To cite a statistic
which the Institute may update, women who work fulltime outside
the home are still paid only 72 cents for every dollar earned by
working men. </p>
<p>Too few women work at secure, good-paying jobs with health
insurance, reliable pensions, and other benefits. Too many
working women are caught in the so-called &quot;contingent&quot;
workforce, being bounced around from one part-time, low-wage
insecure job to another, with little or no health care or pension
rights and few labor protections. </p>
<p>As you know, women's wages are absolutely essential for
American families -- and not only for households that are headed
by women. In most families, it is necessary for husbands and
wives to work -- so, when women are underpaid and exploited,
everyone suffers. That is one reason why families are sending
more members into the work force, working longer hours and,
often, second jobs, as well. </p>
<p>Women, in particular, are working longer hours -- outside and
inside the home. In what Americans still think of as the typical
household -- a husband, wife, and children all living under the
same roof -- the mother is now working 32.3 percent more hours
outside the home per year than she'd done in 1979. And, because
women still shoulder heavier responsibilities at home, the
average woman spends another 2.6 hours on chores and 3.75 hours
with the children during the workweek. </p>
<p>All this means that working women are hardpressed for time as
well as money. For instance, listen to Marina Foley, a grocery
buyer and mother of two young daughters in Tallahassee, Florida,
describing her daily routine: </p>
<p>&quot;This morning, my alarm went off at 5:45. I hit snooze
and squeaked out another fifteen minutes. Put the coffee on and
then walked the dog and fed him. Started a load of laundry.
Emptied the dishwasher. Daughter #1 has a huge track meet at
school, so she had to be driven today, then head to work. At 4:45
p.m., I leave work to rush home to my latch-key nine- year-old
daughter...I usually don't sit down until 10:30 p.m.&quot; </p>
<p>There's a new movie out, called &quot;Multiplicity,&quot; in
which a working man played by Michael Keaton has so many demands
on his time that he clones himself. That movie would be even more </p>
<p>timely if the leading character were a working woman.
Listening to working women like Marina Foley talk about the
demands on their time, at home and on the job, I'm tempted to
change my slogan from &quot;America needs a raise&quot; to
&quot;America needs a nap.&quot; </p>
<p>Because working women are desperately squeezed for time and
money, they are urgently in need of union representation. One
other wage fact says it all: Union women earn 37 percent more
than nonunion women -- and even earn 4 percent more than nonunion
men. </p>
<p>Now, here's why it's a practical necessity for unions to reach
out to working women. </p>
<p>First, women work in the fastest-growing part of the economy
-- the service sector. When you look at the industries that are
gaining rather than shedding employees -- health care, data
processing, telecommunications, building services, hotels and
restaurants, to name just a few -- all have large numbers of
working women. When you look at the handful of unions that have
gained members over the past two decades -- such as my old union,
the Service Employees, as well as unions representing teachers,
government workers, and retail workers -- they have all grown by
organizing working women. </p>
<p>Second, it's not only where women work - it's what they
believe. The AFL-CIO's surveys of working Americans show that
women are more likely than men to support the idea of organizing
a union where they work. This finding is borne out by a simple
fact: From 1985 through 1995, more women than men joined unions
through elections conducted by the National Labor Relations
Board. At this moment in history, women may be more receptive
than men to the labor movement's message of fairness, community,
and solidarity. </p>
<p>And, third, working women are determining the future of
political campaigns as well as union organizing. We have all
heard a lot about the so-called &quot;angry white men,&quot; but
the most important segment of the electorate this year could be
called the &quot;anxious working women.&quot; </p>
<p>In a paper she prepared for the AFL-CIO, the public opinion
analyst Celinda Lake explained that one of the most volatile
groups in the electorate is younger working women without four-
year college degrees. These women supported Bill Clinton for
President in 1992. But, in 1994, many stayed home, and others
shifted to the Republicans. They are concerned about the economy
and jobs, Social Security, education, and health care -- and also
about crime and drugs and moral decline. The common element among
their concerns is security for themselves and their families and
a better future for their children. </p>
<p>These are some of the reasons why the labor movement needs to
reach out to working women. So what are we doing about it? </p>
<p>First, we are making an unprecedented effort to put the needs
of working families at the center of public debate. Earlier this
year, we held &quot;America needs a raise&quot; hearings in 30
cities across this country, where working women and men told
about the pressures on their family budgets and family lives. </p>
<p>For instance, in Columbus, Ohio, a college graduate and single
mother named Karen Meadows talked about how she works at two
low-wage jobs just so her family can make ends meet. She said she
wants he four sons to know that hard work makes a difference. But
she said: &quot;They see me working two jobs, and they can't see
where it makes a difference. I want better for my sons, but a
two-room trailer is all I can afford.&quot; </p>
<p>Our effort also includes everything from paid advertising
promoting working families' priorities to grassroots organizing
and education on political and legislative issues. </p>
<p>Already, our efforts have helped to win an important victory
-- the votes in the House and Senate to raise the minimum wage by
90 cents over two years. Increasing the minimum wage will lift
the living standards of 12 million working Americans -- and at
least 60% of them are women. </p>
<p>This summer and fall, we will keep union members informed
about where their representatives stand on the issues that shape
their lives and livelihoods, from the minimum wage to education
and training, health and safety, Medicare and Medicaid. We will
help working Americans, including the anxious working women, make
informed decisions, based on their own interests and values. </p>
<p>Second, we are beginning to organize at a scale and pace that
are unprecedented. </p>
<p>These are some of the workers whom unions are organizing or
preparing to organize: Clothing and textile workers -- from the
sweatshops of our major cities to the mill towns of the South.
Hospital workers, nursing home workers, and home care workers.
Poultry workers throughout the South. Strawberry workers in
California. And hotel workers in Nevada. </p>
<p>As you know, most of these workers are women. And </p>
<p>unions are appealing on the full range of issues that concern
working women -- from better pay and benefits to more dignity and
opportunity on the job. </p>
<p>Third, the faces of our leadership and staff are beginning to
reflect the faces of Americans at work. </p>
<p>I was elected president of the AFL-CIO in a contested campaign
that emerged from an effort to revitalize the labor movement, so
that we can better organize and represent the new American
workforce. </p>
<p>Among other changes, the AFL-CIO convention created a new
position, executive vice president, to work with state and local
labor councils and our allies across the country. To fill that
position, the delegates elected Linda Chavez-Thompson, who served
as president of the public employee union, AFSCME, for the states
of Arizona, Colorado, Nevada, New Mexico, Oklahoma, Texas, and
Utah. In addition, we expanded the executive council from 35 to
54, with the proportion of women and minorities rising from 17 to
27 percent. We're not where we need to be, but we're better than
we were. </p>
<p>At the AFL-CIO headquarters, women serve as directors of
communications, legislation, field mobilization, occupational
safety and health, and the Organizing Institute. We have also
created a new Working Women's Department to inject the issues and
concerns of working women into every major program at the AFL-CIO
and to develop programs that speak specifically to working women. </p>
<p>I'm sure many of you know the director of the Working Women's
Department, Karen Nussbaum, and admire her as much as I do. She
spent 20 years as an organizer and president of her local union,
District 925 of the Service Employees. Most recently, she served
as the director of the Women's Bureau in the U.S. Department of
Labor. I'm pleased and proud that she decided to come home, to a
labor movement that is trying to do more than ever before to
organize, represent, and empower working women. </p>
<p>The test of our efforts will be whether we help working women
make tangible improvements in their jobs and their lives, their
communities and their country. With leaders like Gloria Johnson,
Linda Chavez-Thompson, and Karen Nussbaum -- and with the hard
work and strong support of many of you here today -- I am hopeful
that working women will revitalize the labor movement and change
America, forever and for the better.</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../index.htm">Public Documents Page</a> | <a
href="../publsear.htm">Public Documents Search</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
</body>
