<html>

<head>
<title>SP 06/12/96 Sweeney ILO</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h3 align=center>John J. Sweeney<br>
President, AFL-CIO</h3>
<h1 align=center>Ministerial Conference<br>
International Labor Organization</h1>
<h2 align=center>Geneva, Switzerland<br>
June 12, 1996</h2>
<p>I am proud to be here with the International Labor Organization. For more than three-quarters of a 
century, the ILO has brought together business, unions, and government to improve the conditions 
of life and labor throughout the world. </p>
<p>The insight that guided the ILO at its founding in 1919 is just as true today, at the dawning of the 
information age, as it was 77 years ago, at the height of the industrial age. </p>
<p>That timeless insight is this: The best way to promote world peace is to advance the cause of 
economic security and social justice, not only in the most prosperous societies but everywhere on 
this planet. </p>
<p>I am here today, on behalf of the more than 13 million men and women of the American labor 
movement, to speak for a cause that is very much in the spirit of the history and heritage of the 
ILO. I am here to urge the ILO to adopt a convention to ban child labor in its most dangerous, 
degrading, and exploitative forms. </p>
<p>The problem we must address is part of the central issue facing humanity as we hurtle into the 
global economy of the 21st Century. </p>
<p>At a time when new technologies allow investment to cross national borders with a keystroke on a 
computer, where capital can shop the world for the least expensive and most vulnerable workers, 
we must make sure that we continue to honor our human values -- the dignity of working men and 
women and our dreams for our children. </p>
<p>We must not allow international economic competition to degenerate into a race to the bottom 
where we sacrifice the standards under which most people live and labor on the altar of private 
profit for a privileged few. </p>
<p>Truly, the challenge of our times is to make sure that every man, woman, and child can benefit and 
not suffer from the new opportunities of global trade and advanced technology. It is in this larger 
context that I ask you to address the problem of child labor. </p>
<p>Throughout the world, an estimated two hundred million children are at work -- and too many of 
them work under conditions that should move us to shame, to anger, and to action. </p>
<p>Let me make clear what I don't mean when I'm talking about exploitation: I'm not talking about 
young people who work after school. And I'm not talking about young people who work alongside 
their parents, on farms, or in stores, or family businesses. </p>
<p>I am talking about children working in the fields and factories, in the mines and mills -- sometimes 
even in bondage or in brothels. </p>
<p>I am talking about a system of child labor that distorts and degrades an entire society. Where 
children are cheated out of their childhoods, denied even the most basic education, and sent out, 
often at an early age, to difficult and dangerous work at pitifully low wages. Where most grown 
men and women may have a hard time finding work because employers would rather hire and 
exploit their sons and daughters. And where a fortunate few are enriched by the sweated labor of 
young boys and girls who can look forward to nothing better than virtual servitude for their entire 
lives. </p>
<p>Those of us here today cannot plead ignorance of this problem. We know the horrors: Children as 
young as four, working fifteen hours a day, seven days a week. Children scrambling for food, 
drugged so that they can work longer and faster, bent and cowed and crippled. Treated as chattel, 
these children are dying from overwork, accidents, and starvation. </p>
<p>And all this happens in spite of good intentions that have too often failed to produce effective 
actions. Despite formal prohibitions against child labor in almost every country, despite laws, 
conventions, studies, documents, seminars, and despite the good works of the ILO and 
innumerable organizations, the problem persists. </p>
<p>That is why we must all do better. The responsibility must not fall on the shoulders of parents in the 
poorest countries. As the ILO has always understood, the responsibility rests with business, labor, 
and governments throughout the world -- and with the leaders of the world community, gathered in 
meetings such as this one. </p>
<p>Let me speak as a citizen of the United States and as the leader of our labor federation, the 
AFL-CIO. </p>
<p>Child labor has been -- and, shamefully, still is -- a problem in the United States, within our own 
borders and especially in the actions beyond our borders of multinational corporations 
headquartered in our country. </p>
<p>I freely admit that business, labor, and government in our </p>
<p>country need to do more, but I am also here to say that many of us are redoubling our efforts. 
Under the leadership of President Clinton and Secretary Reich, the U.S. government is taking 
action against sweatshops and child labor in our own country. And they are beginning to hold U.S. 
companies accountable for the actions of their contractors at home and abroad. A growing number 
of U.S. companies -- although not nearly enough -- are answering the call to corporate 
responsibility. </p>
<p>As for our labor movement, we are fighting on every front. The American labor movement is 
working with the ILO, the ICFTU, the international trade secretariats, the Child Labor Coalition, 
and many more labor, human rights, children's rights, and religious groups to end the exploitation of 
children worldwide. We work with business and government as we challenge them to do more. </p>
<p>And let me speak also as a citizen of the world. </p>
<p>Sometimes, we are told that it is a kind of &quot;cultural imperialism&quot; for working people in prosperous 
countries to call for the abolition of child labor. As it happens, the members of our movement have 
their origins in every continent, every country, and every culture on the face of this earth. </p>
<p>We know of no culture or creed that tolerates the exploitation of children. We know of no culture 
or creed that teaches that children should lose their health, their promise, and their innocence 
laboring in the mines and mills. We know of no culture that holds that the proper place for children 
to spend their days is not in schools but in sweatshops. </p>
<p>It is not our oldest traditions that produce this injustice but the demands of the modern 
marketplace, untamed by the values and standards that humanity has developed over the ages. If 
there is anything that is universal to the human race and inspired by our Creator is our love for our 
children and our willingness to do whatever is necessary to guard their safety and nurture their 
promise. That is the cause we must serve in our deliberations here today. </p>
<p>And we are also told that setting standards against child labor would benefit some economies 
against others. The truth is: At the dawn of the Information Age, no economy on earth benefits from 
exploiting, rather than educating, its children. No economy on earth benefits from impoverishing its 
working men and women. In the race to the bottom, there are no winners -- only losers. </p>
<p>Yes, we will hear arguments that it is not feasible or expedient to set standards which prohibit the 
most dangerous and exploitative forms of child labor. These arguments are familiar - - and so are 
the refutations -- for this battle has been fought in every society that enters the industrial age, as well 
as in worldwide forums such as this one. </p>
<p>At this meeting -- and at this moment in history -- it is our responsibility to make sure that we do 
the right thing and not just the easy thing. That is what every honored heritage on earth would have 
us do -- and what the mission and tradition of the ILO call up us to do. We must make sure that 
working men and women and their children throughout the world do not enter the 21st Century 
burdened by the injustices of the 19th Century. </p>
<p>Thank you very much.</p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="/publ/publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
