<html>
<head>
<title>SP 06/03/96 Sweeney to The New School for Social Research</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<h1 align="center">THE LABOR MOVEMENT IN `96 -- THE NEW ACTIVISM</h1>
<h2 align="center">JOHN J. SWEENEY<br>
PRESIDENT OF THE AFL-CIO<br>
THE NEW SCHOOL FOR SOCIAL RESEARCH</h2>
<p align="center">JUNE 3, 1996 </p>
<p>Thank you, Dean Krauskopf, for that very kind welcome and
introduction, and for the invitation to participate in this most
important discussion. </p>
<p>It is, as always, both a pleasure and an inspiration to come
home to New York City. </p>
<p>A pleasure and an inspiration because coming home again makes
even more vivid the wonderful memories I have of growing up here. </p>
<p>And because it also makes even more vivid the lessons about
life and the meaning and value of work that I first learned here. </p>
<p>Those lessons are still valid, and still vivid in a city where
Wall Street and Park Avenue and Harlem and Chinatown and the
garment district and Flatbush and Forest Hills and the South
Bronx and Carnarsie and Staten Island are in reality little more
than a brisk walking distance from each other. </p>
<p>New York is where my family built a new life in a new land.
Where I got my education and my start in the labor movement. And
where, last fall, I gained the honor and privilege of leading the
national labor federation, the AFL-CIO. </p>
<p>My father was an Irish immigrant, a New York City bus driver
and a proud member of the Transport Workers Union. </p>
<p>Some of my earliest memories are of going to union meetings
with him, where we'd listen to Mike Quill explain paycheck
economics to workers and their families. </p>
<p>In those years after World War II, working people, business
people, and public officials shared a certain understanding -- a
&quot;social compact.&quot; </p>
<p>Working people knew that if they did their jobs, the
businesses which employed them would prosper, and they could earn
a better life for themselves and a better chance for their
children. </p>
<p>Business people knew that if they paid their workers fairly
and plowed some of their profits back into their communities,
they could count on loyal employees, and loyal consumers. They
understood that good citizenship is good business. </p>
<p>And government officials understood that a compact between
business and labor, in which each side contributed to the well-
being of the other, was good for the society as a whole. This was
the proof that, as President Kennedy put it, &quot;a rising tide
lifts all boats.&quot; </p>
<p>That social compact held despite the differences between us
and the bumps along the way, and produced a tremendous increase
in the standard of living for millions and millions of Americans,
not just a fortunate few. That was the reason that, when things
went broke, we fixed them -- together. </p>
<p>It was a social compact that produced the strongest economy,
the largest middle class, and the most successful society the
world has ever seen. </p>
<p>Now, however, the stresses of global economic competition in
the era after the oil shocks of the 1970s, of the new
technologies and of the deregulation of the domestic economies
have led some to think that the way for businesses to compete is
to shred that compact, to use workers up and then throw them
away. </p>
<p>That is the reason we are in a crisis today. </p>
<p>It is both a real crisis and a crisis of confidence. </p>
<p>It is a real crisis because of where a growing number of
American workers -- whether they wear a blue collar, or white
collar, or no collar -- find themselves in an economy that has
lost respect for workers and the jobs they do. </p>
<p>The impact on American workers and on their communities which
has resulted from that loss of respect, that shredding of the
social compact was achingly evident in the extraordinary
seven-part series the New York Times published in March called
&quot;The Downsizing of America.&quot; </p>
<p>That series told a large part of the story of the American
worker today: of people who want to work and want to contribute,
and who have wonderful, profitable ideas to contribute to their
companies, and to the society as a whole . . . people who have
suddenly found themselves bereft. </p>
<p>But the desperate straits a growing number of American workers
find themselves in -- and their courageous efforts to hold on to
a faith in the future -- was actually foreshadowed more than a
year earlier in a prophetic article in the Times in January of
1995. </p>
<p>There Lou Uchitelle wrote: </p>
<blockquote>
    <p>Something is wrong with America's economic boom. After
    four years of ever-stronger growth, people's wages should be
    going up faster than their expenses. For most people, they're
    not, and this is the first time in decades that a recovery
    has gone on so long without putting more money in more
    pockets. </p>
</blockquote>
<p>In fact, workers' wages and health benefits and pension
security have lagged far behind the large productivity gains made
in American business since 1980, creating a sense of unease and
outright fear of the future among many Americans who are
employed, and a sense of desperation among that growing number of
other workers who have already been laid off, or
&quot;downsized&quot; -- workers who are running out of money,
running out of options, and running out of hope. </p>
<p>While many workers in both groups have exhausted their savings
and are loaded with debt -- despite working two and sometimes
three jobs -- they see the stock market soaring and company
profits roaring, and they wonder, &quot;Who the hell is getting
my share?&quot; </p>
<p>The asking of that haunting question by more and more workers
has produced the widespread free-floating anger against and
distrust of government that is at the heart of the crisis of
confidence in American society. It is a question which reveals
how deep the connection is between having a decent job and
feeling oneself a citizen of the United States of America. </p>
<p>We should not think that the crisis of confidence in our
political system and the crisis in the American workplace are not
related -- that the latter is not at least partly a result of the
growing inequality in opportunity and compensation in the
workplace. </p>
<p>Some people say this inequality is okay. </p>
<p>Some politicians and business leaders today advocate an
atomized, divided society, one in which the rule is a war of all
against all. They offer a world where security belongs to those
who can buy it. Where hard work and loyalty are merely weaknesses
to be exploited by the quick and well-connected. Where the only
hope offered to the downsized is the chance to hate those even
less well off. </p>
<p>But we cannot give in to a short-sighted economic strategy
motivated by individual and corporate greed. </p>
<p>American workers cannot afford it. </p>
<p>America cannot afford it. </p>
<p>As President of the AFL-CIO, I stand with many others in
offering a humane and profitable alternative to the noxious ideas
of the apostles of downsizing and the apologists for the low-wage
economy. </p>
<p>I offer the idea of a corporate economy guided by the proven
truth that a productive partnership produces greater stability
and greater profitability in the long term for companies and for
the economy as a whole. </p>
<p>I propose an economy made up of companies that give workers
tangible, positive incentives to produce to their maximum
efforts. </p>
<p>An economy where workers and other consumers can feel a sense
of loyalty to American companies -- loyalty that translates into
the purchase of those companies' products -- because all are
contributing to the strengthening of American society. </p>
<p>Remember that consumer spending has always made up about
two-thirds of the American economy. What kind of shape is the
American economy going to be in if American consumers don't have
the wherewithal to spend! </p>
<p>When companies squeeze the last possible ounce of productivity
out of their workers, and then throw them on the scrap-heap of
unemployment or old age, with reduced pensions and health
coverage . . . who else are they hurting? </p>
<p><strong>This is a case where what goes around is going to come
around! </strong></p>
<p>Only a healthy American economy that raises workers and
consumers up can sustain the long-run profitability companies
need and the prosperity America needs. </p>
<p>The facts which have produced this crisis are stark and deeply
worrisome. Many of you already know them as well as I do. </p>
<p>But let me cite a few of them before I discuss some of the
things we in the AFL-CIO are doing and intend to do in order to
arrest the disruption of the American economy and the downward
slide of American workers and their families: </p>
<ul>
    <li>Corporate profits rose 64 percent from 1989 to 1995, to a
        45-year high, according to Business Week. And executive
        compensation is up 400 percent since 1980. But workers'
        wages and health benefits and pension security are way
        down. </li>
    <li>Since 1995 workers' wages have increased only 2.8
        percent, in contrast to productivity, which has gone up
        3.4 percent. </li>
    <li>Between 1947 and 1973, the median paychecks of American
        workers more than doubled -- and the bottom 20 percent
        enjoyed the biggest gains. But since 1973 median earnings
        have fallen by about 15 percent, and the bottom 20
        percent have fallen the furthest behind. More than 40
        percent of all earnings gains have gone to the richest 1
        percent of the American population. </li>
    <li>Meanwhile, wealth has become even more concentrated. The
        top 20 percent of all households now control more than 55
        percent of all wealth. The rest of us -- the 80 percent
        -- get to split the rest. Yet, the Republicans in
        Congress showed in the recent battle to -- finally --
        increase the minimum wage that they believe that those
        least well-off should continue to bear the greatest
        financial burden in the society. </li>
    <li>Henry Ford used to say that he wanted to pay his workers
        enough to afford the cars They were building. Well, in
        the last 10 years the average price of a car has jumped
        70 percent, while family incomes have climbed only 40
        percent! </li>
</ul>
<p>And there are even more dangerous developments at work in the
American workplace. </p>
<p>One has to do with the growing gap the Dunlop Commission found
in the earnings of American workers who constitute the high wage
skilled workers and those who make up the increasing `underclass'
of low paid labor. </p>
<p>This `underclass,' it should be noted, is not some small
minority of the workforce. Rather, it actually includes all
workers whose formal education ended with high school -- which is
a majority of the American workforce! The wages of high school
educated workers have been in free fall for the past two decades
-- with the result that one in five full-time full-year workers
in America today earns wages below the poverty level -- a 50
percent increase since 1979. </p>
<p>A second worrisome development is the trends which have much
more sharply divided the workforce into four, identifiable
groups: </p>
<ul>
    <li>&quot;core, skilled workers,&quot; </li>
    <li>&quot;peripheral, skilled workers&quot; -- a group which
        includes both those who are skilled but work on a
        contingent or temporary basis, such as lawyers, nurses,
        accountants and other professionals who are unable to
        find permanent employment -- and those who are unskilled. </li>
    <li>&quot;unskilled, core workers&quot; such as hotel bellmen
        and maids, and dishwashers and waiters, and </li>
    <li>&quot;unskilled peripheral workers&quot; -- a category
        which includes taxi drivers, and office-cleaning workers,
        and many temporary and part-time employees. </li>
</ul>
<p>Representing each one of these groups -- and all of them do
need representation -- raises its own set of challenges for the
labor movement. </p>
<p>But let me end this particular focus on statistics by citing
some from a poll conducted by the Times-Mirror organization late
last year. </p>
<p>Their survey found that 66 percent of Americans were concerned
about being able to pay for health care if a family member gets
sick . . . that 57 percent were concerned that their children
will not have good job opportunities . . . that 48 percent were
worried they wouldn't have enough money for retirement . . . that
44 percent worried that they would not have enough to afford
college . . . that 34 percent were worried about losing their job
or having to take a cut in pay. </p>
<p>All of those numbers were up 6 and 7 percent from March of
1994. </p>
<p>These are not the measures of a society brimming with
confidence. </p>
<p>Instead, these survey results show that working Americans know
that an economy like this won't work for long. A lot of the
run-up in stock prices seems to be based on the expectation that
our economy is structurally in a downward wage spiral that will
keep putting more money in investors' pockets forever. The
markets seem to be calculating that working people will just keep
on producing more and more for less and less pay. </p>
<p>But American workers and those with common sense know better.
They know that an economy where growth is not shared will soon
collapse upon itself. </p>
<p>The American worker's problem is stagnant wages -- America
needs a raise! </p>
<p>And the solution is a larger, stronger, smarter labor
movement, one that forcefully articulates and works to achieve
the idea that the common path to long-term value -- for
companies, for workers, for the nation itself -- lies in the
investment in those things which benefit the common good. </p>
<p>It lies in the re-building of a partnership between workers
and owners based on mutual respect, cooperation, and gain. </p>
<p>So we in the labor movement will reach out to management --
from a position of strength --because that is the only way we can
build a stronger, high-wage economy. </p>
<p>We will tell management that they -- and we -- need to follow
the examples of workers and their unions in companies and
government agencies and school systems across the country who are
winning a voice in improving the products they make and the
services they deliver. </p>
<p>That is the way to avoid foolish and shortsighted management
policies </p>
<p>And the AFL-CIO is going to work to increase the incentives
for business to do that by challenging the climate of hostility
to the American worker in the political arena. </p>
<p>We are mounting a campaign of unprecedented scale to involve
working families in the governance of this nation. This year, as
I announced earlier this spring and as Republican operatives in
Washington have often repeated and twisted, we are going to spend
$35 million dollars providing information and education around
the issues that affect working people's lives and our children's
futures. That's more than three times what we've ever spent. </p>
<p>But it's not going to candidates. And it's not going to
political parties. It's going to educate and motivate our members
and other working families. And it includes our new national
political training institute, which is already recruiting and
training political organizers, campaign managers and candidates. </p>
<p>Every union is going to do its share by contributing ideas,
money, and staff so that we can work to identify candidates who
stand with working people -- and more importantly, so that we can
build a base of working people who hold elected officials,
regardless of party, accountable for insuring that workers'
rights and values be represented properly in our national debate. </p>
<p>Most of all, the AFL-CIO is going to work for the American
worker by rebuilding our labor movement . . . by pouring vast
resources into organizing new members, from the Sun Belt to the
Rust Belt, and from software writers to sweatshop workers. </p>
<p>We are going to reach out to unorganized workers -- because
that is the only way we can build a stronger movement. For too
long, too many unions have been satisfied with a shrinking
membership base. As our membership strength has declined, so has
our bargaining power. </p>
<p>It used to be that strong unions lifted all workers up. Now,
non-union employees are dragging all workers down. </p>
<p>Yes, the truth is, our weakness encouraged employers to take
the low road. Only by rebuilding our strength can we bring
American business back to the high road of high wages. </p>
<p>That's why I have challenged every union and every level of
our labor movement to do what the fastest-growing unions do: Put
at least 30 percent of your resources into organizing. That is
why we are training at least a thousand organizers a year, and
pouring $20 million into organizing programs. </p>
<p>Our message to the American worker is simple, but powerful:
Whether you wear a blue collar, a white collar, a new collar, or
no collar, we can help you make your job better. </p>
<p>And our message to the American people is simple, too: This is
the way to build a better, stronger economy and a better,
stronger America. An America that honors work and rewards
workers. <strong>ALL its workers. </strong></p>
<p>Thank you.</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../index.htm">Public Documents Page</a> | <a
href="../publsear.htm">Public Documents Search</a></p>
