<html>
<head>
<title>SP 06/03/96 Sweeney at Conference on Prospects for a
Global Economy</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<h2 align="center">Remarks by John J. Sweeney<br>
President of the AFL-CIO</h2>
<h1 align="center">Conference on Prospects for a Global Economy</h1>
<h2 align="center">Boston College<br>
June 3, 1996</h2>
<p>I've been asked to give a workers' perspective on SOURCES OF
AND SOLUTIONS TO UNCERTAINTY, so I'll start with
&quot;sources.&quot; Workers believe, quite simply, that business
and government are the sources, that they've conspired to create
a wage and wealth gap that's eating away at the economic and
social fabric of our nation. </p>
<p>In a large national poll taken this spring by the AFL-CIO, we
asked a cross section of workers, union and non-union, what they
believed to be the root cause of their economic problems. Out of
12 possible causes, 70 percent of the respondents ranked
&quot;corporations have become too greedy&quot; number one. </p>
<p>The poll further showed that the vast majority of workers
believe companies aren't loyal to their employees and that
companies are choosing to boost short-term profits, stock prices
and executive salaries at the expense of their employees. Only 29
percent believe American companies are squeezing more
productivity out of workers, downsizing and outsourcing because
they're &quot;doing what they have to do&quot; to compete in the
global economy. </p>
<p>In the same poll, workers fingered government as the second
culprit behind an economy that is making some people rich, while
causing others to work two and three jobs and put more and more
family members to work just to survive. They believe government
is taking too much in taxes from working families, allowing too
much speculation and too many corporate takeovers, not making the
wealthy pay their fair share of taxes, not demanding a level
playing field in trade and not fixing the health care system. </p>
<p>There are those in business and in government who would have
us think these are only perceptions, the result of media hype
about a wage and wealth gap that really doesn't exist and,
therefore, couldn't have been caused by either government or
business. But, based on my visits with workers all across this
country, I believe these attitudes are correct reflections of
reality. The only thing that surprises me is that workers are not
more critical, given the 10, 15 and 20 years of punishment
they've endured. We can't begin to address the question of
&quot;solutions to uncertainty&quot; until we understand the
bleak economic realities faced by average-wage Americans. </p>
<p>In the early 1970s, business was forced to find new ways to
compete in a new world marketplace and for the most part they
decided to do so not by American team-work and American know-how,
but by driving down labor costs. Government did its share of
picking workers' pockets with 12 years of Reaganomics --- massive
tax giveaways to wealthy taxpayers and to big corporations that
created a budget deficit that is now being used as justification
for cuts in safety nets, wage standards and income protections
working people depend on most. </p>
<p>The result? A radical redistribution of incomes and wealth.
Over the past 20 years, 97 percent of the income increase in our
country went to the top 20 percent of wage earners. </p>
<p>The gap between the rich and everyone else keeps getting wider
--- the top 10 percent now control almost 68 percent of the
wealth. Since 1980, productivity went up 24 percent, and American
workers should have been able to enjoy a significant increase in
purchasing power. Instead, the productivity was converted into
increases in corporate profits, which went up 200 percent between
1980 and 1995, and into executive compensation, which is up 400
percent. </p>
<p>For the past five years, our economy has been
&quot;recovering.&quot; But the recovery hasn't reached workers.
Working families have little money to spend, they are loaded with
debt and they have NO TIME to spend with their children or their
families. They are threatened by downsizing, pension raids,
outsourcing and runaway plants and their anger is exceeded only
by anxiety over keeping their jobs. </p>
<p>&quot;Economic uncertainty&quot; and &quot;economic
insecurity&quot; are terms now being used to describe the mood of
working America, and they suggest that most Americans are doing
pretty well, but somehow unsure of their future. The truth is
that working Americans are insecure, and angry, not because of
perceptions, but because of the harsh reality that our nation has
lost respect for workers and the jobs they do. </p>
<p>Our problem: America needs a raise --- people can't spend
money or save money unless they HAVE money. The solution: we need
to find new ways to grow the American economy, American
companies, and American wages in the new world economy. And to
bridge the growing gap between the great majority of Americans
who are working longer and harder for less and the fortunate few
who are prospering as never before. </p>
<p>The solutions needed from labor: we have to grow ourselves, on
a massive scale, because we can no longer afford the luxury of
pretending that productivity, quality, and competitiveness are
not our business. They are our business, our jobs, and our
paychecks. We must gain a voice in improving the products we
make, the services we deliver and in the decisions that affect
our futures and our families. </p>
<p>The solutions needed from business: take more of your profits
and invest them in American workers. Offer them the training they
need for tomorrow's jobs. Work with your employees and their
unions. Give them a voice in decision-making. Give them half a
chance to improve the quality of your goods and services. That is
the path to lasting prosperity. And Put some money in their
pockets so they can buy your refrigerators, and mobile homes. </p>
<p>The solutions needed from government: restore some sanity to a
tax code that has reduced taxes on millionaires by one-third over
the past 15 years while raising taxes by a similar amount on
middle-income Americans. Put an end to corporate welfare. Put
some new fences around the Wall Street wizards who are operating
dangerously beyond the fringe of current regulation. Reform
health care so we can begin to control costs. And raise our
paltry minimum wage to $5.15 an hour! </p>
<p>What do workers say we need to do? Workers think business
needs to abide by simple rules, that they shouldn't replace full-
time jobs with part-time no-benefit jobs, or lay off thousands of
workers when they are making a good profit. </p>
<p>They think government should make some new rules that
encourage companies to invest in America instead of shipping jobs
overseas and that guarantee fair trade, where countries that sell
products here also open their markets to us and agree to basic
human rights and worker protections. New rules that level a
playing field on which employers today hold the upper hand. </p>
<p>These are common-sense solutions and they would go a long way
toward closing the wage and wealth gap and putting us back on a
track of prospering together. </p>
<p align="center">Thank you very much.</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../index.htm">Public Documents Page</a> | <a
href="../publsear.htm">Public Documents Search</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
</body>
