<html>

<head>
<title>SP 05/13/96 Sweeney to Presidential Emergency Board</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p align=center>Remarks by AFL-CIO President John J. Sweeney<br>
</p>
<h1 align=center>Presidential Emergency Board 228</h1>
<p align=center><br>
</p>
<h2 align=center>May 13, 1996</h2>
<p>Thank you, Bob. I appreciate the opportunity to appear before the members of the Presidential 
Emergency Board today, and I especially appreciate the opportunity to speak on behalf of the rail 
workers represented by TCU. </p>
<p>As Bob noted, this is, to my knowledge, the first time in history that a President of the AFL-CIO 
has appeared before a Presidential Emergency Board on behalf of a rail union. I do not do this 
lightly. A fair settlement of the issues facing our nation's transportation industry workers will 
reverberate far beyond TCU's 30,000 affected members. </p>
<p>TCU's negotiations with the railroad industry are a microcosm of what's happening to American 
workers everywhere. </p>
<p>The issues that will be brought before you -- declining real wages, jobs lost to outsourcing, attacks 
on workers' health insurance -- are the same issues bedeviling all of American workers. </p>
<p>The workers I talk with as I travel around the country are desperate for some re-balancing of the 
scales. They are filled with a profound sense that things are badly out of kilter -- that America 
doesn't work for them anymore. </p>
<p>Things weren't always this way. For nearly 30 years after winning World War II, businesses and 
workers enjoyed a kind of social compact. We all prospered because we prospered together. </p>
<p>Here's what working people knew back then: if we worked hard and played by the rules, we could 
count on a better life for ourselves and a better future for our children. </p>
<p>Here's what business knew: if they paid their workers fairly and plowed some of their profits back 
into their communities, they could count on loyal employees and loyal consumers. </p>
<p>That social compact was a formula for the strongest economy, the largest middle class, and the 
most successful society this world has ever known. </p>
<p>A lot has changed since then: global economic competition . . . new technologies, and more. </p>
<p>But those changes spawned another, bigger threat: too many employers have discarded any sense 
of loyalty or respect for their employees. </p>
<p>It is the #1 theme I hear from workers . . . &quot;No loyalty&quot;. . . &quot;No respect&quot; . . . even when companies 
and their top executives are doing very well. Employees are treated like expenses on a balance 
sheet -- instead of assets to be invested in. </p>
<p>And the #1 answer workers give to the question of what is wrong with the economy is corporate 
greed. </p>
<p>The result is that at a time when productivity is up, when profits have soared to a forty year high, 
and when executive compensation has risen to obscene levels, wages and benefits for most 
workers are stagnant or declining. </p>
<p>Workers have no money to spend, no time to spend with their families, and they are loaded with 
debt. </p>
<p>That is a recipe for economic and social disaster. And that is why the AFL-CIO and our 13.1 
million members are taking the message of &quot;America Needs A Raise&quot; to communities across this 
country. </p>
<p>Nowhere is the disparity between the fortunes of executives and shareholders on the one hand and 
workers on the other more glaring than in the railroad industry. </p>
<p>When CEO compensation climbs 50 percent and rail profits charge up 78 percent since 1990 -- 
while workers' real wages decline 10 percent -- it is simply wrong. </p>
<p>When Drew Lewis, the CEO of Union Pacific, makes 335 times what a TCU worker on Union 
Pacific makes --as he did in 1994 -- it is simply wrong. </p>
<p>Rail shareholders have enjoyed the gravy train -- they've seen their rail stocks double in value since 
1990. </p>
<p>The only ones who haven't shared in the railroad renaissance are the workers who made it 
possible. They have not only seen their real wages decline, they have also suffered drastic cuts in 
their employment levels, as jobs have been lost to outsourcing, technology, and merger mania. </p>
<p>That is why this Board is so critically important -- to TCU, its members and workers throughout 
this country. You have the power to redress these wrongs. </p>
<p>Frankly, this forum is not of our choosing. We would have preferred to see this dispute settled 
through traditional collective bargaining. </p>
<p>There is no doubt in my mind that if TCU were permitted to exert economic pressure -- to strike 
these railroads -- we would not be here today. This contract would have been settled long ago. </p>
<p>That is because TCU's demands are not pie in the sky. They are measured, reasonable requests for 
across the board percentage wage increases, instead of lump sums, from an industry that can easily 
afford them. </p>
<p>I know Bob Scardelletti. He is not unreasonable. His whole history has been to negotiate 
agreements. He led the way in this round of rail bargaining by making an agreement with the only 
Class I railroad -- Illinois Central -- willing to negotiate in good faith. </p>
<p>But the railroads in this room represent the worst aspect of America's corporate greed culture. 
They have cynically manipulated the fact that their industry has such strategic economic importance 
that the government will not allow a strike of duration to occur. </p>
<p>Thus insulated from any economic pressure, they have refused to bargain in good faith, secure that 
the worst that can happen is they'd wind up -- a year and a half after bargaining began -- before a 
panel such as this one. </p>
<p>They remember what happened last time, in 1991, when they testified with a straight face before 
Presidential Emergency Board 219 that their industry was on the verge of economic collapse and 
they needed to hold the line on workers' wages. PEB 219 bought their bill of goods -- yet every 
economic prediction the railroads made has since been proved wrong. The recommendations of 
that last Board are a major part of the story as to why rail workers have been the only economic 
casualty in the railroads' prosperity. </p>
<p>The railroads are counting on history repeating itself. But you have the opportunity to leave a 
different history. </p>
<p>You are in a unique position. Even Wall Street is now publishing articles about the imbalance 
between corporate profits and workers' wages. </p>
<p>Politicians of every stripe are suddenly discovering the plight of America's middle class. They are 
talking about it. You can do something about it. </p>
<p align=center>You have the power to send a message: &quot;America needs a raise.&quot; I urge you to send that message. 
I urge you to recommend TCU's contract proposals as the basis on which to settle this dispute. 
Thank you.</p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="/publ/publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
</body>

