<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3O/DTD HTML//EN">

<html>
<head>
<title>SP 04/26/96 Sweeney at OSHA 25th Anniversary Event</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<h2 align="center">Remarks by AFL-CIO President John J. Sweeney</h2>
<h1 align="center">OSHA 25th Anniversary Event<br>
Friday, April 26, 1996</h1>
<p>Mr. Secretary, Vice President Gore . . . </p>
<p>I was lucky to be able to spend a little time earlier this
morning with the workers and family members here with us. They
are from a diverse group of occupations and states: Mississippi,
West Virginia, North Carolina, Pennsylvania, Minnesota, Indiana,
Kansas, Maryland, Ohio, Virginia, D.C., New York, Oklahoma,
Vermont, and New Hampshire. </p>
<p>But they share a common message: the Occupational Health and
Safety Act is one of the most important laws ever passed for
working people. Workplaces are safer. Fewer people die on the
job. Fewer people are injured. But it's still not enough. </p>
<p>The working men and women here, like too many working people
across our nation, have had their lives turned upside down by
jobs that are unsafe. Some have lost the use of limbs; many have
lost jobs and income. </p>
<p>We still have construction workers like carpenter Ron Taylor
who lost his job this month after he suffered respiratory damage
from toxic fumes. We still have workers like Jackie Whittaker
whose life was dramatically altered by a mine explosion. Workers
like James Haynes, tragically disabled by a contruction accident.
And workers like David Cain, whose wife Jamie can tell of the
horror of the burns David suffered from an unsafe job -- David is
still in critical condition in a Pittsburgh hospital. We still
have deaths from lung cancer caused by exposure to radioactive
materials -- Corrilla Kelly, widow of machinist Herb Kelly, can
speak volumes about that loss. </p>
<p>And there is a whole host of new problems we haven't even
begun to attack. Repetitive stress injuries like carpal tunnel
syndrome cripple hundreds of thousands of workers each year, as
Josephine Smith, Marie Torres, Martha Edmonds, and Betty Green
can testify. And workplace assaults are claiming more casualties
every year, as nurse Mark Allen and social worker Marcia Stulbaum
can tell you. In the service sector, where I come from, injuries
and illnesses continue to mount. Nursing homes are now one of the
most dangerous industries in America. </p>
<p>All this is documented in this new report from the AFL-CIO
that tells the story of the last 25 years in health and safety in
facts and figures. </p>
<p>We know the basic law works, but we know it needs to work even
better. </p>
<p>Yet we have spent the last year and a half fighting a
relentless attack by Congressional Republicans, at the behest of
their corporate allies, who want to weaken the law and take us
back in time. </p>
<p>The Clinton administration has stood its ground and vowed to
veto any legislation that would weaken job safety laws. </p>
<p>When the OSHA law was passed, this nation made a commitment
that every worker has the right to a safe job. That's a promise
worth keeping. And working families across America thank and
commend you, Secretary Reich, and you, Vice President Gore, for
committing not only to honor this promise, but to strengthen it. </p>
<p>Thank you.</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../index.htm">Public Documents Page</a> | <a
href="../publsear.htm">Public Documents Search</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
</body>
