<html>
<head>
<title>SP 04/12/96 Renewing the Social Contract Forum</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<h3 align="center">Remarks by John J. Sweeney<br>
President of the AFL-CIO</h3>
<h1 align="center">Renewing the Social Contract Forum</h1>
<h2 align="center">Minneapolis, MN<br>
April 12, 1996<br>
</h2>
<p>Thank you for, Congressman Sabo, for that cordial introduction
and for inviting me here to speak on behalf of American workers
and their families. </p>
<p>And thank you for continuing to be a beacon of hope for social
justice in a United States Congress that has grown stormy and
dark with the politics of greed and hatred. </p>
<p>By hosting this event here today, you have once again
demonstrated the kind of leadership that is going to bring us
through these troubling waters and once again into the sunshine -
- and the entire labor movement thanks you. </p>
<p>Likewise, I'd like to recognize the terrific leadership being
shown here in Minnesota by our state federation president, Bernie
Brommer, as well as by Kristine Jacobs of the Minnesota Now
Coalition and Chuck Collins of Share the Wealth. If we could
recreate this kind of partnership in every state in the country,
it wouldn't be long before we took our country back. </p>
<p>I am grateful for the chance to speak today on the subject of
&quot;Renewing the Social Contract&quot; because I am a product
of that contract -- one that lifted America out of the Great
Depression and lifted working Americans into the middle class. </p>
<p>My father was an Irish immigrant, a New York City bus driver,
and a proud member of the Transport Workers Union. My earliest
memories are of going with him to union meetings and listening to
Mike Quill explain checkbook economics in his thick Irish brogue.
My father lived and worked in tough times. </p>
<p>But working people, business people, and public officials
shared certain understandings -- a social contract, if you will. </p>
<p>Here's what working people knew: If we got up every morning
and did our jobs, then we could earn a better life for ourselves
and a better chance for our children. </p>
<p>Here's what business people knew: If they paid their workers
fairly and plowed some of their profits back into their
communities, they could count on loyal employees and loyal
consumers. </p>
<p>For companies back then, good citizenship was good business.
And here's what our leaders in government understood -- and
President Kennedy said it best: &quot;A rising tide lifts all
boats.&quot; </p>
<p>For almost 30 years after winning World War II, we all
prospered because we prospered together. We were concerned with
raising the standard of living for all Americans -- not just
accumulating enormous wealth for a fortunate few. That social
contract was a formula for the strongest economy, the largest
middle class, and the most successful society this world has ever
known. </p>
<p>In the early 1970s, however, we began drifting from our
course. The oil embargo . . . global competition . . . new
technologies . . . and deregulation of the domestic economy --
all these put the squeeze on American business. Then business
made a fateful decision to compete, not by American team-work and
know-how, but by driving down labor costs -- by squeezing the
last possible ounce of productivity out of workers . . . then
throwing them on the scrap-heap of unemployment or old age . . .
with reduced pensions and health coverage. </p>
<p>The result? Working family incomes have declined greatly and
we now have a shocking maldistribution of wealth in this country.
Between 1947 and 1973, the median paychecks of American workers
more than doubled -- and the bottom 20 percent enjoyed the
biggest gains. But since 1973, median earnings have fallen by
about 15 percent, and the bottom 20% have fallen the furthest
behind. </p>
<p>More than 40 percent of all earnings gains have gone to the
richest one percent, and 97 percent of the income increase in our
country has gone to the top 20 percent. During the past two
decades productivity went up 24 percent, and American workers
should have been able to enjoy a substantial increase in
purchasing power. Instead, the productivity was converted into
increases in corporate profits, which went up 205 percent since
1980 and are now at an all-time high. And it was converted into
executive compensation, which is up 360 percent since 1980. While
productivity, profits, executive pay and the stock market keep
going up . . . working family incomes keep going down, widening
the gap between the rich and the rest of us. </p>
<p>Workers are having to labor harder and longer just to keep
even, and more and more family members are having to work in
order to maintain living standards. Working families have little
money to spend, they are loaded with debt and they have no time
to spend with their children. They feel threatened by
restructuring . . . downsizing . . . pension raids . . .
privatization schemes and runaway plants . . . they are disgusted
with business and government and their disillusionment is
straining the fabric of our society. And more than 12 million
workers at the bottom of the wage structure have lost hope
altogether -- victims of a federal minimum wage that in real
terms is now 25 percent below its 1981 level. </p>
<p>To add insult to injury, we've been hit this past year and a
half with an all-out assault on all the government programs and
policies that protect the standard of living for workers and
their families . . . and a safety net for the young, the old, the
poor and the disabled. Cuts in Medicare and Medicaid and student
loans. Attempts to repeal the 40-hour work week, overtime pay,
OSHA, affirmative action and Davis-Bacon. So-called
&quot;reform&quot; of welfare and the National Labor Relations
Act. All capped off with another tax cut for the rich and an
insidious movement to undermine the most successful
income-protection program in history by privatizing Social
Security. </p>
<p>Add to this witch's brew the stories we've been reading on the
business page over the past year. Mobil Oil announces big layoffs
and their stock goes up. Chase Manhattan and Chemical Bank
announce a merger that puts 12,000 people out of work and their
stock goes up. AT&amp;T says they plan to lay off 40,000 men and
women and their stock goes up. </p>
<p>Does a rising tide now sink all ships --- except for the
luxury yachts? </p>
<p>And what's wrong with this picture: Caterpillar is doing
great, racking up record profits, enjoying great productivity.
Instead of sharing their prosperity, they decide to squeeze a
little harder with a two-tier wage system and more work on the
weekends without paying overtime pay. They force thousands of
workers out on strike, commit 300 unfair labor practices, and
make even bigger profits. Caterpillar says it did it to stay
&quot;competitive&quot; with Komatsu. That's not true. Komatsu is
struggling with a global market share below three percent, while
Caterpillar has the lion's share. Know why? Because the United
States government has spent American tax dollars fronting them
into emerging nations in Europe, including Russia, and helping
arrange financing for their operations through the World Bank! </p>
<p>And how about this picture: over a period of nearly 50 years,
organized labor is an outright sponsor of Kaiser Permanente as a
low-cost, high-quality health plan for working families. We bring
members in by the hundreds of thousands through our Taft-Hartley
plans because Kaiser promises to buy union, build union and hire
union --- a great social contract. Then suddenly, HMOs enter a
new world of competition, similar to what corporations
encountered in the early 1970s. Kaiser decides to take the same
low-road to the bottom by slashing labor costs - -- restructuring
. . . outsourcing . . . right-sizing . . . closing hospitals and
changing patient care standards without consulting either the
plan members or the workers that deliver their care. What
happens? A huge labor-management crisis is created. We now have
30,000 AFL-CIO union members with open contracts in the HMO that
labor built. </p>
<p>I appealed personally to CEO David Lawrence for a
&quot;strategic partnership&quot; to keep Kaiser from destroying
itself and its relationship with labor. He rejected me and said
that union members would never have a say in patient care
decisions --- meaning Kaiser employees will continue to have less
input into the vital services they deliver than auto workers have
into the cars they make! </p>
<p>For American workers and their families, these are snapshots
from hell. They paint an ugly portrait of an economy that has
lost respect for workers and the jobs they do. And the captions
are written in clinical terms like outsourcing . . . downsizing .
. . right-sizing . . . and contracting out that workers now know
are code words for <em>laid off and out-of-luck.</em> </p>
<p>Corporate horror stories like these do more than disrupt the
lives of working Americans and their families. They violate our
most basic values -- and tear at the fabric of American life. </p>
<p>People who get up every day, put in a decent day's work, and
give a lifetime of loyalty to their employers have been treated
like disposable parts or plant equipment, to be trashed and
forgotten. </p>
<p>Imagine what they must tell their children when they come home
on the day they've gotten their downsizing notice: 'Your dad
worked for the company all his life . . . now, they've told me to
clean out my desk tomorrow.' </p>
<p>Imagine how hard it must be for these parents to tell their
kids that, if they study hard, work hard, and do right by their
companies and their colleagues . . . the world will do right by
them. </p>
<p>Imagine the lesson their kids must really be learning from all
this: that playing by the rules is just for fools. </p>
<p>It is time for Americans to take a look at how corporate
America is downsizing the American dream and say three simple
words: <strong>THIS IS WRONG</strong>. And seven more: <strong>WE'VE
GOT TO DO SOMETHING ABOUT THIS. </strong></p>
<p>So what can we do about it? On the most basic level, American
business must change the way it does business. There are still
responsible business people, but far too much of Corporate
America has spent the last decade going after Working America.
American labor must also change. The fact is that it takes at
least two sides to make a social compact, and that is why we are
rebuilding and revitalizing our labor movement. </p>
<p>The years when American wages stagnated are the years when our
labor movement declined from 35 percent to 16 percent of the
total work force. Here's the truth: The weakness of labor
encouraged employers to take the low road. And only by rebuilding
our strength can we bring American business back to the high road
of high wages. That is why I am challenging every union and every
level of our labor movement to do what the fastest-growing unions
do: Put at least 30 percent of our resources into organizing. </p>
<p>That is why we will be training at least a thousand organizers
a year . . . pouring millions into organizing programs . . . and
organizing from the sunbelt to the rustbelt and from health care
to high tech. That is why we are rebuilding our grassroots
political strength . . . training candidates . . . and training
political organizers. We have to be able to reach out to
business, to management -- from a position of strength -- because
that is the only way we can build a stronger, high-wage economy. </p>
<p>We can no longer afford the luxury of pretending that
productivity, quality, and competitiveness are not our business.
They are our business, our jobs, and our paychecks. </p>
<p>As America's unions become stronger and smarter, we will be in
a position to offer business a challenge: Take some of your
profits and invest them in growing the American economy, American
workers, and American wages. Offer your workers the training they
need for tomorrow's jobs -- not just the big-shots in the
executive suites -- but all your employees. </p>
<p>Work with your employees and their unions. Give us a voice in
decision-making. Give us half a chance to improve the quality of
our goods and services. That is the path to lasting prosperity -
- and we want to walk down that road with you. </p>
<p>This year, we will begin to offer these challenges not only to
the leaders of labor and business but to all Americans. </p>
<p>This month, the AFL-CIO will begin to hold a series of town
hall meetings on falling living standards in 29 communities
across the country to put the issue of wages and wealth at the
center of political debate. </p>
<p>We will listen to working men and women talk about what is
happening to their jobs, their paychecks, and their family
budgets. And we will listen to working Americans' ideas on how to
address the issues that affect our lives and our children's
futures -- together. </p>
<p>As we go through this election year and demonstrate that
working Americans are regaining our political power, we also want
to issue a few challenges to government at every level -- but
especially to the United States Congress. Restore some sanity to
a tax code that has reduced taxes on millionaires by one-third
over the past 15 years while raising taxes by a similar amount on
middle-income Americans. Put some new parameters around the Wall
Street wizards who are operating dangerously beyond the fringe of
current regulation. </p>
<p>Stop beating up on the poor, the young and the elderly. Beef
up Social Security and Medicare, don't destroy them. </p>
<p>When the Baby Boomers got ready to go to kindergarten, we
didn't tear down schools, we built more! </p>
<p>And for God's sake, honor the wishes of 83 percent of the
American people and raise our paltry minimum wage to $5.15 an
hour. </p>
<p>In every speech I give, from this forum to picket lines across
the country, I'm trying to make this simple point: America needs
a raise. And the sooner we get together and deliver one, the
better off we will be, labor and business and government alike. </p>
<p>As I travel the country, I've seen how eager working men and
women are to come together to answer the assault on their jobs
and wages. And I can tell you this: working Americans are ready
for the messages we are delivering today -- and they are ready to
come together with real leaders like Martin Sabo so he can
continue to champion the cause of working Americans and their
families. </p>
<p>Thank you very much.</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../index.htm">Public Documents Page</a> | <a
href="../publsear.htm">Public Documents Search</a></p>
