<html>
<head>
<title>SP 04/11/96 New Vigor in the Labor Movement</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<h3 align="center">Remarks by John J. Sweeney<br>
President of the AFL-CIO</h3>
<h1 align="center">New Vigor in the Labor Movement</h1>
<h2 align="center">Kennedy Library Public Forum<br>
Boston, Massachusetts<br>
April 11, 1996</h2>
<p>Thank you for this opportunity to speak on behalf of American
workers and their families. </p>
<p>I know there are many friends and allies from inside and
outside the labor movement here with us tonight. I want to thank
all of you for the support you have given Rich Trumka, Linda
Chavez-Thompson, and me as we work to create a &quot;New Voice
for American Workers.&quot; </p>
<p>On behalf of the 13.1 million members of the AFL-CIO, I would
also like to express our support for the workers who have been
locked-out at the Commonwealth Gas Company since March 31st.
Management tactics like that lock-out explain why American
workers need a labor movement with as much vigor as possible. </p>
<p>I would also like to thank one of the people who helped bring
me here, a friend and scholar of the labor movement, Professor
Barry Bluestone. </p>
<p>Tonight, I would like to make three points: First, America
owes much of its progress and prosperity to the social contract
that existed for roughly three decades after World War II. During
that era -- thanks, in large measure, to a strong labor movement
and the understandings it achieved with business and government
-- workers shared in the gains of a growing economy. Second, for
at least the past two decades, Corporate America has gone after
Working America. The result has been stagnant living standards,
increasing inequality, and the sense that our social fabric is
fraying and our political system isn't working. And, third, at
long last, working Americans are fighting back -- and finding
their voice. The labor movement is reviving itself, from
organizing drives at workplaces around the country to
long-overdue changes in national unions and in the AFL-CIO. As we
regain our strength, we will strive to create a new social
contract of shared power and shared prosperity. All this may
sound like abstract rhetoric, but I've seen these things happen
in my own life. </p>
<p>My background is similar to many families here in Boston. My
father was an Irish immigrant, a New York City bus driver, and a
proud member of the Transport Workers Union -- the TWU. </p>
<p>The union helped him win the building blocks of a decent life:
a living wage, a stable job, more vacation days, and secure
health and pension benefits. When he was able to buy a home for
our family or spend a few more days with us at the beach, he'd
say: &quot;Thank God for the union.&quot; </p>
<p>Because the union helped him climb the first few rungs on the
ladder of opportunity, he was able to see his kids go to college.
So you could say that I'm a product of the post-war social
contract that lifted America out of the Great Depression - - and
lifted working people into the middle class. </p>
<p>Here's what working people knew: If we got up every morning
and did our jobs, then we could earn a better life for ourselves
and a better chance for our children. </p>
<p>Here's what business people knew: If they paid their workers
fairly and plowed some of their profits back into their
communities, they could count on loyal employees and loyal
consumers. For companies back then, good citizenship was good
business. </p>
<p>And here's what our leaders in government understood -- and
President Kennedy said it best: &quot;A rising tide lifts all
boats.&quot; </p>
<p>For almost 30 years after winning World War II, most Americans
prospered because we prospered together. That social compact was
a formula for the strongest economy, the largest middle class,
and the most successful society this world has ever known. </p>
<p>But now, those days are gone -- long gone. </p>
<p>You know what happened: The oil embargo of 1973. Global
economic competition. New technologies. The deregulation of the
domestic economy, from transportation to communications. And the
decline of basic industries, from auto and steel to electronic
appliances. </p>
<p>It seemed that, all at once, there was a new economy, with new
rules or none at all, a few winners, and lots more losers. </p>
<p>All that is true, but the real problem is: Corporate America
made a fateful decision to compete in the new global economy, not
by American team-work and American know-how, but by driving down
labor costs. Too often, companies chose to squeeze the last
possible ounce of productivity out of American workers, then
throw them on the scrap-heap of unemployment or old age, with
reduced pensions and health coverage. </p>
<p>That is why, from 1978 through 1995, the buying power of
workers' hourly earnings fell by 12%. American families tried all
kinds of coping mechanisms. They sent husbands, wives, and teen-
age kids into the labor force. They took second and third jobs.
They went deeper into debt. But, in spite of it all, median
family income fell 5 percent between 1989 and 1994. </p>
<p>Meanwhile, the wealthiest Americans are doing better than
ever. Between 1980 and 1995, the Dow Jones Industrial Average
rose 404 percent. That provided huge payoffs for investors -- but
no wage gains for workers. </p>
<p>Corporate profits have risen 205 percent since 1980. Corporate
chief executive officers are raking in 360 more -- and now they
earn 187 times more than the average worker. And that's in spite
of the fact that workers' productivity has risen 24% since 1979
-- while their real wages fell! </p>
<p>It seems something is way out of kilter. And now, instead of
raising workers' wages, profitable corporations are wiping out
workers' jobs. </p>
<p>You've seen the stories -- and I hope you and your friends and
families haven't suffered personally. Mobil Oil announces big
layoffs and their stock goes up. Chase Manhattan and Chemical
Bank announce a merger that puts 12,000 people out of work and
their stock goes up. AT&amp;T says they plan to lay off 40,000
men and women and their stock goes up. Does a rising tide now
sink all ships --- except for the luxury yachts? </p>
<p>And what's wrong with this picture: Caterpillar is doing
great, racking up record profits, enjoying great productivity.
Instead of sharing their prosperity, they decide to squeeze a
little harder with a two-tier wage system, more work on the
weekends without paying overtime pay. They force thousands of
workers out on strike, commit 300 unfair labor practices, and
make even bigger profits. </p>
<p>Caterpillar says it did it to stay &quot;competitive&quot;
with Komatsu. That's not true. </p>
<p>Komatsu is struggling with a global market share below three
percent, while Caterpillar has the lion's share. Know why?
Because the United States government has spent American tax
dollars fronting them into emerging nations in Europe, including
Russia, and helping arrange financing for their operations
through the World Bank! </p>
<p>And how about these stories, right here in Massachusetts:
Boston City Hospital and Boston University Medical Center are
planning to merge so they can save B.C.H. through downsizing.
Last year, the people who come to work every day and take care of
desperately ill patients in these hospitals had to fight like
hell to protect the public mission of these institutions and to
get some protections for the patients and themselves. Yet, for
nine months, they've been kept totally in the dark, awaiting
specific information on the merger, just 82 days from now.
Yesterday, Mayor Menino released his plan, but refused to
guarantee &quot;no layoffs,&quot; or, in fact, job protections. </p>
<p>I guess the workers at N.E.C. Technologies just up the road in
Northboro are a little luckier --- they know they are going to
lose their jobs, 500 of them. The company says it is going to
contract out for desktop computers from a &quot;domestic
source,&quot; but the decision was &quot;driven more by global
market factors&quot; than by business costs in Massachusetts. </p>
<p>When you translate that into English, it means N.E.C. is going
to &quot;outsource&quot; from non-union manufacturers in Georgia,
rather than producing its own computers with full-time, decently-
paid union workers in Massachusetts. </p>
<p>For working families, these are snapshots from hell. They
paint an ugly portrait of an economy that has lost respect for
workers. And the captions are written in clinical terms like
outsourcing, downsizing, right-sizing and contracting-out that
workers now know are code words for &quot;laid off and
out-of-luck.&quot; </p>
<p>And corporate horror stories like these do more than disrupt
the lives of working Americans and their families. They violate
our most basic values -- and tear at the fabric of American life. </p>
<p>People who get up every day, put in a decent day_s work, and
give a lifetime of loyalty to their employers have been treated
like disposable parts or plant equipment, to be trashed and
forgotten. Imagine what they must tell their children when they
come home on the day they've gotten their downsizing notice:
&quot;Your dad worked for the company all his life . . . now,
they've told me to clean out my desk tomorrow.&quot; Imagine how
hard it must be for parents caught in this calamity to tell their
kids that, if they study hard, work hard, and do right by their
companies and their colleagues, the world will do right by them.
Imagine the lesson their kids must really be learning from all
this: that playing by the rules is just for fools. </p>
<p>It is time for Americans to take a look at how corporate
America is downsizing the American dream and say three simple
words: This is wrong. And seven more: We've got to do something
about this. </p>
<p>So what can we do about it? On the most basic level, American
business must change the way it does business. There are still
responsible business people, like Aaron Feuerstein who refused to
move his textile mill out of Methuen, Massachusetts, in search of
cheap labor. Instead, Feuerstein modernized the product line,
keeping the company profitable. </p>
<p>As you all have heard, even when his plant was destroyed by
fire last December, Feuerstein rebuilt it and continued to pay
the 2,400 employees. Hailed as a national hero, he said: &quot;I
haven't really done anything. I don't deserve credit. Corporate
America has made it so that, when you behave the way I did, it's
abnormal.&quot; </p>
<p>President Clinton, Senator Kennedy, and Labor Secretary Reich
are right: America should honor and reward responsible business
people like Aaron Feuerstein. But it takes at least two sides to
make a social compact -- and that is why we are rebuilding and
revitalizing our labor movement. </p>
<p>Here's the truth: The weakness of labor encouraged employers
to take the low road. And only by rebuilding our strength can we
bring American business back to the high road of high wages. </p>
<p>The years when American wages stagnated are the years when our
labor movement declined from 35% to 16% of the total work force
-- and only 11% of the workers in private industry. </p>
<p>To put it bluntly, that is no accident. As part of the
policies that drove down wages, Corporate America and their
allies in Washington did their best to break existing unions and
prevent working people from organizing new ones. </p>
<p>That is why the Reagan Administration broke PATCO and packed
the National Labor Relations Board with sworn enemies of
collective bargaining. That is why Corporate America tried a
whole new tactic -- permanently replacing workers who exercised
their right to strike. And that is why a whole new industry
emerged of attorneys, publicists, and pop psychologists who
advise companies on how to keep out unions. </p>
<p>But it is also true that our labor movement must change. That
is why I ran for President of the AFL-CIO, and that is why I won.
We understand, that while the world and the workplace have
changed, labor stood still and lost ground. Just as I challenge
business to change, every day on my job I challenge labor to
change. </p>
<p>That is why I am asking every union and every level of our
labor movement to do what the fastest-growing unions do: Put at
least 30 percent of our resources into organizing. That is why we
will be training at least a thousand organizers a year, pouring
millions into organizing programs; and organizing from the
sunbelt to the rustbelt and from health care to high tech. </p>
<p>That is why we are rebuilding our grassroots political
strength, training candidates and political organizers, educating
our members and the public on a scale that has Radical Right and
the Chamber of Commerce screaming &quot;foul.&quot;</p>
<p>And that is why unions across the country are changing
themselves, with a view to building more power for working
people. </p>
<p>Last year, the International Ladies Garment Workers Union and
the Amalgamated Clothing and Textile Workers Union joined
together and formed a new union appropriately called UNITE.
They're pouring $20 million into organizing drives, from the
sweatshops of New York City and Los Angeles to the mill towns of
the South. </p>
<p>On an even larger scale, the <a href="http://www.uaw.org/">United
Auto Workers,</a> United Steelworkers, and International
Association of Machinists have announced plans to merge by the
year 2000 --- and form a two- million-member union. That will
give them the clout to confront global companies, from General
Motors to Boeing. </p>
<p>Working Americans are angry at how they're being treated on
the job. The AFL-CIO has been talking in discussion groups with
working people across the country. </p>
<p>A 50-year-old Cleveland man said: </p>
<blockquote>
    <p>&quot;My company makes $72 million dollars a year. And
    still they're telling us, &quot;Well, you're overpaid. You
    may have been there for 29 or 30 years. You may have the
    experience. But that doesn't mean a damn thing. We can always
    replace you with somebody else. That's what we hear,&quot; he
    said. </p>
</blockquote>
<p>A 39-year-old Georgia woman said: </p>
<blockquote>
    <p>&quot;It's not like it used to be. Where raises were
    expected. You really have to kill yourself to get
    anything.&quot; </p>
</blockquote>
<p>Stories like these explain why working people nod in agreement
when union representatives -- from leaders like me to the
organizers who leaflet them at plant gates and visit them at
their homes -- say these four simple words: &quot;America needs a
raise.&quot; </p>
<p>And there are also signs that working people in every industry
and every walk of life are turning to unions. Here in the Boston
area, several years ago, the clerical and technical workers at
Harvard, with help from the national union, <a
href="http://www.afscme.org/">AFSCME,</a> organized a union of
their own, won an election, and bargained a trailblazing
contract. </p>
<p>Far away, in Martinsville, Virginia, more than 2,000 workers
at the textile company, Tultex, won a union election and
bargained their first contract. As <a
href="http://www.boston.com/">Boston Globe</a> columnist Bob
Kuttner reported, soon after Tultex signed a contract that raised
workers' wages, several non-union employers in the area also
raised their workers' wages. That's a sign of how a stronger
labor movement can raise living standards and change lives well
beyond our own ranks. </p>
<p>My old union, the <a href="http://www.seiu.org/">Service
Employees,</a> is doing its best to make sure that a rising tide
of unionism lifts all the workers in its industries. In industry
after industry -- building service, nursing homes, and home care
-- the union is conducting national campaigns to organize
workers, raise wages, and improve conditions. </p>
<p>I truly believe that, for all the hurt in this country, this
is the beginning of hopeful times for working Americans, if only
because they have suffered so much that they have no choice but
to fight back. Just as previous generations have done, they will
build new unions, revitalize old ones, and restore the labor
movement. </p>
<p>And, as we rebuild our strength, we will regain the power to
influence corporate policies at the bargaing table and government
policies in the political process. We can build an America with
more Aaron Feuersteins and fewer corporate cut-throats. We can
forge a new social contract where working men and women take
greater responsibility for the quality of the products they make
and the services they provide -- in return for a fair share of
power, profits, and prosperity. </p>
<p>I am reminded of the prize-winning poet Seamus Heaney, who
once wrote these words: &quot;History says don't hope on this
side of the grave. But, once in a lifetime, the longed-for tidal
wave of justice can rise up -- and hope and history rhyme.&quot; </p>
<p>Soon, in answer to the assault on their jobs and wages,
working men and women will once again &quot;rise up&quot; like
&quot;the longed- for tidal wave of justice.&quot; And we can
make this one of those rare moments when &quot;hope and history
rhyme.&quot; </p>
<p>Thank you.</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../index.htm">Public Documents Page</a> | <a
href="../publsear.htm">Public Documents Search</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
</body>
</html>
