<html>
<head>
<title>SP 04/02/96 Sweeney to Council of Institutional Investors</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<h1 align="center">Remarks by John J. Sweeney<br>
President, AFL-CIO<br>
</h1>
<p align="center">Council of Institutional Investors<br>
April 2, 1996 </p>
<h2 align="center">Challenging Chain Saw Management:<br>
A Common Path for Working Americans <br>
and Their Money Managers</h2>
<p align="center">Thank you very much, Bill, for that kind
introduction. Whether marching with Martin Luther King or Nelson
Mandela, or marshaling our pension fund billions, Bill Lucy has
led the labor movement at some of our finest hours, and I am
always honored to share the podium with him. </p>
<p>Let me say what a great pleasure it is to be here with the
people who take seriously the promise of a secure retirement for
America's workers. It's a major responsibility to be a fiduciary
for thousands of people's futures, as I have found in my twenty
years as trustee for the <a href="http://www.seiu.org/">Service
Employees</a> pension funds. Because I know how important the job
you all do is, I have always been particularly proud of the work
of SEIU members like Chuck Valdez and Bill Crist. Chuck and Bill
serve on the board of CALPERS, and are just two of literally
thousands of AFL-CIO union members helping to oversee America's
public and Taft-Hartley pension funds. </p>
<p>I want to take a few minutes of your time here today to bring
you some good news and some bad news, and then to talk about what
we can and should do about both. </p>
<p>First the good news. America's pension funds, and particularly
the organized funds of the Council of Institutional Investors,
are the patient capital our economy needs. Pension fund
investment objectives are measured in decades, not in quarters.
You have to invest your funds in companies that are planning for
the long-term, companies that will make the American economy the
same engine of prosperity for our children and grandchildren it
was for us. </p>
<p>Unlike so many people who play the market, pension funds are
genuine investors. But for too many years long-term investors
were a silent presence in the capital markets. </p>
<p>The Council has changed all that. The Council is creating a
collaborative vision of the future of corporate America -- a
vision that seeks common ground between shareholders and other
corporate constituents in the pursuit of long-term value. </p>
<p>Where that vision can lead was recently displayed in Business
Week's cover story on <a href="http://www.ual.com/">United
Airlines</a>, where workers, managers and investors have together
revitalized a major company to everyone's benefit. Together, they
have shared the rewards of their success. </p>
<p>So the rise of the Council as a forceful advocate for long-
term value is definitely good news. </p>
<p>But the bad news is this: our economy as a whole is headed in
a very different and destructive direction -- one that will
ultimately endanger your funds' ability to meet their
obligations. And some people are even using pension funds' recent
prosperity as an excuse for the path we are taking. </p>
<p>We all know the last few years on Wall Street has been one
long party. It's made the pension board meetings I've attended
more cheery, and I'm sure that's been true for most of you too.
But where is all this expected new value coming from?
Technological change is creating new value, and productivity is
going up -- but it's not being shared with the people who do the
producing. </p>
<p>The truth is that working Americans' paychecks haven't seen
any of the large productivity gains made in American business
since 1980. Meantime, corporate profits were up 64 percent from
1989 to 1995. Executive compensation? Up 360 percent since 1980.
But worker wages and health benefits and pension security are
down. Way down. </p>
<p>Think about the millions of American workers who are running
out of money, running out of options, and running out of hope.
They've exhausted their savings, they're working two and three
jobs, and they're loaded with debt. They see the stock market
soaring and profits roaring and they wonder: &quot;Who the hell
is getting my share?&quot; </p>
<p>Think about the one million additional Americans who lose
health coverage every year . . . forty million total with no
coverage now. They're frustrated and bitter and their anger is
exceeded only by anxiety over losing their jobs. </p>
<p>And can you imagine, in the middle of all this, the Republican
leaders in Congress voting not to consider an increase in the
minimum wage of $4 dollars and 25 cents an hour -- that's less
than $9000 a year -- after five years with no increase? I don't
know if that's more callous or stupid. </p>
<p>Working Americans know an economy that works like this won't
work for long. Last week the AFL-CIO gathered together a group of
working men and women to talk about their lives and their
economic futures, and to a person they told us one thing: an
economy where growth is not shared will soon collapse on itself. </p>
<p>Working people get it. Yet a lot of the run-up in stock prices
seems to be based upon the expectation that our economy is
structurally in a downward wage spiral that will keep putting
more money in investors' pockets forever. The markets seem to
calculate that working people will just keep on producing more
and more for less and less pay. </p>
<p>Well, part of the bad news I have to deliver is that if rising
equity prices reflect expectations of an infinity of falling
wages driving rising profits, then the bull market is exactly
that -- and long-term investors will be the losers when the
bubble bursts. </p>
<p>When the apostles of downsizing and the apologists for the low
wage economy want to shift the blame, they say, &quot;we only do
what we do because the institutional investors make us do
it.&quot; Some have even had the stupidity to say that the very
people they are putting on the unemployment lines are the real
winners from downsizing because of their pension plans. </p>
<p>Well let me assure you, as far as the union pension community
is concerned, we don't believe the downsizing trend is going to
create much sustainable value. And whatever working people gain
through their benefit plans is dwarfed by their losses-- in jobs,
wages, benefits, and security. </p>
<p>Downsizing is a negative sum game. I cannot say this strongly
enough. Chain saw managers like Scott Paper's Al Dunlap have no
mandate from America's union pension funds to destroy the
American middle class. </p>
<p>Rather, my mandate as president of the AFL-CIO is to lead a
reinvigorated labor movement in a great struggle for economic and
social justice. Justice for the 13.1 million members of the AFL-
CIO, and for every working American, and for every American who
wants to work and can't. And the first step to justice is a fair
share of the wealth working Americans create. </p>
<p>By this time some of you must be thinking, justice for workers
means money out of shareholder pockets. And I don't want to
suggest there are never conflicts between workers and
shareholders. But I do want to take most of the rest of my time
today to talk about a few steps workers and shareholders can take
together on a path toward a healthier corporate economy that can
generate long-term value for all of us. </p>
<p>Think for a moment how far we have come since the mid-1980s.
In those days, the capital markets were an arena of struggle
between entrenched, self-interested managers on one side and
short-term-focused financial buyers and arbitragers on the other.
Ten years ago words like proxies and independent directors had
not entered the corporate governance dictionary. No public or
union pension fund had ever filed a shareholder proposal. The
notion that a corporate CEO would return the phone call, let
alone meet with pension fund representatives, was unthinkable.
Some funds were uncritical supporters of existing management,
often under pressure from their plan sponsors. Others funded LBO
funds and junk bond entrepreneurs that ended up destabilizing the
entire American financial system. </p>
<p>In this difficult environment, institutional investors with a
long-term perspective came together in the Council to forge our
own independent, long-term perspective. These investors favored
neither the short term-ism of the corporate raiders, nor the
complacency of entrenched managers. It was natural, then, that
the Council, through the bold leadership of the public pension
funds, was the driving force in the transition from corporate
governance by hostile takeover . . . to proxy contests over
specific governance issues . . . to efforts at developing
sustained, productive relationships with company managers. . </p>
<p>America's union-affiliated pension funds, jointly governed by
labor and management under the Taft-Hartley Act, brought a unique
perspective to the Council. Union funds and their worker trustees
see companies differently than other outsider investment
analysts. Our experiences inside the companies we invest in lead
us to see long-term mutually beneficial economic cooperation
among shareholders and other corporate constituencies as the
source of value. I should note that this perspective lies at the
heart of our skepticism about downsizing's effect on value. </p>
<p>In the second wave of shareholder activism that followed the
public funds' initiatives of the late 1980's, this Taft-Hartley
perspective has been critical in helping the institutional
investor community as a whole find its own voice. </p>
<p>Just last year, we saw a number of major initiatives that grew
out of Council members sharing perspectives and strategies:
During the last proxy season, Taft-Hartley funds affiliated with
the AFL-CIO sponsored 43 resolutions addressing corporate
governance issues in America's major companies, including leading
the opposition to excessive executive compensation and urging
executive evaluation policies that protect shareholder interests. </p>
<p>During the past year, CALPERS has launched The Workplace
Practices Survey initiative-- aimed directly at encouraging
corporations to add value for shareholders by developing human
capital. </p>
<p>Finally, in what may be its finest hour thus far, during 1995
the Council led Chrysler's shareholder community in opposing Kirk
Kerkorian's destructive efforts to loot the company's working
capital. The Council's leadership preserved value for
shareholders and workers alike. </p>
<p>I have been talking about a common path to long term value.
The next step on that path is clear. If we are serious about
advocating long-term value, we must ask the management of the
companies we invest in to join us and pursue a partnership with
their workforce as a whole -- a partnership based on mutual
respect, cooperation and mutual gain. </p>
<p>We must work together to reform corporations like Archer
Daniels Midland. At ADM, a business philosophy of bad corporate
citizenship risks dissipating shareholder value in a tangle of
regulatory, legal, and workplace problems. </p>
<p>More generally, we must challenge directly the two most
salient trends in corporate life today. One I have already
mentioned -- destructive downsizing. The other is the widening
gap between the pay of a handful of the very top executives in
the companies we own and everyone else in American society. </p>
<p>First let me say a few more words about downsizing.
Destructive downsizing is about breaking a critical covenant
between shareholders and other corporate constituencies -- a
covenant necessary for complex corporations to generate value. </p>
<p>Once, companies and workers had an understanding that goes
like this: workers invest in company-specific skills early in
their career in return for long-term employment. </p>
<p>The company that downsizes fires workers after having
benefitted from those skills. The company may get a one-time
gain, but no rational worker will ever invest in the firm-
specific skills that company needs again. Where does that leave
the stockholder in a company like AT&amp;T today? What are the
scientists at Bell Labs doing now -- are they spending their late
nights creating value for shareholders or keeping their resume up
to date? The rational worker's response to the shredding of that
understanding is what we in the unions call work to rule-- do the
minimum and use your brain to help yourself, not your firm.
Downsizing is a business strategy that encourages work to rule.
That's one reason downsizing destroys value. </p>
<p>There's a second reason. Destructive downsizing is also about
cutting corporate activities and resources that are vital to
long-term profitability, so that costs that are cut in one part
of the income statement end up either reappearing as larger costs
elsewhere or are more than counterbalanced by lost revenues. I
suspect the Kimberly Clark shareholders who recently paid $6.8
billion for a gutted Scott Paper are about to find out how costly
destructive downsizing can be. </p>
<p>That brings me to the second big dangerous trend in corporate
life today. Just as destructive downsizing tears at the covenant
between constituencies that is at the heart of the corporation,
so too does the orgy of greed in the executive suite --
especially in a time of often difficult technological and
organizational change. </p>
<p>Thanks to the Council's work with Graef Crystal, we all know
the extent of the problem of excessive pay to mediocre
executives. Corporate boards dominated by cronies of the CEO
award a mediocre executive multi-million dollar pay packages
while the company's stock stagnates and the firm lays off
workers. Then the board members are rewarded with generous fees,
pensions, consulting contracts, legal fees and so forth. </p>
<p>CEOs should be paid for performance. But how do we measure
performance, and how much should we pay for performance? CEO
performance-based pay should be based on three principles. </p>
<p>First, executive compensation should be based on long-term,
sustainable value creation, not short term stock market
manipulation. </p>
<p>Second, compensation should be actively managed by an alert
board. Mechanical, stock option-based compensation can have
hidden, perverse incentives. Any mechanical system encourages
manipulation and allows the board of directors to avoid genuinely
monitoring what the CEO is doing. </p>
<p>Finally, CEOs should be paid no more than necessary to attract
and retain capable people. Extraordinary people are available to
work for $1 million a year. I see no reason to pay over hyped
mediocrities like Al Dunlap one hundred times that. </p>
<p>Excessive pay creates a divisive corporate culture. It signals
frontline workers that excellence is only demanded from those
without the power to protect themselves from meaningful
evaluation. In an era of downsizing, when CEO pay goes from 41
times the average workers' pay in 1980 to 149 times in 1993,
what's the message? </p>
<p>Is the company a cooperative enterprise built on teamwork, or
a treacherous arena of struggle governed by the motto
&quot;everyone for themselves, and the devil take the
hindmost&quot;? </p>
<p>The boards that okay excessive pay are destroying value. They
are overpaying for managerial expertise and they are eroding any
basis for a partnership between shareholders, senior managers,
and the employees who do the work that makes companies valuable.
In response, the Taft-Hartley community and the unions of the
AFL-CIO have taken significant steps in the direction of board
reform in recent years. </p>
<p>Funds affiliated with the <a href="http://www.teamster.org/">Teamsters</a>
and UNITE are running former Arnold and Porter partner and
current Northwest Airlines trustee Steve Hester for the K-Mart
board, a company that has suffered from years of complacent
management. In the steel industry, the United Steel Workers have
negotiated long-term contracts with the major industry players
that have put people like former Secretary of Labor Ray Marshall
on steel company boards and aligned worker and shareholder
interests in company performance. Most recently, the Teamsters
have released a report on America' Least Valuable Directors that
we all should find interesting proxy season reading. </p>
<p>Now is the time for the Council to realize the opportunities
created by these reform efforts. Now is the time to seek
substantive changes that will renew the partnerships every
corporation depends on to create value for shareholders. </p>
<p>In closing, let me say a word about what I see as the major
challenge confronting every person in this room. </p>
<p>Over the past decade, the Council has become a powerful voice
for long-term value. Now that voice must be heard above the roar
of the short-termers. The Council must be a voice for a corporate
economy of productive partnerships. An economy of good corporate
citizens. An economy that can reach out to enfold all Americans
in an embrace of prosperity. Only such an economy, an economy
free from fear, can sustain the long-run profitability pension
funds require. </p>
<p>As President of the AFL-CIO, I intend to lead the American
labor movement in a fight on behalf of all working people to
reaffirm the social compact that made America great -- the
promise that prosperity will mean growing together, not apart. As
a trustee, I know that only a corporate economy founded on
equitable prosperity can create value for investors over the
long-run. </p>
<p>Some politicians and business leaders today point us toward an
atomized, divided society, a war of all against all. They offer a
world where security belongs to those who can buy it. Where hard
work and loyalty are merely weaknesses to be exploited by the
agile and well-connected. Where the only hope offered to the
downsized is the chance to hate those even less well off. </p>
<p>America's unions offer a different vision. We seek positive
change. But we demand that both the costs and benefits of change
are equally shared. We believe economic growth cannot be
sustained without rewarding working people's efforts with
something more than a pink slip. And we believe that only when
working people of every race, religion, gender and nationality
stand together can America move forward. </p>
<p>By helping millions of Americans enjoy a financially secure
retirement, all of you help make that vision a reality every day.
Our challenge today is to move forward and build on your daily
achievement. To meet that challenge, the Council and the larger
community of institutional investors must ask companies to forge
partnerships -- partnerships between shareholders, managers,
employees, communities and other constituencies that make
profitable corporations possible. </p>
<p>The union pension community and I look forward to
participating in the Council's efforts to meet that challenge, so
that together we can help shape an economy we can all be proud
of. </p>
<p>Thank you.</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../index.htm">Public Documents Page</a> | <a
href="../publsear.htm">Public Documents Search</a></p>
