<html>

<head>
<title>SP 03/12/96 Sweeney Older Women's League</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h4 align=center>Remarks by John J. Sweeney, President<br>
AFL-CIO<br>
</h4>
<h3 align=center>Older Women's League<br>
Washington, D.C. </h3>
<p>March 12, 1996 </p>
<p>Thank you very much. </p>
<p>And to all my friends from OWL, let me tell you how grateful I am to be honored by a group that I 
have admired and supported for so many years... </p>
<p>and that I know is deeply committed to promoting the welfare and dignity of all members of 
society. </p>
<p>A good friend of working people, the late Hubert Humphrey, said, &quot;The moral test of government is 
how it treats those who are in the dawn of life -- the children... </p>
<p>... those who are in the twilight of life -- the aged... </p>
<p>---and those who are in the shadows of life -- the sick, the needy, and the handicapped.&quot; </p>
<p>OWL is an organization that has worked tirelessly to hold our government to this moral standard in 
its relationship with midlife and older women. </p>
<p>And you have fought for the principle that the quality of service that older Americans receive -- 
particularly health care -- is closely linked to the quality of work life of those who provide that care. </p>
<p>We in the trade union movement share your values. </p>
<p>We, like you, are trying to build a society that is more equal, more fair, more humane. </p>
<p>We, like you, work for a society in which everyone has a right to a decent job, a secure retirement, 
the necessities of life, and basic human dignity. </p>
<p>Let me suggest that there is no institution in our society that does more to build women's economic 
security than the labor movement. </p>
<p>It is dedicated to serving the interests of millions of women -- and men -- who teach our kids, sew 
our clothes, build our houses, and take care of us when we are sick. </p>
<p>I'd like you to meet two people who represent our movement at its very best. </p>
<p>Helen Smith works at Elmwood Geriatric Village in Detroit, which is part of the Bortz chain of 
nursing homes -- and she's a steward in Local 79 of the Service Employees International Union. </p>
<p>Helen helped lead the campaign for a union contract for Bortz employees. </p>
<p>They won. </p>
<p>The result is they now have health insurance -- they have pension benefits through the union -- and 
they set the pattern for wages in nursing homes throughout Michigan. </p>
<p>Helen Miller is a home care worker for the Department of Aging and the Department of 
Rehabilitative Services in Illinois. </p>
<p>She helped organize home care workers into Local 880 of the Service Employees, and she now 
serves her local as Vice-President. </p>
<p>She has led fights for better wages and benefits for over 10,000 workers in Illinois, often against 
tremendous odds -- and I can assure you that they never would have gotten those wages and 
benefits without the dedication and tenacity of Helen Miller and many others just like her. </p>
<p>Helen Smith and Helen Miller are what the labor movement is all about. </p>
<p>They are the movement. </p>
<p>I'd like to ask each of them to say a few words. </p>
<p><strong>[AFTER SMITH AND MILLER:]</strong> </p>
<p>Thank you, Helen Smith and Helen Miller. </p>
<p>I am delighted to receive the OWL Leadership Award. </p>
<p>But I know who the real recipients are. </p>
<p>The award actually belongs to my union sisters and brothers -- to Helen Miller, Helen Smith, and 
the 13 million working people who make up the AFL-CIO. </p>
<p>On their behalf, I thank each of you for this honor.</p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="/publ/publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
