<html>
<head>
<title>SP 03/05/96 Trumka to PA AFL-CIO</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<h3 align="center">Remarks by AFL-CIO<br>
Secretary-Treasurer<br>
RICHARD TRUMKA<br>
to the Pennsylvania AFL-CIO<br>
</h3>
<h4 align="center">Philadelphia, PA * March 5, 1996</h4>
<p>Thank you, Billy, for that fine introduction. </p>
<p>You know, friendship is something that money just can't buy
and Billy has stood by me through thick and thin for so many
years. </p>
<p>When the miners squared off against the coal companies and
their police and their judges during the Pittston battle, and
again during the 1993 BCOA strike, boy, was I glad to have Billy
George in my corner. </p>
<p>He is a dear friend and a brother in the struggle. </p>
<p>I want to thank all of you for this invitation to come
&quot;home&quot; to my native Pennsylvania in my capacity as
Secretary-Treasurer of the AFL-CIO. </p>
<p>It was here, in a small coal patch town called Nemacolin,
where I was born and grew up. </p>
<p>It was there I learned the value of hard work. </p>
<p>I learned that the best social program is a job, where a
person can earn a living wage in order to feed and clothe and
house his or her kids. </p>
<p>I learned how working men and women weren't about to get a leg
up and be able to build better lives for themselves and their
families unless they joined together in a union. </p>
<p>And today, brothers and sisters, I am pleased to have the
opportunity to speak with you about the new day that's dawning
for the American labor movement. </p>
<p>Just after I was elected Secretary-Treasurer, with John
Sweeney as President, and Linda Chavez-Thompson as Executive
Vice-President, House Speaker Newt Gingrich let it be known that
he was none too happy. </p>
<p>He told a bunch of Wall Street executives that the new
leadership was -- and I quote -- &quot;potentially a
disaster.&quot; </p>
<p>He continued by saying &quot;We do not need a more
confrontational, more hostile, more divisive union leadership. We
need a union leadership that understands the world market&quot;
and works to &quot;improve the work ethic&quot; and &quot;the
efficiency of labor.&quot; </p>
<p>In other words, Newt Gingrich wanted a union movement that
would roll over and play dead while he and his minions continued
their dastardly work of diminishing opportunities for working
people and their families. </p>
<p>In your dreams, Mr. Gingrich, in your dreams. </p>
<p>What he got instead was a new AFL-CIO, determined to stand up
to every employer, every politician, every special interest who,
if given half a chance, will rob us of our dignity, our security,
our respect, and our power. </p>
<p>Our message to Newt Gingrich and to every employer, whether
public sector or private sector, is that the era of
union-busting, contract-trashing, and strikebreaking is over,
period. </p>
<p>When they push us, we push back. It's as simple as that. </p>
<p>This comeback of ours arrives just in the nick of time. The
assault on the rights and the living standards of American
working men and women is in full swing. </p>
<p>People are angry when they see productivity, profits, and the
stock market going up, while they watch their own incomes stay
the same or decline. </p>
<p>People are angry at the lack of respect given to working men
and women and their families by employers, by public officials,
and by the news media. </p>
<p>People are angry with an economic policy that disinvests in
workers here at home while aiding and abetting the export of good
American jobs to low-wage countries that forcibly deny their
workers the right to organize. </p>
<p>Working men and women want jobs that will enable them to put
food on the table and afford a decent roof over their heads. </p>
<p>They want a world of opportunity for their kids and a chance
to build for security in old age. </p>
<p>They want access to quality health care at reasonable cost.
They want a safe workplace and a decent environment. </p>
<p>Instead, American workers are being outsourced, downsized,
subcontacted and permanently replaced. </p>
<p>The other day I was reading about Robert E. Allen. </p>
<p>Mr. Allen is the chairman of AT&amp;T Corporation, who in
January announced layoffs and restructuring that will cost nearly
50,000 of his employees their jobs. </p>
<p>Last year -- a year in which AT&amp;T said they made next to
no profit -- Mr. Allen received $16 million in compensation, more
than double the $6.3 million he received in 1994. </p>
<p>Working men and women see companies merge and workers get laid
off. </p>
<p>They see stock prices skyrocket and CEOS getting big bonuses. </p>
<p>Chief executives all over are turning in lackluster
performances and eliminating jobs and being well paid for their
work. </p>
<p>Something is wrong with this picture. </p>
<p>Thomas D. O'Malley, the CEO of Tosco Corporation, is another
case in point. Bob Wages of the Oil, Chemical and Atomic Workers
told me that Mr. O'Malley bought up another oil refinery, this
time in Delaware County. </p>
<p>He refused to talk contract with his workers and shut down the
plant in retribution. </p>
<p>In doing so, he's shorted the retail market by 200,000 barrels
and pocketed an extra $20 million in profits. </p>
<p>Now, he says he'll reopen the refinery if the taxpayers ante
up $60 million in restart costs. </p>
<p>What a sweetheart. </p>
<p>Between 1993 and 1996, Fortune 500 companies have eliminated
300,000 jobs. </p>
<p>For the most part, these are not layoffs, forced on a company
because business is bad. </p>
<p>These downsizings are occurring at a time, according to
Business Week magazine, when corporate profits are the highest
they've been in 45 years. </p>
<p>Executive compensation is growing. </p>
<p>Corporate profits are booming. </p>
<p>Every time a company announces another downsizing, they pop
the champagne corks on Wall Street. </p>
<p>Bad news for workers is good news for stockbrokers and bond
traders. </p>
<p>Whose boat is stuck on the bottom during this rising tide? </p>
<p>You guessed it -- yours and mine. </p>
<p>According to the Labor Department, the rise in the cost of
labor during 1995 was the lowest ever recorded. And it isn't just
affecting blue collar workers, but also white collar employees. </p>
<p>It isn't just line workers, but also technicals who are taking
a hit.It isn't just less skilled workers hitting the streets, but
also highly trained employees. </p>
<p>To quote Business Week: &quot;All but the most elite employees
have landed in the same leaky boat.&quot; </p>
<p>Since 1979, the productivity of American workers went up by 24
percent. </p>
<p>Real earnings for workers, however, declined by 12 percent. </p>
<p>Increases in productivity should have given us a substantial
increase in buying power. Instead that productivity gain was
converted into corporate profits -- which are up 64 percent in
the last six years -- and executive compensation -- up 360
percent since 1980. </p>
<p>The rich are getting richer, the poor are falling further
behind and the middle class is treading water, with more family
members working longer and harder just to try to stay even. </p>
<p>Working families have little money to spend, lots of bills to
pay, and damn little time to spend with their kids. </p>
<p>How do we turn this around? We organize, we mobilize, and we
take this country back for working men and women! </p>
<p>The Republican majority in Congress was hellbent on cutting
Social Security, Medicare and Medicaid -- our safety net for
retired folks and for poor families. </p>
<p>We stopped them. </p>
<p>They want to abolish the 40-hour week so that employers won't
have to pay out so much overtime. </p>
<p>We are stopping them. </p>
<p>They want to make it legal for businesses to establish phony
&quot;company unions.&quot; </p>
<p>We are stopping them. </p>
<p>They wanted to repeal the Davis-Bacon Act, which requires that
decent wages be paid on federal construction projects. </p>
<p>We stopped them. </p>
<p>They want to cut billions of dollars in the college loan and
work study programs, making it even more difficult for working
families to make sure their kids get a college education. </p>
<p>So far, we've stopped them. </p>
<p>A headline in the Washington Post said it best. </p>
<p>It read: &quot;The Battle That Business Lost: Its Legislative
Agenda Was Crushed in '95 and Unions Have Mobilized for a '96
Repeat.&quot; </p>
<p>Despite Republican majorities in the House and the Senate --
bought and paid for by big business -- we beat back the agenda
big business was just sure they would win. </p>
<p>The AFL-CIO conducted the most aggressive grassroots lobbying
campaign in our history against the Republicans &quot;Contract
with America.&quot; </p>
<p>Over the past six months, we've spent millions of dollars in
radio and television advertising in key districts. </p>
<p>We've sent out over two million pieces of literature in the
mail to our members and coordinated hundreds of demonstrations
and visits to members of Congress. </p>
<p>We generated over 400,000 phone calls to Senators and
Representatives about their votes on issues effecting working
families. </p>
<p>But that's just one part of our counterattack. </p>
<p>Already this year, we've won three big contract victories --
for 35,000 building service workers in New York City, 35,000
Boeing machinists, and 35,000 CWA workers at Bell Atlantic. </p>
<p>Starting this month, the AFL-CIO will kick off our
&quot;America Needs a Raise&quot; campaign with high-visibility
&quot;town hall&quot; meetings in 29 cities coast-to-coast. </p>
<p>We'll be asking workers and their families to tell their
stories about the effect that stagnant wages have on their
abilities to raise themselves up and grab a piece of the American
dream. </p>
<p>Last November, labor played the key role in electing a
pro-labor governor in Kentucky. </p>
<p>I spoke to rallies of thousands in the critical closing days
of the contest and we won a stunning victory. </p>
<p>Then, in January, we took a Senate seat away from the
Republicans in Oregon, the first time a pro-labor candidate and
Democrat won a Senate seat there since 1962. </p>
<p>Senator Ron Wyden won because he was the labor candidate. </p>
<p>He walked our picket lines, toured plants with our stewards,
and spoke to the issues that concerned working people. </p>
<p>We asked him to run with the union label and he put it right
there on his lapel. He didn't hide it away in his pocket. </p>
<p>We shifted our labor political machinery into high gear and
won a decisive victory over a reactionary, rightwing billionaire. </p>
<p>As we continue to battle the big business agenda in Congress,
we will also lay the groundwork to elect in 1996 a Congress that
listens to the voices of working people. </p>
<p>We need a Congress that will act to strengthen opportunities
for working men and women and advance a level playing field so
that we have a fighting chance to organize the unorganized. </p>
<p>We intend to build a vast grassroots network, anchored by at
least 100 labor activists in every congressional district. </p>
<p>We will register voters and talk about the issues critical to
working people. We will mobilize our members and others in
support of candidates who stand with us on working family issues. </p>
<p>At the same time, we will be rebuilding a base of working
families who can hold public officials accountable -- next year
and for years to come. </p>
<p>Finally, we must put special emphasis on organizing. </p>
<p>We must and will provide leadership, coordination, and support
for a movement-wide effort to return unions to a dominant role in
improving the lives of all Americans. </p>
<p>We will increase our spending on organizing and work with you
to enhance your organizing efforts and capabilities. </p>
<p>We will recruit and train a new generation of organizers
through our Organizing Institute. Our &quot;Union Summer&quot;
project will deploy 1,000 college and rank-andfile youth to work
in union organizing drives around the country. Enthusiasm is very
high, I can tell you. </p>
<p>We will raise the visibility and public profile of unions so
that folks can more clearly see how we are vehicles for improving
the jobs, working conditions, and lives of American families. </p>
<p>People should know that labor's victories are America's
victories. </p>
<p>Just recently, UNITE, our newly-formed union of textile and
clothing workers, won a contract -- and a raise -- for 2,300
workers in Martinsville, West Virginia. </p>
<p>Before long, 10,000 non-union textile workers in the area had
themselves a raise, too.<br>
A coincidence? I don't think so. </p>
<p>These are the kinds of stories Americans need to hear a whole
lot more about. </p>
<p>All of you are on the frontlines of this historic battle. Our
state federations are vital in the effort to build this new
AFL-CIO. </p>
<p>The dreams and the aspirations and the progress of
Pennsylvania's working men and women rely on your power. I am
talking about power on the shop floor and power on the picket
line, power in the media and power at the polling place. </p>
<p>In this critical political year, I ask you to join hands with
me in building a labor movement that will reach out and win over
young workers and women workers, African Americans, Latinos, and
Asians. We must take our message to people who live in the cities
and the suburbs, and in our small towns. </p>
<p>We have something important to say to all working people who
are angry and frustrated and looking for the energy and the
leadership we can provide. </p>
<p>We will build a lean, mean political fighting machine able to
take on and defeat politicians who turn their backs on working
men and women and their unions. </p>
<p>We do so because we know that politics isn't just about
campaigns and rallies, contributions, and get-out-the vote. </p>
<p>Politics determines whether we have an economic policy that
works for working Americans, rather than mostly for the rich and
powerful. </p>
<p>Politics determines the kind of schools our kids will attend
and whether the streets and playgrounds they play in will be as
safe and secure as they ought to be. </p>
<p>Politics determines whether our brothers and sisters will have
a fair chance to organize themselves into unions and bargain for
decent wages and safe working conditions. </p>
<p>Union folk understand the word &quot;solidarity&quot; pretty
well. </p>
<p>It means we are all in this together, this bold and historic
effort to build an America where all working people have a future
for themselves, for their kids and for their communities. </p>
<p>This is the kind of union movement that America needs and
deserves. </p>
<p>Out of our diversity and the many different roads we've
travelled, comes unity and strength and determination. </p>
<p>In the words of the old labor hymn: </p>
<blockquote>
    <p>&quot;It is we who plowed the prairies, built the cities
    where they trade, dug the mines and built the workshops,
    endless miles of railroad laid...&quot; </p>
</blockquote>
<p>I believe this country belongs to us, not to the Newt
Gingrichs and the Robert Allens and the Rush Limbaughs. </p>
<p>It's high time we took it back. </p>
<p>Thank you.</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../index.htm">Public Documents Page</a> | <a
href="../publsear.htm">Public Documents Search</a></p>
