<title>SP 03/01/96 Sweeney to the Rainbow Coalition Labor Breakfast</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<pre>                       Remarks by John J. Sweeney
                        President of the AFL-CIO
</pre>
<h3 align=center>Rainbow Coalition Labor Breakfast Chicago March 1, 1996 </h3>
<p>Thank you, Rev. Jackson, for those very kind words and for inviting me to be with you here this 
morning. I bring you greetings from Rich Trumka and Linda Chavez-Thompson, the other members 
of our &quot;New Voice for American Workers&quot; team. They said to tell you they still think you are the 
&quot;true voice&quot; for all Americans, workers or otherwise! </p>
<p>As for me, you can call me &quot;new,&quot; you can call me &quot;true,&quot; but you cannot call me &quot;blue,&quot; because I 
am happy to report that I escaped unharmed from a fender bender on my way in from the airport. </p>
<p>The cab I was in was pulling away from the curb, and we nicked the fender of a long, white 
limousine that was parked in front of us. I got out to investigate, only to discover that it belonged to 
Mayor Daley. </p>
<p>Being from New York, I know how to handle such things, so I told the cab driver not to worry and 
I wrote a note and left it on the windshield. </p>
<p>The note said: &quot;Dear Mayor Daley, I'm sorry we caught your fender, but I'm late for a big meeting 
downtown and I don't have time to stop. Please have your office call my office and get the number 
of my insurance company and we'll get this thing settled.&quot; </p>
<p>And I signed the note, &quot;Jesse Jackson .........&quot; </p>
<p>I've been told that I am the first president of the AFL-CIO to ever address a formal event of the 
&quot;Rainbow Coalition.&quot; Well, when I got the invitation, I accepted immediately because Jesse 
Jackson always accepted my invitations to speak to my union, the Service Employees Union. 
Jesse, you have always been there for us any time working Americans and their families are in 
trouble. And union members from San Francisco to Seattle to New York to Detroit know that 
when Jesse Jackson hits town, the BOSS is gonna go down! </p>
<p>So I thank you and this great organization for your support and I want you to know that as long as 
I am president of our federation, the AFL-CIO will &quot;be there&quot; for you. </p>
<p>Serving as president of the AFL-CIO is pretty rarified air for the son of Irish immigrants who came 
to this country not too many years ago hoping for just a small slice of the American dream. My 
father was a New York City bus driver, a member of the Transport Workers Union, and my 
earliest memories were of going to union meetings with him and listening to Mike Quill explain in his 
thick brogue the harsh realities of pocketbook economics. </p>
<p>Those were still the days of &quot;No Irish Need Apply,&quot; and times were tough. But you knew that, if 
you worked hard and had a union, you could earn more money and live a better life, maybe send 
your kids to college, buy a small home. </p>
<p>Employers knew that if they paid their workers fairly and plowed a little of their profits back into 
their communities they could count on employee loyalty and healthy consumer spending --- which 
has always made up two-thirds of our economy. And they knew that if they didn't treat those 
workers fairly, there would be an accounting at the hands of their union. </p>
<p>Even though there were often bumps along the way, we had what we called a &quot;social compact&quot; 
between labor, business, government and the communities in which we lived. </p>
<p>President Kennedy found a simple but eloquent way to describe this successful social and 
economic compact: &quot;A rising tide lifts all boats.&quot; </p>
<p>When things were good -- as they were for almost 30 years after the end of World War II -- most 
of us prospered because we prospered together. We were concerned with raising the standard of 
living for working Americans, not just accumulating enormous wealth for a fortunate few. When 
things broke down, we fixed them -- together. </p>
<p>Unfortunately, those days are gone. Today, there are no rules. The only rule for employers is that 
you take what you can get away with. </p>
<p>American business decided the best way to compete in the global economy was by driving down 
labor costs. Not by innovation, not by Yankee ingenuity, not through labor-management 
cooperation, and not by insisting on international social standards and rights for workers. But by 
squeezing the last possible ounce of productivity out of American workers, and then throwing them 
on the scrap-heap of unemployment or old age with reduced pensions and health insurance 
coverage. </p>
<p>Since 1979, all of the income growth in our country has gone to the top 40 percent of households 
-- and nearly all of that went to the top 20 percent. </p>
<p>Meanwhile, corporate profits are up, up, UP. In fact, according to Business Week, they're at a 
45-year high. The stock market is up. Productivity is up -- it has been since the late 1970's -- and 
it's way out front of compensation. </p>
<p>This past year, workers' wages and benefits increased only 2.8 percent -- the lowest since 1981 -- 
while productivity was up 3.4 percent. </p>
<p>Twenty years of declining wages and disappearing benefits are taking their toll on American life. 
There's a free-floating anger among hardworking people for whom the American dream is turning 
into a nightmare of unpaid bills and unfulfilled aspirations. Increasingly, American workers are down 
on their government, down on their employers, and down on their future. American workers are 
running out of money and running out of hope. </p>
<p>And what of those American workers who never really shared in the prosperity in the first place? 
The women and minorities who couldn't ride a rising tide because they didn't even have a boat? 
Now comes American business and American politicians to declare that affirmative action -- the 
one vehicle women and minorities can use for improving their living standard -- is somehow 
un-American. And they want to destroy the safety nets for those who have been totally left behind 
--- the young, the old, the poor and the disabled who depend on Medicare, Medicaid, Social 
Security, and AFDC just to SURVIVE. All in the name of supposedly &quot;balancing the budget.&quot; </p>
<p>Writing in the New York Times last year, Lou Uchitelle gave voice to the plight of lower- and 
middle-income families. &quot;Something is wrong with America's economic boom,&quot; he wrote. &quot;After 
four years of ever-stronger growth . . . people's wages should be going up faster than their 
expenses. For most people, they're not, and this is the first time in decades that a recovery has 
gone so long without putting more money in more pockets. And now, if the recovery runs out of 
steam in 1995, as so many economists predict, that money might never show up.&quot; </p>
<p>Our problem is stagnant wages -- America needs a raise. And I think the solution is a larger, 
stronger, smarter labor movement and a revived civil rights movement. </p>
<p>The AFL-CIO is going to do its part by rebuilding our labor movement, by pouring vast resources 
into organizing from the Sun Belt to the Rust Belt and from software-writers to sweatshop workers. 
Our message to American workers is simple but powerful: Whether you wear a blue collar, a white 
collar, a new collar, or no collar, we can help you make your job better. We're going to be 
stronger and we are going take it to greedy employers who've been picking our pockets and then 
trying to tell us we stupidly lost our wallets. </p>
<p>We're also going to reclaim our political power and use it to reclaim our country. Last month, we 
wrote the first chapter in a new book on electoral politics with a remarkable Senate victory in 
Oregon. Ron Wyden was more than just the first Democrat to win statewide office in Oregon in 
more than 30 years, he was an up-front, out-front LABOR candidate. </p>
<p>Ron Wyden won because we poured money and people into his campaign and because he listened 
to our advice. He won because he walked picket lines, toured plants with union leaders and made 
hundreds of phone calls to union members. </p>
<p>We asked him to run with the union label and he wore it on the outside of his lapel, not hidden in his 
pocket. We promised him that if he campaigned on the core issues of working families, we would 
boot him home. And he responded by booting a buckraking billionaire businessman right in his...... 
bank account! </p>
<p>That's the way we are going to take back the House of Representatives and take back our country 
this fall --- by supporting candidates who say, &quot;I am proud to carry the banner of working 
Americans .... I am proud to stand up for America's working families .... and I am proud to be 
UNION.&quot; </p>
<p>I don't need to tell you that this is perhaps the most critical election year in the long history of our 
great movement. Last year, we let the reactionary, anti-worker forces in this country slip up on us 
and the result is that we've been fighting for our lives ever since. </p>
<p>We've survived, but just barely. We started out by getting an ironclad commitment from President 
Clinton to veto any bill that damaged Davis-Bacon or the Service Contract Act and he has lived up 
to that commitment. But we've had to fight like hell during the budget battle that still continues. We 
spent $7 million dollars on television advertising in the districts of the radical, right-wing followers of 
Newt Gingrich. We poured direct mail into those same districts. And we generated over 500,000 
telephone calls to members of Congress carrying our core message: &quot;no cuts in Medicare, college 
loans, or worker protections to pay for a tax cut for the rich.&quot; </p>
<p>We ended up the current round by forcing the Republicans to back off and end the government 
shutdown. And we got virtually full funding for the National Labor Relations Board, at least through 
March 15th. But right now, we're getting hit hard where it hurts. OSHA's budget has been cut 22 
percent and agencies like the EPA have been cut 30 percent. They are proceeding to throw all the 
programs for poor children into block grants that will be given with no strings attached to the states 
to administer. The safety net we've worked so hard to weave over the past 50 years isn't just 
coming unravelled, it is being ripped to shreds by greedy corporations and Wall Street wizards who 
want to strip away all protections for workers, destroy the union movement as we know it, and tell 
the old, the young, the poor and the disabled to go straight to their graves. </p>
<p>I don't want to live in a country like that. That's why I announced at our first AFL-CIO Executive 
Council meeting that we are going to spend $35 million dollars on politics this year --- more than 
three times what we've ever spent. We are proceeding with plans to establish our new national 
political institute, which is charged with recruiting and training political organizers, campaign 
managers and candidates. </p>
<p>We're going to lay the groundwork for political success with an initiative called &quot;America Needs a 
Raise,&quot; holding &quot;town hall&quot; meetings in 29 cities over the next three months to show how workers 
and their families are suffering because of the wage and wealth gap, and to educate our members, 
the media and the public. </p>
<p>In June, we'll continue a high public profile with &quot;Union Summer.&quot; Our goal is to recruit and deploy 
1,000 young workers and college students into organizing and political campaigns around the 
country during June, July and August. Recruiting is already underway and we're getting a terrific 
feedback. </p>
<p>Then we're going to have a &quot;Union Fall&quot; as we regain control of our government. We will 
concentrate on up to 75 House districts, primarily where freshmen Republicans are vulnerable, and 
we will support candidates who will carry the banner of working Americans. </p>
<p>In addition, we will establish a core of at least 100 union activists in every congressional district in 
the country to carry us through this election and then become a permanent and powerful network 
for grassroots lobbying. We have to have more members involved in political action, we have to 
educate more members and we have to get more members to the polls --- it's as simple as that. </p>
<p>If we don't, we're going to see working Americans --- our members and our potential members --- 
slipping away to the likes of Steve Forbes, Ross Perot and Patrick Buchanan --- right-wing 
politicians who use populist appeals to tap into the frustrations and fears of working class people. I 
remember the last time that happened. The candidate's name was George Wallace. I remember 
that the AFL-CIO was largely silent on Wallace, because our leaders felt we might even alienate 
our members if we took him on, and he gained influence and power because of our silence. </p>
<p>That's why I decided two weeks ago to publicly respond to candidate Buchanan by saying, &quot;He is 
a racist, he's anti-semitic, he bashes women right along with labor and immigrants and he's a 
believer in supply-side economics.&quot; I wanted working people to know that candidate Buchanan has 
come very late to the issue of declining worker incomes in the midst of economic plenty and that he 
is against the minimum wage, against wage standards, against worker health and safety protections, 
and against the right of workers to freely join and form unions. </p>
<p>Likewise, I want working Americans to know that the &quot;budget battle&quot; in Washington isn't a fight 
about dollars --- we have plenty of those. It's a fight about who gets those dollars. It isn't a fight 
about government downsizing and returning power to the states, it's about a return to state's rights. 
Well, state's rights held working men and women in this country in VIRTUAL captivity for 200 
years while black men and women were being held in ABSOLUTE captivity. And it's time for us to 
tell our elected officials that as long as there is breath left in our bodies we will not go back. We will 
not return to those awful days in our history. </p>
<p>Finally, I want you to know the fight about affirmative action is more than a struggle to sustain a 
program that has put billions of richly-deserved dollars into the pockets of women and minorities 
who have been systematically cheated out of decent wages. </p>
<p>It's about whether the federal government should play a role in setting wage standards to protect 
workers from the unbridled greed of monopolistic multi-national employers. If affirmative action 
goes down, Davis-Bacon and the Service Contract Act and the Fair Labor Standards Act and the 
minimum wage will soon follow and it is time for us to tell our elected officials that as long as there 
is a breath in our bodies, we will not allow that to happen. </p>
<p>Thank you very much .....</p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="/publ/publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
