<head>
<title>SP 02/21/96 Sweeney's Press Conf. Feb 21</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<h3 align="center">Statement by John J. Sweeney<br>
President of the AFL-CIO<br>
AFL-CIO Executive Council Meeting </h3>
<h4 align="center">Bal Harbour, Fla.<br>
February 21, 1996 </h4>
<p>JOHN SWEENEY: I know the New Hampshire primary results are a
big topic today, so I thought I'd start by sharing the statement
I made to the Executive Council this morning: </p>
<p>Quote: the media will be asking, &quot;Isn't Patrick Buchanan
really singing your song with his messages about the wage gap,
the plight of workers and the need for new trade protections. If
he gets the Republican nomination, will you endorse him? Will he
attract union votes?&quot; Here's my response: Patrick Buchanan
is a racist, he's anti-semitic, he bashes women right along with
labor and immigrants and he's a believer in supply-side
economics. </p>
<p>We are none of those things. </p>
<p>Our movement isn't about dividing people through fear, it's
about bringing people together through compassion. </p>
<p>We don't want to build a wall around our country, we want to
tear down walls in other countries ---- not so workers compete
one against the other, but so working families everywhere can
share a decent portion of what their labors produce. </p>
<p>Candidate Buchanan has come very late to the issue of
declining worker incomes in the midst of economic plenty. He is
against the minimum wage, he is against wage standards, against
worker health and safety protections, against the right of
workers to freely join and form unions and FOR the supply-side
economic policies that have transferred billions of dollars from
the tattered pocketbooks of middle-income Americans to the
silklined purses of the rich over the past 15 years. </p>
<p>And his positions on trade and immigration aren't our
positions at all. Our opposition to NAFTA wasn't opposition to
open markets, we were against the treaty because it lacked
appropriate worker protections, environmental, human rights and
union rights standards. Expanding our exports means good jobs and
we're for it. But we have to demand that we are not discriminated
against in foreign markets. And we have to insist that workers in
other countries be paid enough money to buy the goods we want to
export. </p>
<p>When it comes to immigration, our positions are also very far
from Buchanan's. We're opposed to refugee or family caps and more
restrictive laws and bureaucracies, specifically the creation of
any sort of national registry or database to track illegal
immigrants. We led the fight against immigrant-bashing in
California. We opposed President Clinton's recent executive order
on immigration and we told him so. </p>
<p>Saying Patrick Buchanan speaks for workers is like saying the
Ayatollah Khomeni speaks for priests and rabbis. I don't think
working Americans are going to be fooled by a Presidential
candidate who talks the talk, but won't walk the walk. End quote. </p>
<p>This morning we had visits from Senator Rockefeller and
Senator Wyden, along with Marian Wright Edelman of the Children's
Defense Fund. Their sobering remarks provided a fitting framework
for our deliberations, which were about our legislative and
political activities. </p>
<p>We approved three statements which will guide our program this
year, and you have them before you. </p>
<p>In the federal legislative arena, we're going to build on a
grassroots lobbying campaign that generated more than 500,000
telephone calls to members of Congress last year and repulsed
efforts by the radical right to roll back 50 years of social
progress led by labor. </p>
<p>Our aim this year is to broaden local bases of informed and
involved workers, train more members in grassroots techniques and
continue to refine our ability to monitor and hold accountable
the candidates we elect to office. </p>
<p>Our legislative agenda is very full. We're going to continue
to defend Medicare and Medicaid beneficiaries from cost increases
and loss of coverage, children of working families from loss of
access to education, and workers from loss of their wage and
workplace standards protections. </p>
<p>We're going to oppose proposals on Medicaid and welfare reform
being advanced by the National Governor's Association. We're
going to oppose efforts to repeal Davis-Bacon, the Service
Contract Act, the 40-hour week and the minimum wage. We're going
to resist efforts to establish company unions, tampering with
rights of workers to freely join and form unions, diminish the
effectiveness of OSHA. We're going to attack corporate welfare
and immigrant-bashing initiatives. </p>
<p>We're going to mount a political action effort of
unprecedented scale, with every union doing its share by
contributing ideas, money, staff, media and materials. While
implementation of our plan will benefit candidates who stand with
working families, that is not our primary goal. Rather, we will
build a base of working people who hold elected officials,
regardless of party, accountable and who will inject workers'
rights and values into our national debate. </p>
<p>To help fund our efforts and consider our presidential
endorsement, the Executive Council authorized me to call a
special AFL-CIO convention and I will do so as quickly as we can
clear dates and accommodations. </p>
<p>The actions we took this morning are the component parts of a
program we think will propel working families back into the
center of American politics. </p>
<p>With me here this morning to help answer questions are Peggy
Taylor, director of the AFL-CIO department of legislation, and
Steve Rosenthal, our political director. But first I'd like to
call on Gerry McEntee, the chair of our political action
committee, to make a few comments. </p>
<p>REPORTER: You had said $35 million in January. This comes to
$23 million. Will the individual unions be making up the
difference? </p>
<p>GERRY MCENTEE: It comes a little higher than that, probably in
around $24 or $25 million. It's important to note, 1199 came in
yesterday. Dennis Rivera on behalf of that union pledged
$500,000. He also pledged 10 staffers and other unions are
pledging staff help in support. The federation has pledged that
they will come forward with dollars, as well. John, Linda
ChavezThompson and Rich Trumka have not, as of yet, decided on an
exact figure. So, we are not sure what that is going to be. But
we do know that when they do decide, it will bring us very close
to the $35 million goal and target. </p>
<p>When we are at that point, we have agreed among ourselves that
a number of unions that are better of financially and healthier
than some of our other unions will sit down and the difference
will be made up. </p>
<p>It was a target of $35 million. It was a goal of $35 million.
We believe and everybody has made the commitment to reach that
goal. </p>
<p>REPORTER: What are the current per capital payments monthly. </p>
<p>MCENTEE: Does anybody know the answer to that? I don't know
it. We'll get the answer to that back to you. </p>
<p>REPORTER: Given the strong showing of Patrick Buchanan, do you
have plans to go ahead and endorse President Clinton? </p>
<p>SWEENEY: The endorsement issue will be taken up at the special
convention. </p>
<p>REPORTER: How does this Labor '96 plan relate to the proposal
Sen. Rockefeller talked about some time back, trying to get a
unified message that would distinguish Democrats from
Republicans? </p>
<p>SWEENEY: Message is just one part of the program. Steve why
don't you say a word about that. </p>
<p>STEVE ROSENTHAL: I think that this program came about as a
result of input from the political directors of a number of
unions. We convened a group of political directors of the various
affiliates following President Sweeney's election and took a look
at what everybody did well and what we needed to improve on. The
program that we came up with is a unified effort to bring
together all of our unions in a plan that will generate the kind
of energy, excitement and enthusiasm and inject back into the
national debate issues that are important to working families. </p>
<p>That's what this is really about -- informing and involving
members in getting the national debate to come back to one that
details the issues and needs of working families. </p>
<p>REPORTER: For all his warts, hasn't Pat Buchanan's campaign
brought worker issues to the forefront in the campaign? Despite
all the ugly parts of his message, hasn't he helped to elevate
worker issues? </p>
<p>MCENTEE: I personally feel like a songwriter who wrote a song
about 7 years ago and he couldn't get anybody to publish it or
sing it and then all of a sudden Pat Buchanan is singing part of
it, Bob Dole is singing part of it, probably Lamar Alexander,
once he looks at the polls in an consistent way, will be singing
part of it. </p>
<p>I think that Pat Buchanan has articulated it to a degree. But
only in a particular sphere. There are many worker issues that he
has not talked about, that he is opposed to. When you judge Pat
Buchanan's candidacy, you have to look at the whole of Pat
Buchanan. If you would go back and look at some of those
Crossfire shows and what he said about American workers -- the
minimum wage, striker replacement and a whole host of issues
pertaining to American workers -- I think you'll find that he is
not shoulder to shoulder or a friend of American workers. He's
got part of a program out there right now where he is talking
about the difference between corporate executives and
corporations in America as compared to American workers. On that
single piece he is right. He has brought it to the front burner.
We've been trying to get it on to the front burner, but that's
only a very small piece of Pat Buchanan. </p>
<p>REPORTER: Regarding him singing this song, is there a danger
that you might lose the message -- that it will be claimed by
people you consider not to be friends of labor? </p>
<p>MCENTEE: I don't know that we are afraid of losing the
message. If Bob Dole would go back to the Congress of the United
States and get them to debate the minimum wage and to pass the
minimum wage. It's wonderful to go out on the stump and make all
these promises and talks. They can return to the Congress of the
United States. There's all kinds of legislation pending that
would help American workers. The proof is in the pudding. If they
go back and do that, then that's a different kind of ball game.
To go out on the stump and look at the polls and deal with the
polls in terms of the American people is another. </p>
<p>We don't believe that the American labor movement is going
lose it's message. </p>
<p>Out message is broader than what Pat Buchanan is talking
about. It's a message that we've had for a long period of time. </p>
<p>ROSENTHAL: As a follow up to that, for the last year, plus, we
have seen the worst assault on working families ever by this
Congress. Virtually every protection for working families has
been under attack -- from Medicare and Medicaid, the eight-hour
day, health and safety on the job, the right to form unions,
student loans, education. When Pat Buchanan is ready to reject
that agenda and to come out with a progressive agenda that is
going to be good for working families ... That's what we are
about, we talking about what's good for working Americans.
Hopefully, the debate should move in that direction. </p>
<p>REPORTER: This is a question for Mr. Sweeney or Mr. McEntee.
Mr. Sweeney just issued a stinging repudiation of Mr. Buchanan.
Do you think the administration is doing enough to counter the
position of Mr. Buchanan and to address the problems of American
workers? </p>
<p>MCENTEE: I think that the president and his administration has
done any number of things in terms of American workers. When you
look at the president's legislative agenda, the minimum wage, I
think members of his administration have gone beyond the
president. Secretary of Labor Reich has put forth a program in
terms of corporate America reform, corporate responsibility in
the community. </p>
<p>But I think it's right to say that we are in the business of
prodding the president more about the issues effecting working
Americans, in terms of wage lag, in terms of a level of job
insecurity that is still out there. I think that in the recent 10
days you have heard the president speak more and more on these
issues. The positions that he has taken on the Federal Reserve
Board when he came forward with the appointment of Felix Rohatyn. </p>
<p>As you know the Federal Reserve Board has a lot to do with the
economy and with growth. He came forward with a candidate that
believes in a tad more inflation -- which would be less
unemployment in our country, which would mean a little more
scarcity in terms jobs, which would mean more growth in terms of
our country. And he was rebuffed by the same kinds of people that
we were talking about earlier -- Republicans and Bob Dole,
particularly Connie Mack of Florida. </p>
<p>We will continue to prod the president and Democratic
politicians to speak more forcefully out on these issue. But when
you compare the record of President Clinton and the Democratic
men and women in Congress to the Republicans, when you look at
the Republican's Contract with America, I don't think there is
much of a question. But we'll continue to prod. </p>
<p>REPORTER: Why are you going through the endorsement process
differently than you have in the past? And where will you have
the convention? Here in Bal Harbour? </p>
<p>SWEENEY: I've said before, the convention will be in
Washington, D.C. The reason that we are having the special
convention is because an assessment of this magnitude requires a
convention. The General Board could not approve an assessment of
15 cents. </p>
<p>Ken, you asked about the current per capita. It's 42 cents per
member, per months. This is 15 cents is on top of that. </p>
<p>REPORTER: Is the endorsement process a matter of convenience
that you will happen to have a convention at the time that you
want to make the endorsement and that's why you are using the
convention instead of a General Board? </p>
<p>SWEENEY: No, actually the convention brings together a broader
representation of the membership and since we aren't going to
have a convention for the financial considerations, it makes a
lot of sense to also take up the endorsement question. </p>
<p>REPORTER: How soon might that convention be? </p>
<p>SWEENEY: We are hoping it will be on March 25th in Washington,
D.C. </p>
<p>REPORTER: You said a base of 100 activists in every
congressional district. Will you be setting up some sort of
organization for that? How does that work with your organizing
plans? </p>
<p>ROSENTHAL: We are going into every union in the district
councils and central labor councils. We'd like to organize house
visits like we do during organizing campaigns where our members
call together groups of 8 and 10 of their coworkers and come
together in the evening. We'll talk about what the issues are.
We'll talk about what's going on in the country and where we fit
in as working families. At the end there will be a pledge that we
will be asking members to sign where they will agree to work 30
hours during the course of this election to move issues to
working families forward. </p>
<p>We used this in Oregon. We signed up about 300 rank-and-file
members of our various affiliates to be active in the campaign
and beyond the campaign so that there is an organization there in
place permanently to continue to work year round on these
legislative and political issues. </p>
<p>REPORTER: Will you be endorsing particular candidates in this
campaign, or will this be just an issues campaign? </p>
<p>ROSENTHAL: This campaign itself is an issue-driven campaign.
We are going to involve our members around the issues and inject
those issues into the debate. </p>
<p>This does not change the normal process of central labor
councils and state federations endorsing candidates and working
to support those candidates. The various affiliates of the
federation will endorse candidates and provide the kind support
for them that they always have in the past. This does not
preclude that. But in this campaign what we are talking about is
really issue driven. </p>
<p>REPORTER: As a follow up to that, on the previous day, on your
America Needs a Raise statement, you set out a list of guidelines
for endorsement of candidates. If a candidate is right on six of
those issues but wrong one, where does that leave the candidate
in terms of endorsement? </p>
<p>SWEENEY: Those are the decisions that will be made within
central labor councils and state federations as well local unions
and affiliates in the various congressional districts and states
around the country. </p>
<p>REPORTER: Mr. Sweeney, you said for organized labor to do what
you want to do, it needs to grow. With AFL-CIO unions
representing so few American workers, could Pat Buchanan become
the representative of working people? Is there a danger that
Buchanan could be looked to by American workers instead of to
organized labor? </p>
<p>SWEENEY: I think that with our plans for this campaign --
which is issue driven, which has a major education component, as
well as a communications component -- working within our own
organizations, with our membership, we are building up a
grassroots campaign structure of activists among our members who
will be talking to there fellow workers and working within their
own community educating folks on the issues. </p>
<p>Patrick Buchanan, as we have said 100 times, may be
articulating the values that workers are concerned about, he is
not, as Gerry McEntee said earlier, coming up with the solutions.
And the easiest one is the minimum wage. He has yet to support
the minimum wage. </p>
<p>REPORTER: When you issue the call for a special constitutional
convention, will there be any other issues besides the special
assessment? </p>
<p>SWEENEY: I believe the Council meeting is not finished yet, so
something else could come up. But as of this time, it's basically
the political issue. </p>
<p>REPORTER: Originally you said 75 congressional districts. Now
you're saying you want to put activists in every congressional
district. What happened to the 75 districts? </p>
<p>SWEENEY: We are going into every congressional district, every
area of the country where we have membership. This will be a
national campaign from the bottom up. This is not a top down
campaign. We will be building on our strongest resource -- our
membership activism. </p>
<p>REPORTER: What happened to the 75 districts? </p>
<p>SWEENEY: We've increased the number. </p>
<p>Thank you all very much.</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../index.htm">Public Documents Page</a> | <a
href="../publsear.htm">Public Documents Search</a></p>
