<html>

<head>
<title>Sp 02/20/96 Sweeney Press Conference</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h3 align=center>AFL-CIO Executive Council Meeting<br>
Press Briefing<br>
Tuesday, February 20, 1996<br>
Bal Harbour, Fla.<br>
</h3>
<p>JOHN J. SWEENEY: This morning the Executive Council participated in a full briefing on the 
economic situation of workers and their families, the issue we believe is central to the debate over 
the future of our country. </p>
<p>We reviewed several &quot;living wage&quot; initiatives now underway in cities and states. And we approved 
a statement, which you have before you, linking the federation's legislative, organizing, bargaining 
and political efforts under a single, powerful theme. </p>
<p>&quot;America Needs a Raise&quot; is an expression of concern on behalf of millions of workers and their 
families. While productivity, profits, executive pay and the stock market keep going up, workers' 
incomes keep going down. The gap between the rich and the rest of us is becoming a sinkhole of 
social and economic conflict, and if we don't fill it in, it is going to swallow us all. </p>
<p>Workers are having to labor harder and longer just to keep even and more and more family 
members are having to work in order to maintain living standards. Working families have little 
money to spend, they are loaded with debt, and they have no time to spend with their children. 
Threatened by restructuring, downsizing, pension raids, privatization schemes and runaway plants, 
their anger is exceeded only by their anxiety over keeping their jobs. They are disgusted with 
business and government and their disillusionment is straining the fabric of our society. </p>
<p>With the help of Secretary of Labor Robert Reich, Congressman Dave Obey and Geoff Garin of 
Garin-Hart Research, we presented a huge challenge to the Executive Council: With workers and 
their families hurting as never before, it is us, America's unions, who must take responsibility for 
closing the wage and wealth gap and restoring respect for workers and the jobs they do. </p>
<p>The Executive Council accepted the challenge and we will begin the job by asking workers to 
speak out publicly about their lives and their jobs and to offer guidance toward solutions. From 
March through May, we will hold town hall meetings in the 27 cities on the list you have before 
you. Our goal: to transform individual concerns into a compelling national cause, sensitizing 
politicians and policy-makers as we mount a massive educational campaign to motivate 
unrepresented as well as represented workers. </p>
<p>We'll take what we've learned and raise the issue of income inequality to a new level of public 
visibility. We'll use it to drive our grassroots lobbying against cuts in programs working families 
depend on. And it will fuel a nationwide organizing drive to bring union wages and benefits to 
workers who need and deserve them. </p>
<p>Finally, we will use &quot;America Needs a Raise&quot; to evaluate the political candidates who want our 
support and to help them campaign on this most important of issues. </p>
<p>We also heard this morning from Treasury Secretary Bob Rubin. This afternoon, we will hear from 
Susan Bianchi-Sand, president of the &quot;Council of Presidents&quot; of women's organizations and from 
Steve Protulis, director of the National Council of Senior Citizens. </p>
<p>At the conclusion of the Executive Council meeting around 3:30, I'll come down to the press room 
and make a couple of important announcements. Then, at 4 p.m., I'll join Steve and 500 senior 
citizens at a rally here in the hotel in the Crystal Room and make my views know on the Social 
Security privatization schemes being floated by the Concord Coalition, Steve Forbes and Senators 
Kerrey and Simpson. </p>
<p>Joining me here today are our Secretary-Treasurer Rich Trumka, our Executive Vice President 
Linda Chavez-Thompson and George Becker the president of the Steelworkers, who is the new 
chairman of our Economic Policy Committee. </p>
<p>Questions? </p>
<p>REPORTER: In your statement, you say you will speak out and support candidates who pledge to 
support your recommendations. Will you then work against candidates to do not make such a 
pledge? </p>
<p>SWEENEY: We will be motivating our membership and educating our membership as to what the 
position is among the candidates on this issue as well as other issues. We will be encouraging our 
members to be active in political campaigns and supporting candidates who are supportive of our 
recommendations. </p>
<p>REPORTER: What are some of the concerns people are expressing about the Republican 
candidates, and did you discuss the endorsement of President Clinton? </p>
<p>SWEENEY: We have not discussed the endorsement of President Clinton. We have been 
developing the programs that we are announcing. Yesterday's discussion around organizing and 
today's discussion is about &quot;America Needs a Raise&quot; and the economy. Tomorrow, we will have 
our political discussion. </p>
<p>REPORTER: How did you choose the sites for town meetings? Will you and other officers 
preside? Can you give us an idea of the mechanics of the meetings? </p>
<p>SWEENEY: Many of these cities are cities where the income gap has been most pronounced and 
where the change that has been created over the past several years in terms of greater numbers of 
poor and working poor families, many are where we have a strong membership. We will be laying 
out more specific plans about these hearings as we develop them. But I can assure you that all the 
leadership of the federation -- the three officers as well as the members of the Executive Council -- 
will be involved in these hearings. There is a rather short time frame and many cities to cover. We 
will be calling upon all the leadership of the American labor movement. </p>
<p>REPORTER: On your criteria for endorsements, let me give you an example. In 1994, the Illinois 
AFL-CIO did not endorse Dan Rostenkowski, even though he had an 11-1 voting record, 
because he voted wrong on NAFTA. Under these guidelines, would you have endorsed 
Rostenkowski? </p>
<p>SWEENEY: You'll have to wait and see. </p>
<p>REPORTER: As part of your campaign on &quot;America Needs a Raise,&quot; will you be focusing on the 
Federal Reserve and the issue of interest rates? Will you be speaking out on who will be the chair 
of the Fed? </p>
<p>SWEENEY: We will be discussing this afternoon the opposition on the Federal Reserve and our 
position on the policies of the Federal Reserve. It has been a subject for the Economic Policy 
Committee. We had hoped to get to it this morning, but we didn't. We'll have more to say about it. </p>
<p>REPORTER: Do you see publicly funded jobs programs as part of the solution in &quot;America Needs 
a Raise?&quot; </p>
<p>SWEENEY: Sure. </p>
<p>REPORTER: I think this is a laudable program. Are you intending to shame corporations into this? 
Because it is the corporations that must come forward and respond in order for America to get a 
raise. </p>
<p>SWEENEY: These are all the things you've been telling us to do. </p>
<p>We'll have to wait and see, but we intend to promote those employers who we think are doing a lot 
of what we think is in the best interest of their most precious resource, which is their work force. 
We will certainly be making examples of those who are not -- look at the cover of Newsweek 
today. </p>
<p>REPORTER: In hitting these target cities, what kind of coalitions will you be mobilizing to work 
with you? </p>
<p>SWEENEY: All of the above. We intend to mobilize all our allies and we will probably be 
developing new relationships with new allies, folks who are seriously concerned about this issue 
and the effect that it's having on American workers. </p>
<p>REPORTER: What did the Secretary of the Treasury tell you about the reappointment of Alan 
Greenspan, or the appointment of a deputy chairman? </p>
<p>SWEENEY: He acknowledged the fact that Felix Rohatyn had been under consideration and 
expressed disappointment that there was strong Republican opposition and that Felix Rohatyn had 
withdrew his name from consideration. We talked a little bit about the Federal Reserve Board, but 
there was no further discussion about any appointments to the Board. </p>
<p>REPORTER: Who are the employers who are doing a good job in dealing with their workers and 
who are not? </p>
<p>SWEENEY: I really don't want to get into that right now. We are in the process of developing a 
list. The Labor Department has been working on this as well. We expect that we will have a 
continuing development of examples of good guys and bad guys. </p>
<p>REPORTER: A list of good guys and a list of bad guys? </p>
<p>SWEENEY: There will certainly be some recognition for those who are doing good programs and 
those who have been focused on serious labor-management programs and have been addressing 
the human resource issues and the training and making sure that their workers share in the high 
productivity and high profitability of businesses. </p>
<p>REPORTER: What sort of leverage would you expect your organization to have to persuade 
companies on the bad-guy list to conform to the kind of guidelines you are talking about? </p>
<p>SWEENEY: We will be using every technique and tool that we can possibly use in terms of 
promoting and communicating essentially with our membership. If employers are in violation of 
some of the laws that are meant to protect workers, we will be calling upon the Department of 
Labor to enforce those laws and to penalize those who are violating safety and health, fair labor 
standards. </p>
<p>REPORTER: I mean in terms of raising wages. </p>
<p>SWEENEY: There will be a continuing campaign. You will have to wait and see how some of 
these situations develop and how some examples are developed as well. </p>
<p>REPORTER: Are you prepared to go beyond the usual confrontational tactics? </p>
<p>SWEENEY: We will build bridges..... and if necessary we will block bridges. </p>
<p>REPORTER: From all the Democrats, except the treasury secretary, we heard that they're serious 
about policies to promote corporate responsibility. Do you foresee the administration pressing the 
issue? </p>
<p>SWEENEY: We are finding that there is a great deal of interest. We think that it is very sincere 
interest in focusing more and more on these issues. We have the highest expectations that there will 
be cooperation and support. </p>
<p>REPORTER: Are you happy with the way the idea is moving on Capitol Hill... </p>
<p>SWEENEY: We are continuing to be involved in those discussions and continuing to monitor the 
situation. </p>
<p>REPORTER: I mean the pace and the level of discussion, in terms of the specifics . . . </p>
<p>SWEENEY: I think that it is a little premature to really speak to that at this point, but there is 
tremendous interest and there has been close coordination and cooperation. </p>
<p>REPORTER: With regard to the good-guy, bad-guy lists, will consumer boycotts be considered? 
Where will these lists be drawn up, at the AFL-CIO or the Labor Department, I'm confused on 
that. </p>
<p>SWEENEY: We haven't arrived at the point of being able to be any more specific. As we develop 
this, we will be advising the press. But I think that you can see from the resolution that was adopted 
that this is intended to be a very comprehensive campaign. As we develop the specifics of it, we 
will be advising you. </p>
<p>REPORTER: On the wildcat strike at the Dodge plant, do you think things like that will crop up at 
other times? What do you plan to do about it? </p>
<p>SWEENEY: Rich Trumka. </p>
<p>RICHARD TRUMKA: I think those types of situations are a manifestation of the continuing 
frustration. Those are what happens whenever the internal mechanism for workers and employers 
to cooperate break down. </p>
<p>Obviously, we don't want to see those happen in the future. We'd like to see every worker and 
every employer be able to sit down and work out a solution amicably without loss of work or any 
kind of disruption. That's the best thing that could happen. </p>
<p>But whenever you get an employer who short circuits that or closes off the resolution mechanisms, 
you have those kind of disruptions. Hopefully, you won't see them in the future. It's the same thing 
with raises. You're seeing people being more frustrated with it because their needs aren't being met. </p>
<p>REPORTER: At the same time, the union supported the company and not the workers. </p>
<p>TRUMKA: I disagree with your characterization. I don't think that the union didn't support the 
workers there. I think they did in fact support the worker there. </p>
<p>SWEENEY: I think George Becker will be able to answer that. </p>
<p>GEORGE BECKER: Briefly, I just know that there is a dispute going on. Certainly this is an 
internal matter with the Auto Workers. Steve Yokich is involved and knowledgeable about it. And 
he is the person that that has to be dealt with. </p>
<p>REPORTER: To some extent, the Republicans in New Hampshire are beginning to address some 
of the issues you address in this statement. I'd like to ask your views of the positions of Bob Dole 
and the rest of the Republicans. </p>
<p>SWEENEY: I think that it's great that the candidates are being educated on this issue and finally 
realizing that America's working families are in a time of crisis. </p>
<p>While they are recognizing the seriousness of the problem, or starting the recognize, I don't think 
that they are facing the serious solutions that it is going to require. </p>
<p>Thank you very much.</p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="/publ/publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
