<body>
<h3 align=center>AFL-CIO Executive Council Meeting<br>
Press Briefing<br>
Monday, February 19, 1996<br>
Bal Harbour, Fla. </h3>
<p>JOHN J. SWEENEY: Today's morning session of the AFL-CIO Executive Council was devoted 
entirely to the most important issue facing our movement, and that is organizing. </p>
<p>In my opening remarks to the Council I said we must all face a basic fact: we cannot bargain decent 
contracts for our members, nor can we obtain public policies that protect working families, unless 
we can build a substantially larger labor movement. </p>
<p>To build a larger labor movement, we must do two things. </p>
<p>First, we have to devote considerably more resources to organizing more resources at the 
AFL-CIO, more resources from our national unions and more resources from our local unions. </p>
<p>Secondly, we need to expend these resources in smart and strategic ways, working together as a 
movement, rather than as a collection of individual unions. </p>
<p>In addition to reports from Arthur Coia, the chair of our organizing committee, and from Richard 
Bensinger, our director of organizing, we heard from Allison Porter, director of the Organizing 
Institute and from several workers and organizers who are currently involved in campaigns. </p>
<p>The Council responded by approving a strategic plan for promoting organizing among our unions as 
well as a plan for the AFL-CIO's own organizing program. </p>
<p>We also approved comprehensive guidelines for the national organizing fund we set up last fall. </p>
<p>I'm going to ask Arthur Coia to comment further on the organizing statement, which you have 
before you, and I want you to hear from Monica Russo, one of the organizers who spoke. </p>
<p>But we go any further, I have a little surprise. Karen, will you join me up here. This is Karen 
Nussbaum, and I just stole her from Bob Reich. (Applause) </p>
<p>As you all know, Karen is now the Director of the Women's Bureau at the Department of Labor. 
She is one of the most commanding and articulate leaders in the labor movement and her 
appointment is a clear statement on behalf of the AFL-CIO that we are there for the working 
women of our nation. </p>
<p>Karen has agreed to be the director of a newly formed Working Women's Department at the 
AFL-CIO and I've charged her with developing a program that will inject the issues and concerns 
of working women into every nook and cranny of our movement and with making the labor 
movement a strong, activist voice for working women. </p>
<p>She will be coming to the Federation in early March. Karen, would you like to say a few words? </p>
<p>KAREN NUSSBAUM: Thank you very much, President Sweeney. I started as a young clerk 
typist in the early 1970s and I was caught up then in the belief that if you came across injustice, it 
was both your right and your obligation to do something about it. And that it was also possible to 
make change. And I took those beliefs into the workplace and with friends started 9-to-5, National 
Association of Working Women which is now a national organization representing women office 
workers. </p>
<p>But we needed more, so we built a new home for office workers in the trade union movement, 
District 925 of the Service Employees International Union, which combines the character and the 
concerns of the working woments movement with the clout of a union. And it is there that I 
experienced first hand John Sweeneyts leadership and itts been my privilege to be able to work 
with him these many years. </p>
<p>I was honored to be chosen by President Clinton to be the 13th director of the Woments Bureau of 
the Department of Labor. I couldntt have enjoyed it more. I might have enjoyed it more if wetd had 
a Democratic Congress, I still enjoyed it greatly. Bob Reich is a great Secretary of Labor and itts 
been a privilege to work for him. </p>
<p>But itts the working women Itve met who have meant the most to me. Over the last three years, 
Itve crossed the country and met with women from many, almost every kind of job -- casino 
workers in Las Vegas, construction workers in Cleveland, clericals in Richmond, nurses in Boston, 
executives, poultry workers, flight attendants, machinists. Over a quarter of a million women 
personally filled out a survey for the Woments Bureau, many of them pouring out their hearts not 
long ago. </p>
<p>Herets what Itve learned. That though their jobs could not be more different and their working 
conditions more different, what they want and what they need is very much the same. And though 
they are eloquent about their problems, they have very little idea about what to do about them. 
Many times after an hourts conversation with a group of working women I think to myself -- they 
dontt need to be meeting with the director of the Woments Bureau, they need an organizer. </p>
<p>And the new Working Woments Department of the AFL-CIO is for these women. I know that 
they are waiting for us. Many of those conversations will stay with me, but in conclusion I just want 
tell you about one women who I think of especially today. Who when asked what she needed to 
make things better on the job, said, tItve got plenty of information, itts power I dontt have.t And I 
want to tell her today, tLinda, hold on, wetre coming and wetre going to make things better soon.t </p>
<p>SWEENEY: Thanks, Karen. Next, Itd like to call on Monica Russo, the Southern Regional 
Organizing Director for UNITE, to share with us some of the remarks she made to the Executive 
Council this morning. Monica. </p>
<p>MONICA RUSSO: Good morning everybody. First Itd like to take this opportunity to recognize 
my brother and sister organizers who are here with us and who also spoke this morning -- Bob 
Gorman with the IBEW, Yanira Merino with the Laborerts International Union and Joanne Joycline 
who is a UNITE volunteer. </p>
<p>I bring you greetings from UNITE, particularly from the southern region of UNITE which is where I 
live and have worked for the last 10 years. Itd like to share with you somewhat a little tidbit, a slice 
of life, a view from the trenches. </p>
<p>We talk to unorganized workers in the South every day. And what wetre seeing out there is that 
workers are tired. Workers are tired of getting their wages cut. Workers are tired of being 
understaffed, stretched out, fed up. Workers are tired of contracting out. Workers are tired of 
racism and sexual harassment. Theytre tired of temporary labor. Workers are tired of the abuse. 
What theytre most tired of is waiting. </p>
<p>Workers are waiting on us, the labor movement, to provide the leadership to fight back. The 
people are ready so, it is incumbent upon us as a labor movement to get out there in the street, roll 
our sleeves up, get our hands dirty, dig in and start fighting back. Wetve got to be ready to take 
some hits, because itts not easy out there. The only thing is that we cantt let them knock us out. We 
have to keep on fighting, keep on fighting, keep on fighting until we win. </p>
<p>For example, at Tultex in Martinsville, Va., where there are 2,500 workers who knit, dye, cut, sew 
and finish sweats for one of the largest fleece wear manufacturers in the world. UNITE, with the 
enormous help of the Organizing Institute and scores of our own rank-and-file activists members, 
ran three NLRB elections against this textile giant in five years before we won. And we finally won 
in 1994 because Tultex, after having won two labor board elections got, very arrogant and they 
started cutting workers and benefits and started taking advantage of people. At the same time, they 
were lining the top executivets pockets with a lot of money. So even after hiring several union 
busters, three to be exact, the workers overwhelmingly voted for union representation two to one. 
This victory, this huge margin enabled us to negotiate a top-of-the-line contract in the textile 
industry. The whole situation in Martinsville, Va., has changed to where mill workers and mill 
owners will never be the same. </p>
<p>During this same time period, this is since 1989, UNITE has organized over 10,000 private-sector 
workers in the South. We have engaged in dozens of first contract battles. From 600 union 
workers in Greensboro, Ga., who make socks for such prestigious customers as Adidas, to the 
K-Mart distribution center workers in Greensboro, N.C., where 550 predominately black and 
Hispanic workers won their union election and are now fighting in a militant battle against race 
discrimination and poverty wages. </p>
<p>In fact leaders in the Greensboro community have launched a full-scale boycott against K-Mart in 
Greensboro reminiscent of the Woolworth sit-in over 30 years ago to protest segregation. </p>
<p>And now, today in 1996, the Greensboro community leaders and the UNITE union members are 
fighting against racial and worker discrimination in Greensboro. All the way to Miami, Fla., where 
we are launching massive organizing drives involving hundreds of low-wage immigrant workers who 
work in health care industry from Haiti to Jamaica to Central America. </p>
<p>In closing, Itd just like to say that in the South we have learned that the only way to sustain 
ourselves through these grueling and tough fights is to develop a whole culture of organizing that 
goes from the shop floor to the union hall all the way to the international headquarters. And Itm 
proud to say that one of the first acts of our newly elected president of our union, our newly 
merged union, President Jay Mazur, was to commit major resources to organizing. Thatts the kind 
of commitment wetre looking for in the field, thatts the commitment we need in the field and thatts 
the kind of commit itts going to take to win. </p>
<p>So, in closing, I want to thank you, President Sweeney, for this opportunity to address the Council 
this morning. Out in the field we are thrilled because we see a new direction in the labor movement. 
Wetve been banging away long and hard for many, many, many years and we look forward to 
working in an environment where we can take more risks, pick more bigger fights and win bigger 
victories for workers in the South and all across America. </p>
<p>Thank you very much. </p>
<p>SWEENEY: Thank you Monica. Monica will be available as will the other organizers who are here 
throughout the whole press conference. </p>
<p>Next Itd like to introduce one who brings a tremendous amount of experience and energy as the 
new chair of the AFL-CIO Executive Council Organizing Committee. Hets the president of the 
Laborer's union, Arthur Coia. </p>
<p>ARTHUR COIA: Thank you, John. When John asked me to chair the Committee on Organizing, it 
was a deep privilege for me personally because I wanted to play a significant part in the new 
direction of the labor movement as we now see it. And especially leading the labor movement into 
the 21st century. </p>
<p>I can report to you that the committee has met. We met a number of times. It is comprised of the 
most aggressive labor leaders that we have seen. Labor leaders that are willing to restructure their 
own organizations. Labor leaders that are willing to take the extra step to lead by example, not by 
demand -- to say yes, when others say no -- who are willing to take a country and an organization 
into the 21st century. </p>
<p>We talked about different methods and opportunities that are before us. The committee addressed 
the financial resources that we hope to make available and will make available to those unions that 
are willing to restructure and willing to go forward, who will provide leadership and coordination 
support for respective organizations, promoting their efforts, willing to share with one another -- 
taking the good from all and distributing them making and curriculum assessments, development of 
strategic commands, promoting and coordinating the integration of political, legislative and legal 
activity. Especially raising the visibility and public profile of our federation and our respective 
organizations. </p>
<p>When we talk about organizing, we talk about a very significant priority in the federation. By not all 
means just that. We are going to be working very closely with the political committee on legislative 
issues and also on our public relations and communications committee, headed by Doug Dority. </p>
<p>So itts a coordinated effort. Itts not only one spoke thatts going to move the organization and move 
the federation forward under the leadership of John Sweeney. But itts a coordinated effort. Itts an 
effort that we hope and we know that we will succeed with. </p>
<p>So if anyone has any questions, I hope that I can answer them. </p>
<p>How about you Mr. Bernstein? </p>
<p>REPORTER: Whatts the difference between this and Operation Dixie 100 years ago? </p>
<p>COIA: I dontt think there is any difference now because the labor laws that we had then, we didntt 
have them. The labor laws that we have now are outdated. They are 60 years old, they need 
revitalization. And thatts why we are looking to a new Congress. And thatts why we are looking to 
the committee headed by Jerry McEntee to work closely with that committee to see a new day in 
Election 96. </p>
<p>So the legislation that is in front of us, labor law reform thatts needed, is very similar to where it was 
100 years ago. </p>
<p>But 100 years ago, we didntt have the power of the privilege, we didntt have the press with us and 
we didntt have any Congress with us. So itts almost the same as it is now. So we hope to rechange 
the imagery of the organization, we hope to get a new Congress for labor law reform. We certainly 
wontt have the power of privilege, though. </p>
<p>REPORTER: How will organizing work with politics? </p>
<p>COIA: In order to have a good organizing campaign, we need some substance behind us. And 
thatts were the law comes in, giving us the real opportunity to choose and select freedom of speech 
and freedom of opportunity coming through the most important thing of the law. So, through that 
activity, through election, through getting out the vote, through grass-roots opportunity, through our 
efforts to our communications department this will all work hand in hand. Without education, 
without communications we certainly cantt carry the message of organizing out there. </p>
<p>REPORTER: You suggested that money would be available to unions willing to restructure. What 
does that mean? </p>
<p>COIA: In order to provide our monies, wetll call it leverage money, not subsidy or grant money, 
those organizations that are willing to restructure not only their philosophy in organizing but to put 
out a meaningful organizing department, meaningful organizing staff to identify targets, to develop 
those targets, to develop ideas and to go forward. </p>
<p>This is not only an effort coming from the federation, but a coordinated effort coming from locals, 
districts and regional concepts out in the field. </p>
<p>REPORTER: What is the highest and the lowest percentages of funds allocated to organizing 
among AFL-CIO unions? </p>
<p>COIA: There are some unions out there that are providing significant amounts of money. I know 
that the Teamsters are have allocated in their budget approximately $25 million. The Laborerst right 
now, we have $6 million allocated for organizing. Bob Wages has just recently upgraded his 
organizing budget, where it was to a point below one percent. Now hets allocated 12 percent. So 
the idea is catching on, the concept is catching on. Organizing is certainly the theme of the day and 
it is certainly the theme of this administration. </p>
<p>REPORTER: How much money is available? How much are you looking to raise? </p>
<p>COIA: We hope to raise significant amounts of money. The heights and the goals are significant. 
More than $50 million. Under the leadership of John, wetll do that. Am I right John? </p>
<p>SWEENEY: Youtre right. </p>
<p>We are reviewing all of the programs of the federation and will be laying out plans in terms of the 
amount of resources and how itts going to be used and where the focus is going to be. As Arthur 
was saying, we are also going to raise a culture of organizing among the affiliates, national unions 
and local unions, working closely with the affiliates. The affiliates will be doing the organizing, the 
federation will be assisting and providing expertise as well as coordination -- encouraging 
multiunion campaigns where more than one union will be involved in particular campaigns. </p>
<p>REPORTER: When you say youtre revising programs, does that mean youtre planning to shut 
down part of the AFL-CIO, to lay off some people? </p>
<p>SWEENEY: We have an outstanding staff at the AFL-CIO and we are looking opportunities for 
developing new programs. This is a good example where there was no organizing department, 
there was a department that was called organization and field services. We have not created a new 
department. We are in the process of working with Richard Bensinger and Allison Porter on the 
changes that are taking place. We will be doing that with every department of the federation. </p>
<p>Richard and Allison are also available for any questions. </p>
<p>REPORTER: Can you talk about the guidelines? </p>
<p>SWEENEY: There are copies of the guidelines and the resolution in your packet. If you want to 
address a question to that you may. </p>
<p>REPORTER: Is the AFL-CIO saying that to get access to the organizing fund the union will have to 
restructure, to have strategic plans and the like? </p>
<p>SWEENEY: Thatts some of what the guidelines say, yes. </p>
<p>REPORTER: How many unions can now meet these guidelines? </p>
<p>SWEENEY: Itts not the unions that meet the guidelines, itts the programs and the proposals that 
the unions will be developing. I am assuming that those proposals would be developed in 
accordance with the guidelines as they are established. And there has to be flexibility involved as 
well in terms of tailoring programs to the needs of a particular industry or a particular jurisdiction. </p>
<p>REPORTER: Help me understand this. What number of unions could meet these guidelines? </p>
<p>SWEENEY: Every union could meet the guidelines. It may require changes in terms how they 
organize or it may require some assistance from the organizing department of the AFL-CIO, but 
every union has the potential to meet those guidelines. </p>
<p>REPORTER: How many have it now. If you were to give a snapshot right now, how many unions 
would fall in this category? </p>
<p>SWEENEY: I cantt give you a stock answer. We are in the process of entertaining and 
encouraging unions to submit proposals. We have some proposals already submitted which are 
under reviews. We will be working together with those unions to see how those proposals meet the 
guidelines. And if there are any changes that we have to recommend, wetll be doing that. </p>
<p>Richard do you want to say a word on the guidelines? </p>
<p>RICHARD BENSINGER: I think the basic concept, as President Sweeney is saying, is that 
traditionally in recent times we too often had just done hot-shop or single-shop organizing going 
worksite by worksite. In many cases, even when we win, we dontt have enough power because 
we haventt taken on either the whole industry -- if itts a service sector industry, we didntt take on 
all of that industry in one round or if itts a corporation, we needed the capacity to take on and 
change the David and Goliath formula where we are always the David. </p>
<p>Itts not just a question of money, itts a question of bringing strategic approaches -- which the 
AFL-CIO is developing an internal capacity to do. Itts a question of mobilizing our base. Itts a 
question of doing organizing smarter, but clearly doing it to scale. It really is more reminiscent of the 
30s. </p>
<p>REPORTER: So a union could come to you and say, tWe have met these guidelines.t Then, they 
could get some money? </p>
<p>BENSINGER: All sorts of things. One is that they can get the troops of the Organizing Institute, 
which has a huge focus on recruiting women and people of color. So, if we are going to organize a 
big target in a Latino community, hopefully, we will have the capacity. Itts going to be hard to 
expand the institute. We cantt expand so fast that we get ahead of ourselves here. But we are trying 
to double the capacity of the institute this year. </p>
<p>They can get strategic advice. They can get, I think, a partnership with the AFL-CIO in looking at 
joint strategic campaigns that really hasntt existed before. </p>
<p>REPORTER: Provide the organizational support? </p>
<p>BENSINGER: Right. </p>
<p>REPORTER: Would the possibility of winning come into play? </p>
<p>BENSINGER: I think President Sweeney would tell me yes. </p>
<p>REPORTER: Where will the money come from? Will you have to have a special assessment? </p>
<p>SWEENEY: Wait and see. </p>
<p>REPORTER: What kind of workers are you looking to organize? </p>
<p>SWEENEY: The thousand recruits that we will have in place this summer will be young workers 
who are active in campaigns as well as college students who have an interest in the values of the 
labor movement. Children of members. And we will be reaching out to young folks to get them 
involved and give them a taste of what the labor movement is all about and we will be looking to 
the affiliates to provide us with the opportunities of ongoing campaigns were these workers can 
learn something and make a contribution in terms of raising the visibility of the labor movement. </p>
<p>REPORTER: Is there a particular area of the country? Or a particular industry? </p>
<p>SWEENEY: It will be diversified. Every region of the country will be considered and every industry 
is a potential. </p>
<p>REPORTER: Are you formally beginning an effort to organize more people in the South? </p>
<p>SWEENEY: Yes, we will be putting more resources into the South and we will be encouraging 
affiliates of the AFL-CIO to organize in the South. And Itm sure that we will be receiving proposals 
from affiliates to do more organizing in the South. </p>
<p>REPORTER: Have you set a deadline for proposals to be submitted for this effort? </p>
<p>SWEENEY: No, this is a long-term program ongoing. There are some proposals already submitted 
and we expect that the number will increase and hopefully it will be a process that the AFL-CIO 
will be undertaking for many years. And changing where necessary in order to make the program 
as successful as we can. </p>
<p>REPORTER: Are there unions not going along? What are you saying to unions not going along? </p>
<p>SWEENEY: We have not heard any opposition to the program. In fact, we have heard enthusiastic 
support. Unions are excited about this. Organizers such as these wonderful people who are here 
today are very excited about it and we have high expectations. </p>
<p>REPORTER: How soon do you think youtll have an organization that will reverse the membership 
losses, to improve on the 10.4 percent private-sector unionization? </p>
<p>SWEENEY: The things that we are talking about are really longterm investments in organizing, 
long-term rebuilding of the culture of organizing. The resources that we put into the organizing and 
training institute, as an example, is a long time commitment to organizing, a continuous program. 
The folks we will be recruiting and training, hopefully, will be with the labor movement for many 
years. </p>
<p>BENSINGER: Corporate American at the flick of the switch can lay off 40,000 people. We dontt 
have a button to push or a magic answer, but I think in the long run we have a lot more the offer 
American workers. </p>
<p>REPORTER: How would you sum up what youtre doing today, in terms of this year? Are you 
planning to pick a particular target, or focus on the South, this year? </p>
<p>SWEENEY: We have some very good proposals that are in the process right now. We are not at 
liberty to reveal what they are. When we conclude the process and make some determinations, we 
will be announcing those. And I think you will see that they will be in different parts of the country. </p>
<p>REPORTER: How does union organizing connect with political action, strategic campaigns and 
communications? How does that all fit together? </p>
<p>SWEENEY: There is an interconnect between all of the programs that you have mentioned aimed 
at rebuilding the labor movement in the United States, turning around the decline in membership, 
creating a stronger political voice for American workers and improving the perception of the 
American labor movement, both within the movement as well as with the public. </p>
<p>REPORTER: What are you doing differently in Detroit? </p>
<p>SWEENEY: Is Rich Trumka here? Rich is chairman of the Strategic Approaches committee and he 
has been coordinating the efforts of that committee and meeting with the unions who are involved in 
the newspaper strike there? </p>
<p>Bill would you like to say a word? Bill Boarman is with CWA. </p>
<p>BILL BOARMAN: I think the total commitment of the labor movement in Detroit is much different 
than wetve had in past newspaper strikes. The AFL-CIO support for the unions there has been 
tremendous since day one and it continues to increase. Wetve had a number of meetings here 
planning strategy that will be, I think, unfolded later in the week and youtll hear about that. But I 
think overall itts just a combined effort by the unions to help each other. </p>
<p>In our industry our unions are relatively small and we are up against huge giants who many of you 
work for. And you can understand the problem. Itts a typical David and Goliath struggle for the 
newspaper unions. And so we really need the support of the AFL-CIO in addition to all of its 
affiliates. I think that itts been tremendous. I think itts working. I think the advertising campaign in 
Detroit and the circulation campaign and the alternative newspaper that the striking workers are 
putting out are all new ideas and all new concepts. And I think youtll see more added to that as this 
week unfolds. </p>
<p>REPORTER: Can I ask a followup question to that? What if you end up with just one newspaper? </p>
<p>BOARMAN: Well, we hope that won't be the case. That happened in Pittsburgh, as you well 
know. And thatts not our desire. But if the corporate giants -- the greedy people that are involved 
in really aggressing this strike at the cost of millions and millions of dollars to the shareholders, to 
the people in Detroit -- that'll be a decision that they'll have to make, but we certainly hope that isn't 
the case.</p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="/publ/publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
