<head>
<title>SP 02/19/96 VP Al Gore Press Conf at EC Mtg.</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h3 align=center>AFL-CIO Executive Council Meeting<br>
Press Briefing<br>
Vice President Al Gore<br>
Bal Harbour, Fla.<br>
February 19, 1996<br>
</h3>
<p>JOHN SWEENEY: We just had a good visit with the vice president and a very frank discussion 
about a number of issues. It is my honor to present to you Vice President Al Gore. </p>
<p>VICE PRESIDENT GORE: I thought he was going to make a longer statement. Itm used to 
standing there behind presidents when they speak at the microphone. Thank you very much, John. </p>
<p>Itll just give you a brief summary of what I said to the Council and then John Sweeney and I will be 
happy to respond to any questions that you might have. </p>
<p>I spoke at some length about the importance of President John Sweeneyts vision for the labor 
movement in the United States of America. Many of the problems that we face in our country, 
wage stagnation, the rising gap between the rich and poor, the difficulty families have getting by in 
spite of the economic progress that is so evident with the millions of new jobs and rising stock 
market and all the rest. A lot of these problems are due to the fact that legislation, policies and 
programs that are designed to help working men and women have not had the vigorous advocacy 
in the organized labor movement that they had when 34 percent of the work force was organized in 
the early 1950s. Labor has been just as vigorous, just as strong and just as determined in 
advocating its point of view, but with a smaller percentage of the work force, the overall impact has 
been somewhat less. </p>
<p>That is why John Sweeneyts vision is so important -- to organize those men and women who really 
want to bargain collectively and be a part of a movement that urges greater progress and justice in 
matters like job safety and health and so forth. </p>
<p>So, Itm very encouraged by what I see from this new team with John Sweeney and Linda 
Chavez-Thompson and Rich Trumka, both of whom are also here. And the whole new team that 
they have put together at the AFL-CIO. </p>
<p>President Clinton has worked very closely with President Sweeney and his team and one of the 
announcements that I made today to the Council was that the president will veto any bill that closely 
resembles the Ballenger Bill in the House or the Kassebaum Bill in the Senate to weaken and 
undermine OSHA. Wetve had thousands of work-related deaths each year, tens of thousands of 
work related injuries or workplace induced illnesses. This legislation which has suddenly arisen in 
the Republican Congress would really undermine and devastate OSHAts ability to do its job. And 
so I was pleased to announced today that the president would veto that legislation if it passes in its 
current form, either the House bill or the Senate. </p>
<p>We also look forward to working with John Sweeney and his team on issues across the board. We 
also look forward to working with them in a political context and I also shared with the Council my 
own first-hand impressions from the race in Oregon -- that organized labor put Ron Wyden over 
the top in that Senate race for a seat that has not been held by a Democrat for 34 years, I believe it 
is. And which was won by Ron Wyden after John Sweeneyts team put a lot of people on the 
ground in key roles organizing voters and getting the message out in that mail-in election campaign. </p>
<p>President Clinton and I want to continue that kind of partnership with the AFL-CIO. We are 
looking forward to their Union Summer activities, which are very promising. We look forward to 
working with them to prevent the kind of damage the Newt Gingrich-controlled Congress is 
attempting to do. And we believe that we will be successful. And then, of course, in November we 
are going to be working very hard together for the reelection of President Clinton and the 
Clinton-Gore ticket. </p>
<p>So, with that let me throw it open to your questions. </p>
<p>REPORTER: Did you talk about any of the other legislation in Congress and what the president 
would do? </p>
<p>GORE: Yes, the president will veto the TEAM Act or any legislation that attempts to create 
company dominated unions. Thatts not the American way. We dontt support that. The president 
will veto the TEAM Act. And as has been previously said, any measure that eliminates 
Davis-Bacon would also be vetoed. I said that last year. </p>
<p>REPORTER: There have been some proposals and some ideas kicked around by Sen. Kennedy, 
Labor Secretary Reich and just a few moments ago Congressman Gephardt about trying to use the 
tax structure to get corporations to be tbetter citizens.t Whatts the presidentts position on that? </p>
<p>GORE: Well, we believe that a variety of measures are warranted in the area of education, health 
care and child care. The president publicly called for passage of the Kennedy-Kassebaum Bill 
which requires portability of pensions. </p>
<p>The president has called for a tax deduction for educational expenses for college or technical 
school, up to $10,000. Where individual employees are concerned, of course, one of the biggest 
changes in our tax code in recent years was the change called for and passed by President Clinton 
to vastly expand the earnedincome tax credit. It has given a reduction of taxes of more than $1,000 
per family -- up to $1,600 per family of four -- for families making under $26,000 per year. Thatts 
been a huge change for the better because it is in those amounts spread out over so many millions 
of families. It doesntt get the headlines, it doesntt get the attention, but it has been a very big 
change. For the first time in 25 or 30 years, just in the last two years we have begun to see a slow 
rise in every income category. Itts not enough. As Itve said before, we want to take steps to 
accelerate it dramatically. Incidentally, one other measure that will very effectively deal with this 
growing gap between the rich and the poor would be an increase in the minimum wage. </p>
<p>I talked about that at some length in the meeting, as well. This year, without changes, the minimum 
will fall to a 40-year low, after you adjust for inflation. President Clinton and I believe the minimum 
wage must be increased. Every single Republican candidate is opposed to an increase in the 
minimum wage and the Republican majority leader in the Congress said he would fight any increase 
in the minimum wage with every breath in his body. Can you imagine? A person in a position like 
that, when the minimum wage is at a 40-year low, saying that he is going to fight any change with 
every breath in his body. It really is amazing. </p>
<p>But thatts what the election is all about in 1996 -- whether wages are going to grow or continue to 
stagnate. </p>
<p>REPORTER: As unions step up their organizing activity, as they have promised, more American 
workers will be faced on the job with a choice, yes or no on a union. How do you recommend they 
vote on that? </p>
<p>GORE: Thatts for them to decide given the circumstances as they judge them. Itve stated my view 
a few moments ago that in my opinion one of the reasons why progressive legislation has had 
rougher sailing in recent years, compared to the 50s and 60s, is the simple fact that instead of 34 to 
35 percent of the work force being organized, 16 to 17 percent of the work force is organized. But 
where an individual employee faces a choice, that is for that employee to decide. You deal with it in 
a pure hypothetical form, it depends on the circumstance. </p>
<p>REPORTER: As a followup to a previous question, did you discuss with the Council changing the 
tax code to penalize companies like Caterpillar and also changing to reward somebody like the 
manufacturer in Dewey, Mass. </p>
<p>GORE: No, we didntt discuss either of those companies. We did discuss the striker replacement 
issue as I did last year and again this year. </p>
<p>REPORTER: Pat Buchanan? What argument would you give voters for not going to his brand of 
solutions? </p>
<p>GORE: Itm going to try my best to stay out of the Republican primary contest. I was one who 
convinced myself in 1980 that if the Republicans would only nominate Ronald Reagan wetd be in 
great shape. I was burned so badly, I decided not to meddle in their primaries any more. </p>
<p>I think that even he [Buchanan] has refused to endorse an increase in the minimum wage. Isntt he 
opposed to an increase in the minimum wage? Itm going to resist getting involved in their primary. </p>
<p>REPORTER: What about wage stagnation? </p>
<p>GORE: Wage stagnation as Itve said is part of the challenge President Clinton and I signed on to 
meet. You remember the oftquoted slogan from the campaign war room back in 1992 -- tItts the 
economy, stupid.t </p>
<p>Well, it is still the economy. There are many issues that are of great concern to American citizens. 
The issue of values, how we strengthen families, how we raise our children, how we protect the 
environment and invest in education and protect Medicare. But it is still the economy that is the 
bedrock of our nationts ability to solve any of these problems. And dealing with the stagnation of 
wages requires policies like the earned-income tax credit, policies like an increase in the minimum 
wage, policies like portability of health insurance, policies like family leave. These deal with some of 
the issues that people in the workplace otherwise have to take out of their pocketbooks, and 
policies that are designed to make American business more competitive and share the profits and 
the wealth with those who earn them and who produce the productivity in the American workplace. </p>
<p>Thank you all very much.</p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="/publ/publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
