<html>

<head>
<title>SP 01/19/96 Chavez-Thompson to IUD</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h3 align=center>Remarks by Linda Chavez-Thompson<br>
Executive Vice President<br>
AFL-CIO<br>
<br>
IUD Southeast Regional Conference on Organizing,<br>
Workers' Rights and Coalition Building<br>
Atlanta, Georgia<br>
January 19, 1996<br>
</h3>
<p>My name is Linda Chavez-Thompson and I am here to help you kick some como se llama. </p>
<p>I see you speak Spanish. Well, since you speak Spanish, you know the Spanish word for &quot;yes,&quot; 
right? Then I want you to follow along and every time I make a statement you agree with, I want 
you to answer, &quot;Si,&quot; OK? </p>
<p>Here we go: Are we winning the budget fight? Are we saving Medicare and Medicaid and worker 
protections and student loans? Are we kicking Newt Gingrich's como se llama? Are we ready to 
give up on the American dream and roll over to corporate America? </p>
<p>I'm sorry, I forgot to tell you the Spanish phrase for saying &quot;NO&quot; to corporations and Republicans. 
Watch my lips and I'll show you. We say, &quot;Kiss my como se llama.....&quot; </p>
<p>I want to thank Elmer Chatak and the IUD for inviting me to join you here in Atlanta. You have a 
rare thing here, something you should treasure, something we rarely see in Washington, D.C. It's 
called &quot;sunshine.&quot; </p>
<p>I appreciate having the opportunity to be here at this regional conference and to speak on behalf of 
John Sweeney and Rich Trumka and the new AFL-CIO. I'm here without John and Rich because 
we believe in never sending two men to do a job one woman can do alone! </p>
<p>I think it's indisputable that a tremendous sense of energy and hope for meaningful change and 
progress was created by the victory of our New Voice leadership team at the AFL-CIO. The 
labor movement in America now has a window of opportunity we haven't seen for perhaps two 
decades or more. That opportunity is to once again become a forceful player in determining the 
nation's political agenda. And, ultimately, the opportunity is to use that power wisely on your behalf 
and that of all working families in America. </p>
<p>The theme of this conference -- &quot;organizing and coalition building&quot; -- could not be more timely. It 
speaks directly to how we can develop the tools and the strategies to take advantage of this 
opportunity, at this special moment in history. </p>
<p>As you know, the New Voice team pledged during our campaign that would invest heavily in 
organizing. We said we'd go anywhere and everywhere -- especially the South -- to organize and 
empower workers. And, in fact, plans are well under way to begin that effort during &quot;Union 
Summer,&quot; which is set to begin in just a few months. </p>
<p>We're going to send 1,000 young people, students as well as rank-and-file workers, into organizing 
campaigns in places like Georgia and Texas and California to help jump-start a movement to 
organize thousands and thousands of new union members. And then we're going to turn &quot;Union 
Summer&quot; into &quot;Union Fall,&quot; as we fan out across the country and launch a massive grass-roots 
campaign to take back the House of Representatives and to take back our country. </p>
<p>One of the most important things I've learned down through the years as an organizer, is that we 
need a lot of help in accomplishing these two great goals this year and the other goals to follow. 
That means &quot;coalition building&quot; in a new and bigger way. While common sense tells us we can all 
get ahead by working together, we have too often succumbed to the corporate imperative that 
drives wedges between people, and employs classic divide-andconquer strategies. New hires vs. 
experienced workers. Minorities vs. whites. African-Americans vs. Latinos. Women vs. men. New 
immigrants vs. not-so-new immigrants. Anything to keep working people from identifying with each 
other and coming together to advance their common interests. </p>
<p>Of course, we're not supposed to see it that way. Instead, we hear constantly about the changes in 
the economy that have created uncertainties and insecurities -- whether it's the global economy, or 
the decline in industrial jobs and growth of the service and information economy, or even the old 
canard that business is hamstrung by excessive government taxes and regulations. </p>
<p>It's always some unseen outside force. But what I see is a stock market that grew 33 percent in 
1995, with companies downsizing and workers paying the price. Is AT&amp;T an ailing company? Of 
course not! It's doing fabulously well. And how do they reward their work-force and move 
forward? They start the new year by eliminating more than 40,000 jobs! That's just the latest 
example. Last year we had an example of corporate &quot;coalition building&quot; when Chase Manhattan 
and Chemical Bank merged. That put 12,000 people out of work. In dozens of industries... in 
scores of cities... the price is paid by hundreds of thousands of workers and their families. </p>
<p>When that happens, you have no choice but to look out for No. 1 -- yourself. And the loyal 
workers who are the engine of the greatest economy on the planet are inevitably pitted against each 
other just to survive. But the reality is that as far as our common interests are concerned, 1996 is 
no different than 1976 or 1956 or the Depression days of 1936.<br>
Notwithstanding all the efforts to build artificial barriers between us, we all want the same things: 
job security, good wages and decent benefits providing health security for our families and income 
security after retirement. And all of us want to make sure our children have every opportunity to 
climb the ladder of success and achieve their dreams. Those are our common interests. Today, our 
challenge is to gain strength from that commonality to overcome our shared plight. In our struggles 
on behalf of working men and women no less than earlier fights for civil rights, we will win by 
reaching out to each other. </p>
<p>You know, the Republicans think they've re-invented the wheel by trying to build coalitions, too. In 
another of those tiresome articles about how those clever Republicans are supposedly remaking the 
capital, The Washington Post this week quotes a vice president of the Heritage Foundation as 
saying: &quot;There are different groups of conservatives who really believe the same thing but don't 
know it.&quot; </p>
<p>The article goes on to say they want to build coalitions not between liberals and conservatives, but 
among conservatives with different agendas, namely taxes, the environment, family values, even the 
elimination of entire departments of the federal government. This phenomenal insight that probably 
took years of deep thinking to uncover is, of course, what those of us in progressive politics have 
always understood to be the essence of activism in our democracy. Inclusive politics. Building 
bridges. Allowing for dissenting views. Eliminating unnecessary barriers and glass ceilings. </p>
<p>Look at me; look at where I am today. I can tell you from my heart, I am a proud Latina, but I 
know the long road I've traveled was paved not just by my own people, but also by many others 
working at coalition building, creating a whole greater than the sum of the parts. Within the 
AFL-CIO, the historic New Voice campaign has brought together the entire labor movement as 
never before, with the unions represented in this room feeling they are truly on equal footing in the 
federation. </p>
<p>We are witnessing in West Virginia, for example, the increasingly influential ACT Foundation -- 
composed of building and construction trades unions -- reaching out to environmentalists to put the 
brakes on the development of a pulp and paper mill unless it's built with West Virginia labor and 
using the safest and cleanest technology. It's not a perfect marriage, but so far by working together 
they've successfully overcome the governor, the federal government and a multibillion dollar 
international corporate giant that, after six years and counting, is very frustrated at not having its 
way. </p>
<p>Here's another grand coalition that is succeeding: Throughout the nation last year and this year, the 
working men and women of the AFL-CIO have stood shoulder to shoulder with community 
groups, with seniors and with people of all ages with disabilities to get the message out that we will 
not permit that como se llama, Newt Gingrich, to destroy Medicare, Medicaid and college loans 
while giving corporate America and the rich one more tax break. We've hit radical right members 
of the House with wave after wave of media advertising, demonstrations and we have driven the 
budget negotiations. </p>
<p>And it is because we need to mount an even bigger effort to inform the American public about what 
the Gingrich Republicans are doing that the AFL-CIO today is three days into our latest media buy 
-- a one-week, million-dollar run aimed at 27 robotic &quot;Newtoids&quot; marching in lockstep with the 
House speaker. One of the keys in labor's increasing visibility in all these campaigns is ever-greater 
emphasis on education and providing more information. No longer will we allow our enemies to get 
away with mischaracterizing us and our positions. We will not stay on the sidelines as others 
attempt to label working men and women as &quot;special interests&quot;. Those common interests I 
mentioned earlier are the core beliefs shared by virtually all Americans. </p>
<p>We've gotten quite a response already to this media campaign. Many of the freshman Republicans 
targeted are squealing like stuffed little pigs. They don't like it when someone calls them on the 
carpet by pointing out their votes to their constituents. Congress may still run itself like a circus, but 
the Republican fun-ride is over. They're not nearly as full of themselves today as they were just a 
few months ago, when they were carrying on about their &quot;Contract on America.&quot; </p>
<p>Those freshman clown-arounds must have thought no one would pay any attention when it came 
time to spell out in a serious way what their public policy agenda would mean for working families, 
for seniors, for students, for poor children, for people with disabilities, for single mothers. Brothers 
and sisters, that's our coalition. </p>
<p>Organized labor, through the AFL-CIO and its affiliated unions, is determined to bring that coalition 
together by devoting enormous time and resources to a year-long campaign we call &quot;America 
Needs a Raise.&quot; In early spring, the AFL-CIO will begin to hold hearings on the low-wage 
economy in communities across the country. We will ask working men and women what is 
happening to their jobs, their paychecks and to their family budgets. We'll take our show on the 
road -- from Iowa to New Hampshire, from the South to the Midwest and the Far West, to put the 
issue of wages at the center of political debate. </p>
<p>We're going to make family incomes the central political issue of 1996. Why?<br>
In a prophetic article in The New York Times last January, Louis Uchitelle brought it all into focus. 
&quot;Something is wrong with America's economic boom,&quot; he wrote. &quot;After four years of everstronger 
growth, people's wages should be going up faster than their expenses. For most people, they're 
not, and this is the first time in decades that a recovery has gone so long without putting more 
money in more pockets. And now, if the recovery runs out of steam in 1995 --- as so many 
economists predict --- that money might never show up.&quot; </p>
<p>What happened is that we've changed from a country concerned with raising the standard of living 
for all to a nation concerned only with raising wealth for a few. Between 1947 and 1973, the 
median paychecks of American workers more than doubled -- and the bottom 20 percent enjoyed 
the biggest gains. Since 1973, median earnings have fallen by about 15 percent, and the bottom 20 
percent have fallen the furthest behind. More than 40 percent of all earnings gains have gone to the 
richest 1 percent. Meanwhile, wealth became even more concentrated. The top 20 percent of all 
households now control more than 55 percent of all wealth. The rest of us -- 80 percent of all 
American households -- get to split the rest. </p>
<p>In every speech John and Rich and I make, we try to make this simple point: America needs a 
raise. And this year, we're going to demand that every candidate for public office tell working 
Americans how they'll get them a raise. We're going to hang a sign in the headquarters of every 
man or woman we support and it's going to read, &quot;It's wages, stupid.&quot; Come this September, we 
are going to organize and mobilize working Americans around the fundamental issue of raising 
wages and increasing incomes. If Americans vote on the issue of who can lift the poor and secure 
the middle class, I am confident they will make the right choices for president and Congress. </p>
<p>If we take that message to every workplace and every polling place, then we will win. And we can 
begin to close the gap between those who do the work of America and those who control their 
lives and livelihoods. </p>
<p>This is a great time to be part of the trade union movement in the U.S. Lots of people who think 
they're real smart have been writing us off for years, but here we are, in the middle of the biggest 
political dogfight in a very long time, battling to keep Newt from reversing more than 50 years of 
progress. </p>
<p>As I look around this room, I see the face of America. That same Washington Post article I 
referred to earlier also quotes some Republican genius as saying that people like us are simply on 
the wrong side of history, and that we just have to deal with it. Well, history is made by doers, not 
talkers. In the last several months I've had the opportunity to travel throughout the entire country. 
The American labor movement today is becoming a surging force for change. Evidently those 
Republican think-tank boys have a hearing problem, because they're missing the squealing &quot;oink, 
oink, oink&quot; we're provoking among their House freshman. </p>
<p>We have an obligation in 1996 to continue to get out our message, to work in our communities, to 
walk the walk. And when we do that, united, we will move our agenda of shared, common 
interests forward. Together, we can make history. </p>
<p>Thank you very much.</p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="/publ/publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
