<html>
<head>
<title>SP 12/14/95 -- Sweeney on SEIU L. 509 Representation</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<h3 align="center">Remarks by John J. Sweeney, President, AFL-CIO
on the Occasion of the Signing of Voluntary Recognition Procedure
Agreement Between Service Employees International Union Local 509
and Commonwealth of Massachusetts-funded Human Service Providers </h3>
<p><b>December 14, 1995 </b></p>
<p>Thank you. It really is a pleasure to be here. </p>
<p>It's a measure of how significant I think this event is -- for
the labor movement, for the entire employer community, for the
human service provider community and for those of us who believe
in the public sector's responsibility for the most unfortunate
among us-- that I changed my schedule so that I could join you
today, add my name to those of these visionary employers and
local union leaders, and still get back to Washington, D.C. for a
meeting with Democratic leaders who are searching for a humane
solution to our nation's budget crisis. </p>
<p>Two months ago, at the AFL-CIO convention in New York City,
there was a great debate about how workers and their unions
should relate to employers in our new economy. In his keynote
address, my old friend and former rival, Tom Donahue, said he was
more interested in &quot;building bridges than in blocking
bridges.&quot; He was referring to one of our SEIU locals in
Washington, D.C. blocking our busiest bridge across the Potomac
during rush hour one morning. </p>
<p>I responded by saying that when employers and other powerful
people refuse to respect working people, we have a moral
obligation to block bridges and even go to jail to dramatize
their plight. But, I was careful to add, I believe in building
bridges any time the shelling stops long enough for us to start
pouring concrete and putting up steel. </p>
<p>And that's what we're marking today -- the decision to stop
the shelling. These employers are choosing not to pick up the
traditional weapons of management anti-unionism. The union is
choosing not to base its strategy for growth in this industry on
knee-jerk anti-management rhetoric. And as is often the byproduct
of a cease-fire, a truly mutually beneficial peace can grow. </p>
<p>We are here to say that in exchange for these employers'
willingness to allow their employees to make a truly free choice
about whether or not to support unionization </p>
<p>without their discouragement, Local 509 (backed both by the
SEIU and my own office as President of the AFL-CIO) has committed
to form a &quot;New Partnership&quot; with these employers if
their employees choose 509 representation. </p>
<p>What's our notion of a partnership? The partnership has at its
core a shared commitment to provide the highest quality of care
to the people these agencies serve at the greatest value to the
taxpayers. The parties have committed to working together
aggressively in order to win the kind of support -- both
political and financial -- to enable that quality, cost-effective
care to continue to improve. It is a relationship of mutual
institutional respect: the union will recognize both the
responsibilities and difficulties of managing for quality care in
such a discouraging political and economic environment;
management will recognize that the union is the collective voice
of their employees and that it also has the responsibility and
right to organize and represent the voice of its members in
decisions which affect them. </p>
<p>The fact that these four agency directors and their Boards of
Directors have made this leap is a credit to their individual and
institutional courage and vision. Most importantly, it is a sign
of their real commitment to the people they serve. They have made
that commitment more important than historical enmity; more
important than old-fashioned notions of managerial prerogative;
more important than the cynicism and criticism of their peers.
SEIU and the AFL-CIO will not forget that commitment. We always
do our best to make unionization pay off for our members. We are
now committed to doing our part to make sure that it pays off for
these agencies and for the people we serve.</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../index.htm">Public Documents Page</a> | <a
href="../publsear.htm">Public Documents Search</a></p>
