<html>

<head>
<title>SP 12/8/95 Sweeney to Calif Assoc of Public Hospitals</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p align=center>Remarks by John J. Sweeney<br>
President, AFL-CIO </p>
<p align=center>California Association of Public Hospitals<br>
San Francisco<br>
December 8, 1995 </p>
<p>Thank you for that generous introduction --- its great to be here in San Francisco and to be greeted 
by a warm welcome as well as warm weather. </p>
<p>This is the first major speech I've made to a health care group since being elected president of the 
AFL-CIO and I'm delighted it is taking place here in the Bay area where my union, the Service 
Employees Union, has such deep roots. </p>
<p>Our great local union 250 here in San Francisco is the oldest health care union in America. It was 
started by low-wage workers at San Francisco General in the early 1930s and by 1941 it could 
claim the first master contract in the hospital industry. </p>
<p>Today, SEIU locals 250, 790, 535, 1000, 616, 707 and 715 represent more than 60,000 health 
care workers in Northern California. SEIU is now the biggest union in the state with close to 
300,000 members from Bakersfield to San Diego and I bring you their greetings and good wishes 
at during this holiday season. </p>
<p>I also bring you greetings from the 13 million members of the AFL-CIO and from the one and 
one-half million health care workers included in those ranks. </p>
<p>Six weeks ago at the AFL-CIO convention in New York City, there was a great debate about 
how workers and their unions should relate to employers in our new &quot;winner take all&quot; economy. </p>
<p>In his keynote address, my old friend and former rival, Tom Donahue, said he was more interested 
in &quot;building bridges than in blocking bridges.&quot; He was referring to one of our SEIU locals in 
Washington blocking our busiest bridge across the Potomac during rush hour one morning. </p>
<p>I responded by saying that when our employers and other powerful people refuse to listen to the 
working people we represent, then we have a moral obligation to block bridges and even go to jail 
to dramatize their plight. But, I was careful to add, I believe in building bridges any time the shelling 
stops long enough for us to start pouring concrete and putting up steel! </p>
<p>This morning, I'm here to try and build a bridge or two and talk about the need for a rejuvenation of 
our labor-management partnership in public health care. For those of you who are more of the 
&quot;bridge-blocking&quot; school, I invite you to join me at 2121 Pine Street at 12:30 this afternoon as we 
march and demonstrate on behalf of the embattled employees of the Hillhaven nursing home chain! </p>
<p>I can't think of a place where management needs labor as a partner more than in public health. 
Historically, we've been bound together by our deep common interest in the patients we serve and 
together we've built and maintained a system that is characterized as much by compassion as it is 
by competency. </p>
<p>Now we face changes that are unparalleled in our years of joint advocacy and our ability to work 
together is being challenged as never before. </p>
<p>I'm going to address some of those changes and challenges in a moment, but I want to ask for your 
help in fighting one battle there is no time to debate over. </p>
<p>Please take out a pen or pencil and write down these two numbers. The first is 
1-800-96-AFL-CIO and the second number is 1-800-97-AFL-CIO. Sometime today, call one of 
those numbers. They will automatically kick your call into the switchboard at the U.S. Capitol, 
toll-free. No matter what part of the country you are from, ask to speak to your Representative 
and when you get their office on the phone, tell them to back off the massive cuts in Medicare and 
Medicaid they are proposing. </p>
<p>Then make two more calls, to Senators Boxer and Feinstein and tell them to keep up the good 
work. Then make a last call, this time at your own expense. Make a &quot;thank you&quot; and &quot;please&quot; call 
to President Clinton at 202-456-1111. Tell him &quot;thank you for vetoing the Republican budget bill&quot; 
and then say &quot;please, please don't let Newt Gingrich and Bob Dole back you down!&quot; </p>
<p>Those toll-free AFL-CIO hotline numbers are the action end of a grass-roots lobbying campaign 
we've been running for the past four months to battle the Medicare and Medicaid budget cuts. In 
the summer and early fall, we spent $4 million on media in targeted House districts and ginned up 
270,000 telephone calls -- plus about 200,000 postcards to President Clinton. </p>
<p>Earlier this week, we purchased another million dollars worth of radio and television time and also 
dropped a million pieces of mail into those same targeted districts. We're also staging events and 
press conferences in 22 of the districts. </p>
<p>I recount all this to you in hopes you will appreciate what the men and women of the AFL-CIO are 
doing to preserve Medicare and Medicaid. And I want you to know we will continue to fight for as 
long as it takes to preserve our health care system in general and to preserve and improve our 
public health system in particular. And I want you to fight with equal vigor because we may all be 
gone if these cuts go through. </p>
<p>My union, the Service Employees Union, is the biggest health care union in North America, so I 
don't need on-the-job training in my new position when it comes to public health. SEIU represents 
475,000 health care workers, half of them in the public sector. Here in California we represent 
nearly 100,000 service workers, technicians, nurse aides and nurses in hospitals, nursing homes, 
home health agencies ambulatory clinics, blood banks, public health programs and HMOs. </p>
<p>We've always worked closely with your national association, the National Association of Public 
Hospitals, and we've begun to establish a working relationship with CAPH here in California. </p>
<p>I hope you will take my presence here today as the strongest possible indication that I intend to 
continue, nurture and expand those relationships in my new position as head of our national labor 
federation. We cannot and must not allow the violent forces now battering our health care system 
to damage our mutual commitment to the mission of public health, which is to provide high quality 
medical care to everyone who needs it, no matter how poor they are, no matter how old, no matter 
how sick, no matter what color and no matter what their immigration status! </p>
<p>Through much of this conference, you've been struggling with how to restructure our public health 
systems so they can survive and continue to provide quality health care for all. Our unions are 
struggling with how to represent health care workers in an environment where cost cutting 
pressures most often mean cutting back staff and redesigning jobs. </p>
<p>Together, we need to figure out how to gain control over the restructuring that is transforming our 
system of providers and payors. How we can maintain a strong role for government in assuring 
health care to all in an environment that favors market reform over government reform. How we 
can fight the Republican agenda of massive cuts in Medicare and Medicaid to fund tax cuts for the 
wealthy. How we can fight deregulation of health care. How we can build a public health system 
that works more efficiently without hurting patients and workers. </p>
<p>Cuts in Medicare and Medicaid have already triggered great changes that are squeezing health care 
workers and raising concerns about quality and access. Our members are telling us that patient 
loads are 50 percent higher than they should be. Nurses say they don't have enough time to spend 
with their patients. A rash of high profile clinical errors in hospitals across the country has captured 
the attention of the media and the general public. </p>
<p>Now there are new threats: more Medicaid and Medicare cuts at the federal level; questions about 
managed care; state and local funding cutbacks; the growing ranks of the uninsured and the poor; 
challenges of substance abuse and violence; and the unwillingness of private sector health care to 
help provide a safety net. </p>
<p>Our projections are that 1.7 million health care workers could lose their jobs, for instance, as a 
result of the proposed cuts in Medicare and Medicaid. Many of those who keep their jobs will be 
faced with moving from hospitals into outpatient settings, with all the professional as well as 
personal stress that attends such uprooting. </p>
<p>Our unions know that we face drastic cuts in funding, no matter how successful we are at lobbying. 
And we know that means we all face tough choices. But, as I have said in city after city over the 
past year, we will not sit silent seeing families ripped to their roots while many of the experts who 
got us into this mess in the first place exclude us from the decisions affecting our future. </p>
<p>We must be full partners. Not only because we have a common interest in serving our community 
and serving the poor, but because we represent experienced workers who have valid and 
worthwhile ideas for change and who have first-hand knowledge of the problems of their 
communities. </p>
<p>We know such partnerships can work, but they are hard to come by. In Boston, for instance, we 
were faced with the merger between Boston City Hospital, which is mostly unionized, and a 
private, mostly non-union facility serving a totally different population. </p>
<p>We were willing to be flexible, to be open for change, but we demanded to be part of the process. 
We had to organize and fight like hell for public health and worker protections, but we got them. 
We are still seen by the private hospital as an impediment to change, but we're working together 
now and the merger will go through by July 1996. </p>
<p>In Los Angeles, we were faced with a more horrendous situation, as you all know. With a $655 
million deficit, the county was faced with the closure of hospitals and clinics and cuts in services to 
thousands of poor patients as well as the loss of jobs for thousands of workers. Early on, we 
offered to cooperate and we were willing to help get federal and state relief if worker and 
consumer issues could be addressed. </p>
<p>Unfortunately, the county manager tried to close us out of the decisions and we had to spends 
weeks and weeks in the streets and in the media to get our concerns addressed. To their credit, the 
county supervisors took control of the process and established a task force that allowed us to begin 
working together more effectively. I went to work in Washington and the Service Employees Union 
went to work in Sacramento. We came out batting .500 with enough money from President Clinton 
to bail things out temporarily. Instead of losing 12,000 jobs, we lost 1,600. But the safety net in 
Los Angeles, however tattered, is still in place. </p>
<p>I want to say one word to the Los Angeles County officials who are here with us today, and it has 
to do with the privatization of clinics. Seven clinics have been privatized and 22 more are 
scheduled. To preserve bargaining rights for the workers who are our members, you made us go 
door to door and have them sign union cards. We signed up a majority in six of the first seven 
clinics. Now we ask that you sit down with us and help figure out a way to continue union 
representation without having to drain our treasury and exhaust our organizers to do it. </p>
<p>We've made real headway in establishing a new partnership. The AFL-CIO is ready to help build 
more such partnerships, to build the kinds of bridges we need in order to preserve our public health 
system. But in places like Los Angeles County, we need a little more quid pro quo to keep things 
moving. </p>
<p>For the next two weeks, we all need to be concerned with minimizing the damage to Medicare and 
Medicaid. Then we need to begin a forceful dialogue about legislative and political strategies at the 
state level to help preserve our systems. </p>
<p>There is no single solution and there are no easy answers, so we need genuine collaboration and a 
genuine commitment to making hard choices. </p>
<p>For labor's part, we will insist on being participants in developing proposals for restructuring and 
we're going to increase our strength by aggressively organizing across the country. </p>
<p>The principles we're guided by are in the best interest of public health and the best interest of 
consumers as well as in the best interest of health care workers. </p>
<p>We want serious consideration of alternatives to privatization or closures, such as creation of public 
health authorities, to help continue the public health mission and tradition.<br>
We want restructuring proposals to recognize the rights of health care workers and their unions, 
and the right of unorganized workers to unionize without management interference or coercion. And 
we want communities, as well as workers and their unions, fully involved in discussing and deciding 
on strategies and tactics for the actual restructuring plans. </p>
<p>If we can reach these kinds of accords, together we can fight effectively to guarantee adequate 
funding, for public policies that ensure high quality care and strengthen communitybased care. And 
we can hold the private sector to our own high standards of access as well as quality. </p>
<p>We must identify our common agenda. We must work together to re-establish the public's trust in 
public service. And we must flex the political muscle it takes to preserve public health care. </p>
<p>Our local unions here in California are ready to work with you. </p>
<p>And our international unions and the AFL-CIO in Washington are ready to work with you. </p>
<p>Let's get to work. </p>
<p>Thank you very much.</p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="../publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
