<head>
<title>SP 11/22/95 Sweeney at ICEF-MIF Merger Congress</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h3 align=center>Remarks by John J. Sweeney, President AFL-CIO </h3>
<h3 align=center>ICEF-MIF Merger Congress Washington, D.C. November 22, 1995 </h3>
<p>Brothers and sisters, it's a pleasure to be here. I want to thank Victor Thorpe and Peter Michalzik 
for inviting me to speak, and Wayne Glenn for his kind introduction. </p>
<p>I come before you to congratulate each one of you for making a dream into a reality. You are 
present at the creation of a new, stronger, larger, more effective ITS, the International Chemical, 
Energy, and Mining Federation. Each of you has helped to bring this about, and you have done a 
magnificent job. Believe me, this ITS has some friends in the AFL-CIO leadership. </p>
<p>As many of you know, I've had the privilege of being active in the ICEF through my own union, the 
Service Employees International. Rich Trumka, our Secretary-Treasurer, has been a leader and 
guiding spirit of the MIF and Linda Chavez-Thompson, our Executive Vice-President, joined many 
of you yesterday in protesting the anti-worker, anti-human rights policies of the Nigerian 
government and their wealthy friends in the oil industry.<br>
All of us have seen first-hand the good work that these two ITS's have done. There are countless 
working people in our country who are better off because of the ICEF and MIF. Each secretariat 
gave tremendous assistance to the Mine Workers during their Pittston and BCOA strikes. When 
the Steel Workers were locked out at Ravenswood, they could count on the ICEF when they 
needed its help the most. </p>
<p>Your two secretariats, each with its own history and tradition, have shown the world what militant, 
idealistic, creative trade unionism can do. And now your merger into the ICEMF is the best thing 
that can happen on both sides. </p>
<p>It is a win-win equation to have one single ITS that brings together the world's unions in energy, 
chemicals, and similar industries. Why? One very simple reason. It's called SOLIDARITY. You 
and I know what that's all about. Solidarity both at home and around the globe. </p>
<p>From the day we signed up in our unions we've known that our strength is in our unity. It's the basic 
insight that drives everything we do. But in the last several years solidarity has taken on a new 
meaning. </p>
<p>More and more the global economy means that the political borders of nations count for little, and 
that economic power is even more concentrated in the hands of fewer multinational corporations. 
There's no better example of this, or maybe I should say worse example, than the petroleum 
industry. Talk about concentrated power! The business empires that already control much of the 
world's petroleum supply are a textbook example. And as our adversaries work in global terms, so 
must we. </p>
<p>Time after time, we trade unionists are finding that we are stronger and healthier when we merge 
our institutions. It is already true for the education I.T.S.'s, which have merged. It may possibly 
prove to be true for your ITS and those that serve food workers, and construction and wood 
workers. In the United States, it is certainly true. Just in the last few months, the Ladies' Garment 
Workers and the Clothing and Textile Workers came together to form a single union in the needle 
trades and the Auto Workers, Steel Workers, and Machinists announced their plans to merge into 
one of the largest independent unions in the world. </p>
<p>In coming together in the ICEMF, you have been a great example for all of us. Your members will 
no doubt stand to gain immeasurably. By that measure, and that is the only measure that really 
counts, your merger is a great success. There's no question about it. </p>
<p>This is a moment of great change for you and the workers you represent around the world, and at 
the same time, for the American labor movement. Our movement has new leadership and new 
priorities. </p>
<p>Let me report to you on where we are and what our priorities will be in the days ahead. This is an 
incredibly exciting time for the AFL-CIO. A time of hope and faith in the labor movement unlike 
what we've seen in decades. A time when we're leaping forward, and a time when the voice of the 
working people of America is being heard. It is a time when the trade union movement is 
committed to building from the grassroots up, and committed to truly creating a strong, 
compassionate new voice for union members and for all workers. </p>
<p>We have three top priorities. The first is to organize new workers at a pace and scale that have no 
precedent. We are committing millions of dollars to our Organizing Institute, which trains young 
organizers. We are creating a Sunbelt Organizing Fund, which will focus on a part of the country 
where right-wing business interests have traditionally resisted unions. And we are creating a new 
Organizing Department and an Office of Strategic Planning at the AFL-CIO. </p>
<p>Second, we are committed to opening up our movement at every level, making it more diverse by 
bringing in more women and more people of color, so that the AFL-CIO will reflect the faces in the 
American work force. This change has already started. At our convention last month, we expanded 
our Executive Council to make more room for women, people of color, and young people, and we 
are creating new roles for organizations of trade unionists who are African American, women, 
Latino, or Asian and Pacific American. Our new Executive Vice-President, Linda 
ChavezThompson, is the first Latina in history to hold an executive position in the Federation. </p>
<p>Our third priority is politics. We are determined to build a progressive new movement of working 
people in the United States. The AFL-CIO will start a National Labor Political Training Center to 
develop campaign organizers, train candidates, and be a seedbed for young political activists. We 
will create a Labor Center for Economic and Public Policy to do the research we need to back up 
our legislative agenda, and we will launch a Campaign '96 Fund to supplement our regular political 
efforts in next year's national elections. Most importantly, we will reengage our members from the 
bottom up to rekindle the passions that built not only our labor movement, but our country. </p>
<p>We face huge challenges. But as I travel around the United States, I find union members and 
leaders filled with a sense of excitement, and ready as never before to take on those challenges. 
We, like you, are keeping our eye on the prize. And for us, like for you, the prize is to make the 
world a place where working people have a chance for good wages, decent benefits, justice in the 
workplace, and simple human dignity. </p>
<p>That is our great goal. That is what it's all about. Thank you very much.</p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="../publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
<hr>
