<html>

<head>
<title>SP 11/20/95 Chavez-Thompson to Public Employee Mtg</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<h3 align=center>Remarks by Linda Chavez-Thompson Executive Vice President, 
AFL-CIO </h3>
<h3 align=center>Public Employee Union Leaders Meeting November 20, 1995 Atlantic 
City </h3>
<p>I'm happy to be here. </p>
<p>You and I are here this week for a tremendously important cause -- a cause that we believe in and 
fight for -- and that is bringing justice and fairness and decency to the public employees in this 
region. </p>
<p>Let me start out by asking, Is there anyone in this hall -- anyone at all -- who is a friend and 
admirer of that buzzard Phil Gramm? </p>
<p>Good! </p>
<p>Then it won't hurt your feelings if I steal one of his lines and improve on it. </p>
<p>He flies around the country saying, &quot;I was a conservative before conservative was cool.&quot; </p>
<p>Well, I'm here to tell you that I was a public-sector unionist before public-sector unionism was cool 
-- and I'll stay a publicsector unionist through cool and hot and everything in between. </p>
<p>I see lots of friends here, and I've met several of the fine speakers who are scheduled to be here. </p>
<p>Most importantly, the problems you're grappling with here are the same issues we're up against in 
Texas and California and Wisconsin and around the country. </p>
<p>I congratulate you for taking on the tough and important issues -- the issues that count -- the mania 
for contracting out, the financing of government services, and where we are with publicsector 
collective bargaining. </p>
<p>I'd like to talk about a broader issue that links all of those three issues together. </p>
<p>That issue is how Americans think and feel about their public sector. </p>
<p>Last week, two days after most of the federal government had ground to a halt, there was a scary 
headline in the New York Times -- scary but not surprising. </p>
<p>It read, &quot;House Republican Freshmen Heed a Call to 'Shut It Down.'&quot; </p>
<p>The article said that there was a meeting of the Republican freshmen Congressmen -- those 
right-wingers in the Class of '94. </p>
<p>Someone asked, &quot;Anyone got problems back home with the fact that the government's shut 
down?&quot; And not one of them raised a hand. </p>
<p>There's something going on here, and it goes beyond the budget battle. </p>
<p>These right-wing Republicans on Capitol Hill are people who are delighted the government is shut 
down. </p>
<p>They think it's great. </p>
<p>They really hate the public sector -- the services it provides -- the people who work in it -- and the 
unions that represent those men and women. </p>
<p>Our members are the people who deliver the mail, teach the kids, clean the streets, and guard the 
prisons. </p>
<p>And their guarantee of dignity and decent wages -- their only guarantee -- is the union. </p>
<p>And it is precisely the unions that the right wing wants to destroy any way it can -- by contracting 
out to non-union shops, by denying us our collective bargaining rights, by cutting back our budgets 
until our agencies wither on the vine. </p>
<p>Make no mistake about it: government-bashing and union-bashing are twins. </p>
<p>One comes with the other. </p>
<p>You see signs of that fact all around. </p>
<p>State employees across the country are confronted with wage freezes, health care givebacks, and 
staff reductions. </p>
<p>Federal employees are being asked to accept pension cuts and wage increases that barely exceed 
the cost of living. </p>
<p>With school violence up and achievement levels down, teachers are told that the answer to all their 
problems is merit pay and privatization. </p>
<p>With handguns proliferating, police officers are being told to ride alone in their patrol cars or 
abandon them completely. </p>
<p>Time after time, in states and cities all over, the messages to public employees are the same: You 
better cut costs, work longer, take a pay freeze, make do with the old equipment, and shortchange 
your clients -- because if you don't, we'll abolish your job or contract it out and put you on the 
street. </p>
<p>There's an interesting article in the current Washington Monthly called &quot;Working for the 
Government is Cool.&quot; </p>
<p>That's a great title, isn't it? </p>
<p>I'd just add an amendment. </p>
<p>&quot;Working for the Government is Cool, Especially When You're in the Union.&quot; </p>
<p>Anyway, this article says, &quot;It's amazing what a bad rap government workers get. </p>
<p>&quot;People who work in all levels of government -- federal, state, and local -- are written off with a 
label that has a powerful hold over the country's imagination: bureaucrat.&quot; </p>
<p>I'm sorry to say that the Washington Monthly is exactly right. </p>
<p>And I tell you here and now that we who work in the public sector, and we who have the great 
mission of representing publicsector workers, are sick and tired of the government-bashing. </p>
<p>You and I have a big job to do. </p>
<p>Part of our job is to turn back the nonsense of contracting out, the mystical belief that private 
business and the unregulated market are always wonderful at everything they do. </p>
<p>Part of our job is to turn back the tax reductions for the wealthy -- these people who privatize their 
own education, their security guards, and their mail service. </p>
<p>Part of our job is to turn back the budget cuts that make it impossible for public-sector agencies to 
do their jobs. </p>
<p>But a big part of our job is also to get our message out. </p>
<p>That message is that we are proud of what we do and who we are -- we want a government that 
does its job for the people -- and government workers have the same rights to good wages, decent 
working conditions, and independent trade unions that every other worker should have. </p>
<p>We're doing all that during a very exciting time for our movement. </p>
<p>This is a time of hope -- a time when we're moving forward -- a time when the voice of the 
working people of America will be heard. </p>
<p>This is a time when the trade union movement is committed to building from the grassroots up -- 
committed to truly creating a strong new voice for union members and for all workers. </p>
<p>As I travel around the country, I find union members and leaders alike filled with a sense of 
excitement and ready as never before to take on the huge challenges we face. </p>
<p>We're keeping our eye on the prize, and the prize is to make America what it should be -- a place 
where working people, public sector and private sector alike, have a chance for good wages, 
decent benefits, and justice in the workplace. </p>
<p>Thank you very much.</p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="../publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
