<head>
<title>SP 09/27/95 Easterling at UFCW Rally</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<pre>For Immediate Release                    Contact: Candice Johnson
September 27, 1995                                   202/637-5010
</pre>
<h2 align="center">Remarks of AFL-CIO Secretary-Treasurer Barbara
J. Easterling at the Food and Commercial Workers Union's</h2>
<h1 align="center"><br>
'Workers Blow the Whistle on Congress' rally</h1>
<h2 align="center">September 27, 1995, at the U.S. Capitol</h2>
<p>I am delighted to be here. I bring you greetings from
President Tom Donahue, the AFL-CIO Executive Council, and the 13
million proud members of the American trade union movement. </p>
<p>Let me thank each of you for coming here today. </p>
<p>Let's talk about a few facts. </p>
<p>Here's Fact Number One. </p>
<p>America's working people -- the women and men on the lower and
middle rungs of the economic ladder -- need trade unions today
just as much as they always have. </p>
<p>The independent trade union is their way for getting decent
wages, good benefits, safe working conditions on the job, a
secure life for their families, and the dignity that every person
deserves. </p>
<p>You know what trade unions work for? We work for an America
where working people get a fair share of what they produce. </p>
<p>We work for an America that is more equal -- a nation where
the telephone operator and the department-store clerk can live on
the same block as the lawyer and the accountant, where people are
treated the same regardless of their gender or the color of their
skin. </p>
<p>We work for an America that is more humane -- a nation where
the poor get a decent minimum wage, where workers don't risk
their lives when they go to work, where retirees know that their
pensions are safe. </p>
<p>Now, here is Fact Number Two. </p>
<p>Newt Gingrich, Dick Armey, and their gang all hate what we do.
They despise everything we stand for. These guys know exactly
what democratic independent unions are all about -- they know how
important we are -- and they are determined to do everything in
their power to destroy our movement. </p>
<p>Look at all of their legislation, and you see a pattern as
plain as day. Their idea of heaven is a nation full of
sweatshops. Their favorite fantasy is workers who are isolated,
powerless, scared. </p>
<p>The Republicans' dirty little secret is that they can't stand
the idea of workers having an independent voice in the workplace.
They're scared of workers having the right to associate and make
their own decisions. </p>
<p>They know how popular unions really are among America's
workers. </p>
<p>They've seen the evidence. When a CNN/Time Magazine poll
asked, &quot;Do American workers need unions?,&quot; a big
majority -- 73 percent of the respondents -- said yes. </p>
<p>When the Associated Press/Media General poll asked workers who
were not union members if they would join a union if the
opportunity presented itself, 37 percent of that group said they
would. </p>
<p>That means that if workers could choose freely whether to join
a union, then the membership of our movement would nearly triple. </p>
<p>And the Republicans will stop at nothing to prevent that. </p>
<p>Fact Number Three is that this gang and the business people
who order them around are all very clever. They're not trying to
outlaw us. No -- their strategy for undercutting the real unions
is to let businesses create pseudo-unions that the bosses keep
under their thumbs. </p>
<p>That's what the Team Act would do, and it's coming up on the
House floor today. </p>
<p>Doug described it very well. Let me just add a couple of
comments. </p>
<p>The Gingrich-Armey gang say that they want teamwork and
cooperation between employer and employee. Cooperation sounds
just great. We trade unionists have been talking about it for
years. But there's one small difference. </p>
<p>We want cooperation between employer and employee as equals.
We believe each side should be independent, and they should sit
down and work out their differences. </p>
<p>The Team Act idea of cooperation is that if you're a worker,
you get to be the puppet, and the boss gets to pull all the
strings. You don't dare make one independent move, or else you'll
crash to the floor. </p>
<p>Some teamwork! Some cooperation! </p>
<p>And that's why stopping the Team Act is one of the top
priorities of the AFL-CIO. </p>
<p>The final fact is that Newt Gingrich, Dick Armey, Bob Dole,
and their people didn't just appear out of nowhere. There is a
bad spirit that is behind what they do, and they represent it
perfectly. </p>
<p>As one observer said, the key words for these people are not
&quot;we&quot; and &quot;sharing&quot; and &quot;the future&quot;
-- they are &quot;me&quot; and &quot;mine&quot; and
&quot;now.&quot; </p>
<p>Their real constituents are the junk-bond speculators -- the
millionaires who avoid paying a fair share of taxes -- the
business people who cheat and exploit their workers if that pads
their profits. </p>
<p>Our job as trade unionists is to change all that. You and I
have a big task -- to make this country a better place for the
people who check our groceries, build our cars, teach our kids,
and care for us when we're sick. </p>
<p>Our job is to work for a society where people care for each
other, help each other, stand together, plan for our future, and
take care of the less fortunate. </p>
<p>It's a tough job -- but we'll do it. That's what we are.
That's what our mission is. That's why we're here.</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../index.htm">Public Documents Page</a> | <a
href="../publsear.htm">Public Documents Search</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
</body>
