<html>
<head>
<title>SP 09/26/95 Easterling at AFGE Conference</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<pre>For Immediate Release                         Contact: Candice Johnson
September 26, 1995                                        202/637-5010
</pre>
<h3 align="center">COMMENTS OF BARBARA J. EASTERLING<br>
SECRETARY-TREASURER, AFL-CIO<br>
AT A NEWS CONFERENCE OF THE<br>
AMERICAN FEDERATION OF GOVERNMENT EMPLOYEES<br>
</h3>
<p>The AFL-CIO is committed to support AFGE and all federal
employees if a shutdown of the federal government takes place.
Federal workers want to work. They want to continue to serve the
American people. </p>
<p>In the event that they are prevented from doing this, the
AFL-CIO is developing a contingency program to help them through
this difficult challenge. </p>
<p>The AFL-CIO Executive Council has already approved a program
of loan assistance to striking workers of unions that do not have
strike funds. We have extended that program to include federal
workers forced off their jobs through no fault of their own. </p>
<p>The AFL-CIO will work with an area bank to create a $5 million
Fund -- $1 million from the AFL-CIO and the rest to be arranged
with the bank. This fund will be used to provide loans that will
be made available to federal workers if they are locked out of
their jobs. The AFL-CIO first adopted this policy in August, and
I presented the first million dollar loan to Teamsters on strike
at the Detroit newspapers. </p>
<p>Loans will be offered to assist federal workers to pay their
mortgages, make car payments, buy groceries and to provide for
other essential needs. </p>
<p>The AFL-CIO also will call upon our state and local
federations across the nation to urge their members of Congress
to support a continuing spending resolution that provides
adequate funding to maintain current government spending and
employment levels. </p>
<p>We will further ask our affiliates and state and local central
bodies to support the September 27 action to protest a government
lockout. </p>
<p>These steps are just the first in a series of actions we are
prepared to implement. If necessary, we will ask the AFL-CIO
Strategic Approaches Committee to develop a strategy that will
focus the combined resources of our affiliated unions in support
of federal workers. </p>
<p>We hope that we do not get to that point. We call upon
Congress to act responsibly toward the federal workers who serve
our nation so proudly and so well. But the AFL-CIO and its
affiliates will assist federal workers to the fullest extent
possible. </p>
<p>It is completely unfair to make federal workers and their
families shoulder this financial hardship. The members of
Congress will still receive their paychecks during a government
shutdown. To hold federal workers hostage to the Republican
budget is unjustified and immoral. </p>
<p>The AFL-CIO will work with AFGE and other unions to encourage
federal workers to use their expanded political rights under the
Hatch Act to make their voices and their votes heard in the next
election to prevent this situation from recurring in the future.</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../index.htm">Public Documents Page</a> | <a
href="../publsear.htm">Public Documents Search</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
</body>
</html>
