<html>
<head>
<title>SP 09/21/95 Donahue EC Press Conference</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<h3 align="center">AFL-CIO President Tom Donahue<br>
Executive Council Meeting Press Conference<br>
Washington, D.C.<br>
September 21, 1995<br>
</h3>
<p>JOHNSON: We're sorry about the delay you went through. You
have a copy of President Donahue's summary of the meeting and
he's here to take your questions. </p>
<p>SUMMARY: We had a long and productive meeting of the Executive
Council. Barbara and I are proud of what the council accomplished
today on behalf of the working families of America. </p>
<p>We adopted a resolution establishing budget levels for our
Organizing Fund that we had approved in principle in August. That
fund will begin next year with $5 million and will grow to $20
million within four years. We have also approved a financing
mechanism for that fund and instructed the Committee on the Role
of the AFL-CIO in Organizing to develop a structure and procedure
for that fund in time for convention action. </p>
<p>The purpose of the AFL-CIO's investing in an Organizing Fund
is to leverage new monies from affiliates to achieve a
substantial increase in overall organizing activity. We think our
fund of $20 million can generate an additional $80 million from
individual unions in new organizing money per year. We believe
this is the scale that will be required to rekindle organizing
activity. </p>
<p>The council was presented with a draft Ethical Practices Code
for union officers and representatives and we agreed to ready
that for adoption in October. </p>
<p>I reported to the council on the work of our ad hoc committee
on governance, which is working on an agreement on a proposal for
the convention that would substantially increase the
representation of women and persons of color on the AFL-CIO
Executive Council. We also approved a resolution on full
participation that commits us to make rules changes and other
efforts to increase the participation of women and minorities in
our state and local central bodies, in all committees of the
AFL-CIO and at the AFL-CIO Convention itself. </p>
<p>Finally, we spent a great deal of time reviewing the
legislative situation and our grass-roots legislative and
political activities. Members of the council expressed alarm and
anger at the multiple attacks by the congressional Republican
leadership on programs that benefit working families in order to
finance tax breaks for large corporations and wealthy
individuals. We met with Rep. Gephardt and Sen. Daschle; reviewed
our Stand UP campaign; and heard a report by Geoff Garin on the
results of our ongoing research concerning the attitudes of union
members. </p>
<p>I advised the council that we are targeting 50 congressional
districts for intensive grass-roots activity; building
Legislative Action Committees in 150 congressional districts;
developing an electronically linked network of thousands of local
trade union activists; starting to train 500 local activists in
grass-roots legislative and political activities; planning now
for a political operation in 1996 that would put 500 union staff
in the field from Labor Day to Election Day to mount the largest
and most effective political operation in our history -- double
the number fielded in 1994 and working with an area bank to
create a $5 million fund for low- or no-interest loans that would
be available to federal workers through their unions in case of a
government shutdown. Union members in federal agencies want to
keep on serving the public. Today we made contingency plans to
help them and their families in case they are prevented from
doing so. </p>
<p>Barbara reported on the progress being made in our internal
review of AFL-CIO operations. Part of her report concerned the
process of reorganizing and consolidating our communications
operations to shift our focus away from publications and toward
proactive media relations. </p>
<p>DONAHUE: I'd be happy to take your questions. </p>
<p>REPORTER: What about the disparaging remarks of corporations
about ghastly union behavior in corporate campaigns? </p>
<p>DONAHUE: I greet their reaction with joy and glee -- to have
them acknowledge the enormous power that we must have and the
ability to so plague them that they are somehow going to join
together and try to force workers to abandon efforts to make
those corporations a little bit more civilized. </p>
<p>I think that's a great tribute to the work that we have been
doing. I understand this arises from the American Trucking
Association and from my namesake there. It would be an
interesting case -- Donohue v. Donahue. </p>
<p>But I think that's a great testimony to the work our unions
have been doing trying to defend workers against those
corporations. </p>
<p>If they'd like to compare the litany of things that unions
have said about those corporations with the things that they have
said about us through the years, there are still several more
volumes on our side than on theirs, I assure you. </p>
<p>These are the same people who have for years carried on a
campaign for a ``union-free environment'' as if we were some sort
of vermin. I really do not have a lot of sympathy for their
concerns on this issue. </p>
<p>REPORTER: There is some argument on the Hill. Apparently there
is going to be a hearing about this issue. I'm just curious, how
concerned are you?<br>
DONAHUE: Well, if the Hill would operate in the fashion that the
nation has gotten accustomed to over the years -- if there are
going to be hearings on this issue -- we would be happy to
appear. In the current Congress that seems to be out of vogue.
They apparently don't hold exhaustive hearings on anything
anymore. </p>
<p>So that part of it can be a serious problem. We will have to
see. Certainly those corporations have a lot of slack on the
Hill. They can and will try to bedevil workers by attacking us
there or anywhere they can. We will have to deal with it. </p>
<p>REPORTER: Could you elaborate on the second-to-the-last item
in the summary and explain what the political plans are for 1996?
How is this operation different from what has been done in the
past? When will the people start? What exactly will they do? What
is hoped will be accomplished and so forth? </p>
<p>DONAHUE: Could I ask for a copy of that? I don't have the same
page two. You are referring to what parts of it? </p>
<p>REPORTER: The 1996 political operations. </p>
<p>DONAHUE: In 1994, we put into the field about 225 people, both
from the federation staff and from the staffs of our affiliates
working with our unions' members in various areas around the
country to carry on registration, education and get-out-the-vote
efforts among union members. That was in a period that probably
covered the last four weeks of the campaign. One of the lessons
we've learned, obviously, is that four weeks is not long enough.
That wasn't a heavy enough effort. </p>
<p>So, what we are going to do for 1996 is try to double that
number of union activists out working with members in specific
districts and double that by doubling the commitment from the
AFLCIO field staff and asking our affiliates to double their
commitment, all together an effort to put 500 people in the
field. We'll put folks in right after Labor Day to work with our
members in those campaigns from Labor Day to Election Day. </p>
<p>We asked our unions to think about that now. Obviously, to do
that by September, you have to begin training and orientation of
those people sometime in June and July, and we have to make
specific assignments. We have pulled the calendar back
substantially. </p>
<p>REPORTER: So, the goal is to mobilize support among union
members for the candidates that have received union backing? </p>
<p>DONAHUE: Right, in as many districts as we can cover and in
districts that are designated marginal or critical to us. </p>
<p>REPORTER: Have you targeted any yet? </p>
<p>DONAHUE: I don't care to say that we have selected the final
targets. In many of them, you don't even know who the opposition
is going to be. </p>
<p>REPORTER: How does this mix with Project '95 and (AFSCME
President Gerald W.) McEntee and company and their support? </p>
<p>DONAHUE: You will have to ask him. I don't know what districts
they are working in. Project '95 is a different kind of project,
as I understand it. Project '95 is designed to focus attention on
the incumbent and to highlight his or her actions or failure to
act on certain matters, or how he or she votes on certain
matters. That is a quite different effort than the federation
effort, which is a legislative issues effort, trying to educate
our members and activists on the legislative issues and to work
those legislative issues between now and the end of this
congressional session. </p>
<p>So, our concentration now is not on any effort to embarrass
the incumbent, but rather to involve our members in issues to
build pressure on incumbents to support us on those issues. We
seek thereby to produce an educated cadre of members in each of
those congressional districts. Those members will then be able to
transfer that knowledge and take it with them when they become
involved in the political campaigns in the latter part of 1996.
The substantial difference, I believe, is that Project '95 has a
different agenda and is geared to work through June or so of next
year. </p>
<p>REPORTER: The Governance Committee -- the proposal that you
are working on says that you are going to increase the
representation of women and people of color on the Executive
council. I am assuming that means that you want to increase the
number of members on the Executive Council and if so, can you
tell us how many people you want to increase it by? </p>
<p>DONAHUE: The answer is yes to the first question and no to the
second. I think that you would have to increase the size of the
council and that is what the committee is examining. But, no I
can't give you an answer as to how many seats we're talking
about. The phrase in the early draft of my remarks said that we
are very close to agreement. I think that exaggerates the case.
We are working in a committee in which everybody is trying to
work together. We have agreed that we are going to discuss
informally and off the record all of these issues. That is what
we have been doing in the committee, I think very effectively. I
don't what to be speaking about the work of that committee. I
only mean to give you an indication that, I think that committee
will be able to come to an agreement on increasing the diversity
of the council and have a recommendation for the convention. </p>
<p>REPORTER: Doesn't that recommendation have to be in within the
next couple of days? </p>
<p>DONAHUE: Resolutions to the convention can come from the
Executive Council as late as the day of the convention and
anywhere during the convention. They don't have to meet the
deadline. The deadline within the next few days is for submission
of resolutions by our affiliates. </p>
<p>REPORTER: Could you tell us a little more about the work of
the Committee on Governance? More specifically, is there just one
proposal or several proposals? What's holding up agreement? And
finally, how many weeks before the convention will this report be
out or will it be on the eve of the convention? </p>
<p>DONAHUE: The committee is considering a number of proposals to
revise the governance structure, including some you submitted
which have been distributed to the members of the committee and
have been discussed. There are a number of proposals before the
committee on revision of the governance structure. </p>
<p>I don't think there's any &quot;holdup.&quot; The committee
has had two meetings. We have had good discussions. We will have
more discussions as to when the committee will finish its work. I
just don't know, except obviously it has to finish before the
convention. But, I think that it may well be on eve of the
convention. </p>
<p>REPORTER: Do you think there is a chance of an agreed policy
in sight, policy on governance? </p>
<p>DONAHUE: That is what we are testing: whether or not there can
be agreement. That committee is pretty evenly divided between
Sweeney adherents and the Donahue adherents. We are examining
that. It is a way to see if we can agree, rather than simply to
have competing proposals on the floor of the convention. </p>
<p>REPORTER: Any commitments from Gephardt and Daschle on
anything? </p>
<p>DONAHUE: No. They both discussed the current situation in the
Congress, the apparent growing irritation of the Democratic
members as reflected in Sam Gibbons' demonstration yesterday.
Gibbons is an old paratrooper. So, I guess that you will have to
understand that. </p>
<p>I don't want to put words in either of their mouths. For my
part, I believe there's a growing feeling among the Democrats in
both the House and the Senate that the Republican leadership is
distorting the process, that there is not a fair opportunity to
have hearings, to see bills before hearings begin, and so forth. </p>
<p>Gephardt or Daschle, I can't remember which one, noted there
are hearings scheduled for tomorrow on something on which no bill
has yet been produced. Medicare is an issue on which the
Democrats are frustrated because they have not yet seen the
proposal that the Republicans are offering on Medicare and
Medicaid revisions. </p>
<p>Generally they only spoke of those things and spoke of their
concerns over the 1996 elections and the need to assure
Democratic control of the House and Senate election or to strive
to achieve Democratic leadership in the House and Senate. </p>
<p>REPORTER: Does any part of the campaign for the presidency of
the AFL-CIO intrude on this meeting in any form? </p>
<p>DONAHUE: Perish the thought. This is a meeting of elected
officers of unions all of whom have their own election contest.
So, it would be surprising if they were not aware that there is a
contest going on in the federation. </p>
<p>It doesn't intrude in the sense of preventing us from finding
agreement on broad range of issues in which we make common cause
on behalf of the working families of America, obviously. </p>
<p>Does it intrude into some of the political discussions that
take place? Yes, I guess it does. I guess it is reflected in
comments by adherents on both sides, and may prolong some of the
discussions. </p>
<p>REPORTER: There are some people who feel that this is very
divisive, and they wish that it would go away, and perhaps one of
the candidates should drop out in the interest of solidarity. Has
that kind of proposition come up? </p>
<p>DONAHUE: No. I haven't heard that at the council. </p>
<p>REPORTER: Did you respond to the letter that you got from six
union presidents urging you to be the person to withdraw? </p>
<p>DONAHUE: I was not ducking your question, Peter. You asked me
did it come up in the council and it didn't come up in the
council. So far as I know John has no plans to withdraw and I
didn't hear that in the council. </p>
<p>With respect to the letter signed by six unions, none of which
are currently supporting me -- suggesting that I withdraw -- I
think that is clearly a dog bites man story. If they were six
unions supporting me, then I think that would be news. </p>
<p>But, what made it news in the proportions that it was played
up, I have now idea, except skillful PR from the other side. It's
a letter from six people who are not supporting me, saying
they're supporting John. I knew that. </p>
<p>REPORTER: On that point, it seems to me, and probably a lot of
outsiders, there is general agreement on many issues and the
Sweeney group -- on organizing, on political action. There may be
shades of difference, but you all want to do the things that are
necessary to help working people. What are the sticking points of
this agreement, if any, outside of the fact that you have a race
for the presidency? </p>
<p>DONAHUE: I think that we have discussed a number of points,
both of agreement and disagreement. I think the judgment has to
be made by the delegates as to who's the person most competent,
the most qualified to lead the federation for the two next years.
I expect to be the person chosen when that question is answered. </p>
<p>REPORTER: Along those lines, are you any closer to producing a
list of what you think those numbers are in terms of who supports
whom? </p>
<p>DONAHUE: I will be happy to give you my version of the
numbers, or what I understand of the numbers. I believe that John
has 24 unions supporting him. </p>
<p>REPORTER: Is it 24 or 26? </p>
<p>DONAHUE: I think that he is saying 24. </p>
<p>REPORTER: He is saying 26. </p>
<p>DONAHUE: Is he saying 26? </p>
<p>REPORTER: His press release said 26. </p>
<p>DONAHUE: My count of John's unions is at 24. My count of my
support is at 48. </p>
<p>REPORTER: Forty-eight is short. But they don't vote by unions,
they vote by membership. Do you have projections from those
unions, their recent per capita figures or what would play out at
the convention? </p>
<p>DONAHUE: I do. (Laughter) I don't anticipate that is going to
play out at the convention. </p>
<p>I wouldn't try to fool you and say that I am not behind. I'm
behind on those counts and those declarations. </p>
<p>I have said from the beginning, &quot;the vote will be taken
Oct. 26.&quot; At that point, you will have the results of the
voting and we will see what the numbers are. I expect a number of
changes in the current alignment, or else I wouldn't be
continuing. </p>
<p>REPORTER: Would there be anything that could persuade you or
possibly Mr. Sweeney to withdraw? </p>
<p>DONAHUE: I can only speak for myself. </p>
<p>REPORTER: Well, you might be very persuasive with Mr. Sweeney. </p>
<p>DONAHUE: I haven't been. </p>
<p>REPORTER: Can you answer that? </p>
<p>DONAHUE: Sure. No, I can't think of anything which would
persuade me not to run. There is a contest. It is to be decided
by the vote of our convention delegates. It will be decided on
October 26. I'll be there. Barbara Easterling will be there. We
will be candidates for election. </p>
<p>REPORTER: There was a union today, the Transport Workers,
which seemed to come out for Mr. Sweeney. You have spoken about
the fluid situation in which you indicated that you thought Mr.
Sweeney had 53 percent. Why does the Transport Workers
declaration today . . . presumably you wish to revise that figure
upward in favor of Mr. Sweeney and what would you like to revise
it upwards to? </p>
<p>DONAHUE: Whatever proportion 58,000 is of 13 million. If you
can do your mathematics quickly you will have the answer. I think
that is about four-tenths of one percent? </p>
<p>REPORTER: United Transportation Union. Is there any other
calibrations that we should make on that 53 percent? </p>
<p>DONAHUE: None that I know of. The only announcement I was told
about was the announcement of the UTU to support the Sweeney
candidacy. That is the only thing that I know of. </p>
<p>REPORTER: What can we look forward to in Las Vegas? </p>
<p>DONAHUE: It depends on what week you are talking about. Tyson
is fighting there. </p>
<p>REPORTER: I am talking about . . . </p>
<p>DONAHUE: Oh, this week. What you might have looked forward to
last week was the endorsement that I received in Las Vegas from
the Amalgamated Transit Union, with I guess 55,000 members or so. </p>
<p>Next week is the Carpenters' Executive Board meeting. I can't
tell you what to look forward to in that convention other than
separate appearances by John Sweeny and me. We will both be there
speaking to the delegates. I can't tell you what is going to
happen there. You all know the history -- that Sig Lucassen was
strongly supporting Sweeney and that he is retiring at that
convention, that the Executive Board of the Carpenters failed to
endorse or did not give John the endorsement when he appeared
before their board here in Washington. It is an open question
with the Carpenters. I am not going to claim anything more than
that. </p>
<p>REPORTER: What is their membership? </p>
<p>DONAHUE: 383,000 or 382,000. About seven times bigger than the
UTU. (Laughter) </p>
<p>REPORTER: Do you expect them to make an endorsement or make a
decision at the convention or do you have an understanding that
that will be done? </p>
<p>DONAHUE: Kevin, I am not dancing. I have no feel for that. I
just don't know what they will do. Whether they will take up the
issue at that convention or whether they will do it by Executive
Board either before, during or after the convention. I just don't
know. </p>
<p>REPORTER: There is still a question of whether the
international unions will vote as a body or whether they will
allow the delegates to have a portion of those votes to cast on
their own. We have had only one contest in the history of the
federation. That is 1969, I believe. The international cast their
complete slate. I know a number of the internationals appoint
their delegates. So, the delegates are usually beholden to the
president and it goes down the line with them. </p>
<p>But, it seems to me that in this situation there may be people
who do not want to go down the line for a particular side -- one
or the other. I would like to see votes by the delegates, because
that would certainly be much more democratic at a convention. Is
there any possibility of doing something to encourage it. I have,
as you know, suggested one delegate/one vote. I think that would
probably get you elected. But, I don't know if the convention has
adopted or is even considering that kind of proposal. </p>
<p>DONAHUE: I will examine it, Harry. If it would get me elected,
I'll take a serious look into it. </p>
<p>To answer your question, I believe that the constitution is
clear that the delegates to the convention are elected or
appointed in accordance with the rules of the individual unions. </p>
<p>Those delegates are appportioned against a number which is the
per capita payment of the national union. The delegates divide
among them, with the divisor being the number of delegates -- and
whatever the number on top is called being the per capita number.
The delegate then votes. A union with a million members, for
example, has 10 or 11 or 12 delegates who would vote 50-odd
thousand votes apiece. </p>
<p>That is my view of the constitution. </p>
<p>REPORTER: I want to clarify something in your statement. You
are talking about the Organizing Fund of $20 million dollars can
generate an additional $80 million dollars from individual
unions. How does that work? </p>
<p>DONAHUE: How the fund will work is still being discussed and
that is what the Norton Committee has been asked to come up with
for the convention. </p>
<p>The general expectation, I guess, would be that you would have
a group of organizing directors who would meet and discuss
possibilities for developing campaigns, prospects in areas,
regions, industries and whatnot. There could well be another
structure above that of general presidents, as a kind of
oversight committee, on the distribution or the allocation of
that $20 million. </p>
<p>It is clearly my anticipation and I think everybody else's
that that money -- the AFL-CIO's money -- being put into these
campaigns would be designed to leverage spending on organizing
from affiliates. So, on the proportions that are there, we would
look to affiliates to be spending $4 for every $1 that the
federation puts up, and we would be putting together $100 million
to spend on organizing in a given year -- using that $20 million
to leverage additional spending by the affiliates. </p>
<p>REPORTER: That would be actual spending or spending in kind?
Providing organizers obviously has a value. </p>
<p>DONAHUE: It probably could be either. But, it would have to be
additional to a union's ongoing effort. We wouldn't want a
situation in which a union has three organizers or 10 organizers
on the payroll and says, &quot;Now I will come into your campaign
and I will put those 10 organizers in.&quot; That is not
additional or new money into organizing. We are talking about new
money added to current expenditures on organizing. </p>
<p>REPORTER: Both you and Mr. Sweeney have sent signals to the
Democrats saying, &quot;don't take us for granted.&quot; Did any
sort of discussion along those lines occur today with Gephardt
and Daschle? </p>
<p>DONAHUE: I think there is a clear understanding from a number
of discussions that we had today that trade unionists, like
voters all across the country, are not as enchanted as they once
were with party labels. They are looking much more at individual
performance of the representative or the senator. </p>
<p>I think that is clear. It comes through in all of the polling
that we do. It comes through in the focus groups and it came
through in the discussions at the Executive Council today. </p>
<p>REPORTER: Speaking of which, were there any other startling
revelations that emerged from the research and the attitudes of
union members that you were briefed on today? </p>
<p>DONAHUE: I was impressed with the concerns our people have
about their own jobs, their own future prospects, their own
expectations of what is ahead for them. And I was impressed with
the evidence of their interest in job training, in partnership
arrangements, which would help to secure their employment and
enhance their employment opportunities. </p>
<p>There is fairly substantial evidence of that and a greater
evidence of that than there is of anti-corporate attitudes as
such. That is something for us to consider. </p>
<p>REPORTER: Did anything emerge that would suggest unions have
become irrelevant to working people? </p>
<p>DONAHUE: Geoff didn't say that at all. No. </p>
<p>REPORTER: On page two, you say that you are going to develop
an electronically linked activists' network of thousands of local
trade union activists. As I am sure you know, there is an AFL-CIO
LaborNET. Do you intend to expand that? </p>
<p>DONAHUE: We have and have maintained for a number of years an
activist list of somewhere over 150,000 trade union activists --
people who have participated in the past in solidarity activities
in one kind or another. They want to be active on other issues. </p>
<p>We have communicated with them extensively through the years
and used them in organizing, in political campaigns and in other
work. </p>
<p>What we are seeing now is that we want to link those folks
electronically, probably through the LaborNET or the World Wide
WEB Page, to be able to communicate with them and to be able to
mobilize them on far shorter notice than the mails will allow. I
don't take that back. Don't tell the postals I said that. </p>
<p>REPORTER: I want to be very clear about the organizing fund.
If these numbers are what you intend on spending each year -- $5
million in the year. . . . </p>
<p>DONAHUE: $5, $10, $15 and $20 million. </p>
<p>REPORTER: That is the annual amount of money that is
anticipated to be spent each year? </p>
<p>DONAHUE: Yes. OK? </p>
<p>REPORTER: Thank you.</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../index.htm">Public Documents Page</a> | <a
href="../publsear.htm">Public Documents Search</a></p>
