<body>
<h3 align="center">AFL-CIO President Tom Donahue<br>
AFL-CIO Public Employees Department Convention<br>
Lake Buena Vista, Fla., September 8, 1995 </h3>
<p>I am delighted to be here. I am accustomed to saying I'm
delighted to be here and bring you the greetings of the
president. Now, I deliver them in person as the president, and
also bring you greetings from Secretary-Treasurer Barbara
Easterling, the AFL-CIO Executive Council, and the more that 13
million working women and men who are the American trade union
movement. </p>
<p>I come before you at a very interesting time for our movement.
As Mario Cuomo noted yesterday, two fine trade unionists -- both
of them New Yorkers, both of them Irish-American, both of them
out of SEIU Local 32B-32J and both balding ever so slightly --
are running against each other to be the future president of the
AFL-CIO. </p>
<p>Those reports are right, and I'm one of the two. I just want
to note how proud I am of the fact that I helped bring the other
candidate, John Sweeney, into SEIU. I knew that he had great
potential, and I was pleased that he rose to the presidency of
the SEIU. I believe it would be wonderful if he continues to
provide my union with many more years of service in that
position. </p>
<p>Many of you in this room are supporting my candidacy and I
thank you for your support. For all the rest of you, I'm counting
you as undecided and will continue to pursue your vote
relentlessly by demonstrating that Barb and I are making changes
happen every day. But the fact is that I have not come before you
to give a campaign speech. That is for other times and other
places. </p>
<p>Instead, I would like to talk about an issue that really
unites us all -- a problem that concerns us all -- and that is
``government itself'' and what it means in our country. </p>
<p>For trade unionists, the public sector isn't just some
sideshow -- it is at the very heart of what we are all about. </p>
<p>We need a government that will ensure our right to associate
and guarantee that independent unions can exist. We need a
government that will ensure against sweatshops and child labor.
We need a government that creates infrastructure and maintains
it. We need a government that insures the purity of our food, the
safety of our work places and the healthiness of the water we
drink and the air we breathe. We need a government that provides
universal health care, and a fair trade policy, a government that
provides a tax code that makes the rich pay their fair share and
a Social Security system for our retirees. </p>
<p>Each of those is as vital to us as the air we breathe, and
each of those falls squarely inside the public sector. </p>
<p>You and I, and this department, are faced with a huge
contradiction in this country. It colors everything we do; it
affects everything we stand for. If we want to deal with it, we
have to call it what it is. </p>
<p>The fact is that in the past 20 years government in our
country has been demonized. We've sunk to the point where our
conventional wisdom is that government -- whether it's federal,
state or local -- always ruins whatever it touches. Another piece
of the conventional wisdom is that everything the government does
just gets worse and worse. </p>
<p>The truth is that the good things that government does in this
country are legion and -- almost always -- the things that only
government can do. You know well what they are. You and your
members do them day in and day out and do them very well. </p>
<p>I'm not suggesting that the public sector is perfect, any more
than businesses, colleges, trade unions or other institutions
made up of human beings are perfect. But consider for a moment
what government agencies -- and that means government employees
-- have accomplished. </p>
<p>You all know well the federal government has built dams,
created millions of public-sector jobs, kept prices steady when
there were shortages, created the interstate highway system,
managed the air lanes of the busiest airspace in the world, and
put together a medical system in the military that led to a
revolution in civilian medicine. </p>
<p>We trade unionists could certainly add to the list. We would
include government agencies that stop employers from violating
the 40-hour week, enforce the minimum wage, keep an eye on
private pensions so they aren't bankrupted by hot-dog speculators
and guarantee that independent unions have a right to exist. </p>
<p>And how about the myth that things always get worse? Look at
the postal service and Social Security. These are two of our
biggest, most important agencies, and both of them work far
better today than they did 20 years ago. There are plenty of
others. </p>
<p>And while we're at it, look at OSHA. For all its petty flaws,
for all its limitations, it has made the workplace safer for
literally millions of Americans over the past quarter-century </p>
<p>We have cut accident/death rates by more than one-half. Still
6,000 Americans are killed on the job each year and tens of
thousands are injured. Now, the Department of Labor estimates
these cuts will cost 50,000 more accidents and year. I don't know
anyone in the country who voted for that. </p>
<p>You could tell the same story about thousands of state and
local government agencies around the country. </p>
<p>Is there reason to complain about the public sector? Sure
there is, but the real truth is that much of what's wrong with
government is that it has too few resources, too little money,
too few staffers, or too limited a mandate to do its job right. </p>
<p>Unfortunately, OSHA itself is a dramatic example of this. It's
a fine agency, but wouldn't it be nice if its protections were
extended to cover everyone in this room and all of the people you
represent? </p>
<p>That's the kind of government reform -- of re-invention, if
you will -- that we'd like to see. When Republicans talk about
``reforming'' government, they usually mean ``annihilating
government.'' When we talk reform, we want to make the thing
better. And that's a far different approach. </p>
<p>The sad fact is that people's trust in government is at a
dangerously low level, and that's the case even among union
members. </p>
<p>A poll commissioned by the AFL-CIO has found that only 38
percent of our own members have ``generally positive'' feelings
about the federal government. There are almost as many -- 32
percent -- who feel negatively, and 30 percent are neutral or
unsure. Those numbers are pretty close to the rest of the
population. </p>
<p>The same poll asked union members to volunteer one or two
things that the president or Congress could do ``to help people
like you.'' The most common answer -- it came from one-third of
our members -- was to lower taxes. And there was quite a bit of
support for reducing government spending and balancing the
budget. </p>
<p>Unfortunately, those results aren't unusual. We've been seeing
the same kind of distrust and cynicism in the general population.
In 1958, 73 percent of Americans said they ``trust the government
in Washington to do what is right most of the time or always.''
Today, only 22 percent do. In 1965, 35 percent of Americans said
that ``big government'' posed ``the biggest threat'' to the
country's future. Today, 67 percent believe that. </p>
<p>So, there we have one side of our contradiction: the American
people don't like government and the people who work for it. The
other side of the contradiction is that the American people like
what the government does. </p>
<p>The political scientist Robert Putnam puts it this way: ``We
[Americans] want government to do things, not just decide things
-- to educate children, pay pensioners, stop crime, create jobs,
hold down prices, encourage family values, and so on. ``We do not
agree,'' Putnam continues, ``on which of these things is most
urgent, nor how they should be accomplished, nor even whether
they are all worthwhile. All but the anarchists among us,
however, agree that at least some of the time on some issues,
action is required of government institutions.''<br>
That's absolutely right. But we're left with this huge
contradiction: people on the one hand, hating government, and on
the other hand, liking what government does. If you're a public
employee, it stares you in the face every time you show up for
work. </p>
<p>But what these polls and this contradiction tells us is very
important. There is a great deal of confusion and ambivalence in
this country, and it's no wonder. For nearly 20 years, Reagan,
Bush, Gingrich and their gang have systematically bashed and
insulted the public sector. In fairness, we ought to note this
didn't begin with Reagan but with Jimmy Carter -- who ran against
Washington and against the very government he aspired to lead. </p>
<p>Then came Reagan's monstrous comments about `getting
government off our backs'' and the rest of his poisonous
rhetoric. The bad politics and the public employee bashing of the
Bush era and of Gingrich were inevitable. </p>
<p>What the American conversation badly needs is a strong,
progressive voice that speaks out against government bashing,
against privatization, against contracting out, against the
idolatry of the market -- a voice for a vigorous, well-funded,
well-managed public sector that deserves and gets America's
support and respect. </p>
<p>America needs to know that the people who clean our streets,
guard our prisons, inspect our poultry, deliver our mail, and
keep our airports safe are vital to this nation. They and
millions like them make this country run. They deserve the same
good pay, decent working conditions and job security as everyone
else. And they are morally entitled to the same collective
bargaining rights as every other worker in America. </p>
<p>There is no institution that is in a better position to take
on that task than the trade union movement. There are two things
we must do. </p>
<p>First, we as leaders need to go out there on the morning news,
the late-night talk shows and the radio call-ins and talk about
what government and public employees really mean to America. </p>
<p>I've said this before, and I'll say it again. When our
principles are attacked, I want us to respond. When our movement
is slandered, I want to speak the truth. When myths are spread, I
want to fight them with facts. </p>
<p>And to each of you -- whatever union you're in, whatever
position you hold, whether you're woman or man, black or brown or
yellow or white, young or old, whether you're talking to ``Larry
King Live'' or your next-door neighbor -- I invite you, I beg you
to join me. </p>
<p>Be proud of who you are and what you represent. Be proud of
the work you do and the movement you are in -- and spread the
world about what you believe. We have an enormous public
educating job to do in the face of very tough odds. </p>
<p>Let this be the moment when the Public Employee Department and
the entire trade union movement move to the center of America's
public dialogue. We've been locked out of it for too long and
have to fight our way back in. </p>
<p>But there is a second thing we need to do. We need a far
tougher, smarter, more sophisticated, more extensive political
effort than ever before to ``take government back'' from the
millionaires and the right-wingers and return it to the American
people who work for a living -- and that is what the AFL-CIO has
started to do this summer. </p>
<p>We have now begun the most intensive political campaign in our
federation's history. We have launched a special project to train
500 labor activists in the nuts and bolts of grass-roots
political activity over the next 12 months. Why? Because there
are lots of our members who no longer know how to run an
effective COPE program -- to activate our members, to get them
registered, voting and involved. This program will provide a
chance for them to learn or relearn those skills. </p>
<p>I have already appointed a full-time director for this
project, Susan Washington. We've had the first weekend planning
session for our directors and staff who'll be involved and we're
going into the field this month. </p>
<p>I have also assigned half of the AFL-CIO field staff and
committed millions of dollars to the Stand UP for America's
Working Families campaign. We have targeted 36 critical
congressional districts during the last recess -- districts that
we have a good chance to win back -- for a grass-roots campaign
between now and the 1996 elections. </p>
<p>We're going to let the voters in those districts know just
what the Republicans are doing to them. They're entitled to hear
the facts. </p>
<p>In just the last two weeks of August, we spent $1 million in
local advertising in 26 of those districts to focus public
attention on the OSHA cuts and the Labor-HHS appropriations bill.
That buy brought us to slightly more than $2.5 million for this
Stand UP for America's Working Families campaign in more than 60
districts and the nation's capital during the three congressional
recesses. </p>
<p>Finally, when the 1996 election campaign starts, we are going
to run the largest political education program we have ever
undertaken. We have more than 13 million names of active and
retired members on our computer lists. With the exception of
AFSCME and the Teamsters, all of our unions now supply COPE with
their membership lists for voter registration and education and
get-outthe -vote activities. We've got to work those lists so
that when trade unionists go to vote on Election Day 1996, they
will know what's at stake. </p>
<p>For public employees and for all Americans, a lot depends on
what happens in November of 1996 and we have to work as never
before to win back the House, to elect a Democratic president and
to begin to recapture our power in the capitols and state houses. </p>
<p>Beyond that we have to engage this nation in the debate on
taxes or we'll lose badly and public employees will suffer badly.
We're going to see extensive debate in the Congress on the
socalled flat tax. That debate will begin next year and running
beyond the election into the next Congress. </p>
<p>The Republican version will be touted as simplification and
reductions for everyone, but of course the major benefit will go
to the rich. </p>
<p>The Democrats seem ready to engage in debate on the same terms
with this version of a flat tax and we'll wind up in a sterile
argument about which version is fairer. </p>
<p>I propose that we have to change the terms of that debate. We
have to say you can't starve government any longer. We have
already cut to the bone on services and employment. It's time to
look at the tax and income side in order to maintain government
services and government efficiency. I believe we have to offer
our version of a fair tax which must include substantial new
taxes on the rich. </p>
<p>The astonishing maldistribution of wealth in this country goes
on and on. Take a look at the top one-half of one percent in the
U.S. -- the 50,000 richest households in America with minimum
holdings of $10 million. They own one-third of the $22 trillion
wealth of the nation. In 1981 they owned $1 trillion, the Reagan
tax cuts gave them $2 to $3 trillion more. And the continuing tax
structure gives them a transfer of $170 billion per year. That's
the rate at which their wealth grows. </p>
<p>It's not their fault. They didn't ask for these additional
trillions and didn't earn them -- but our tax system gives it to
them. </p>
<p>So, we need to propose a Wealth Tax -- a special one-time or
continuing levy on wealth as Switzerland and several other
nations now do. And we ought to set up a new period of
``givebacks,'' this time from the super rich. It's to us trade
unionists to propose and pursued that dialogue. </p>
<p>Let me just touch on two other subjects. </p>
<p>I note from your program that you received reports yesterday
on the work of the Secretary of Labor's Task Force on Excellence
in State and Local Government Through Labor-Management
Cooperation. (I would like to nominate that for the longest title
in history.) </p>
<p>I gather John Brock and the two co-chairs have done a good job
in drawing together a substantial body of information on the
subject and I'm going to testify next week. I will be trying to
add what we all believe is the crucial element on which
excellence can be based: the collective bargaining relationship.
That relationship has to be developed and fostered on the basis
of decent laws that give public employees the right to associate
freely and to choose their representatives to bargain over all
the condition of their employment. </p>
<p>Let me say that all through the early 1960s and 1970s -- when
I was at SEIU -- I was the voice of that union in all the debates
about public employee legislation. Don Wasserman of AFSCME and I
carried the dialogue all around the country to file for public
employee collective bargaining rights and collective bargaining
laws. </p>
<p>Now you can look and say we made a lot of progress in all of
the states and our unions have grown in pubic employment, but the
reality is we still have 24 states without full collective
bargaining rights; nearly 4 million workers are denied their
rights. </p>
<p>And that is a disgrace. </p>
<p>We all believe in excellence. We all believe in partnership.
I've led the course of the federation that forged those policy
positions over the years. But you can't have excellence, you
can't have partnership, if you deny workers their fundamental
rights by resorting to an outmoded theory of the sovereignty of
the state. So we have lots of work ahead of us on that count. </p>
<p>Finally, let me note the problems coming at us in the federal
sector on Oct. 1. There is a very real possibility, even a very
real probability, that some or all federal agencies are going to
be without funds and will lock out their workers. </p>
<p>The maneuvering of the Republicans in the House and Senate
seem designed to force the president's hand to veto some or all
of the appropriations. Certainly we will strongly urge a veto of
the Labor, Health and Human Services appropriations bill. In its
current form, it guts OSHA, practically repeals Davis-Bacon, guts
the Mine Safety and Health Act, the National Labor Relations
Board, the college student loan program and so on. </p>
<p>The stage is set for a different confrontation with a
president who won't accept these kinds of cuts and the Republican
leadership delighted to have government grind to a halt and try
to blame gridlock on the president. As politics, it will provide
high drama. </p>
<p>But for the workers involved, it will lock them of their jobs
-- not just federal employees, but lots of grant workers in the
states as well. </p>
<p>For our part, we have to worry about them and find ways to
ease their burden. I have begun some consultations to explore
what the federation and the affected unions can do in the way of
nointerest or low-interest loans to tide members over until the
political sparring ends. </p>
<p>I think it should be possible to do this in the same way we
help out on strike funds and strike assistance in the private
sector and we are looking into the use of Union Privilege funds
or AFL-CIO Reserve funds. </p>
<p>I am aware that the PED is working with an AFGE Task Force
created by President John Sturdivant and we want very much to
help in any way we can. </p>
<p>In this meeting, as in all other, the Federation has to be
taking an activist role in support of its affiliates. That's been
my direction for as long as I have been in the federation and it
will continue for as long as I serve as your president. </p>
<p>Thank you.</p>
<p align="center"><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a
href="../index.htm">Public Documents Page</a> | <a
href="../publsear.htm">Public Documents Search</a></p>
