<html>

<head>
<title>SP 09/04/95 -- Alemeda County Labor Day Picnic </title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p align=center><strong>AFL-CIO PRESIDENT TOM DONAHUE</strong><br>
<strong>ALAMEDA COUNTY LABOR DAY PICNIC</strong><br>
<strong>PLEASANTON, CALIFORNIA, SEPTEMBER 4, 1995</strong> </p>
<p>I am delighted to be here and to celebrate this Labor Day with you. I bring you greetings from 
Secretary-Treasurer Barbara Easterling, the AFL-CIO Executive Council, and the more than 13 
million proud women and men who are the American trade union movement. </p>
<p>This is the day we wait for all year, the day we celebrate those who make our cars, teach our kids, 
clean our buildings, sew our clothes, build our homes, and load onto ships the goods that we 
produce. </p>
<p>This year, we also have to mark the struggles of workers on strike today. We mark our concerns 
for the strikers at the Detroit Free Press and News, at Staley, Caterpillar, Bridgestone, Diamond 
Walnut, for those at the Frontier Hotel in Las Vegas -- who mark the fourth anniversary of their 
strike on September 21 -- and for workers locked in similar struggles all around the country. </p>
<p>These are brave people, brave trade unionists standing up for their rights, their dignity, and against 
those who would attempt to destroy them and their unions. </p>
<p>I ask all of you to take a minute of silence sometime on this Labor Day for those workers, or to 
pray in your own way that their struggles will soon be won. </p>
<p>If you can send a contribution from your local, that would help them, too. </p>
<p>This Labor Day, we have to note that these are difficult times for working people and for their 
unions. </p>
<p>Wages have been stagnant despite high corporate profits. Last year, profits of major corporations 
were up 40 percent, productivity was up 2 1/2 percent, but real wages were up only onetenth of 
one percent -- and half of the workers in the nation were earning less than $24,000 per year. </p>
<p>It's true that union wages are still one-third higher than non-union wages, but we face continuing 
challenge to our wages and our benefits from all sides. </p>
<p>All of us, all of you, are working hard to overcome the difficulties that beset us -- working hard to 
change labor and change America -- working hard to grow, to improve the lives of our members, 
to establish decent conditions of work for our members, and to establish decent conditions in our 
society for all Americans. </p>
<p>We are working hard for conditions in which families can live with dignity and with confidence in 
their future. </p>
<p>We have a big job ahead of us in the next year, with contract negotiations for many of you and with 
political work for all of you. </p>
<p>We have to mobilize and motivate all of our members as never before. We need a friend in the 
White House and we need Democratic control of the House of Representatives if we are to make 
any progress. </p>
<p>Here in California, we need to reassert Democratic control in the legislature to protect the workers 
of this state against your governor -- that man who has libelled every immigrant and then, in one of 
the most hypocritical acts of American politics, posed in front of the Statue of Liberty to announce 
his campaign for the presidency. </p>
<p>She must have closed her eyes and he should have blushed with shame. </p>
<p>Over these past three years, in our efforts to advance the cause of workers, to advance their 
economic and social interests, we have had a friend in the White House. </p>
<p>We have had a president who passed and signed the Family and Medical Leave Act, so workers 
can take care of their families, a president who passed and signed the Hatch Act reform so federal 
workers can take part in politics like everyone else. </p>
<p>We have had a president who, in his first months in office, repealed the three executive orders 
George Bush had put in place at the urging of the National Right to Work Committee to plague our 
unions and weaken our ability to defend workers' interests. </p>
<p>We have had a friend in the White House, a president who peopled his administration with decent 
trade unionists -- who appointed people to the National Labor Relations Board and other agencies 
who would enforce the laws designed to help workers. </p>
<p>We have had a president who fought long and hard at our side to ban the evil practice of allowing 
employers to fire strikers and hire scabs -- and after the Republicans blocked him and us in the 
Senate, he signed an executive order to stop federal agencies from doing business with companies 
with scabs. </p>
<p>He has stood with us for affirmative action, for OSHA reform, for increasing the minimum wage. It 
hasn't been an easy time. His and our hopes, the hopes of 1992 and 1993 were dashed by the 
1994 elections -- dashed by a crop of right-wing Republicans who are bent on repealing or 
weakening every law that protects workers and killing all the programs that help workers. </p>
<p>They want to gut OSHA, repeal Davis-Bacon, throttle the NLRB, cut college loans, cut Medicare 
and Medicaid -- all to advantage the rich. </p>
<p>And what stands between us and them is the veto pen of the president of the United States. </p>
<p>Who's side is Bill Clinton on? Make no mistake about it: he's on your side, he's on the side of 
everyone in this country who has to work for a living. He's on the side of the trade union 
movement. </p>
<p>I am proud to introduce the most pro-worker, pro-union president in more than a generation, my 
brothers and sisters, the President of the United States -- Bill Clinton.</p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="/publ/publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
<hr>
<p>Copyright &#169; AFL-CIO</p>
