</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML//EN">

<html>

<head>
<title>SP 08/31/95 1995 Donahue at Labor Day Roundtable</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>AFL-CIO President Tom Donahue<br>
1995 Labor Day Roundtable<br>
Thursday, Aug. 31, 1995<br>
<br>
<br>
CANDICE JOHNSON, AFL-CIO press secretary: Let me just note, in the<br>
handouts are some of the things from our Stand UP campaign. We have<br>
ads running right now in about 26 districts and activities in about<br>
36. It is our legislative and political campaign. Probably our<br>
biggest concern was the Labor/HHS Appropriations bill the House<br>
voted just before recess. When the Senate comes back, they are<br>
going to take that up.<br>
<br>
DONAHUE: Thank you all for coming. I'm delighted to visit with<br>
you, talk a little about the state of labor on Labor Day. I don't<br>
have any formal opening statement. I thought we'd save some time<br>
and take your questions and I can try to respond.<br>
<br>
QUESTION: Why don't you start with the state of labor?<br>
<br>
DONAHUE: Okay. I think there is both good news and bad news on<br>
Labor Day. <br>
<br>
If you look at the membership figures over the last two years,<br>
BLS reports that labor has grown by 390,000 members. And I believe<br>
that trend is continuing in '95. That's not a large growth, that's<br>
3 percent, but it is going in the right direction.<br>
<br>
QUESTION: Bringing membership to what, then?<br>
<br>
DONAHUE: A little over 13 million. Our membership has been fairly<br>
static for a lot of years. We haven't lost a lot of membership, but<br>
we have not grown with the growth of the work force. <br>
<br>
In terms of where workers find themselves and consequently the<br>
labor movement finds itself on Labor Day, I think the state of the<br>
world for workers is a very insecure and difficult one. And when<br>
times are hard for workers, then times are hard for their unions.<br>
What the workers see is big profit increases in 1994. Forbes<br>
magazine says 40 percent for the major 900 corporations.<br>
Productivity is up 2.5 percent wages up 0.1 percent. <br>
<br>
Clearly, America needs a raise on Labor Day. That ought to be<br>
the message: that there ought to be some sharing of those profits<br>
with the people who create them.<br>
<br>
When workers look at the federal Congress this Labor Day, what<br>
they see is a Congress that is attempting to strip away from them<br>
what protections they have and to wipe out or diminish the programs<br>
that affect them and benefit them. So they are getting hit from<br>
both sides in terms of stripping away protections -- OSHA, the<br>
attack on the 40-hour week and all the rest of it. And they are<br>
seeing the programs that improve life for workers taken away in the<br>
form of the college loan reductions, the effects of Medicare,<br>
Medicaid cuts and so forth. <br>
<br>
I think what workers are feeling on Labor Day is that this is<br>
not what anybody intended. And the country is going in the wrong<br>
direction -- not just in a political sense, but clearly in an<br>
economic sense. We continue to enrich the already rich and we<br>
continue to re-enforce the enormous maldistribution of wealth and<br>
increase the concentration of that wealth in the hands of fewer and<br>
fewer people.<br>
<br>
We are now at a point at which one-half of 1 percent of the<br>
people hold nearly a third of the total wealth of the country. Half<br>
of 1 percent -- that's probably everybody with more than $10<br>
million. And they own $7 trillion of a $22 trillion wealth package.<br>
<br>
I think it's time that serious consideration be given to the<br>
theories that are being advanced out there, to talk about a wealth<br>
tax and to foster the idea that it is indeed time for give-backs --<br>
and it's time for give-backs from the rich this time. Workers paid<br>
their share and now it's time for give-backs from the rich.<br>
<br>
I think the Congress, instead of talking about flat taxes,<br>
instead of talking about cutting taxes for the rich, ought to be<br>
talking about a wealth tax. We ought to be taking back some of the<br>
trillions of dollars that have been transferred to the rich over<br>
the last 12 to 15 years.<br>
<br>
QUESTION: Isn't it fair to assume that a good number of the people<br>
who are in your various labor unions actually helped create this<br>
situation by voting for the Republicans? They couldn't have done it<br>
without ...<br>
<br>
DONAHUE: If you say a fair number, it's something less than a<br>
majority, however. But point well taken.<br>
<br>
Some of our people, like lots of other people in the country,<br>
were so distressed with the way the country was going that they<br>
sought relief in the anti-government mood, in the concept that<br>
government was the devil. Get government off my back. That became<br>
a popular cry. I'd only footnote that by noting that in every<br>
election that our people, the majority of union workers, have voted<br>
for the Democratic candidate or the progressive candidate. <br>
<br>
Now, was there a departure of some percentage of people who in<br>
previous times voted Democratic or progressive, who in the last 6,<br>
8, 10, 12 years shifted over to the right? Sure. The percentage<br>
among trade union members was far less than the percentage of the<br>
population at large. But I don't think anybody who shifted over,<br>
anybody who voted for the crop of right-wing Republicans in the<br>
House, I don't think any of those people voted to cut Occupational<br>
Safety and Health and none of those people voted for a condition<br>
which the Labor Department says is going to cost us 50,000<br>
additional injuries next year on the job, God knows how many<br>
additional deaths on the job. We have spent 20 years bringing that<br>
number down, cutting it in half and now we are going to stop<br>
enforcing the law. We are going to cut enforcement by 50 percent.<br>
<br>
That's obscene and nobody voted for that. Nobody voted to do<br>
away with the 40-hour week, I assure you. I don't know anybody in<br>
this nation who even dreamt of such an obscene idea. But the right-<br>
wingers in the Congress apparently accept it and think that it is<br>
a sound idea to say that we should tear up the fabric of American<br>
society, tear up the concept of the normal five-day work week and<br>
two days off, and allow employers to work people up to 20 days<br>
straight.<br>
<br>
QUESTION: One of the things that happened in that last election<br>
was not so much that they switched sides but that a lot of people<br>
stayed home. There was a very low, very low turnout. Is there<br>
anything to suggest, and I don't know where you are getting your<br>
readings on this, but is there anything to suggest that it would be<br>
different at the next election, that there is a counter-anger<br>
building or is it about the same as it was?<br>
<br>
DONAHUE: I think in terms of the presidency, there is some turning<br>
and some more enthusiasm among workers for the Clinton<br>
administration, as they see the horrors of the other side. <br>
<br>
I think that there is some turning and some recognition that<br>
this is not what we voted for among people who voted for<br>
Republicans last time around. I think you see that.<br>
<br>
I think that certainly there is a growing recognition among<br>
our members and I think among workers generally that this Congress<br>
and this nation are not worker-friendly. Nobody is advancing the<br>
interests of workers, except the AFL-CIO. But not many of our<br>
politicians on the Republican side.<br>
<br>
QUESTION: Including Clinton?<br>
<br>
DONAHUE: Oh no. Certainly not. The Democrats and Clinton have been<br>
trying to advance the worker interest. They don't control, but they<br>
have been trying to advance worker interest. Certainly Clinton has<br>
been.<br>
<br>
QUESTION: Mr. Donahue, you mentioned earlier the national rise in<br>
union members, but that percentage of the overall work force, that<br>
number, has declined steadily for quite some time. Why do you think<br>
that is happening and, then, what can you do to change that?<br>
<br>
DONAHUE: The reasons for the decline are several. One, the<br>
diminution of employment opportunities in the industries in which<br>
we were traditionally best represented, the destruction of our<br>
manufacturing base. And the reduction of employment in<br>
manufacturing is one of the bigger reasons.<br>
<br>
The continuing shipment offshore of jobs from those same<br>
industries is another. Look at the UAW, now at half its previous<br>
size. Look at the condition of our textile and clothing workers<br>
union, less than half its former size. That's part of why<br>
membership has dropped and why as a percentage of the work force we<br>
haven't been growing. Because the industries in which we were<br>
traditionally most strongly represented are the industries that<br>
have been hardest-hit by downsizing, shipping offshore and so<br>
forth.<br>
<br>
Secondly, where we're experiencing growth has been largely in<br>
the service areas -- particularly health care in the service<br>
industries -- where conditions for organizing are quite similar to<br>
the traditional conditions that provide people the desire to form<br>
and join unions. And in the public sector, the growth has come<br>
largely because of the changes in collective bargaining laws. We<br>
argue that if it was possible in the private sector to easily form<br>
and join a union, if it was possible to suggest having a union in<br>
the workplace without threatening your livelihood, without knowing<br>
that the boss is going to fire certain people who are engaged in a<br>
campaign, without knowing if people were free of the fear of<br>
harassment and intimidation from the boss in the private sector,<br>
they would do what the people in the public sector are doing under<br>
appropriate laws. So the growth in the public sector has come --<br>
and it's a series of states -- that have provided workers real<br>
protection and the opportunity for collective bargaining. And they<br>
vote overwhelming for union representation.<br>
<br>
So that's where the growth has come. <br>
<br>
QUESTION: Do you think labor needs to adopt a new approach in<br>
terms of attracting attention in areas that are white collar,<br>
office, and what not? We had a major bank merger this week and the<br>
first thing, practically, they announced was 12,000 people are<br>
going to lose their jobs. This is what seems to be happening all<br>
over the country. And the 85 percent or so of the work force that<br>
is not represented by unions are going through tremendous tumult.<br>
Is that where organized labor's future lies? Is this an area to go<br>
after? Or do you have your hands full just trying to deal with<br>
keeping what you've got on the books in terms of labor protection<br>
laws?<br>
<br>
DONAHUE: I've got a two-part answer, but let me just preface it by<br>
saying we don't have our hands full keeping what we have. The<br>
reality is that most of our unions are busy organizing and bringing<br>
members into their ranks every day. The static condition of the<br>
overall number reflects enormously successful organizing, replacing<br>
enormous job losses. The fact is -- for all our unions -- that if<br>
you could stop the leakage out the bottom, they'd all reflect<br>
growth. But their growth is now being offset against the job<br>
destruction and the leakage from the bottom. <br>
<br>
In terms of the future, I think we have a primary obligation<br>
to work among low-wage workers and we have always fulfilled that<br>
responsibility. I think that's a primary area for continuing our<br>
organizing activities and one in which there is a great deal of<br>
enthusiasm for traditional union organizing and for the achievement<br>
of collective bargaining. I think in the white-collar, semi-<br>
professional and professional areas, there is a desire for<br>
associational unionism, if you will, for people coming together for<br>
purposes that may not reach all the way to traditional collective<br>
bargaining. That's very clear from the National Bureau of Economic<br>
Research study, the Freeman-Rogers piece. There is an enormous<br>
desire. Their numbers run into the 70th percentiles of people who<br>
absolutely want to have some way of coming together, forming an<br>
association, dealing with some workplace problems, dealing with<br>
their professional relationships, their professional training,<br>
knowing more about education and work opportunities and so forth.<br>
9to5 is, I guess, the earliest precursor of that. But I think the<br>
expression of desire on the part of these people and the NBER study<br>
goes quite beyond 9to5. <br>
<br>
I think we have to answer that. There are three or four things<br>
we have to do. But one is to answer the desire of workers for<br>
traditional organizing for traditional collective bargaining, which<br>
arises most strongly among the heavily exploited class who see very<br>
short-term futures in their current employment and who feel very<br>
insecure.<br>
<br>
Among this other group of workers, whether you call them<br>
white-collar or semi-professional or professional, there is an<br>
equal amount of insecurity and they want something. They are not<br>
quite sure what it is. I think we have to provide the type of<br>
associational relationship that they want. So we need to modify<br>
some of our structures to do that. <br>
<br>
Thirdly, I think we have to look at the contingent, temporary,<br>
part-time work force where you are talking about some 20 percent of<br>
the population. Now some of that, particularly among the part-<br>
timers, is in industries that are susceptible to traditional<br>
organizing and among workers who want a traditional collective<br>
bargaining approach in some form in these other areas. And I think<br>
we have to try to address the part-timers, the contingent work<br>
force. Those are fairly tough assignments and the contingent work<br>
force and this so-called independent contractor work force requires<br>
yet another approach and a kind of attempt to organize people by<br>
their skill category or by their job titles, I guess you'd say,<br>
rather than by their place of employment. And that's yet another<br>
approach. So I think we have to do all three of those.<br>
<br>
QUESTION: In the study that you cited, the Freeman-Rogers study,<br>
the overwhelming desire for a voice in the workplace that was<br>
expressed seemed to have the condition that workers would rather<br>
have a weak organization that had management's blessing rather than<br>
a strong organization that management opposes. And so, if you're<br>
trying to address the wants and desires of those workers, it seems<br>
that what they are crying out for are company unions. <br>
<br>
DONAHUE: I read the results of the survey as proving the<br>
effectiveness of the boss's terror tactics. He has convinced<br>
workers that if you look for a traditional union approach here, you<br>
will experience even more insecurity. And there will be harassment<br>
and intimidation. So they succeeded in frightening people in the<br>
workplace. There is no question about that. <br>
<br>
I don't hear those people as speaking for a company union in<br>
the traditional sense of that word at all. They are not looking for<br>
a patsy organization. They want a real voice in the workplace. <br>
<br>
QUESTION: But they don't want to upset their boss in the process.<br>
<br>
DONAHUE: Yes, that's right. They don't want to upset the boss.<br>
They are saying, I think, &quot;We don't want a confrontational<br>
situation here. Because we know what will happen in a<br>
confrontational situation. The boss is going to intimidate, harass<br>
and terrorize and make us even more insecure.&quot;<br>
<br>
I think you provide what they want. You provide a voice which<br>
is not in its initial stages confrontational. You attempt to behave<br>
rationally and hope that an employer responds rationally. <br>
<br>
I have to say to you that there is very little evidence that<br>
that'll happen. But you have to hope. Hope springs eternal that the<br>
boss will behave rationally and will respond to peoples' desires.<br>
There is lots of anecdotal information that he will, and that in<br>
the early stages of such an effort he does respond to efforts of<br>
people to have voice.<br>
<br>
As those people become more and more accustomed to the<br>
expression of voice, sooner or later, that voice expresses the<br>
desire for a larger share of the profits of what they produce. It<br>
expresses itself as wanting conditions or wanting freedoms that the<br>
boss isn't prepared to give up. He wants control in the workplace<br>
and he doesn't want to give up control in the workplace. <br>
<br>
So history is replete with the examples of associations that <br>
were formed and later grew into true, full collective bargaining<br>
mechanisms. I think that is a natural evolution and I think that's<br>
what the people in the Freeman-Rogers survey are saying.<br>
<br>
QUESTION: Is that what you are going to try to cultivate as far as<br>
organizing people in white-collar jobs, rather than the traditional<br>
approach?<br>
<br>
DONAHUE: Yes. Let me be clear about one thing. The traditional<br>
organizing approach is not necessarily a confrontational approach.<br>
It is an approach to the people to form and join a union. It<br>
doesn't necessarily have to be confrontational. It becomes<br>
confrontational when the boss creates that confrontation. I don't<br>
know anybody who wants to fight with the boss. The boss is much<br>
more ready to fight with the people.<br>
<br>
When I distinguish between traditional and non-traditional,<br>
I'm not talking about confrontation. I'm talking about the<br>
distinction of the goal that's being sought. Some organizing looks<br>
to the short-term achievement of collective bargaining. And I'm<br>
saying to you that among this group of people we are talking about,<br>
white-collar workers or semi-professional workers, they are not<br>
ready yet for that. They don't want to fight to achieve that degree<br>
of recognition from the employer. But they want a voice. And we<br>
have to adapt the product we offer to meet that need.<br>
<br>
That's all I'm saying.<br>
<br>
QUESTION: What do you suppose the image is of labor these days --<br>
Labor Day 1995? Not just among your members, but among the country<br>
as a whole?<br>
<br>
DONAHUE: I would hope that it is increasingly understood that we<br>
are standing up for America's working families. That the only voice<br>
in this country that speaks up on a daily basis for the protection<br>
of workers and the advancement of their interests is the labor<br>
movement of this country. That's absolutely true.<br>
<br>
And I'm getting hoarse from trying to do that and trying to<br>
say that.<br>
<br>
QUESTION: Various surveys are going to show a different attitude<br>
toward labor unions as too pushy, maybe even outdated in the role<br>
that they take on. Is that something that you are working on?<br>
<br>
DONAHUE: I think we are certainly working on making clear to the<br>
American people that we are the representatives of workers in this<br>
nation. That's our role in life. And that we are not a narrow<br>
interest, pursuing only the interest of those who are trade<br>
unionists. Obviously, on the job, in the workplace, in terms of<br>
wages, hours, conditions and benefits, that's what we are for union<br>
members -- that's our primary function. But our secondary function<br>
is to advance the interest of those members who are our members in<br>
society. And the only way we can do that is to advance the<br>
interests of all workers in society. So at the political and<br>
legislative level, we are the voice of all of the workers in this<br>
society.<br>
<br>
When we fight for OSHA protections or fight against the<br>
Republican efforts to cut those protections, we are certainly not<br>
fighting only for the 16 percent of American workers who are trade<br>
union members. We are fighting for the 100 percent who are going to<br>
be put at risk by cutting OSHA protections.<br>
<br>
So I would argue that people ought to see the trade union<br>
movement as the voice of workers in this country -- all workers.<br>
<br>
QUESTION: Can you talk a bit more about the political climate? You<br>
said earlier that you didn't think a lot of folks knew what they<br>
were getting when they voted for a lot of these Republicans. Yet it<br>
seems to me that the Republicans were quite up front about what<br>
they represented and what they were going to do. Newt Gingrich kept<br>
referring to that Readers' Digest article, I think it was, about<br>
unions ruining New York City. He had this anti-union rhetoric all<br>
along, so why do you think that people are surprised by it and how<br>
are you going to counter that?<br>
<br>
DONAHUE: I don't think that people all across the country in<br>
congressional races voted for Newt Gingrich. <br>
<br>
QUESTION: But he kind of set the tone.<br>
<br>
DONAHUE: He set the tone. He laid out their &quot;Contract on America.&quot;<br>
But you'd be hard-put to find a lot of voters around the country,<br>
including in Georgia, who had a sense of what the &quot;Contract&quot; was<br>
about. What Gingrich was promising was small government. It was a<br>
repetition of &quot;We'll get the government off your back. We are going<br>
to reduce government.&quot; That's a fancy slogan. People like that kind<br>
of slogan. It's simplistic. And they're finding out now the<br>
consequences of that kind of a simplistic appearance. And the<br>
consequences are the cutting back of services that help people, the<br>
endangerment of people on the job, the reduction of opportunities<br>
for their kids and so forth.<br>
<br>
They will find out even more about that as more and more<br>
programs and responsibilities are transferred to the states and<br>
state or city taxes have to be increased to cover the shortfall in<br>
those programs. That is as inevitable as tomorrow. City taxes,<br>
state taxes will increase and you all know it. Once the federal<br>
government cuts back, somebody is going to have to pick up that<br>
slack. It's going to result in increases all the way down the line.<br>
This will be a slower education for the people who voted for the<br>
Republican right, but it'll come.<br>
<br>
QUESTION: Isn't there a danger that if the labor movement's No. 1 <br>
priority -- organizing the most exploited segment of the work force<br>
-- is successful, that by focusing on that segment that the labor<br>
movement is going to lose political clout because that segment of<br>
the work force is just not as influential as the middle class, as<br>
white collar workers, the semi-professionals. And that if you want<br>
to build labor's image among the influential segment of the country<br>
that you have got to appeal to them. Is there a danger in<br>
alienating them?<br>
<br>
DONAHUE: I don't think so. I was thinking as you offered the<br>
question that if I really believed that I'd work someplace else.<br>
I'd work in a public relations firm trying to influence the middle<br>
and rich class as a way of improving the nation.<br>
<br>
No, I don't think so at all. I think that we have always<br>
organized workers. And most workers are badly paid. That's the<br>
reality. It is the people in the most exploited groups who most<br>
seek a way out of their more desperate situations. The middle-class<br>
earner is less prone to do that. So our organizing has always been<br>
concentrated on those people who are in the lower pay groups. <br>
<br>
The truth is, however, that we've been quite successful in<br>
other areas of the work force. And I think the labor movement<br>
represents a very interesting spread, from the lowest-paid janitors<br>
to the actors and artists to the writers and the airline pilots.<br>
And lots of earners in between. So I don't think there is any risk<br>
of distorting the labor movement's interests. I think that we have<br>
worked as hard with the airline pilots, for example, and with the<br>
flight attendants and with the teachers to see that their needs are<br>
met within the federation and that we help them in their organizing<br>
efforts just as much as we have with unions organizing low-paid<br>
workers.<br>
<br>
QUESTION: This wouldn't be complete without a campaign question.<br>
I heard you got a good reception at the Building and Construction<br>
Trades meeting in Chicago. Is there anything you can tell us about<br>
what the changes in the Carpenters union, for example, might mean?<br>
Was Mr. Lucassen's departure and Mr. McCarron's ascension good news<br>
for you?<br>
<br>
DONAHUE: I thought the good news was that the Carpenters union<br>
refused to vote an endorsement to John Sweeney at their executive<br>
board meeting, though it was my understanding that Sig Lucassen<br>
asked for such an endorsement.<br>
<br>
I thought that was good news.<br>
<br>
I had asked for an opportunity to speak to that board. Sig had<br>
invited me the night before and I was unable to go to the meeting.<br>
But I'm told that I will have an opportunity to speak to their<br>
board at their convention. I'd been invited to speak to their<br>
convention many months ago. And I'll be having a meeting with their<br>
executive board then.<br>
<br>
So I regard that as indicative that that union is still making<br>
up its mind, as I believe a number of other unions are making up<br>
their minds. I just don't believe that the Iowa primary decides the<br>
presidential races and I don't believe that whatever figures<br>
anybody wants to cite in May, June, July or August decide a race<br>
that's going to be held on the 25th of October.<br>
<br>
We'll take the vote on the 25th of October.<br>
<br>
QUESTION: You have said a couple of times in the past that in the<br>
future you would state who was in your camp and offer the same sort<br>
of numbers of support that Sweeney-Trumka has been promoting. Are<br>
you close to doing that?<br>
<br>
DONAHUE: The reality is that I'm being supported by 47 to 48<br>
unions. Sweeney is claiming 22 to 24. I think that leads me to<br>
conclude that I have the support of the majority of leaders who are<br>
most informed about the work of the federation and about what needs<br>
to be done.<br>
<br>
Now, it's perfectly true that the unions that are supporting<br>
John are bigger unions and so he has a numerical advantage at this<br>
point. That's clear. Part of the reason he has a numerical<br>
advantage is because he started with 1 million votes in his pocket<br>
which are from my union. <br>
<br>
That's a fair question. I think that the numbers will change.<br>
<br>
QUESTION: Do you believe that the number of unions, would you<br>
agree that it is about the 60 percent for him?<br>
<br>
DONAHUE: No, I think that's an exaggeration. I think it's more<br>
like 53, 54 percent. And there are still seven or eight unions that<br>
are in flight.<br>
<br>
QUESTION: What about the strength of the labor movement in the<br>
South? The last couple of years there have been some major plant<br>
openings with Mercedes and BMW in South Carolina and Alabama. The<br>
South has a strong right-to-work tradition and this is where a lot<br>
of businesses are going. How are you doing in the South and what<br>
are you doing to make any gains down there?<br>
<br>
DONAHUE: I think the question on Mercedes, BMW is really a UAW<br>
question. They have been involved in efforts to organize and to<br>
represent the workers in those plants and I think those will<br>
obviously continue over some time.<br>
<br>
The interesting thing about plant movement to the South is<br>
that I think of the Saturn operation, where the UAW has been a<br>
prime mover in the effort to create the new company, and I think<br>
it's setting a style for the South. I hope it is. That it is a<br>
model that would carry through into a lot of other parts of the<br>
auto industry production in the South. But the federation has not<br>
been singly involved on the Mercedes, BMW issue or the other issues<br>
there. <br>
<br>
There is continuing organizing in the South by lots of our<br>
affiliates and the IUD, the Industrial Union Department, has long<br>
coordinated a Southern organizing strategy, with continuing slow<br>
growth.<br>
<br>
QUESTION: A lot of governors who are getting elected are quite<br>
open about promoting their right-to-work states and their anti-<br>
union environment. And they succeed in getting a lot of businesses,<br>
not just automotive. The success is to promote yourself as non-<br>
union. How do you make gain?<br>
<br>
DONAHUE: But that's not new. That's been going on for 40 years, 50<br>
years.<br>
<br>
QUESTION: What will you do to combat that?<br>
<br>
DONAHUE: It's not just the movement of the South that I say<br>
accounts for our membership, our inability to grow. It's a movement<br>
all the way South beyond the border, where you find 600,000<br>
American jobs in the maquiladoras; 165,000 of those belong to<br>
General Motors. They're hard to organize, clear on the other side<br>
of the border. They're even harder than other parts of the South. <br>
<br>
But that's not a new phenomenon, the states bidding against<br>
one another on either the largest tax advantage or a benefit they<br>
can offer a corporation or their right-to-work status. Indeed it is<br>
a question that's been raised in some of the discussions we've had<br>
with the Canadian Labor Congress about whether or not the right-to-<br>
work states confer an unfair trade advantage on companies which<br>
move from Canada to a right-to-work state. Is that not a subject<br>
that should be addressed under the side agreements on NAFTA? I<br>
think it's a fascinating question. <br>
<br>
Clearly, if you entice a company to move from Canada, where<br>
you don't have right-to-work laws and part of the enticement is to<br>
come to a Southern state where you do have right-to-work laws, then<br>
they do confer an unfair trade advantage?<br>
<br>
I think it's something that ought to be examined in the NAFTA<br>
side agreement.<br>
<br>
QUESTION: Taking a look at Congress coming back next week and the<br>
Senate, realistically what kind of changes do you see being made in<br>
the Labor/HHS Appropriations? And have you had contact with Senator<br>
Specter, who chairs the Labor/HHS subcommittee? And out of that<br>
whole bill that was so critical coming out of the House, which of<br>
the points are you going to be working hardest to get modified in<br>
the Senate?<br>
<br>
DONAHUE: I think that the general view that the Senate is the more<br>
deliberative body will influence to a fair extent the Labor/HHS<br>
appropriations legislation and the other legislation coming along. <br>
<br>
I think that you would see in the Senate much less stomach for<br>
the kind of atrocious cuts in OSHA enforcement, the cuts in the<br>
National Labor Relations Board and so forth. <br>
<br>
So I think there is a different attitude in the Senate on some<br>
of those things and I think that the bills which will emerge in the<br>
Senate, hopefully, will be less vicious to workers than the House<br>
versions.<br>
<br>
QUESTION: In the Senate, you also have a Republican presidential<br>
nomination playing out.<br>
<br>
DONAHUE: Yes, but it may well be that in some issues that race<br>
benefits us. <br>
<br>
QUESTION: How is that?<br>
<br>
DONAHUE: It seems to be stalling the discussions on worker rights<br>
in the Chile negotiations -- as opposed to the earlier Republican<br>
positions in the Senate that there would never be any inclusion or<br>
discussion of worker rights. Even standing still is better than<br>
that proposition.<br>
<br>
So I am hopeful that the Senate will prove to be slightly more<br>
rational. <br>
<br>
Yes, I met with Sen. Specter to discuss . . .<br>
<br>
QUESTION: When did you talk to him and what was his . . . <br>
<br>
DONAHUE: I'm sorry I can't give you an exact date, but it was<br>
probably about two weeks ago. I'm sorry it was more than that, it<br>
was the last days of the session, so it's three weeks ago.<br>
<br>
We talked, simply, about the prospects for Labor/HHS and how<br>
he was going to handle it, and I had the sense that there will be<br>
less action on some of those matters in the Senate committee and<br>
more of the amendments will be offered on the floor of the Senate.<br>
Whether that all goes or augurs well or ill, I can't divine at this<br>
point.<br>
<br>
I think, however, that the more the program is exposed to<br>
public discourse and public discussion the more people understand<br>
what the effect of these bills really are. Then I think that to<br>
that extent the Senate will be more cautious. I don't expect,<br>
however, the Senate to pass a bill on Labor/HHS appropriations that<br>
we will think is a splendid and sterling bill. <br>
<br>
I think you'll see much of what was done in the House remain<br>
and I think you'll see a presidential veto. And then we'll go on<br>
from there.<br>
<br>
But I thank that's going to be the course of lots of things as<br>
the legislative session heats up from now until December.<br>
<br>
QUESTION: You mentioned your anticipation of presidential vetoes.<br>
What can you say to your members and people in general would be the<br>
consequences of a Republican victory in the presidential level next<br>
and retaining the Congress? What would that augur for labor?<br>
<br>
DONAHUE: A Republican victory in the presidential race? I think it<br>
would put at risk the social gains that the nation has achieved<br>
over the last century. Certainly the social gains of the last 60<br>
years would all be put at risk.<br>
<br>
I would regard that most seriously. And I think that's<br>
absolutely accurate. If this Congress, in the face of a Democratic<br>
president, is willing to put at risk the education of kids, the<br>
safety and health of workers in the workplace, then surely they are<br>
willing to put at risk such matters as Social Security, Medicare,<br>
Medicaid all the rest of the benefits that people have achieved<br>
over the years.<br>
<br>
Certainly they would be prepared to create new systems for<br>
pensions and destroy the current pension system and pretend that we<br>
can rely upon savings as a substitute.<br>
<br>
I think it is accurate to say that it would put at risk every<br>
social gain that this nation has made over the last 60 years<br>
including the successful efforts we've made in developing a more<br>
color-blind society, and certainly all of our efforts in<br>
affirmative action, and so forth.<br>
<br>
QUESTION: Will that sort of thinking persuade the Reagan Democrats<br>
among your members?<br>
<br>
DONAHUE: I believe so. The truth is, I insist to you, that we have<br>
had fewer defections and a smaller shift of trade union members to<br>
the Reagan philosophy or to a right-wing philosophy than is true of<br>
the society at large.<br>
<br>
So it is less of a problem for us, but it is nonetheless a<br>
problem.<br>
<br>
QUESTION: But your members count the most because they are not<br>
expected to go the other direction.<br>
<br>
DONAHUE: That may be true. It's clearly something we have to work<br>
very hard at. We have to make sure that our people understand the<br>
consequences of the political decisions they make. And we have to<br>
make them understand that it is easy to talk about government in<br>
terms of slogans, but it is quite another thing when you get behind<br>
the slogan and look at the effect it has on that worker and on his<br>
or her family. That's what we have to make them realize. We have to<br>
make them realize that it makes no sense to vote a prejudice<br>
against big government, whatever that is. When in fact the result<br>
of that is that more workers are going to get killed on the job.<br>
That just makes no sense. It makes no sense to vote for politicians<br>
who keep preaching that we need to make the rich richer when you<br>
are one of the poor and you are getting poorer.<br>
<br>
I think that we need to make sure that our people understand<br>
those facts.<br>
<br>
QUESTION: Do you think that if all of these horrible things come<br>
to pass with a Republican victory, it will make people want unions<br>
more?<br>
<br>
DONAHUE: The answer may be, things get worse before they get<br>
better. I certainly hope that's not true for the benefit of all of<br>
the workers in this country. Things don't have to get so bad before<br>
it turns around.<br>
<br>
QUESTION: Have you essentially forgiven Clinton for NAFTA at this<br>
point? Political reality has forced one to accept what is? Is NAFTA<br>
a dead issue?<br>
<br>
DONAHUE: What is true about NAFTA is that we were right. And<br>
everybody else was wrong. We take very small comfort in that<br>
knowledge. But we were right. We said that the Mexican economy was<br>
unstable. We said repeatedly during the consideration of NAFTA that<br>
there was to be a devaluation and it was going to happen and when<br>
it happened America would be further disadvantaged. And that's<br>
precisely what happened. We said that we would lose far more jobs<br>
than we would gain. And the administration and the other advocates<br>
of NAFTA kept touting all the statistical studies which told us we<br>
were going to gain hundred of thousands of jobs. And we said they<br>
were wrong. And as it turned out, they were wrong. And we are<br>
looking at major deficits in Mexican trade this year and worse<br>
deficits next year. <br>
<br>
In terms of the Clinton administration, you have to remember<br>
that NAFTA was not a Clinton-negotiated agreement. He attempted to<br>
salvage the protection of worker rights and the environmental<br>
rights. We don't think he did it well enough. And so we campaigned<br>
against NAFTA. <br>
<br>
We would have won, but for the fact that the administration<br>
gave away enough sugar beets and grapefruit protections and other<br>
protections to gain the votes to pass it.<br>
<br>
There is no question that we were speaking for the American<br>
people on that issue and that the majority of Americans agreed with<br>
us. <br>
<br>
I know that the current surveys tell you differently. But<br>
that's because people changed their mind after the event.<br>
<br>
But I don't think that is a factor in our judgments today<br>
about support for Bill Clinton or respect for his administration<br>
and for what he has tried to do for workers.<br>
<br>
QUESTION: Or for Democrats in Congress who voted for NAFTA?<br>
<br>
DONAHUE: I think that continues to be a very difficult vote for<br>
them and people continue to judge those who voted for NAFTA harshly<br>
on that count. There is no question about that.<br>
<br>
That was a serious fight and our membership and our leadership<br>
were properly incensed about people who voted against America's<br>
workers' interests in that fight.<br>
<br>
And those who had what we would term a bad vote on NAFTA will<br>
continue to be troubled by that vote. No question in my mind about<br>
that.<br>
<br>
And I submit to you that in the future that will -- not the<br>
NAFTA vote, but the question of our support for politicians -- will<br>
be, I think, much more related and much more balanced against what<br>
politicians do for workers.<br>
<br>
I don't think there is any more of a change here -- no more<br>
blank checks here, no more free rides for politicians who would<br>
vote against the interests of workers. That's not to say that<br>
somebody who disagrees with us on one issue will be voted out of<br>
office or not have any trade union support. But I think you will<br>
see a much more measured support for politicians which will be much<br>
more closely related to their overall performance.<br>
<br>
Attending were reporters from: Associated Press, Buffalo News,<br>
Cleveland Plain Dealer, New York Times Group, Pittsburgh Post<br>
Gazette and Reuters.</p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="/publ/publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
