<html>

<head>
<title>SP 07/11/95 Donahue at CWA Convention</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>Remarks of AFL-CIO Secretary-Treasurer Tom Donahue<br>
to the Communications Workers of America Convention<br>
Anaheim, California<br>
July 11, 1995<br>
<br>
<br>
I am delighted to be here. I bring you greetings from the more<br>
than 13 million working men and women who are the AFL-CIO. I come<br>
to pay tribute to your union and its leaders -- Morty, Barbara,<br>
Nick -- and to all of you as its leaders for having created this<br>
fine union.<br>
<br>
Let me begin by also thanking Morty Bahr and each one of you<br>
for being willing to share your Secretary-Treasurer with the entire<br>
American trade union movement.<br>
<br>
I must confess that I feel some guilt standing here before<br>
you, but I want to assure you that I conducted this &quot;raid&quot; only<br>
with the blessing and, indeed, the encouragement of your good<br>
President and my good friend, Morty Bahr.<br>
<br>
Morty and I have been through lots of struggles and lots of<br>
good times through the years, both in New York and in Washington.<br>
There is no one I am prouder to be associated with and to have at<br>
my side.<br>
<br>
Above all, I want to thank Barbara for agreeing to join with<br>
me to lead the AFL-CIO in difficult years. As I said when we<br>
announced our ticket, Barbara will bring to the AFL-CIO not only<br>
her &quot;breadth and depth of experience,&quot; but special &quot;qualities of<br>
mind and heart.&quot; <br>
<br>
I wish you could have been there at the press conference.<br>
Barbara talked about the lessons she had learned growing up as the<br>
daughter of a coal miner. She talked about the lessons she had<br>
learned in her local union, representing the operators and other<br>
employees of Ohio Bell.<br>
<br>
And she talked about the lessons she had learned on the staff<br>
and as an officer of this great union -- as she put it, &quot;the need<br>
to embrace change ... to make it work for working people and not<br>
against us.&quot;<br>
<br>
She captured what our campaign and our vision for the AFL-CIO<br>
are all about. It is a campaign about solidarity, diversity, and<br>
above all, innovation.<br>
<br>
Barbara herself represents one innovation that's long overdue.<br>
I am proud to be on the ticket with the first Secretary-Treasurer<br>
of a national union to run for Secretary-Treasurer of the AFL-CIO -<br>
- indeed, the only candidate for leadership in the history of our<br>
movement who happens not to be a white male, and who is running for<br>
a real, existing post as one of the two executive officers of the<br>
AFL-CIO.<br>
<br>
If, as we expect, we are elected by the Executive Council on<br>
August 1, we will begin together to hasten the pace of innovation,<br>
of progress, of growth in this labor movement.<br>
<br>
Barbara and I and the unions that support us are out to change<br>
things for the better -- change to ensure progress.<br>
<br>
Indeed, there is probably no better example of what the AFL-<br>
CIO needs to do than the CWA itself, under the leadership of Morty<br>
Bahr, Barbara Easterling, and M.E. Nichols. Your union is a model<br>
for trade unionism: idealistic, progressive, militant, far-sighted,<br>
and absolutely dedicated to improving the lives of its members.<br>
<br>
It is always ready, willing, and able to play an appropriate<br>
and realistic role in our struggle to make this nation responsive<br>
to the needs of working families.<br>
<br>
When it comes to long-term planning, you wrote the book. More<br>
than a dozen years ago, you pioneered with your Committee on the<br>
Future. <br>
<br>
You've broken new ground by demonstrating how much can be<br>
accomplished through real partnerships between labor and management<br>
-- partnerships based on equality, independence, and mutual<br>
recognition and respect. Your Workplace of the Future agreements<br>
are a model for the rest of the labor movement.<br>
<br>
Your organizing program is second to none in its level of<br>
energy and creativity, organizing both in old and new industries,<br>
from newspapers and cable television to the information<br>
superhighway.<br>
<br>
Even more important, you are organizing in new ways. The<br>
employee associations you have created at NCR, at Sprint, and at a<br>
number of other companies offer a new model for the labor movement.<br>
And the agreement you recently negotiated with AT&amp;T marks a<br>
historic breakthrough in securing for individual workers at what<br>
was NCR the right to be represented by a union. <br>
<br>
While others talk about the need to integrate our unions into<br>
larger industrial groupings, you've actually done it. You have<br>
brought under one roof unions representing working people<br>
throughout the communications industry -- the United Telegraph<br>
Workers, the International Typographic Union, NABET, and very<br>
likely the Newspaper Guild.<br>
<br>
Every single member who has been part of this consolidation is<br>
getting more effective representation in each of those divisions<br>
because of your unity.<br>
While others talk about the need for diversity, you've elected<br>
an Executive Board that is representative of the diversity of your<br>
union.<br>
<br>
You've done all this without compromising your core<br>
responsibilities, and you've done it with an informed and actively<br>
involved membership.<br>
<br>
When businesses all across the country are trying to chisel<br>
away our wages and benefits, you have just succeeded not only in<br>
resisting cutbacks in your health benefits but in negotiating<br>
healthy and well-deserved pay increases at AT&amp;T. <br>
<br>
I congratulate you for that -- but nothing in this movement is<br>
easy or simple, nor are any of our victories ever final.<br>
<br>
When we settle one contract or dozens, we then go on to the<br>
others. And so you now face real struggle in New Jersey, where the<br>
Republican governor finds it very simple to say, &quot;I'm going to<br>
change the health benefit formulas and you have to pay for that<br>
change.&quot; And you will face struggle in dozens of other negotiations<br>
throughout the year.<br>
<br>
In reviewing your accomplishments, it is not my purpose to pit<br>
the CWA against other unions. Nor do I mean to suggest that your<br>
way is &quot;the way&quot; or &quot;the only way.&quot;<br>
<br>
As I'm sure you know, my union is the Service Employees. While<br>
John Sweeney will be running against me in October, I do not doubt<br>
for a minute that, as John's press release says, the SEIU &quot;fairly<br>
sparkles with energy, creativity, and hope.&quot;<br>
<br>
The point is that no individual, no union, and no group of<br>
unions has a monopoly on these efforts. Each union has something to<br>
learn from, and something to teach to, other unions.<br>
<br>
That's why unity and innovation must go hand in hand. And<br>
that's why the Federation needs leaders like Barbara and me who can<br>
draw the labor movement together behind a program of progressive<br>
change.<br>
<br>
Talk is cheap. Rhetoric about innovation is easy. If talk<br>
organized members, we would be four or five times our current size.<br>
<br>
If rhetoric made change happen, we would all be dizzy from new<br>
forms and new successes.<br>
<br>
But talk and rhetoric won't cut it.<br>
<br>
We need to talk specifics. Let me tell you what Barbara and I<br>
believe the challenge for our movement really is, and how we want<br>
to address it.<br>
The challenge is to grow, not for numbers alone but because we<br>
have a moral responsibility to offer the opportunity to have a<br>
union -- the opportunity to enjoy respect -- to every worker in<br>
this nation.<br>
<br>
The challenge is to serve better every current member and<br>
every future member -- to serve them on the job, to serve them in<br>
their communities, and to serve them in the legislative and<br>
political arenas at the federal, state, and local levels.<br>
<br>
The challenge is to make our nation better, to stand up for<br>
America's working families and to insist that our politicians do<br>
the same.<br>
<br>
The challenge is to insist that tax policies and economic<br>
policies should provide a better distribution of the wealth of this<br>
nation, and should create and maintain an economy that serves the<br>
people, not vice versa.<br>
<br>
The challenge is to do a whole lot better job of explaining<br>
this trade union movement and its goals and activities to the<br>
American people, a better job than we have done up to now.<br>
<br>
We all know that this is a virtuous movement, designed to make<br>
America a better place for everyone in it, but we clearly have<br>
failed to get that message across to all Americans.<br>
<br>
It is small wonder that this is true, given the domination of<br>
the media by business interests. But while that is a huge obstacle,<br>
we have to find the ways to overcome that bias.<br>
<br>
All of these challenges and all of the solutions to them --<br>
the ways of meeting them and overcoming them -- are linked.<br>
<br>
We can't grow if we can't explain ourselves better. We can't<br>
serve members better unless we make the nation better. <br>
<br>
We can't change tax and economic policies unless we are<br>
politically stronger. And we can't be politically stronger if we<br>
don't grow. <br>
<br>
And if we don't grow, we can't negotiate better in the face of<br>
non-union competition.<br>
<br>
It is all a seamless garment. We have to take on all the<br>
challenges and make progress on each one of them.<br>
<br>
The first is to grow. You all know the numbers. We represent<br>
16 percent of the work force and we used to represent more than 30<br>
percent.<br>
<br>
We also know that salvation won't come from on high. We can't<br>
wait for a better law before we organize the unorganized.<br>
<br>
Things won't change until we make them change.<br>
<br>
The job of the federation can't be to do the actual<br>
organizing. That's the job of each affiliated union. They know<br>
their industries, their industries' problems, their workers' needs.<br>
But lots of our unions are too small to be able to put resources<br>
into organizing, and they are having a tough time adequately<br>
serving current members.<br>
<br>
There is a lot that the federation can do to encourage, and<br>
energize, and support the organizing efforts of the affiliates.<br>
<br>
First, the Federation can do more to recruit and train a new<br>
generation of organizers through the Organizing Institute.<br>
<br>
The Institute already has a great track record. It has become<br>
one of the largest, most successful programs of the Federation.<br>
<br>
It has already graduated nearly 400 organizers, and this year,<br>
we will graduate about 150 more. Those graduates, more than half of<br>
them women or people of color, are now involved in just about every<br>
large organizing campaign in our movement. <br>
<br>
I think we can expand the Organizing Institute until it can<br>
graduate enough organizers to meet the needs of every union in the<br>
Federation. And I would like to work with every union to increase<br>
their ability to hire and use Institute graduates.<br>
<br>
I believe that next year, we can double the number of<br>
organizers that graduate from the Institute, and we intend to do<br>
that.<br>
<br>
But in the final analysis, the best organizers in the trade<br>
union movement are in this room and in your workplaces.<br>
<br>
Member involvement is our best hope of continuing the<br>
membership growth cycle we are in. As quiet as the news has been<br>
kept, the Bureau of Labor Statistics has reported growth of trade<br>
unions in each of the last two years, a total of 340,000 members.<br>
<br>
This is a growth rate of only 3 percent, but these are the<br>
first years in a decade that we have grown in absolute numbers.<br>
<br>
Member involvement cannot be just rhetoric. It means an<br>
emphasis on real worker ownership of our unions, locally and<br>
nationally, and the investment of real resources in members as<br>
volunteers and full-time local organizers. <br>
<br>
Second, I believe we should create a multi-million-dollar<br>
organizing trust fund to encourage organizing projects that are<br>
important to the strategy of the entire trade union movement. The<br>
fund would be used to leverage affiliates' spending in industries<br>
that are hard to organize and industries where unions haven't been<br>
much of a presence up to now.<br>
<br>
Third, I believe the AFL-CIO should help start new kinds of<br>
worker organizations, side by side with unions that do traditional<br>
collective bargaining.<br>
<br>
We should experiment more with &quot;less-than-exclusive&quot;<br>
recognition and representation, just as you have done with the<br>
workers at NCR. <br>
We should also explore associations of workers who are linked<br>
together by a certain kind of occupation rather than the same<br>
workplace.<br>
<br>
These days, more and more workers aren't attached to a single<br>
employer. They're attached to a specific kind of work or an<br>
industry. <br>
<br>
These are the part-time and temporary workers, or &quot;contingent<br>
workers.&quot; They need unions just as much as the rest of us need<br>
unions, maybe even more. But if they're going to be at a single<br>
workplace for just a few weeks or months, it makes sense to<br>
organize them according to the type of work they do rather than the<br>
workplace.<br>
<br>
It makes sense to bond them together by their work, to make<br>
that bond effective in the workplace, and then to help them move to<br>
career opportunities and security.<br>
<br>
What is true of contingent workers is also true of many<br>
professional and technical workers -- and ten years down the line,<br>
they'll make up 40 percent of all non-managerial employees.<br>
<br>
Fourth, the AFL-CIO should set up an American Association of<br>
Working Persons to serve the active workforce, in ways similar to<br>
those in which the AARP and the National Council of Senior Citizens<br>
serve older Americans. <br>
<br>
Fifth, I believe that we should set up a Labor Leadership<br>
Institute for Workplace Change to help trade union leaders develop<br>
new sets of skills and new kinds of representation for workplaces<br>
that are far different from those we're used to and are getting<br>
more different every day.<br>
<br>
There are millions of unorganized workers in those new<br>
workplaces, especially white-collar and pink-collar workers, who<br>
want an independent voice on the job. But at the same time, they<br>
read the papers. They know how determined bosses are to make life<br>
hard for those who seek a union. And lots of them are either not<br>
ready, or not able, or not willing to take on what appears to them<br>
to be a war with their employers.<br>
<br>
We need to learn more about how to serve their needs, how to<br>
represent them in the way they want to be represented.<br>
I have spent a lot of time on organizing because we simply<br>
have to grow. Let me now turn to our challenges in government and<br>
politics.<br>
<br>
You know and I know that the corporations and the wealthy now<br>
control Congress and many state governments. Their prime targets<br>
are programs that help America's working families -- from OSHA, to<br>
the 40-hour week, to an attempt to legislative away the very<br>
existence of independent trade unions.<br>
<br>
To defend ourselves and then to get back on the offensive, we<br>
have to go back to basics.<br>
<br>
First, we need to harness the energy of our trade unionist<br>
activists. I want to build a network of activists from our unions<br>
across our movement, all of them linked together electronically,<br>
updated on important issues, and able to move into action on a<br>
moment's notice.<br>
<br>
Second and even more important, we need to reach out to each<br>
and every rank-and-file member. We have to educate and activate all<br>
of our members.<br>
<br>
There are simply too many trade unionists, especially among<br>
our newer and younger members, who have little contact with their<br>
unions and little understanding of what unionism is all about.<br>
<br>
They see the union as a slot machine. We haven't educated them<br>
about the real linkage between their activism and their political<br>
and economic well-being.<br>
<br>
The campaign we are now waging to Stand Up for America's<br>
Working Families illustrates what the AFL-CIO can do. In that<br>
campaign, we have brought together our legislative, political and<br>
communications operations to develop a coordinated set of messages<br>
to our members. These messages explain exactly what the stakes are<br>
for them in the Republican agenda -- what a weak OSHA law means on<br>
their job, what &quot;less government&quot; or &quot;getting government off our<br>
back&quot; means to their families' well-being.<br>
<br>
We have produced a set of campaign materials -- videos,<br>
pamphlets, pins, bumper stickers -- that are being disseminated<br>
widely throughout the movement. <br>
<br>
The AFL-CIO has assigned half of its field staff to the<br>
campaign. During each congressional recess, our staff and that of<br>
affiliated unions is working in carefully selected congressional<br>
districts to coordinate Stand Up activities, from leafletting at<br>
plant gates to confronting congressmen at their country clubs.<br>
<br>
And we have bought nearly a million dollars of local radio,<br>
television, and newspaper advertising, the largest media buy since<br>
the NAFTA campaign.<br>
<br>
All of that is designed to make clear to these politicians<br>
that we are going to be much tougher in measuring their<br>
performance.<br>
<br>
We will match our efforts for or against them to their efforts<br>
for or against us. No more free rides!<br>
<br>
All politics is not, as some say, a choice between the lesser<br>
of two evils. Our politics can be one of real, dedicated,<br>
determined support for good politicians who represent the best<br>
interests of working people. <br>
<br>
We are going to develop the sophisticated ways of opposing<br>
those who don't. As for those who find it possible to support<br>
worker interests only some of the time, we can find it possible to<br>
be lukewarm to ice cold in our support for them.<br>
<br>
We also need to make our public communications work better, to<br>
explain ourselves, our ideas, and our programs better.<br>
<br>
To do that, we need better coordination with affiliated<br>
unions. We have to work together to attract attention to those<br>
messages and events that are most important for the public to<br>
understand.<br>
<br>
We have to recognize that most of the communications in the<br>
nation today take place not through national media but at the local<br>
level, through local papers, radio and TV.<br>
<br>
We also need to figure out how, in a coordinated fashion, to<br>
make best use of the newer forms of communication -- from talk<br>
radio and cable television to the Internet and the information<br>
superhighway -- as well as how best to use paid advertising and how<br>
to earn free media attention.<br>
<br>
We need to get our message out, to get it heard and<br>
understood. Only then can we change America. <br>
<br>
Let me close with a few thoughts.<br>
<br>
The challenges we face are enormous, but we are still the<br>
largest, strongest, most vibrant labor movement in the world. <br>
<br>
And there are plenty of good, sound ideas for renewing and<br>
strengthening our movement -- ideas at AFL-CIO headquarters, at <br>
every national and international union, at every local. We just<br>
need to get them out, get them heard, and get the best of them in<br>
place.<br>
<br>
We need to look at changing some of the structure and<br>
techniques of the AFL-CIO. But it is not change in the inner<br>
workings of the AFL-CIO that will turn things around for the<br>
working men and women of this country or for the unions that<br>
represent them. It is the renewed dedication and energy of the men<br>
and women of this movement that will make the difference. <br>
<br>
We are a movement of 13 million people and their families. We<br>
are a movement of 80 national unions, 50 state federations, over<br>
500 city central bodies, 50,000 local unions, and over a quarter-<br>
million local officers.<br>
<br>
We are amazingly diverse in every sense. We have to be<br>
respectful of that diversity, and we have to find the common ground<br>
that unites us all.<br>
<br>
No small group of unions or union presidents can separate<br>
themselves out, declare their program to be the only way forward,<br>
and seek by sheer numbers to force those decisions on everyone<br>
else.<br>
<br>
This federation will survive and prosper only if everyone in<br>
it is given an opportunity to work with everyone else to form a<br>
dynamic consensus on our future program.<br>
<br>
I promise you that Barbara Easterling and I will work as hard<br>
as we know how from August 1 on to forge that dynamic consensus, to<br>
equip this movement to best serve the interests of all our members<br>
and of the nation.<br>
<br>
The working men and women who depend on this movement and the<br>
millions more who seek a genuine voice on the job require that we<br>
make common cause. I'm confident we can.<br>
<br>
Thank you.</p>
