<title>SP 06/30/95 Kirkland at ACTWU/ILGWU</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>Remarks of AFL-CIO President Lane Kirkland<br>
ACTWU/ILGWU Merger Convention<br>
Miami Beach, Florida<br>
June 30, 1995<br>
<br>
<br>
President Mazur, Brother Sheinkman, Brother Loevy,<br>
Brother Raynor, Brother Romney, brothers and sisters:<br>
<br>
It is a special pleasure to be here for this historic<br>
convention, which merges two proud, unions into a major<br>
force for progressive change in the 21st Century -- a force<br>
for working people and the dignity and justice they deserve.<br>
<br>
&quot;In unity there is strength.&quot; It is the oldest and yet<br>
the most modern bedrock principle of this labor movement. <br>
And it is the clarion call from your decision this week to<br>
merge the Amalgamated with the ILG.<br>
<br>
On behalf of your 13 million brothers and sisters who<br>
belong to the unions of the AFL-CIO, I am proud to help you<br>
inaugurate your new era as the Union of Needletrades,<br>
Industrial and Textile Employees.<br>
<br>
I have no doubt that UNITE is going to be in the<br>
forefront of the labor movement's struggle to make life<br>
better for working families everywhere.<br>
<br>
For what it's worth, I want you to know that this<br>
merger has my blessing with only one qualification -- and<br>
that is that UNITE must still have Evy Dubrow, fighting the<br>
good fight for all of us on Capitol Hill. We young people<br>
must stick together, Evy.<br>
I want to extend my personal congratulations to Jack<br>
Sheinkman and Jay Mazur, whose leadership and vision made<br>
this extraordinary event actually happen. Together, they<br>
have carried forward the ideals that ACTWU and the ILG have<br>
so forcefully advocated since the turn of the century.<br>
<br>
Just as all of labor looked to Sidney Hillman and David<br>
Dubinsky for their leadership and their ideas to confront<br>
the challenges of an earlier era, Jack and Jay have kept the<br>
needle trades unions on the cutting edge of the critical<br>
issues of today.<br>
<br>
I'm referring very specifically to the globalization of<br>
the economy and the exploitation of working people both at<br>
home and abroad. Let me address that issue for a moment.<br>
<br>
As you know, over the past several months, there has<br>
been much debate over the leadership of the AFL-CIO and its<br>
policies and programs.<br>
<br>
There is nothing inherently troubling about that. We<br>
are a democratic movement and such debate is part and parcel<br>
of that fact.<br>
But there is one thing that disturbs me very much --<br>
and that is the tendency of some to make a political issue<br>
of our movement's activities on behalf of our brothers and<br>
sisters in other countries.<br>
<br>
The argument -- and I've heard it put forth, recently,<br>
by prominent trade union leaders -- goes something like<br>
this: &quot;We appreciate what the AFL-CIO has done to advance<br>
democracy in places like Poland, Chile, South Africa and<br>
elsewhere in the world. But that fight is over. Workers in<br>
our own country have real problems, and we should stop<br>
focusing our attention abroad and come home.&quot;<br>
But you can't go home again -- the world won't let you.<br>
<br>
What they are advocating is nothing less than the<br>
abandonment of a principle that the American labor movement<br>
has championed since the days when Samuel Gompers helped<br>
launch the International Labor Organization -- poverty<br>
anywhere is a threat to prosperity everywhere.<br>
<br>
It's bad enough that the right wing in Congress has<br>
again succumbed to the fatal lure of isolationism. We hear<br>
from Senators Dole and Helms that the ILO is going to be<br>
history if they get their way.<br>
<br>
The barbarians are at the gates. They have launched a<br>
direct attack on the labor standards and conditions that the<br>
ILO has set forth and which provide a framework for<br>
defending and advancing worker rights in the new global<br>
economy. We've got to stop their campaign to scuttle the<br>
only body in the UN family that addresses the lives and<br>
problems of the billions of working people on whose<br>
shoulders this world rests.<br>
<br>
But above all, let us not join them, under whatever<br>
pretext, in turning our backs on our brothers and sisters in<br>
the far places of this shrinking globe.<br>
<br>
One of the bulwarks of the AFL-CIO Constitution -- the<br>
&quot;Objects and Principles&quot; section -- contains a paragraph<br>
that defines the federation's mission as: &quot;To give<br>
constructive aid in promoting the cause of peace and freedom<br>
in the world and to aid, assist and cooperate with free and<br>
democratic labor movements throughout the world.&quot; If it<br>
should now be said in lofty derogation, that the AFL-CIO<br>
takes this commitment very seriously, that we are overly<br>
concerned with the plight of the wretched of the earth, then<br>
I must plead guilty as charged -- and proudly so.<br>
<br>
There is a reason for this. It is not blithe<br>
rhetoric -- or sentimentality. And our international<br>
responsibilities must not be kicked around like a political football.<br>
<br>
You have learned the hard way that we do not live on an<br>
island. We cannot make a separate peace with those who<br>
would abuse and exploit workers if given a free hand to do<br>
so.<br>
<br>
The global marketplace, the rapid mobility of capital,<br>
the inscrutable nature of flags over workplaces and the<br>
indifference of corporate managements to national values and<br>
aspirations that do not turn into profit -- all of these are<br>
facts of life that we cannot simply wish away.<br>
<br>
The defense of worker rights and standards in our own<br>
country requires that we act in close concert with free<br>
labor everywhere.<br>
<br>
That's why your predecessor unions have worked<br>
tirelessly with your brothers and sisters in the developing<br>
world -- all for the purpose of improving their conditions<br>
and helping them stand on their feet rather than live on<br>
their knees.<br>
<br>
And I am confident that the men and women of UNITE will<br>
continue on this course in the years ahead.<br>
<br>
The grim consequences of rampant market capitalism have<br>
already been felt by workers everywhere, as enterprises roam<br>
the world in search of the cheapest and most repressed<br>
labor.<br>
<br>
They sentence working men and women to misery and death<br>
through starvation wages in fire-trap factories. They<br>
conspire with economic systems that conscript little<br>
children into hard labor. And they forge alliances with the<br>
world's cruelest dictators to undermine the rights,<br>
standards and conditions of working people in the name of<br>
trade, investment and profit.<br>
<br>
Contrary to the arguments of their lackeys in<br>
government, in the usual well-endowed think tanks, and in<br>
journals supported by their ads, these people are not the<br>
tribunes of human freedom and human hope, but are in league<br>
with the deadliest enemies of those values. <br>
<br>
They must be opposed vigorously by all who love liberty<br>
and democracy and the right of workers to band together,<br>
lest a great gulf open into which human beings will fall to<br>
ruin. The AFL-CIO must remain in the vanguard of what will<br>
surely be the next century's greatest and most difficult<br>
struggle.<br>
<br>
Societies and states are raised among men to serve, not<br>
the faceless marketplace, but the aspirations of real<br>
people. We must compel those responsible for affairs of<br>
state and finance to face these questions:<br>
<br>
What prospect motivated those workers whose sacrifice<br>
of their lives is memorialized on the wall of the shipyard<br>
in Gdansk?<br>
<br>
What aspirations moved those young workers who ended up<br>
in unmarked graves in a cemetery on the outskirts of<br>
Budapest, executed in cold blood in the aftermath of the<br>
uprising of 1956?<br>
<br>
What dreams prompted working people to look down the<br>
barrels of guns in the streets of Soweto, the boulevards of<br>
Santiago and at Tiananmen Square?<br>
<br>
What ambitions inspire ordinary, working people<br>
anywhere to place life and limb in harm's way?<br>
<br>
Their valor is summoned to advance, not business<br>
license and market ideology, but rather the right of<br>
ordinary people to live a decent and honest life and not to<br>
be humiliated and kicked around by idiots with the power of<br>
arms or other people's money.<br>
<br>
They seek to fulfill the democratic promise that<br>
ultimate power should reside not in capital or centralized<br>
government -- not in pure individualism or coercive<br>
collectivism -- but rather in communities of people<br>
exercising their rights to free association in order to<br>
express their common aspirations.<br>
<br>
The great and burning question in the world today is<br>
whether this new world order is to serve the ends of those<br>
who brought it to life -- the quest for simple human dignity<br>
and just societies -- or is to be held in thrall by the<br>
agents of ruthless capital.<br>
<br>
It is up to us to see that the answer is not handed<br>
down from on high, but wells up from the places where<br>
attention has been truly earned, from the workplaces and the<br>
streets, wherever plain people band together to build a<br>
decent life.<br>
<br>
We cannot and we must not retreat from that<br>
responsibility. It is what we are all about.<br>
<br>
And I have no doubt that you are up to the challenge.<br>
Thank you. Congratulations. And the very best of luck<br>
in your new era of unity and solidarity.</p>
