<head>
<title>SP 06/21/95 Donahue Utility Workers Union</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>AFL-CIO Secretary-Treasurer Thomas R. Donahue<br>
Utility Workers Union of America<br>
San Diego, California<br>
June 21, 1995<br>
<br>
<br>
This is my third consecutive Utility Workers convention, and<br>
after sweltering with you at the Diplomat both in 1987 and again in<br>
1991 I want to salute you for your choice of this magnificent city<br>
for your 1995 convention. I'm happy to be here with you again, and<br>
not just because we're in San Diego.<br>
<br>
As you all know, last week Lane Kirkland announced his intent<br>
to retire as President of the AFL-CIO and I announced my candidacy<br>
to succeed him. I am proud to say that one of the first persons to<br>
announce his support for me was your good president, Marshall<br>
Hicks, and the resolution you have adopted supporting me is the<br>
second formal convention endorsement I have received. I thank you<br>
for it. Your resolution confirms my view that my candidacy offers<br>
the best opportunity to unite the labor movement behind a program<br>
of solidarity, diversity and innovation. <br>
<br>
President Kirkland's resignation as President of the AFL-CIO<br>
marks the end of an era. Amidst the current debate about what we<br>
ought to accomplish, it is too easy to lose sight of what has been<br>
accomplished during those years. The AFL-CIO of today is a vastly<br>
different -- and better -- organization than it was in 1979. Lane<br>
led us through exceedingly difficult times, and did so with great<br>
distinction. We would be unworthy of our values if, in the heat of<br>
the moment, we were to fail to recognize and pay tribute to Lane<br>
Kirkland. I for one do not propose to allow that to happen.<br>
<br>
At the same time, an impending change of leadership creates an<br>
occasion to reassess where we as a labor movement are and where we<br>
are heading. That is an exceedingly healthy process, and one which<br>
I welcome. <br>
<br>
As you know, for the past ten years I have devoted a great<br>
deal of my time and energies to focusing the Federation and our<br>
affiliated unions on the challenges of the future. That has not<br>
always been easy. Ours is a movement so engaged with our present<br>
responsibilities -- so preoccupied with current economic problems<br>
and so beset by the hostile climate in which we defend worker<br>
rights -- that we too often find it impossible to take the time to<br>
look to the future. It is awfully hard to focus on tomorrow when<br>
today demands so much of us. <br>
<br>
But we have made headway, I think, in introducing for our<br>
affiliates' consideration new and promising approaches. Some did<br>
not pass inspection; others, quite frankly, were tried and failed;<br>
but many have proven to be quite successful and are now part of the<br>
warp and woof of the AFL-CIO.<br>
<br>
In the wake of last November's disastrous elections, there was<br>
and is now a widespread recognition that we need to do more -- to<br>
accelerate the pace of change. The times demand a stronger, more<br>
self-sufficient labor movement. Such a movement requires a strong<br>
Federation at its core. And a strong Federation requires strong<br>
and creative leadership and the united support of all our unions. <br>
<br>
<br>
Our Federation is a peculiar and, in some respects, fragile<br>
institution. It is a voluntary organization of 80 autonomous<br>
unions who represent different kinds of people in different<br>
jurisdictions with different needs. Achieving consensus is never<br>
easy and often frustrating. The need for a broad agreement to<br>
support AFL-CIO action has stalled many a proposal that you might<br>
think -- and that I have thought -- eminently worthwhile. Those<br>
proposals failed because some affiliates -- faithfully representing<br>
their own members -- thought otherwise. <br>
<br>
This process of securing as broad an agreement as possible<br>
cannot be short-circuited. Ultimately what holds us together is the<br>
understanding that in solidarity and in unity lies our strength. <br>
That makes it incumbent upon the next president of the AFL-CIO to<br>
put forth a bold program of innovation that will capture the<br>
imagination of the labor movement and to build the breadth of<br>
support needed to propel that program forward.<br>
<br>
We all know that the trade union movement is in a period of<br>
difficulty. Our unions are in difficulty because working families<br>
are in difficulty. That is not an excuse, it is a simple fact!<br>
<br>
I would like to talk to you today about the challenges as I<br>
see them and about the steps I think we need to take if we are to<br>
fulfill our historic mission.<br>
<br>
Our first, most pressing challenge is to help the unorganized<br>
workers in this country to form and join unions. When I joined the<br>
trade union movement, roughly four in ten workers in this country<br>
belonged to a union. Today, in the private sector, the number is<br>
closer to one in ten. And if present trends were to continue,<br>
within ten years only one in twenty private sector workers would be<br>
part of our movement.<br>
<br>
Some have suggested that labor unions are &quot;no longer relevant&quot;<br>
to today's workers. I disagree. Even if union membership were<br>
ever to reach the end of the road, trade unionism still would be<br>
the most vital, most meaningful force in the work life of its last<br>
100 members, assuring the recognition of their dignity and the<br>
decency of their working conditions. <br>
But such a labor movement would no longer be a major force in<br>
our society. It would no longer help set labor standards. It<br>
would no longer be able to represent working families in the body<br>
politic. <br>
<br>
We cannot allow that to happen.<br>
<br>
We all know the extraordinary obstacles that unorganized<br>
workers face in trying to create independent representation in<br>
their workplace. &quot;Only in America,&quot; as the saying goes, is<br>
business so determined to crush any independent voice for working<br>
people. And only in America does the law allow management free<br>
rein to terrorize workers who seek to stand up for themselves. <br>
<br>
A writer for the Philadelphia Inquirer recently noted that<br>
&quot;organizing a union these days is like breeding pandas in<br>
captivity. If everything goes right, it can be done. Miracles do<br>
happen. But it's so difficult, so risky, so fraught with<br>
frustration and disappointment that fewer and fewer people are<br>
wiling to try.&quot;<br>
<br>
What will change this? We know that salvation will not come<br>
from on high. Things won't change until we make them change. We<br>
can't wait for a better law before we go about the task of<br>
organizing the unorganized. Indeed, in my view our best hope of<br>
achieving labor law reform is first to bring millions of new<br>
workers into our ranks.<br>
<br>
We have all heard -- and given -- stirring speeches about the<br>
importance of organizing. But the truth is that no one and no<br>
institution -- and I include the AFL-CIO in this -- is doing<br>
enough. All of us can, should and must do more.<br>
<br>
Let me cite a couple of shocking statistics to you. Each<br>
year, fewer than two-tenths of one percent of all unorganized<br>
workers are afforded the opportunity to vote for or against union<br>
representation in an NLRB election. Less than forty elections are<br>
held in units with 500 or more employees. The number of elections,<br>
and the number of workers involved in those elections, is now half<br>
of what it was in the 1970's, even though the labor force is quite<br>
a bit larger. <br>
<br>
The AFL-CIO cannot itself do the critical front line work of<br>
organizing unorganized workers. The Federation will never<br>
adequately know the needs and wants of utility workers, for<br>
example, as well as the Utility Workers Union. But I believe that<br>
the Federation can energize the organizing process and assist the<br>
work of our affiliates. <br>
<br>
Last January, we created an Executive Council Committee to<br>
reexamine the Federation's role in organizing. That Committee is<br>
now hard at work. I do not know what will come out of its work,<br>
but let me offer you some specific ideas of my own.<br>
<br>
One critical role for the Federation is to recruit and train<br>
a new generation of organizers. In 1985, the Evolution of Work<br>
Committee which I chair, in its report on The Changing Situation of<br>
Workers and Their Unions, called attention to the need for &quot;broad<br>
recruitment efforts&quot; and &quot;extensive training&quot; of organizers. The<br>
result of our recommendation was the AFL-CIO Organizing Institute.<br>
<br>
The Institute opened its doors in 1990 as a two-person<br>
operation with a tiny budget. Since then, I am proud to report <br>
the Institute's budget has increased five fold to roughly $2.5<br>
million. It is one of our greatest success stories.<br>
<br>
Since 1990, the Institute has graduated 400 organizers. This<br>
year alone the Organizing Institute will provide classroom training<br>
programs to 900 individuals, and will provide supervised<br>
internships and apprenticeships to 200, most of whom will go on to<br>
become full-time organizers. When you look at just about every<br>
large organizing campaign in our movement, you will notice that a<br>
graduate of the Institute is involved.<br>
<br>
I believe we need to expand the Organizing Institute until it<br>
can graduate enough organizers each year to meets the needs of<br>
every union in the Federation. Whatever the cost, that is<br>
something we must find the way to do.<br>
<br>
There is, I believe, a second and equally important role for<br>
the AFL-CIO to play in the organizing process. I believe, the<br>
Federation should create a multi-million dollar organizing trust<br>
fund to be used to stimulate and support organizing projects which<br>
are of strategic importance to the movement as a whole. Organizing<br>
today generally involves small shops that happen to present<br>
themselves to a union somewhere as a target of opportunity. <br>
Organizing is not driven by any strategic sense of important<br>
industries, employers, regions, or occupational groups who we need<br>
to organize. <br>
<br>
I believe the AFL-CIO can change that by using this trust fund<br>
to support organizing projects which are of movement-wide<br>
significance and to which the interested unions make substantial<br>
commitments of their own. In that way the Federation could use its<br>
expenditures to secure much larger commitments of resources from<br>
our affiliates.<br>
<br>
Financing such an effort may not be easy. But it can and<br>
should be done.<br>
<br>
The first group that I would propose we reach out to with this<br>
kind of organizing effort are the low-wage workers in this nation -<br>
- especially immigrants, women and persons of color. They belong<br>
in our movement. And, tragically the low wage workforce is<br>
expanding rapidly; the number and proportion of full-time worker<br>
whose earnings are below the poverty level doubled in the past<br>
fifteen years.<br>
<br>
If we are to organize these workers we must make sure that the<br>
representatives of our unions reflect the diversity of today's<br>
workplace. The Organizing Institute has concentrated on this need<br>
and more than half its graduates are women or persons of color. <br>
But the commitment to diversity and full participation must extend<br>
to all levels of the trade union movement. <br>
<br>
We at the AFL-CIO have been working at this at the staff level<br>
and I am proud to say that in the past ten years almost half of the<br>
newly-appointed department heads have been women or minorities. <br>
And we've seen the beginning of change -- but only its beginning --<br>
in our state federations and city central bodies. <br>
<br>
But the time has now come, in my view, to make the same<br>
commitment with respect to the top leadership of the AFL-CIO. <br>
Yesterday, I gave reality to what up to now has been promises by<br>
announcing that my running mate for the position of AFL-CIO<br>
Secretary-Treasurer will be Barbara Easterling, the Secretary-<br>
Treasurer of the Communication Workers. <br>
<br>
Barbara is one of the highest ranking women -- as well as one<br>
of the most able leaders -- in our movement. The daughter of a<br>
coal miner, she joined the union at age 17, and rose through the<br>
ranks -- as shop steward, secretary and then vice-president of her<br>
local union, national staff representative for CWA, Assistant to<br>
the National President, Executive Vice President, and for the past<br>
three years Secretary-Treasurer. She's going to make an<br>
outstanding Secretary-Treasurer of the AFL-CIO. (Only my high<br>
regard for the incumbent keeps me from saying she will be the best<br>
in recent memory.) <br>
<br>
There is yet a third way in which the AFL-CIO can<br>
significantly contribute to the revitalization of organizing: we<br>
can stimulate the creation of new forms of worker organizations to<br>
supplement our traditional, collective-bargaining institutions. <br>
<br>
One way to do that is to experiment much more broadly with<br>
&quot;less-than-exclusive&quot; recognition. This was one of the ideas<br>
developed in our Evolution of Work committee. We have experience<br>
with it in the public sector where it has been a &quot;building block&quot;<br>
to full collective bargaining.<br>
<br>
Over the past few years the Communications Workers has been<br>
particularly active in testing this idea in the private sector. At<br>
NCR, for example, CWA helped build an NCR employees association. <br>
Now, in the agreement negotiated just last week between AT&amp;T and<br>
CWA, the union was successful in winning the right to represent<br>
individual workers at AT&amp;T Global Information Solutions -- formerly<br>
NCR -- who designate CWA to be their representative. This is an<br>
historic breakthrough and it, and other efforts like it, can blaze<br>
a new trail.<br>
<br>
There are other new trails we need to explore as well. Today,<br>
companies and jobs are less stable than they used to be. Workers<br>
are increasingly attached not so much to their workplace or<br>
employer, but to their occupation and sometimes their industry. <br>
This is especially true of contingent workers, who account for 20%<br>
of today's workforce and who are growing at an exponential rate. <br>
And it is also true of professional and technical workers who will<br>
account for 40% of all non-managerial employees in ten years. <br>
<br>
I believe that we can serve these workers by creating<br>
organizations modeled after our craft unions (in the building<br>
trades, maritime, and printing industries) and professional<br>
associations with an occupational rather than a workplace focus. <br>
This was one of the centerpieces of the Evolution of Work<br>
Committee's 1985 report. At that time, many within the labor<br>
movement were concerned about an active AFL-CIO role in developing<br>
what came to be known as &quot;associate membership&quot; and so the AFL-CIO<br>
largely was limited to creating benefits and services which our<br>
unions offer to those who join their ranks. That program -- the<br>
Union Privilege program -- has been a huge success but we need to<br>
go further.<br>
<br>
I propose that the Federation be authorized to experiment with<br>
different types of associations structured on occupational or<br>
industrial lines. I also continue to believe that we should create<br>
an American Association of Working Persons to serve the active<br>
workforce in much the same way that AARP and the National Council<br>
of Senior Citizens serve older Americans. Such organizations<br>
eventually can become bridges to forming workplace organizations as<br>
well.<br>
<br>
There are millions and millions of unorganized workers --<br>
especially white collar and pink collar workers -- for whom bridges<br>
are not necessary but who need to be reassured that they can have<br>
an independent voice on the job without endless conflict with their<br>
employer. These workers are hungry for a new way of dealing with<br>
their employers.<br>
<br>
Last year, after many years of discussions and debate, the<br>
Evolution of Work Committee paved the way for that to happen with<br>
a report entitled, A Call for Partnership. That Report calls upon<br>
unions &quot;to take the initiative in stimulating, sustaining and<br>
institutionalizing a new system of work organization based upon<br>
full and equal labor-management partnerships.&quot; The Report also<br>
urges the Federation to assume a leadership role in &quot;helping unions<br>
-- and employers -- identify paths to success.&quot; <br>
<br>
We've already taken the first steps. Our Labor Studies Center<br>
has been working this past year with four unions to develop a Labor<br>
Leadership Institute for Workplace Change. <br>
In my view, that kind of program needs to be expanded to serve<br>
the entire labor movement. We need to help this generation -- and<br>
to develop a new generation -- of labor leaders who are prepared to<br>
function in a very different environment requiring expertise and<br>
skills quite different than those required in the past. I would<br>
like to see the AFL-CIO create a new institute, modeled on the<br>
Organizing Institute, but with the mission of training union<br>
leaders for new roles and responsibilities. <br>
<br>
I have talked at great length about organizing because in the<br>
long run, we cannot survive unless we succeed in reorganizing the<br>
workforce. But in the short term, we face challenges which are, if<br>
anything, even more urgent and pressing. <br>
<br>
We talk about building partnership with employers but we know<br>
that many employers still would love nothing better than to<br>
annihilate us, to silence the independent voice of workers and to<br>
regain total control of the workplace.<br>
<br>
In recent years, management has increasingly used or<br>
threatened to use one of the most deadly weapons in its arsenal:<br>
permanent replacements. The law says that workers have a right to<br>
strike, that they cannot be fired for exercising that right, but<br>
that they can be permanently replaced. Charles Dickens was right: <br>
the law is an ass!<br>
<br>
We tried to change the law. We tried to prohibit permanent<br>
replacements in 1992 and again in 1994 but each time we were<br>
defeated by a filibuster led by Senator Hatch and his right-wing<br>
friends. <br>
<br>
I was on Capitol Hill, meeting with Senators, up until the<br>
moment of the vote each time. I know that we waged the good fight<br>
and did everything in our power to win. I know we had the support<br>
of a majority of the Senate to win. But the 60 votes simply<br>
weren't there to break the filibuster.<br>
<br>
President Clinton is now doing what he can to address this<br>
situation through his Executive Order prohibiting the federal<br>
government from doing business with companies which hire permanent<br>
replacements for strikers. The regulations implementing that Order<br>
take effect next week and we need to be ready to make full use of<br>
it.<br>
<br>
In the final analysis, however, it is up to us as a labor<br>
movement to marshall the strength to prevent employers form<br>
successfully breaking our strikes and destroying the lives of<br>
working families through the use of permanent replacements. It is<br>
up to us to do that, whatever the law is. <br>
<br>
The AFL-CIO several years ago created a Strategic Approaches<br>
program to harness the strength of all of our unions in important<br>
struggles. That program has contributed vital support in a number<br>
of epoch battles, and has, I am persuaded, been a substantial<br>
factor in the successful outcomes of several of these. One need<br>
only look at the struggles at Ravenswood Aluminum, or in the New<br>
York, Pittsburgh, and San Francisco newspaper fights, to see the<br>
efficacy of this support mechanism. This program needs to be<br>
nurtured and strengthened. <br>
<br>
We need to make it clear to friend and foe that there will be<br>
no lost strikes. There will be no permanent replacement of<br>
strikers. No matter how long it takes, this labor movement will<br>
stand in solidarity with our strikers for as long as it takes --<br>
and one day longer -- and we will find the resources to sustain the<br>
brave and determined workers who are locked in these struggles.<br>
<br>
Let the word go out to employers who may be inclined to test<br>
our mettle. We seek no conflicts. We seek partnership and<br>
sharing. But neither will we shrink from battles forced upon us.<br>
<br>
Tell the Bridgestones and the Caterpillars and the Staleys and<br>
all the rest, we won't go away. You may produce, but you will not<br>
sell to decent minded people. You will not live in peace in any<br>
community where you oppress workers. We will use every tactics<br>
available to us to make you pay a price every bit as dear as that<br>
which you seek to impose on workers. <br>
<br>
For our part, our affiliates need to ensure that there are no<br>
ill-conceived strikes, no major struggles lightly entered upon<br>
without the fullest consultation. But in the final analysis, where<br>
workers are pressed to a breaking point and determine that they<br>
must fight for decency, they'll have the support of every man and<br>
woman in this Federation, and we will, in turn, seek to enlist the<br>
support of every citizen in the community.<br>
<br>
<br>
We face equally important and tough fights in the legislative<br>
and political arena. The supporters of the wealthy now control<br>
Congress and they are targeting America's working families -- the<br>
government programs that assist them and all the employment laws<br>
that protect them, from OSHA to the 40 hour week. Our unions are<br>
the last bastion of defense for working families.<br>
<br>
To mount that defense -- and get back on the offensive -- we<br>
need to develop a grassroots mobilization effort that will put the<br>
Christian Coalition, and the National Federation of Independent<br>
Businesses, to shame. The right wingers and the corporate<br>
interests learned political organizing from us and they've poured<br>
their millions into refining these techniques in the service of the<br>
privileged few. <br>
<br>
We're never going to be able to match the other side dollar<br>
for dollar, although I believe we have to narrow this gap<br>
substantially. But I'll put the vitality of our trade union<br>
activists up against them any day of the week, so long as we give<br>
our activists the tools. <br>
<br>
We have finally reached the point where virtually all unions<br>
supply our COPE program with their membership lists so we can mount<br>
coordinated political efforts -- although there are still a few of<br>
our largest affiliates who remain outside this process. We have to<br>
continue to try to persuade them of the need for unity in these<br>
efforts and of the program-weakening effects of their abstention. <br>
But with or without them, I believe we now need to take the next<br>
step of building a movement-wide network of activists linked<br>
together electronically and capable of being activated on short<br>
notice, through the Federation and our affiliates.<br>
As important as our activists are, however, our ultimate task<br>
is to reach out to each and every rank-and-file member. The truth<br>
is we spend much of our time &quot;preaching to the choir.&quot; In the<br>
meantime, too many trade unionists, especially among our newer and<br>
younger members, are members in name only. They joined ongoing<br>
unions as a condition of their employment and they have little<br>
contact with and even less understanding of trade unionism. <br>
<br>
If we are to build an effective grassroots legislative and<br>
political operation, we need to attend to the task of what I call<br>
unionizing the already organized. This is another area in which I<br>
think no one -- again, including the AFL-CIO -- has done enough.<br>
<br>
Like all other organizing, the ultimate responsibility must<br>
rest with the individual unions. But here, too, the AFL-CIO can,<br>
and should play a strong leadership role.<br>
<br>
A good example of what the Federation can do was the campaign<br>
against NAFTA, which I was proud to lead. <br>
<br>
We lost against the united forces of the entire business<br>
community and the administration. That was a formidable army<br>
fighting us. But our members -- and working families everywhere --<br>
saw us, heard us, and knew who was fighting for the working people<br>
of this country. We made clear to our members what we are all<br>
about, and made them proud to be members of the labor movement.<br>
<br>
Right now, we are waging a campaign against the Republicans'<br>
legislative assault -- our campaign to Stand UP for America's<br>
Working Families. It's a different kind of operation, but it also<br>
shows what the Federation can do to lead the way back.<br>
<br>
In this campaign we have brought together the legislative,<br>
political, and communications operations of our affiliates. We<br>
have worked out a set of messages which can be repeatedly<br>
communicated to our members to explain what the stakes are for<br>
them. Our messages have been informed by a sophisticated research<br>
program and captured in professionally-developed campaign materials<br>
that are being disseminated widely throughout the labor movement.<br>
<br>
In addition, in a number of key congressional districts, we<br>
have taken to the ground and to the air with both the AFL-CIO field<br>
staff -- almost half of whom have been deployed on this campaign --<br>
and with our largest media buy since NAFTA. <br>
<br>
We intend to continue this effort throughout the year, and<br>
with your help to keep hammering on our messages until each and<br>
every union member -- and in our targeted districts every member of<br>
the public -- understands the threat facing working people and<br>
knows who it is that is leading the fight for America's working<br>
families.&quot;<br>
<br>
As the NAFTA and Stand UP campaigns illustrate, our<br>
legislative-political efforts -- and also, I believe, our<br>
organizing efforts -- require a sophisticated communications<br>
program. Here, again, we have significantly expanded our<br>
capacities, especially for electronic communications.<br>
<br>
I am still not satisfied, however, that we have done enough in<br>
these areas. In 1993, at my urging, the AFL-CIO commissioned a<br>
full-scale audit of our communications program which resulted in a<br>
hard-hitting report with recommendations for a strategic<br>
communications program for the labor movement.<br>
<br>
We took some criticism for this effort -- especially when some<br>
of the results were leaked to the press. Holding a mirror up to<br>
one's face is seldom entirely pleasant, and in this case we learned<br>
some painful lessons about how we are perceived by a portion of the<br>
general public. But in my view, this was important to do and I am<br>
determined to move forward in implementing this strategic<br>
communications program.<br>
<br>
One element of that program is a far more systematic effort to<br>
earn media attention. The days when the press would seek us out<br>
are long gone. We need to adapt accordingly. We also need to<br>
recognize that most of the communications in the nation today take<br>
place not through national media but at the local level, through<br>
local papers, radio and TV.<br>
<br>
We also need to figure out how to make best use of the newer<br>
forms of communication -- from talk radio and cable television to<br>
the Internet and the information superhighway -- as well as how to<br>
best use paid advertising. <br>
I've talked now at probably too-great length and yet I feel<br>
that I have only begun to scratch the surface. Allow me to close<br>
with a few, more general observations.<br>
<br>
While the challenges we face are, enormous, we can take heart<br>
in the fact that we are still the largest, strongest, most vibrant<br>
labor movement in the world -- with 13 million members and an<br>
activist core second to none. We are still the strongest, most<br>
vital progressive force in the nation, seeking justice, fairness<br>
and decency for all American working families.<br>
<br>
We can also take heart in the fact that there is no shortage<br>
of promising ideas as to how to go about creating the kind of labor<br>
movement working families need. Those ideas exist not just at AFL-<br>
CIO headquarters but at every national and international union, at<br>
every local union, and at every state and local central body<br>
throughout the nation. Our challenge is to get all those ideas on<br>
the table and then decide which are most worth pursuing and how to<br>
fund them.<br>
<br>
This is not to say that the decisions we face in revitalizing<br>
our movement are easy or the path ahead clear. If that were true,<br>
the decisions would have been made long ago. <br>
To the contrary, we face complex and challenging decisions<br>
about priorities and about roles -- about how best to use the very<br>
limited resources that are allocated to the AFL-CIO and about how<br>
to maximize the contributions of the Federation in a system built<br>
upon autonomous, decentralized unions.<br>
<br>
That brings me to my final point -- a terribly important note<br>
of caution. How we go about making these decisions is every bit as<br>
significant as what we ultimately decide. The AFL-CIO is nothing<br>
more -- and nothing less -- than the sum of its parts. I said<br>
before and I say again, we are an organization dedicated to seeking<br>
consensus as a basis for action. The Federation cannot be held<br>
together if it is run by 52-48 votes or if it is run by a group of<br>
large unions acting separately. Nobody can &quot;proclaim&quot; the way<br>
forward. <br>
<br>
That need not mean -- as it sometimes has in the past -- that<br>
one union or even a small group should be able to tie the<br>
Federation's hands. Such an approach can produce inertia -- and<br>
inertia is the last thing we can afford.<br>
<br>
I believe we need to reexamine the Federation's entire<br>
structure, governance and decision-making processes so as to assure<br>
that they are open, inclusive and capable of decisive action. If,<br>
as I expect, the Executive Council elects me in August to fill the<br>
remainder of President Kirkland's term, I intend as my first act to<br>
appoint a special committee drawn from our affiliates to undertake<br>
that task.<br>
<br>
It would be a mistake, in my view, to rush to conclude that<br>
examination in a time of partisan politics. But with strong<br>
leadership I am confident we can reach agreement over how to bring<br>
about the restructuring of the Federation's governance mechanisms<br>
and make it an even more effective instrument in the service of<br>
America's working families. <br>
<br>
When all is said and done, however, it is not change in the<br>
inner workings of the AFL-CIO that is going to turn things around<br>
for the working men and women of this country or for the unions<br>
that represent them. It is the renewed dedication, the renewed<br>
energy of the men and women of this movement that will make the<br>
difference. <br>
<br>
The opportunities before us are endless. But the one sure<br>
means of squandering the possibility for renewal is to fall into<br>
factionalism. <br>
<br>
I am determined to do everything in my power not to allow that<br>
to happen. The working men and women who depend on this movement<br>
and the millions more who seek a genuine voice on the job require<br>
that we make common cause. I'm confident we can.<br>
<br>
Thank you.</p>
