<html>

<head>
<title>SP 04/11/95 Kirkland Roosevelt Institute</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>Remarks of AFL-CIO President Lane Kirkland<br>
at Franklin and Eleanor Roosevelt<br>
Institute Awards Dinner<br>
Warm Springs, Georgia<br>
April 11, 1995<br>
<br>
<br>
I appreciate the opportunity to offer a few remarks on<br>
behalf of the many millions of Americans whose lives have<br>
been shaped in some way by Franklin Roosevelt. I am proud to<br>
be in their number.<br>
<br>
When I was a kid I spent a summer at a National Youth<br>
Administration vocational training camp named for Aubrey<br>
Williams, the NYA's director.<br>
<br>
It was Franklin Roosevelt's Merchant Marine Act of 1936<br>
-- expanding the American flag fleet -- that enabled me, a<br>
small town kid from South Carolina, to go to sea and learn<br>
that trade for a living.<br>
<br>
Included in that law was a special program to train<br>
merchant ships' officers. At the age of 18, I shipped out,<br>
under that program, as a cadet aboard a freighter named,<br>
appropriately enough, &quot;Liberator.&quot;<br>
<br>
Shortly after Pearl Harbor, at the age of 20, I became<br>
a mate on vessels carrying weapons and ammunition to various<br>
war zones. Trained officers were so scarce that I was a<br>
chief mate at age 21, and got my Master's ticket for command<br>
of vessels of any tonnage, on any ocean, when I turned 24.<br>
<br>
The wartime merchant marine was where I came of age. <br>
It was where I was educated and where I first became a trade<br>
unionist.<br>
<br>
I went on to spend the rest of my career in the<br>
movement that Franklin Roosevelt nourished and promoted with<br>
the proclamation of his belief &quot;in the right of workers to<br>
join unions and to protect their unions.&quot;<br>
<br>
You can imagine what that simple, declarative statement<br>
meant at the time to millions of wage-earning Americans who<br>
were struggling for that right.<br>
<br>
Today, those who would further limit trade union rights<br>
are fond of saying that unions &quot;may have been appropriate<br>
for the 1930s, but not for today.&quot;<br>
<br>
But, in the 30s, I saw the machine guns of my state's<br>
national guard around the cotton mills where workers were<br>
trying to organize. The business community didn't like<br>
unions any better then than they do today, and the state<br>
served the business commmunity. That's how I remember it.<br>
<br>
Nevertheless, millions of courageous and steadfast<br>
working people -- encouraged by the President of the United<br>
States -- stuck their necks out for their unions, built<br>
their ladder into the middle class, and created a market<br>
that became the envy and target of the world.<br>
<br>
I would suggest that the benefits of this struggle have<br>
flowed not only to working people but to the corporate<br>
enterprises that have flourished in that market.<br>
<br>
The more fiercely the current debate rages about the<br>
appropriate role of the federal government in our society,<br>
the more clearly I remember a lot of things about our<br>
country before there was such a role -- when about all the<br>
federal government did was collect tariffs, run the post<br>
office and pay the military, rather poorly.<br>
<br>
I remember when there were county poorhouses out on the<br>
edge of town. That's where people went when they became too<br>
old or too sick to work. Then Social Security came and tore<br>
those poorhouses down -- freeing young and old alike of that<br>
specter.<br>
<br>
I remember when the rivers of my state ran brick-red<br>
from the erosion of farms and deforested uplands stripped by<br>
unregulated free enterprise. I remember when the topsoil of<br>
the Great Plains literally blew away -- turning thousands<br>
upon thousands of farm families into homeless nomads.<br>
<br>
Then came the tree-planting of the CCC and the farm<br>
programs of the New Deal. Today those rivers run black and<br>
clear and the Dust Bowl is but a distant memory. Free<br>
enterprises such as the paper, forest products and<br>
agribusiness industries shared abundantly in those<br>
government initiatives.<br>
<br>
I remember when rural homes were lit by kerosene. And<br>
then the REA electrified and humanized them, bridging the<br>
cultural gap between town and country -- and incidentally<br>
creating new markets for the appliance industry. <br>
<br>
I am proud to acknowledge that I am a child of Franklin<br>
Roosevelt's New Deal. But, then, every person alive today,<br>
regardless of age or previous condition, is an heir of the<br>
works of that great period in our nation's life.<br>
<br>
I do not and cannot forget those roots in the past. So<br>
today, if asked whether the label &quot;liberal&quot; or<br>
&quot;conservative&quot; or misanthrope fits, I can only respond that<br>
I am a New Dealer, pure and simple and unreconstructed.<br>
<br>
Thank you.</p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="/publ/publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
