<html>

<head>
<title>SP 03/29/95 Kirkland Industrial Union Department</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>Remarks of AFL-CIO President Lane Kirkland<br>
to the Industrial Union Department, AFL-CIO<br>
1995 Legislative Conference<br>
Washington, D.C.<br>
March 29, 1995<br>
<br>
<br>
President Chatak, Secretary-Treasurer diCicco, brothers<br>
and sisters:<br>
<br>
I'm delighted to be back for your annual legislative<br>
conference.<br>
<br>
This year, as you well know, the situation is different<br>
than in years past.<br>
<br>
We're in the fight of our lives right now.<br>
<br>
The extreme right wing is driving the agenda in Congress. <br>
They are guided by an ideology that is almost 100 percent<br>
contrary to everything for which this labor movement has ever<br>
stood.<br>
<br>
The would turn the Gompers doctrine upside down. They<br>
are for more jails and less schoolhouses; more arsenals and<br>
less books; more vice and less learning; more greed and less<br>
leisure; more revenge and less justice.<br>
<br>
Now, they've got the gavel in both houses of Congress. <br>
And they've targeted nearly everything in government that<br>
smacks of the Great Society or the New Deal or even Teddy<br>
Roosevelt's agenda from the turn of the century.<br>
<br>
They talk about &quot;empowerment&quot; and &quot;opportunity.&quot; But you<br>
and I know that the only power they want to enhance is that<br>
which is already held by the privileged elements of our<br>
society. <br>
<br>
Despite their rhetoric, their agenda has nothing to do<br>
with giving power to the people. Rather, it is to give the<br>
business interests of this country more power than they've had<br>
since the days just prior to the Great Depression, when a full<br>
third of our nation was ill-housed, ill-clad and ill-<br>
nourished.<br>
<br>
They're looking to undermine virtually every gain our<br>
movement has championed for working people in this century. <br>
I'm talking about decent wages, secure retirement income,<br>
safer jobs and the right to an independent voice at the<br>
workplace -- a voice that can only be asserted by a real trade<br>
union.<br>
<br>
They want to throw it all away. And they want to do it<br>
quickly before the American people realize what's happening. <br>
That's what their &quot;Contract on America&quot; is all about. But<br>
that's not the full extent of it.<br>
<br>
If this new majority in Congress gets its way, you can<br>
say good-bye to the programs that have helped working<br>
Americans create a better and more decent society out of the<br>
market jungle that once claimed our land.<br>
<br>
At a time when 10,000 Americans are killed on the job<br>
each year, they say American business is &quot;over-regulated&quot; --<br>
so they're trying to strip the Occupational Health and Safety<br>
Administration of any real power and turn it into a<br>
&quot;consultant.&quot;<br>
<br>
They want to force welfare recipients to work, but they<br>
propose nothing that would create decent jobs for the<br>
underprivileged. Instead, they're looking to slash the<br>
programs that help provide food, housing and education to the<br>
least fortunate in our society.<br>
<br>
At a time of falling wages and growing job insecurity,<br>
they seek to repeal the prevailing wage laws, ship more jobs<br>
overseas and encourage &quot;contingent&quot; employment here in this<br>
country.<br>
<br>
This country has just recorded its highest monthly trade<br>
deficit in its history. U.S. exports are dropping, not<br>
rising, while imports continue to increase.<br>
<br>
Remember NAFTA and the huge market that would be open to<br>
U.S. exporters when Mexico dropped it tariffs? Well, those<br>
barriers were put right back up with the devaluation of the<br>
peso. And you know what happened? The trade surplus we had<br>
with Mexico in December became an $863 million trade deficit<br>
in January.<br>
<br>
Just like that. So much for the rosy projections of the<br>
NAFTA lobby.<br>
<br>
They may talk about helping working middle-class<br>
families. But you can be sure that members of the new<br>
majority in Congress will do everything they can to aid and<br>
abet corporate America's flight from our shores. And they'll<br>
do it while cutting the programs that help displaced workers<br>
train for new jobs.<br>
<br>
They're aiming their budget axe at defense conversion<br>
programs, as well. As far at they're concerned, government<br>
has no place rendering assistance to the working people who<br>
helped this country win the Cold War. Those workers can just<br>
go flip burgers, for all they care. <br>
<br>
Through their balanced budget amendment, they went after<br>
the Social Security system. Social Security -- probably the<br>
best and most successful federal program ever devised. This<br>
is a program that works. It is in surplus. It will remain in<br>
surplus for many years into the future.<br>
<br>
And yet, to listen to the members of the new majority in<br>
Congress, you'd think that nothing good ever came of any<br>
government program enacted in the last 60 years.<br>
<br>
Let me tell you, I remember what it was like before we<br>
had these programs. I remember the county poorhouses, where<br>
people were sent when they became too old to work for a<br>
living.<br>
<br>
I remember when the federal government had virtually no<br>
role at all in our society -- except, perhaps, to pay the<br>
military, run the Post Office and collect tariffs.<br>
<br>
I remember when the countryside was stripped of trees by<br>
the plundering of commercial interests without the restraint<br>
of law or environmental concerns -- when the rivers ran red<br>
with the runoff and the topsoil of the Great Plains literally<br>
blew away.<br>
<br>
I remember the days before there was a minimum wage. <br>
Today, we need a higher minimum wage, in order to ensure that<br>
America's lowest paid workers are able to earn enough to<br>
provide at least the barest essentials for themselves and<br>
their families.<br>
<br>
Now we have a majority leader of the House of<br>
Representatives who hates the minimum wage, who has always<br>
hated it, and has pledged to do away with the minimum wage.<br>
<br>
I remember company unions, too. And now, our adversaries<br>
are trying to bring those back.<br>
<br>
The working men and women of this country do not want to<br>
return to that era. But that's what lies ahead if we allow<br>
these ideologues to dismantle our government and turn the<br>
country over again to the tender mercies of corporate<br>
enterprise.<br>
<br>
The immediate threat to our movement does not end at the<br>
Capital Beltway. In state capitals across the country, new<br>
conservative majorities are advancing right-to-work and other<br>
anti-union proposals.<br>
<br>
Clearly, we've got to be active at all levels of<br>
government.<br>
<br>
Brothers and sisters, we face a major challenge -- the<br>
challenge of standing up for this country and defending<br>
everything our movement has ever done to build a decent<br>
society for working people and their families.<br>
<br>
We have a great deal of work to do. If working people<br>
ever needed their trade union movement to stand up for them,<br>
that time is now.<br>
<br>
We've got the resources to win this struggle. We've got<br>
dedicated and talented leaders. We've got good people here in<br>
Washington -- legislative and political representatives at all<br>
of our AFL-CIO affiliates -- who are working day and night to<br>
stand up to this onslaught.<br>
<br>
But our greatest strength is our members. The other side<br>
may have all the money in the world, but we've got more than<br>
13 million people out there -- 13 million people who,<br>
everyday, stick their neck out for a trade union. We have a<br>
level of vigor and commitment within our ranks that is<br>
unmatched anywhere in the world.<br>
<br>
And that resource does not stop there. Think of all the<br>
family members. They don't pay dues. They aren't counted on<br>
our membership rolls. But they're out there. If they're of<br>
age, they can vote and they can contact their elected<br>
representatives. We've got to reach them.<br>
<br>
Think of the retirees. They're ready to do their part,<br>
too.<br>
<br>
So our numbers do not stop with our dues-paying members. <br>
We've got a vast army out there. And we have to educate and<br>
mobilize them as never before.<br>
<br>
But we can't do it without your participation and<br>
support. The most effective lobbying program in the world<br>
won't work unless you are out there making it work at your<br>
locals and in your communities.<br>
<br>
It means working together -- with the AFL-CIO's regional<br>
COPE directors, who now serve as our legislative field arm,<br>
and through your state federations and central labor councils. <br>
We've got to strengthen our grass roots activism, educate our<br>
members about the threat facing working Americans, get them<br>
involved, and motivate them to join labor's campaign to stand<br>
up for working families.<br>
<br>
It means working with AFL-CIO Legislative Action<br>
Committees in targeted congressional districts and engaging in<br>
other grass roots activities designed to ensure that union<br>
members understand the issues and communicate their views to<br>
their elected representatives.<br>
<br>
In the early going, we've had some outstanding successes.<br>
<br>
We helped stop Congress from enacting a balanced budget<br>
amendment that would have devastated this country's economy.<br>
<br>
And, for the time being, we have staved off congressional<br>
attempts to kill the President's executive order banning<br>
government contractors from permanently replacing their<br>
workers.<br>
<br>
We have every right to be proud of these victories. But<br>
I would remind you that our winning margins were razor-thin,<br>
and we can be sure that the assault on worker rights will<br>
accelerate in the days ahead. <br>
<br>
Looking beyond the current right wing agenda in Congress,<br>
there's another reason to build and mobilize at the grass<br>
roots.<br>
<br>
One of the great things about this country is that<br>
elections are never permanent. In a couple of years, you<br>
always get another chance.<br>
<br>
I am convinced that our ongoing legislative field efforts<br>
can and will pay off in November of 1996. If trade unionists<br>
and their family members become the best-informed voters in<br>
the country by that time, I have no doubt that they will help<br>
turn the tide in Washington and elect a Congress that really<br>
cares about working people and is committed to making life<br>
better for them.<br>
<br>
We can elect a Congress that stands up for good jobs and<br>
for decent wages and benefits.<br>
<br>
We can elect a Congress that stands up for fair trade and<br>
refuses to sell out working people to the vagaries of<br>
international trade agreements like NAFTA and GATT.<br>
<br>
We can elect a Congress that stands up for safer<br>
workplaces and gets tough on employers who kill and injure<br>
their workers.<br>
<br>
And we can elect a Congress that stands up for the idea<br>
that the best way to maintain a safe and decent society is to<br>
enhance the freedom of working people to join independent<br>
trade unions.<br>
<br>
But first we have to stand up for working families --<br>
together, every affiliated union, in solidarity.<br>
<br>
That is the immediate goal of the AFL-CIO, and I know we<br>
can count on you for your active support and participation.<br>
<br>
Thank you, and best of luck to you all.</p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="/publ/publhome.html">Public Documents Page</a></p>
