<body>
<pre>AFL-CIO Reviews the Issues                          Report No. 83
                                                       June, 1995
</pre>
<h2>TRASHING THE CPI</h2>
<h3>What Is the Consumer Price Index?</h3>
<p>The Consumer Price Index (CPI) is the nation's best known and
most widely used barometer of inflation. For most people, the
&quot;inflation rate&quot; is the percentage increase in prices
as measured by the CPI. </p>
<p>Basically CPI is constructed by taking a reading of the
&quot;market basket&quot; of consumer purchases at a particular
time period and then repricing the contents every month. </p>
<p>The basket is updated about every ten years. Periodic
revisions are needed so as to take account of population shifts,
changes in what people buy, and to eliminate other discrepancies
that may creep into the index over time. </p>
<p>The market basket in use today reflects average consumer
purchases over the years 1982-84 and went into effect January
1987. The next update is scheduled for January 1998 and will
represent average purchases for 1993-95. </p>
<p>Today's CPI is a complex and sophisticated instrument,
produced under exacting standards and tight deadlines. Every
month the Bureau of Labor Statistics collects some 80,000 price
quotations in 21,000 retail and service establishments in 85
areas around the country. An additional 40,000 landlords or
tenants and 20,000 home owners are surveyed in regard to housing
costs. </p>
<h4>Origin of CPI</h4>
<p>The CPI dates back to World War I, when it was first developed
by the Bureau of Labor Statistics for use in adjusting wartime
wages for shipyard workers. Coverage was later expanded to a
national basis and calculated back to 1913 (its official starting
point). </p>
<p>CPI-W. The original CPI survives today as the Consumer Price
Index for Urban Wage Earners and Clerical Workers (CPI-W),
covering about 32 percent of the population. </p>
<p>CPI-U. A broader index was started in January 1978 for All
Urban Consumers (CPI-U), covering about 80 percent of the
population. In addition to the traditional wage-earner/clerical
group, this index also includes retired, unemployed,
self-employed, professional and supervisory workers. CPI-U is the
index used to mark the general inflation rate. </p>
<h4>CPI and Wages </h4>
<p>CPI-W is the index generally used in collective bargaining.
Contracts often include a specific COLA (&quot;cost-of-living
adjustment&quot;) clause automatically tying wage increases to
increased prices. Or price index rises may simply be factored
into an overall package at the time of agreement. </p>
<p>Formal COLAs are popular when inflation rates are high but
interest falls off in times of low inflation, such as at present.
COLAs can become a &quot;cap&quot; on wage adjustments, and may
not even produce full recovery of living cost increases. </p>
<p>In 1994, COLA clauses were in effect for less than a quarter
of the 5.4 million wage earners covered by major collective
bargaining contracts in private industry. COLAs are rarely used
in public employment, although, as in the private sector, living
cost increases indirectly enter into wage and salary
determinations. </p>
<h4>CPI for Retirement and Disability Benefits </h4>
<p>Today the most widespread use of formal COLAs is in the
automatic adjustment of social security benefits each year.
Indexing also applies in other Federal programs for retired and
disabled workers and their dependents and survivors. </p>
<p>The largest group--social security--numbers nearly 43 million.
About 4 million people receive payments under the Federal
government's retirement and disability systems for its own
civilian and military employees. </p>
<p>Several million people get means-tested benefits. Over 6
million (including 2.5 million social security beneficiaries)
qualify for Supplementary Security Income (SSI) for aged, blind,
and disabled persons. Veterans' pensions and compensation (also
means-tested) go to about 3.4 million. </p>
<p>Legislation to index social security benefits was enacted in
1972 and became effective in 1974. Federal employee retirement
indexation had started earlier. </p>
<p>Indexing of social security benefits (with CPI-W) was designed
to produce fairness in benefit increases and to insulate the
program from political pressures. President Richard Nixon put it
this way in 1969: <quote> &quot;The way to prevent future unfairness
is to attach the benefit schedule to the cost of living...We
remove questions about future years; we do much to remove this
system from biennial politics; and we make fair treatment of
beneficiaries a matter of certainty rather than a matter of
hope.&quot; </p>
<p>The indexing system is a vital adjunct to the &quot;safety
net&quot; for American workers and their families. When working
years are over, pensioners are not usually in a position to
recover living cost increases in other ways. </p>
<p>Private industry retirement and disability systems almost
never provide inflation adjustments--and indeed count on social
security to do it. For six out of ten workers in private
industry, social security is their only pension. </p>
<h4>A Special Index for the Elderly?</h4>
<p>Past proposals to create a special CPI for the older
population have failed of enactment, but one outcome was a series
of studies by the Bureau of Labor Statistics to show what such an
index would look like. </p>
<p>The most recent study is consistent with earlier ones. It
shows that an index generated for the population age 62 and over
moves up more than either CPI-W or CPI-U. From December 1987 to
December 1993, the rise in the special index averaged .3 percent
more per year than CPI-U and .4 percent more than CPI-W. The
difference mainly reflects the larger portion of older people's
outlays that goes for out-of-pocket medical care expenses. </p>
<h4>A New Use for COLAs: Federal Income Taxes </h4>
<p>In 1985 federal income taxes were tied to the annual inflation
rate, as registered by CPI-U. Escalation applies to tax brackets,
personal exemption amounts, and standard deductions.
Additionally, the Earned Income Tax Credit (designed for the
&quot;working poor&quot;) comes under its own indexing provisions
for credit amounts. </p>
<h4>COLAs and the Federal Budget</h4>
<p>Indexation of Federal benefits and income taxes naturally
attracts the attention of would-be budget cutters. </p>
<p>Total budget outlays in 1994 came to $1.5 trillion, of which
indexed benefits accounted for about 30 percent. Individual
income taxes, all subject to indexing, produced $543 billion in
1994, or 40 percent of all budget receipts. </p>
<h4>Political Pressure on the Price Index</h4>
<p>If social security benefits are supposed to be off-limits to
politics, another approach is to change the price index so that
it will go up less. </p>
<p>The Chairman of the Federal Reserve Board, Alan Greenspan, has
frequently complained that CPI &quot;overstates inflation.&quot;
At hearings on January 10 of this year, he offered estimates of
the &quot;overstatement&quot;: namely, from .5 to 1.5 percentage
points per year. He invited Congress to select a number in this
range and reduce the inflation rate accordingly. (In later
hearings he proposed that Congress establish a special Commission
to set the adjustment each year.) </p>
<p>Illustrations of possible budget savings were provided by the
Federal Reserve staff. If, for example, the rate were reduced by
1 percentage point, the annual level of the deficit would be
lower by about $55 billion after five years, with cumulative
five-year savings of about $150 billion. </p>
<p>Chairman Greenspan urged speedy action because the effects
cumulate over time. (Each year a benefit is cut, the base is
lowered for calculating next year's adjustment.) </p>
<p>Congress could, of course, simply mandate an arbitrary cut in
the CPI rate for benefit and tax purposes. Greenspan, however,
provides a technical rationale--which makes it politically easier
to do. A mere &quot;correction&quot; in faulty measurements
absolves Congress from responsibility and mutes the objections of
those who would be injured. </p>
<p>But Greenspan may have opened up a can of worms. </p>
<p>In the first place, the technical grounds upon which his claim
rests are weak to non-existent. </p>
<p>Second, any &quot;mismeasurements&quot; in the CPI and its
component subindexes feed directly into a host of other
government statistics and private sector uses. Collective
bargaining negotiations and commercial contracts are affected.
Government numbers on national output, worker productivity, the
&quot;poverty line&quot; and trends in family income are among
those using CPI-U or its components. The whole statistical
edifice is undermined, not just the programs Greenspan wants to
target for savings to the federal budget. </p>
<h4>Is the CPI Really &quot;Overstated&quot;?</h4>
<p>The CPI is as reliable a measure of price inflation as the
&quot;state of the art&quot; permits. Research may lead to
further improvements, but no index can ever reach perfection. </p>
<p>There are both understatements and overstatements of price
change in the CPI, which largely cancel out. </p>
<p>The staff backup paper for Greenspan's claim presents a range
of .4 (not .5) to 1.5 percentage points per year. </p>
<p>At the outset, it should be noted that certain items have
already been taken into account in BLS price measurements--or
will be by the time the new market basket goes into effect. (They
involve computation glitches discovered by BLS itself.) If these
items are subtracted from the Fed totals, the Fed's overall range
shrinks to .1 at the minimum to 1.0 at the maximum. </p>
<p>The Fed estimates start at zero--with no allowance for
negative numbers to represent understatements. So the result is a
one-way upward street. </p>
<p>The maximums are estimated &quot;upper bounds&quot; on the
largest conceivable degrees of overstatement that might be
present. They are broad brush and thinly based, including
extension of small amounts of unreliable or conjectural data to
large areas of the index. </p>
<h4>The &quot;True Cost of Living&quot; Argument</h4>
<p>For the minimum, the remaining item of .1 (included as .2 for
the maximum) is the possible divergence of the CPI from a
&quot;true cost-of living index.&quot; &quot;Bias&quot; is said
to exist because the CPI uses price changes for a fixed market
basket. This does not allow for alternative lower-priced
purchases consumers may make when prices rise for particular
products, and thus keep down their living costs. A
&quot;true&quot; cost of living index would include allowance for
such substitutions. </p>
<p>While this view is accepted by many economists, there is no
way &quot;substitution bias&quot; can actually be measured for an
ongoing index--if indeed it exists at all. The effect can only be
inferred through studies of past index behavior. </p>
<p>Even the theoretical bias is erased when a new market basket
is put into place (until presumably it starts to build up again.)
Consumer price indexes throughout the world use a &quot;fixed
market basket&quot; in their calculations of price change. </p>
<p>What degree of satisfaction is lost for consumers who trade
down from steak to hamburger? Is the purchase of a used car
really as satisfactory as a new car when new car sticker prices
jump? </p>
<p>In any case many consumers at the lowest income levels really
don't have much room to &quot;trade down.&quot; They would
include many recipients of such Federal benefits as social
security, SSI, and veterans pensions. </p>
<h4>Quality Adjustment. </h4>
<p>&quot;Overstatement&quot; is said to occur because of failure
to make enough allowance for improvement in the quality of
products on the market. The Fed counts this as .3 for the
maximum. </p>
<p>Currently, BLS has several different ways of handling quality
change, although some items present especially difficult problems
to which answers are not really known. </p>
<p>The Fed authors rely on a single study for &quot;consumer
durables&quot; suggesting overstatement by as much as 1.5 points
per year. The 1.5 figure is then extended to goods covering
nearly a quarter of the index--household appliances, lawn
equipment and power tools, clothing, automobiles (both new and
used), airline fares, medical care, and entertainment
commodities. </p>
<p>Totally ignored are the quality adjustments BLS already makes
for such important products as automobiles and clothing. New car
prices, for example, would have come out 80 percent higher over
the 1967-94 period without BLS changes. Particularly since no
allowance is made for understatements, the Fed's .3 maximum
carries no credibility. </p>
<h4>New Products</h4>
<p>There are many problems with accounting for new products in
the index, such as the definition of &quot;new,&quot; and timing
of introduction into the index. </p>
<p>In the absence of actual data, the Fed authors constructed an
&quot;upper bound&quot; estimate of .5 by making what they admit
are &quot;some rather extreme assumptions&quot; for household
appliances, lawn and power tools, and drugs. It is simply assumed
that the prices of these items decline at the rate of 20 percent
per year! </p>
<p>This estimate boils down to conjecture rather than a serious
number. </p>
<p>New goods are not ignored in present BLS procedures--and
improvements are scheduled for the upcoming general index
revision. </p>
<h4>Conclusion</h4>
<p>The Consumer Price Index is an enormously important statistic
--one of the linchpins of our entire system of federal
statistics. It is of crucial importance that its computation be
free of political pressures. </p>
<p>While the AFL-CIO and its predecessor unions have not always
agreed with BLS technical determinations, labor has supported the
function of the Bureau as an independent source of expertise and
authority on price and labor statistics. The BLS technical work
should not be overridden either by direct Congressional fiat or
by any type of special Commission. </p>
<p>The claim by Chairman Greenspan of the Federal Reserve Board
CPI is &quot;overstated&quot; by .5 to 1.5 percentage points per
year does not hold water. It is just as likely that CPI is
understating inflation as overstating it. </p>
<p>The higher rate of inflation for the population age 62 and
over makes rate cuts for Federal benefit programs particularly
unjustified. </p>
<p>The attack on the CPI is clearly an effort to produce a
politically easy way to create savings for the Federal budget.
without regard to other consequences. It should be firmly
rejected in favor of continued work by the Bureau of Labor
Statistics to produce the most accurate and solidly based numbers
possible. </p>
<p>Prepared by Anne Draper </p>
