<html>
<head>
<title></title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body>
<p>Who wouldn't prefer a tax so simple that you could fill out
your return on a postcard, and so fair that every loophole on the
books today would be closed? These are just two of many claims
about the flat tax made by its advocates. In reality, the flat
tax would be neither simple nor fair. It would create a double
standard in which workers&thorn; hard-earned wages and salaries
are taxed, while the interest, dividends and capital gains
received primarily by the wealthy are not taxed directly at all.
The flat tax would be a bad deal for everyone making less than
$200,000 per year. </p>
<p>According to Treasury Department estimates, a &quot;revenue
neutral&quot; flat tax (one which neither gains nor loses
revenues compared with the current personal and corporate income
tax) would result in a 9% increase in Federal income taxes for
taxpayers with incomes between $30,000 and $75,000 per year.
Taxpayers with incomes above $200,000, on the other hand, would
enjoy a whopping 26% income tax cut. </p>
<h4>How Would It Work?</h4>
<p>While there are many variations of the flat tax, most or all
are traceable to a book first published in 1983 by conservative
economists Robert Hall and Alvin Rabushka, Low Tax, Simple Tax,
Flat Tax. Embraced by politicians ranging across the political
spectrum from Representative Richard Armey (R-TX) to Senator
Arlen Specter (R-PA) and ex-Governor Jerry Brown (D-CA), in 1995
the flat tax has emerged as the leading Republican contender to
replace the current federal income tax, both personal and
corporate. </p>
<p>While details differ between proposals, most flat tax plans
embody the following major features: * All income that is subject
to tax would be taxed at a single rate. (Hall and Rabushka
proposed a 19% rate; Rep. Armey has called for 17%.) * There is a
business tax and a personal tax. The personal tax would be levied
only on wages, salaries and pensions. There would be a sizeable
personal allowance, but no or very few deductions. (Sen. Specter
would allow deductions for mortgage interest on debt up to
$100,000 for owner-occupied homes, and for charitable
contributions up to $2,500; Rep. Armey, following Hall-Rabushka,
would not allow any personal deductions.) * The personal tax
return would be simple to fill out. For most people, the tax form
would be no bigger than a post card. Under Rep. Armey&thorn;s
version, income tax withholding would be abolished. Instead,
taxpayers would be responsible for remitting their taxes by check
to the Internal Revenue Service (IRS) once a month. * The
business tax would apply to all business receipts, less wages,
salaries and pension contributions paid, and less purchases of
materials, supplies and services from other businesses.
Expenditures for fixed assets (buildings and equipment) would
also be fully deductible. Interest payments would not be
deductible; nor would employer payments for non-pension
job-related benefits (such as medical insurance). </p>
<h4>What's Wrong With the Flat Tax?</h4>
<p>Despite its surface appeal, and despite all of the problems
and unfairness of the present tax system, the flat tax would be a
very bad deal for working people. Citizens for Tax Justice
estimate that the flat tax would increase the annual taxes of
those making $50,000-$75,000 per year by an average of $2,000.
Those with incomes above $200,000 per year would enjoy an annual
tax cut averaging more than $50,000! </p>
<p>The flat tax would therefore result in a tremendous increase
in unfairness of a tax system which is already far from fair.
This increase in unfairness stems from three major causes. First,
under the flat tax, recipients of non-wage income would no longer
be taxed directly on the interest, dividends, capital gains and
other non-wage income that they receive. Second, the flat tax
with its single rate would take a smaller bite out of high
incomes than does today&thorn;s moderately progressive personal
income tax. Third, a considerable part of the business portion of
the flat tax would be passed on to consumers. This portion of the
flat tax would be highly regressive, hitting those with low
incomes the hardest. </p>
<h4>Non-Wage Income Not Taxed</h4>
<p>One of the greatest inequities to working people resulting
from the flat tax stems from the fact that non-wage income, such
as interest payments, stock dividends, and capital gains on the
sale of real estate or financial assets such as stocks or bonds,
would no longer be directly taxed. </p>
<p>How much of a shift in tax burdens from upper income to lower
and middle income taxpayers would this represent? A lot.
Taxpayers with incomes of between $30,000 and $75,000 per year
derive 83% of their incomes from wages and salaries, and only 6%
from dividends, interest and capital gains. The richest
taxpayers, by contrast, with incomes of $200,000 per year and up,
receive a much smaller 49% of their incomes in the form of wages
and salaries, but derive 25% from dividends, interest and capital
gains. Under the flat tax, their tax bill for these billions of
dollars in non-wage income would be zero. </p>
<h4>Loss of Progressivity</h4>
<p>A key principle of tax fairness is that taxes ought to be
based on ability to pay. This means that people with higher
incomes should pay a higher percentage of their incomes in taxes
than people with lower incomes. A tax system which embodies this
key principle of fairness is said to be
&thorn;progressive.&thorn; The current federal income tax, which
starts out with a low tax rate on those with lower incomes, with
higher tax rates applying to those with higher incomes, is an
example of a progressive tax. </p>
<p>Shifting to the flat tax would result in a major loss of
progressivity from the tax code. Because of the large personal
exemption, the flat tax would be slightly progressive, but far
less so than today&thorn;s federal income tax. Today&thorn;s top
tax rate of 39.6%, which applies to taxable incomes in execess of
$250,000, would be replaced in the Hall-Rabushka flat tax by a
uniform 19% tax rate. For upper income taxpayers, this would
represent a huge tax cut. For revenues to remain unchanged, taxes
would have to be higher&thorn;and would be higher on everyone
else. </p>
<p>Though they deny it today, in their original 1983 book Hall
and Rabushka were candid enough to admit that the flat tax
&quot;will be a tremendous boon to the economic elite.&quot; They
also conceded: &quot;Now for some bad news...it is an obvious
mathematical law that lower taxes on the successful will have to
be made up by higher taxes on average people.&quot; (From Hall
and Rabushka, Low Tax, Simple Tax, Flat Tax, 1983, p.58 and
p.67.) </p>
<h4>Regressive Business Tax</h4>
<p>A flat &quot;business tax&quot; would apply to all business
receipts, less the offsetting deductions described earlier.
Unlike today&thorn;s corporate income tax which applies to
corporate profits, the business tax portion of the flat tax would
more closely resemble the &quot;value added taxes&quot; (VATs)
which are common in other countries. Much of today's corporate
income tax is generally thought to be shifted to, and therefore
paid by, the owners of the corporation (e.g., wealthy individuals
and other stockholders). Value added taxes, by contrast, are a
cost to all firms and are generally thought to be shifted, in
large measure, to consumers who purchase a firm&thorn;s products
or services. They are therefore borne disproportionately by lower
income people, since they spend a greater proportion of their
incomes than higher income people. It is probable that a
disproportionate share of the business tax portion of the flat
tax would likewise be borne by taxpayers of low and moderate
means. </p>
<h4>Huge Revenue Loss</h4>
<p>Proponents of the flat tax say their intention is to offer a
proposal which is &quot;revenue neutral.&quot; In other words,
the flat tax is not supposed to increase or decrease revenues
compared with the current individual and corporate income tax.
Treasury Department analysts, however, find that the flat tax
would result in a huge revenue shortfall, thereby causing an even
bigger budget deficit than we have today, or requiring even
deeper cuts in federal spending than the massive cuts already
under consideration. Alternatively, in order to achieve revenue
neutrality, the &quot;uniform tax rate&quot; would have to be
considerably higher than the rate proposed by flat tax advocates
to date. In the case of Rep. Armey&thorn;s plan, for example, the
Treasury Department estimates that his proposed 17% tax rate
would result in a $186 billion revenue shortfall. The tax rate
would have to be increased to 23% in order to avoid a revenue
shortfall. </p>
<h4>Flat Tax Not Even Simple</h4>
<p>Even the claim that the flat tax would be far simpler than
today&thorn;s income tax system does not stand up under close
scrutiny. Nearly 20 million taxpayers use the Form 1040-EZ. For
these taxpayers, filing their income tax is no more complicated
than completing the famous flat tax postcard-size tax return. </p>
<p>For other taxpayers, the flat tax return would indeed be
simpler than todays Form 1040, but at a huge cost. Apart from
Sen. Specter&thorn;s version which would retain deductions for
mortgage interest and charitable contributions, no deductions
whatsoever would be permitted on the flat tax return. This means,
for example, that someone with a serious illness and inadequate
medical insurance would have no tax deductions for their medical
expenses, no matter how large they were. This may be simpler than
today's income tax, but it certainly is not fairer. </p>
<p>The business side of the flat tax, by contrast, is neither
simple nor fair. In order to prevent widespread fraud and abuse,
record keeping requirements, monitoring and enforcement would
actually have to be beefed up compared with today&thorn;s levels.
This is partly because the business side of the flat tax would
create many new possibilities for abusive tax shelters. Even
defining revenues and deductions for flat tax purposes would be
enormously complicated. </p>
<h4>Job-Related Benefits Not Deductible</h4>
<p>One thing that would not be deductible on the business side of
the flat tax is employer payments for employee benefits, other
than pension plan contributions. This means, for example, that
employer payments for employees&thorn; medical insurance premiums
would no longer be deductible. At a time when national health
insurance still has not been enacted and is not even any longer
on the horizon, the flat tax would therefore undermine and erode
the job-related medical insurance coverage that millions of
workers and their families depend on. Employer payments for other
job-related benefits, including education and training, life
insurance and child care, to name a few, would not be deductible,
either. </p>
<h4>AFL-CIO Wants Real Tax Reform</h4>
<p>Despite its surface appeal and notwithstanding the misleading
claims of its supporters, the flat tax would be a lousy deal for
working Americans. The current tax system has serious problems,
but the problems would be made worse by the flat tax. Real tax
reform would require taxing capital gains at the same rate as
wages, adding more progressivity to the tax rate structure, and
requiring corporations to pay a fairer share of the federal
income tax. </p>
<p>Current tax provisions which encourage corporations to export
jobs, or to destroy them through excessive, unproductive mergers
and aquisitions, should be ended. Transfer pricing abuses which
permit huge multinational corporations to avoid billions of
dollars in tax obligations should be stopped. </p>
<p>These are among the key ingredients of real tax reform, not a
flat tax system under which the richest and most privileged
Americans would get a huge tax cut and everyone else would pay
more. Prepared by Sheldon Friedman </p>
<p>AFL-CIO Economic Research Department </p>
<p>For additional copies write to:<br>
AFL-CIO Publications and Materials<br>
Office 815 Sixteenth Street, N.W.<br>
Washington, D.C. 20006</p>
