<p>Slash &amp; Burn </p>
<h3>1996 Republican Budget Resolution</h3>
<pre>AFL-CIO Economic Research
May 1995
</pre>
<hr>
<p><br>
<strong>SLASH AND BURN --</strong><br>
<strong>1996 REPUBLICAN BUDGET RESOLUTION</strong> <br>
<a href="#1">Wealthy Winners, Middle Class Losers</a><br>
<a href="#2">No Budget Fairness</a><br>
<a href="#3">Cuts vs. Unmet Needs</a><br>
<a href="#4">Balanced Budget--A Drag on the Economy</a><br>
<a href="#5">Tax Cuts For Wealthy and Profitable Corporations</a><br>
<a href="#6">Unfair Tax Cut for Capital Gains</a><br>
<a href="#7">Davis-Bacon, Service Contract Protections to be Killed</a><br>
<a href="#8">Medicare to be Cut 25 Percent by 2002</a><br>
<a href="#9">Social Security to be Cut Through CPI Flim-Flam</a><br>
<a href="#10">Pro-People Programs to be Cut or Killed</a><br>
<a href="#11">Military Spending</a><br>
A Tale Of Two Cities<br>
<a href="#13">What's Magic About 2002? Or a Zero Deficit?</a><br>
Alternatives<br>
<a href="#A">Program Cuts Proposed by the House Budget Act</a> (Appendix A)<br>
<a href="#B">Federal Regulations Targeted by the Budget Resolution</a> (Appendix B)<br>
The Budget Process (Appendix C) . . . . . .. . . . . . . . . Inside Back Cover </p>
<p><strong>CHARTS AND TABLES</strong> <br>
Unequal Impacts: How Tax And Spending Cuts Would Affect Different Income Groups<br>
Well-Off Benefit From Tax Cuts: Republican Proposed Tax Cuts By Income Class<br>
Nondefense Discretionary Spending<br>
Nondefense Discretionary Spending, Cuts From Current Services In Reconciliation Bills</p>
<hr>
<p><br>
Slash &amp; Burn </p>
<p>1996 Republican Budget Resolution </p>
<p><a name="1"><strong>WEALTHY WINNERS,</strong><br>
<strong>MIDDLE CLASS LOSERS</strong></a> </p>
<p>Republican &quot;slash-and-burn&quot; budget policies threaten destruction of pro-people programs that help 
workers and their families. </p>
<p>The 1996 budget resolution of the Republican-dominated United States Congress will kill or 
drastically cut basic long-established, labor-supported programs. </p>
<p>Losers in the budget battles include children and elderly, middle class and moderate income 
families, college students and pre-school Head Start children, adult workers with jobs and workers 
without jobs, elderly victims of deep cuts in Medicare, Social Security, and Medicaid, and the adult 
children of these elderly victims of budget-cutting. </p>
<p>Winners in the budget battles include big business and high income individuals who have promises 
of Republican tax cuts. </p>
<p>House and Senate budget resolutions have proposed deep and painful spending cuts to balance the 
budget by the year 2002. These proposals have passed the respective houses and differences will 
be resolved and bills will be enacted later this year for reconciliation and appropriations to 
implement the budget. The Senate has proposed spending cuts of $961 billion over seven years, 
the House $1.4 trillion. </p>
<p>These cuts range across the entire federal budget. Davis-Bacon and Service Contract Act 
protections would be eliminated. Big cuts would be made in Medicare, Medicaid, and lesser cuts in 
Social Security. Federal pensions would be lowered and the contributions of federal employees 
raised. </p>
<p>Unemployment compensation for jobless workers, pensions for civilian and military retirees, 
veterans benefits and programs for roads, bridges, highways and housing will be cut. Mass transit, 
Amtrak and maintenance support would be slashed. The Federal Aviation Administration would be 
privatized in the Senate bill. </p>
<p>Specific training programs would be eliminated and a general block grant to the states would be 
substituted, while overall funds would be slashed by 40 percent. </p>
<p>An appendix to this report highlights some of the program cuts and terminations under the budget 
resolution in areas of the budget ranging from education and training to the environment, worker 
safety and more. Another appendix lists a number of federal regulatory protections of prevailing 
wages, worker safety, health and other areas of social concern that are on the Republican hit list. 
An appendix also shows the unequal impact on income groups of the various spending and tax cuts. </p>
<p><a name="2"><strong>NO BUDGET FAIRNESS</strong></a> </p>
<p>The tax and spending changes proposed by the budget reconciliation bills would worsen the 
distribution of incomes in this country. The combined effect of the tax and spending cuts would be 
to shave 7 percent from the after-tax income of families making less than $30,000 in the year 2002, 
according to a Washington Post compilation of the House resolution included in this report. For a 
family earning $30,000, this loss would amount to $2,100. </p>
<p>Families in the $30,000 to $75,000 range would lose almost 2 percent of income, from $600 to 
$1,500 on average. </p>
<p>The Washington Post compilation shows, for example, that about 85 percent of the cut in Social 
Security would hit middle class families below $75,000. About half of the cut in student loans 
would affect families with incomes below $30,000, which include about 40 percent of U.S. 
families. Eighty-five percent of the $3.2 billion in cuts in job training would affect families with 
incomes below $30,000. </p>
<p>On the other hand, two-thirds of the $90 billion in tax cuts would go to the 22 percent of families 
with incomes above $75,000. Less than 5 percent of the tax cuts would benefit the 40 percent of 
U.S. families with incomes below $30,000. </p>
<p>The Senate does not contain tax cuts, but promises to use a $170 billion saving from a balanced 
budget for an unspecified tax cut. </p>
<p><a name="3"><strong>CUTS VERSUS UNMET NEEDS</strong></a> </p>
<p>While the Capitol Hill rhetoric revolves around cutting spending, ironically there is a growing 
backlog of unmet needs. A need to repair the nation's physical infrastructure. Significant 
shortcomings in education in inner cities. College students need support and aid to prepare for jobs. 
Workers need training so that American firms can compete overseas. </p>
<p>This year's annual budget process has become the focus of some basic questions. Is balancing the 
budget in the way being considered at this time the right thing to do? Is it fair and wise to enact tax 
cuts that go mainly to the wealthy and to profitable businesses, while asking citizens to do without 
essential government services? What is the human price to be paid? Can federal spending and taxes 
be brought into balance in any other way? Should balancing the budget be considered to the 
exclusion of tax fairness and full-employment? Should the nation take a meat ax to essential 
programs and protections and government activities? Is it fair to scapegoat federal workers and the 
federal establishment? </p>
<hr>
<hr>
<hr>
<p>A balanced budget amendment to the Constitution having failed enactment earlier this year, the 
congressional budget process has become the forum for tax and spending changes and deficit 
reduction. This is so even though the possibility of balancing the budget by the year 2002 is 
problematical and may even be undesirable. </p>
<p><a name="4"><strong>BALANCED BUDGET:</strong> <strong>A DRAG ON THE ECONOMY</strong></a> </p>
<p>Why so? Balancing the budget through massive spending cuts will slow the economy and contribute 
to unemployment and may even push the U.S. economy into recession. Big budget cuts planned by 
Republican budgeteers will further weaken an economy which is already slowing down in 1995 
because of the interest rate hikes engineered by the Federal Reserve over the last year. </p>
<p>The WEFA forecasting group, for example, recently predicted that the balanced budget plan would 
result in an unemployment rate more than 2 percentage points higher in 2002 than under current 
spending policies and that the economy would slow by an average of 0.3 percentage points a year 
between now and 2002. </p>
<p>To force strict and mindless adherence to a balanced budget regime takes out of the hands of 
policy makers the ability to counter the effects of recession. For example, in past downturns, 
Congress has been able to enact countercyclical measures to put people to work and to increase 
their incomes to get the economy moving again. A balanced budget wouldn't allow extra spending 
and would undermine the economy's so-called automatic stabilizers which automatically increase 
federal spending on such things as unemployment aid to jobless workers, food stamps and welfare 
when the economy turns down. </p>
<p>The budget resolution is the framework within which the various authorizing and appropriations 
committees must work in setting tax and spending policies. </p>
<p>The budget bill sets overall limits on spending. It requires the various committees of the Congress to 
stick within these limits. The budget assumes suggested program levels and cuts that could be 
adopted by the various appropriations committees in order to meet their mandated targets. The 
committees are free to adopt the recommendations on specific programs or not, but they must 
work within the mandated totals assigned them. If, for example, an appropriations committee fails 
to enact a program cut assumed by the budget committee and does not make another cut to make 
up the difference and the total of the committee bill exceeds the budget resolution target, an 
individual member can stop the bill on the House floor on a point of order. A reconciliation bill will 
be drawn up to make reductions in entitlement programs such as Medicare, Medicaid and veterans 
programs. Authorizing committees will need to produce policy changes to achieve the savings 
outlined in the budget resolution. </p>
<p>The Budget Process chart from the May 13 Congressional Quarterly is included in this report. It 
traces the path of the budget through the year up until final enactment in the fall when the 
implementing legislation and reconciliation bills are made final and submitted for the President's 
signature. </p>
<p><a name="5"><strong>TAX CUTS FOR WEALTHY AND PROFITABLE CORPORATIONS</strong></a> </p>
<p>The House budget plan includes $340 billion in tax cuts passed earlier in the year. Among other 
things, the tax plan would cut capital gains taxes and hike depreciation deductions as well as reduce 
corporate tax rates. The plan also includes a $500 tax credit for children. </p>
<p>The tax cuts aren't fair. The majority of those benefits go to corporations and people earning more 
than $100,000. According to the U.S. Treasury Department, people earning $350,000 a year or 
more could get a $20,000-a-year tax break while working people would be offered minor benefits 
in comparison. Meanwhile, middle class people would find benefits such as Medicare, student 
loans and training assistance, veterans benefits and retirement cut back. </p>
<p>As an example, a family might find that while it could claim a small tax credit for a child, several 
thousands of dollars would be added to the cost of another child's college education as the 
in-school interest subsidy is taken away from college students (as in the House bill). A student who 
borrows the maximum each year for four years of college now owes $17,100 when he or she starts 
to pay back the loan. Under the Republican proposal, that would go up to $20,500, and the 
monthly repayment amount would rise from $205 to $246. </p>
<p>Suppose the student spends six more years getting a doctorate in engineering. His or her loans for 
undergraduate and graduate studies would total $68,100 now, but a staggering $101,150 under the 
Republican proposal. </p>
<p><a name="6"><strong>UNFAIR TAX CUT FOR CAPITAL GAINS</strong></a> </p>
<p>The tax cuts for capital gains are the least justified and least fair to working people. </p>
<p>The income from capital gains is already taxed on highly preferential terms. The 1993 tax law 
changes which increased the top tax rate to 39.6 percent on amounts of taxable income in excess 
of $250,000 kept the top tax rate on capital gains at 28 percent, a full 11.6 percent lower. To 
make matters worse, last year a brand new tax preference was created which lowered the 
maximum tax rate on capital gains to 14 percent for certain new investments and certain newly 
issued stock. </p>
<p>The House tax bill further reduces taxes on capital gains by providing a 50 percent exclusion and 
indexing. This would make a bad situation dramatically worse. Tax preferences accorded income 
from capital gains result in taxing the wages and salaries of working people at a higher rate than the 
profits made by the wealthy on their sales of stocks, bonds, real estate and other property. It is a 
tax preference not available to most working men and women who pay the lion's share of taxes and 
who must meet their income tax obligations every payday. </p>
<p>The fact that 93 percent of all tax returns report zero income from capital gains underscores how 
skewed in favor of the rich this tax preference is. More than two thirds of all the benefits from 
capital gains tax preferences accrue to taxpayers with incomes in excess of $200,000 per year. </p>
<p>Cutting capital gains taxes will also stimulate the tax shelter industry, which is based heavily on 
schemes to convert ordinary income into preferentially taxed capital gains. The huge 50 percent 
exclusion, plus indexing, would mean almost two thirds of capital gains avoids taxation. This will 
prove to be an irresistible lure to these wasteful, revenue-losing and highly inequitable tax shelter 
activities. </p>
<p>The Senate denies Earned Income Tax Credits to undocumented workers and maintains indexing 
of the credit, but limits prospective increases. </p>
<p>Additional depreciation tax breaks for corporations via neutral cost recovery are unjustified. U.S. 
corporations are already taxed more lightly than their competitors in such highly successful industrial 
nations as Germany and Japan. Corporations have also shouldered a smaller proportion of the 
federal income tax burden in each successive decade since the 1950s. Corporate income taxes 
accounted for only 9 percent of federal revenues in 1993, down from 16 percent in 1973 and 31 
percent in 1953. Against this backdrop, there is no justification for further deep cuts in the form of 
a &quot;neutral cost recovery&quot; depreciation scheme that will cost $120 billion in lost revenues over the 
next ten years, according to Treasury Department estimates. </p>
<p><a name="7"><strong>DAVIS-BACON, SERVICE CONTRACT PROTECTIONS TO BE KILLED</strong></a> </p>
<p>The Davis-Bacon and Service Contract Acts are elimination targets of the Republican 
slash-and-burn attack on the budget and federal regulations. Republican hard-liners have vowed to 
do away with these protections, which assure that federal funds are not used to undercut prevailing 
wages. Congressional budgeteers estimate that doing away with these essential labor protections 
would result in $1.5 billion in annual budget savings. If these protections are kept, however, there 
would have to be cuts to make up these amounts in other areas of the budget. </p>
<p>The Davis-Bacon Act covers federally funded construction. The Service Contract Act is a 
prevailing- wage statute for workers providing cleaning, clerical and other services to the federal 
government. The purpose of these Acts is to ensure that competitors for federal government 
contracts compete on their management ability and quality rather than cutting the wages and 
working conditions of their employees. </p>
<hr>
<hr>
<hr>
<p><a name="8"><strong>MEDICARE TO BE CUT</strong> <strong>25 PERCENT BY 2002</strong></a> </p>
<p>The budget resolutions call for deep cuts in entitlements, especially Medicare. The Senate, for 
example, cuts Medicare by $256 billion, Medicaid $175 billion and other mandatory programs by 
$209 billion. Both proposals achieve cuts by reducing the rate of growth of the programs. 
However, these reductions in growth will actually result in significant reductions from the level of 
services under current law. The House bill cuts Medicare by $282 billion over seven years, 
Medicaid by $187 billion and other programs by $219. </p>
<p>Medicare cuts proposed in the Senate and House assume savings through greater efficiency, but 
there are likely to be higher costs on providers and beneficiaries. The Medicare program will be 25 
percent smaller in 2002 than it would be if the government honored its commitments under current 
law, according to a Joint Economic Committee (JEC) minority report. </p>
<p>Since 1965 Medicare has provided health care for people aged 65 and over. It is a nationwide 
health insurance program for the aged and certain disabled persons, consisting of hospital insurance 
and supplement medical insurance. There are over 31 million aged and 3.5 million disabled who 
have protection under part A alone. It is a middle class program where roughly 60 percent of the 
benefits go to the 77 percent of families with incomes below $75,000. But most of all it is an 
insurance program that people have paid into over their working years with the promise that they 
will receive medical coverage when disabled or retired. </p>
<p>Republicans have argued that cuts in Medicare are necessary to save the program, from being 
insolvent after the turn of the century. However, the proposed savings are $116 billion greater than 
estimates of what is needed by 2002 to rescue Medicare's Part A hospital insurance trust fund. </p>
<p>Minority Leader Gephardt said the House plan could cost retired people $1,300 in increased 
Medicare fees and reduced Social Security benefits by the time the budget is balanced in the year 
2002. </p>
<p>Senate Republican leaders want to appoint a commission to figure out how to hold down costs. 
Medicare reform will be addressed as a distinct legislative initiative in September although the 
figures will be included in the budget resolution. </p>
<p>Medicaid bears substantial cutbacks as the program is transformed into a block grant to the States. 
The proposed cuts would reduce the program by 30 percent compared to current law by 2002, 
according to the JEC report. Other benefit programs will be cut, including agriculture subsidies, 
welfare, student loans, veterans benefits and more. </p>
<p>Medicaid is a federal-state matching entitlement program providing medical assistance for 
low-income persons who are aged, blind, disabled, members of families with dependent children 
and certain other pregnant women and children. </p>
<p>A Senate proposal would change the basis for federal retiree pensions from the average of the top 
three highest salaries to the five highest annual salaries. The House has a similar provision for 
Foreign Service. </p>
<p>Both provisions increase the payment by federal workers. </p>
<p><a name="9"><strong>SOCIAL SECURITY TO BE CUT</strong> <strong>THROUGH CPI FLIM-FLAM</strong></a> </p>
<p>Social Security is the only pension for 6 out of 10 workers in private industry. All but the wealthiest 
retirees depend less on private pensions, more on Social Security. Between 70 and 80 percent of 
total income is from Social Security for retirees in the bottom 40 percent of incomes. </p>
<p>The budget plan supposedly excludes Social Security, Defense and interest on the debt. However, 
changes in the way cost of living adjustments are figured will reduce Social Security payments. The 
House, for example, assumes a Consumer Price Index flim-flam adjustment to cut by 0.6 of a 
percentage point beginning in 1999, which would reduce increases in Social Security benefits tied 
to the index and increase individual taxes. </p>
<p>The proposal would reduce the basic amount on which future adjustments are calculated, and the 
cumulative effect would be a total loss of several hundred dollars a year for the average Social 
Security beneficiary. </p>
<p>By 2002, the 0.6 CPI cut reduces Social Security payments by $10 billion or $240 per beneficiary, 
according to the JEC. The Senate assumes a CPI reduction of 0.2 percentage points, beginning in 
1999. </p>
<p>The cuts in Social Security would especially hurt low and middle income families. For example, 
only about 16 percent of the benefits under Social Security go to these with incomes above 
$75,000. Forty-two percent goes to these with incomes below $30,000. </p>
<p><a name="10"><strong>PRO-PEOPLE PROGRAMS</strong> <strong>TO BE CUT OR KILLED</strong></a> </p>
<p>The budget resolutions cut a huge swath out of domestic programs, covering everything from 
education and training, to spending on highways, and other infrastructure, housing, the environment, 
energy and other areas. </p>
<p>The budget proposals continue the Republican assault on the federal government and the 
scapegoating of federal workers. The House plans the elimination of the Departments of 
Commerce, Education and Energy. The Senate eliminates Commerce. </p>
<p>Overall domestic programs would be cut by about $190 billion over seven years based on the 
1995 freeze funding base used by the Republicans. Actually the real figure is $450 billion by 
traditional budget calculation based on current services. Current services is an estimate of the 
spending needed in future years to continue programs at their current levels, reflecting costs of 
continuing these programs at their spending levels without any policy changes. The House and 
Senate bills spend $1.77 trillion, roughly 20 percent less than current services, for domestic 
discretionary programs over seven years. </p>
<p>The Republicans compare their budgets to the 1995 freeze level, rather than to current services. 
Thus, their $190 billion 7-year reduction in domestic discretionary spending seriously understates 
the actual drop in programs from levels which would be necessary to maintain current services. </p>
<p>Domestic program cuts begin taking effect in 1996, with an overall reduction in the 5-6 percent 
range. In the year 2002, domestic programs would be roughly 30 percent below the current 
services level. </p>
<p>In order to make room for some program increases, many programs will be cut much more than 
the average amount. In the Justice area of the budget, the Senate proposes an increase of $27 
billion over seven years. While the Senate budget, for example, provides an additional $2.7 billion 
in funding for the FBI, drug enforcement and immigration and naturalization, there is a 65 percent 
reduction in funding for the Legal Services Corporation. </p>
<p>Hundreds of programs, agencies and commissions are targeted in the House and Senate bills. The 
House budget would eliminate a number of agencies, including the Corporation for Public 
Broadcasting and the Economic Development Administration. The Senate would terminate the 
Interstate Commerce Commission, as well as phase out operating subsidies for Amtrak. The House 
would terminate 283 federal programs; the Senate 100 programs. </p>
<p>The National Service Initiative would be dropped by the Senate. The House bill includes a 
20-percent cut in Mine Safety and Health Agency funds. MSHA would be combined with OSHA 
and OSHA would be cut by 20 percent. </p>
<p>The Community Development Block Grant (CDBG) program supports a wide range of activities in 
cities across the country, including economic development, job creation, public facilities, public 
services and housing. The program would be cut by half beginning in fiscal 1996 in the Senate bill, 
20 percent in the House bill. </p>
<p>An attached appendix to this report gives more details of program cuts proposed by the budget 
resolutions for selected programs in employment and training, education, safety and health, housing, 
infrastructure and the environment, energy, transportation, economic development, federal workers, 
maritime and other areas. </p>
<p><a name="11"><strong>MILITARY SPENDING </strong></a></p>
<p>Military spending in the budget is affected by the proposals. There are significant real cuts from the 
current services level, reflecting in part the reduced international threats in the post Cold War era. </p>
<p>Both Houses and Senate resolutions assume that production of major weapons systems such as the 
Seawolf submarine would be continued. </p>
<p>The House would spend about $68 billion more than the Administration and the Senate propose. 
All three military budgets contain significant cumulative declines in inflation adjusted terms of from 
12 to 15 percent by 2001, according to the Defense Budget Project estimates. </p>
<hr>
<hr>
<hr>
<hr>
<p><a name="13"><strong>WHAT'S MAGIC ABOUT 2002? OR A ZERO DEFICIT ?</strong></a> </p>
<p>The federal budget is not out of control. The congress enacted a budget act in 1993 which reduced 
the deficit by $500 billion over five years. The budget deficit is declining as a percent of the Gross 
Domestic Product, making it more manageable in future years, without passage of a devastating 
balanced budget measure. </p>
<p>The congressional Black Caucus has offered a balanced budget which would cut spending by half 
the amount proposed by the House and Senate Republicans. The proposal would raise corporate 
taxes and taxes on the wealthy and not out Medicare, Medicaid or Welfare. See the box. </p>
<p>The deficit has declined from the 4.6-4.8 percent range of Gross Domestic Product in the 
mid-1980s to 2.8 percent in 1994. The Congressional Budget Office in January projected that 
annual deficits would rise to 3 percent only in the year 2000, assuming that the economy operates 
at its potential. Dramatically cutting spending under a balanced budget law would threaten that 
timeline. Further, the fact that the deficit is under control for the foreseeable future makes it possible 
to deal with emerging problems, such as the financial pressures of Medicare and the eventual need 
to put Social Security on a better long-term basis. </p>
<p>A more modest goal such as keeping the deficit below the level of growth of the economy is more 
realistic and desirable. It would result in the decline in the deficit as a percent of Gross Domestic 
Product over time. </p>
<p>The inflexible goal of balancing the budget by 2002 exclusively through spending cuts is arbitrary 
and unnecessary. It puts a particularly hard burden on the elderly, on working people, on college 
students, on children. This is grossly unfair and unjust -- and even more unfair if it includes 
significant tax cuts for wealthy individuals and profitable corporations. It ignores the tax subsidies 
that benefit primarily corporations and wealthy individuals. </p>
<p>Substantial revenues could be raised by closing tax loopholes which treat capital gains income and 
inheritance preferentially, and which reward corporations for exporting and destroying jobs. </p>
<p>Changing the foreign tax credit to a deduction, for example, could raise $16.5 billion. At present, 
U.S. based multinationals are able to take a credit against their U.S. corporate income tax 
obligations for income taxes they pay to foreign countries. This provides them with an incentive to 
invest abroad, costing the Treasury and shifting production overseas. Another example. Cracking 
down on transfer pricing abuse by multinationals, by which firms avoid taxes by shifting their costs 
of production on paper, could raise an additional $28.7 billion. Now a firm can over charge itself 
for an item produced by a subsidiary in a low tax country. This shifts its income out of the U.S. and 
into a low tax location. </p>
<p>The deficit is a moving target. All estimates will be out the window in the event of a recession, 
which would change budget and political realities significantly. The budget process should move 
toward balance in a deliberate manner, but there should be enough flexibility to deal with economic 
realities such as recessions as well as the unforeseen and emerging priorities. Furthermore, 
consideration should be given to improved tax equity and eliminating corporate tax and spending 
subsidies. Such measures would improve the quality of public policy and help lower the deficit. </p>
<p>Squeezing the budget into a balanced budget straitjacket is an unrealistic way to address national 
needs. It focuses on a single issue and fails to deal with other key priorities, including faster 
economic growth and full employment -- goals which help achieve a budget balanced over time. </p>
<hr>
<hr>
<hr>
<hr>
<p>APPENDIX A </p>
<p><a name="A"><strong>PROGRAM CUTS PROPOSED BY THE HOUSE BUDGET ACT</strong></a> </p>
<p>The House and the Senate budget resolutions target specific programs for cuts over seven years. 
Many of these programs directly or indirectly help workers and their families. While the two bills 
contain many similarities, there are a number of different programs and levels of detail. Some 
programs that would be affected by budget actions in the House of Representatives include the 
following in the areas of employment and training, education, safety and health, housing, 
infrastructure and environment, energy, transportation, economic development, federal workers, 
maritime, trade and export promotion, technology and miscellaneous. Proposed actions vary by 
program and cuts are from the fiscal 1995 level. Funding levels are generally measured in outlay 
amounts. Dollar cuts sometimes are small in 1996 and then rise for later years, which are shown 
below. <strong>PROGRAM 1995 FUNDING ALL PROGRAMS CUT BY</strong> </p>
<p>($ MILLIONS) 20%--ADDITIONAL CUTS </p>
<p>EFFECTIVE IN 2002 </p>
<p><strong>EMPLOYMENT AND TRAINING</strong> </p>
<pre>
Davis-Bacon Act                         N.A.                       $833 million
Service Contract Act                    N.A.                       $700 million
</pre>
<p>The Davis-Bacon and Service Contract Acts are basic labor protections which assure that local 
prevailing wages are paid in federal contracts for construction and for service contracts. The 
purpose is to prevent the use of federal funds from undercutting local wage rates. </p>
<p>Training and Employment Services </p>
<p>Federal training assistance now provided through various specific programs aimed at particular 
problem groups such as: workers displaced by trade, disadvantaged minority youth, Indians, etc. 
are proposed to be combined into a massive job training block grant that is turned over to the 
states. Spending overall would be cut by 20 percent. Many specific programs would be eliminated 
as such. </p>
<p>Vocational and Adult </p>
<p>Education $1,468 Eliminate </p>
<p>State formula grants to prepare in-school youth for good jobs and further education and training. 
Provides adults with opportunities to succeed through adult education and family literacy. </p>
<p>Extended Unemployment<br>
Benefits ----- Eliminate<br>
Employment and Training Admin.<br>
Unemployment Trust Fund $166 Eliminate </p>
<p>This income-support program for long-term jobless workers provides an additional 13 weeks of 
unemployment compensation -- beyond the normal 26 weeks of state unemployment insurance 
payments -- for workers who are unemployed for extended periods of time when overall 
unemployment increases during a recession. This program also acts as an anti-recession stabilizer. 
During periods of high state unemployment, extended benefits, financed one-half by state payroll 
taxes and one- half by the federal unemployment payroll tax, are paid. </p>
<p>State UI and Employment<br>
Service Operations $810 Eliminate </p>
<p>The public employment service is a nationwide system providing no-fee employment services to 
individuals who are seeking employment and employers who are seeking workers. State 
employment service activities are financed by allotment to states distributed under a 
demographically based funding formula. Federal requirements would be repealed by doing away 
with the Wagner-Peyser Act. </p>
<p>Trade Adjustment Assistance<br>
(Training) $ 93 Eliminate<br>
Trade Adjustment Assistance<br>
(NAFTA) $ 9 Eliminate<br>
Trade Adjustment Assistance<br>
(Benefits) $212 Eliminate </p>
<p>Adjustment assistance, including cash weekly benefits, training, job search and relocation 
allowances, are paid to workers as authorized by the Trade Act of 1974, as amended. Adjustment 
assistance, including weekly cash benefits, training, job search and relocation allowances, is paid to 
workers determined to be adversely </p>
<p>affected as a result of the North American Free Trade Agreement. The training and NAFTA 
programs become part of a block grant, while the benefits program dies. </p>
<p>Office of the American Workplace $ 30 Eliminate </p>
<p>This office in the Department of Labor encourages labor-management cooperative practices and 
other practices that increase the skills of workers, assist them in becoming more productive and 
innovative, help them in obtaining better jobs. Elements are being transferred to other areas of the 
Labor Department. </p>
<p><strong>EDUCATION</strong> </p>
<p>Subsidy Program for Student<br>
Loans $5,237 Eliminate in-school subsidy </p>
<p>Federal student loans are the largest single source of financial aid for undergraduate and graduate 
students. The federal government helps lower- and middle-income students by paying the interest 
on their loans until the students finish their studies. The aid extends for six months after a student 
leaves school. This in- school interest exemption based on need benefits some 4.5 million students. 
It encourages students to complete their degrees, keeps them from facing enormous debts when 
they graduate, and lessens the chance they might default on repayment. </p>
<p>Bilingual and Immigrant Education $251 Eliminate </p>
<p>These programs provide assistance of local educational agencies and other entities to develop and 
enhance their capacity to provide high-quality instructional programs to children and youth of 
limited English proficiency. </p>
<p>Funding for Libraries $155 Eliminate Funding </p>
<p>This program assists public libraries in Improving access to public library services. States are 
encouraged to undertake activities that further the National Education Goals. </p>
<p>Head Start $3,339 Cut $209 million </p>
<p>This program provides comprehensive early childhood education services through the Department 
of Health and Human Services. It has been one of the most popular, most enduring and most 
successful programs originating from the Great Society of the 1960s. </p>
<p>Goals 2000 $133 Eliminate Funding </p>
<p>Goals 2000 sets eight national education goals and provides support for states and communities to 
establish challenging academic standards and advance school improvements through local 
participation. One goal is to raise the high school graduation rate to at least 90 percent. At present, 
many states have much lower graduation rates. California, for example, has a 77 percent rate. </p>
<p>TRIO Program $419 Eliminate funding </p>
<p>Five programs that assist at-risk students from getting access to higher education. Over 680,000 
students will benefit from these programs under the current year budget proposal. </p>
<p><strong>SAFETY</strong> </p>
<p>Occupational Safety and Health<br>
Administration (OSHA) $312 Cut 20 percent </p>
<p>New and revised standards are proposed and promulgated to protect the safety and health of 
workers. Compliance with occupational safety and health standards is gained in part by the physical 
inspection of plants and facilities, and by encouraging cooperation between employers and 
employees to ensure safe and healthy workplaces. Technical assistance provided on all aspects of 
standards setting, variances, compliance assistance, and enforcement programs. Compliance 
assistance is provided and OSHA maintains management information and statistical support for 
OSHA'S programs and field operations. </p>
<p>Mine Safety and Health Admin. $201 Cut 20 percent </p>
<p>Enforcement of the Federal Mine Safety and Health Act of 1977 includes inspection of mines, the 
development and promulgation of health and safety standards, assistance in mine rescue operations, 
investigations of serious accidents in mines, recommendations to reduce working hazards, and 
on-site education and training assistance. This activity assesses and collects civil monetary penalties 
for violations of safety and health standards. Transfer MSHA to OSHA. </p>
<p>National Institute of Occupational<br>
Safety and Health (NIOSH) $1,888 Cut $133 Million </p>
<p>The National Institute of Occupational Safety and Health (NIOSH) conducts research and sets 
criteria for standards aimed at reducing on-the-job illness and injury. </p>
<p><strong>HOUSING</strong> </p>
<p>The House and Senate budget reconciliation bills cut programs back and create block grants for 
housing assistance. In the area of rental assistance, the Senate bill cuts $5.7 billion over 5 years, the 
House $37.4 billion. Both the House and Senate bills terminate all additional Section 8 rental 
assistance and the House bill provides renewal of only half of expiring rental assistance so that the 
total number assisted would decline at a time when housing problems for lower income people are 
getting worse. The U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development estimates that after seven 
years, 1.3 million fewer families would receive housing subsidies under the House budget than 
under the Administration's budget. Under the House bill, for example, in 1996, instead of adding 
50,000 incremental units of tenant-based assistance, there would be a loss of 78,000, a swing of 
128,000 units. </p>
<p>HOME Housing Block Grant $909 Cut $280 million </p>
<p>Proposed is a 10 percent cut in 1996 followed by a 20 percent cut in 1997. The HOME program 
provides flexible assistance to states and localities to help in developing rental and home ownership 
housing for lower income people. A part of the funds are allocated to rural areas and non-profit 
organizations have a setaside for some funds under the program. This program would be 
consolidated into a larger block grant. The Department of Housing and Urban Development 
estimates that the cuts </p>
<p>under the program over the next two years would result in 23,000 fewer units and families assisted 
through rehabilitation, new construction, and tenant based assistance. </p>
<p>Homeless Shelter Grants $ 88 Cut $31 million </p>
<p>This program authorizes assistance to promote development of supportive housing and services for 
deinstitutionalized homeless individuals, homeless families with children, homeless individuals with 
mental disabilities, and other homeless. Aid goes for acquisition, rehabilitation, construction, or 
leasing of structures for homeless as well as operating costs and supportive services. This program 
would be consolidated into a block grant. A ten percent cut in HUD's homeless programs in 1996 
would eliminate emergency services available to about 140,000 homeless and transitional services 
available to more than 99,000 homeless. The cut rises to 20 percent in 1997. </p>
<p>Public Housing Construction $571 Eliminate </p>
<p>The U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development has financed the construction of low 
rent housing for lower income people over the years. This is last resort housing for many, including 
the elderly poor and others who cannot afford decent housing in the private rental market. There 
are over one million public housing units in the U.S. Senate bill creates a block grant for public 
housing. </p>
<p><strong>INFRASTRUCTURE-ENVIRONMENT</strong> </p>
<p>Veterans Administration Major<br>
Construction $541 Cut $369 million </p>
<p>The VA provides a whole range of services to American military service veterans, including 
pensions, health services, housing assistance, education, burial services and more. The VA 
constructs hospitals, clinics, nursing homes, psychiatric buildings and small projects, including such 
things as parking lots. </p>
<p>National Park Service Operations $1,047 10 % Operations cut<br>
National Park Service New Construction $ 245 50 % Reduction<br>
</p>
<p>The Park System contains 368 areas and 80 million acres of land. These areas have been 
established to protect and preserve the cultural and natural heritage of the U.S. and its territories. 
Park visits total over 270 million annually. There is also a proposed 50 percent reduction in new 
construction and a 5-year moratorium on land acquisition proposed. </p>
<p>National Forest System $1,248 Cut $134 million </p>
<p>The 156 National Forest, 20 National Grasslands, and 9 land utilization projects are maintained 
under the Forest System, including the natural resources of timber, minerals, range, wildlife, 
outdoor recreation, watershed, and soil. There is a 10 percent cut in construction of trails 
proposed. </p>
<p>NOAA--Oceans and atmospherics $1,800 $350 million cut </p>
<p>The National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration carries on a variety of activities related to 
marine and air navigation, marine fisheries, ocean and atmosphere research, National Weather 
Service and environmental satellites. NOAA construction is also proposed to be eliminated. 
NOAA would be dismantled and parts divided among various other agencies and 2 of the 4 
weather satellites would be shut down. </p>
<p><strong>ENERGY</strong> </p>
<p>Energy Supply R&amp;D $3,265 Cut $1,200 million </p>
<p>Energy supply research and development is conducted to develop new energy technologies and 
improve existing ones. These include solar and renewables, fusion and technologies for clean and 
efficient burning of coal. </p>
<p>Energy Conservation Research $691 $409 million cut </p>
<p>Energy conservation research involves research to improve the energy efficiency of buildings, 
industrial processes, advanced vehicle technologies and appliances. </p>
<p>Energy Information Administration<br>
(EIA) $82 Reduce by half </p>
<p>This would cause a cutback in the availability of energy statistics, reports and forecasts now 
supplied by the U.S. Department of Energy. </p>
<p><strong>TRANSPORTATION</strong> </p>
<p>Mass Transit Operating Subsidies N.A. $770 million cut<br>
Transit Capital Grants N.A. Cut $590 million<br>
</p>
<p>These programs provides resources for a wide variety of mass transit purposes, including planning, 
construction of facilities, purchase of buses and railcars, and for operating assistance. In 1995 the 
federal government spends $1.8 billion in urban formula grants for operations and capital 
expenditures. Mass transit facilities are needed in cities to balance transportation system and to 
eliminate transportation gridlock and reduce pollution. There is a $1+ billion cut resulting from 
changing the federal match rate for remaining capital expenditures to 50 percent. </p>
<p>Amtrak assistance $752 Eliminate </p>
<p>The National Railroad Passenger Corporation, or Amtrak, was established in 1970. It is operated 
and managed as a for profit corporation. The government provides support for the on-going 
operations of Amtrak and capital grants to support Amtrak capital requirements as well as support 
for costs associated with long-term restructuring of the Corporation. Amtrak provides essential 
passenger rail service and provides some balance in the national transportation system, which is 
heavily skewed toward automobiles and air transport. </p>
<p>Local Rail Freight Assistance $26 Eliminate </p>
<p>This program provides discretionary and flat-rate grants to states for rail planning and for 
acquisition, track rehabilitation, and rail facility construction with respect to light density freight lines. </p>
<pre>
N.E. Corridor Improvement               $194                No new improve-
                                                     ment funds after 
                                                     1999


</pre>
<p>Provides funds to continue the upgrade of passenger rail service in the corridor between 
Washington, D.C. and Boston. Program reductions would occur beginning in the year 2000. </p>
<p>High Speed Rail $14 Eliminate </p>
<p>The Next Generation High-Speed Rail Program will fund research, development and technology 
demonstration programs plus expenses in connection with analysis required to evaluate proposals 
under the program. </p>
<p>Intelligent Vehicle Development $18 Eliminate Funding </p>
<p>Vehicle systems intended to reduce traffic congestion, improve safety and aid motorists through 
electronic communication. Examples of such technologies include electronic toll-charging devices, 
message signs along highways and auto navigation devices that &quot;read&quot; road signs and traffic 
conditions and suggest alternative routes. </p>
<p><strong>ECONOMIC DEVELOPMENT</strong> </p>
<p>Community Development Financial<br>
Institutions $34 Eliminate </p>
<p>Authorized in 1994, the CDFI fund will provide grants, loans and technical assistance to new and 
existing community development financial institutions such as community development banks. Funds 
support mortgage, small business and economic development lending in currently underserved, 
distressed neighborhoods. </p>
<p>Community Development Block<br>
Grants $4,000 Cut $924 million </p>
<p>This successful program of the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development provides 
flexible development assistance to cities across the country. The program assists in infrastructure 
and housing development. The program would be cut by 20 percent in the House bill and 50 
percent in the Senate bill. </p>
<p>Appalachian Regional Commission $202 Eliminate </p>
<p>Program investments are made in the Appalachian Region for wide-ranging assistance including 
development and human resource development. The states, acting through the ARC, are 
responsible for recommending local and state projects within their borders for assistance under this 
program. Special targeting to distressed counties is a part of the state allocation formula. </p>
<p>Economic Development Admin. $317 Eliminate </p>
<p>The programs of the Commerce Department's Economic Development Administration provide 
grants for public works and development facilities, other financial assistance, and the planning and 
coordination needed to alleviate conditions of substantial and persistent unemployment and 
underemployment in economically distressed areas and regions. </p>
<p>Federal support for TVA $141 End Federal Support </p>
<p>The Tennessee Valley Authority was created in 1933 as a government-owned corporation for the 
unified development of a river basin comprised of parts of seven states. TVA's responsibilities 
include maintaining water stewardship, development, recreation and power. </p>
<p><strong>FEDERAL WORKERS</strong> </p>
<p>The House budget abolishes the departments of Commerce, Education and Energy. Also, the 
House eliminates 14 agencies such as the Economic Development Administration. It terminates 283 
federal programs. These cuts would affect federal workers, whose numbers have declined in recent 
years. The number of federal workers declined by 66,000 to a level of 2,818,000 in the year 
ending March of 1995. There has been a decline of 267,000 federal workers since 1990. </p>
<p>Departments of Commerce, Energy,<br>
Education Eliminate </p>
<p>The Commerce Department houses the Bureau of the Census and numerous other agencies and 
departments related to exports and fostering business development. The Education Department 
manages 240 programs covering grants to school systems, student loans, national education 
statistics and more. The Energy Department manages environmental cleanup of weapons facilities, 
domestic energy supply, nuclear weapons stockpile, research and development in the area of 
energy conservation and supply. </p>
<p>Federal Buildings $627 BA Eliminate </p>
<p>Impose a five-year/seven-year moratorium on construction and acquisition of new federal buildings. 
There also is proposed a reduction of federal agency overhead of $1.25 billion over seven years. </p>
<p><strong>MARITIME</strong> </p>
<p>Federal Maritime Commission $19 Eliminate Commission </p>
<p>The Federal Maritime Commission regulates the domestic offshore and international waterborne 
commerce of the U.S, In addition, the Commission has responsibility for the licensing of ocean 
freight forwarders, ensuring that non-vessel operating common carriers are tariffed and bonded, 
ensuring that vessel owners or operators establish financial responsibility for death or injury to 
passengers or other persons on voyages to and from U.S. ports, and indemnification of passengers 
for the nonperformance of transportation. </p>
<p><strong>TRADE--EXPORT PROMOTION</strong> </p>
<p>The House and Senate resolutions contain numerous reductions in the trade and international 
programs supported by the U.S. The Senate bill, for example, reduces export financing and trade 
promotion programs by $755 million in budget authority and $404 million in outlays over five years. 
International Labor Organization </p>
<p>Separate legislation might reduce the $64 million U.S. contribution to the International Labor 
Organization to $53 million in the House. </p>
<p>National Endowment for Democracy </p>
<p>The National Endowment for Democracy (NED), which encourages the development of 
democratic institutions overseas, such as labor organizations, might be cut. The funding of 
International Institutes of the AFL-CIO could be vulnerable under a foreign aid authorization bill. </p>
<pre>
International Trade Admin.              $259                Eliminate Trade
</pre>
<p>Promotion Activities </p>
<p>The activities of the ITA in the Department of Commerce are intended to </p>
<p>develop the export potential of U.S. firms in a manner consistent with national security and foreign 
and economic policy and to promote an improved trade posture for U.S. industry. ITA pursues 
policies to open markets and boost exports of U.S. goods and services. </p>
<p>Public Law 480 $1,066 Reduction </p>
<p>Food distribution to the less-developed and famine-stricken world. The program is administered 
jointly by the Agriculture Department and the State Department's Agency for International 
Development. Food is provided to the countries through low- interest, long-term loans and grants. 
The Senate proposes reducing PL480 food aid by $386 million in outlays over five years. The 
House also proposes reducing aid to the former Soviet Union and to Eastern Europe. </p>
<p><strong>TECHNOLOGY</strong> </p>
<p>Industrial Technology Services $181 Eliminate </p>
<p>This activity of the U.S. Department of Commerce supports the extension of technology to 
American industry and fosters the development of broad based high-risk technology by industry. 
The advanced technology program is the focus of a national effort to help accelerate the 
commercialization of technologies with commercial potential to stimulate economic growth. The 
manufacturing extension partnership emphasizes the role of the National Institute of Standards and 
Technology (NIST) in transferring technologies to smaller businesses and extension services. A 
quality program extends U.S. competitiveness through quality technology development and 
information transfer. </p>
<p><strong>MISCELLANEOUS</strong> </p>
<p>Federal funding for National<br>
Endowment for Arts and <br>
Humanities $351 Eliminate </p>
<p>National Endowment for the Arts programs encourage individual and institutional development of 
the arts, preservation of American artistic heritage and availability of the arts. The National 
Endowment for Humanities improves the quality of education and teaching in the humanities. </p>
<p>National Service Program $790 Eliminate </p>
<p>Encourages community service programs for education, public safety, human needs and the 
environment. Does so without displacing workers and helps participants pay for their education. </p>
<p>Welfare </p>
<p>The Senate cuts $47 billion from AFDC over five years, while the House appears to incorporate 
most of the measures in the welfare bill the House passed earlier this year, which aimed at saving 
$66 billion by 2000. There is the danger that under a radical change it would no longer be an 
entitlement, but be reduced to a block grant administered by the states. Substantial costs would be 
shifted to the states or else benefit levels could fall if the total assistance was reduced significantly. 
Organized labor has favored reform of welfare, but including safeguards and measures to make a 
reasonable transition for welfare recipients to work. Labor has expressed serious concern about 
the possibility of displacement of current workers. There may well be a shortage of jobs for welfare 
recipients in view of the large number of those unemployed and underemployed at present. Care 
needs also be taken so that reform is not punitive. </p>
<hr>
<p>APPENDIX B </p>
<p><a name="B"><strong>FEDERAL REGULATIONS TARGETED BY THE BUDGET RESOLUTION</strong></a> </p>
<p>The Republican-led budget assault on the federal government also includes a slash-and-burn attack 
on protections of safety, health and social concerns adopted over the years. The House and Senate 
Budget Resolutions contain assumptions about the repeal of the Davis-Bacon and the Service 
Contract Act labor protections. These laws assure that the government's power of procurement of 
construction or services is not used to undercut prevailing wages. In addition, the House resolution 
contains a list of federal regulations and mandates that, in their estimation, &quot;warrant elimination of 
reform.&quot; The House Budget Committee, which considers these regulations the most &quot;expensive and 
onerous,&quot; encourages authorizing and appropriations committees to wipe out or cripple these 
regulations, among others. </p>
<p>OSHA Ergonomics Rule. This would require employers to address repetitive motion injuries, 
injuries due to repeated hand, wrist, or other physical motions that cause of aggravate 
musculoskeletal disorders. </p>
<p>Worker Protection Standards. The Environmental Protection Agency issues worker protection 
standards under the Federal Insecticide, Fungicide and Rodenticide Act in 1992 and EPA has 
since ordered enforcement. The rule covers farmers in areas of safety, training, decontamination, 
information posting, emergency assistance, and worker reentry into fields after pesticides are 
applied. </p>
<p>Fall Protection. These construction regulations, drawn by the Occupational Safety and Health 
Administration in order to reduce accidents and injuries, safeguard workers and apply when 
employees are working high above the ground. </p>
<p>Teenage Cardboard Baler Rule. This 40-year old rule prohibits teenagers from loading paper 
balers or compactors, since it is hazardous work. </p>
<p>Comprehensive Occupational Safety and Health Programs. The Occupational Safety and Health 
Administration is preparing a rule that requires employers to develop and implement an 
occupational safety and health program in their workplace. </p>
<p>Motor Voter Act. This act allows eligible citizens to register to vote when applying for or renewing 
a driver's license and at various other government agencies or through the mail. </p>
<p>The Community Reinvestment Act. This act requires depository institutions to reinvest a portion of 
depositors' funds back into the communities they came from in order to address unfair local 
community redlining. </p>
<p>Job Service Requirement. Under the Job Training Partnership Act, states must provide job 
placement services for men, women, and youths, with special priority for veterans. The Job Service 
also must maintain a national network to clear employer job openings statewide and between states 
using a computer job bank. </p>
<p>Boren Amendment Regulating Medicaid Payment Levels. This provides that Medicaid payment 
rates for hospitals and nursing facilities must be &quot;reasonable and adequate&quot; to meet the costs of 
&quot;efficiently and economically operated&quot; facilities in providing care that meets federal and state 
quality and safety standards. </p>
<p>Meat and Poultry Inspection. The Department of Agriculture plans to issue a rule that would 
require new requirements for meat and poultry in order to assure the quality of food and protect 
consumers. </p>
<p>CAFE Standards-Fuel Efficiency. Corporate Average Fuel Efficiency (CAFE) standards 
encourage automobile manufacturers to produce more fuel efficient cars. </p>
<p>Enhanced Monitoring Rule. The Environmental Protection Agency is currently developing 
regulations to establish uniform pollution monitoring, recordkeeping, and reporting requirements for 
major sources of air pollution. </p>
<p>Indoor Air Quality. The Occupational Safety and Health Administration is preparing new 
regulations to require retailers, office building owners, and other businesses to implement indoor air 
quality programs and ventilation plans to safeguard public health. </p>
<p>Waste Disposal Rules for Environmentally Sound Practices. Regulations on the transportation, 
storage and disposal of hazardous wastes. </p>
<p>Great Lakes Water Quality. Draws up uniform EPA standards for water quality on eight states, 
Illinois, Indiana, Michigan, Minnesota, New York, Ohio, Pennsylvania and Wisconsin.</p>
<p align=center><a href="/index.htm">AFL-CIO Home Page</a> | <a href="http://localhost/issues/ertochome.html">Research Library Page</a></p>
