<body>
<p>Discussion Paper </p>
<h2>NAFTAmath</h2>
<h3>After Peso Devaluation in Mexico: A Tale of Two Countries</h3>
<h4>It was the best of times. . . . </h4>
<p>Five months after the meltdown of the peso, Mexican government
officials are making the claim the worst is over and that the
austerity package imposed on Mexico as part of the financial
bailout is yielding results. Mexico's finance ministry points to
a $540 million first quarter 1995 overall trade surplus thanks in
good part to the drop in import purchasing power and the surge in
exports. The Mexican stock market, the bolsa, has bounced back 30
percent to the 2000 level and has recovered some of the losses of
1994. The free- falling peso has stabilized in the past month and
now hovers near 6 pesos to the dollar. </p>
<p>Since the devaluation of the peso, exports from Mexico,
approximately 80 percent of which go to the U.S. are booming.
Overall exports in March grew 32 percent over the same period
last year to give Mexico a $460 trade surplus for the month. The
export boom was fueled by a 74 percent increase in mining
exports, a 70 percent increase in agricultural exports and a 29
percent increase in manufactured exports. Exports were notable in
the textile, chemical and mining industries. The U.S. trade
balance with Mexico continues to worsen and totalled a $3.8
billion deficit for the first quarter. </p>
<p>Contrary to NAFTA proponents who claimed that the agreement
would eliminate the need for the maquiladora assembly plants
located along the U.S. border, as many as 160 new maquiladoras
are likely to be established in 1995-96, according to a new study
by the forecasting service, WEFA. WEFA estimates that the number
of maquiladora jobs will rise by more than 130,000 to total
710,000 by the end of next year. </p>
<p>The maquiladora expansion confirms that producing in peso
denominated costs and selling in the U.S. for dollars is very
profitable for multinational firms operating along the
U.S.-Mexico border. William Smith of KPMG Peat Marwick claims,
&quot;You'll never get a better deal if you're buying a company
in Mexico where the costs of parts are extremely low and where
prices are lower than ever.&quot; After peso devaluation,
multinational employers in the maquilas will realize an annual
windfall of more than $750 million from lower labor costs. </p>
<hr>
<p>Top executives of U.S. companies producing in Mexico for the
U.S. market are well rewarded beyond the dreams of their Mexican
employees. In at least one case, the CEO's compensation was worth
far more than the companies entire annual Mexican payroll. Allied
Signal CEO Lawrence Bossidy took home $12.4 million last year,
while the company's 3,800 Mexican employees combined made an
estimated $7.8 million. At Ford, CEO Alex Trotman made $8.1
million, more than 2,000 times the annual pay of an average Ford
employee in Mexico. Ford has about 10,000 workers in its Mexican
assembly plants. </p>
<h4>It was the worst of times. . . .</h4>
<p>Things are much worse for ordinary Mexicans. With credit
tight, prices soaring, and hundreds of thousands of jobs already
gone, the peso's stabilization against the dollar won't mean much
to Mexicans struggling to survive. The real Mexican economy -
namely workers and small to medium-sized businesses - are
suffering their worst crisis in decades. </p>
<p>When stock market analysts and politicians say that the
Mexican economy is &quot;recovering&quot; what they mean is that
the speculative sector is stable. Christopher Walen of Legal
Research International warns, &quot;Unfortunately this has little
immediate or even long term benefit for or impact on the
productive sector where the majority of people live and the
income to service Mexico's foreign debt must be generated.&quot; </p>
<p>Official estimates of unemployment have doubled in the first
quarter. Most estimates are that 500,000-700,000 Mexican people
have lost jobs since the devaluation - the number is expected to
double before the end of the year. </p>
<p>The austerity measures imposed on Mexico as part of the
financial bailout include 35 percent hikes in fuel and energy
prices, raising the value added tax from 10 to 15 percent, and a
20 percent increase in electricity and gas billings. The
increased costs will hit hardest on those least able to pay. </p>
<p>Since most foreign made products are now out of their reach
following the peso devaluation, Mexican workers are primarily
concerned with real wages in pesos. During the Salines years of
1988 to 1994, the daily minimum wage in real terms fell from 10.9
pesos to 8.4 pesos. In 1995, with inflation expected to be 50-60
percent, Mexican workers will be hit by a substantial loss in
their standard of living. </p>
<p>Testifying before the Senate Banking Committee on May 24,
1995, Mexican businessman Javier Livas stated, &quot;I am
concerned that the enormous sacrifice to bring back foreign
investment will not have time to work and may easily end up in
unprecedented social unrest. The economic medicine may in fact
kill the patient. A dangerous feeling of helplessness is invading
the country.&quot; </p>
<p>One symptom of the economic crisis is the surge in the number
of street children. A 1992 U.N. survey estimated that 11,000
&quot;street children&quot; live in the Mexican capital,
consisting of homeless as well as those put on the streets by
their parents to bring home money. Today, there are 30,000 to
40,000 according to Jose Manuel Capellin, whose organization
operates eight shelters for children across Mexico City. </p>
<p>With the economic crisis already pushing Mexico to the limit
of its endurance, a severe drought across the northern half of
the country is killing hundreds of thousands of cattle, withering
crops and pushing the country deeper into debt with the U.S. The
loss of crops will eliminate crucial farming jobs at a time of
rising unemployment and, by forcing Mexico to import costly food
from abroad, could affect the county's ability to repay foreign
loans. In desperation, Mexico asked Washington's permission to
divert 26 billion gallons of water from the Rio Grande. Thus far,
the U.S. has declined. </p>
<p>Meanwhile, in Mexico City and Guadalajara, the country's two
largest cities, the extended dry season has contributed to record
setting pollution levels. Exceedingly high temperatures have
spurred a cholera epidemic in Tamaulipas and states further south
- triple the number of cases reported in 1994. </p>
<p>Another result of the economic crisis is the increase in
lawlessness. Shippers say truck hijackings in Mexico have
skyrocketed since peso devaluation. The surge in highway crime is
a big problem for business because 85 percent of the trade
between the U.S. and Mexico is carried by truck. The Mexican
police say 270 truck hijackings were reported on federal highways
alone in 1994, and there were many more on state and local roads. </p>
<h4>The worst is yet to come. . . . .</h4>
<p>The short term improvement in selected financial statistics
masks fundamental problems that indicate that the situation will
get worse in Mexico before it gets better. From mid-July to
mid-August, Mexico faces a &quot;payments bubble&quot; of $6.2
billion in short-term debt. The huge payout could put new
pressure on the peso. </p>
<p>Mexico's weaker banks are in big trouble - bad loans are
soaring to 10 percent of nearly $70 billion outstanding. Seven
banks have already had to borrow more than $1 billion from the
government to boost their capital to a minimum. And that
percentage is expected to grow in the second half of the year as
bankruptcies and unemployment multiply with the deepening
recession. The worry is that even strong banks will get so bogged
down in dealing with their troubled loans that they'll have few
spare resources to finance a recovery. Wealthy Mexican investors
took their money out of the country before the crash and have yet
to return. The U.S. bailout protected the interest of Wall Street
investors who purchased high-risk debt instruments in Mexico. </p>
<p>Predictions of the 1995 decline in economic output range from
the optimistic government estimate of -2 percent to the more
realistic private estimate of -5 percent. The economic
contraction will make it more difficult for Mexico to pay its
foreign debt, and increase the potential for social unrest at
home. </p>
<p>It is clear that NAFTA has provided the opportunity for
windfall profits for multinational companies exporting to the
U.S. under the protection of a free trade agreement. It is also
clear that the prosperity realized from increased trade has not
yet trickled down to the workers in Mexico. The peso devaluation
has precipitated an economic crisis for which the solution is to
once again squeeze the Mexican workers to the subsistence level
and below. So far, the combination of peso devaluation and NAFTA
has been detrimental to the interests of workers on both sides of
the border. </p>
<p>As a result of events following the enactment of the flawed
NAFTA, the AFL-CIO will work together with trade unionists from
other countries to make respect for basic worker rights and
standards a central feature of trade agreements in this
hemisphere. Addressing worker interests would clearly demonstrate
that movement toward freer trade can be beneficial to the
majority of people and not just corporate and political elites. </p>
<pre>
                  U.S.-Mexico Merchandise Trade
              Customs value in millions of dollars

                         Imports    Exports   Balance

          1992           35,184     40,597     5,413

          1993           39,930     41,635     1,705

          1994           49,493     50,840     1,348

          1995 (1st Qtr.) 14,976    11,157    -3,819
</pre>
<p>May 1995 </p>
